<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BATTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS: TOO EARLY TO KNOW  
 TEAM STILL SENDS MIXED MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ The Diamondbacks' meteoric sprint out of the spring
training gate with a nine-game winning streak had their fans
feeling euphoric. Since then, the club has fallen from orbit and
re-entered the atmosphere of the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Is it cause for concern or merely a minor glitch? Just how good
are the Diamondbacks, anyway? How much stock should be taken in
their spring record?
</P>
<P>
   After a day of rest Monday, the club stands at 13-7-1 entering
today's split-squad games at Tucson Electric Park against the
Anaheim Angels at 1:05 p.m. and the Chicago White Sox at 7:05.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff, upgraded considerably over the winter, has
shown some improvement, but the bullpen remains a mystery. The club
ERA is 4.55, compared to a 4.94 finish in the first spring.
</P>
<P>
   A more significant improvement is on offense. The club is
hitting .291, slightly ahead of its spring pace of .289 last
season, but at 7.3 runs per game is averaging almost two more runs
per game than last spring's 5.7, when the record was 16-15. The
club has scored 10 or more runs in eight games. During the regular
season, the club averaged 4.1 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're scoring six or seven runs a game, that helps the
pitchers, and when the pitchers are more relaxed, they pitch
better, and that in turn helps the offense. So each is dependent
upon the other,'' said left-hander Randy Johnson, who has a 1-0
record, a 3.46 ERA and 16 strikeouts in 13 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The record itself is not a true measuring stick of progress or
problems, but a winning record does help create confidence entering
the season, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope that will help you start off well,'' Johnson said.
``You can't just turn it on when the season starts. A good spring
record doesn't guarantee you anything. Kansas City has one of the
best records in baseball this spring. Does it mean they'll go to
the World Series? No. You have to go out and produce, earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Arizona's top producers this spring has been catcher
Kelly Stinnett, who is hitting .440 with four home runs. While he
wants to keep things in perspective, he can't discount what a
successful spring can mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've listened to some people on the radio, and they've said,
`Take it easy, take it easy, it's only the spring.' Well, I'm
sorry, I can't take it too easy. Going out and playing hard, trying
to win whether it's the spring or regular season, that's the way
I've been taught,'' Stinnett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go out and get in shape and all that stuff, but
winning does give you that confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams started slowly at the plate, in part
because he's using a more wide-open batting stance. He has been
swinging the bat with more authority of late, and his average has
inched up to .250, still quite a way from where he would like it to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what spring is for. You just keep trying things,
working on things to help make you better. Sometimes it takes
longer than you want,'' said Williams, who has one homer, one more
than he had last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people look at just the record. You obviously would
like to win as much as you can, but we who are out there every day,
those involved with the game every day, see things a little deeper.
The things you do before the spring training games start, in those
couple of weeks, all the work you put in, you know what it takes to
get where you are. You see the cause for the success.''
</P>
<P>
   Some guys even work on off days. Right-hander Todd Stottlemyre
had his regular turn on the mound Monday, but instead of skipping
it because of the off day or having it pushed back and the rest of
the rotation pushed back, he was scheduled to pitch five innings in
a minor league game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about the wins, it's how you approach the game, get
into your routine, prepare for the season,'' Stottlemyre said.
``I'd like to have better numbers (he is 0-0 with a 5.59 ERA), but
I'm more concerned about my mechanics. . . . Victories in the
spring are nice, but you don't want to get a false sense of
security.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
