<HEADLINE>
WITH TRADE, COYOTES GET RENEWED LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The vortex was spinning out of control, gathering
force, spewing debris.
</P>
<P>
   Swirls of paranoia over a wobbly stadium referendum. Perceived
sabotage from Jerry Colangelo and the Evil Empire. A mysterious man
floating an offer to buy the entire organization.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that lingered like sore groins. Losing streaks that
wouldn't end. A coach whose job came down to two points on a
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the relationship between fact, fiction and the Phoenix
Coyotes, it was all nasty and black, sucking the life from a hockey
team trying to cultivate a hockey town in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, Robert Reichel drops in, skates like he's
been here all along, changing the face and the outlook of the
entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say a fresh start,'' Rick Tocchet said. ``I'd say
renewed life.'' &QL; 
`Robert Reprieve'
</P>
<P>
   For so many reasons, the Coyotes needed this. They needed to
break Daniel Briere's heart, get in the game, invest in the
present. They needed to shake up the room with a symbol of hope,
something more substantial than new sweaters. They needed to make a
big-time move, and they did.
</P>
<P>
   So Robert Reichel becomes Robert Reprieve. A legitimate
second-line center who can make plays and watch his own back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only proven,'' Jeremy Roenick said. ``He's
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of Reichel does many things. He solidifies the top
two lines, relieving Tocchet of his baby-sitting chores. He allows
everyone else to slide into roles where they can succeed. And he
provides a dash of giddiness where queasiness had set in, the
growing fear of another first-round flame-out.
</P>
<P>
   Really, what's important here is the message. To the paying
customers and the people who might be tempted to vote on the Los
Arcos project. And, of course, to the players.
</P>
<P>
   From the time they learn to skate backwards, hockey players hear
all about holding up their end of the bargain. Well, that applies
to ownership, too.
</P>
<P>
   Without its own commitment to excellence, management cannot ask
a team to pursue a Cup with zealous belief. When a team knows it is
flawed, the shadows and distrust are always there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at this like a beginning or an end,'' Coyotes
coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``Rather, a piece that has been missing
all season long.'' &QL; 
Payroll an issue
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that team payroll has become an issue with the
Coyotes. Across the league, players have privately commented on the
thrifty nature of the organization. Which is why a bold stroke like
Reichel does wonders for morale.
</P>
<P>
   It's important because, somewhere along the way, owner Richard
Burke has grown resentful. Of the deal he signed at America West
Arena, the battle for a new stadium, the heavy losses that keep
pouring in. It's nice to know he didn't penalize his team for a
lack of profits.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this might be a temporary boost. Smith has already
promised that Briere's ice time ``will be a lot more next season,''
just as he expects Reichel to be around a few years. You have to
wonder if that makes Roenick expendable.
</P>
<P>
   It would be silly, seeing that Roenick has flair, a guy who
actually sells tickets in the NHL. But in an organization with a
history of cost-cutting, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I don't give a (bleep),'' Roenick said.
``I love it here in Phoenix, but if they want to deal me, that's
their prerogative. If they feel they can make the team better by
doing it, that just means I go somewhere else and try to win the
Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, all that matters is the present. That Reichel
and Roenick provide an answer for Yzerman and Fedorov, Forsberg and
Sakic, Nieuwendyk and Modano. That Burke held up ``his'' end.
</P>
<P>
   For all the chaos on the periphery, the focus finally landed
where it needed to be all along.
</P>
<P>
   On the ice. On the belief that the product comes first and
everything else will fall into place. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
