<HEADLINE>
BIBBY'S RETURN HOME TAKES ON FAMILIAR LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Vancouver's  &UR; Mike Bibby, who played his high school
basketball at Shadow Mountain and collegiately at Arizona, got his
hair cut by a familiar barber, had lunch with his mom,  &UR; Virginia,
and visited some old friends Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bibby, who used to make America West Arena his personal
stage as a prep star, played his first NBA game there.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said he's had to adjust to the NBA's travel schedule, but
doesn't have any second thoughts about leaving Arizona after two
seasons. He was the second player taken in the June draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going by quick,'' Bibby said. ``It's all right. There's
nothing really that different except I'm making more money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More'' money?
</P>
<P>
   Teammate  &UR; Shareef Abdur-Raheem, who played at California, wasn't
going to let that one go by without comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all you (media) guys said about my school, he's making
more money now,'' Abdur-Raheem said. ``I want to read that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Per diem,'' Bibby claimed. &QL; 
De-Kleine-d &QL; 
Suns center  &UR; Joe Kleine said he has removed himself from
consideration for the vacant head coaching position at
Arkansas-Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Kleine interviewed in Dallas for the job on March 13, and he
said he spoke with officials from the school over the weekend.
Kleine said he would have to agree to leave the Suns now to get the
job, and he is not willing to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first time I talked to them, I told them I wouldn't
leave until the season is over,'' Kleine said. ``They wanted to
interview me anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost case &QL; 
A U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that Suns forward  &UR; Clifford
Robinson must pay a partnership the $517,000 he owes on a home
loan, the Associated Press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in a 2-1 ruling, said Robinson waited too long to
claim he was defrauded. The claim arose from Robinson's dispute
with his former financial advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court said Robinson was bound by a 1993
contract with one of the lenders for his $1.5 million home in
Newtown, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, then with the Portland Trail Blazers, paid interest on
the loan for three years but failed to pay the $468,000 principal,
which was due in a balloon payment in May 1996. The damage award
also includes late fees and interest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Geil, Robinson's lawyer, said he would recommend that
Robinson appeal to the Supreme Court. If a lender commits fraud, he
said, ``I think it's fair that it should be treated as a defense to
any collection'' on the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson filed claims in August 1996 against the lenders saying
he had been defrauded.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's former agent,  &UR; Larry Gillman, paid Robinson $457,000
in a 1997 settlement stemming from a separate suit that alleged the
agent took kickbacks from contractors building Robinson's home and
that Gillman used the money to remodel his own home. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
