<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SPRING-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY PRACTICES COULD BE IN WORKS FOR ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The fear of a particularly hot summer has
prompted Arizona State Coach
 &UR; Bruce Snyder to consider a dramatic change in the team's practice
schedule for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say, ``Rise and shine''?
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are thinking about early-morning practices
instead of the late-afternoon schedule the team has followed
recently. Workouts would get under way at approximately 6:45 a.m.,
allowing enough time for the players to attend morning classes.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder emphasized it is one of several options he is
considering.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear this could be the hottest summer of the
millennium, and with the Valley becoming more and more humid than
it was 15, 20 years ago, you have to take a look a things,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Night practices were considered but Snyder believes they are not
conducive to academic success. A 7 p.m. practice would require a 3
p.m. training table (a four-hour differential is recommended) and
the time between ``with a big stomach of food is probably not the
best time to study,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Early-morning practices would allow for the rest of the day to
be spent on academics.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's three sub-.500 seasons in the last decade have coincided
with some of the worst heat and humidity in the Valley in years.
</P>
<P>
   Several other teams in the country practice in the morning, but
it is more popular with basketball programs. Temple basketball
Coach  &UR; John Chaney does it, and former Southern California Coach
 &UR; George Raveling did it for years. &QL; 
Academic help &QL; 
In an effort to improve academic retention on the football team,
ASU has hired former fullback  &UR; Kelvin Fisher as the coordinator of
academic accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt he could address a need, which was a hands-on approach
with teaching young people how to navigate through the
university,'' Snyder said. ``He'll help teach them how to take care
of their business, how to be responsible, how to act, where to sit
in class, time management, all the different things to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who played at ASU from 1988-91 and amassed 1,763 rushing
yards, will serve as a liaison among the players, coaches,
professors and academic counselors.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils lost two starters, linebacker  &UR; Larry Johnson and
wide receiver
 &UR; Ricky Boyer, and No. 2 tailback  &UR; Marlon Farlow for all of last
season because of academics.
</P>
<P>
   Three current starters _ wide receiver  &UR; Tariq McDonald,
defensive tackle
 &UR; Junior Ioane and cornerback  &UR; J'Juan Cherry are not participating in
spring drills because of academics. &QL; 
Back in action &QL; 
The Sun Devils resumed spring practice Monday and have 12 workouts
remainings. Three scrimmages, the maximum allowed, are scheduled
for Saturday, for April 2 and for April 8. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
