</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LIGHTNING-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS GAIN GRETZKY BUT STILL LOSE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Wayne Gretzky is back in the lineup. The New York
Rangers are falling further back in the playoff race. The league's
trading deadline is Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In one of their worst performances of the season, the Rangers
were beaten, 6-3, Monday night by the Tampa Bay Lightning, the
worst team in the National Hockey League, before a howling crowd in
the half-filled Ice Palace. It was the Rangers' fourth game in a
row a without victory (0-2-2). They held a lead briefly, but
squandered it, a recent habit.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 10th-place Rangers remain five points behind
eighth-place Boston in the quest for the final playoff berth in the
Eastern Conference, they lost ground because the Bruins were idle
and the Rangers have played two more games. New York also has
played two more games than ninth-place Florida, which holds a
1-point lead on the Rangers. The Panthers, who were also idle
Monday night, will play host to the Rangers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Rangers' third game in four nights, and they started
Dan Cloutier, the rookie goalie, who lasted less than two periods
and departed with a stick-shattering display in the corridor behind
the Rangers' bench after giving up five goals on 18 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, in his 20th NHL season, will not be traded, but other
Ranger veterans are candidates, including the injured defenseman
Ulf Samuelsson, who is expected to miss two to three weeks with a
broken bone in his right foot. Others who might draw bids from
playoff contenders include left wing Kevin Stevens, who scored his
20th goal of the season Monday night, and John MacLean, who has 25.
</P>
<P>
   Niklas Sundstrom and Adam Graves scored the other Ranger goals.
Colin Forbes scored twice for the Lightning, which had lost its
three previous games and five of its previous six.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky last played on Feb. 22 in Calgary, then missed 12 games
with a protruding disk in his neck that limited his mobility and
caused him pain. The condition improved after a cortisone
injection, and Gretzky began skating last week, apart from the
team, without contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've skated really hard,'' Gretzky said. ``There is no pain
and tremendous mobility.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky traveled with the Rangers to Tampa on Sunday night,
after a 2-2 tie with Pittsburgh at Madison Square Garden, he said
he would practice during the road trip and return to the lineup for
the third game, Saturday afternoon in Philadelphia. But after
practicing with the team Monday morning, the decision was made to
dress him in his familiar No. 99 jersey. Christian Dube, another
center, was returned to Hartford to make room on the roster for
Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky had not scored in the eight games before his idleness
and came into Monday night's game still seeking his 1,072d
major-league goal, combining regular season and playoff games in
both the National Hockey League and the World Hockey Association.
His total of 1,071 tied him for first place with Gordie Howe, who
also played in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers used four lines Monday night, and Gretzky centered
the fourth unit. After Tampa Bay took a 1-0 lead on an
even-strength goal by Mike Sillinger 10 minutes 47 seconds into the
first period, the Rangers scored twice in a 20-second span to go up
by 2-1. But the Lightning scored twice in a 16-second burst to go
up by 3-2.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stevens got the first Ranger goal, making it 1-1 at 12:24, on
the power play, finishing a rush and passing combination with Mike
Knuble and Marc Savard. It the first time Stevens has reached 20
goals in a season since he scored 41 with Pittsburgh in 1993-94.
Sundstrom made it 2-1 at even strength at 12:44 with his 13th; he
had no points in his previous seven games.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes and Michael Nylander scored at 17:19 and 17:35,
respectively, making it 3-2, after taking advantage of sloppy
checking by the Rangers that left Cloutier vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Cloutier, Mike Richter's backup, last played on March 14, a 3-2
victory over the Islanders at Nassau Coliseum. He came into the
game with a 6-5-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Chris Gratton scored on the power play at
8:34 to make it 4-2 for the Lightning after a gratuitous
high-sticking penalty against Brent Fedyk of the Rangers. Forbes
got his second goal of the game on a rebound to make it 5-2 after
Brian Leetch turned over the puck in his own zone while the Rangers
were on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   When Richter skated out to replace Cloutier, the rookie goalie
stalked down the corridor behind the New York bench and smashed his
big stick to pieces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
