<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TARVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK TARVER, 82, FORMER PUBLISHER OF THE ATLANTA CONSTITUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Fla.)  (lh) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Tarver, who used his influence as publisher of The Atlanta
Journal and The Atlanta Constitution in the 1960s and early 1970s
to protect Ralph McGill, The Constitution's Pulitzer Prize-winning
editor, from bitter complaints about his support for the civil
rights movement, died of a heart attack on Sunday at his home in
Atlanta, his daughter, Margaret Tarver Jason, said. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the one who propped up Ralph McGill's soapbox,'' said
James Minter, who held a number of editorial posts under the two
men.
</P>
<P>
   Tarver regularly tangled with fellow members of Atlanta's
conservative establishment during the civil rights years, Minter
said. Once when the owners of Rich's, Atlanta's biggest department
store, threatened to quit advertising, Tarver responded that he was
confident that Davison's, the city's second-largest department
store chain, would be delighted to get the space.
</P>
<P>
   But supporting McGill did not mean following all his suggestions
for civil rights coverage. The two men disagreed over whether to
send their reporters to places like Birmingham and Selma, Ala., to
cover confrontations, and Tarver prevailed with his cautious
decision to use news agency reports instead.
</P>
<P>
   Tarver's tenure as publisher of the Atlanta papers included a
climb up the executive ranks of Cox Enterprises, their parent
company. He was named president of Cox in 1969 and vice chairman in
1976, the year he stepped down as publisher. He held that position
until 1983, devoting much of his time to work with The Associated
Press news service, which he served as chairman from 1976 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the rise to prominence as a newspaper executive,
Tarver maintained an acerbic sense of humor. In a 1957 interview
after being named president of Atlanta Newspapers Inc., the Cox
holding company, he noted that his index finger on his left hand
was permanently crooked as a result of an accident at The Toombs
County Democrat, a one-man weekly that he founded in rural
southeast Georgia in 1939 at the age of 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized almost immediately after I got it caught in the
gears of that old flat-bed press that if I were ever going to
amount to anything in the newspaper business it would have to be on
the executive level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, he first won attention with a weekly humor column he
wrote for The Macon News after The Democrat closed. His review of
``Gone With the Wind,'' which was reprinted in more than 40
newspapers, said that Scarlett O'Hara ``was as changeable as a
baby's underwear.'' The movie was so long and the seats in the
theater so hard, he added, that by the time Rhett Butler tells
Scarlett, ``Frankly, my dear, I don't give a damn,'' neither did
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Such work caught the eye of McGill, who persuaded him to come to
The Constitution as associate editor and humor columnist in 1943.
But Tarver's business skills became apparent to the paper's owners
and he was recruited to help restore the paper to profitability in
1949. After The Constitution and The Journal came under the joint
ownership of what is today Cox, he rose rapidly through the ranks
to become publisher in 1958. The Constitution remains the evening
paper and The Journal the morning one; the two are published as one
on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Williams Tarver was born March 2, 1917, in Savannah,
Ga., the son of Otis M. Tarver and deLuth Williams Tarver. His
father owned a chain of hotels that was decimated by the
Depression, so Tarver took advantage of a football scholarship at
Mercer University in Macon. An injury ended his playing days, but
his coach kept him on as a trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Tarver began his newspaper career at The Vidalia Advance, a
weekly, in 1938 before moving to Lyons, Ga., the following year to
establish The Democrat. He later described that ill-fated effort to
create a second newspaper in ``a one-dentist town'' as proof that
he was optimistic by nature.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter, who lives in Jacksonville, Fla.,
Tarver is survived by his wife, the former Margaret Birch Taylor; a
son, Jackson W. Tarver Jr. of Atlanta, and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
