<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-MILLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER'S STATUS STILL IN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Suitors of free-agent linebacker Jamir Miller are
backing off, apparently in the belief that he ultimately will
re-sign with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, New England Patriots Coach Pete Carroll said that
while he likes Miller, the club will pursue him no further until it
sees whether Miller accepts the two-year offer worth about $6
million he has on the table from the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the Cardinals' leading tackler last season, visited the
Patriots last week. He also has visited the Chicago Bears.
Representatives of the Tennessee Titans have had conversations with
Miller's agent, Steve Baker, but have not scheduled a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one is a unique situation for us,'' Carroll said. ``And
it's not one that we're going to move quickly on. It really is
going to depend on what happens with Arizona. We wanted to find out
where he was because he's a quality player and can help a club. But
we're not going after it at this time. We're just going to monitor
what takes place in the Arizona negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To attract him right now is more than we want to pay. Maybe it
goes further past the draft and things can change by then. We think
he's a good football player, but it's not the time for us to go
ahead and break the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, Cardinals vice president of player personnel, has
said that he will do what he can to keep Miller, even if Miller
receives an offer from another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamir has to understand what his market value is, and we
appreciate that,'' Ferguson said. ``But we have an offer on the
table and we've got to do something in the next few days, or we
have to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said Miller (6 feet 5, 266 pounds) made it clear that he
wants to sign with a team that will use him as a pass rusher more
extensively than the Cardinals, who drafted Miller 10th overall in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he would like to do is rush the passer all the time as an
outside guy, which he has not been able to do with the two guys
(ends Andre Wadsworth and Simeon Rice) that they have in place,''
Carroll said. ``You could use Jamir as an outside rusher in nickel
situations. That's what he wants. He's also played nickel
linebacker behind the line of scrimmage. He's done a lot of things.
That is what makes him attractive. He's a very flexible player.
</P>
<P>
   ``His heart is set on rushing the passer right now. That's why
he's hesitant to fully commit to Arizona, because they can't
promise him that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said that he believes ``strongly in what Jamir can do,
but nobody's going to design a defense for him. He's a young player
who can come back in here with an up-and-coming defense and really
establish himself, but we will determine what we are going to do if
and when he signs. There will be no promises. But I believe you
take care of your own, and we've made it clear that we want Jamir
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
