<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-DUKE-TENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE UPSETS TENNESSEE, 69-63 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Georgia Schwetzer, the sophomore guard for
Duke, said, before Monday night's game against favored Tennessee
that ``it was just another game for us; we'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would have imagined that they would have been this ready.
</P>
<P>
   Chamique Holdsclaw's career and the University of Tennessee's
reign ended in stunning fashion.
</P>
<P>
   With Holdsclaw, perhaps the best woman player ever in college
basketall, held to 8 points, 13 below her season average,
Tennessee, winner of the last three National Collegiate Athletic
Association titles, was upset by Duke, 69-63, in the East Regional
final at Greensboro Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The victory means the Blue Devils (28-6) and not the Lady Vols
(31-3) advance to the Final Four, where they will play Georgia in
one semifinal on Friday night. That winner will go on to Sunday's
championship game, something that had become a habit for Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Duke's night, as the women's team matched the men's
team in reaching the Final Four this weekend, the first school to
do so since Georgia in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer, a sophomore, led the Blue Devils with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw, who won four straight New York state titles at Christ
the King High School before winning three straight collegiate
championships, just could not get going. She missed her first 10
shots, finished 2 for 18 from the field and fouled out with 25
seconds to play. The 8 points matched her season low.
</P>
<P>
   Semeka Randall led Tennessee with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Duke was not only ahead, but it also was dominating
Tennessee and turning Holdsclaw, the Vols' four-time all-America,
into a toothless tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Duke led at the half, 35-24, and Holdsclaw the leading scorer in
NCAA tournament history had just 1 point. Not only that but she was
0 for 10 from the field, and had three shots blocked and lost a
ball off her foot while driving the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she was sometimes double-teamed, but the senior star many
consider the greatest college player in the history of the women's
game was also forcing shots and missing shots she often makes so
regularly that in the previous three tournament games this year she
had scored 23, 37 and 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Holdsclaw had a lot of company in the area of misfiring. Her
all-America counterpart, Tamika Catchings, also was throwing up
air-balls as if they were confetti.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Duke was getting consistent shooting from Schweitzer
_ she hit two of two from 3-point range, and five field goals in
five tries overall _ and from Michele VanGorp, the 6-6 sophomore
center, who also was five-for-five.
</P>
<P>
   Only Kellie Jolly was on her game for the Vols, hitting on four
of six shots, and leading the team with 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, ranked second in the nation, was seeking to get past
Duke, ranked 10th, in the East regional in order to reach the Final
Four for the fourth straight season, having won the title in each
of its last three attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Final Four semifinals will be played on Friday in San Jose,
Calif. Tennessee, under Coach Pat Summitt, has won five of the last
six NCAA titles and seven of the last eight.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Duke and Tennessee played, Dec. 6, in Orlando,
Fla., Tennessee won handily, 74-60. But the Blue Devils were able
to draw some confidence from the whipping because, after a sluggish
start, they felt they had given the great Tennessee team a
late-game run for its money.
</P>
<P>
   Duke entered Monday night's game having drawn moral strength
from its 76-63 victory over Old Dominion in Saturday's semifinals.
Like the Lady Vols, Old Dominion is an athletic team, a team that
uses pressure defense and offensive rebounding as prime weapons.
</P>
<P>
   What Old Dominion doesn't have that Tennessee does is the air
force. That is, Holdsclaw, the 6-2 senior who can fly, as well as
use such spinning, stop-and-go moves that she has virtually
revolutionized the concept of what a woman can do with a
basketball. She is so versatile, in fact, that the Tennessee media
guide lists her position thus: ``guard/forward/center.''
</P>
<P>
   For one half tonight though, she was just another player on the
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
