<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0528 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-GRIZZLIES-AZ     03-23 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-GRIZZLIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS PULL AWAY FROM GRIZZLIES IN 4TH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Danny Ainge's season of survival continues.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't pretty. Nothing about mediocrity ever is. A .500 record
is an unforgiving tightrope. One misstep, and it's a very short
fall to being known as a loser.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns continued to walk it Monday night with an 89-84 victory
over the Vancouver Grizzlies at America West Arena in front of
18,855 fans, 168 fewer than a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Before tipoff, a Suns' victory looked like a gimme. Vancouver
arrived in the Valley with 14 losses in their past 15 games. The
Grizzlies appeared to be a mercy mission for a Suns team that was
mired in a three-game skid, their longest losing streak of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But about a week ago Ainge called this season an exercise in
survival. That isn't easy by definition.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Suns needed a rescue mission from a very
dependable source to survive for their 13th victory in 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Robinson's jersey number is 30. But these days it could
be 911. He arrived just in time against the Grizzlies, who led by
four with about six minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:34 left and the Suns on top of a 76-75 score, Robinson
hit a three-point goal. On Vancouver's next possession, he tied up
Shareef Abdur-Rahim as the Grizzlies forward stepped into the lane
in a move toward the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson controlled the tip as the Suns went on to extend their
lead to seven during the next minute on a couple of free throws
from Jason Kidd and Tom Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cliff has been stepping up night after night,'' said Kidd, who
was 11 for 22 from the free-throw line on a night when the Suns
free-throw percentage was 58.8 percent, a bricklayer's special.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Robinson drew the primary defensive assingment on
the opposition's most dangerous threat. Abdur-Rahim is the NBA's
third-leading scorer. Against the Suns, he had 26 points, about
three more than his average.
</P>
<P>
   But he failed to score in the final 90 seconds, because of
Robinson, who blocked one of his attempts with 1:21 left.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's presence has been pivotal throughout the season. His
emotional impact is as evident as his defense. With 7:30 left, he
came off the floor in anger after he was called for his third foul.
But it wasn't the call that angered him. He wanted to be more
involved in what had been a hit-and-miss effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I just feel as though I get taken out of the offense
because I'm playing so hard on defense,'' said Robinson, who had 10
points and eight rebounds. ``We seem to forget I can post up Rahim
just as well as he can post up. I don't want every shot, but I
don't mind one now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   The first half was just another reminder that maybe the NBA
lockout wasn't as bad as everybody thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns 37 points at halftime equalled a season-low set last
month at San Antonio. The Grizzlies' 33 points didn't equal
anything. Their halftime output, a season low for a Suns foe, was
rock bottom. Then again, maybe not. The depths are apparently
unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   For the Suns, at least, the problem is their continuing
inability to maintain any momentum from quarter to quarter. This is
Team Schizo. Sometimes good, mostly bad.
</P>
<P>
   The good side was evident in the opening minutes against
Vancouver, the Midwest Division's bottom feeder. The Suns played a
crisp, up-tempo brand of basketball. It looked as if a day away
from the game after Saturday's loss at Houston had re-energized
them.
</P>
<P>
   They were shooting about 60 percent from the floor, had a
9-point lead midway through the opening quarter and moving
effortlessly at what appeared to be a runaway victory. But just
when it looked as though it would be breeze, the Suns suddenly went
into a stall.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Grizzlies ran off six straight points. Then, Ainge
went to his bench. Kidd's backup, Gerald Brown, got the call along
with Danny Manning and Joe Kleine.
</P>
<P>
   For Brown, it was the chance to face Vancouver rookie Mike
Bibby. It was a match-up between probably the two best guards to
ever play for Valley high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was Arizona's Player of the Year at Carl Hayden High
before Bibby came on to dominate the state during his years at
Shadow Mountain. Brown _ with rookie Toby Bailey alongside at
shooting guard in the second quarter _ made a good account of
himself with six points in 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But, by then, the Suns' bad side had shown itself. What does it
look like? How about 27.3 percent shooting from the floor in the
second quarter? Ugly enough for you? Vancouver wasn't much better
at 40 percent, which wasn't enough for the Grizzlies to gain
control by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns held on to a four-point margin that looked tenuous.
During the third and fourth quarters, Vancouver would prove that it
was. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 0036EST &QL; 
