<SLUG> BC-STABBING-TRIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAYING VICTIM'S FATHER FACES ACCUSED KILLER IN COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DONNA HUFFAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sobbing into his hands, Souren Mekhrabian turned
to the judge for help Monday when the man accused of killing his
son began to cross-examine him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is the man who murdered my son. I don't want to
see him,'' Mekhrabian said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Curtis B. Rappe told Souren
Mekhrabian he understands this is a difficult situation for the
grieving father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, under our system I have no choice. I have to
let him represent himself,'' he told Mekhrabian, who testified
through a Russian interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Standing just feet away was murder suspect Edward Dixon,
representing himself on the first day of his trial and
cross-examining Mekhrabian about the 1997 slaying of David
Mekhrabian in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, 42, is accused of stabbing David Mekhrabian to death
after David, 22, and his father rebuffed a request for 25 cents.
Dixon has been acting as his own attorney for more than a year in
the 18-month-old case.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Monday, Dixon peppered the grieving father with
questions about who else was in the area during the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Mekhrabian broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was holding my dying son. I was not looking around to see
who was coming and going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about himself in the third person, Dixon denied killing
Mekhrabian during opening statements Monday, saying it is
impossible for him to have been in two places at once. Standing
before jurors in a blue Los Angeles County Jail uniform, Dixon also
said his fingerprints were not found on the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   During testimony, Rappe sustained about a dozen objections from
Deputy District Attorney Bob Villa &UR; , &LR;  who found many of Dixon's
questions vague, irrelevant, argumentative and speculative.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're confusing things and dragging out the time,'' Rappe
said at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon also won some arguments, as when the judge refused to
allow Villa to show the jury an enlarged color photograph of David
Mekhrabian taken two days before his death.
</P>
<P>
   David Mekhrabian left Israel in September 1997 for his first
visit with his family in three years. On Sept. 29, he rode with his
father to the Pershing Square Building in downtown Los Angeles to
pick up the victim's mother, Stella Mekhrabian, from work. The
building is just a few blocks from where he works, Souren
Mekhrabian testified.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting outside the building, the father and son were
hassled by a panhandler to whom Souren Mekhrabian said he had given
money in the past. But on this day, he had no money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult for Souren Mekhrabian to understand the
transient, whom he identified as Dixon. He said Dixon waved a knife
in his face, cursed and pushed him. So he said he asked a woman
standing nearby, Shakeh Esmaliei, to tell the transient the
Mekhrabians had no money. That's when David volunteered to explain
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A minute later the woman began screaming. I looked at my son
and he said, `Papa, I was stabbed with a knife.' Then he fell to
the ground,'' Mekhrabian testified through tears.
</P>
<P>
   Although Esmaliei testified she saw the knife in Dixon's hand
and watched as he cleaned the blood from the blade, she said under
cross-examination that she could not identify the knife because it
went so rapidly from Dixon's pocket into David Mekhrabian's chest.
</P>
<P>
   Esmaliei said she was three feet away when she saw Dixon stab
the young man.
</P>
<P>
   Referring frequently to his brown file folder stuffed with
papers, Dixon challenged the fairness of how both witnesses
identified him to police. Both picked his photo out of six photos
of African-American men wearing similar clothes, Villa said.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to hourlong hearings with each witness, Rappe
ruled that no improper means were used to identify the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the day's testimony, Dixon objected to having
to wear his jail uniform in court. Rappe pointed out clothes had
been brought for him but they did not fit. Dixon has gained almost
90 pounds since the arrest, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
