<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR GIVES BLISS DEADLINE FOR DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Mexico's Dave Bliss said last night that he is still
considering whether to become Baylor's next basketball coach as
sources say he has until today to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baylor is a special place, and I'm saying that not only
because I'm a Baptist,'' Bliss said. ``And I do love Texas. I'm
just glad they're not still playing in Heart O' Texas Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss visited the campus again over the weekend. Butler
University athletic director John Parry said that Bulldogs coach
Barry Collier also was in Waco over the weekend, but it was his
understanding that Collier had not been offered the job.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the search said he believed Baylor would
turn to Collier if Bliss decided to remain at New Mexico, but that
Bliss was the No. 1 option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my understanding \RBaylor and Bliss\S have agreed on a
contract and now Baylor is waiting on Bliss to say yes or no,'' the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   The source said he did not know what could be delaying Bliss'
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss met yesterday morning with New Mexico athletic director
Rudy Davalos and the two have scheduled to meet again this morning.
A source familiar with yesterday's meeting said that at that time
Bliss remained undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about contract, it's not about money,'' the New
Mexico source said. ``He has a red ball in one hand and a green
ball in the other. But everyone knows he cannot wait any longer to
make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Parry confirmed Collier's visit, but said, ``Based on our
communication, I don't believe that Barry has been offered the job.
And I think I would know.''
</P>
<P>
   In 10 years Collier has taken the Bulldogs to the NCAA
Tournament twice and three berths in the National Invitation
Tournament. Butler lost to Clemson in the NIT quarterfinals this
season to finish 22-10.
</P>
<P>
   Collier was an assistant under Stanford coach Mike Montgomery
for three years and for Don Monson at Idaho and Oregon.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
