<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-LAKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS DROP `WINNABLE GAME' TO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Just like the award-winning halftime magic act, Quick
Change, the momentum changed quickly last night in the game between
the Mavericks and Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   One moment the Mavericks had the Lakers on the run, piercing
their defense with precision passes and accurate shooting. The next
moment the Lakers were playing like potential world champions.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Lakers had enough magic to hold off the
Mavericks, 96-93, before a sellout crowd of 18,121 at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are 9-18, while the Lakers improved to 19-9. It's
the seventh time this season the Mavericks have lost by six or
fewer points, as their offense crumbled again in the waning
moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a winnable game,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson
said. ``We played them pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy with how hard we played and how well we played.
Again, it's not quite good enough. No complaints about the game.
They're very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Lakers are good, but the Mavericks missed too many
chances to drive a stake into the West Coast team. Most notably was
a wide-open layup Steve Nash missed with 16 seconds remaining and
the Mavericks trailing by four points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rushed it,'' said Nash, who had three points, eight assists
and four turnovers. ``It was in my heel \Rof his hand\S. I choked.
I don't want to make any excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws by Glen Rice increased the Lakers' lead to 96-90
with 12.7 seconds remaining. Erick Strickland sliced the deficit in
half with a 3-point field goal with 4.3 seconds remaining, but the
Mavericks couldn't get the ball back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team did a good job,'' Lakers coach Kurt Rambis said.
``They played good defense and got the job done when they had to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks put on a performance in the first period that was
worthy of an Oscar. They shot .579 in the quarter and led by as
much as 10 points (25-15).
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green ignited the charge with 11 points and eight rebounds,
and Michael Finley contributed eight of his 23 points and four
assists. But the Lakers were undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   In Shaquille O'Neal, Glen Rice, Kobe Bryant and Dennis Rodman,
the Lakers have a quartet of all-stars. But it was Travis Knight
who jump-started the Lakers' offense with five baskets and a steal
in the early stages of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got strung out a little bit on him because we were
double-teaming the ball in the backcourt, and on two occasions we
got open,'' Nelson said. ``He had a big quarter, and that's a guy
that you think you can contain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we concentrate on him, we can contain him. But we played
well in that quarter and he hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   After that the Lakers got serious, the Mavericks missed a bushel
of shots and the Lakers gradually pulled away to complete a
six-game road trip with a 3-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal survived the foul-fest the Mavericks swarmed him with to
score 25 points and grab nine rebounds. Bryant finished with 21
points and Rice added 17.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who picked up 17 rebounds, was being, well, Rodman.
After hitting a free throw in the third period, he drew a technical
for blowing a kiss at Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Rodman was disturbed because Nelson ordered Finley
to intentionally foul Rodman _ a .333 shooter from the line _
although Rodman didn't have the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so many weapons now that you can't really
concentrate on just Shaq,'' Nelson said. ``I thought overall we did
a pretty good job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
