<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-DALLAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHING THE WORM: RODMAN ATTRACTS A CROWD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dennis Rodman bumped into the common folk last night at
Reunion Arena. Unlike himself, they had natural hair color, a
general respect for the broad guidelines of human civilization and
no tatoos.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 70-something lady who hung a Rodman No. 73 jersey
from a long string, hoping to reel in an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   There was Dr. Tony Evans, dressed in a three-piece suit and
toting a Bible on his way to pregame chapel. In the hall he passed
Rodman, wearing plaid pajama pants, a plain white T-shirt, a black
do-rag, sandals and enough body piercings to short-circuit a metal
detector.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Mavericks' Chris Anstey, whose eyes became
Australian for terrified when Rodman _ after 30 minutes of
scribbling notes while watching a tape of the Mavericks' last game
_ bolted into Dallas' locker room and began lifting weights while
listening to a blaring CD on his headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, the NBA's reigning bad boy, even crossed paths and
traded elbows with A.C. Green, the NBA's choirboy.
</P>
<P>
   And there were two unidentified white males, meeting with
Rodman, Dallas police and NBA security after the game concerning
what the men described as a previously filed lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   As much as two hours before the Lakers' 96-93 victory, Rodman's
first Dallas appearance since he jumped on stage with Pearl Jam at
Reunion last July had already generated scalpers, children in
rainbow wigs, the second sellout and the first real electricity of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   All in a day-and-night's work _ oh yeah, and don't forget the 17
rebounds and the technical foul for blowing a kiss _ for the
league's best attention and rebounder grabber.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the real excitement. All-Rodman, All-Night.
</P>
<P>
   That's where, lucky for Rodman, he always bumps into Kelly
Davis. For the last four years, it has been Davis' daily duty to
control the most uncontrollable person on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep his life as normal as possible,'' Davis said
with a sheepish grin. ``I'm his friend, a guy he trusts. When he
strays, I try to be a voice of reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, in another shrewd move, hired Davis off the Chicago
police force to be his bodyguard. Davis was there when Rodman
kicked a Minnesota cameraman in the groin, when Rodman showed up in
New York's Rockefeller Plaza in a wedding dress, and, yes, there
last week during Rodman's sabbatical to attend to personal
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't about Carmen \RElectra\S,'' Davis said laughing.
``He was with her most of the time. If he's not with her, he's on
the phone calling her every second.''
</P>
<P>
   As Davis quickly found out, his job is as much about keeping
Rodman away from the public as much as vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life is crazy, more than people realize,'' Davis said.
``He can't go to the movies or the mall without getting hassled.
It's my job to keep his path as clear as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Davis' jobs last night included getting nine tickets for
Rodman's immediate family, including his mother, who still lives in
the Dallas area. Rodman spends lots of his time here in the summer,
and has a growing excavation company in Frisco. Davis said Dallas
is one of the safest places for Rodman, because people know him
best here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this sounds crazy, but Dennis is quiet, shy and
introverted,'' Davis said. ``Off the court, he's as down-to-earth
as anyone you'd ever want to meet. Of course, he's got a marketing
side to him, and you can see for yourself how successful he is at
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who was fined $100 for his eight-day leave, said he is
back with the Lakers for good and that his departure was more about
finding out if he really wanted to play basketball rather than
problems with drinking, gambling or Carmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still enjoy playing, as you can see,'' Rodman said after
lifting weights for an hour after the game. ``If I keep my head
right I can have a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the ultimate distraction, most feel Rodman is not
only good for the Lakers, but the NBA. His controversial tirades
and ferocious rebounding keep the league in the headlines and the
Lakers in the hunt for their first championship in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound strange, but he's worth the trouble,'' said
Lakers guard and former Mavericks star Derek Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Added Shaquille O'Neal, ``It's cool to have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   By his standards Rodman was tame last night. Sporting a new
tattoo of a scantily-clad woman on the back of his right calf,
Rodman played an efficient, emotionless 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the game midway through the first quarter to an 80-20
cheer-jeer ratio, regularly called out Dallas' offensive plays to
teammates and LA's coaching staff, helped up Erick Strickland after
a second-quarter collision and drew his only technical in the third
for blowing a kiss toward Nelson after sinking a free throw created
by an intentional foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just having fun, entertaining the fans a little,''
Rodman said. ``But, unfortunately, the league is trying to take the
fun out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, Rodman is all about entertainment. Just ask one of
the 18,121 common folk who paid to see something out of the
ordinary last night.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
