<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTS-ON-THE-NET-TEX </SLUG>
 
VIRTUAL RACE-CAR DRIVERS, START YOUR PCs! 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rather than drive with the mass of humanity that will inch and
nudge toward Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth this weekend, some
NASCAR enthusiasts will try to experience the thrills of racing in
a less-congested way.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be sim racing.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be racing against other gearhead gamers who are online,
on a network or one-on-one. They'll be clutching a steering wheel
or joystick in front of a personal computer loaded with software
that simulates the NASCAR experience.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these virtual drivers won't exactly face the G-forces
or smell the combustible fuel that real drivers encounter. But,
thanks to some software developers who tediously duplicate the
track to the closest detail, they'll get an idea of the strategy
involved in driving in a NASCAR environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us will never get the chance to climb in a real stock
car and race,'' said Shawn D. Kosloff, publisher of Inside Sim
Racing Webzine. ``Sim racing offers us all of the thrills and
excitement of real racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sim racers have been around since before the World Wide Web,
back when their races were conducted or posted move by move like a
chess match. As the Internet and technology has developed, so, too,
has simulated racing.
</P>
<P>
   Internet search engines list scores of sites for online and
offline sim racing, several for Grand Prix and Formula driving, but
most for NASCAR interests.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR legitimized sim racing last season by sanctioning the
NASCAR Racing Online Series on the Total Entertainment Network
(www.ten.net). Veteran driver Dale Earnhardt Jr. was a frequent
competitor in the 15-race series.
</P>
<P>
   To go along with this weekend's Primestar 500 at TMS, Sierra
Sports of Watertown, Mass., has introduced NASCAR Racing-1999
Edition. Sierra software developers toured TMS and updated the
track's environment, complete with changes to the notorious Turns 1
and 4, and the addition of a 10-story office and condominium tower
at Turn 2 and seating on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the customer to see what the track is really like
through our products,'' said Dave Matson, a Sierra Sports
developer.
</P>
<P>
   It's an example of the attention to detail that goes with sim
racing.
</P>
<P>
   And depending on how competitive sim racers want to be, virtual
drivers can spend several hundreds of dollars on hardware,
software, fees and Internet connections. Standard PC specifications
will work, but most competitive drivers prefer high-end graphic
cards and connections to their Internet server simply because a
split-second-delay in data translation can result in a major
pileup.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers have gone so far as to build or purchase their own
racing cockpits, Kosloff said.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Keefe of Lewisville, Texas, who helped develop a site
called Virtual Racing Online Connection (www.vroc.net) for online
drivers, said he was a competitive driver in California before
moving to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the debate on virtual racing of whether it
makes you a better real-life racer or a better real-life driver,''
he said. ``I think it goes both ways.''
SIM SITES TO SEE A few sites for virtual drivers:
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Sports (www.sierrasports.com): Lists the latest in
simulation games created by Sierra Sports, a division of Papyrus
Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Total Entertainment Network (www.ten.net): Hosts NASCAR2, a
popular multiplayer online racing site.
</P>
<P>
   Sim World (www.sim-world.com): Offers the latest in support for
NASCAR2 and other racing simulations.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Racing Online Connection (www.vroc.net): Provides Grand
Prix Legends online racing for free.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Sportspage (www.digitalsports.com): Provides reviews of
racing simulations.
</P>
<P>
   SimRacing Online (www.simracing.com): Links to sites that deal
in racing simulations.
</P>
<P>
   Newsgroup (rec.sports.simulators): Usenet discussion area for
virtual drivers.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
