<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0552 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KINGS-ROCKETS-HNS     03-23 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KINGS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Rudy Tomjanovich was worried. His team looked loose and happy, on a
roll. And Tomjanovich, watching this, saw danger.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Things are going good, but this is a team that can lull you to
sleep in relaxed comfort,'' Tomjanovich said of the Sacramento
Kings. ``You think, `Let's play some offensive basketball.' And you
look up, and they're on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, that was obvious to every stunned fan at Compaq
Center. But Tomjanovich came to this unhappy realization 8{ hours
before the game.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Rockets build a 22-point lead, then blow all
but four points of it before beating the Kings 110-100, Tomjanovich
could not have described the Rockets' seventh win in their last
eight games better than he did before it started.
</P>
<P>
   That duty fell to center Antoine Carr, who was activated Monday
but unable to leave the bench as another huge lead disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The order of events, just a bit skewed Monday, should be clear,
Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You crush them, then you laugh,'' he said. ``After you cut the
jugular vein and they bleed to death, then you can laugh about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the Rockets couldn't help but bust out the grins
in the third quarter. Everything they tried offensively seemed to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen (25 points) and Michael Dickerson (23) were
attacking the basket with ease. Hakeem Olajuwon, who scored a
season-high 32 points, had his jump shot going as well as in any
game this season. Charles Barkley controlled the paint offensively
and the boards on both ends as the Rockets were on their way to
outrebounding the Kings 54-34.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley shut down more celebrated rookie Jason Williams,
who made one of eight shots for two points (he is 10-of-45 in his
past four games). And the Rockets had their best passing game,
finishing with a season-high 32 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were rolling so easily that they were picking
through offensive plays like Christmas presents. They pushed their
lead to 22 midway through the third quarter and were still leading
by 20 with 9:51 to go in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets almost let the Kings have the last laugh.
Sacramento went on a 23-7 run in 6:51 to pull within 99-95 with
three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   In that stretch, the Rockets made six of 11 shots but had eight
turnovers to let the Kings back in the game. The Rockets finished
with 23 turnovers, with Olajuwon giving away nine and Barkley six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had turnovers, and there wasn't that much defensive
pressure on,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We didn't have the mental
toughness to execute. We outrebounded them by 20, and we didn't get
more shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lacked the killer instinct to put this one away and get our
guys some rest. We have a back-to-back coming up (against Dallas
and Toronto on Wednesday and Thursday). We talk about this all the
time. We have to get hungrier and hungrier. If the lead is at 16
points, we've got to make it to 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings guard Vernon Maxwell haunted his old haunt with 10 of his
25 points during the spurt, and Chris Webber chipped in eight of
his 29. And if the prospect of losing the rest of a sizable lead
wasn't frightening enough, for a few moments it appeared the
Rockets would lose even more.
</P>
<P>
   With 2:05 left, Olajuwon fell to the court, having turned his
right ankle. He missed just 20 seconds, however, and said later
that he knew the ankle was all right after two or three minutes of
walking on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came down wrong,'' Olajuwon said.
</P>
<P>
   And just like Olajuwon, the Rockets quickly recovered. Barkley
made a jumper in the lane and three consecutive free throws to put
the game away. Dickerson took a long pass from Olajuwon to push the
lead back to double figures, and at least one Rockets player
believed that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our killer instinct is not as bad as people make it out to
be,'' Barkley said. ``We're still learning. Vernon Maxwell shot
them back in it. It would be great if we could win every game by 20
points, but it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's, however, was a lone voice of restraint, excluding
Maxwell, who would only say, ``This ain't my home no more.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Rockets were only too willing to lament the rout
that got away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big deal,'' Pippen said of the team's continued
inability to increase safe leads. ``I would like to see our bench
get out there and have the opportunity to play and have some fun.
Our lackadaisical performance has really cost them a lot of games
when they could have gotten involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is. I think it's a lot more mental now
than anything. I think we're fighting it so hard to keep it from
happening, it's almost like we're jinxing ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Brent Price: ``Sooner or later, if you play enough with
fire, you're going to get burned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
