<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0555 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     03-23 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS ENDURING `STRANGE YEAR' OF LIFE ON SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Thankfully for the Sonics, they caught Allen Iverson
on an off night.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's reigning player of the month showed up a little
off-kilter Monday night. Call it a temporary regression, although
the Sixers guard has outgrown the cold, hard knocks against him.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson dribbled out of control here and there. He took the ball
coast-to-coast when he should have passed off to a supporting cast
that, for the most part, he has helped be better in this
post-lockout, nutball season.
</P>
<P>
   The kid left the door open for Gary Payton to have himself a
small field day _ much deserved after the disaster in Denver Sunday
night and the Sonics' loss Friday at Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's stumble and the Sixers' sub-par night was a small but
much appreciated gift from a suddenly promising Eastern Conference
franchise. It saved the Sonics a terrible fate in letting them
chalk up a 92-76 win. A loss would have put the Sonics at .500, and
there is no way this team or its fans are prepared to face such a
harsh reality as that.
</P>
<P>
   Mediocrity? The Sonics haven't shown much more than that all
season, despite a 6-0 early season mirage that only delayed the
inevitable truth about this former elite of the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   They have lost their identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty bucks we paid for this,'' one KeyArena patron screamed
Monday night when things started out a little sluggish and sloppy _
a common affliction for these now 13-11 Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   But $80 was probably worth it, if only because the win kept the
Sonics above .500, and psychologically, symbolically, there is no
way they are prepared for not being winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't lost this many games in a long time. This is a
strange year. I don't know if it's the lockout or what, but this is
strange,'' Detlef Schrempf said.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf's expectations for this season were the same as any
during the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compete for the title. Win a lot of games during the regular
season. Secure home-court advantage,'' Schrempf said.
</P>
<P>
   If there was optimism at the start of the season among Sonic
veterans, it was that enough of the nucleus of the winning
franchise was intact and therefore capable of remaining a force.
But there was a slew of evidence that the Sonics were headed for a
serious slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah the (bulk of the starting) players are the same, but
you're missing some major ingredients,'' Schrempf said.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, any chance for momentum and chemistry were small.
There was George Karl's departure, the aging core of veterans, new
head coach Paul Westphal's lack of training-camp time to work out
lineup and personnel issues, a poor start by Vin Baker and overall
poor team shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Someone must have made the mistake of promising newcomer Billy
Owens starting minutes, because Westphal's tinkering with the
lineup has helped flatten the Sonics and turn them into a shell of
their former selves.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is even scared of us anymore,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost midway through this nutball, 50-game season, the
scouting report on the Sonics is simple and apparently common
knowledge throughout the NBA: Get a jump on them early because they
don't come out with intensity, and they can't or won't come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the personnel to come back,'' Payton said. ``We
can come back part of the way, but that's not all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors proved that Friday night by going on a 16-0 run in
the first quarter. The Sonics never regained the lead, losing
90-78. Same thing Sunday in Denver. The Nuggets barraged the
Sonics, shooting 50 percent from the floor in running up a 29-point
lead while the Sonics spat out a meager 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the Sixers offered little resistance. But the
funny thing was, even as the Sonics' lead stretched to 20-plus
points in the fourth quarter, KeyArena was well on its way to
clearing out.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be, at least in the old days, when the force was with
them, it was fun to stick around and watch the Sonics dominate.
Times they are changing, to quote Westphal's favorite singer, Bob
Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have not been a .500 team since 1990-91. That was the
second consecutive season they finished .500, but by then they had
drafted Payton No. 2 in the 1990 draft, making their misfortune pay
off with a ticket to the NBA lottery.
</P>
<P>
   They have won 55 games or more since 1992-93, with three seasons
over 60 wins. This too-close-for-comfort proximity to mediocrity
flies in the face of everything that's been established _ or so the
people in the $80 seats thought Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics themselves will take whatever they can get. Payton
wants 15 more wins, at least. He said he'll even take an eighth
seed in the post-season, if Baker's thumb injury means the Sonics
are in for a tougher road the next 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sonics are stunned almost to the point of catatonia when
it comes to coming to grips with the prospect of falling so far, so
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, (the losing) stinks,'' Hersey Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not sure everyone feels that way. We think we're
playing hard, but we're not. I'm so sick of thinking about it my
head hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
