<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT TAKES IT ALL IN STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The highlight shows Sunday night and newspapers across
the nation Monday morning were filled with tales of Kobe Bryant's
exploits in Orlando. The career-high 38 points, the 33-point second
half, the entire back-breaking performance he dumped on the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando coach Chuck Daly called it the 20-year-old's
``coming-out party on national TV.'' Horace Grant said Bryant could
have scored from half-court at will. The only one not raving about
it was Bryant himself. A day later, he was still aw-shucksing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it before,'' he said, ``in high school.'' As if
that's the same as bringing the Lakers back from a 24-point deficit
against a top NBA team on the road before a national audience. ``To
me it is. Because it's just basketball. It's not a big deal to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was nearly historic. The second-half outburst was four
points shy of Elgin Baylor's team record for points in a half. Yet
Bryant hesitated to call it his best game as a pro. With him, it
often looks as if he can just flip the switch and rattle off a
15-point quarter. And yes, it's something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just do it,'' he said. ``It's just part of me, it's in my
nature.'' Like he's unstoppable? Bryant had to laugh. ``Pretty
much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Parting shot: Shaquille O'Neal denies it, but waiting for him
in the locker room in Orlando was a crystal piece honoring him as a
former Magic player on the occasion of the team's 10th anniversary.
Derek Harper got one, too.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal's came with a handwritten note from Magic owner Rich
DeVos, who wrote, ``I can tell you still love this city and its
franchise, so stop bad-mouthing us.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal pretended he never saw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get nothing. I told you I wasn't gonna take it,'' he
said. ``If they ain't man enough to bring it over to me, I
definitely ain't gonna take it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he hadn't heard about DeVos' words. But O'Neal did
refrain from Orlando-bashing after the victory. ``Because I got
class,'' he said Monday. ``You know, I could have ripped that whole
(bleeping) town apart, but I got class, brother.''
</P>
<P>
   So is he done Orlando-bashing?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I ain't done with it. I'm gonna show that they miss me and
they want me back,'' he said. ``That (stuff) happened three years
ago, 365 times three, that's a lot of days. There's a lot of
(stuff) that happens in three years, and they're still (ticked) off
and still crying about (O'Neal leaving). They (screwed) up, the
organization (screwed) up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should name me the general manager. I brought Penny here,
I brought Darrell Armstrong, I brought Horace (Grant), and I was
the one that told them to bring Chuck Daly and Dr. J. You can quote
me on that _ I'm the general manager of that team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
