</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER-LESS SONICS SHOW LESS THOUGHT, BETTER REACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Perhaps Sonics coach Paul Westphal knew better than
anyone how his team would respond.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because he set the tone after learning that the team's
second-best player could be headed for an extended stay on the
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal was calm and resigned. Meanwhile, his Sonics simply
followed suit Monday night and refused to hang their heads.
</P>
<P>
   They hung the Philadelphia 76ers instead.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Gary Payton's 26 points, 13 of which came in a decisive
third quarter, the Sonics overwhelmed the Sixers 92-76 at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Sonics' third straight victory at home, and perhaps
their most germane. Not only did they snap a two-game skid, but the
Sonics (13-11) compensated for the loss of Vin Baker against a big
and talented Sixers (14-11) squad.
</P>
<P>
   Baker sat on the Sonics bench in street clothes with a cast and
plastic stabilizer on his right thumb. The 6-foot-11 power forward
has a partially torn ligament and could miss four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden void caused a shakeup in the lineup. Detlef Schrempf
started in place of Baker, and Billy Owens reclaimed his spot at
small forward. The Sonics then chucked the adversity about as
convincingly as Lennox Lewis beat Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team that showed up tonight is the one we like,'' Westphal
said. ``... We had the energy, and we moved the ball, we had good
scoring from several different players and we beat a real good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had lost two straight games against beatable teams,
being embarrassed at Golden State last Friday and falling short in
Denver on Sunday. In both games, the Sonics lacked early intensity
and fell behind by double digits in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, however, was completely different.
</P>
<P>
   After the first quarter ended in an 18-18 tie, the Sonics ran
past the Sixers and went ahead 45-35 at halftime. With a smaller
lineup, the Sonics used their speed and quickness to blow by the
Sixers and create easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were tired in the first quarter,'' Sixers coach Larry Brown
said. ``Their energy was a lot better than ours. Their defense was
great. They did exactly what they wanted to do. The more we
struggled, the more they turned it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said the Sonics were ``thinking less and reacting
more.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the strategy as long as Baker is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been missing that lately. We need to get easy baskets,''
said Owens, who had 11 points on 4-for-8 shooting. ``We've got guys
who can run the floor, and we need to use that to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics outhustled the Sixers in every aspect of the game,
especially on the boards. Seattle held a 27-18 rebounding advantage
at halftime. The team's defense also stymied Philadelphia, which
shot just 37 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that we're not good enough to just show up
and overpower people,'' Schrempf said. ``Our style is to scrap.
That's how we've always played. We've always played with the
attitude that we're the underdog, but we haven't being doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf chipped in 17 points and 10 rebounds. Olden Polynice
also grabbed 10 boards.
</P>
<P>
   Payton won his battle with Sixers guard and NBA scoring leader
Allen Iverson, who finished with 14 points on 4-for-13 shooting.
Iverson left the game late in the third quarter after suffering a
cut on his lower lip. He received several stitches, and did not
return after missing all five shots he took in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Hersey Hawkins mostly guarded Iverson, whom the Sixers run most
of their offense through. The Sonics also occasionally
double-teamed Iverson, who had four turnovers and one assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he caught the ball, we tried to make a passer out of
him,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, meanwhile, collected eight assists and six rebounds to
go with his game-high point total.
</P>
<P>
   The game was decided in the third when Payton took control.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sonics leading 53-41 and 7:44 remaining in the period,
Payton scored 13 straight points in a six-minute span. Twice he
took Sixer guard Eric Snow to the basket and converted three-point
plays.
</P>
<P>
   His last field goal in the third was a 3-pointer that put the
Sonics ahead 64-46. Seattle took a 20-point lead into the fourth
quarter, which was garbage time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
