</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW UCLA CAN SAY IT HAS BEEN THERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Another school with a storied men's basketball
program showed the UCLA women it could be done. Forty minutes
before the 15th-ranked Bruins met third-ranked Louisiana Tech in
the NCAA Tournament West Regional final on Monday night, Duke upset
three-time defending champion Tennessee in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Bruins be the Dukes of hazard in the Lady Techsters'
path to the Final Four?
</P>
<P>
   It sure looked like UCLA had copied Duke's blue(devil)-print for
success when it bolted to a 10-point lead after 13 minutes at the
Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Bruins had the inspiration. But that and pounds of
perspiration were no match for the sophistication that comes with
having been down this road before. In the end there simply was no
staving off the expiration of UCLA's finest season in two decades.
UCLA succumbed 88-62 in front of a partisan crowd of 5,302 that did
all it could from the opening tip to breathe life into the UCLA
players.
</P>
<P>
   Proving attendance numbers have no bearing on noise levels,
Bruins fans were louder than a lot of those 40,000-plus crowds were
at the Coliseum next door on Saturdays this past fall. They were a
formidable sixth man, though on this night what the Bruins really
could have used was an Amanda Wilson clone.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-0 forward was a big reason the Lady Techsters were able to
crash the boards and the Bruins' party. One of three senior
starters, Wilson finished with 23 points and 12 rebounds. In all,
the Lady Techsters grabbed 22 of the 35 rebounds at UCLA's end,
which placed the Bruins in double jeopardy. Not only was UCLA
denied second-chance baskets, Louisiana Tech was able to ignite its
patented fast break.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Lady Techsters missed the first shot, no matter; they
pulled down 27 offensive boards, giving them plenty of second and
third and even fourth chances. Their overall rebounding goes a long
way toward explaining the considerable discrepancy in shots.
Louisiana Tech took 82 to UCLA's 55.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were making their first appearance in the NCAA's
Elite Eight. Louisiana Tech, as UCLA coach Kathy Olivier was quick
to point out ``has been in this position so many times and it
showed.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this was Louisiana Tech's 13th NCAA Tournament game in
three years. There's not a play Olivier could diagram to defend
against that kind of experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Techsters, on the strength of an 11-0 run, wrested the
lead from the Bruins with 2:29 to play in the first half. UCLA
would lead only once after that, in the 23rd minute when LaCresha
Flannigan stole the ball and converted a layup, as the Lady
Techsters roared to their 10th NCAA Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (26-8) will get there one day, maybe even as soon as
next year. All the principals will be back in 2000, with the
possible exception of fourth-year junior point guard Erica Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   If she was indeed playing her final game as a collegian, Gomez
bowed out with a bravura performance, gamely contributing 20
minutes and a team-high ( &UR; !ital! &LR; egads) three assists (the Bruins
only had eight) on a gimpy right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Greco, one year removed from stardom at Crescenta
Valley High, ran the team when Gomez couldn't and fell victim _ as
so many more veteran guards have before her _ to the Lady
Techsters' pressure, which they applied like a tourniquet.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind working the ball inside to take advantage of their
height advantage; the Bruins' backcourt had all they could handle
just holding onto the ball. Greco had four of UCLA's 24 turnovers.
Marie Philman turned the ball over six times, mostly because the
Lady Techsters jumped on her passes as though the passes were meant
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just very quick and aggressive,'' a glum Oliver
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   All is not lost for UCLA. There's no shame in failing as long as
you're able to learn something from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the experience of playing Louisiana Tech, who has
been in this situation, was great for us,'' Olivier said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on this first day of finals week for the Bruins, junior
Maylana Martin admitted to learning a couple of valuable lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew their quickness going in. We just have to be a little
smarter (and) do more ball faking to get them out of position ,''
said Martin, who played most of the second half with three fouls.
``In a big game like this you can't afford to have mental lapses
because (the other team) will capitalize on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The task ahead of UCLA is to capitalize on one super season.
There's nothing we saw Monday that suggested the Bruins won't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
