<HEADER>
A0579 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN     03-23 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA CAN'T TAKE BIG LEAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Duke did it earlier Monday night, upsetting a
top-seeded team. So why couldn't UCLA duplicate the feat?
</P>
<P>
   Because Louisiana Tech wouldn't let the Bruins get a board in
edgewise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a size disadvantage, the top-seeded Lady Techsters
nonetheless used their speed and leaping ability to control the
tempo and take an 88-62 victory in the NCAA West Regional women's
final before 5,302 at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech (30-2), winner of 22 in a row, now heads to its
10th Final Four in 18 years, beginning Friday in San Jose. It will
meet Purdue, the last team to beat the Lady Techsters.
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded UCLA, which had never reached the regional final
until this season, had its five-game win streak ended and finished
26-8.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons the Lady Techsters were ranked third for much
of the season: an unyielding pressure defense and athleticism to
make up for their deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, athleticism led to 13 steals and a lot of
rebounds. Tech thoroughly controlled the boards, often getting
second, third or even fourth attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was their leaping ability, and we didn't do a good job
blocking out,'' UCLA forward Maylana Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Just like UCLA held the board advantage in Saturday's semifinal
win over Colorado State, the Bruins found themselves on the short
end of a 49-30 rebounding margin. That included a 27-13 difference
on the offensive glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were good on the boards,'' UCLA coach Kathy
Olivier said, ``but they did a number on the offensive boards. We
had to stop them, but they were very quick and aggressive. They
took it to us on the second and third attempts.''
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with the pressure defense, and it's easy to see how
Tech scored 11 in a row in the first half to turn a 28-18 deficit _
UCLA's largest lead of the game _ into a 29-28 lead it would
relinquish only once.
</P>
<P>
   Tech broke the game open with a 9-0 run in 1:32, and then poured
it on with a 31-12 run over the game's final 8:53.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Lady Techsters attempted 27 more shots and made 17
more field goals than the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Amanda Wilson scored 23 points and had 12
rebounds in being named the West Regionals' most outstanding
player. She was followed closely by senior forward Monica Maxwell
with 22 points and 13 rebounds. She, too, made the all-tournament
team.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of emotional lifts from Erica Gomez playing or
Michelle Greco starting could counter that.
</P>
<P>
   Greco started for Gomez, who had sprained her ankle, and had her
supporters. One brought a ``Greco 3:16'' sign. Another had one that
read ``Yo Quiero Greco.''
</P>
<P>
   And Greco didn't disappoint, scoring on two driving layups early
to give the Bruins a 10-6 lead. She played 35 minutes and finished
with six points, two assists and four turnovers in being named to
the all-tournament team.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez came in with 14:12 to play in the half to a standing
ovation. She alternated at the point with Greco and contributed six
points on free throws, three assists and two steals.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez appeared in pregame warmups with her ankle taped and in an
air cast. She was given the OK to play after X-rays Sunday revealed
no breaks. Gomez iced her ankle every two hours and followed that
with electrical stimulation, massage, elevation and a range of
motion exercises.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA used its height advantage early. Led by all-tournament
player Martin's eight points, the Bruins took a 28-18 lead with
7:25 to play. Martin finished with a team-best 16 points, but all
eight of her second-half points came in the final 1:21.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes:Although there were some initial fears about slow
ticket sales back in January, USC officials considered hosting the
regionals to be an overall success.
</P>
<P>
   The first session on Saturday drew more than 4,000 to the Sports
Arena and Monday night's final between UCLA and Louisiana Tech drew
5,302.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the USC women's team will play all of its home games
at the Sports Arena, instead of the on-campus Lyon Center, which
seats about 1,200.
</P>
<P>
   The change in venue was requested by USC coach Chris Gobrecht,
who is trying to raise the profile of the women's basketball
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
