 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2529 - March 22, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2529 -- March 22, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. LEVI'S BLUES For decades, Levi's jeans have been cool. In the
1950s they were associated with James Dean, Marlon Brando and
teenage rebellion. In the Vietnam War era, they were a symbol of
the rock-and-roll generation. But today's trendy teenagers wouldn't
be caught dead in tight-fitting Levi's jeans. Baggy pants are in,
and Levi's missed the boat. Now it's trying to climb back aboard
with a new line and a new marketing strategy. By Hal Espen. From
The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (4,000 words) + edited
article available. 2. AN ADOPTION TRAGEDY When Martin and Phyllis
Juman adopted Michael in 1965, the adoption agency concealed from
them the fact that both his parents had serious mental illnesses.
In fact, as they later learned, his mother was a schizophrenic who
had undergone a lobotomy. When Michael too became schizophrenic and
learned the truth about his biological parents, he urged his
adoptive parents to sue the agency - a suit that is still alive and
raising provocative questions, though Michael himself has died. By
Lisa Belkin. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (6,600
words) + edited article available. 3. THE SALON MAKEOVER In David
Talbot's Web dream, his tweedy 'zine' is a full-service scandal
sheet for the global village. Launched in 1995 as an online
literary club, Salon still has at its core book reviews, political
and cultural commentary from writers like Garrison Keillor and
Camille Paglia, candid articles about sex, and a reader's feedback
forum called ``Table Talk.'' It has added sections on academia,
parenting, travel, personal finance and technology. While its
diversity has built Salon's audience, the most dramatic spikes in
readership have come when the site posts a big scoop. Talbot wants
to make Salon the leading brand for Web journalism. By Warren St.
John. From WIRED magazine. (N/A Japan) 4. FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE
(N/A France and Spain. Embargo 19h00 GMT March 24.)
</P>
<P>
   A. FREED BY THE POWER OF THOUGHT Patients with whole-body
paralysis could soon be able to communicate by the power of thought
alone. A word-processing system, driven by brain waves, can be used
by patients unable to move a single muscle. By Henry Gee. 400
words. B. BEETLES SNIFF OUT FOREST FIRES A species of beetle could
sniff out forest fires and even help protect storehouses and public
buildings from fire. By Henry Gee. 400 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. MOSAIC OF A MAMMAL The exquisitely preserved mouse-sized
skeleton of a fossil mammal from China sheds light on the earliest
history of all modern mammals - the group that includes all
warm-blooded, hairy animals from cats to kangaroos, and, of course,
ourselves. By Henry Gee. 400 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
SWIMMING MILES WITHOUT MOVING AN INCH Mini swimming pools or
'flumes' are now the rage in at-home fitness. Currents keep the
swimmer in place, like the tread on a treadmill. Flumes are also
playing an increasingly important role in training world class
athletes (their performance can be closely monitored in the tanks.)
By Alex Frankel. From The New York Times Science Times. 580 words +
photo
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
DOCTORS DISCOVER THE MAGIC OF MAGGOTS With concerns about germs
developing resistance to antibiotic drugs, many physicians are
thinking twice before they prescribe antibiotics for some
conditions. Now one British doctor is recommending a prescription
of maggots (they destroy the bacteria in wounds.) By Suzanne Leigh.
From Medical Tribune News Service. 500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM PROSPECT MAGAZINE A. HAVING SOME OF IT Pamela Meadows welcomes
an accessible overview of women and work, but is not convinced by
its gloomy picture of a world of workless men and exploited women.
Pamela Meadows reviews 'Having None Of It : Women, Men and the
Future of Work,' by Suzanne Franks. 1,800 words. (N/A U.K.) B.
CRISIS, WHAT CRISIS? The Asian crisis has not brought down global
capitalism. Most of the affected countries are now recovering
strongly and some have more liberal regimes. But while the world's
attention has been diverted eastwards, western corporations have
been quietly rewriting the rules of global trade. By Gerald Segal.
From Prospect magazine. 3,000 words. (N/A U.K.) Please fax to Paris
