<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHGORE-POLL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 POLL SHOWS BUSH, GORE TIED IN STATE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Vice President Al Gore, who has made 53 trips
to California, still comes in a close second to Texas Governor
George W. Bush in a head-to-head matchup for the 2000 presidential
race in California, according to a new Field Poll.
<P>
   Were the presidential election to be held today in the nation's
most populous state, a Bush-Gore race would end in a statistical
tie. Bush would get 48 percent of the vote and Gore 46 percent _ a
difference smaller than the margin of error _ with 6 percent
undecided, the poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   And both Gore on the Democratic side and Bush on the Republican
side hold dramatic leads over their closest party rivals, former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley and Elizabeth Dole respectively, the
poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is running 10 to 12 points behind in most of the national
polls, so relatively speaking, he's doing better in California than
nationally,'' said Mark DiCamillo, director of the Field Poll.
``The bad news (for Gore) is, he's not ahead of Bush. Were the
election held today, it would be a very tight election.''
</P>
<P>
   With a year to go before the California 2000 presidential
primary, 37 percent of Republican voters polled say Bush is their
first choice for a party candidate. That's nearly twice the support
of Dole (19 percent) and more than rest of the pack of ``second
tier'' GOP candidates combined.
</P>
<P>
   But next year's March 7 presidential primary will be the state's
first under the ``open primary'' system, which allows voters, no
matter how they are registered, to choose candidates from any
party. Both Democratic and Republican leaders are trying to push
legislation to modify that law _ in one case, involving counting
ballots two different ways, and in another case, through a separate
count of presidential votes restricted to party lines.
</P>
<P>
   In an ``open primary'' race, Bush still edges out Gore, 24 to 23
percent, with Dole coming in at 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a Republican should score more votes in the open primary
than Gore, it will be written as a weakness, and probably
justifiably so,'' said DiCamillo. ``It is seen as a mini-general
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The polling of presidential preferences in California a year
before voters make their choices serves as a ``benchmark'' for the
2000 race, and already points up some key factors that could help
shape the race, said DiCamillo.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Gore, a standing vice president, faces unusually strong
challenges from Bush and Dole, who are already well-known and
viewed positively by most state voters, DiCamillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, the criteria of early polls is that you have one
candidate who's very well known, and the rest not,'' said
DiCamillo. ``We're registering opinions about Bush and Dole that
are almost as high as we're getting for Gore. ... It's almost an
equal-footing comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Other findings of the Field Poll:
</P>
<P>
   -- Looking toward a Republican field in the 2000 presidential
primary, an equal number of state voters _ 48 percent _ say they
would be inclined to vote for either Bush or Dole. Specifically
among GOP voters, 79 percent are inclined to vote for Bush,
compared to 12 percent who are not; 65 percent say they're inclined
to vote for Dole, with nearly a quarter saying they would not.
</P>
<P>
   -- Columnist Pat Buchanan appears to have the highest negative
rating among Republicans voters. One quarter of Republicans say
they're inclined to vote for him, but a whopping 65 percent say
they would not _ and only 10 percent remain undecided on the
question. ``That's a tough row to hoe, even in his own party,''
said DiCamillo.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. _ while still an unknown to most
Republicans _ manages generally positive ratings among party
loyalists. Fully 35 percent of GOP voters say they would be
inclined to vote for him, compared to just 28 percent who would
not, with 37 percent still holding no opinion. ``That shows some
room for expansion,'' said DiCamillo. ``He needs to build
awareness, to introduce himself and convince people to vote for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On the Democratic ballot for the 2000 primary, Californians
are split (47-47) on whether or not they would be inclined to
support Gore, with 6 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   -- But among registered Democrats, fully 73 percent said they
would be inclined to support Gore, compared with 20 percent who
would not and 7 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The Field poll was conducted March 3-14 among a representative
sample of 718 registered voters in California. The margin of error
is plus or minus 3.8 percentage points among general voters, and
plus or minus 5.8 percent among the Democratic and Republican voter
samples.
</P>
</TEXT>
