<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oh, to be young again
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ When I was eight, I asked for a strapless
bathing suit. My mother's response? ``NO! Absolutely not. You're
too young.'' No big surprise there. That was her answer to
everything.
</P>
<P>
   The subject was dropped, for the time being, but by summer I was
back at it, begging for a ``big girl'' bathing suit. Mother
reminded me I was not a big girl and had nothing to hold up a
strapless bathing suit. ``It'll fall right off of you,'' she
warned. I moved on to plan B.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in an old photo album is a shot of me standing
ankle-deep in the surf on Jacksonville Beach, clinging to my
shapeless old silver bathing suit and looking seriously silly. In
an attempt to transform myself into a sultry bathing beauty, I had
untied the black ribbon that held up the front of my suit, the one
my mother had so carefully double-knotted around my neck that
morning before she let me out the door, slipped it under my arms
and retied it in the back. At the time I thought myself stunning.
Truth is, I looked like a Christmas tree ornament with legs.
</P>
<P>
   And guess where the armholes hit?
</P>
<P>
   When I was 11, I had a fit for a see-through blouse and a
flesh-colored slip with skinny straps like Ginger Rogers was
wearing in her latest movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous,'' my mother said as she handed me the garbage to
take out. ``You're too young.''
</P>
<P>
   When I was 12, I asked if I could shave my legs. ``Cer-tain-ly
(when she was really annoyed she pronounced every syllable) NOT!
What nonsense. You're too young to grow a beard.'' I thought she
meant on my chin and don't think I didn't sweat it when I finally
sneaked around and shaved. Daily, I checked my chin in the bathroom
mirror for telltale signs of a 5 o'clock shadow.
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday afternoon over a particularly satisfying dinner of
fried chicken with rice and gravy, I began to take special notice
of our guest, Mrs. Ussery's chin. Before Mother could stuff a
biscuit in my mouth, I managed to blurt out the question: ``Mrs.
Ussery, did you shave your legs when you were too young?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ussery looked puzzled, Daddy dropped a drumstick in his
lap, and my mother decided I?d had enough to eat and ordered me
outside. Later, she explained that Mrs. Ussery's mustache and chin
whiskers were a hormone problem, not a shaving one. I'd never heard
of a hormone before so I asked what one was. Mother explained that
young ladies my age didn't have any so I wasn't to worry about it.
I asked when I could have some and she said we'd discuss it when I
was older.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 14, I wanted a strapless evening dress with sequins.
Mother asked where I thought I might be going to wear such a dress.
Nowhere, I confessed, but I thought it would be a good thing to
have on hand. She reminded me I still had no chest. I asked for a
pair of falsies for Christmas. Ho! Ho! HO!
</P>
<P>
   For my 16th birthday, I wanted a glass of wine with my birthday
dinner. Mother said the only wine that would cross my lips as long
as I lived in her house would be at communion. I reminded her the
Baptists used grape juice. She reminded me I was too young.
</P>
<P>
   And now life seems to have come full cycle. See-through blouses
are back and I don't even want one. Shaving my legs stopped being
fun the day after I'd started doing it, and over the weekend I went
shopping for a bathing suit. I've yet to figure out how that old
bag staring back at me in the three-way mirror managed to sneak
into my dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Life is all backwards. If my mother were still around, I'd
probably be bugging her for a new body and she'd still be giving me
the same old answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait until you're older.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail to: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
