<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: OP-ED, OPINION PAGE EDITORS
 &HT;    Youth should draw strength from family's past
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Tex. _ A seventh-grade homework assignment has
provided some surprising insight: For a glimpse of your kid's
future, look at his past.
</P>
<P>
   As I helped my son, Joaquin, illustrate his family tree for a
lesson, I enjoyed pointing to different branches of that tree
occupied by the ancestors for whom he is named. The youngest of our
children, he was blessed with three given names, although he
sometimes claims it is a burden.
</P>
<P>
   His first name is Neff, for his Uncle Neff and paternal
grandfather Pat Neff Walker, who in turn was named for the late
Texas governor and Baylor University president. My father-in-law
Pat, a poor East Texas boy who had to borrow his brother's boots to
travel to the Army enlistment post, worked his way through college
and then law school after serving in World War II. His second name,
Joaquin, after his maternal great-grandfather who came to Texas and
dreamed of an education for my mom and her sisters then died before
he
</P>
<P>
   could provide it. His third name is Eusebio, after his maternal
grandfather, my dad, who fulfilled those dreams, albeit a
generation later.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to illustrating his family tree, Joaquin had been
asked to write down family stories or anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   So I recounted how Joaquin's paternal great-great-grandfather,
Moses Jepson, sailed from Denmark to the United States with his two
brothers and wound up in Chicago in 1871, right at the time of the
Great Chicago Fire. In the terror and confusion of that disaster,
the trio, frightened and unable to speak much English, became
separated, and Moses never saw his brothers again.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime East Texans might remember his son, H.O. Jepson, who
operated the Leverett's Chapel grocery store for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin's maternal great grandfather, A.B. Pecina, was among the
myriad laborers who helped build Carswell Air Force Base in Fort
Worth. As a young man, he traveled throughout Central and South
America and many years later, entertained his young granddaughter
with stories of his travels, spiced with descriptions of exotic
jungle snakes and the mermaids who dwelt in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   I recounted much more family lore during that homework lesson
about those who labored so their children could go to school, built
successful businesses and struggled for the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as I reviewed the session, I realized I probably came
away with more than I dispensed.
</P>
<P>
   Moms spend a lot of time worrying about the world's dangers that
await their children. Each day, those dangers seem to become more
numerous and more severe. But after contemplating my son's
heritage, the good folks from which he comes, I realized he is
naturally well-armed to face whatever comes his way. His
inheritance includes determination, courage, a sense of civic
responsibility, the will to survive and the will to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   And one other thing.
</P>
<P>
   Family values. Not in the political sense in which that phrase
has been cheapened and bandied about, but in the sense of valuing
family.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box 1792, Longview, TX 75606. E-mail:
awalker(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
