<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOTRODS-MUSIC24-COX     03-23 1928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTRODS-MUSIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot-rod kings cruise the sweet and low road
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For the ``Hot Rod Gang of Austin, Texas,'' the
question is such a no-brainer it answers itself. Why would a grown
man drive a custom car? Just look at one of these rolling, revving
sculptures on wheels, these open-highway declarations of
independence, these emblems of the teen-age exhilaration of rock
'n' roll, with the sensuous curves that conjure the lusts of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Take a spin riding shotgun in Jimmie Vaughan's seductively
lavender '51 Chevy Fleetline _ the car that was built the same year
he was born _ so lovingly restored and remade, its chrome gleaming
and its interior immaculate. Or put yourself behind the low-riding
wheel of Mike Young's award-winning '60 Impala ``Exotica,''
designed by Jimmie and customized by Gary Howard, a car of such
classic lines and retro beauty that it might as well be the Mona
Lisa of the car-show circuit. Or for a real ride on the wild side,
hop into Steve Wertheimer's 1930 Model A roadster, where the door
has ``The Continental Kid'' emblazoned in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Then just look at the way everyone else is looking at you. But
take it in stride. Exhibitionism is not the point. Style is. Cool
is. It wouldn't be cool to need to be the center of attention, but
style recognizes that such stares come with the territory. It's a
little like being in love with a woman whose beauty invariably
attracts attention; if you act as if you don't deserve to be seen
with her, you don't.
</P>
<P>
   After an afternoon on the road with the Hot Rod Gang, when you
slink back to your anonymously functional, economy-minded compact
box _ maybe a Mazda or a Honda or a Ford, maybe forest green or
sandy beige, as if there's really any difference _ you are no
longer asking yourself why a grown man drives a custom car.
</P>
<P>
   You are asking yourself why anyone drives anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about having a dream and doing it,'' said Vaughan, who is
as renowned in car circles for the exquisite taste of his custom
designs as he is in music circles for the understated flash of his
bluesy guitar. ``To me, it all goes together, it's just the whole
thing about being American. Young's car over there could be an old
Willie Nelson song or a Thelonious Monk tune. It's art. When I'm
driving, everything else just goes away, problems don't seem to
matter so much. Same with playing music.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcing the all-American connection between cars and guitars
is Rhino Records' new box-set release of the four-disc ``Hot Rods &AMP;
Custom Classics: Cruisin' Songs &AMP; Highway Hits.'' The 88-song
selection extends from Chuck Berry's ``Maybellene'' to Golden
Earring's ``Radar Love,'' from Dave Dudley's ``Six Days on the
Road'' to Duane Eddy's ``Forty Miles of Bad Road'' to Robert
Mitchum's ``Ballad of Thunder Road.''
</P>
<P>
   It features an invitation from TV's Dinah Shore to ``See the
U.S.A. in your Chevrolet'' and a warning from James Dean about the
dangers of drag racing. Packaged to resemble a model-car kit, the
set comes complete with fuzzy dice for the rear-view mirror, a
decal sheet and a 64-page booklet explaining and celebrating
hot-rod culture. And it has the stamp of Austin all over it, from
its cover illustration of Young's ``Exotica'' to its dedication to
Vaughan, Wertheimer and Young, dubbed the Hot Rod Gang of Austin,
Texas, for keeping the classic custom spirit alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are my inspiration,'' said James Austin, the Los
Angeles-based custom nut and Rhino executive who produced and
compiled the ``Hot Rods'' package. ``Because of Jimmie, I got a
whole new awareness of what really makes a car beautiful. Mike
Young's `Exotica' is absolutely the most beautiful car that has
ever hit the ground, and Jimmie designed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go to him for design advice, and he would say, `James, I
go for traditional, traditional, traditional. Keep it simple, you
can't go wrong.' Same with his music. Each note is played with such
feeling. With his cars, his designs may seem simple on the surface,
but look closely and there's a whole lot going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there is plenty of overlap between hot rods and custom
cars, and the terms are occasionally used interchangeably, the
emphasis of the hot rod is on the go, where the custom is more
concerned with show. In each case, the vehicle in question is a
vintage automobile that typically rides lower, looks sharper,
sounds louder and goes faster than your standard street-issue car.
Customizing takes the essence of cool from the past and makes it
even cooler. Or hotter.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the release of Rhino's box set, Wertheimer's
Continental Club hosted an informal hot-rod show (cars outside,
music inside) last week. That evening, Vaughan marked his 48th
birthday with his South by Southwest midnight showcase at the
Austin Music Hall. Though Vaughan had never attempted to turn his
hobby into his musical image, the whole spirit of car culture is as
integral to his artistry as it is to the hubcap, tailfin and Elvis
decor of Young's Chuy's restaurants (he also owns Shady Grove and
the Hula Hut) or the timewarped allure of Wertheimer's Continental
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was born 20 years too late,'' said the
40-year-old Wertheimer. ``I missed that whole period and I won't
let go of it. It's plainly very present here in the club and the
kind of music we book here and the people that hang out here, and
the cars kind of go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of one to 10, I'd say my obsession is probably an
11,'' he continued. ``It's definitely my biggest passion, and it's
the reason I work so hard at the club, so I can do the car deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater love hath no man than these three for their cars. The
obsession begins in boyhood, when most car fanatics start designing
their dream cars on paper. From there, they progress to models, to
slot cars, to magazines devoted to the hot-rod world. Getting their
own rod is the ultimate emancipation from parental control, the
rite of gearhead passage. Some guys _ let's face it, this is a
testosterone-driven obsession, though attracting female attention
is invariably an early impetus _ pour as much as a quarter of a
million dollars into a single vehicle, though the average
investment isn't appreciably more than one might spend on a new
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like guys who have a boat, a bottomless pit, but you can
do it less expensively,'' said Vaughan. ``It is less expensive to
do what I do with some of my cars than it is to buy a new Lexus.
Any four-door sedan that looks just like the rest of them costs 30
or 40 grand, and you can have a really nice car for less than 10
grand if you watch what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a money thing; it's making that car look cool,'' said
Young. ``I've got a nice BMW. I park that downtown, and it's a car.
I park my '60 Caddy down there, and there's a crowd of people
around it. When Jimmie or Steve drive one of their cars, people
freak out over them. If you can get a car that's this cool for the
same money, why would anybody buy a used Toyota? You can buy a
Ferrari for $150,000 or whatever, and people will say it's a nice
car, but nobody's going to go nuts over it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time one arrives at the middle age of this particular
generation of Austin hot-rodders, cruising for chicks takes a back
seat to male bonding. Before Vaughan convinced Young to customize
his Impala into the ``Exotica,'' the two were casual acquaintances.
Now they frequently hit the road together, along with Wertheimer,
hiring a trailer to haul their cars to California for an annual
excursion of cruising up the coast and hitting the car shows, like
last month's Grand National Roadster Show at San Francisco's Cow
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always admired hot rods and custom cars, but I never
thought I could do that,'' said Young, whose ``Exotica'' was the
rage of the Grand National when he debuted it there in 1995. ``And
Jimmie, in his way, he's the smoothest cat in town, said, `You
know, you could make that car look really cool. All you have to do
is lower that thing a little bit, and nose it and deck it and paint
it, and you'd have a really cool car. And I'd have somebody to
drive around with.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmie just has such an eye for design, it's amazing,''
continued Young, who saw Vaughan's designs take metal-and-chrome
shape in the custom shop of Gary Howard in Weir. To hear Young tell
it, Howard is the Michelangelo of the retro roadster: ``You look at
Gary and the way he thinks and the way he works with a car, he's as
much an artist as any sculptor in the world. He has the temperament
of an artist, and the taste and the skill and the eye, and the
obsession to make the car perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is just being creative,'' said Vaughan. ``You take
a car and you change it, make it more pleasing, smoother, lower.
The fun part is driving down the street, preferably with a couple
of other guys driving 'em too. You're looking out the window and
putting on a show for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what's the deal with lowering the cars so their chassis are
closer to the ground?
</P>
<P>
   ``It just looks so much longer and nastier,'' said Young. ``When
you look at a car that has been lowered just right, it looks so
sleek and efficient, like a cat in the wild, stalking prey, ready
to pounce.''
</P>
<P>
   And louder?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tastefully loud, a really nice, throaty sound,'' said
Wertheimer. ``When we customize most of these cars, the first thing
we do is get a new exhaust system put on, to get 'em as loud as we
possibly can. I remember one night I got pulled over in the
warehouse district, and the officer said, `I'm thinking of giving
you a ticket for exhibitionist speed.' I explained that maybe it
sounded like it was going faster than it was.''
</P>
<P>
   To drive a custom is to live a fantasy, to inhabit a world that
has not been homogenized into strip malls and sports utility
vehicles. On most Saturday nights at the Whataburger off Interstate
35 in Round Rock, it becomes a mass fantasy, as hundreds of
hot-rodders and muscle-car connoisseurs converge in the parking lot
from as far away as Waco and San Marcos. Except for such oases, the
hot-rodder is a driver for whom the time is out of joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I get into one of those cars and close my eyes,
it's 1955,'' says Wertheimer. ``I have no idea what I look like
when I'm going down the street, but I feel like I'm 17 years old. I
keep wishing there were more drive-ins here in town where we could
cruise and do what they used to do, and that every night when you
pulled up to the (Continental) club, all you'd see would be hot
cars. Because you know that's how South Congress used to look. The
Whataburger in Round Rock isn't exactly what I'm looking for, but
that's all there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, the car will spark a fantasy flare-up when
it's least expected. Take Young's experience when he was recently
cruising in his Caddy, and found himself at a stoplight next to a
woman in her 70s driving a Buick.
</P>
<P>
   She looked over and said, ``Nice car.'' He said, ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``Does it go fast?'' He said, ``Pretty fast.''
</P>
<P>
   When the light turned green, she floored it, leaving Young in
the dust, laughing in her rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``She smoked me!'' said Young, still incredulous days later.
``In a Buick! Seventy years old, and she still remembered how it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Don McLeese writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
