<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTRODS-MUSIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot-rod kings cruise the sweet and low road
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For the ``Hot Rod Gang of Austin, Texas,'' the
question is such a no-brainer it answers itself. Why would a grown
man drive a custom car? Just look at one of these rolling, revving
sculptures on wheels, these open-highway declarations of
independence, these emblems of the teen-age exhilaration of rock
'n' roll, with the sensuous curves that conjure the lusts of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Take a spin riding shotgun in Jimmie Vaughan's seductively
lavender '51 Chevy Fleetline _ the car that was built the same year
he was born _ so lovingly restored and remade, its chrome gleaming
and its interior immaculate. Or put yourself behind the low-riding
wheel of Mike Young's award-winning '60 Impala ``Exotica,''
designed by Jimmie and customized by Gary Howard, a car of such
classic lines and retro beauty that it might as well be the Mona
Lisa of the car-show circuit. Or for a real ride on the wild side,
hop into Steve Wertheimer's 1930 Model A roadster, where the door
has ``The Continental Kid'' emblazoned in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Then just look at the way everyone else is looking at you. But
take it in stride. Exhibitionism is not the point. Style is. Cool
is. It wouldn't be cool to need to be the center of attention, but
style recognizes that such stares come with the territory. It's a
little like being in love with a woman whose beauty invariably
attracts attention; if you act as if you don't deserve to be seen
with her, you don't.
</P>
<P>
   After an afternoon on the road with the Hot Rod Gang, when you
slink back to your anonymously functional, economy-minded compact
box _ maybe a Mazda or a Honda or a Ford, maybe forest green or
sandy beige, as if there's really any difference _ you are no
longer asking yourself why a grown man drives a custom car.
</P>
<P>
   You are asking yourself why anyone drives anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about having a dream and doing it,'' said Vaughan, who is
as renowned in car circles for the exquisite taste of his custom
designs as he is in music circles for the understated flash of his
bluesy guitar. ``To me, it all goes together, it's just the whole
thing about being American. Young's car over there could be an old
Willie Nelson song or a Thelonious Monk tune. It's art. When I'm
driving, everything else just goes away, problems don't seem to
matter so much. Same with playing music.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcing the all-American connection between cars and guitars
