<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS24-COX     03-23 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American Red Cross encourages companies to buy life-saving
equipment
 &HT;    (EDS: This is a compilation of health stories which moved to the
wires this week.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new, easy-to-use device that jump-starts a stopped
heart could save up to 100,000 lives a year, if it goes into
widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   The device is an Automated External Defibrillator, a simplified
version of the defibrillators used by medical professionals on
people suffering cardiac arrest. The device delivers a powerful
electric shock to the heart, forcing it to resume beating.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross is recruiting companies across the nation
to buy defibrillators and train employees in their use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the workplace that many of these (cardiac arrest)
incidents happen,'' Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   The device literally talks users through the steps of restarting
a person's stopped heart. ``Apply pads,'' the device says. ``Plug
in connector.'' It checks for a heartbeat; if none is detected, the
device tells the user to shock the victim by pressing a flashing
button.
</P>
<P>
   The defibrillator, which was developed by Heartstream, a
division of Hewlett Packard, costs about $3,500 per unit, said
David Todd of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross eventually will expand its program to include
shopping malls and stadiums, where emergency response tends to be
slower because of difficult access, Bullock said
</P>
<P>
   Self-assessment tests on Internet helpful but limited
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ever felt younger _ or older _ than your actual age in
years? The Internet offers a quick and simple way to find out
whether you may be right: Online self-tests assess everything from
your medical history to how fast you drive, then determine your
overall health outlook and compute the age you resemble, compared
to the average American.
</P>
<P>
   These health risk assessments provide users with a good general
overview of their health status, as well as an indication of how it
could be improved.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Internet as a whole, these self-tests shouldn't be
taken as gospel. Most health assessment Web sites have a disclaimer
reminding users that the questionnaires aren't diagnostic tools,
and that people should seek a doctor's advice for medical
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, (health assessment tests) are helpful in making
people aware of possible problems they may have,'' said Dr. Kelleen
Fitzgerald, an internist and clinical instructor at Emory
University . ``They should almost always be followed up with a talk
with your physician, so the physician can help the patient put it
in context.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald pointed out that most risk factors are broad
generalizations based on statistics from large medical studies, and
may not be applicable to each individual. Some health risk tests
deliberately err on the side of caution, to avoid mistakenly
inspiring confidence. The risk assessment tests offered by the
American Diabetes Association and the American Heart Association,
for example, each have fewer than 10 questions _ but they're enough
to send up a red flag if the answers merit it. Some sites include:
</P>
<P>
   The American Diabetes Association's Diabetes Risk Test:
http://www.diabetes.org/ada/risktest.asp
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association's quiz:
http://www.americanheart.org/risk/quiz.html
</P>
<P>
   HealthCentral (online health information service):
http://www.healthcentral.com
</P>
<P>
   Greenstone Healthcare Solutions (a detailed questionnaire/report
on risky behaviors, cholesterol and blood pressure):
http://www.youfirst.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
