<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0752 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-DOGS24-COX     03-23 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-DOGS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Dogs of War: Heroes, Best Friends, Sacrifices
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Thirty years past the blood and the
battles, middle-aged Vietnam veterans can talk about their war in a
calm, resigned voice. They're matter-of-fact even when showing you
faded photos of buddies who didn't come home.
</P>
<P>
   But ask them about the war dogs that saved their lives and you
see the hard emotion that time can't wear away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we did was nothing,'' says retired Army Maj. Paul
Morgan. ``What the dogs did was everything. The dogs had such
unconditional love. Suzie saved my butt several times. I can't
believe how totally devoted she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzie. Duchess. Jet. Crypto. Many were family pets, German
shepherds and Labrador retrievers, sent to war by patriotic owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saved lives and they gave us great confidence and
boldness,'' says Morgan, who lives in Jupiter, Fla. and has written
a book, K-9 Soldiers _ Vietnam and After, due out in April.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who served two Vietnam tours, estimates that the
58,000-plus U.S. soldiers killed would have been ``well over 75,000
without the dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   There were about 10,000 dog handlers and more than 4,000 dogs
used in Vietnam from 1966 to '75. Dogs have been used by the
military since the Civil War. But the animals proved invaluable in
Vietnam because it was a guerrilla jungle war. The enemy, capable
of living and fighting from underground, had a huge home-field
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   German shepherds were used as sentries and to scout ahead of
U.S. troops. Labs proved exceptional for tracking, even able to
warn of enemy soldiers underwater, breathing through hollow bamboo
poles.
</P>
<P>
   Both breeds could take the heat and humidity and, unlike
bloodhounds, could be taught not to bark. The dogs used human scent
to warn of danger and could even hear wind pass over a booby trap
trip wire as thin as a human hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I pulled point as much as I did without a dog, I wouldn't
be here talking about it,'' says Bob Azzaro. ``I never walked into
an ambush. I always had enough warning because of Duchess.''
</P>
<P>
   Azzaro, a West Palm Beach auto mechanic, was one of the first 28
dog handlers trained and sent to Vietnam. He arrived in 1966 with
his German shepherd scout dog, Duchess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scout dogs were a pre-warning device,'' says Morris Huggins,
``and you knocked on wood every time you went on a mission that
everything worked out right. The dog worked, you worked, the
training worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, 51, owns a Delray Beach construction business. As a
sergeant, his five-man tracking unit always had a scout or tracking
dog walking point about 50 yards ahead of the unit to warn of
ambush or booby traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Booby traps are meant to maim and injure because for every one
man injured it takes five to six men to take care of him,''
explains Huggins. ``And the psychology of a booby trap is to
demoralize you. One minute you're walking along and you're fine,
and the next minute half your body's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scout dogs served a purpose psychologically, especially
with the dog handler,'' he continues. ``The dog gives you an
advantage only to the extent that if he picks up on something, he
can give you that split second as a handler to do whatever you've
got to do to cover your ass and get down, get cover, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   War dogs suffered infections and combat fatigue just like the
men they protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have dogs go bad mentally,'' says Huggins. ``He'd become
a biter, he'd lose his cool. You'd either turn him into a blood
donor for other dogs or you'd destroy him. Those are the only two
choices you had.''
</P>
<P>
   Azzaro saw a change in Duchess after the team graduated from 12
weeks of training at Fort Benning, Ga., in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we arrived in-country she was docile,'' he recalls, ``but
her personality changed. She got into it. When she saw me going for
that harness, for her, it was a game. They're in it for the praise.
She picked up on life or death real fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The war dogs were so effective that the Viet Cong offered a kill
reward. ``The bounty was that either they came back with (the
dog's) tattooed ear or came back with one of our (dog handler's)
insignia patches,'' Huggins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could take out a dog and handler,'' says Morgan,
``they could bring the unit to a stop for days.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan and Huggins belong to the 1,000-member Vietnam Dog
Handlers Association started in 1994. The group was instrumental in
the making of War Dogs, America's Forgotten Heroes, a documentary
film that aired on the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The film couldn't have been made without the former dog
handlers, says Jeffrey Bennett, a dog breeder and founder and CEO
of Nature's Recipe pet food.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Bennett took up the war-dog cause after he saw
a four-minute clip of Vietnam handlers talking about their dogs.
But the U.S. military kept no war-dogs records before 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam Dog Handlers Association, based in San Diego, filled
in the blanks, Bennett says.
</P>
<P>
   After making the $1.5 million film with GRB Entertainment,
Bennett planned two national war-dog memorials. The first will be
dedicated on President's Day 2000 at Riverside National Cemetery
near Los Angeles. The second will be in Washington, D.C., by the
end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-minute documentary uncovered a shocking fact. When the
U.S. pulled out of Vietnam in April 1975, the dogs were left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without being gross or mortifying to people, they were treated
as surplus equipment,'' Bennett says.``We showed them (in the film)
pushing the helicopters off the aircraft carriers. The dogs were
the same thing, surplus equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing to me,'' continues Bennett, ``is that the
government can push out $10 million tanks, $10 million helicopters
like they're a dime a dozen, and then they take these living,
breathing creatures and give them to the South Vietnamese, who ate
them or euthanized them because it was too inconvenient to bring
them home.
</P>
<P>
   ``And any one of those handlers would have done just about
anything to bring them home,'' he concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Azzaro, 53, says a lot of post-traumatic stress syndrome
suffered by combat dog handlers comes because of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can't get over leaving that dog behind,'' he says of
Duchess.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgan, 62, who started a K-9 private security service when
he left the military, says that the U.S. abandoned more than dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea about the dogs,'' says Morgan, wounded and sent
home from Vietnam in 1970. ``But there were South Vietnamese people
that we said we'd never leave. We abandoned those people, our
allies. A black page in our history. The dogs were the last thing
we thought about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We soldiers are memorialized, we get parades, citations,''
says Morgan. ``But the dogs never got anything because they were
all dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, the war dogs are being remembered. By the
men whose lives they saved, and many more.
</P>
<P>
   Video copies of War Dogs, America's Forgotten Heroes, are
available at PetsMart stores with the purchase of Nature's Recipe
dog food.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
