   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WCW-GOLDBERG _ Sit-down with the biggest star of World
Championship Wrestling, Bill Goldberg. The former SEC
all-conference nose tackle for the University of Georgia and
Atlanta Falcon defensive lineman, would rather be a football
player. A stomach injury cut that career short. He'd rather be an
actor. But, lately, what he'd really rather be _ time permitting _
is a human being. We talk to him, and those in his out-of-the-ring
life about Goldberg as a person: an aspiring actor, suburban
dweller with girlfriend and roommate, semi-observant Jew, animal
lover and pulled-in-all-directions celebrity. (Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 56. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WCW-GOLDBERG-BIO _ Bio box on WCW star Bill Goldberg. (Scott,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-DOGS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Thirty years past the blood
and the battles, middle-aged Vietnam veterans can talk about their
war in a calm, resigned voice. They're matter-of-fact even when
showing you faded photos of buddies who didn't come home. But ask
them about the war dogs that saved their lives and you see the hard
emotion that time can't wear away. ``Whatever we did was nothing,''
says retired Army Maj. Paul Morgan. ``What the dogs did was
everything. The dogs had such unconditional love. Suzie saved my
butt several times. I can't believe how totally devoted she was.''
Suzie. Duchess. Jet. Crypto. Many were family pets, German
shepherds and Labrador retrievers, sent to war by patriotic owners.
``They saved lives and they gave us great confidence and
boldness,'' says Morgan, who lives in Jupiter, Fla. and has written
a book, K-9 Soldiers _ Vietnam and After, due out in April.
(Lomartire, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
