<HEADER>
A0758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK24-COX     03-23 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Transfer to Roth IRAs comes with big tax bite
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of diligent retirement savers are suffering from sticker
shock.
</P>
<P>
   They converted a traditional individual retirement account to a
Roth IRA last year, and it's just now soaking in that they have to
pay income tax on the money they transferred.
</P>
<P>
   The tax obligation was never a secret, and responsible advisers
always pointed it out. But for a lot of people, it was an
abstraction last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's concrete. ``People always knew there was going to be a
tax impact,'' said Roger W. Lusby III, a certified public
accountant with Frazier &AMP; Deeter in Atlanta. ``But now that they
have prepared their return and they're looking at line 68, with the
large amount due, they are in real shock.''
</P>
<P>
   An example will show how deep the tax bite can be. Suppose a
middle-income taxpayer, who will always be in the 28 percent income
tax bracket, transfers $50,000 to a Roth IRA in 1998. The tax bill
will be $14,000, although a one-time tax break allows the taxpayer
to recognize the income in four equal, annual installments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Roth IRAs are tremendously attractive. There are two
primary reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ Once you put your $2,000 a year into a Roth IRA, that seed
money and the money it earns will be free of income taxes when it
is properly withdrawn. With a traditional IRA, you will have to pay
taxes on your earnings, at ordinary income rates, when you retire
and start taking the money out.
</P>
<P>
   _ With a Roth IRA, you are not required to start taking the
money out after you turn 70 1/2. That can make the Roth IRA an
outstanding tool for estate planning. Lusby explained why: ``When
money in a traditional IRA passes along to your beneficiaries, it
is still subject to income tax. This is not the case with the Roth
IRA. Here, there might be estate taxes, but you and your kids would
never have to pay income taxes on the Roth IRA.''
</P>
<P>
   But the trade-off with the Roth IRA is the current tax
obligation. If you put $2,000 into a Roth IRA, you still have to
pay income taxes on it.
</P>
<P>
   If you transfer money from a traditional IRA to a Roth IRA, you
have to pay income taxes on the full amount you transfer. In our
hypothetical example of a $50,000 transfer, you decide to pay
$14,000 in income taxes now because you expect to reap a lot more
in investment and tax gains later.
</P>
<P>
   The deal usually makes economic sense only if you pay the tax
with dollars from some other resource, not with a portion of the
money you transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The sticker shock has arrived for those who took the goodies
months ago but didn't earmark some money to pay the tax obligation
now.
</P>
<P>
   What options do they have?
</P>
<P>
   One is to ``reconvert,'' meaning you can switch the money back
to a traditional IRA. You can direct your broker or mutual fund
company to make the switch. ``You'll still have to report the
conversion,'' Lusby said. ``But now it won't be taxable.''
</P>
<P>
   The other option is to stick with the Roth IRA and hunt down
some source to pay the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Lusby emphasized the impact of the one-time break on this tax
obligation. For transfers made in 1998 _ but not in 1999 or later _
the amount of the transfer can be reported over four years.
</P>
<P>
   For the $50,000 transfer, that means you report only $12,500 in
1998. The tax due right now is $3,500. You report the same income
amount for 1999 and the following two years. The tax would remain
the same unless your tax bracket changed. Use Form 8606 to report
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most situations, if people can afford to pay the tax
liability with other assets, then it probably is to their advantage
to leave the conversion alone and take advantage of the four-year
spread,'' Lusby advised.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
