A0759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRING-DRESSES24-COX     03-23 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-DRESSES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time to Spring for new clothes
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Choices, choices, choices.
</P>
<P>
   A cornucopia of colors and clothing combinations is cropping up
this spring, delighting fashion finders with new options and fresh
looks for work and play.
</P>
<P>
   This spring calls for a dressy-casual look _ outfits that, with
the right accessories and shoes, can serve for dressy functions
like weddings or a dinner but can also be dressed down for a casual
luncheon or shower.
</P>
<P>
   Bright pinks, racy purples, ocean blues and sunny yellows have
found their way back to the clothing aisles, replacing the dull
grays and muddy browns of winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people get so tired of the drab from winter. By
spring, they're ready for an uplift _ something that gives them
some feel-good and color to their wardrobe,'' said Rene Masiongale,
store manager of Leon's Cinderella. ``The bright colors make you
feel that much more feminine and gives you a little lift.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Masiongale said build on the basics. If you're a
pants person, white, black or even navy linen pants are always a
staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like having sugar or coffee in your cupboard, it's
something everyone should have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Keep a cute black, white or navy jacket in your closet _ whether
it be a short jacket, a vest, a longer tunic type.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really encourage people to stick to the whites, blacks,
navies, off whites _ whatever color they feel comfortable with _
and then just work around that _ add to it, layer to it,'' she
said. ``You can add any type of little shell, sweater underneath or
a bright color.''
</P>
<P>
   She also suggests keeping some type of casual-wear, a patterned
or solid-colored, lightweight pair of pants or a long skirt for an
afternoon tea, shopping or to the movies. Look for tops that match
a skirt and pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good, especially if people travel a lot and don't
want to pack a lot, you can take a top and mix and match it with
several bottoms and make it look completely different,'' Masiongale
said.
</P>
<P>
   Look for jackets you can wear by themselves during the day and
throw a shell or blouse underneath to dress up.
</P>
<P>
   Long sundresses for summer are great because they're lightweight
and fun to wear. Many come with a little jacket or sweater you can
wear if you're self-conscious about bare arms or chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Layering is an excellent idea,'' Masiongale said. ``If you're
cold inside, then you can walk outside and pull off a layer. It
also adds to the appearance of the outfit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hats are a good accessory to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of ladies think they can't wear hats, but they can,''
Masiongale said. ``Hats come in all different shapes and sizes. If
people are going on cruises or to an afternoon wedding, we really
encourage them to put on a hat. Have some fun. Don't make life any
more serious than it already is.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't overlook the importance of accessories _ a sleek handbag,
stylish jewelry and fashionable footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone can take a basic beige pants or suit they think is so
ugly, and throw a pretty scarf with it, a shell, jewelry, a hat,
anything like that and make all the difference in the world,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the blockbuster movie Titanic inspired loose-fitting,
flowing dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's more fitted and constructed,'' said shop owner J.J.
Simpson. ``Darts are coming in, and we haven't had darts in for a
while. Built-in bras are in, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Embroidery, crochet and beading are spicing things up a bit this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, everything was real plain and kind of loose,''
she said. ``But now it's more fitted and very detailed.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheath dress with a long jacket is really popular, said
boutique owner Linda Vela.
</P>
<P>
   Sundresses coupled with silk cardigans are great for church, or
pair some sandals with them for dinner or a luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do a lot of different things, depending on what you
put with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There are tons of fun looks this spring, including the
traditional skirt and suit jacket, which is perpetually popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really strong look and in a lot of lines this spring,''
she said. ``That way, you can take the jacket off and put pearls
with it to dress it up. Or wear it to work. You can dress it up or
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides pink, which is reportedly the color of the season, Vela
said she's seeing every shade of solid brights and pretty pastels,
like wedgewood blue, mint green and buttery yellow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say really this year, more than I've seen in a long
time, there's colors for everyone. It's not just limited to pastels
because there are a lot of brights.''
</P>
<P>
   Even black is a popular color choice this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put black with a whimsical print, pastel colors and
light fabric, then it's perfect,'' Vela said.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
