<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0789 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABYHOME-LIFEBEAT-NYT     03-23 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABYHOME-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BABY COMES HOME
</HEADLINE>
  By SUZANNE B. GLEASON 
 c.1999 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I remember changing our first baby's diaper on our last day in
the hospital. Or, I should say, attempting to change it. Every time
Bettina squirmed, I'd freeze, convinced I was doing something
terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A passing baby nurse came to my side and said, ``You've got to
show that baby who's boss. If she cries a little, she cries. That's
what babies do.'' I grasped Bettina's ankles with a firm, loving
touch and tried again, this time successfully.
</P>
<P>
   That little episode boosted my self-confidence and taught me a
lesson that helped me through the first month_that trying but
rewarding time when you get to know your baby. Like me, you'll be
an old pro in no time. Until then, here's a guide to your baby's
basic needs in the first month of life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sleeping: Don't Follow the Clock &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Your newborn will probably spend most of her first month in the
Land of Nod. If you're like many parents, you probably left the
hospital with instructions to wake the baby every two to three
hours during the day to feed.
</P>
<P>
   But is it really necessary to rouse a sleeping newborn to eat?
The American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) urges parents to watch for
hunger signals (crying, nuzzling against the breast, making sucking
motions) rather than watching the clock. The AAP advises waking a
healthy baby only during the first two weeks, every three to four
hours, in order to set the baby's feeding pattern and, if you're
breastieeding, to establish your milk supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should consider yourself lucky if your baby can sleep four
or more hours between feedings,'' says Dr. Richard Molteni, medical
director at Children's Hospital in Seattle. ``Long periods of sleep
are a sign of trouble only if the infant doesn't awaken vigorously
hungry and eager to feed or if the baby has these long stretches
back to back,'' because all that sleep means she's not eating
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``One stretch of five or even six hours in a 24-hour period is
perfectly OK,'' Molteni observes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Burping: Coax, Don't Force &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I remember being obsessed with getting a loud belch out of my
babies after every meal, rubbing and tapping their tiny backs
maniacally for up to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely overkill,'' says Molteni, who suggests
gently coaxing a burp out for a minute or two at the most.
``Neurologically, babies are perfectly wired not to inhale milk
from their food pipe into their lungs, so it's not dangerous when
you can't get a burp.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the main reason to burp a baby is to keep her
comfortable_and to avoid a mess. Her tiny stomach can contain only
so much food, and any air gulped in can form an uncomfortable
bubble that she'll eventually bring up herself_together with milk
or formula.
</P>
<P>
   Use your baby as a guide to gauge when to burp: ``If you get
messy, wet burps during every feeding, then you've got a baby who
needs to be burped more often during each feeding,'' says Molteni.
``Try every two to four minutes, or when you see her abdomen
getting rounded, and certainly when the baby seems uncomfortable.''
If she tolerates an entire feeding without discomfort, try burping
her before switching breasts or midway through the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Diapering: Watch the Bottom Line &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Expect the unexpected when it comes to your newborn's bowel
movements. ``A baby's bowel movements can change in consistency,
color, texture and smell from one diaper to the next,'' says
Molteni. Nevertheless, you can assume that your baby's output will
start out tar colored and creamy, gradually taking on a color and
texture much like pureed spinach and eventually evolving into a
mustard-yellow color and a seedy consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Diapers, needless to say, should be changed after every bowel
movement and whenever they seem full (cloth diapers feel wet;
disposable ones feel heavy and squishy). Since most very young
babies have a bowel movement each time they eat, change the baby
after every feeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to check a sleeping baby's diaper unless
there's evidence of diaper rash,'' says Molteni. Because a rash can
become painful (and can worsen) when exposed to urine or stool, you
should change your baby frequently when he has diaper rash, wiping
with a wet washcloth, patting dry, then applying a thick layer of
ointment. Baring your baby's bottom_without ointment_also speeds
the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nails: Nibble Them Off &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Babies are often born with long, paper-thin nails with which
they can scratch their face. Even worse, the nails seem to grow
back within seconds of being clipped off. Surprisingly, one of the
easiest nail-control methods is nibbling them off yourself, a
technique Molteni suggests to his patients. Don't worry about
bacteria. ``Kissing has the same bacterial exposure,'' he notes.
Carefully wielded manicure scissors do a good job, but they're best
left to intrepid (and experienced) moms and dads. Baby clippers can
be hard to control on such tiny nails, and many a parent (myself
included) has been reduced to tears after snipping off a tad too
much.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Skin Care: Less Is More &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Newborn skin requires little special treatment. In fact, using
products like baby lotion is best put off for a few months, advises
Dr. Molteni. ``The very delicate skin a baby is born with still
lacks the protective top layer, so it's more susceptible to
irritation,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some babies will develop small, pimply, red or white bumps on
their faces from blocked immature sweat glands_a condition that
usually goes away before 3 months of age. If your child has this,
you can use a mild soap once a day, being careful to rinse well.
</P>
<P>
   Another common skin condition is cradle cap_patches of waxy,
scaly crust on the baby's scalp. Gently rub mineral oil on the
scalp to loosen flakes, brush off with a dry wash cloth, and then
shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Suzanne B. Gleason, the mother of two and a contributing
editor to Child, also writes about beauty and health.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
