<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0790 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSTV-LIFEBEAT-ART-N     03-23 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSTV-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS AND TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color, horizontal illustration of toddlers reaching out
to touch various well-known TV characters emerging from a TV set.
The illustration, in JPEG format, is available in minutes by
calling Joe Applegate at 212-499-3342 or graphics assistant William
Gonzalez at 499-3355.) 
 By BILL DEAN 
 c.1999 New York Times Newspaper Group 
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve, the energetic, wide-eyed host of ``Blue's Clues,'' speaks
to his young viewers as if they are in the same room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you see the next clue?'' he'll ask, bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``BEHIND YOU,'' a chorus of off-camera preschoolers will yell,
as if answering him from their couches at home.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the hottest new TV programs aimed at the 2- to
5-year-old crowd, the show (9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. on
Nickelodeon) is a trendsetter in interactive programming.
</P>
<P>
   Steve, and the show's animated dog Blue, guide children through
story lines that ask questions ranging from object recognition to
sentence construction.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence ``The __ threw a __,'' appears on the screen, with
the picture of a ball in the first space, and a girl in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball threw a girl,'' Steve says. ``Is this right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' say 16 preschoolers in near unison as they watch the
show at the La Petite Academy in Lakeland, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't make sense!'' says Tabitha Abercrombie, 4. ``A
ball doesn't have arms!''
</P>
<P>
   Many educators, psychologists and media watchers generally
applaud the approach of ``Blue's Clues'' and similar children's
shows, including the purple, preschool icon ``Barney,'' the
toddler-friendly ``Teletubbies'' and the groundbreaking ``Sesame
Street,'' which celebrates 30 years this season.
</P>
<P>
   But most warn that television for young viewers should be doled
out sparingly, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless what you're watching is enhancing your life, it's
taking away from your life,'' says Carole Lieberman, a Los Angeles
psychiatrist who specializes in media and was among the first to
testify for Congress in favor of ratings for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the programs that are on television for children are
much too violent or have no education value,'' says Lieberman, also
former chairwoman of the National Coalition on TV Violence.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents, such as Cheryl Joe, assistant principal at
Florida's North Lakeland Elementary School and the mother of
5-year-old Errin, say some of the flashier shows are too fast for
small children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent this summer watching 'Blue's Clues,' because it has a
slow pace, and they talk so little ones can understand it,'' Joe
says. ``Little ones ... need time to absorb the language and the
information, and that's what attracts them to those types of shows,
like 'Barney.'''
</P>
<P>
   The worst shows, says Lieberman, include the aggressive ``Power
Rangers'' and other violence-oriented children's programming. ``And
at best, most of the others are simply mind-candy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Charren, a children's media consultant who founded Action
for Children's Television, says a little candy is not such a bad
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Programs such as ``Blue's Clues,'' ``Barney'' and ``Sesame
Street'' represent the good side of what is popular, Charren says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there's the other side, junk that they want to see
anyway,'' she says. ``And I think that's OK. A little junk is OK,
particularly if you talk about it with kids. There's benign junk
and there's horrible junk.''
</P>
<P>
   Charren, after all, remembers reading her share of comic books
as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Now a visiting scholar at Harvard University's Graduate School
of Education, she is a member of the Gore Commission that authored
recommendations on what broadcasters must do in exchange for
receiving more airwaves for digital TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be careful ... children learn from everything
they see on television,'' she says. ``And that is what's the matter
with the junk: they learn from that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   SOME DISAGREEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Experts disagree on the value of Nickelodeon's ``Rugrats,'' in
which animated babies such as Tommy Pickles and pals Chuckie, Phil
and Lil roll along through a series of misadventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't all that thrilled with 'Rugrats,''' Lieberman says.
``The old 'Muppet Babies' was very sweet, funny and clever. But
'Rugrats' took the concept of 'Muppet Babies' and made it more
sinister.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Joyce Brothers, the nationally known psychologist who
offers advice on a variety of family and social topics, says
``Rugrats'' offers ``nothing really unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch 'Rugrats' with your children and talk about how
people deal with them in real life, that's useful,'' Brothers says.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the tactic that Beverly Hartley, who works in the
Polk County, Fla., school district office of community relations,
takes with her sons, Trevor and John.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 and 11 years old, respectively, her sons have outgrown the
target age of ``Barney'' and ``Blue's Clues.'' But they fall
directly in the age range that prefers the more adventurous Tommy
Pickles and pals. But, Hartley says, no matter what happens on the
program, good usually prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it at first,'' she says. ``Because the kids on
there are kind of ugly. It's not like a cute cartoon, which is
probably what appeals to my boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they usually have some kind of morals, some kind of moral
story at the end. It's kid's sibling stuff, from the kid's point of
view.''
</P>
<P>
   KIDS' SEINFELD
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mitchell, management supervisor with Small Talk, a
children's marketing consultancy in Cincinnati, says ``Rugrats''
has become the kid's version of ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It works on any age level,'' says Mitchell, whose company
helps such clients as Motorola, Proctor &AMP; Gambel, JVC, Smuckers and
Sylvan Learning Centers understand children's viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a story line that kids can relate to, like fighting
with an older sister,'' Mitchell says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw 'Teletubbies' and saw it repeat a
segment, I thought 'That's boring,''' he says. ``But for a
2-year-old, that's exactly what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Teletubbies,'' which like ``Sesame Street'' and ``Barney''
is produced by PBS, the lead characters are animated and lovable,
with names like Po, Tinky-Wink, Dipsy and Laa-Laa.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell says younger children usually find ``rounded''
characters more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that Disney learned years ago; that
characters with soft, round edges like Blue and Barney are very
appealing to young children.''
</P>
<P>
   WATCH IT FOR YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   Stevanne Auerbach, director of the Institute for Childhood
Resources in San Francisco, says parents should carefully view
children's programs before deciding which shows are suitable for
their own children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to watch the show, you have to see what the show is
all about,'' says Auerbach, who, at the U.S. Department of
Education in 1969, approved the first government grant for ``Sesame
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like if you're going to go to a day care center,''
she says. ``You've got to check it out. You're not going to put
your kid in just any day care center.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Dean writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
