<HEADER>
A0807 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERTO-BENIGNI-IN-LI     03-23 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTO-BENIGNI-IN-LIFE-IS-BEAUTIFUL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCING IN HITLER'S SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Roberto Benigni with Giorgio Cantarini in
a scene from ``Life Is Beautiful.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The comedian is telling a story, and nobody's laughing.
 &HT;    ``Two years in a Nazi concentration camp,'' Roberto Benigni's
father would begin his stories, and his young son and daughter
would shudder with fear in their Tuscan villa.
 &HT;    The senior Benigni, an Italian farmer of Albanian descent,
fought for Italy in World War II. He was captured by the Nazis
after Italy changed sides in 1943, and spent the next two years in
a concentration camp in northern Germany.
 &HT;    By day, he was forced to build weapons for the Nazi army.
 &HT;    ``At night, he would watch his friends die,'' Benigni says.
``You see, the conditions were the same as a concentration camp for
Jews, except there was no gas chamber.''
 &HT;    The story always ended the same way, with the children's father
muttering about ``the 35 skeletons in the bunks near me. All my
friends, they die.''
 &HT;    Naturally, the children had nightmares, until one day their
mother put her foot down. She told her husband that he could no
longer speak of the war years unless he could do it with humor.
 &HT;    ``That night, my father started telling a different story,''
Benigni recalls. ``One with levity, about the captain in the camp
and the time he falls down. I know it sounds impossible, but the
stories were funny.
 &HT;    ``We started to laugh, and the nightmares ended.''
 &HT;    The young boy grew up to be Italy's favorite comedian, and those
stories sowed the seeds of what is being hailed as his greatest
film, ``La Vita E Bella,'' a.k.a. ``Life Is Beautiful.'' The film,
which on March 21 won him the 1998 Oscar for Best Actor,
 &HT;    is as much one man's creation as any film can be: Benigni wrote
it, directed it and stars in it, with his real-life wife playing
his on-screen wife.
 &HT;    It's the tale of Guido, an Italian Jew who has grand dreams of
owning his own bookstore until the Nazis take over. Only three
months before the war's end, he and his 5-year-old son are deported
to a German concentration camp. In order to save his son's life,
Guido uses his bold imagination and physical comedy to convince the
boy that they are just there to play a game.
 &HT;    It may sound unlikely, but it's hardly unlikable: ``Life is
Beautiful'' won the Grand Jury Prize at the 1988 Cannes Film
Festival, and is being touted as a candidate for multiple Oscars.
 &HT;    It represents a new level of fame for the 45-year-old Benigni,
previously best known outside of Italy for Jim Jarmusch's cult
classic ``Down by Law'' (1986) and Blake Edwards' ``Son of the Pink
Panther'' (1993).
 &HT;    But according to Benigni, as he sits down to talk about his film
at a Toronto hotel, he's already won the biggest prize he could
ask.
 &HT;    ``I screen the movie for my father in Florence,'' he says,
laughing. ``At the end, he screamed, `Son, you finally did good
movie! First time! Good movie!'''
 &HT;    Italians generally think Benigni has made good movies before,
but not movies like this.
 &HT;    ``In Italy, I'm so well known as a popular comedian. I am like
Donald Duck,'' he says. ``So Donald Duck making a movie about
Holocaust was hard for people to understand.''
 &HT;    The idea for the film came to him, Benigni says, when he came
across a line attributed to the Russian revolutionary Leon Trotsky.
Trapped in a bunker, waiting for Stalin's assassins to kill him _
as they ultimately did _ the Russian supposedly nevertheless wrote,
``Life is beautiful.''
 &HT;    ``The message to me is that, no matter what happens, there is
beauty in this life,'' the comedian says. ``You can find the
goodness.''
 &HT;    At core, he adds, ``Life is Beautiful'' isn't about the
Holocaust at all _ it's a love story between father and son.
 &HT;    ``What is more simple than a father protecting his son?'' he
asks. ``That is true love, with a real purity and innocence.''
 &HT;    Casting the role of the young boy was a challenge. Even when
Giorgio Cantarini won the part, problems continued.
 &HT;    ``I test hundreds of boys. When he entered, I stopped with
everything,'' Benigni recalls. ``This boy looks like me _ big nose!
His face is not right for TV!''
 &HT;    But young Cantarini couldn't read at the time.
 &HT;    ``He had to learn his lines by sheer memorization, which seemed
impossible,'' the director says. ``But he did it.''
 &HT;    Benigni filmed in Tuscany, where he was born and raised, and
where he could work closely with Milan's Center for Contemporary
Jewish Documentation. Camp survivors reviewed the script and gave
advice, but Benigni admits that he approached test screenings with
trepidation.
 &HT;    ``I was afraid I could hurt or offend someone because I am a
comedian,'' he admits. ``I didn't want to offend, because I respect
these survivors so much.''
 &HT;    To his delight, Milanese Jewish groups welcomed the film.
 &HT;    ``They loved the movie very much,'' he says, relief still
evident in his voice. ``There is no problem. Some survivors did
talk to me about it and said, `This not right. This could not have
happened this way.' I told them I am an artist. I needed to take
some license. I must be free.
 &HT;    ``Then I asked, `Are you offended or hurt by the script?' They
told me the script was wonderful.''
 &HT;    Even so, he admits that he found the screenings disconcerting.
 &HT;    ``As a comedian, I'm used to hearing people laugh,'' he says.
``In this movie, everybody was crying. I was confused, but happy.''
 &HT;    The film was already big before Miramax Films picked it up. Now
Benigni hears rumors of Oscars, not only for Best Foreign Film but
possibly also for Best Actor, Best Director, even Best Picture.
 &HT;    Not that he's short on prizes, mind you.
 &HT;    ``In Italy, they give me hundred prizes for this movie,'' he
says. ``In each town, Jewish community give me prizes. Now people
stop me on the street and say, `Hey, Benigni, here is a prize. Do
you want this?'
 &HT;    ``Every week, I have something new for the mantel. It's nice.''
 &HT;    It's a nice change for a comedian who has often talked his way
into trouble. Some jokes about Pope John Paul earned him a one-year
suspended prison sentence, while his sarcastic mockery of former
Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi have been credited with
contributing to the politician's downfall.
 &HT;    Even with the occasional controversy, Benigni says, he loves
being a comedian.
 &HT;    ``All men in Italy like to talk so much,'' he says, laughing.
``Every bum in Italy is a comedian except for our serious actors.
People like good laughter there, which always made me happy.''
 &HT;    Making movies is just an extension of his comedy act, he adds.
 &HT;    ``When I make movies, the crew becomes my audience,'' Benigni
says. ``I don't imagine that in six months people will be watching
in the theater. To be alive as an actor, you must act for someone.
You need someone to look at you in that moment.''
 &HT;    Comedy has its spiritual side, the comedian adds, which is part
of the appeal of ``Life Is Beautiful.''
 &HT;    ``When you laugh at something bad, it gives you a strange
power,'' he says. ``I think if you have the power to laugh, you
have the power to say, `I will not die.'
 &HT;    ``When we laugh, we are naked _ we are vulnerable,'' Benigni
says. ``But I think sometimes the biggest act of resistance is a
smile. If you turn your cry to a laugh, it is a triumph of the
human spirit.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
