<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOSEPH-FIENNES-IN-SHA     03-23 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOSEPH-FIENNES-IN-SHAKESPEARE-IN-LOVE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HOLDS BARD: JOSEPH FIENNES TACKLES SHAKESPEARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Joseph Fiennes in a scene from
``Shakespeare in Love.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Ralph Fiennes may do Shakespeare, but Joseph Fiennes is
Shakespeare.
 &HT;    Well, at least in his current movie. Playing the immortal bard
in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' voted the Best Picture Oscar for 1998,
the younger Fiennes once and for all escapes his brother's shadow,
proving his own merit as a master of light comedy and passionate
romance alike _ and, oh yes, as a Hollywood hunk to boot.
 &HT;    After all, the man currently sitting down for an interview at
Manhattan's Parker Meridian Hotel, flashing long, seductive
eyelashes and a boy's mischievous smile, can be seen romping au
naturel with Cate Blanchett and Gwyneth Paltrow in his first two
films, both currently playing.
 &HT;    That would include the critically acclaimed period drama
``Elizabeth,'' in which Fiennes as the lustful Earl of Leicester
engages in some anything-but-chaste revels with the so-called
``virgin queen,'' and ``Shakespeare in Love,'' a romantic comedy in
which Fiennes plays a lovesick bard struggling with writer's block
as he tries to pen a new play, ``Romeo and Ethel, the Pirate's
Daughter.''
 &HT;    And romping around with a naked Paltrow, which is a heck of a
way to start a big-screen career.
 &HT;    ``Oh, it's not as glamorous as one might think,'' Fiennes
insists. ``I'm so shy that these scenes were torture for me. Give
me a sword fight any day.''
 &HT;    Believe it or not, he's serious.
 &HT;    ``Let's start with the fact that Gwyneth's boyfriend, Ben
Affleck, is in this movie,'' the actor says. ``And he's a big guy.
You don't want to get on the wrong side of Ben and say, `Guess
what? I will be spending the duration of the day in a bed with your
girlfriend.'
 &HT;    ``Thankfully, our director, John Madden, placed the love scenes
in the middle of shooting,'' he adds, ``and Gwyneth and I already
got on like a house on fire. Still, we had a bit of a laugh when we
had to get into bed. It was so surreal. But then we just got on
with it.''
 &HT;    Actually, Fiennes says, he didn't expect to wind up anywhere
near that bed.
 &HT;    ``I blew the audition for this movie,'' he recalls. ``I gave a
horrendous reading of the script when I first read for John. About
a month later he called, saying he managed to squeeze some
potential out of it.''
 &HT;    A screen test with Paltrow followed, and he was suddenly faced
with the challenge of being Shakespeare.
 &HT;    ``In one sense, he's sacred ground to so many people like
academics and theater-goers,'' Fiennes says. ``On the other hand,
from the little research that I did, William Shakespeare is a blank
sheet _ no one really knows anything about him as a man. So it was
a bit of a can of worms.
 &HT;    ``You can profile him from the sonnets and from the plays, but
his faith, his politics, his sexuality and his take on life is a
mystery,'' the actor says. ``From my sense, that's great. No one
can say that I did it right or wrong.''
 &HT;    For insight on a writer's mind, Fiennes turned to his novelist
mother.
 &HT;    ``My mother told me that writing was one of the most isolating
ways to spend a life,'' he says. ``She felt that the huge amount of
solitude put a shadow on a person, which is what I thought of when
I played William Shakespeare.''
 &HT;    Otherwise, it was a case of working from the script.
 &HT;    ``I figured Shakespeare was a genius who didn't quite know it,''
Fiennes says. ``He knew he was a pretty damn good writer, but he
was also a man who had to pay the rent. He's got writer's block.
All of this indicated to me someone who was knocking out his plays
to pay the rent. He was a survivor.''
 &HT;    The same applies to the actor, who comes from a family of
survivors. The youngest of six children _ his fraternal twin Jacob,
now a gamekeeper, is minutes older _ he grew up in a family
constantly on the go, as a child moving a dozen times to various
spots in both Ireland and England. His father was a sculptor, while
his mother was a writer.
 &HT;    ``Being the youngest makes you long for more of a voice,'' he
says. ``You find that voice early in theatrics of the kitchen. I
was the one screaming, `Hey, where is my food?'''
 &HT;    Given their genes, it's perhaps not surprising that the six
children include three actors and a director among them.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what it is that made us all find careers of
expression,'' Fiennes says. ``Maybe it has something to do with my
mother and father having careers that were creative. There was
never a lack of stimulus in terms of literature or painting and
drawing.''
 &HT;    He pauses.
 &HT;    ``I know I'm making it sound so romantic and bohemian,'' he
says. ``It wasn't. It was chaotic, dirty and noisy. I couldn't wait
to get out. I guess that was the stimulus.''
 &HT;    For this Fiennes, the path to independence started with his
theatrical debut, in a third-grade production of ``Joseph and the
Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat.''
 &HT;    ``The only bad thing is my teacher didn't want me to sing,'' he
recalls. ``She told me to mime it. It hurt my feelings.''
 &HT;    But by age 9 he was on his way, performing in youth theater at
the Young Vic. Two years later he was studying at the Guild Hall of
Music and Drama in London, where he spent three years training for
the stage.
 &HT;    After a year off in Italy, where he worked on the reconstruction
of a 12th-century villa, Fiennes returned to England and the
theater.
 &HT;    ``Ever since I've been battling for parts,'' he says.
 &HT;    Ironically, his rise to stardom may have been slowed by his
brother's own ascent. Seeing the public spotlight that has followed
Ralph Fiennes since ``Schindler's List'' (1993) left his shyer
brother feeling awkward.
 &HT;    ``I keep thinking about what that costs in terms of your persona
and how much you would like to keep your persona under wraps,'' he
says. ``Unfortunately, to a certain degree you've got to let a
little bit of it go. That's rough for me, because deep down I am
shy.''
 &HT;    Well, maybe. His brother also once claimed to be shy, only to
turn up on the cover of Vanity Fair shirtless and wild-haired in
leather pants.
 &HT;    ``That was just too many vodkas,'' Joseph Fiennes says,
laughing.
 &HT;    His two Elizabethan adventures just might make Fiennes the most
popular member of the family. But the actor, who is single and
lives in London, isn't making any such plans.
 &HT;    ``I don't know where I'm going,'' he says, not apparently overly
concerned about it. ``Any job I've ever taken has not been about
pursuing fame. The only thing I can do is respond to certain
material. If that leads to a career, then so be it.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
