<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, March 23, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MISSING (Long Barn, Calif.) _ Hours after authorities
identified one of two charred bodies found in the trunk of a
burned- out car in this mountain hamlet as that of missing
sightseer Carole Sund, the murder investigation was moved to the
area surrounding Sonora, Calif. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and VICKIE
HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPUS-JUSTICE (Albany, N.Y.) _ In this courtroom, defendants
have no right to face their accusers or have an attorney present.
The proceedings are secret, but the verdicts are not. Such are the
conditions under which university student conduct courts are
allowed to mete out justice on campuses, dealing with matters
ranging from cheating to accusations of major felonies. By ANDREW
BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-RIGHTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Adopting the ``all politics is
local'' philosophy, gay rights activists say they are increasingly
turning to state legislatures over Washington power brokers in
pushing their civil rights agendas. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-PLAN (San Francisco) _ An idea to give panhandlers a
hand-held machine that could accept ATM or credit cards is being
tossed around City Hall with at least partial blessings of Mayor
Willie Brown and his homeless coordinator. But one of the city's
leading homeless advocates calls the idea ``bizarre.'' By GREGORY
LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MENSTRUAL-BLEEDING (Albany, N.Y.) _ For an estimated 180,000
women each year, the solution to dysfunctional uterine bleeding or
severe menstrual periods has been a hysterectomy. Now there are
other ways of dealing with the problem. By SYLVIA WOODS.
</P>
<P>
   ADOPTION-CHALLENGES (Waterford, N.Y.) _ Adopting children can be
a costly and time-consuming task. One parent, Cathy Dresseau,
describes the paperwork, waiting and stress that preceded the
adoption of three Russian girls as reminiscent of the pain of
childbirth. By MIKE HUREWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-BANKS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The biggest threat of the year 2000
on banks is not a computer breakdown or a power outage, experts
say. Instead, they say it's the possibility of bank runs and public
panic at the end of this year. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-RETURNS (San Francisco) _ The days of slaving over tax
returns with pencil and paper appear to be numbered. If the
Internal Revenue Service and Congress have their way, all of the
nation's 200 million tax returns will be filed electronically _ via
computer or telephone _ within a decade or so. By EDWARD IAWATA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-OSCARS-ASSESS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The 1999 Academy Awards show
was surprising to the point of post-traumatic shock. Compared with
the '98 broadcast, a politely bloated coronation ceremony for
``Titanic'' and its self-dubbed ``King of the World,'' James
Cameron, Sunday's affair looked like a riot. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SERIES-PREVIEWS (Undated) _ Is it too early for a
``Seinfeld'' imitator? Can the acerbic and weird Norm Macdonald
carry a show all by himself? Those are the questions ABC is no
doubt fretting over as it launches two new series on Wednesday. By
TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FAJITAS (Houston) _ Fajitas have earned their stripes as a
favorite Tex-Mex food _ as common as tacos and enchiladas. Like
other legendary dishes, such as chili, fajitas have an obscure
origin. Technically, only beef has a fajita, but the term has
evolved over the years to cover meats, including chicken, seafood
(even lobster) and vegetables. (Photo available on NYT database) By
ANN CRISWELL
</P>
<P>
   W/ FOOD-FAJITAS-TIPS and FOOD-FAJITAS-RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-DUKE (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ In theory, the Duke Blue
Devils are only human. They have demons that can get the best of
them. They have deficiencies that can be the death of their
desires. The Blue Devils are beatable. Of course they are. They've
been beaten before, so they can be beaten again. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ After attending a state
convention in which the Republican Party seemed more like the
Donner party, I said the GOP has no chance of winning the
presidency in 2000 because of its rigid stand against women's right
to abortion. It was a political insight of the ``Duh'' variety. But
this time even the Republicans seem to get it. The Republicans'
great, white, Spanish- speaking hope, George W. Bush, is trying to
downplay abortion. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Hillary Clinton has been warned
repeatedly that a U.S. Senate run in New York would be no walk in
the park. That's why, I suppose, the First Lady has been calling
Democratic party leaders around the state. So far, she supposedly
has talked to roughly 200 of them. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   FLORES-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Statistics show that the number of
men killed by their girlfriends has dropped by more than two-thirds
since 1976, but the number of women slain by their ``significant
others'' has remained high. These startling figures leave the
people who protect battered women frustrated and searching for
answers. By VERONICA FLORES.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HISPANICS (Alexandria, Va.) _ What worries Democrats in
California is the specter of Republican Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and his brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, crisscrossing the state
speaking fluent Spanish to Hispanic audiences. Six months ago, I
would have bet against a Republican winning California. As of now,
my optimism grows with each word of Spanish we speak. By DOUGLAS
MACKINNON.
</P>
