<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      03-23 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ALL TOO HUMAN &QL; 
 &UR; George Stephanopoulos (Little, Brown, $27.95)
</P>
<P>
   One morning in 1996, Stephanopoulos was in a coffee shop near
his home when he was approached by a woman with a familiar face. He
didn't know her well _ he remembered her only as ``a pretty, busty,
flirty intern'' he'd passed in the halls of the White House. They
made small talk, and then she suddenly asked, ``Does your president
tell the truth?'' ``I thought her phrasing was peculiar,''
Stephanopoulos writes, ``but people stopped me on the street to say
strange things all the time. After mumbling some answer like `He
does his best,' I bought my coffee and didn't think about it
again.'' It's Monica Lewinsky's first notable appearance in this
memoir, and it doesn't occur until Page 433 _ good news for those
of us who run for cover at the mention of her name. But the specter
of things to come is everywhere in Stephanopoulos' account of his
years as adviser to Bill Clinton. His book is a fascinating,
ruthless and often humorous insider's view of politics, power and a
gifted, charismatic president with serious personal flaws. Among
Stephanopoulos' duties was damage control during a succession of
``bimbo eruptions.'' At first, he thought that ``doing the dirty
work was not only necessary but noble, a landmark on the road to
greater good.'' Four years later, burnt out and on antidepressants,
he quit, ``grateful for the privilege of serving a president,
relieved to be leaving in one piece.'' Now, he's making money
telling tales on the Clintons, Dick Morris (``the dark buddha whose
belly Clinton rubbed in desperate times''), James Carville, Al Gore
and others in the cold-blooded arena of Washington politics. New &AMP;
Notable dreaded reading this, but could not put it down. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BOOKNOTES: LIFE STORIES &QL; 
 &UR; Brian Lamb (Times, $27.50)
</P>
<P>
   Albert Einstein's brain, coveted by scientists everywhere, ended
up in pieces in Princeton, Philadelphia and Japan. ``It was exactly
what he didn't want to happen,'' Einstein biographer Denis Brian
says. Amelia Earhart was very pretty, but she had thick ankles.
``She hated them,'' biographer Susan Butler says. ``She was
obsessed even when she was famous with her ankles, which is one of
the reasons why she always wore pants _ because they showed off the
best of her figure and hid the worst.'' C-SPAN's ``Booknotes'' will
observe its 10th birthday next month, and Lamb celebrates with this
new collection of essays based on interviews with ``Booknotes''
authors. As with 1997's ``Booknotes: America's Finest Authors on
Reading, Writing, and the Power of Ideas,'' the writers speak in
their own words _ Lamb's questions are omitted _ and although the
transcripts have been edited, they have a conversational tone.
Among the biographers included: Ron Chernow (who is in Flagstaff
this weekend at the Northern Arizona Book Festival) on John D.
Rockefeller Sr.; David McCullough on Harry Truman; Charles A.
Fecher on H.L. Mencken; Doris Kearns Goodwin on Franklin D.
Roosevelt; Frank McCourt, Anita Hill and Katharine Graham on
themselves; James Tobin on Ernie Pyle, and David Maraniss on Bill
Clinton. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EZRA AND DOROTHY POUND: LETTERS IN CAPTIVITY 1945-1946 &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Omar Pound and Robert Spoo (Oxford, $35)
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was puzzled over having missed a cog somewhere,''
Ezra Pound told Donald Hall years later. ``I expected to turn
myself in and to be asked about what I learned. I did and I
wasn't.'' He spoke of the spring of 1945, when American troops
arrived in Rapallo, Italy, and Pound, who had passed the war there,
presented himself and asked to be taken to the United States ``to
give information to the State Department.'' He was determined to
help Harry Truman negotiate peace with the Japanese. This was, he
told the Americans, ``a serious matter and not just eccentricity.''
Instead, he was indicted for treason because of fascist radio
broadcasts he had made during the war, and held for months in an
army detention camp outside Pisa. He was 60, and for the first
three weeks lived in an open-air, wire cage with blankets on a
concrete floor and a tin can for a toilet. Only when he suffered a
breakdown was he moved to a tent in the medical compound (described
in ``The Pisan Cantos'' _ ``Only shadows enter my tent/ as men pass
between me and the sunset''). This is a collection of previously
unpublished letters written by Pound and his wife, Dorothy, while
he was held in Italy and later at a mental institution in
Washington, D.C. They show less of the disintegration of the poet
than the allegiance of his wife, who kept up a steady flow of news
even after Pound was confined to St. Elizabeths Hospital for the
Insane. The editors include copious notes on the letters, as well
as FBI documents and photographs. Omar Pound is Ezra Pound's son. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; OPEN HOUSE &QL; 
 &UR; Merritt Ierley (Holt, $32.50)
</P>
<P>
   Ierley traces the evolution of the American house since the
beginning of European settlement. He focuses on a chronological
sequence of houses that are now museums open to the public,
beginning with the home that English settler Jonathan Fairbanks
built for his family in Dedham, Mass., in 1637. (Ierley does
include a brief acknowledgment of Acoma Pueblo in New Mexico, which
is believed to be the oldest continuously inhabited settlement in
the country, built a full 700 years before Fairbanks was born).
Other houses here include the Harriet Beecher Stowe House in
Hartford, Conn.; Frank Lloyd Wright's Pope-Leighey House in Falls
Church, Va.; and Thomas Jefferson's Monticello. Ierley addresses
issues of heat, light and indoor plumbing and constructs a timeline
of technological developments that includes 100 houses across the
country. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(You can reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-HISPANICS-HNS &LR;      03-23 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENOR GORE: HABLA USTED ESPANOL? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUGLAS MACKINNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ A friend of Vice President Al Gore told me of
growing concerns about the Democratic candidate's campaign in
California for the presidential election next year.
</P>
<P>
   His worry manifests itself in two ways.
</P>
<P>
   First: ``The Republicans, for the first time in history, may
make a real attempt to bring minorities into their party.''
</P>
<P>
   And second, and more importantly: ``Those Bush brothers!''
</P>
<P>
   As a Republican long disgusted with the lip service my party
pays to minorities, I discussed with the vice president's friend
(and a friend of mine) the power of the Latino vote in California.
</P>
<P>
   He was not shy. It is his hope to ``Pete Wilsonize'' every
Republican presidential candidate who visits the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   That is, paint every GOP candidate as one who is out of touch
with Latinos, their needs and their growing power.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps him awake at night now, he said, is the specter of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush,
crisscrossing the state speaking fluent Spanish to Hispanic
television and radio stations and to Latino audiences.
</P>
<P>
   As my friend made clear, ``Vice President Gore knows about 15
words of Spanish and is really going to come up short against a
governor (Jeb Bush) who speaks perfect Spanish and whose wife is
from Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a deep concern for the Democratic Party because,
according to conventional wisdom, the Republican candidate can lose
in California and still win the election, while the Democratic
candidate has almost no chance should he lose in the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   As each successive Republican candidate has announced his or her
intentions for the upcoming campaign, I have been heartened to hear
most of them speak of the need to reach out to blacks, Hispanics
and minorities in a substantive way. Like the wife of Jeb Bush, my
wife is Hispanic (she is from Venezuela). One day we hope to have
children, and I want those children to have every opportunity in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when dinosaurs walked the Earth, and there was
a time when dinosaurs ruled the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few kicking around in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   And those dinosaurs have told me that reaching out to minorities
will ``alienate our base.''
</P>
<P>
   To that I have always said, `If those kinds of people represent
our base, then we have to drive them from the party as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   We are starting to do that, and my Democratic friend now has a
right to be worried about California.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that the new generation of Republican leaders now
rising to the top look at the people of the United States in a much
more diverse and inclusive way. Many of them not only want
minorities in the GOP, they believe we need minorities in the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, I would have bet against the Republican
candidate winning California. As of now, my optimism grows with
each word of Spanish we speak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Douglas MacKinnon was a writer for former Presidents Ronald
Reagan and George Bush.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
