<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATISTICS SEND TREMORS THROUGH WOMEN'S SHELTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ ``Sometimes it's easier to live with the abuse
than to live with nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The quotation, first spoken by a battered woman more than 11
years ago, resounds in Joyce Coleman's mind and drives her frenetic
pace to save women from family violence.
</P>
<P>
   So it's with understandable frustration that Coleman, executive
director of the Battered Women's Shelter in San Antonio, views the
results of a study funded by the National Consortium on Violence
Research that examines the impact of the campaign against domestic
violence. The study of the 29 largest U.S. cities suggests that the
increased availability of services and outreach to family violence
victims has saved thousands of lives _ the lives of men.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, the number of men killed by their girlfriends has
dropped by more than two thirds, but the number of women slain by
their ``significant others'' has remained high, according to a
report in the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity appears to stem from the fact that
domestic-violence resources are aimed at getting women to change
their behavior, to leave an abusive relationship before they use
deadly force to protect themselves. Men who kill, on the other
hand, more often act out of rage or a sense of control and thus may
be angered rather than calmed by programs that split up abusive
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, female deaths have declined as have homicide rates
in other categories, the Post reports, but in 1997, domestic
violence nationwide led to the deaths of 1,174 women.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, more than 150 women were killed by their partners in
1997, the most recent data available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think that if I worked long enough and hard enough,
if we provided enough services, we would save more women,'' Coleman
said last week. ``I had hoped to work myself out of a job
someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who also heads the Family Violence Prevention Services,
doesn't begrudge batterers their lives. ``Any life we save is
important,'' she says. ``but I just wish we could save more women's
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman has done plenty to that end. Under her direction and
with community help, women in the San Antonio area have access to
services beyond the shelter. The safe house was all Coleman could
offer women in October 1987, when she became the shelter's
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The haven now boasts the state's largest intervention program
for batterers _ last year 2,000 men were ordered to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Transitional housing for family violence victims now is
available as are drug and alcohol programs, a juvenile violence
intervention program, counseling for the homeless and various forms
of outreach to families at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman estimates that shelter staffers touch the lives of
9,500-10,000 clients every year.
</P>
<P>
   But even as she recites the impressive gains, Coleman is
intensely focused on the lapse that glares at her from the
statistics about women killed by their partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel we've made a difference, but when you look at
these numbers nationally, I guess I feel a little frustrated
because I don't know what more we need to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I not doing right?''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman and her colleagues around the country have done plenty
right. And, incrementally, so do lawmakers and others in a position
to help victims.
</P>
<P>
   But the scourge of family violence isn't so easily erased.
``We've made giant strides,'' Coleman says. ``but as a community,
we have to look at how to keep women from dying.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
