<HEADLINE>
CALLING ALL CHAIRS, CALLING ALL CHAIRS: SIT UP STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Police work has always had its inherent dangers, but
the Seattle Police Department's Identification Unit has apparently
become a particularly perilous place.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, two employees slipped off their rolling desk
chairs and landed on the linoleum floor.
</P>
<P>
   In response, all the unit's civilian employees have been ordered
to undergo a training session on how to safely sit in a chair,
rolling and non-rolling alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``... Take hold of the arms and get control of the chair before
sitting down,'' advised a recent supervisor's memo to the unit's
fingerprint and photo lab specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, workers have been falling out of their chairs laughing:
``It's so ridiculous,'' said one employee. ``We've been joking that
this is for the sitting-impaired.''
</P>
<P>
   About 26 employees were expected to attend Tuesday's half-hour
session, including two supervisors on overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The class will cover the fine art of chair-sitting,
chair-rolling and chair-placement,'' joked an employee.
</P>
<P>
   For department safety officer Patrick Sweeney, however, the
recent ``chair-related injuries,'' though rare, are no laughing
matter.
</P>
<P>
   In two of the cases, the chair rolled out from underneath the
employee. In a third case, an employee hurt her back when the seat
height fell abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything that results in injury to an employee
of the Seattle Police Department is funny,'' he said. He said one
worker's injuries kept her out of work.
</P>
<P>
   After the accidents, employees suddenly found their chairs
replaced with awkward, non-wheeled ones. They complained about
headaches and backaches. Then, some of the rolling chairs
reappeared. The unit's acting manager, Marty Sullivan, was
unavailable to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Safety officer Sweeney said that ``some people know how to sit
in a chair,'' while others need a little education. He said his
session will also cover ``common hazards associated with working in
an office space,'' including open cabinets and drawers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
