<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME REPUBLICANS ARE TRYING TO SIDESTEP THE ABORTION ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A few weeks ago, after attending a state
convention in which the Republican Party seemed more like the
Donner party, I said the GOP has no chance of winning the
presidency in 2000 because of its rigid stand against women's right
to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   It was a political insight of the ``Duh'' variety.
</P>
<P>
   But this time even the Republicans seem to get it. The
Republicans' great, white, Spanish-speaking hope, George W. Bush,
is trying to downplay abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have the least chance of being elected president in
the general election _ Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer and Pat Buchanan _
have made the loudest pro-life noises in hopes of winning the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a conservative activist who bears a startling
resemblance to a fetus, constantly speechifies about how abortion
must be fought by ``the party of Lincoln and Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many abortions Lincoln was responsible for, but
according to the California Department of Public Health, 609,209
abortions were performed in California while Reagan was governor _
and he signed the act legalizing them.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican friend forwards a press release dated June 13,
1967, and signed by then-Gov. Reagan's press secretary Lyn
Nofziger. It began, ``Governor Ronald Reagan announced today that
he will sign a bill liberalizing California's abortion laws . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan was quoted as saying. ``I am fully sympathetic with
attempts to liberalize the outdated abortion law now on the law
books of California.'' He described the goals of the liberalized
law as ``humanitarian.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan later changed his position on abortion, but for Bauer or
others in the Republican Party to cite Reagan in arguments against
abortion is disingenuous, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   If they truly believe their own rhetoric, then Reagan killed
609,209 babies.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Reagan was such a towering figure he could
contradict himself coming and going.
</P>
<P>
   Not many fiscal conservatives can get away with putting a
country into massive debt, and few pro-lifers have a record of
legalizing abortion. Yet few presidents have been as popular.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan was so popular no one could ever attack him for having
been soft on abortion, or anything else. It was another story with
his successor, George Bush the elder, who was forced to kowtow
before the radical right.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1980, Bush supported Planned Parenthood and abortion
rights. He came out against abortion when he became Reagan's
running mate. Because he once backed Planned Parenthood, the right
wing of the Republican Party always distrusted and sniped at him.
</P>
<P>
   None of the right-wingers ever brought up the fact that Reagan
legalized abortion in California and then changed his mind. No one
ever talked about the 609,209 fetuses that never became California
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   What this shows is that abortion is not the absolute moral issue
that the Republican platform makes it out to be. It is a political
issue, and a politician with the stature of Reagan could make his
history on it a non-issue.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Bush the younger, and he is getting easier treatment
from some important Republicans trying to shed the image of being
American women's medical and moral dictators.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been downplaying abortion, instead talking about
encouraging adoption, requiring parental consent for minors seeking
abortions and promoting sexual abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   These are part of his ``reverence for life'' agenda, a reverence
that doesn't extend to death row in Texas prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes and Bauer plan on attacking Bush for not continuing to
target fights like so-called ``partial birth'' abortion. But Pat
Robertson and David O'Steen, head of the National Right to Life
Committee, are defending Bush. O'Steen called for an end to
more-pro-life-than-thou fights between candidates.
</P>
<P>
   What do you know? There may be some closet pragmatists on the
right, people who actually want to win in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Young Bush has been playing it cagey, not taking any position on
whether he'd demand that his judicial appointees oppose abortion, a
key litmus test of the right wing.
</P>
<P>
   He says he supports abortion in the case of rape, incest or when
the life of the mother is endangered. He's vague on the Republican
platform demand for a constitutional amendment outlawing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Elizabeth Dole announced that she was forming an
``exploratory committee'' on running for president, which means
she's prospecting for money. However, exploring reporters couldn't
get her to express any position on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party is stuck with a losing issue, and enough
people know it that they want to hide it. But they can't hide the
fact that they're stuck with pee-wee candidates.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Reagan who can get away with any kind of
inconsistency. There are few remaining moderates like John Chafee
of Rhode Island, who announced he is retiring as of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The party of Lincoln and Reagan only has Bush the younger and
the Dole who doesn't do Viagra ads. The Republican party definitely
needs a reverence-for-life agenda _ it's own life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
