<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0889 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-HNS &LR;      03-23 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE BLUE DEVILS ARE BEATABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In theory, the Duke Blue Devils are only
human. They have demons that can get the best of them. They have
deficiencies that can be the death of their desires.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils are beatable. Of course they are. They've been
beaten before, so they can be beaten again. The NCAA Tournament is
full of kids who are still trying to become men. And kids can do
the craziest, most unexplainable things at the most unthinkable or
inappropriate times.
</P>
<P>
   Houston in 1983 happens. Georgetown in 1985 happens. Nevada-Las
Vegas in 1991 happens. Kansas in 1997 happens.
</P>
<P>
   The Temple Owls embraced a good many of those theories _ plus
whatever else coach John Chaney could cram into their heads on one
day's notice _ when they took the court for the East Regional
final. But no theory could prepare them for the reality of a Final
Four-stakes game with a vintage Mike Krzyzewski team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Owls played with passion, purpose and poise for the
better part of Sunday afternoon at Continental Airlines Arena. The
result? An 85-64 thrashing by a top-seeded, top-ranked team that is
on anything but a top-secret mission.``Whoever plans to beat 'em,''
Chaney said, ``I hope they believe in the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 19,557 saw firsthand what those from less privileged
vantage points might miss. From a distance, it's easy enough to get
deluded into shrinking down the Blue Devils to life size. Through
the lying eyes of a television camera, some of the beauty marks
could get mistaken for warts.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoning that the shortest distance between two points is right
under the baskets, the Owls surrounded the Blue Devils' incredible
bulk, sophomore All-America Elton Brand. The Owls did this so
diligently, Brand didn't score a single point in the first 12 and a
half minutes. When Brand got his first basket, Duke led by nine.
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Trajan Langdon began shooting holes in the Owls'
revered matchup zone defense barely five minutes into the game.
Langdon scored 11 of his 23 points during a 2:17 binge, putting the
Blue Devils ahead for good. His aim was so sharp from so far, he
opened up all sorts of avenues to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   After the Owls went to all that trouble to corral Brand, he
still wound up with 21 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that somebody is going to start hitting baskets from
the outside,'' Chaney said. ``But you just don't know how well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Owls had a 9-5 lead when Langdon hit a runner off the
fast-break at 14:38. Fifty-seven seconds later, he squeezed off a
3-pointer from the right corner. Swish. Fifty-four seconds after
that, Langdon squeezed off another 3 from the right side. An entire
86 seconds elapsed before Langdon dropped a bomb from the left
side.
</P>
<P>
   The senior had shown the way to a 16-11 lead that grew to 43-31
by halftime. Langdon scored 47 points in the two regional games at
the Meadowlands. He needed only 21 shots to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a little nervous at the beginning of the game,''
Krzyzewski said. ``Trajan wasn't, but I sensed they were ... not
afraid. They were young. How Trajan went into that spree was bigger
than the points, because it really settled everybody down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Devils wound up shooting a free-and-easy 60 percent
from the field. They slashed to the basket and they passed, getting
19 of their 27 field goals off assists. The Owls, on the other
hand, generated just about all of their offense on solo efforts (25
baskets, only 10 assists). Temple forward Mark Karchner missed 18
of 25 shots. The entire Duke team missed 18 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is equipped to play at the highest level of
basketball right now,'' Chaney said. ``Not just physically, but
their will and their skill. Believe me, there's something up here
... they've got wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the Blue Devils can be beaten. Somebody has, and that
somebody was Cincinnati, which didn't make it past the first
weekend of the NCAAs. The defeat came 32 games ago. By two points.
In November.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that the cast of players is as talented as any
Steven Spielberg ever assembled. The coach is college basketball's
answer to Spielberg, an artistic success who doesn't waste his time
with unworthy projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got better athletes than any other team that we ever
played,'' Temple guard Rasheed Brokenborough said.
</P>
<P>
   The most sublime moment of Duke prowess came in the final
seconds of the first half, when freshman forward Corey Maggette set
his sights on a missed 3-point attempt by William Avery. The
6-foot-6 Maggette soared over 6-10 Lamont Barnes, slammed the ball
into the basket and did a chinup while everybody scurried for
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the first telltale sign of Temple trouble came when
Langdon flew off a screen from Chris Burgess to shoot his first
3-pointer. Barnes fought through the screen just in time to take a
good close look at Langdon making the first of five `3's'. At the
time, Chaney scolded his player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had practiced very hard to try and get them to understand
that (Langdon) only needed to look through a hole in the needle to
see the basket,'' Chaney said. ``There's no way I could describe
it, no way I could explain it, no way I could demonstrate it in
practice to get it across. The only thing I wanted to do was to get
into Lamont's head to maybe give it an extra amount of effort. And
even if he had done that, I still would have given him hell, and
Langdon still would have made the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Campbell can be reached by calling 518-454-5496.
</P>
</TEXT>
