A0894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FAJITAS-RECIPES-     03-23 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FAJITAS-RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORTUGA'S COASTAL CANTINA GREAT GUACAMOLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
(See FOOD-FAJITAS) c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (This recipe is from Tortuga's Coastal Cantina in Houston) &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 8 medium-size ripe avocados &QL; 
1/2 cup diced onion &QL; 
Juice of 1/4 large lemon (1 tablespoon) &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon ground black pepper &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon garlic powder &QL; 
1 teaspoon hot red pepper sauce &QL; 
1 cup diced tomato &QL; 
Finely chopped cilantro to taste &QL; 
Fresh tortilla chips &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut avocados in half. Remove pits. Scoop pulp into a large
mixing bowl. Add onion, lemon juice, salt, pepper, garlic powder
and pepper sauce. Mash ingredients with a potato masher, leaving a
few small chunks of avocado. Spread tomato and cilantro liberally
over top. Serve chilled with chips, or use as a garnish for
fajitas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAJITA MARINADE &QL; 
 &QL; 
(This recipe is from Carlos Antonio Rios, a photographer at the
Houston Chronicle.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
4 cups light soy sauce (the dark, imported kind is too strong) &QL; 
1 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon each: garlic powder and onion powder &QL; 
8 tablespoons (1/2 cup) fresh lemon juice &QL; 
4 teaspoons ground ginger &QL; 
Skirt steaks, 3/4 inch thick (each 1-pound steak will serve 3) &QL; 
Flour tortillas, warmed &QL; 
Prepared pico de gallo or picante sauce &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine soy sauce, brown sugar, garlic and onion powders, lemon
juice and ginger in jar; shake to mix ingredients and dissolve
sugar. Let marinade stand in sealed jar overnight. Reserve 1 cup.
Pour remainder over steak. Marinate, covered, in refrigerator 2
hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Remove steak from marinade. Grill over very hot coals a short
time; it should take only about 10 minutes per 3/4-inch-thick
steak. Brush meat with reserved marinade 2 or 3 times while
cooking. Chop meat with a cleaver into thin strips. Fold into
tortillas and serve with pico de gallo.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 quart, enough to marinate 3 pounds of steak (3 to
4 steaks).
</P>
<P>
   Note: As a safety precaution, do not reuse liquid in which steak
has been marinated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEEF FAJITAS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Dictionary of American Food and Drink'' by John
Mariani (Hearst Books, $19.95). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1/2 cup fresh lime juice &QL; 
1 tablespoon crushed garlic or 1 teaspoon garlic powder &QL; 
1/4 cup each: vegetable oil and white vinegar &QL; 
1 (1-pound) beef skirt steak, about 3/4 inch thick &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mix lime juice, garlic, oil and vinegar in glass container or
resealable plastic bag; place steak in container. Marinate,
covered, 2 hours or overnight in refrigerator. Drain steak; discard
marinade. Grill steak over hot coals. Cut steak into strips and
serve in flour tortillas. Makes 3 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LA MANSION'S CHICKEN FAJITAS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Accent mark needed over o in La Mansion)
</P>
<P>
   (This recipe is from La Mansion del Rio in San Antonio, Texas) &QL; 
 &QL; 
1/2 cup fresh lime juice &QL; 
1 tablespoon each: chopped garlic and black pepper &QL; 
6 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
4 tablespoons chopped cilantro &QL; 
Salt to taste &QL; 
2 pounds skinless, boneless chicken breasts &QL; 
Flour tortillas, warmed &QL; 
Toppings: shredded lettuce, tomato, pico de gallo, guacamole, sour
cream &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine lime juice, garlic, pepper, oil, cilantro and salt.
Marinate chicken, covered, in refrigerator 1 hour or overnight.
Grill over hot coals or mesquite wood until done. Cut into thin
strips. Place on tortillas and add toppings as desired. Makes 4 to
6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CARMELO'S ITALIAN RESTAURANT DUCK FAJITAS ITALIANA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This recipe is from Carmelo Mauro of Carmelo's Italian
Restaurant in Houston.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 ounces each: brandy and balsamic vinegar &QL; 
2 (8-ounce) boneless duck breasts &QL; 
12 corn tortillas, heated &QL; 
 &QL; 
Carmelo's Italian Spicy Green Fajita Sauce (recipe follows) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pour brandy and vinegar into glass container or resealable
plastic bag. Add duck. Marinate, covered, in refrigerator 3 hours.
Grill duck over coals as desired. Carmelo's has a wood grill and
uses mesquite wood; pecan also could be used. Slice duck thinly. To
serve, place duck in corn tortillas; add Fajita Sauce. Makes 4
servings (3 fajitas each).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Carmelo's Italian Spicy Green Fajita Sauce &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
3 tablespoons chopped white onion &QL; 
6 green tomatoes, chopped &QL; 
1 garlic clove &QL; 
10 chopped basil leaves &QL; 
1 teaspoon each: sugar, salt, black pepper and red pepper flakes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in skillet; saute onion until golden. Add tomatoes;
saute 4 to 5 minutes. Add garlic and basil, then sugar. Stir in
salt, pepper and pepper flakes. Pour cooked sauce into an electric
blender; blend 1 minute or until smooth. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHRIMP FAJITAS &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 pound medium shrimp, peeled and deveined (see note) &QL; 
5 tablespoons oil, divided &QL; 
2 tablespoons each: cornstarch and fresh lemon juice &QL; 
1 teaspoon each: garlic powder and seasoned salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon each: crushed oregano and ground black pepper &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon liquid smoke flavoring (optional) &QL; 
1 cup each: green bell pepper strips, thin onion wedges and thin
tomato wedges &QL; 
Mild chunky taco salsa &QL; 
Corn or flour tortillas, warmed &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, combine shrimp, 2 tablespoons oil, cornstarch,
lemon juice, garlic powder, seasoned salt, oregano, pepper and
smoke flavoring. Marinate, covered, 2 to 8 hours in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   In 10-inch skillet, heat remaining oil until very hot. Saute
shrimp just until they turn opaque; remove from pan. In drippings,
saute bell pepper and onion until crisp-tender. Return shrimp to
skillet. Add tomato and 1/2 cup salsa. Simmer, tossing shrimp and
vegetables 1 minute longer. Serve immediately with tortillas and
additional salsa. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If desired, substitute 1 pound beef skirt steak or
skinless, boneless chicken breast for shrimp. Cut across the grain
into 1/2-inch strips. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRINGO'S MEXICAN KITCHEN PICO DE GALLO &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 cup diced Roma tomatoes &QL; 
1/2 cup diced white onion &QL; 
1 tablespoon each, chopped: garlic, cilantro and jalapeno &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lime juice &QL; 
Salt and ground black pepper to taste &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine tomatoes, onion, garlic, cilantro, jalapeno and lime
juice in bowl; mix. Add salt and pepper. Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
