<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FAJITAS-TIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKING TIPS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ A hot fire and short cooking time are the secrets to success
in grilling fajitas. Beef should be no more than 3/4 inch thick and
should be quickly seared over very hot coals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flank steak, boneless sirloin, tenderized round steak, or
boneless chicken breast strips or chunks may be substituted for
skirt steak. Rub with fajita seasonings; marinate meat several
hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   _ For marinade, use bottled fajita marinade or seasoning,
bottled barbecue sauce or lime juice. A typical marinade includes
lime juice, garlic, a little oil, and often beer and chopped
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   _ Accompany with Pico de Gallo or Salsa Cruda (fresh tomato,
onion, lime juice and cilantro relish); Salsa Roja (a hotter red
sauce) or picante sauce; Salsa Verde (a mild green chili salsa);
guacamole; sour cream; shredded cheese (such as Cheddar, Monterey
Jack or Mexican blend); beans and rice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
