<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FAJITAS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAJITAS: TEX-MEX FAVORITE HAS MANY VARIATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Fajitas have earned their stripes as a favorite
Tex-Mex food _ as common as tacos and enchiladas.
</P>
<P>
   Like other legendary dishes, such as chili, fajitas have an
obscure origin. In the early 1970s, they were just a glimmer on the
culinary horizon in Houston restaurants. The forerunner of fajitas,
Tacos al Carbon, were introduced to the world on the menu at the
original Ninfa's Restaurant on the edge of downtown Houston in July
1973.
</P>
<P>
   They were created at the suggestion of a customer, Glenn Smith.
On his return from a trip to Mexico City, he asked the Ninfa's
staff to slice the carne asada (steak) so he could make his own
tacos. They added some accompaniments _ cilantro, onion, tomatoes,
serrano chilies, sour cream and cheese _ and it became a favorite,
says Froilan ``Froggie'' Hernandez, who was general manager of
Ninfa's at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Ninfa's created a variation of tacos al carbon with
grilled meat strips, condiments and flour tortillas. Owner Ninfa
Laurenzo approved, and they were added to the menu as Fajitas for
One, Fajitas for Two, etc. Later that year, chicken and pork
fajitas were added,
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, people stumbled over the pronunciation.
(``No, sir, that's pronounced fah-HEE-tas, not fah-GEE-tas.'')
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the dish grew even more, John Mariani writes
in ``The Dictionary of American Food and Drink'' (Hearst Books,
$19.95) after the Hyatt Regency Hotel in Austin, Texas, featured
them as fajitas. By 1982, the hotel was selling 13,000 orders a
month. The first reference in the Houston Chronicle Food section
files _ ``flajitas'' _ was in 1977. They were described as ``a
Tex-Mex beef and tortilla sandwich,'' and the recipe called for
boneless sirloin instead of the characteristic skirt steak or
``faja,'' which gives the dish its name. ``Faja'' derives from the
Spanish word for girdle or belt; the meat is the supportive organ
covering the diaphragm of the steer.
</P>
<P>
   Like brisket, skirt steak has a layer of fat that should be
trimmed. It's also important to trim off any membrane covering the
meat, or it may be somewhat chewy.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1984 interview, Gilbert Cuellar, founder of El Chico Corp.,
says fajitas were seldom heard of before 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Mexican-Americans grew up eating a similar dish called
carne asada, a term meaning roasted meat,'' Cuellar says.
</P>
<P>
   Cuellar says the tradition of marinating thinly pounded skirt
steak, whatever it is called, to tenderize it and then grilling it
began with Mexican ranch workers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexican immigrants in the 1940s often worked in ranches in
West Texas near the Mexican border. When a steer was butchered, the
workers were given the least desirable parts _ the head, intestines
and skirt steak. Skirt steak, of course, was a delicacy compared to
the head and intestines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The workers would pound out the meat and marinate it, usually
in lime juice, to tenderize it. Then they would cook it over an
open fire and serve it with condiments rolled in a flour tortilla
...''
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, restaurants (and meat markets) could hardly give
skirt steak away, says Larry Forehand, founder and vice-chairman of
Casa Ole Restaurants, which opened in 1973 and added fajitas to the
menu in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, fajitas cost 20 cents a pound. Now, fajitas
are more $2 per pound,'' Forehand says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fajita really isn't a tender cut of meat. It's the
tenderizer and the marinade that make it taste great.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, only beef has a fajita, but the term has evolved to
cover meats, including chicken, seafood (even lobster) and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can wrap it in a tortilla, it's a fajita,'' says
Forehand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
