<HEADLINE>
ABOUT THE DUKE. . .AND `DUKES OF HAZZARD'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: A 1970 newspaper article from the National Tattler says that
John Wayne received Oscar nominations for ``True Grit,'' ``Sands of
Iwo Jima'' and ``Blue Bonnett.'' Do you have any information about
this third film?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.S., Whitehall, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Internet Movie Database turns up only one film close to
that title: ``The Blue Bonnet.'' This silent movie was released in
1919, seven years before Wayne made his acting debut in ``Brown of
Harvard'' as ``Yale football player No. 35.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne received two Best Actor Oscar nominations, winning for
``True Grit'' in 1970 and being nominated for ``Sands of Iwo Jima''
in 1950. Broderick Crawford won for ``All the King's Men'' that
year.
</P>
<P>
   A 1961 Best Picture nomination went to ``The Alamo,'' a film
that Wayne directed, produced and starred in.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Movie Database is published on the World Wide Web
at www.imdb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We're huge fans of ``Dukes of Hazzard,'' especially my son.
He watches every evening with his two die-cast General Lee cars,
and even sleeps with them. Where can we write to their fan club?
</P>
<P>
   _ V.B., New Philadelphia, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to The Dukes of Hazzard Fan Club, Box 29154, Chicago,
Ill. 60629-9998, or send e-mail to dukesclub(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Members pay $15 per year and receive a quarterly newsletter and
a chance to purchase episode videos and the ``Dukes of Hazzard''
animated series.
</P>
<P>
   The series, which originally aired from 1979 to 1985, is
broadcast twice a day on The Nashville Network.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is David Letterman credited as Earl Hofert in the movie
``Cabin Boy''?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Earl Hofert is the name of David's maternal grandfather, and
there's also an uncle named Earl Hofert Jr. Letterman has used that
name occasionally since ``Late Night With David Letterman,'' where
he would sometimes call himself Earl Hofert in skits.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman also was credited as Hofert in ``Beavis and Butt-Head
Do America,'' the 1996 film in which he provided the voice for
``Motley Crue Roadie No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
