A0912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SERIES-PREVIEWS-HN     03-23 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SERIES-PREVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC'S TWO NEW SERIES ARE IN DIRE NEED OF PATIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it too early for a ``Seinfeld'' imitator? Can the acerbic and
weird Norm Macdonald carry a show all by himself?
</P>
<P>
   Those are the questions ABC is no doubt fretting over as it
launches two new series on Wednesday. It wasn't that long ago that
ABC was struggling so badly it didn't want to keep any of its new
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Now, flush from a great development season, the network's newest
problem is its irritating tendency to kill shows too quickly _
hello ``Cupid.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not bode well for the network's latest offerings,
``It's Like, You Know ... '' and ``The Norm Show,'' both in dire
need of patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Like, You Know ... '' _ yet another poorly named ABC
series _ comes from Peter Mehlman, who wrote for ``Seinfeld'' for
six seasons. The knee-jerk reaction to this show is to say it's
``Seinfeld West,'' and in many ways that's true. Mehlman's voice is
so Seinfeldian that when these new characters open their mouths and
ask whether the letter Q comes too early in the alphabet, a
Jerry-rigged bell in your head goes off.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is giving ``It's Like, You Know ... '' a six-week run, and
rumors are already flying that the network doesn't know how to
promote it _ true _ or really believe in it. We'll see soon enough.
But those seeking something a little different need to give this
show a chance. All the elements are in place.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is simple enough. A die-hard New Yorker named Arthur
(Chris Eigeman) goes to Los Angeles to write a book about how
people can stomach living in the entertainment _ and smog _ capital
of the world, even though he's never been there himself.
</P>
<P>
   He's staying with a friend, Robbie (Steven Echholdt), who got
rich by turning the Jewish High Holy Days into a ``Pay-Per-Jew'' TV
event so no one needs to leave home.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Robbie's good friend Shrug (Evan Handler) is a trust
funder with a lot of rootless stress. Both do nothing but drink a
lot of water and celebrity-spot in L.A. _ which is perfect because
their next-door neighbor is Jennifer ``Dirty Dancing'' Grey, who
plays herself in this series to marvelous effect.
</P>
<P>
   She's had a nose job, see, and now no one recognizes her.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Seinfeld'' were a show about nothing _ not true, but go
with it _ then ``It's Like, You Know ... '' is a show about doing
nothing in Los Angeles, a city filled with peculiar ticks found
nowhere else. In one episode, the entire 22 minutes is spent with
the gang watching a high-speed freeway chase, a wonderful send-up
of how that city really does shut down for this bizarre modern-day
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Eigeman is wonderful as the fish-out-of-water who can't fathom
why people are so caught up in health food, bottled water, what
cars celebs are driving, tanning, etc. But you know from the pilot
that he'll slowly succumb to the sunny wonderland he despises in
his head.
</P>
<P>
   Mehlman has created a show that is searing and seething but also
hilarious and knowing _ giving L.A.-haters all they can handle
while revealing truths people throughout the country can relate to.
The first three episodes are funny if not fall-down hilarious like
``Seinfeld,'' but at least they hint at what can come from shining
a spotlight back on Tinseltown. Whether ABC let's it build an
audience remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the network seems more committed to ``The
Norm Show,'' which is odd in that if you don't like Macdonald,
you're never going to watch. Macdonald, most famous for his
``Weekend Update'' gig on ``Saturday Night Live'' before getting
fired because an NBC honcho didn't think he was funny, is the kind
of comedian you love or hate.
</P>
<P>
   And while he's likely to hold the post-``Drew Carey Show''
audience, he may not attract new fans. Which is a shame because
``The Norm Show'' is tremendously, well, Norm. He's a brilliant
stand-up in that he can make dumb into funny without slapstick
antics and he never leaves you thinking that it's all third-grade
name calling and finger pointing.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald's humor can also seem mean-spirited (although if
someone on ``Frasier'' said it, we'd call it highbrow fun). But TV
needs that kind of attitude. Here's hoping he can shoulder the
burden of a show built around him.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald plays Norm Henderson, an ex-hockey player who bet on
his own games then got busted for tax-evasion. Instead of spending
five years in jail, he's forced to become a social worker. Of
course, being a social misfit, he's lousy at his job but clings to
freedom mostly thanks to co-worker Laurie (Laurie Metcalf).
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot he tells one kid, ``You stole a comb? Run along.
Come back when you've stabbed someone.'' He also works to get a
prostitute a job because, without that, ``look, you're a huge
whore.''
</P>
<P>
   And after Norm takes a man's abused dog, the owner shows up at
his house demanding it back and saying, ``You can't take my dog!''
Norm: ``What do you mean, pal? We're social workers. We can take
children.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll find out later whether those people who never warmed to
Macdonald's sarcastic ``Weekend Update'' will give him another
chance. And we may learn even sooner whether ABC will live up to
its reputation for having an itchy trigger finger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. E-mail:
goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
