<HEADER>
A0922 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-AHI-SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-AHI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe 
 for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success.  
   
   
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: AsiaSF Spices Ahi Burger to Perfection  
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Spicy, vibrant and delicious food is what you'll
find at AsiaSF, and the ahi burger is one example.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matthew Metcalf pairs the ground ahi with a teriyaki glaze and
fresh horseradish-Chinese cabbage slaw on a scallion focaccia roll.
Other dishes at the restaurant include duck quesadillas, spicy
minced chicken in lettuce cups and a trio of baby ice cream cones
for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   The good-humored chef is fighting an uphill battle for
recognition, however. He's competing with a sexy room where two of
the walls glow and slowly change from red to pink to gold. And the
central bar, covered in red vinyl, also doubles as a stage for the
entertainers, who also double as waiters. They're ``gender
illusionists,'' meaning they're guys who dress up and perform in a
variety of outfits from outrageous to sexy. However, it's
sophisticated and all-around fun.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the end, Metcalf's food really does upstage the
``girls.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  AsiaSF, 201 Ninth St. (at Howard), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 255-2742. Dinner Wednesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE SECRETS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The tuna.  &LR; Use only top-grade fish. To save time, ask your
fishmonger to prepare the fillets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The food processor.  &LR; Pulse only a couple of times so the meat
is in tiny chunks. It shouldn't be pureed or smooth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The oil.  &LR; Use peanut oil, which has a higher smoking point than
other oils. The burgers need the high heat to sear the outside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The standing time.  &LR; Forming the burgers several hours before
cooking allows the flavors to become infused throughout. Letting
the burgers stand a minute or two after cooking helps redistribute
the juices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ASIASF'S AHI BURGERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ingredients: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ahi tuna (preferably grade No.1)
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch scallions, trimmed and thinly sliced on the bias
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons peeled and chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   6 sesame rolls
</P>
<P>
   Peanut oil as needed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Slaw &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 head napa cabbage
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peeled and finely grated fresh horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Teriyaki Glaze &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peeled and chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch mixed with 1 tablespoon cold water
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Instructions: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the tuna:  &LR; Carefully remove all the skin and the
deep red meat that runs down the side of the fish. Cut the fish
into 3/4-inch cubes and place in a food processor. Pulse quickly 2
or 3 times. Scrape down the sides of the work bowl and pulse again
once or twice. This is very important in order not to over-process
the fish. The fish should still be in little chunks, but should
hold together when formed into a patty. Transfer to a bowl. Add
scallions, garlic, ginger and Worcestershire sauce; mix gently by
hand until incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   Form the meat into 6 patties, place on a plate, cover with
plastic wrap and refrigerate for a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the slaw:  &LR; Remove the darker green leaves from the
cabbage, then cut the head in half lengthwise. Remove the core.
Place a cabbage half cut-side down on a cutting board. Starting at
the end opposite the base, slice the cabbage into thin ribbons.
Place in a large mixing bowl. Repeat with the other half.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the carrots and using a mandoline, cut into julienne
strips, or grate on the large holes of a box grater. Add to the
cabbage, along with the horseradish, vinegar, salt and sugar; mix
well. Let stand for 1 hour. Check for seasoning and adjust as
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the glaze:  &LR; Combine the soy sauce, brown sugar, oil,
garlic, ginger, sherry and vinegar in a saucepan. Bring to a boil
over high heat. Reduce heat to a simmer, then slowly add the
cornstarch/water mixture, whisking constantly. Bring to a boil;
remove from heat. The glaze will thicken as it cools. (It should be
the consistency of ketchup. If it is not thick enough, simply
repeat the process, adding a little more cornstarch/water mixture.)
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 cups glaze. Store any leftovers in the refrigerator for
up to 3 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the burgers:  &LR; Warm the rolls in a preheated 350-degree
oven.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a nonstick saute pan over high heat. Add enough peanut oil
to just coat the bottom of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Season the ahi patties with salt and pepper and place in the
pan, but do not crowd. Fry for about 45 seconds on each side for
medium-rare.
</P>
<P>
   For each burger, place an ahi patty on the bottom half of a
roll, spoon on 1 tablespoon of the teriyaki glaze and a half-inch
layer of slaw. Replace the top half of the roll. Insert 4 small
sandwich picks in the top of the roll, centering one in each
quadrant. Cut the sandwich into quarters and arrange on a plate,
cut sides facing out. Garnish with the extra slaw.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 445 calories, &LR;   &LR; 43 g protein, 48 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 9 g fat (2 g saturated), 68 mg cholesterol, 3247 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 5 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
