<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-23 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELEANOR'S EXAMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hillary Clinton may chat with the ghost of Eleanor
Roosevelt in the White House corridors, but Elizabeth Dole also has
much in common with Franklin Roosevelt's intelligent,
independent-minded wife.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelts are endlessly fascinating. No matter how many
books are written and television shows aired about them, we are
always captivated by some surprising and unexplored facet of their
extraordinary lives. In ``Eleanor: An American Love Story,'' a
charming new musical that premiered last week at Ford's Theater in
Washington, we are treated to yet another nostalgic look at how
they got to the White House and stayed there until his death.
</P>
<P>
   The musical traces Eleanor's evolution from shy young idealist
to pragmatic political companion and prominent crusader for social
justice. Her transformation into a national figure in her own right
came slowly, as she learned to speak effectively in public forums
and to ignore the social and family pressures that initially
inhibited her.
</P>
<P>
   She did not fully emerge until FDR moved into the political
limelight as New York's governor, disabled by being confined to a
wheelchair after his bout with polio. She became essential to his
aspirations, traveling around the country and carrying his message
where his legs would not let him go.
</P>
<P>
   At first she said, ``My husband thinks ... '' Then, as she grew
bolder, she said, ``My husband and I think ... '' By the time the
couple reached the White House, she was saying, ``I think.''
</P>
<P>
   In this gradual transformation, Eleanor is more like Elizabeth
Dole than Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Hillary Rodham graduated from law school and
married Bill Clinton, she has had no hesitation about speaking her
mind in public. She has been blessed with the self-confidence and
courage that did not come naturally to the repressed Eleanor.
</P>
<P>
   As a working mother with her own professional credentials,
Hillary Clinton has never played the customary wifely role as
silent helpmate. We have always known where she stands. She
campaigned as Bill Clinton's intellectual equal and tackled
controversial public policy issues from the minute she had access
to the political forum afforded the wife of the Arkansas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, however, has followed a more traditional path to
prominence. Although, like Hillary, she is a lawyer who has never
been a stay-at-home housewife, she has frequently put her own
career on hold in order to help her husband. And she has seldom
expressed her own views, preferring to hide behind his.
</P>
<P>
   She left her job at the Federal Trade Commission to campaign for
Bob Dole's losing 1980 presidential campaign. As secretary of
transportation, she resigned from the Cabinet to campaign again for
him when he ran for president in 1988. And she took a leave of
absence from the American Red Cross to campaign with him after he
finally won the Republican presidential nomination in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As Eleanor Roosevelt did, she often campaigned alone, extending
her husband's message to groups and towns that he could not visit
himself. But she did not express her own thoughts; she quoted her
husband's. When she spoke at the 1996 GOP convention, the opinions
she ventured were in praise of his qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole's popularity, in fact, has been based in part on
the fact that although she has had a distinguished career as a
high-ranking political appointee, she is not perceived as a threat,
as Hillary Clinton has sometimes seemed to be.
</P>
<P>
   She has stood beside her man rather than behind him, but she has
regularly deferred to him. Until now, she has been content to be
the junior partner.
</P>
<P>
   Only now, as Elizabeth Dole moves toward a presidential race of
her own, will she be forced to take that final step toward
independent leadership that Eleanor Roosevelt made so long ago. She
is going to have to say, ``I think ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Does Elizabeth disagree with Bob on any of the major issues at
stake in the 2000 campaign? We do not know. But she will never be
elected president if she merely parrots her husband's thinking. The
voters, remember, rejected his views when he sought the presidency
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   We know that Eleanor disagreed sometimes with Franklin, pushing
him toward humane domestic policies, better opportunities for women
and vigorous internationalism. We know that Hillary and Bill
sometimes disagree, too, and that he has bowed to her political
judgment numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   We do not know whether Elizabeth has exerted much influence over
Bob because they have always put up a united front. Finally,
however, she will have to speak for herself. It should be good
listening. Eleanor would be pleased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
