<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: This occasional series profiles Bay Area cooks and 
 their renovated kitches.  
   
   
 COOKS' KITCHENS: PlumpJack Chef Mixes Tradition With Innovation  
   
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 NAPA VALLEY, Calif.  _ It's fitting that there is a baby rocking in
a cradle in Maria Helm's kitchen. It's equally fitting that little
Emma Louise Sinskey's cradle is mechanized.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That mixture of tradition and innovation is what characterizes
the kitchen and home of the executive chef of PlumpJack
cafes/Balboa Cafe and her husband, winery owner Robert Sinskey,
crafted on the site of an old barn in the Carneros district of Napa
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Sinskey built the rustic house while he was still
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why there was only one bedroom,'' albeit a large one,
Helm says, laughing and guiding guests up the open stairs from the
ground floor. That ground floor is essentially one large room, with
areas for cooking, dining and lounging.
</P>
<P>
   More upstairs rooms are under construction, as is a spacious
pantry behind the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a work in progress,'' Helm says. The kitchen,
however, is finished. And this is the room that defines Helm's home
and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Helm, the exacting chef, has made sure her home kitchen
equipment is as good as what she's used in top-flight restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new 60-inch Viking stove with six burners, griddle and
grill, all of which ``are in use all the time,'' she says. There is
the no-nonsense Euroflair Frigidaire refrigerator, backed up in the
pantry by a General Electric refrigerator wide enough to
accommodate sheet pans. There are three sinks, one equipped with a
large professional sprayer, and there is an eight-foot work island.
The kitchen is no longer all cement, as had been originally, but
has country pine cabinetry, with two enormous drawers ``which I
still have to organize,'' she confides.
</P>
<P>
   The island has been raised to 37 inches _ from the standard 34 _
because Helm and Sinskey are tall and because the height of the
cement floor has in effect been raised by the sturdy professional
rubber mats that soften its harsh impact on cooks' backs and feet.
</P>
<P>
   Radiant heat also provides comfort, and a stain finish makes the
flooring less industrial looking. The cement work counters are
stained, too, not with a commercial finish but as a result of their
everyday use for food preparation.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Helm, whose idea of a home kitchen is decidedly
not of the slick shelter magazine genre. State-of-the-art
appliances are integrated with old objects and materials _ genuine
antique and just plain recycled.
</P>
<P>
   There's a commodious old Irish cupboard, for example, with its
mottled green paint unretouched. The same goes for an Irish dairy
cabinet with grooves that once held milk pans; an English pine
baker's table and, in the living area, a large counter from a
butcher shop in France.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinskey winery on the Silverado Trail, just the other side
of the Napa Valley, has also yielded material for the owners' home,
like the large teak doors found a new life as cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   Helm spends a fair amount of time at the winery, overseeing
cooking classes, special dinners and the menu offered in the
tasting room. ``Robert,'' she says of her husband, ``feels that
wine needs food'' _ specifically, his wife's kind of food.
</P>
<P>
   It's no quirk that Helm, a top-flight chef (she won national
acclaim at Sherman House in Pacific Heights before joining the
PlumpJack operation with its venues in San Francisco and Squaw
Valley), feels at home in the country. Her cooking reflects her
family's part-German heritage (``I love braised dishes'') and her
love of Italian and French peasant food.
</P>
<P>
   What Helm generally cooks at home is rustic, regional and
seasonal. It's the kind of food on which she plans to raise her
children _ she'd like future siblings for Emma Louise, ``a real
family,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Helm has a good start on that part of her life's ambition. Emma
Louise _ who travels with Mom to work in the city, in the Sierras
and at the winery _ is such a laid-back baby that a couple of
future brothers or sisters isn't intimidating. And the Helm-Sinskey
home boasts the kind of kitchen that can well accommodate that
family.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE GOOD AND THE BAD OF THE NEW KITCHEN &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; P ut together the culinary sensitivities of a chef and the
trained eye of a photographer, and there isn't much chance that
their joint kitchen design would go awry.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no surprise that Maria Helm, executive chef of the
Plumpjack/Balboa cafes, and her husband, Robert Sinskey, winery
owner and professional photographer, find little _ if anything _
they would change in the kitchen of their home in Napa's Carneros
region.
</P>
<P>
   Sinskey ``framed'' every window in the house he built on the
site of an old barn behind a small farmhouse, which the couple use
as a guest house. So views from the kitchen _ and the rest of the
home _ make the most of the surrounding vineyards, trees and gently
rolling hills. They set the rural mood the couple aimed for in
their home.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights that Helm loves in her kitchen include:
</P>
<P>
   Lots of space _ ``much more than at PlumpJack in the city'' _
organized for maximum efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Her six-burner Viking stove with griddle and grill.
</P>
<P>
   A pantry refrigerator wide enough to accommodate sheet pans.
</P>
<P>
   A chain-hung rack over the work counter for drying herbs in
large bunches.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of wood _ much of it old _ in built-in cabinets and in
antiques such as an Irish kitchen cupboard and a French butcher's
counter.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling racks that can hold ingredients and finished dishes and
can also be rolled to the dining area as instant buffets.
</P>
<P>
   What she would change if she had to do it all over again:
</P>
<P>
   A bigger refrigerator near the stove and work counter.
</P>
<P>
   Even more storage space.
</P>
<P>
   The final word on kitchen design, she says: Your lifestyle and
cooking style, rather than current design trends, should determine
the look and feel of your kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; _ Karola Saekel &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RED WINE-BRAISED OXTAILS
</P>
<P>
   Helm serves this with homemade spaetzle. A commercial
small-shape pasta would also complement this saucy dish.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds meaty oxtails
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 carrots, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 stalks celery, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 large shallots, peeled and cut in medium dice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound small crimini mushrooms, stems cut even with tops
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped, or 3/4 cup chopped
canned tomatoes such as Pomi brand
</P>
<P>
   4 cups dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf (fresh if available)
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh thyme, or 2 teaspoons dried
</P>
<P>
   Chopped Italian parsley for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a heavy saucepan. Season the oxtails with salt
and pepper; add to the pan and brown on all sides. Add the carrots,
celery, shallots and mushrooms; cook over high heat until the
vegetables are golden.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomatoes and wine, bring to a boil and cook over high
heat until liquids are reduced by three quarters. Add the bay leaf
and thyme and enough water to cover well. Bring to boil, then
reduce heat and simmer, partially covered, for 4 hours, checking
several times and adding more water if the meat is not covered by
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Check the meat for doneness. Adjust seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Serve over spaetzle or other noodles. Garnish with chopped
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   If you wish, let the oxtails cool, then remove and discard
bones; return the meat to the broth.
</P>
<P>
   This dish reheats extremely well, and cooling also allows you to
remove excess fat from the broth.
</P>
<P>
   Served 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 520 calories, &LR;   &LR; 70 g protein, 16 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 19 g fat (6 g saturated), 157 mg cholesterol, 208 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPAETZLE
</P>
<P>
   Cookware shops carry spaetzle makers, but Helm says with a
little practice, you can make this German noodle in the simple,
old-fashioned way without special utensils.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   13/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten with 3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour, salt, baking powder and nutmeg in a bowl.
Make a well in the center and add the beaten eggs, mixing well.
Cover with plastic wrap and let rest for at least 20 minutes. The
batter should be elastic and thick.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large, shallow pot of salted water to a boil. Tilt the
dough bowl until the batter reaches the edge. Dip a small knife
into the boiling water and scrape off small pieces of dough,
sliding the knife along the edge of the bowl to ease dough pieces
into the water. The dough pieces will rise to the surface when they
are cooked; remove them with a slotted spoon and place in a warm
bowl. Or place them in ice-water, then drain and reserve for
reheating later by briefly sliding back into boiling water. Drain
well before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Variation:  &LR; 1/4 cup chopped fine herbs or chopped truffle peel
may be added to the batter; the finished spaetzle may be drizzled
with truffle oil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 145 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 27 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 2 g fat (1 g saturated), 70 mg cholesterol, 570 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ESCAROLE &AMP; ENDIVE SALAD WITH BOSC PEARS
</P>
<P>
   For a heartier version, blue cheese may be crumbled over the
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 small head escarole
</P>
<P>
   2 heads Belgian endive
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe Bosc pears, quartered, cored and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup toasted walnut pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon walnut oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Wash the greens and drain well. Tear the escarole into
bite-sized pieces and place in a salad bowl. Cut the endive in half
and remove the core. Slice crosswise into 1/2-inch pieces. Add to
the salad bowl, along with the pears and walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle with walnut oil and toss. Season with salt, pepper and
sugar; toss again. Add the vinegar and toss once more. Adjust
seasonings to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 125 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 11 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 8 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 5 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALSATIAN APPLE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   This cake has a crumbly texture and rich taste. It's
particularly good served with warm caramel sauce and French vanilla
ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 to 10 Fuji or other firm apples (about 31/2 pounds), peeled,
cored and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups panko or other dry breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees. Grease (or coat with cooking
spray) an 8-inch springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the apples, sugar, water, lemon juice and cinnamon stick
in a saucepan. Cover and cook until the apples are soft but not
mushy. Uncover the pan during the last few minutes of cooking until
the liquid evaporates. Discard the cinnamon stick. Stir in the
vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a saucepan. Add the crumbs, stirring until
well mixed. Add the ground cinnamon and brown sugar; heat,
stirring, for 2 minutes. Remove from heat and cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle a third of crumb mixture over the bottom of the
springform pan. Top with half of the apples, then sprinkle with
half of the remaining crumbs. Make a final layer of apples and top
with the remaining crumbs. Pat smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for about 45 minutes, until the crumbs are golden.
</P>
<P>
   Cool on a rack, then loosen the edges of the pan and remove the
rim. Cut the cake into wedges (it will be crumbly) and serve with
caramel sauce and vanilla ice cream, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 405 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 72 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 13 g fat (8 g saturated), 32 mg cholesterol, 290 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
