<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OSCARS-ASSESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCARS: PLENTY OF BOMBS WERE DROPPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Never badmouth the Academy Awards. Never call
them stuffy, or predictable, or dull. Never say they honor
big-wallet, safe-vanilla moviemaking over little-wallet films with
big ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Never say the Academy doesn't have a sense of humor, can't
muster the courage to give best picture to a comedy and won't give
a best actor award to a guy with jubilantly bad English.
</P>
<P>
   Don't say those things. At least, not today.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you like in any other year (particularly 1991, the age
of the ``Dances with Wolves'' debacle), but the 1999 version of the
venerable awards show was surprising to the point of post-traumatic
shock.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the '98 broadcast, a politely bloated coronation
ceremony for ``Titanic'' and its self-dubbed ``King of the World,''
James Cameron, Sunday's affair looked like a riot. No one threw any
Molotov cocktails, but plenty of bombs were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least of them was dropped by ``Shakespeare in Love,''
which became the first comedy to win best picture since ``Annie
Hall'' _ released in 1977, as in the Jimmy Carter administration,
as in 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden's literate, passionate flight of fancy triumphed
over the logical favorite, Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' a towering war saga that earned boodles at the box office
and critical raves to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Why did ``Shakespeare'' win? Was it ``Ryan's'' gore?
``Shakespeare's'' romance? The doublets? The dog? Miramax's
megabucks Oscar campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say, but it was probably the words. There's a mad beauty
to Tom Stoppard's screenplay that recalls, if not mimics,
Shakespeare's barmiest dialogue. It's brainy, goofy and crisp, a
``Dumb and Dumber'' for frustrated English majors.
</P>
<P>
   And, like ``Annie Hall'' before it, ``Shakespeare in Love'' is a
comedy with a meaty dramatic core; it's about something. It's deep.
Academy members could vote for it without feeling lightweight or
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   So they did. And ``Shakespeare in Love'' beat ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' And, lo, the people were stunned.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy performed a few other stunning maneuvers Sunday
night. For one thing, it gave directing honors to a filmmaker
(Spielberg) whose movie lost in the best picture category _ a feat
that last occurred in 1990 (technically, the 1989 awards), when
``Driving Miss Daisy'' won best picture, but Oliver Stone won best
director for ``Born on the Fourth of July.''
</P>
<P>
   Such splits occur when voters admire a director's work but don't
quite enjoy it enough to give it best picture. Or maybe they occur
when voters are feeling indecisive and squishy. Nothing happened as
planned Sunday night. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Did anyone think Roberto Benigni had a microscopic smudge of a
chance to win best actor? No. And did he? Yes. Benigni had two
major strikes against him: One, he's a comedian. Two, his film,
``Life is Beautiful,'' is in subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this is not to say that the Academy has any obvious bias
against Italian funnymen, but face it: The best actor award has
never gone to a man in a foreign-language film. Never. Sophia Loren
won the 1961 best actress award, for her performance in Vittorio De
Sica's ``Two Women,'' but no male counterpart had ever before
managed the same trick. And Loren's wasn't a comic role.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are, on a closer look, a few extraordinary
similarities _ beyond the fact that they're both Italian.
(Coincidentally, Loren presented Benigni's foreign-film Oscar.)
``Two Women'' is set during World War II; ``Life is Beautiful'' is
set during World War II. ``Two Women'' follows a mother (Loren) as
she attempts to shield her daughter from the horrors of wartime;
``Life is Beautiful'' follows a father (Benigni) as he attempts to
shield his son from the horrors of wartime.
</P>
<P>
   Benigni's film is indeed a comedy, and his performance is
unquestionably funny, but that's not all it is. Set against the
Holocaust, the movie is a deftly gentle commentary on parental
love; it is as heartbreaking as it is hilarious, worthy of
comparison with Chaplin's silent work.
</P>
<P>
   It defies categorizing. So does ``Shakespeare in Love.'' So does
Spielberg's directing award. And so, for once, does Oscar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
