<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-MAGN-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses 
 more than a half century old.   
   
   
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Buyers Flock to Berkeley Poultry Shop  
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 BERKELEY, Calif. _  Once upon a time, Oakland was dotted with
family-owned poultry markets where a customer could walk in, cast a
critical eye upon the pecking chickens, choose the one that met his
or her standards and have it butchered out back. Today, markets
that butcher on site are as scarce as hens' teeth, but one shop in
Berkeley, Magnani Poultry, is an offshoot of what was typical in
the early part of this century.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Magnani Poultry, which purveyed additive-free poultry and
meats before it was politically correct, there is still the sense
of catering to the customer's needs. You can buy 100 pounds of
beef, 100 roasted chickens _ or just one egg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bone anything at no extra charge,'' says Sharon Magnani
McCormick, ``give free chicken bones for soup and, except for
during Thanksgiving week, will roast any bird to order.''
</P>
<P>
   Some customers buy chicken feet for soup and ask for the
toenails trimmed. ``We do it,'' she says, laughing. ``Magnani is
known for customer service.''
</P>
<P>
   The Magnani name has been trusted in the East Bay for poultry
and meat since 1917, when McCormick's grandfather, Alberto Magnani,
and his four brothers opened Magnani Bros. at a public market in
Oakland. The business wholesaled and retailed fresh-killed chicken,
turkey and duck.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick's father, Atilio (``Babe''), rejoined the family
business after World War II and then worked at Hayward Poultry in
Oakland, his mother-in-law's market. ``Both sides of my family had
chicken shops even before they came here from Lucca, Italy,''
McCormick says.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '70s, Atilio opened his own wholesale-retail shop,
Magnani Poultry, on College Avenue in Oakland, where he built a
fiercely loyal clientele and attracted more family to the business
_ his grandsons, Tim and Terry McCormick, who ran the shop after
Atilio retired in 1984. Terry died in 1990, and Sharon McCormick, a
former reporter for The Chronicle, her husband and their two
daughters joined the business.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to what McCormick calls ``a great staff,'' there is
usually at least one family member helping customers in the small,
narrow, no-frills storefront in Berkeley that is nearly taken up by
meat counter on one side and dry-goods shelves on the opposite.
Red-framed family photos hang on the wall behind the counter, and
brightly colored wood roosters and hens perch here and there.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick's sons opened the Berkeley shop in 1985 because they
saw an opportunity in the area. They closed the College Avenue shop
last year after the 1991 Oakland Hills fire contributed to a steady
loss of business, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were angry when we closed in Oakland,'' McCormick says,
smiling. ``They saw it as their place. And we are more than a shop.
Our customers are like friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends who are hungry to buy. Magnani sells 2,500 fresh turkeys
the week of Thanksgiving. Regulars know that means a line out the
door, a greeting before you step inside and an organized plan for
picking up orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, one customer told me she had a book with her and
was all prepared for the wait,'' McCormick says.
</P>
<P>
   Easter and Passover are another busy season for Magnani, with
roasters and lamb big sellers for Passover, and ham and lamb for
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Year-round strong sellers are the chicken sausages made by Tim
(10 varieties) and the house rotisserie chickens seasoned three
ways. (Top seller: ``original barbecue'' with Italian herbs.) The
turkeys and chickens come from Fulton Valley in Sonoma County;
organic chicken comes from Hoffman Game Birds in Manteca.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the family added meats to the selling roster,
including Harris Ranch beef, pork from Iowa and lamb from a Sonoma
County producer.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick foresees the family's presence in Magnani's future.
Her children are the fourth generation to be involved, and her
teen-age grandson _ the fifth generation _ pitches in during
holidays. McCormick forsees an increase in prepared items for
takeout, such as stuffed flank steak and kebabs _ ``value-added''
items that are ready for busy customers to cook at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
