<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUGS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Would You Like a Side of Flies With That?  
 Celebrity Bug Chef Will Buzz Into Museum  
   
   
 By Holly Ocasio Rizzo  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  On Friday night, David George Gordon will point
his car north from Santa Cruz, where he'll have put a positive spin
on cockroaches for a museum group, and head to the Exploratorium in
San Francisco for one of the insect activities he likes best:
cooking them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; st  &LR;  Then he'll eat them. And he'll invite anyone who cares to
to join him this weekend in the museum's makeshift Green Frog Cafe,
created for the event, ``Eat Your Own Frog Food.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, a naturalist and free-lance writer in Port Townsend,
Wash., used to be a vegetarian but expanded his culinary horizons
while working at an aquarium in Tacoma. The showcase creatures
weren't the fish, which were mostly drab brown, but the undersea
invertebrates. By extension Gordon became interested in the
invertebrates' insect cousins.
</P>
<P>
   As he learned about bugs, he discovered that they're not just
frog food _ they're people food throughout much of the world
because they're plentiful and nutritious. But in Europe and much of
North America, they're viewed as pests and crop destroyers, not
food. However, there are some U.S. entomophagists _ bug eaters _
and they gather to indulge. In mid-June, they dine at a museum
event in New Orleans; in August, at a natural-science museum in
Raleigh, N.C. Many network through ``Food Insect News,'' published
by Montana State University. And many have found new ways to serve
bugs in Gordon's 33-recipe ``The Eat-a-Bug Cookbook'' (Ten Speed
Press, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has become a celebrity bug chef, cooking recently for
Regis Philbin and Kathy Lee Gifford and feeding grasshoppers to
actor George Hamilton, whom he called ``an adventurous eater
because he's been around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Because arthropod entrees are light and served in small
portions, Gordon recommends accompanying them with several salads
and side dishes, with and without bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Wash them down with wine, he says: Pinot Gris with delicately
flavored dragonflies, fruity Sauvignon Blanc with woodsy-tasting
crickets. Broiled centipedes call for Zinfandel or an Australian
Shiraz, but heavier wines, such as Merlot, tend to overwhelm a bug
meal.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up with Gordon at home, where he writes science
articles about sea life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How do you deal with bugs' ickiness factor? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some people are genuinely enthusiastic about eating bugs. But an
incredible number of people on our planet have bug phobias.
</P>
<P>
   I love it, though, when someone tastes something I've cooked and
says, ``Not bad.'' The thing about bugs for most people who don't
like them is the crunch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What's tastiest? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My favorites are wax worms. They're considered a pest by
beekeepers, because they eat the wax in honeycombs. Wax worms out
of the box are great, sort of sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Crickets have a very mild shrimplike flavor. They're a good bug
for starting out because they're available all year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How do you develop recipes? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the recipes come from indigenous cultures. Some of the
other ones I pretty much made up on the spot. But some basics about
bugs are universal, like using a wok and not overcooking them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Do bugs have nutritional value? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dried grasshoppers have something like six times more protein
than beef ounce for ounce. Crickets are rich in calcium, so they
might benefit people who have osteoporosis. Termites are rich in
iron.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Do you catch your own ingredients? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some things, I do _ dragonflies, for example. But I try to steer
people away from collecing their own bugs to eat. There are
endangered insects. And I tell people who do collect insects to do
it away from civilization, because you don't know about bug sprays.
Even if you're an organic gardener, your neighbor might use bug
sprays, and then the bugs crawl into your yard.
</P>
<P>
   I mail-order bugs that are raised for consumption. My favorite
supplier is in North Carolina (Carolina Biological Supply Co., 2700
York Road, Burlington, NC 27215; 800-334-5551). You can get about
3,000 crickets shipped to your home for about $30. You can specify
the growth stage; I like them about 5 weeks old, before they have
wings. About 250 crickets make up a cup for a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Is there anyone who shouldn't eat bugs? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you know you're allergic to shellfish, it's probably not a
good idea to eat bugs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What's up for the Exploratorium visit? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I'll talk a little about insect-eating in other cultures but
mostly about food frogs would eat. Then I'll make Scorpion
Scaloppine, and we'll have Orthopteran Orzo (made with young
crickets) and Wax Worm and White Chocolate Cookies. Not everyone
will get to try the scaloppine, but there should be enough orzo and
cookies for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
GO BITE A BUG
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Dine like frogs do at ``Eat Your Own Frog Food,'' at 1 p.m. and at
3:30 p.m. Saturday and Sunday ( &LR; 3-27, 3-28 &LR; ) at the Exploratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Naturalist David George Gordon, author of ``The Eat-a-Bug
Cookbook'' (Ten Speed Press, 1998), will explain what frogs and
toads enjoy eating, then will give attendees the opportunity to
sample Scorpion Scaloppine, Orthopteran Orzo, and Waxworm and White
Chocolate Cookies. All the critters are commercially raised for
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation is part of the museum's exhibit ``Frogs,''
running through September 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Exploratorium is inside the Palace of Fine Arts at 3601 Lyon
St., San Francisco. Admission to the cooking demonstration is free
with regular museum admission. For information, call (415)
561-0360.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
