<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BANKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. BANKS SAY THEY ARE READY FOR THE NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.199 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The biggest threat of the year 2000 on banks is
not a computer breakdown or a power outage, experts say. Instead,
it's the possibility of bank runs and public panic at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nine months before Y2K, one of the biggest concerns
is scam artists getting hold of customers' account numbers by
preying on their fears of Y2K, witnesses told a state legislative
panel Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While some Y2K doomsayers think the nation's banks will not
survive past New Year's Eve, experts said 97 percent of banks in
the country have made great progress toward preparing their
computers for the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry appears well on its way to Y2K compliance,''
Michael Smith, president of the New York Bankers Association, told
the state Senate Committee on Banks and the Senate Committee on
Consumer Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K refers to the problem many computers have accepting 2000 in
programs. Some, instead, will assume the new date is 1900, causing
computers to crash or come up with faulty data. It is expected that
fixing computers in both government and industry will cost hundreds
of billions of dollars, including $9 billion for banks.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K is a problem the banking industry has been working on since
the mid-1990s, said John F. Carter, deputy regional director of the
New York office of Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Of 16,000 banks in the U.S. he said, only two-tenths of 1
percent are considered to have unacceptable Y2K efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has lost a penny in an FDIC deposit in our 66-year
history,'' he said. ``Y2K will not change this fact.''
</P>
<P>
   But some bank customers have lost thousands of dollars in a
recent Y2K scam, said Elizabeth McCaul, acting superintendent of
banks at the state Banking Department.
</P>
<P>
   McCaul declined to say where the scams took place. But now,
banks all over the state are starting to warn their customers about
the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Someone calls a customer, purporting to
work for the customer's bank. The caller tells the customer the
bank is not able to get its accounts Y2K-compliant by the end of
the year and wants to get permission to transfer the customer's
funds to a special Y2K-safe bond account. To do that, the caller
needs the customer's account number.
</P>
<P>
   With the account number, of course, it's a simple matter for the
caller to empty customers' savings before they catch on.
</P>
<P>
   McCaul said customers should be wary of discussing finances with
any stranger. But they should continue to have faith in the banking
system, even small banks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before anyone heard of Y2K, all banks, large and small, have
had contingency plans in place for natural disasters like fires,
floods, tornadoes and earthquakes,'' she said. ``Just think back to
the ice storm in the North Country last winter. Small banks were
among the first to open.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks are letting their customers know about their progress by
distributing handouts with monthly statements. Some banks are also
making contingency plans like buying generators and cellular phones
in case power goes out for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Robinson, president and CEO of Cohoes Savings Bank, said
his bank is in the midst of planning for its worst-case Y2K
scenario. No bank employees will be allowed to take days off during
the last week of 1999 and the first week of 2000. In addition, one
branch office will soon practice a day of banking without
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like they used to do it,'' he said after the hearing. ``This
bank survived for 140 years without computers. We think we can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   While banks are encouraging customers not to take out more money
than they would need for a long weekend, the Federal Reserve will
release to local banks an extra $50 billion in cash, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the FDIC has 1,400 examiners in the process of auditing
banks to determine how ready they are for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said most banks will be finished testing their computer
programs by the end of March and will be ready for the last stage
of Y2K compliance _ coming up with contingency plans and making
sure the computers can interface with the rest of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
