<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-RETURNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF PAPER IRS TAX RETURNS MAY BE COMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The days of slaving over tax returns with pencil
and paper appear to be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   If the Internal Revenue Service and Congress have their way, all
of the nation's 200 million tax returns will be filed
electronically _ via computer or telephone _ within a decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS started its electronic filing system, or e-filing, in
the early 1990s with successful pilot programs. Now it has spread
nationwide, with millions of people signing on each year.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 25 million people filed electronically for 1997, paying
$1.6 trillion in taxes to Uncle Sam and getting $52 billion in
refunds.
</P>
<P>
   In the IRS Restructuring and Reform Act last year, Congress
mandated that 80 percent of all tax returns must be filed
electronically by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   To help reach that goal, the IRS has launched a national ad
campaign in all media. Its slogan: ``Click. Zip. Fast Round Trip.''
</P>
<P>
   One poster reads: ``Hey, you'd have your refund at home by
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Most taxpayers who e-file do so through one of 73,000 ``e-file
providers,'' which are accounting firms and other tax preparers
authorized by the IRS. Consumers also can e-file via personal
computer with tax software such as TurboTax, MacInTax or SecureTax.
Still others file their returns by touch-tone telephone _ if they
have incomes under $50,000 and no dependents.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of pluses to e-filing, according to the IRS and
the growing number of CPAs, enrolled agents and other tax preparers
who love the system.
</P>
<P>
   For the IRS, it cuts down on mountains of paperwork. Tax
officials say it's more expensive now to process electronic returns
than paper returns, but the costs will shrink drastically once
everyone starts e-filing.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, e-filing eases the pain of tax preparation.
</P>
<P>
   If Uncle Sam owes you a refund, it comes quickly, within two to
three weeks. In contrast, paper tax returns take six to nine weeks
to process before a refund check is mailed.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers who owe the government money can pay electronically
from their checking or savings account, by credit or debit card
(MasterCard, American Express or Discover) or by check or money
order.
</P>
<P>
   People who e-file also make fewer mistakes. Since they often use
tax preparation software, their error rate of 1 percent is much
lower than the 20 percent rate for paper filings. That means less
contact with the dreaded tax man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wins here,'' said Larry Wright, an IRS spokesman in
Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   While the IRS hails e-filing as the wave of the future, there's
still debate in the tax and accounting field over its merits.
</P>
<P>
   Some tax pros praise e-filing, saying it streamlines their work
and makes clients happy. One accountant said his clientele has
grown 20 percent a year since he began filing their returns by
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marvelous thing that eliminates so much unnecessary
inputting and processing,'' said John Stoller, head of John D.
Stoller CPA Inc. in Encino, Calif., and a big cheerleader for
e-filing who speaks often on the topic at seminars. ``My clients
love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are leery of e-filing at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   Tax preparers who wish to sign up with the IRS as authorized
e-file providers must go through a credit check, fingerprinting and
a criminal background check. Intended or not, this process has a
chilling effect, according to Mary Kay Foss at Marzluft, Giles,
Tulis &AMP; Foss CPAs Inc. in Danville, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   It's also costly for some older accounting firms, which must
upgrade their technology by buying new computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants who use special tax preparation software for IRS
e-filing also must pay the software firms a fee ranging from $2 to
$9 per return.
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle for tax preparers and their corporate clients:
While 2 million businesses e-filed last year through the Electronic
Federal Tax Payment System (EFTPS), many more have shied away from
it.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons? Not all complex business returns can be filed
electronically with the IRS at this point. Corporate bureaucracies
and their technology systems have been slow to deal with the
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Many also fear that electronic filing may make them easier
targets for IRS audits because their financial data are fed
instantly to the IRS. By contrast, it takes several long weeks for
thousands of workers to enter millions of paper tax returns into
IRS databases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appear to be a lot of barriers to acceptance among
CPAs,'' said Curt Olsen, a spokesman for the California Society of
CPAs in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the IRS is happy to let the popularity of e-filing grow
each year through its splashy marketing campaign and positive
word-of-mouth among tax professionals and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The government has no plans yet to use a big hammer _ tax
penalties and sanctions of some sort _ to compel people to file
electronically, IRS official Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of technology is the biggest bugaboo for the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing studies show that most taxpayers still are wary of
using computers for personal finance. The IRS's goal is to develop
services so cheap, simple and secure that people will prefer
e-filing to snail mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
