<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-CHALLENGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOPTIVE PARENTS SURMOUNT ROADBLOCKS TO A NEW FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERFORD, N.Y. _ A month ago they were in a Siberian orphanage,
their most valued possessions the photo albums the three sisters
each slept with. The duplicate collections depicted the home and
faces of a New York couple seeking to become their adopted parents.
</P>
<P>
   This week the girls were sprawled wide-eyed on the carpeted
floor of the living room in the home of Don and Cathy Dessureau,
giggling repeatedly as they pushed a miniature white-gowned doll on
a plastic replica of Cinderella's castle.
</P>
<P>
   Blue lights from the castle towers shone on the radiant faces of
Lena, 11, Katrina, 9, and Genia, 7. The sounds of ``Here Comes The
Bride'' poured from the toy's interior.
</P>
<P>
   For the three sisters, as well as the Dessureaus, this was
indeed a fairy tale come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally we have our lives back again,'' said Don Dessureau,
his eyes welling with tears. ``Once again, we have a family.''
</P>
<P>
   For the girls, who speak almost no English, the need for a bit
of magic is obvious. They had been transported from one of the
harshest places on Earth, where many people have no running water
or electricity and many live in log cabins.
</P>
<P>
   Now they were in the magical kingdom of America, a yellow ranch
house filled with the comfortable trappings of the unpretentious.
The childrens' rooms are overpopulated with Barbie dolls, Teddy
bears and other cuddly wonders. At the orphanage their only toys
were those they made themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, as judged by the various agencies in the United
States and Russia, it's a place where the girls have finally found
the most precious gift of all _ a mother and father who love them.
</P>
<P>
   The Dessureaus, who live in Waterford, a town north of Albany,
had been living in a world of desolation and deprivation not as
immediately apparent. They were looking to adopt to fill a void
created a year ago Easter when they lost their only son David, 13,
in an accident in their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had to do something with our lives, and do it
fast,'' said Cathy, a homemaker, ``because if we didn't we were
going to die.'' They ended up at Children at Heart in
Mechanicville, whose proprietors, Janice and Mark Bergeron, have
now adopted five children of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The price of adoption can be high. Janice Bergeron, an attorney,
said the cost for adopting a young child from Russia, the country
in which they specialize, is roughly $23,000. It can be
significantly less for older children. Both the agency and
Dessureaus declined to discuss how much was spent in this case.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, while thumbing through one of the countless
photo albums they had seen at numerous agencies, Cathy Dessureau
saw a picture of the three girls. She called her husband at work
and he came to look at the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked in their eyes,'' said Don, who is safety manager for
a trucking company, ``and I had a feeling inside of me that those
children needed us as much as we needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   They had originally intended to adopt two children. But the
three girls had requested they be adopted only as a group or not at
all. And that was consistent with both the regulations in Russia
and with the Dessureaus' sense of what was right.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a time of paperwork and waiting and stress
that Cathy Dessureau describes as reminiscent of the pain of
childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already felt love for these girls, and to think maybe we
wouldn't get them was very painful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news came in late January, and on Feb. 18 the
Dessureaus left for their two-day, 19-hour series of flights to
Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   At the orphanage, a clean, well-run brick building, the whole
staff was at the door to meet them. And after taking the couple on
a tour, they were seated in the office and the girls were brought
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were holding each other's hands, looking up at us, and
then looking down. We stared at each other for about 20 minutes,''
Don Dessureau said. ``And then we hugged and I said to myself, `Now
the dream is coming true.'''
</P>
<P>
   After a few days getting acquainted, they were approved to come
home to America. But first, the new parents took their three
daughters out for ice cream _ the first time ever for the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week they were attending the nearby Waterford-Halfmoon
school where they are in the first, third and fourth grades,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   They communicate mostly with sign language, but are quickly
amassing a vocabulary that includes ``drink,'' ``thank you'' and
``Papa.'' But the orphanage had provided them with a solid
educational background, and, Cathy beams proudly, ``they are
already getting A's in math.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And on a recent evening, the sound of their laughter and the
padding of their feet as they ran shoeless from the living room to
a downstairs family room filled the Dessureau household.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooking the scene is a picture of the couple's late son, and
in a nearby shelf, an urn with his ashes.
</P>
<P>
   David had begged his parents to take him to Russia since the
time he attended school in nearby Maplewood with its large
Ukrainian community.
</P>
<P>
   Both parents think he has had a hand in what followed. They note
that Katrina's birthday is the same as David's but a different
year. Genia's birthday is the day David died. The passports on
which the girls came to America were stamped with the same day that
David was baptized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've been guided in all this,'' said Cathy softly,
``both by David and from up above.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
