<HEADLINE>
S.F. PANHANDLERS MAY GET HAND-HELD ATM MACHINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS +
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A proposal to give panhandlers hand-held
machines that accept ATM or credit cards is getting a mixed
reaction from both Mayor Willie Brown and his homelessness
coordinator, Terry Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, called the Benevolending Box Program, is the
brainchild of Karen Gatter, president of Solutions 2000, a company
she founded to address social issues. She hopes to find investors
and form a public-private partnership that will raise money for
shelters and aid the individuals who raise the money.
</P>
<P>
   Gatter would provide the ATM- credit card machines to homeless
people, who would keep 20 percent of the donations they received
and give 80 percent to shelters and other community homeless
programs. A share of the homeless person's 20 percent would help
pay the costs of that person's stay at a homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Gatter said she believes the concept will work because ``a lot
of people want to donate to homelessness but don't feel there's a
way to do it without causing harm to the person. This way the money
goes directly to the shelter, and the homeless person gets a
percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a Band-Aid solution,'' Gatter said. ``What
we're looking at is creating a means for homeless people to sustain
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatter's idea sits on the drawing board as she searches for
support from officials, nonprofit agencies and potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the city's leading homeless advocates calls the idea
bizarre and says the positive response from the mayor is a slap at
those working for genuine, permanent solutions to homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, meanwhile, says he likes the concept of an ATM-type
machine that would accept donations aiding the homeless, but
questions putting the machines in the hands of panhandlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supportive with conditions,'' Hill said. ``We don't want
to endorse any program that pushes panhandling. . . . We like the
machines with merchants on counters so people can make
contributions (to homeless programs) with purchases. But creating
portable ATMs for homeless people to solicit money needs some
thinking through.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 28 letter, the mayor stopped short of endorsing the
part of the plan that would have homeless people soliciting
donations on the streets. He said that particular idea ``requires a
broader policy discussion, which we are eagerly prepared to enter
into.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said one of the problems city officials have with the
proposal is security regarding the use of a debit card.
</P>
<P>
   But Gatter said technology and fingerprinting might eliminate
those fears. Plus, ``the people soliciting funds will be high-level
individuals who have already passed security system checks. This is
an incentive for people to get toward the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   The program would reward people as they raised money and offer
incentives _ such as their own bank account _ to raise more.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone shares Gatter's enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think there's a couple of levels where it's just
bizarre,'' said Paul Boden of the Coalition on Homelessness, who
noted that some supervisors are searching for ways to get
panhandlers off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Boden said the proposal is a slap in the face to advocates and
service providers who are trying to come up with permanent
solutions to homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you get some business person that calls Terry Hill,
sends a memo and dangles money in front of the mayor's office to
have homeless people solicit with debit cards and graduate them in
a class system of shelter programs,'' Boden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (idea) seems to bring in more panhandlers to raise more
money to open more shelters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Brown said he supports the concept, adding, ``We
are committed to help in the development of this unique homeless
mentoring and shelter fund-raising program during the appropriate
phase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
