<HEADLINE>
GAY RIGHTS ADVOCATES TARGET STATES FOR ACTION, AVOID WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Adopting the ``all politics is local''
philosophy, gay rights activists say they are increasingly turning
to state legislatures over Washington power brokers in pushing
their civil rights agendas.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the national weeklong ``Equality Begins at Home''
rally that began Monday, activists plan to converge upon the
capitals of all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   In Bismarck, N.D., the return to local politicking showed up in
the formation of a new gay and lesbian lobbying group. In Hartford,
Conn., it was a rainbowed flag _ symbolizing tolerance for people
of all stripes and colors _ flying over the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   And in Albany, it was 150 activists from across New York pepping
themselves up to talk to their local lawmakers about several
legislative priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we want?'' state Sen. Tom Duane, D, asked the crowd
gathered in the Empire State Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equality!'' they boomed back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When do we want it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now!'' they cried.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan battles in the nation's capital have fueled a growing
frustration with federal lawmakers by gay activists who believe
they have a better chance of being heard closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focusing much more on state legislatures _ it's totally
where the action is,'' said Urvashi Vaid, policy institute director
of the Manhattan-based National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
``Washington is important, but frankly it'll be our state capitals
where we'll win our civil rights. Washington will not lead.
Congress will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year in Albany, two of the three state government
power brokers have moved on a top gay-rights legislative priority _
a bias-crime bill that would heighten penalties for crimes
committed against people specifically because of their race,
religion, gender, sexuality or other characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Democratic-led Assembly and Republican Gov. George
Pataki have proposed to enact a hate-crime bill; the GOP-led Senate
is the last missing link.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, R, has repeatedly opposed
hate crime legislation, expressing concern over targeting the
motive behind a crime rather than the offense. Recently, however,
Bruno has seemed more open to allowing the legislation to go to a
vote in his chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bruno will be able to convince some of his chamber's
conservative members to support a bias-crime bill, however, is
another story.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Frank Padavan, for example, is ``opposed to the
bill the gay pride agenda is backing,'' said his spokesman, Ed
DeCosmo. Padavan ``agrees with Senator Bruno in that the penalty
should fit the crime _ not the motive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
