<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-JUSTICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPUS COURTS ON TRIAL FOR RELENTLESS JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In these courtrooms, defendants neither have the
right to face their accusers nor have an attorney present.
Furthermore, the proceedings are secret, but the verdicts are not.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the conditions under which university student conduct
courts are allowed to mete out justice on campuses, dealing with
matters ranging from cheating to accusations of major felonies.
</P>
<P>
   College judicial courts go where civilian law enforcement fears
to tread, their critics say, handling often convoluted, politically
charged cases on issues like date rape and sexual harassment behind
close doors and without legal training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are kangaroo courts everywhere, on every campus,'' said
Ashwani Prabhakar, president of the Student Association at the
State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most controversial use of student courts is in the
area of date rape, where youth and the preponderance of binge
drinking make the issue all the more complicated on a college
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Critics span the ideological spectrum. Women's groups and rape
prevention centers have alleged that female students are pressured
by administrators into using the in-house courts to keep damaging
publicity out of the public eye. Conservatives and civil
libertarians say the courts trample on the rights of the accused.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Pavela, an administrator at the University of Maryland and
a scholar of student conduct courts, said the federal government
encourages universities to investigate rape cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks are asking us to do what the larger society has not done
well, which is to prosecute cases of acquaintance rape where
drinking is involved,'' Pavela said. Prosecutors ``won't touch
these cases. So it's left to colleges to resolve these very
convoluted situations.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case challenging these campus courts, the Rensselaer
Society of Engineers has filed suit in New York state court against
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute. The society is suing because, it
claims, it didn't receive justice from the campus tribunal that
suspended the fraternity two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though the case, which involves a strip show at a house ``rush''
event, is less weighty than many of the cases critics point to, the
RPI lawsuit opens a window on the secret world of campus justice.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Rensselaer group invited strippers to its 1997
rush, the 132-year-old fraternity was already in hot water with the
RPI administration.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternity had been put on probation in 1995 after strippers
played topless volleyball outside the house. The probation was
twice extended _ once for loud partying, and another time when an
underage student was given alcohol at a party.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1997 rush event, which 100 freshman attended, the
fraternity contracted with an exotic dance company. The fraternity
did not allow alcohol at the event. After the main performance was
over, three dancers invited students to join them on stage.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, the university alleges the
strippers simulated sex acts with one another; one student, not a
fraternity member, paid $40 to join them onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, a female student overheard two men talking
about the event and reported it to the dean of students.
</P>
<P>
   The case was heard before the Greek-Student Judicial board and
appealed to the Review Board _ which includes faculty, staff and
students _ and finally to RPI's then-President R. Byron Pipes, also
a defendant in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternity was put on suspension for 18 months, but now may
not be able to function on campus until 2003. The fraternity said
the university tried to make an example of it at a time when many
universities are closing or scaling back their Greek programs.
</P>
<P>
   Though the university said the fraternity violated the state
penal code, no criminal charges were sought in the case. And in
court papers filed in Albany, the fraternity said actions at their
party did not reach the level of a violation of student conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators disagreed. A lawyer for RPI, Jeffrey Armstrong,
said the ``sordid behavior'' added to a ``pattern of misconduct''
that was indeed disruptive to the campus' educational mission.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to reverse the suspension and to overturn two
other measures suggested by the university: one that would force
the fraternity to get a live-in adviser and another requiring the
fraternity to apply for national status.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling favorable to the fraternity, state Supreme Court
Justice George B. Ceresia said in September that the Rensselaer
Society of Engineers raised ``a question of whether there is
substantial evidence to support the determination of the
university.'' He then sent the case to the Appellate Division of
state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critics like Alan Kors and Harvey Silverglate, authors of ``The
Shadow University: The Betrayal of Liberty on America's Campuses,''
believe universities, through the unchecked use of such tribunals
and the discipline they impose, have introduced a new right not
accepted in the courts: the right not to be offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The claim is not that they did something to a female student
on campus,'' said Silverglate, a Boston attorney and self-described
liberal.
</P>
<P>
   University administrators say that critics are confusing its
internal justice system with criminal courts, and say that the
tribunals function more like arbitrations in a private corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an administrative process,'' RPI spokesman Eddie
Knowles said. ``It allows us to operate in a way that is
educational rather than punitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
