<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-MISSING-HNS &LR;      03-23 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-MISSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI AGENTS IDENTIFY ONE VICTIM IN CALIFORNIA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and VICKIE HADDOCK +
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BARN, Calif. _ Authorities have identified one of two
charred bodies found in the trunk of a burned-out car in this
mountain hamlet as that of missing sightseer Carole Sund but are
still searching for the missing third person.
</P>
<P>
   Sund's body, burned beyond recognition, was identified through
dental charts, according to Tuolumne County Sheriff Dick Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   A second body found in the trunk was not identified. Officials
said that they may have to use DNA testing to complete the
identification, and that it could take at least several days.
</P>
<P>
   There was no news of the whereabouts of a third member of the
sightseeing trio, who have been missing since Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Sund's parents, Francis and Carole Carrington, spoke briefly
Monday after their daughter was identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like a nightmare that you never wake up from,''
said Carole Carrington, dry-eyed but clearly stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Sund, 42, of Eureka, Calif., along with her daughter,
Julie, 15, and Silvina Pelosso, a 16-year-old family friend from
Argentina, were last traced by investigators to Cedar Lodge in El
Portal, where they had been staying during a visit to Yosemite
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Their car was found Thursday near here in a wooded area off
Highway 108 and investigators expect that the other body may be
either Julie Sund or Silvina Pelosso.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could take some time but we feel confident we will get
identification on the second victim,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators said they were shifting the focus of
the investigation to Sonora, Calif., the central location for the
combined task force of federal and local law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In another development Monday, the FBI released seven photos,
developed from film found among the evidence near the car, that
show the trio in the days just before they disappeared. The
pictures, taken in Yosemite National Park, show them smiling and
happy as they ice skated, posed in front of a waterfall and hiked
along the Merced River.
</P>
<P>
   Special Agent James Maddock, head of the FBI's Sacramento
office, said the time-stamped photographs were from an undeveloped
roll of film found among evidence near the car, but he would not
reveal the exact location. He said investigators decided to keep
other pictures in the roll.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said the decision to release the photographs to the
public was made by the families, who hope the pictures may generate
useful clues about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone out there knows something, knows what happened,''
Rogers said. ``We need that person to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sund's badly burned body was identified by the FBI crime lab in
Quantico, Va., using dental charts.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff confirmed that an autopsy had been performed, but he
declined to disclose the cause of her death. Nor would he say when
Sund died or whether the two victims in the trunk were still alive
when the car was set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The trio's disappearance prompted a massive search in this
mining country just outside Yosemite National Park. The car was
discovered late last week about three hours north of the park in a
remote wooded area just off Highway 108.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know how they got here,'' Maddock said. ``We
still don't know where the crime occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents are talking again with witnesses who said they saw
the trio shopping and buying gas the next day along Highway 108
near where the car was found.
</P>
<P>
   They were reported missing Feb. 17 _ a day after they failed to
meet Carole Sund's husband, Jens, at San Francisco International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants and tourism officials in Sonora, Twain Harte and
Sierra Village have reported seeing the trio in the area on Feb. 16
and 17.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and Maddock said authorities have been inundated with
tips about sightings, but that not all can be correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't necessarily believe one eyewitness sighting and not
another,'' Maddock said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which said weeks ago that the three were victims of a
violent crime, has been working on the theory that they were
kidnapped or carjacked outside El Portal late Feb. 15 or early Feb.
16. The FBI requires documentation or corroboration before it
confirms a sighting in a missing persons case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have a confirmed sighting beyond the Cedar
Lodge,'' Maddock said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, authorities moved the car to a hangar at
nearby Columbia Airport, where arson experts from the federal
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms were looking for telltale
chemical residues in the vehicle's burned-out shell.
</P>
<P>
   Using relatively new technology, they are looking for
case-breaking clues _ even fingerprints _ from the car, outside
experts told The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The experts believe investigators already know much more than
they are admitting about the crime, including, some say, the
identity of the victim found burned in the trunk with Carole Sund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I think they knew the IDs on both days ago,'' said one San
Francisco-based investigator who's handled similar cases. ``My
hunch is they have a good idea who did this and they're trying to
`roll' one of the guys'' by trapping him into revealing
unpublicized details of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   While criminals can destroy a lot of valuable evidence with a
fire, ``there are a lot of guys sitting in jail now because they
made the mistake of thinking they were covering themselves,'' said
Jean Daly, a San Francisco assistant district attorney who
specializes in crimes involving arson.
</P>
<P>
   She and other experts tick off an inventory of evidence that
could be retrieved from a torched car:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fingerprints. While blackening a metal surface often erases
fingerprints, new chemicals make them recoverable in some cases.
Specialists also would check for any areas of the car not damaged
by flames, including the exterior windows, the undersides and
insides of the glove compartment, the inside pages of things like
maps, checkbooks and notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Physical evidence like hair, pollen and fibers. Again,
specialists are likely to zero in on pockets not demolished by
flames. Because fires tend to burn upward, floorboards sometimes
still contain clues. And if the fire-starter neglected to leave the
windows down to allow oxygen to feed the fire, flames might have
extinguished themselves in areas like the trunk or even the
interior compartment before they had a chance to do much damage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cause of death. While the FBI is not revealing anything about
the cause of death of either victim, forensic experts may be able
to determine if they were shot or strangled before the fire.
</P>
<P>
   _ How the fire started. Tests for chemicals along a spectrum
will indicate whether the accelerant of the fire was gasoline,
butane or some other fuel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
