</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PALM-BEACH-2ND     03-23 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PALM-BEACH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PALM BEACH, Fla.: ... venue on earth.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The overused word ``palatial'' really does apply to The
Breakers. The grand lobby and and other public spaces with their
antique tapestries, gilded ceilings, and ornate furniture resemble
the reception rooms of the Doge's Palace in Venice. A world unto
itself, the Breakers has its own ocean beach and two swimming
pools, two 18-hole golf courses (one of them more than 100 years
old, practically Jurassic by Florida standards), 14 tennis courts,
a luxurious new health and fitness spa, seven restaurants and four
bars, and a shopping arcade that is a mini-Worth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, all this doesn't come cheap. In the high
season, rooms at the Breakers start at $360 a night and end at
$2,200 for the Imperial Suite.
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz Carlton (561-533-6000) in Palm Beach opened only in
1991, but the decor is classic Ritz, the same sort of subdued,
old-fashioned elegance that you find in much older sister hotels in
London, Paris, New York, and Boston. (The bathtubs are marble, of
course.) However, instead of a busy city street, this 200-room
hotel looks out on a sandy beach and a lot of ocean. And the guests
in the formal lobby are more apt to be wearing shorts and sandals
than business suits. Room rates in high season are $350-$1,095.
</P>
<P>
   Another distinctive Palm Beach hotel is the Chesterfield
(800-243-7871), a 55-room-and-suites boutique hostelry on Cocoanut
Row, just off Worth Avenue. Owned by a London-based company, the
Chesterfield has a decor and ambience that are a cross between an
English country house and an Edwardian men's club.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rooms off the Chesterfield's paneled lobby is a
library with a marble fireplace, leather upholstered armchairs, and
shelves of books that reflect current best-seller lists. Across the
hall is the smoking room with more armchairs and also humidors
filled with fine cigars. Needless to say, afternoon tea is served.
The Leopard Room, the hotel's combination lounge, restaurant, and
supper club, is a popular local hangout. Rates are from $229 to
$1099.
</P>
<P>
   Delray Beach is just a short drive down the dune- and
beach-rimmed coast from Palm Beach but a very different place:
Vacationers are younger and less formal, it's a bit arty, and a lot
cheaper. Delray was founded by Japanese immigrants in 1904 as an
agricultural settlement, which was abandoned in the 1920s. One of
Delray's popular attractions is the Morikami Museum and Japanese
Gardens founded by George Morikami, a settler who remained in the
area and eventually prospered as farmer.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, a pagoda-like building, has exhibits on the history
of the settlement, a collection of typical Japanese household
artifacts and children's toys along with changing displays,
demonstrations, and audiovisual presentations on different aspects
of Japanese culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Morikami also has an excellent Japanese restaurant (not easy
to find in Florida) that looks out on the gardens and is a great
place to have lunch. The 200-acre garden park is beautiful, with
nature trails, waterfalls, formal and bonsai gardens, and an
ornamental pond filled with carp.
</P>
<P>
   Delray's mile-long main shopping street, appropriately named
Atlantic Avenue, ends at a broad ocean beach. It, too, has had a
makeover recently _ it's now lined with palm trees and brick
sidewalks _ but is neither as upscale as Worth Avenue nor as
entertainment-oriented as Clematis. Pleasant but unpretentious,
Atlantic is a mix of utilitarian mom-and-pop stores, art galleries,
craft shops, and cafes. A notable Delray pub is the Blue Anchor on
East Atlantic, run by expatriate Englishmen, which has the
preserved facade of a demolished historic pub that once stood in
London's Chancery Lane.
</P>
<P>
   An Atlantic Avenue anchor and landmark is the Colony Hotel and
Cabana Club (800-552-2363). The Colony is a proudly old-fashioned
1920s Florida ``Gold Coast'' resort hotel _wicker funiture, ceiling
fans, and all. Room rates are $139 to $189 in the high season,
substantially less at other times.
</P>
<P>
   Boca Raton, just south of Delray, isn't the Social Register
bastion that Palm Beach is, but it's pretty posh. Among other
recreational amenities, for instance, it boasts two polo clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Influential in Palm Beach, architect Addison Mizner was the key
figure in the development of Boca Raton, and most buildings in town
are in the pink stucco, arcaded Mediterranean Revival style he
popularized. The centerpiece of Mizner's planned resort community,
built in 1926, was the Cloister Inn, which is now the Boca Raton
Resort (561-395-3000).
</P>
<P>
   Elegant and impressive (lots of antique tapestries, furniture,
and Italianate touches) but not as intimidatingly grand as The
Breakers, the main building of the Boca Raton Resort is Mizner's
masterpiece. The 350-acre grounds are lushly landscaped with
tropical trees and flower, and in the evening the air is scented
with night-blooming jasmine. There are nearly a dozen restaurants,
a full range of sports activities, and a marina generally filled
with enormous yachts.
</P>
<P>
   A high-rise tower has been added to the orginal hotel, and the
resort has nearly a thousand rooms. In-season room rates are
$240-$485.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Boca Raton created a sort of instant downtown
called Mizner Park, a shopping development built around a
Mediterranean-style square. Along its arcaded walkways are upscale
boutiques, art galleries, restaurants, outdoor cafes, a large
bookstore, a movie theater, and something that even Worth Avenue
can't claim _ guaranteed laughs.
</P>
<P>
   There are also chuckles, chortles, and guffaws to be had at
Mizner Park's International Museum of Cartoon Art, the only one of
its kind in the country. Devoted to the collection, preservation,
and study of cartoon art, the museum _ housed in a handsome new
building _ displays hundreds of comic books, editorial cartoons,
caricatures, cartoon strips, movie cartoons, graphic novels, and
the latest thing in computer-generated cartooning. Best of all,
it's filled with familiar and very funny faces, from Betty Boop,
Little Orphan Annie, and Li'l Abner to Charlie Brown, Michael
Doonesbury, and Dilbert.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
