<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PALM-BEACH-2TA     03-23 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PALM-BEACH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALM BEACH COUNTY IS RICH IN MUCH MORE THAN JUST MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Only the width of the Intracoastal Waterway,
here called Lake Worth, separates West Palm Beach from Palm Beach.
It takes just a minute or so to cross the bridge connecting the
two, but in many important ways (such as per-capita income) they
are far apart.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach is the largest city of Palm Beach County, a
2,000-square-mile subtropical enclave an hour's drive north of
Miami with a 47-mile-long coastline that is practically all white,
sandy beach. An attractive and mostly middle-class community, West
Palm is the county seat.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach, on the other hand, is casually elegant,
architecturally baronial, and has long been the winter resort of
choice for some of the wealthiest people in the country. We're
talking immense fortunes and very old money, as in Vanderbilts,
Rockefellers, Mellons, et al.
</P>
<P>
   It's a town of wide avenues lined with rows of royal palm trees
and enormous homes discreetly tucked away behind ivy-covered walls
and high, artfully sculptured hedges. The most impressive Palm
Beach mansion of all (which is saying something) is Mar-a-Lago,
built for cereal heiress Marjorie Merriweather Post, which boasts
58 bedrooms, 33 bathrooms, and three fallout shelters, one
presumably for the servants. Once the winter home of Donald Trump,
Mar-a-Lago is now a private club.
</P>
<P>
   The main shopping streets of the two communities speak volumes
about their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach's Worth Avenue is Florida's equivalent of Beverly
Hills' Rodeo Drive: in other words, shamelessly high-priced and
upmarket. Gucci, Pucci, Ralph Lauren, Laura Ashley, Louis Vuitton,
and Tiffany's are all represented, along with many one-of-a-kind
boutiques, specialty shops, and galleries. Designed by architect
Addison Mizener, who in the 1920s created a distinctive South
Florida version of the Mediterranean style, Worth Avenue is noted
for its ``vias,'' _ narrow passageways leading to charming inner
courtyards, usually occupied by art galleries, restaurants, and
cafes and often with a fountain in the center.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach's Clematis Street offers an eclectic and
affordable shopping and dining mix (there are more than 30
restaurants and cafes) along with a lot of free entertainment for
the hoi polloi. Downtown West Palm has had a civic spiffing up in
recent years, and Clematis Street, with its restored storefronts,
brightly painted metal sculptures, and colorful banners and cafe
umbrellas, showcases this renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Centennial Fountain, actually a plaza dotted with shooting
geysers, is the focal point of Clematis and the scene of frequent
concerts, performances, and art exhibitions. ``Brown Bag in the
City,'' a Friday afternoon lunchtime concert series, and ``Clematis
by Night,'' a Thursday evening entertainment series, are among the
regular events that enliven downtown West Palm. The last weekend in
April, the city stages SunFest, an outdoor festival featuring
musical events of all sorts, along with food stalls and crafts
booths.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach is also home of the splendid Norton Museum of
Art, generally acknowledged to be Florida's finest. The museum,
which recently underwent a $19 million expansion that tripled its
size, has particularly strong collections of French Impressionists
and post-Impressionists as well as 20th-century American paintings.
The museum also has an outstanding Oriental collection, consisting
of archaic Chinese bronzes, jades, ceramics, and Buddhist
sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is currently hosting a virtual heavenly host: ``The
Invisible Made Visible: Angels of the Vatican,'' a blockbuster
exhibition of some of the world's best works of art portraying
angels. Drawn from Vatican collections, the show includes paintings
by Raphael, Fra Angelico, Salvador Dali, and nearly 100 other
artists, along with sculptures, ceramics, liturgical vessels, and
vestments representing Assyrian, Etruscan, and pagan Greek and
Roman as well as Christian traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The man who founded both Palm Beach and West Palm Beach was
Henry Morrison Flagler, an industrialist and railroad baron who
almost singlehandedly transformed South Florida from swampy
backwater to winter vacation destination. In the 1890s, he began
extending his Florida East Coast Railroad south from St. Augustine
to open up what had been a remote and sparsely settled region.
</P>
<P>
   In 1893, Flagler acquired land on both shores of Lake Worth. On
the eastern shore _ the long sand spit of an island that is now
Palm Beach _ he built the 1,100-room Royal Poinciana, a vast wooden
building that was the largest hotel in the world at the time. Next
to it, he later built a smaller hotel that after various
incarnations (it burned down and was rebuilt twice) became the
Breakers. The Royal Poinciana is long gone, but the Breakers is
very much the grande dame of Palm Beach hotels.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach was initially developed to provide Flagler's
workers and the servants of the socialites he attracted to his
resort a place to build modest homes well removed from the lavish
digs of their employers. This rigid social division between the
communities no longer exists (although not many wage slaves can
afford to live in Palm Beach), but it hasn't been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Flagler died in 1913, but his memory and that of the Gilded Age
he epitomized live on in Whitehall. This is the 55-room Beaux
Arts-style neoclassical mansion he built beside Lake Worth in 1902
as a wedding present for his third wife, Mary Lily Kenan Flagler.
Now the Flagler Museum, the mansion is preserved much as it was
when the couple grandly held court there. Think vast marble-floored
and high-ceilinged rooms, thick Oriental rugs, silk tapestries,
massive pieces of furniture, and lots of crystal chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   The Breakers (561-655-6611) is also an enduring and impressive
piece of Flagler's legacy. Still in the family (the present owners
are related to his wife), the 572-room hotel, built in 1926, is
Palm Beach's signature building _ its twin towers, illuminated at
night, are visible all over town and well out to sea _ and also its
traditional social center. More money has been raised for charity
in the Breakers ballroom, it is claimed, than in any other venue on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
