<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ROME-BOS &LR;      03-23 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ROME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROPE SPRUCES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ If age determines rank among European cities, and it
does, Rome looks down its nose on everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Paris? Yawn. Most of the Paris we know today was created in the
middle of the last century by Baron Georges Eugene Haussmann, who
razed the old warrens of that city to build his grand boulevards
about the time that Boston was filling in the Back Bay. Beacon Hill
is older than much of Paris, for God's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Rome was already the center of the universe when its legions
were civilizing brutish tribes in England and western Europe.
Athens may be older, but it is hors de combat because it has the
ambience of an exhaust pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Like all true aristocrats, Rome has never cared a whit about
appearances. It is the noble who, secure in his bloodlines, serves
claret in the odd peanut butter jar at dinner parties. Where Paris
prides itself on its cleanliness and amenities, Rome luxuriates in
decay. No one does decay better than Rome. That's why Americans
love the place. We don't have any.
</P>
<P>
   But the visitor to Rome today will find that the city is in the
midst of doing something very un-Roman: It is cleaning up its act.
</P>
<P>
   today, Rome resembles a woman in curlers getting ready for a big
night out. Scores of its architectural gems like St. Peter and the
Palazzo Farnese are obscured by netting and scaffolding in
preparation for ``il Giubileo,'' the Jubilee celebrating the
millennium. Workmen are scouring the exteriors of these buildings
to uncover shades of stone unseen by any living Roman.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there are 700 projects underway. The municipal
government concedes in a huge sign on the Palazzo Venezia, where
Mussolini used to uncork his endless speeches, that these
restorations may be a tad inconvenient but they will make for a
swell future: ``Oggi i disagi, domani una citta migliore.''
(``today inconveniences, tomorrow a better city.'')
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government is also giving tax breaks to private
landlords who improve their buildings. Suddenly, owners who have
not fixed a faucet since Garibaldi rode with his redshirts are hard
at work sprucing up their palazzi. The streets are also being torn
up with brio. Thoroughfares that went in one direction for
centuries no longer do so. This makes for hallucinogenic driving.
</P>
<P>
   Rome's pride is on the line now as never before. The Vatican
expects 30 million people to visit the city and holy sites next
year. Still, there is something unsettling about all of this
estimable work. Rome has always been a respite from order. People
can always visit Frankfurt or Minneapolis for that. We flock to the
Eternal City for its chaos and decline. We love Rome precisely
because it has never seriously entertained the notion of urban
renewal. If they restore these buildings, what's next? Will they
have the gall to go after the pollution and the noise?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone buys the Roman act. The Milanese, among
the most sophisticated Europeans, dismiss Rome as ``the Cairo of
the South.'' (Indeed, a technician who computerized the foreign
bureaus of an international magazine in the late '80s declared that
the task was easier in Cairo than in Rome.)
</P>
<P>
   Milan is the center of Italian finance, design, and fashion.
They make money there. They produce things, too. Rome, by contrast,
spends money and produces nothing. Where the Milanese embrace a
proud work ethic, the Romans follow a blend of ``dolce far niente''
(``it is sweet to do nothing'') and ``chi se ne frega'' (``who
gives a damn''). The charm of this approach, it must be said, is
limited for anyone who actually has to do something.
</P>
<P>
   Milan is a true European city. It looks north toward Brussels
rather than south toward Calabria. Rome, in contrast, looks inward
when it bothers to look anywhere at all. It is ironic that the
treaty establishing the European Economic Community in 1957 was
signed in Rome, a city that has maintained a solipsistic view of
the world since its days of empire. Europe, shmeurope.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate its ego is a workout. Rome is considered a walking
city for tourists only because there is no alternative. Rome wipes
out people who attempt to walk from hotels near the Via Veneto to
Trastevere, the Gianicolo, the Aventino, and the Forum. Don't even
think about the Appian Way. Rome is huge. We're not talking
Florence, which, like Boston, has the right scale for bipeds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to even contemplate driving a car in Rome is lunacy. A
motor scooter makes the most sense, but not for the uninitiated,
who would end up on the police blotter. The city has a subway
system, but almost no one takes it. The buses are good and, if you
want to cheat, free, since they work on the honor system. Barring
the rare appearances by inspectors who check for freeloaders, no
one cares if a passenger has a ticket or not. The odds are with
you.
</P>
<P>
   So visitors should take a chance. Rome is best played without a
net. No guidebooks. Read voluminously before you arrive and then
wing it. Get lost in the dark alleys between Piazza Navona and the
Tiber. Wander from the Borgo around St. Peter's into Trastevere,
past Regina Coeli, unexpectedly sporting the flag of the European
Union over its entrance. Check out the ghetto, the ancient Jewish
quarter whose gates were locked each night by the Romans until well
into the last century.
</P>
<P>
   Do not miss the Aventino, one of the loveliest of Rome's seven
hills. Affluent and tranquil, it boasts the Giardine delle Arancie
(Garden of the Oranges), a sublime spot full of orange trees, with
a great view of the city. Another jewel on the Aventino is the
sight through the keyhole in the door of the Sovereign Military
Order of Malta. If you peer through it, you see the dome of St.
Peter's perfectly framed by an alley of trees. For my money, it is
the most magic scene in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Rome overflows with fountains. They speak to the sensuality of
the Italians that is so utterly lacking in Americans. (Why else are
there so few fountains in our cities?) There is something for every
taste. I favor the small ones, and none more than the Fontana delle
Tartarughe in the Piazza Mattei, a seductive little square in old
Rome near the ghetto. The fountain, modest by Roman standards, is
an exquisite affair with four youths, each of whom holds a dolphin
spouting water into a shell, while supporting a turtle climbing
into the bowl above. You don't need a guidebook to appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   The vast Borghese gardens remain one of Rome's primo walking
areas. Enter at the top of the Via Veneto and wander past the
grandiose statue of Umberto I, into the pines, and on to the Piazza
di Siena, where dressage competitions are held in the spring and
summer. (No one loves horse flesh more than the Italians.) Nearby
is the lago, a pond where folks can rent rowboats for 20 minutes at
a stretch and paddle aimlessly into one another. A delightful spot
for a proposal or a fight.
</P>
<P>
   The Borghese gardens abut Pincio, yet another oasis of
tranquillity, overlooks the Piazza del Popolo. Well-heeled mothers
and their Filipino au pairs play with children near the famous
water clock there. On a recent morning, a multicolored hot-air
balloon was tethered a few feet above the main plaza in Pincio. It
was a stunning sight. In the balloon basket were a handful of city
gas workers mounting a three-hour protest over pay and working
conditions. A colleague guarding the hawsers cheerfully conceded
that the workers, like the balloon, were going nowhere, but the
balloon certainly was pretty. Now that is a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   Rome has never been the same since the arrival of the cell
phone. With the possible exception of the Israelis, no other people
on earth have taken to these devices like the Italians. You wonder
how they survived all those centuries without them. Their odious
sounds now punctuate meals at trattorias, bus rides, and shopping
sprees. The throngs of teenagers who descend on the Spanish Steps
like crows all have cell phones. They call each other incessantly
and chain-moke. (Italians do not appear to have made the link yet
between smoking and cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Romans have refined the cell phone to accommodate
their need to talk with both hands. One well-dressed man was
spotted recently walking up the Via Veneto sporting a Madonna-like
headset connected to the phone in his coat pocket. He was carrying
on a spirited conversation with someone while gesticulating with
both hands. He was observed with envy.
</P>
<P>
   Jogging has also finally caught on. Enough said.
</P>
<P>
   Rome will survive cell phones and joggers just as it did the
Brazilian transvestites on the Via Veneto during the '80s and the
McDonald's in the Piazza del Pantheon today. It will make it
through the millennium and its attendant restoration projects as
well because it adheres to a different credo than the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tutto e relativo,'' explains Adrian Rodriguez, an artisan who
lives in Trastevere. Indeed, everything in Rome is relative. This
is an exotic concept to Americans. It is also the reason so many of
us favor it over countless other vacation spots around the globe:
For deep in our hearts, we admit that the Roman outlook on life
trumps our silly American rigidity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-RUSSIA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-23 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RUSSIA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ST. PETERSBURG: ... desperately hungry.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A two-minute stroll from the Grand is the Russian State Museum,
originally a grand duke's palace but converted into a showcase for
Russian art in 1898. In the midst of current economic chaos that
has left museum guards unpaid months at a time, the Russian State
Museum is celebrating its centennial this year.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the museum is the Pushkin Park, with its statue of
Russia's most revered poet. In the West, you're taught that Russia
has many great writers: Tolstoy, Dostoevsky, Gogol, and others. In
Russia, you're told there's a hierarchy, with Pushkin at the
pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest foreign-visitor day at the Russian State Museum is
Monday _ the day when the Hermitage is closed. I went on a Sunday,
and still had the place pretty much to myself. Make sure you buy
the $6 guidebook at the entrance, not only for the helpful
information you won't get from the minimal labels, only some of
which are in English, but also for gems of the translator's art,
like the description of the demise of the medieval Prince Vladimir:
``Intestine strife broke out following his death.'' An epidemic of
diarrhea?
</P>
<P>
   Even the overgilded ceilings can't mute the impact of the
museum's 12th- and 13th-century icons. The slender saints in these
paintings are, in their own way, as dour as the museum's hefty
female guards. These icons are among the museum's greatest
treasures, their attenuated figures often bowed as if under the
weight of faith. After the icon era, Russian art lost its fervor
and authenticity, and settled for imitating Europe. By the end of
the 19th century, though, Russia had regained her oomph. By the
early 20th century, radicals like Kandinsky and Malevich were
turning out some of the most exciting art anywhere, and Russia's
great designers were creating stage sets so forceful they ranked as
great art in their own right. The exhibitions in the Russian State
Museum track that epic development.
</P>
<P>
   At least they do now. In the bad old days, the Maleviches were
hidden away in storage, lest the party authorities discover these
objectionable abstractions. Curators told party officials that
they'd destroyed the avant-garde works. ``The only way to preserve
the work,'' says Karlov, ``was to lie.'' At least Stalin didn't
sell off Russian art, as he sold off Rembrandts and Raphaels from
the Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, the party paid for, and controlled, the museum.
Now, the government still gives the museum money, but the museum
must raise funds, too. Among other things, this means a museum
shop, renting the place out for a film of ``Anna Karenina,'' and
seeking corporate sponsorship. On the walls above the museum's
huge, echoing, ornate staircase are inscribed the names of its
corporate sponsors: Finnair, Coca-Cola, the Grand Hotel. Welcome to
late-20th-century fund-raising for the arts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hermitage occupies a string of pastel palaces along the Neva
River. You're first conscious of its amazing scale, of the reality
that merely walking around the outside of the building would be a
half-hour hike. The complex even has its own theater, which was for
the czar's personal use; nowadays, ballet companies and musicians
perform tourist-oriented shows there. One I attended had an
English-only program and the silliest curtain calls ever: The live
orchestra left and a recorded medley of jazzed-up Tchaikovsky
accompanied the strutting dancers.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer sumptuousness of the Hermitage is numbing, all those
acres of gilt and malachite, all those masterpieces. The conditions
in which these world-famous paintings live are sometimes appalling,
though: Major Post-Impressionist works exist next to open windows,
under fluorescent lights that make a buzzing sound. The labels in
some of these 20th-century galleries are equally appalling. They
freely acknowledge that a dazzling array of paintings by van Gogh,
Matisse, Cezanne, and Monet are from the collections of two
prominent and prescient families, the Shchukin and Morosov clans.
Their art was nationalized during the Revolution, and the state
hasn't moved to give it back, although the families' heirs have
asked for restitution. There's also an exhibition of ``Hidden
Treasures'' confiscated from Germany by Soviet troops at the end of
World War II and ``preserved'' by the Hermitage, which hasn't seen
fit to return them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether to give things back is a small problem,'' insists
Hermitage director Mikhail Piotrovsky. ``We have big problems.''
The biggest is money. At the time I spoke to him, Piotrovsky hadn't
been able to pay his fire brigade for two months. But he talked,
like the eternal optimist, about ``increasing the Hermitage's role
as a humanistic center for the city.'' His plans include luring a
foreign developer to build a museum of decorative arts, creating an
education center where children can dress up in period costumes or
replicas of armor, and opening cafes where you can eat off copies
of the czar's porcelain services you've seen in the galleries.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to expand the Hermitage until it is once again the
world's biggest museum, a title it lost to the Louvre after the
Paris museum's recent enlargement. I think the Hermitage is already
quite big enough, and that some funds ought to be put toward
Louvre-level loos: The Hermitage bathrooms are filthy, few, and
free of toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   But the paintings are jaw-dropping. While my Russian guide says,
``If we returned everything that people want back, there wouldn't
be anything left in the museum,'' this isn't quite the case.
Catherine the Great's purchases aren't in dispute, and she bought
by the cartload, including already-formed collections from
down-and-out Western European aristocrats, hundreds of paintings at
a pop. She and other royals stashed so much art in the Hermitage
that it is said that if you looked at each object for one minute,
it would take you a year to get through the place.
</P>
</TEXT>
