<HEADLINE>
GRAND EXHIBITS AT US MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington has John Singer Sargent, Monterey is going for the
mysteries of the deep, Denver offers a colossal fossil vacation,
and great toys from our childhood are on view in Pittsfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Spring is a grand time to visit a museum. The ground outside may
be a bit muddy, but inside, America's museums offer some great
shows and great reasons for hitting the road.
</P>
<P>
   In the art world, the first major retrospective since 1926 of
the work of John Singer Sargent is on view through May 31 at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington. The exhibit includes 113
paintings and watercolors. ``An astute portraitist, Sargent painted
many of the leading personalities of the age in works of great
elegance and panache,'' said Earl A. Pwell III, director of the
gallery. The exhibit will be at the Boston Museum of Fine Arts June
23-Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kid Stuff: Great Toys from Out Childhood'' is on view at the
Berkshire Museum in Pittsfield through May 30. This highly
imaginative show takes you back to your childhood and the games and
gadgets of the past. ``Kid stuff is about live ant farms, Colorform
activities, Easy-Bake Ovens, and running Lionel Trains,'' said
Sharon Blume, museum director. So, enjoy the show and check out the
View-Master, the Twister, Play-Doh, and more. For information, call
413-443-7171.
</P>
<P>
   At the Colossal Fossil Vacation at the Denver Museum of Natural
History, through July 5, you can go on a ``dig,'' touch fossil
specimens like a mammoth tooth, or even climb into a giant dinosaur
nest. Want more? Call 303-322-7009.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mysteries of the Deep'' is designed to introduce visitors to
the earth's largest habitat _ the dark, cold ocean waters that make
up 80 percent of the available living space on the planet. The
``Mysteries'' at California's Monterey Bay Aquarium continue
through Jan. 6 and include more than 40 species collected from
waters as deep as 3,000 feet below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Among other museum shows is the ``Pilgrim's Progress,'' one of
only a handful of surviving 19th-century ``moving panoramas.''
Presented in theaters and elsewhere, the enormous canvas was wound
onto a giant wooden spool and unrolled across a stage, scene by
scene. ``Pilgrim's Progress,'' a nearly 400-foot-long section from
this work, is on view at the Montclair Art Museum in New Jersey
through May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Just opened at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City
is ``The Treasury of Saint Francis of Assisi.'' The exhibit is in
conjunction with the massive restoration efforts following the 1997
earthquakes in Assisi, and includes 70 masterpieces of medieval and
Renaissance panel paintings, textiles, and manuscript
illuminations.
</P>
<P>
   Filling the entire Whitney Museum in New York for nine months
will be ``The American Century: Art and Culture 1900-2000.'' The
exhibit, to be presented in two parts _ the first from April
22-Aug. 30 and the second from October through February _ is
designed to enhance the ways in which museum visitors experience
and learn about works of art. For information, call 877-WHITNEY,
toll-free.
</P>
<P>
   One of many good reasons to visit Montreal this summer is the
opening of ``Cosmos: From Romanticism to the Avant-garde'' June
17-Oct. 17 at the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts. The exhibit takes
viewers from the myth of the New Frontier from the 19th-century
explorations of America to contemporary explorations of the solar
system. There will be works from 20 countries. For information,
call 514-285-1600.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women's history
</P>
<P>
   Throughout March, Colonial Williamsburg is celebrating National
Women's History Month with programs that explore the intricacies of
relationships and connections between 18th-century African,
British, and Native American women, free and enslaved. Particular
emphasis is given to the mistress and slave relationships that were
forged for sheer survival on the eve of the American Revolution.
For information, call 800-HISTORY.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good deals
</P>
<P>
   It's your choice: Paris and Burgundy or Paris and Champagne. The
packages, which begin at $749 and $789, provide a week in France
combining Paris with either the Burgundy or Champagne regions. Both
packages are good through Oct. 31 and offer round-trip air fare
from New York, accommodations, a gourmet dinner, a rental car, a
museum pass, and more. Or perhaps you'd rather sample Scotland on a
Lochs &AMP; Whisky Tour. The tour includes a nine-day car rental, full
Scottish breakfasts, accommodations, and air fare, beginning at
$1,049. For information, call New Frontiers at 800-366-6387.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran is offering travelers a business class upgrade for just
$25 over any fare until May 31. Seats are subject to availability;
there are only 16 business-class seats on the DC-9s and eight on
the 737s. For information, call 800-247-8726.
</P>
<P>
   How old do you have to be to qualify for senior discounts?
Consider these senior deals:
</P>
<P>
   Senior travel discounts of up to 50 percent off published rates
are being offered at nine Novotel hotels in the United States and
Canada. For details, call 800-668-6835. The rates are for those 55
and older, except in New York, where you must be 60 or older, and
in Montreal, where the requirements call for 65 and older.
</P>
<P>
   The Sanibel Inn on Sanibel Island on the southwest coast of
Florida is offering Boomer Plus, which offers travelers 50 and
older a 20 percent discount April 18-May 31 and a 25 percent
discount from June 1 through Dec. 23. The package includes
breakfast and a gift. For information, call 800-237-1491.
</P>
<P>
   The Equinox in Manchester Village, Vt., is offering a spring
escape through March 27, and April 10 through April 29. The
$109-a-person rate includes accommodations, breakfast and dinner,
and the use of the Fitness Spa. Skiing, off-road driving, and spa
services are available. For information, call 800-362-4747.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making plans
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts isn't the only place that celebrates Patriots
Weekend in April. Maine, once part of the commonwealth, also marks
the holiday, especially in Ogunquit, where the ninth annual
Patriots Weekend Celebration runs April 16 through 18. Many events
will be staged under the big top on Ogunquit Beach. Also planned is
a public supper Friday evening; the famous fireman's cookout; a
beach bazaar throughout the weekend; and a taste-of-the-town
Saturday, with each taste from area restaurants just 75 cents.
Saturday is casino night on the beach, and on Sunday, Elvis (or a
reasonable facsimile) will be there to sing ``On the Beach.''
Ogunquit is just over an hour from Boston and is one of Maine's
most picturesque villages. For information, call the Chamber of
Commerce at 207-646-2939.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LA tours, stay
</P>
<P>
   Tim Moreland knows his ``Rebirth of the Earth Tour'' down to a
fault _ the San Andreas Fault. Moreland and Miracle in the Desert
Destination Services are offering a three-hour eco-adventure tour
of the San Andreas Fault in the Palm Springs Desert Resort area.
``It is one of the most active geological areas in North America,''
says Moreland. ``We take people down to where they can stand and
look directly into the fault.'' For information on this and other
Palm Springs activities, call 800-41-RELAX and ask for the Palm
Springs Desert Resorts Vacation Planner. The planner also includes
discounts on accommodations, dining, and activities.
</P>
<P>
   While in Palm Springs, why not pay your respects to Frank
Sinatra, Sonny Bono, and other celebrities. The Desert Memorial
Cemetery makes it easy with a free map to the stars' graves. Other
dignitaries who rest here include songwriters Frederick Lowe and
Jimmy Van Heusen, choreographer Busby Berkeley (who hailed from
Athol, Mass.), and actor William Powell (the Thin Man).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevada bonus
</P>
<P>
   The ``Discover Nevada Bonus Book'' provides travelers with
information on attractions in Nevada along with discount coupons
for use within Nevada's six tourism ``territories.'' For a copy,
call 800-NEVADA-8.
</P>
</TEXT>
