<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO APPOINT A COMMISSION?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a way out of the unpleasant confrontation building
between the Republicans and the Democrats over the GOP's proposal
to build a new runway at Logan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The way to begin to fix the airport is for the governor to
appoint a small blue-ribbon commission to study the matter
intensely for a year, then seek to build a consensus around its
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The business community, which has a deep interest in a smoothly
functioning airport, should stop for a moment and consider both the
situation in the US Congress and the long history of the argument
over the plans for an additional east-west runway.
</P>
<P>
   When it was first proposed in 1973 by then Massport chief Edward
J. King, the 14/32 runway (so called after its compass heading) was
billed as the only way for Logan to continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Eight million passengers passed through Logan annually then; the
figure is 27 million now. King defeated Michael Dukakis in the race
for governor in 1978, was defeated by Dukakis in 1982, and moved on
to other things. The passenger traffic at Logan is expected to rise
to 40 million or so in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The alternatives for handling additional traffic are pretty much
today what they were then:
</P>
<P>
   _Hope that bigger, quieter planes will be built;
</P>
<P>
   _Institute a system of peak pricing designed to cut down on
congestion through economic incentives;
</P>
<P>
   _Build the short runway, which would permit the airport to
continue to operate near full capacity when the wind is from the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent episode began when Massport hired a political
consultant and announced plans to go to court to ask a judge to
withdraw an injunction against building the runway that had been
entered in 1974 at the request of then Mayor Kevin White.
</P>
<P>
   Led by men appointed by former Governor William F. Weld _ board
chairman Mark Robinson and executive director Peter Blute _
Massport has its reasons for wanting the additional runway. Though
only the nation's 17th busiest airport, Logan ranks sixth in
delays.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately there followed salvos from leading Democrats: first
US Representative Michael Capuano, whose 8th Congressional District
includes the towns around the airport; then Boston Mayor Thomas M.
Menino. Few neigborhood issues are more emotional than those that
arise from noise. ``We've got to make sure that injunction stays in
place,'' said Menino.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, who supports the new runway, so far has
avoided becoming deeply embroiled in the controversy, aside from a
few straightforward observations. ``With a new convention center
coming on line and the development in South Boston, we have to have
a first-class airport if Boston is to be a first-class city,''
Cellucci said the other day. He called the arguments for a new
runway ``overwhelming,'' and added: ``I believe the vast majority
of people in this state support it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Logan's congestion is the problem of little
planes. As a result of longstanding local custom, the airport sees
a far higher proportion of civil aviation at all hours of the day
than most urban airports.
</P>
<P>
   Congestion pricing would be one answer to the ubiquity of the
little planes, whose very presence forces big commercial jets to
keep greater distances, lest their jet wash blow little Cessnas and
Beechcraft into the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The Dukakis administration instituted a form of peak pricing in
1989, and for a time congestion dropped dramatically as the small
fry stayed out of the queue. But the owners of little planes
successfully appealed the measure to Congress, threatening to play
rough with Massport's charter in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The real subtext of the runway controversy is the likelihood
that Congress finally will take action on an omnibus aviation bill
later this year. Federal purse strings finally will be unloosed
after years of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   This is no time for the state's leadership to be squabbling
among themselves. Cellucci should do what Governor Frank Sargent
did when he was confronted years ago with a similar problem with
state highways. He should appoint a commission in the firm
expectation that the problem will diminish with time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
