<HEADLINE>
HE'S HERE, HE'S THERE, HE'S . . .  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What better way to brighten your day than to tell you about
three travel-related Elvis Presley items? Here they are:
</P>
<P>
   --Almost anywhere you travel, you're likely to run into
reminders of Elvis. ``The Field Guide to Elvis Shrines''
(Renaissance Books, $15.95) makes it easy to find them. The guide,
for instance, can lead you to Joni Mabe's Traveling Panoramic
Encyclopedia of Everything Elvis, the Elvis Presley Auto Museum,
and the 24-hour Church of Elvis in Oregon. There are photos, maps,
and walking-driving tours. For more information, call 800-422-5589.
</P>
<P>
   --Beginning Oct. 1, Bremerhaven, Germany, will host four days of
events commemorating Presley's arrival there 40 years ago, marking
the first time he stepped on German soil. There will be an
American-style hamburger joint, nonstop Elvis films, a concert, and
a music museum. Even the King's military uniform will be on
display. For more information, write to the Bremerhaven Tourist
Office, Van-Ronzelen-Strasse 2, 27568 Bremerhaven, Germany; or
phone 011.49.471.9464610. (With thanks to William Buchanan of Lake
Mary, Fla., an authority on matters Germanic.)
</P>
<P>
   --Jukka Ammondt, a Finnish academic known for recording Elvis
Presley songs in Latin, is planning a new record _ this time in
ancient Sumerian. Ammondt told Reuters he intends to bring out a
Sumerian single soon and an album in the autumn. He has been
practicing with ``Blue Suede Shoes,'' translated into the cuneiform
language of Babylonia that died out around 2000 BC. And how is that
travel-related? Well, you'll obviously be making a trip to Finland
to snag one of the first copies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What is the largest island in the Mediterranean?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The Doodlebug is the name of a remanufactured 1920s'
vehicle that takes 50 passengers on a tour of scenic Lake Dora,
Fla. And watch out: The Doodlebug hits speeds of 20 m.p.h.! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Why buy good luggage? You only use it when you
travel.'' _ Casey Stengel. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Freebie: You can walk through a glade surrounded by hundreds of
butterflies, including monarchs, swallowtails, and cabbage whites,
on the Hawaiian island of Kauai. Wings Over Hawaii, the state's
only producer of butterflies for release at weddings and other
special occasions, has its visitors' area and gift shop at
Kilohana, a former sugar plantation near Lihue that also contains a
dozen stores and galleries, a restaurant, gardens, and carriage
rides pulled by Clydesdales. For more butterfly information, call
808-2458838 or 888-BUTTERFLI.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A queenly birthday: Britain's Queen Elizabeth will be celebrating
her 73d birthday April 21 in the small southeastern Korean city of
Andong. During the celebration, elderly village women will join the
queen, who has said she wants to mingle with residents. She has
also expressed interest in lessons on making Korean food, including
that powerfully pickled dish called kimchi. (For more information
about visiting Korea, call the Korea National Tourism Organization
at 800-868-7567 or visit www.knto.or.kr.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glug: Americans drink about 310 Coca-Colas each every year. Britons
drink 100, Russians drink five and Chinese drink four. And,
according to the International Society of Worthless Information,
Iceland consumes more Coca-cola per capita than any other nation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Big Mac beat: At McDonald's in New Zealand, they serve apricot
pies instead of cherry ones. (With thanks to uselessfacts.net via
frequent contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Sicily. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
