<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RUSSIA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURISTS OFTEN MISS THE RUSSIAN STATE MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The standard tourist route for Western
visitors to this city includes a mandatory stop at the Hermitage
Museum, where they see Western art _ Rembrandt, Rubens, Matisse,
van Gogh.
</P>
<P>
   The standard route does not necessarily include the Russian
State Museum, where they would see Russian art, medieval icons to
20th-century iconoclasts. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   My most recent visit to the city of Peter the Great coincided
with the famous White Nights in June, when the sun barely dips
below the horizon. It's the most tourist-heavy time of the Russian
year. You'd never know it from the Russian museum, though.
``Foreigners here go to the Hermitage,'' laments Russian State
Museum chief curator Ivan Ivanovitch Karlov. ``They are brought
there as part of package tours sold by travel agencies. Ninety-five
percent of tourists here are on package tours. Individual tourists
just don't come.'' They stay away because of justifiable fears
about the roller-coaster Russian economy, concerns for their
safety, and worries about logistics: This is a city where even
negotiating a cab ride can be daunting and exhausting. Almost every
taxi meter in St. Petersburg is ``broken.'' Almost every taxi
driver demands $10, whether to go across town or a few blocks.
Almost no taxi driver will accept Russian rubles. I like walking
long distances, and it's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding Russian cabs is worth running the gantlet of beggars
and people selling newborn kittens on the street, and negotiating
the lines that form outside stores selling prized Western goods
like Nike shoes: Only a few people are allowed in at any one time,
because shopkeepers are so afraid of thefts. The Western newcomer
stores _ Gucci, etc. _ are the only ones with any on-street
presence; Soviet holdovers don't even have signs. But if you pay
close attention to windows, you'll notice some with goods that
beckon you inside. The consignment shops along the Nevsky Prospekt
are examples. Here you can pick up relics of Russia's stormy past _
mother-of-pearl opera glasses and malachite desk accessories from
Czarist times, dishes stamped with Lenin's face from a later era.
The Nikes will probably be next.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest shopping challenges in Russia is bottled
water. After spending $14 on water plucked from my hotel minibar
the first night of my first stay in St. Petersburg, so I could
brush my teeth without fear of intestinal reprisals, I learned to
comparison-shop. Avoid buying water outside tourist destinations
like palaces or museums; it's cheaper in the stores that cater to
Russians, although, like everything else here, it's cumbersome to
buy. In most stores, everything for sale is locked away under
glass, so you can't pinch it. You pick out what you want, hope you
can figure out the price, go to a cashier somewhere else in the
store, pay her (it's always a her), take the little receipt she
gives you back to the object of your desire, and hope there's a
clerk around who will get it out of the case and give it to you.
After all this, you will indeed need a drink, possibly of vodka
rather than mineral water. In Russia, vodka's often cheaper anyway.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the challenges of St. Petersburg worth the effort is
the glorious, if run-down, ambience, the astonishing architecture
reflected in still canals, the sculpture-lined bridges. And
churches _ once again open and fully operational _ including the
Kazan Cathedral, degraded during the communist era by being turned
into the Museum of Atheism. The 19th-century Church of the Holy
Blood _ built in Muscovite style, complete with gilded onion domes
_ boasts glorious, newly restored mosaics in a style that resembles
Byzantine crossed with Diego Rivera. There's a ``tourist'' entrance
fee of $16: Be prepared. Tourists also pay higher prices for
ballet, opera, and symphony performances. Tickets tend to be
available at the last minute, I've found. Pricewise, you're better
off going to the theater box office than buying them from a hotel
concierge.
</P>
<P>
   The bells of the Trinity Cathedral are being rung again, by
young men recently trained in the ancient art. Their sound is
mournful and distinctly Eastern, far from the more exuberant
tonalities of Western European church bells. The cathedral is part
of the Alexander Nevsky Monastery, located at the eastern end of
Nevsky Prospekt, which is also where you'll find the overgrown
Tikhvin cemetery, burial place of notables including Dostoevsky and
Tchaikovsky. In the cathedral, you see people kneeling on hard
stone floors for long periods, as if making up for lost time. As
you turn to leave, you see a digital clock blinking over the
doorway of this otherwise mystical place, time marching on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I stayed at the Grand Hotel Europe in St. Petersburg, in a
top-floor room with a terrace. In a city that seems to be crumbling
before your eyes _ the great palaces all seem to be handyman's
specials _ the Grand Hotel is an oasis of perfect decor and calm,
although the service is somewhat unreliable. The hotel is partly
owned by the City of St. Petersburg, but it's managed by the
esteemed German-based Kempinski group. The sullen employees who
wish you would get your own food, and who helpfully point out that
you should leave them tips in American dollars, are the Russians.
The few Western Europeans are the ones who smile and ask if they
can help.
</P>
<P>
   The food in the Grand is St. Petersburg's best: It's all trucked
in from Germany because Russian supplies are unreliable. The Grand
has Chinese and Italian restaurants, a sports bar, an atrium cafe,
a caviar bar (the caviar is not trucked in), and a fancy restaurant
called the Europe, which offers the city's finest dining and boasts
stained glass by none other than Alexandre Benois, designer of
Ballets Russes landmarks like ``Petrouchka.'' Timid tourists who
don't want to venture beyond the walls of the Grand to eat can find
quite a bit of variety within them. For even more of a choice, the
city's two runner-up hotels, the Nevsky Palace and the Astoria,
also have good restaurants, although not on a par with the Grand's.
And you'll want to try independent restaurants, too, although
possibly not when you're desperately hungry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
