<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS-MOTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTION BLINDNESS MAY BE CAUSE OF ALZHEIMER'S DISORIENTATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists say they have discovered why many Alzheimer's disease
patients get lost as they try to do what the rest of us take for
granted: navigate our way through the world.
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do with memory loss, as specialists have long
assumed. Rather, many Alzheimer's patients have ``motion
blindness,'' as Dr. Charles J. Duffy and Sheldon J. Tetewsky of the
University of Rochester term it in a study published Tuesday in the
journal Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that they don't remember where they've been, but they
can't tell where they're going,'' Duffy said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes motion blindness occurs months before the memory or
language difficulties that characterize Alzheimer's. This
information may help doctors diagnose the disease earlier. Tests of
the sort the Rochester scientists used could also help doctors and
families determine when an Alzheimer's patient needs to stop
driving or move into a supervised living situation, or help monitor
the effect of Alzheimer's drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Motion blindness results from damage to cells in a part of the
brain that processes and interprets the complex flow of information
that the eyes take in when individuals move through the world. This
region is where the occipital, parietal, and temporal lobes of the
brain meet. It is distinct from the nearby hippocampus, the
memory-processing center that is also affected by Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of motion blindness, Duffy said, is a perpetual
version of what most people experience momentarily when they cannot
locate their car after shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to the grocery store, park your car, and walk in,
you see this pattern of motion all around you that tells you what
your path was,'' Duffy said. ``When you walk out, you go back along
that path. We've all had the experience of forgetting that path,
but many Alzheimer's patients have this all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Motion blindness is not a cognitive or thinking disorder like
forgetting a conversation or the location of car keys, the
Rochester neuroscientist said. It is a disorder of perception and
perceptual processing.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy and Tetewsky unmasked the disorder by comparing 11
Alzheimer's patients with 12 healthy elders and six college
students in a battery of tests that simulate the visual experience
of motion. Their studies are reported in the journal Neurology
which is being published  &UR; today &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Duffy has also studied rhesus monkeys to determine which brain
structures are involved in perceiving and interpreting visual input
about motion.
</P>
<P>
   The experiments indicate that motion blindness is the product of
two separate deficits in the brain. One is perceptual; for
instance, Alzheimer's patients have difficulty discerning the
direction of motion in a pattern of moving dots.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Alzheimer's patients could tell the dots were moving
in a given direction, they could not use visual cues to judge if
they themselves were moving or standing still _ a disorder not of
visual perception but of interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, people use the apparent motion of objects in the
external world to determine if they are moving, in which direction,
and how fast. Momentary failure of this mechanism occurs when one
is sitting on a train that starts to move; it often takes a moment
before individuals can tell if the train is actually moving.
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's patients with motion blindness have this confusion
about self-movement much or all the time, Duffy said. ``They're
unable to put together the visual cues that would allow them to
navigate,'' he said. ``They can become overwhelmed by information
they can't process.''
</P>
<P>
   If further studies confirm the results, Duffy said, the kind of
simple tests the Rochester team used may help doctors diagnose
Alzheimer's and monitor the disease's progress. The researchers
found that some apparently healthy elders with abnormal results on
the visual-motion tests subsequently went on to develop classic
signs of Alzheimer's, a sign that in some people, ``motion
blindness'' can develop before memory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy said that the loss of the ability to navigate can pose
more painful problems for Alzheimer's patients than memory loss.
``Patients are often not so much bothered by not being able to
remember a name,'' he said. ``What bothers them more is that they
can't get to the grocery store and get back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
