<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-REPARATIONS-B     03-23 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-REPARATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APARTHEID'S VICTIMS FEAR THEY WON'T RECEIVE COMPENSATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRA, South Africa _ Mildred Theys has a song in her head.
She has heard it every day since the night 13 years ago when the
police came. They broke down her door and beat her, and hauled her
eldest son, Christopher, into the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   She was left with only their voices, singing in Afrikaans,
``Tonight the birds are going to get food.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son's plight has placed Mildred Theys among thousands of
victms representing one side of South Africa's fragile search for
racial healing. As the country weighs the needs of those who
suffered human rights violations, it is also beginning to grant
amnesty to some of apartheid's most infamous perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   But to many South Africans, there is a sense that amnesty is
unjust, and that reconciliation is hollow, if those who suffered
most are not helped. The nation now finds itself battling over how
best to compensate them.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher survived, but the torture he faced over two long
periods of detention left him mentally enfeebled.
</P>
<P>
   Once a top student and a charismatic youth activist, Christopher
now cannot carry on simple conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Once his family's prospect as a breadwinner, now he is reduced
to sitting beside his mother while she sells candy outside the
gates of his old high school, for a meager income.
</P>
<P>
   Mildred told her son's story to the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission, the panel charged with investigating apartheid human
rights abuses. After reviewing Christopher's case, the commission
declared him a victim. That entitles his family, and those of more
than 20,000 others found to have suffered at the hands of the
apartheid regime, to compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The government now says it cannot afford reparations for
individual victims, and may decide instead to make symbolic
gestures, such as national monuments and community halls. The
reaction, among survivors such as Mildred, is closer to bitterness
than resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get mad to see those people get amnesty,'' Mildred said, a
tear streaking her cheek as she retold the story. ``How can they
forgive those people and they don't help my son? Thou shalt not
kill. This is not going to help the country. Seriously not.''
</P>
<P>
   Reparations and amnesty are the primary components of South
Africa's experiment in racial healing. The amnesty provision was a
key part of the agreement that led to democracy in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Whites, though, feared a witch hunt. Amnesty guaranteed that
those who made full disclosures about politically motivated human
rights abuses could avoid prosecution. The tradeoff, it was hoped,
would enable South Africa to learn as much as possible about the
apartheid years.
</P>
<P>
   But something was also needed to address the suffering of
victims and to balance the reconciliation equation. The amnesty
implied that victims would lose the right to legal redress. So when
Parliament passed legislation establishing the Truth Commission, it
included a provision for reparations, which could include a wide
range of possible measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without adequate reparation and rehabilitation measures, there
can be no healing or reconciliation,'' the commission concluded.
``Reparation is essential to counterbalance amnesty, which denies
victims the right to institute civil claims against perpetrators.''
</P>
<P>
   While the commission concluded most of its work last October,
the amnesty and reparations processes are just beginning to reach
fruition. The Amnesty Committee still must hold public hearings on
roughly 600 cases, and has more than 400 others to decide in
chambers. In recent weeks, however, it has made rulings on a number
of high-profile cases.
</P>
<P>
   It denied amnesty, for example, to the five police officers who
interrogated Stephen Biko, the charismatic young leader of the
Black Consciousness Movement, but it cleared a number of ranking
police officials whose names were associated with brutality.
</P>
<P>
   As amnesties go forward, however, reparations lag. The
commission's founding legislation left it to the commission to
recommend, and the Parliament later to enact, specific forms of
redress.
</P>
<P>
   In its final report, the panel argued strongly for financial
payments to individual victims: short-term interim payments of as
much as $1,000 to meet urgent needs and a six-year annual grant of
as much as $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament approved the interim payments, but checks take up to
18 months to reach victims.
</P>
<P>
   The form of final reparations, however, remains unsettled.
President Nelson Mandela's office is reviewing the commission's
proposals, but even the president has indicated that the idea of
individual cash grants probably won't fly.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Hofmeyr, a member of Parliament from the African National
Congress who has worked extensively on the reparations issue,
argues that the framers of the Truth Act never envisioned
significant financial redress for individual victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to balance what we do for individuals with what we do
for victims of apartheid generally,'' he said. The number of people
who testified or submitted statements about what they suffered is a
tiny fraction of the masses who felt apartheid's grip. ``How can we
say that the people who didn't speak out suffered less than those
who did?''
</P>
<P>
   Hofmeyr, reflecting the views of the ANC generally, has
advocated a wider range of reparations targeted toward communities
as well as individuals, including counseling and medical services,
community halls, and monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the amnesty process painless for those who did wrong.
``It doesn't let perpetrators off scot-free,'' Hofmeyr said. ``They
face a significant amount of public censure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hlengiwe Mkhize, chairwoman of the commission's reparations
committee, disagrees. Symbolic reparations are important, she says,
but they do not redress individual suffering. Many people, and
their families, suffer from the long-term damage of human rights
abuses, such as interrupted education, homelessness, and
post-traumatic stress. While more suffered than spoke out, she
said, ``it is wrong to compromise those who were willing to take
the risk of revisiting past traumas.''
</P>
<P>
   A final policy is unlikely to take effect anytime soon.
Parliament closes this week, ahead of elections on June 2. Amnesty
decisions, meanwhile, continue to go public. Those victims, who
have lost the right to prosecution because their aggressors have
been granted amnesty, must now wait to hear if they will one day
receive state financial help to begin rebuilding their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The commission essentially said ``we will deny victims justice
because we will give them reparations,'' said Brandon Hamber, an
analyst at the Center for the Study of Violence and Reconciliation
in Johannesburg. ``What gave birth to the TRC? Amnesty. From Day
One, victims were always going to come second. They are never going
to get what they really deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether South Africa can strike a balance
between perpetrator and victim, and whether reconciliation will
follow. In the meantime, Mildred Theys waits.
</P>
<P>
   She has no money to help her three younger children finish
school, no money to give Christopher proper medical and psychiatric
treatment to heal the wounds that began the night he was dragged
away.
</P>
<P>
   All she has is that song in her head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
