<HEADLINE>
AN `EASY' WAY TO ENLARGE A SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you add 203 staterooms, a second swimming pool, and a
second dining room to an existing cruise ship? Just cut it in half
and insert a new midsection. It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what Norwegian Cruise Line has done to Boston's
popular Norwegian Majesty. When the ship returns to its
Boston-Bermuda weekly schedule on April 11, travelers will see not
only a larger ship but also one with added renovations throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Lengthening a ship by cutting it in half is not a new technique.
The cruise line has already done it before on its Norwegian Wind
and Norwegian Dream.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish the lengthening, Norwegian in January sent the
Majesty to Bremerhaven, Germany, where the ship was cut in half.
Then the fore and aft sections were floated apart and the new
prefab midsection inserted. Finally, the three sections were welded
together and internally joined with wiring and plumbing. The prefab
section was begun some nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the ship's length this way has economic benefits, as
well as minimizing the time the ship is out of service. ``The fact
that this lengthening can be accomplished at two-thirds the price,
per berth, of a new ship building while actually lowering the
operating costs per guest is an added bonus to our efforts to
improve both our product and our bottom line at the same time,''
said Art Sbarsky, NCL's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Majesty has increased its passenger capacity by 40
percent, from 1,056 to 1,462 passengers. In addition to adding
staterooms and other facilities, the Palace Theater has been
enhanced with improved seating, the Royal Observatory now doubles
as a sports bar with sports memorabilia and television monitors,
staterooms have new colors and comforts, two additional elevators
have been added, and even crew accommodations have been increased
from 438 to 570.
</P>
<P>
   The new 274-seat Four Seasons Dining Room will offer panoramic
sea views through floor-to-ceiling windows; a new 58-seat Le Bistro
restaurant is next door featuring alternative dining, and the
existing 574-seat Seven Seas Dining Room, formerly known as the
Epicurean Restaurant, is being updated with new chairs and
carpeting. The Majesty will also offer more room for sunning with
the addition of a Sky Deck. There's also a new casino, coffee bar,
and other features.
</P>
<P>
   Sbarsky says the lengthening offers the Majesty a more sleek and
hydrodynamic profile, allowing the ship to maintain its 20-knot
speed with the same power plant despite the ship's added size and
amenities. The Majesty is growing from 568 feet to 680 feet and
increasing in tonnage from 32,400 tons to 38,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Majesty will offer 30 weekly cruises from Boston's
Black Falcon Cruise Terminal to Bermuda, followed by a 10-day
voyage from Boston to San Juan on Oct. 24. Beginning Nov. 3, the
Majesty will feature a series of 10- and 11-day Panama Canal
cruises between San Juan and Acapulco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Greek isles
</P>
<P>
   Orient Lines is featuring cruise-tour vacations of the Greek
isles and Mediterranean from April through October. The five- to
seven-day cruises depart from Rome, Athens, Barcelona, and Istanbul
and are coupled with included stays in some of Europe's finest
hotels before and after the voyage, along with sightseeing,
transfers, and more. Complete vacations from 12 to 18 days begin at
$1,550 and air fare is available beginning at $595 round trip from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Just for mothers
</P>
<P>
   Cunard is offering a special Mother's Day one-day, one-night
cruise from New York on May 9. The special sailing allows mothers
and families to enjoy dining, a garden-party tea, entertainment,
and dancing lessons. The cruise sampler ranges from $199 to $1,699
a person.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
American history
</P>
<P>
   A collection of three cruises showcasing some of the country's
most famous harbors and coastline will be offered aboard Premier
Cruises SeaBreeze, a classic luxury liner, with departures from
Baltimore May 28 and 30. The weekend cruises depart Fridays at 3
p.m., returning Sunday at 9 p.m. On Sept. 28, the ship will offer a
weeklong cruise calling on Newport, R.I.; Portland, Maine; and
Halifax, Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For food lovers
</P>
<P>
   Menus faithfully culled from dynastic history will be featured
during the Three Emperors' Dinner on a 10-night cruise from
Edinburgh to Stockholm beginning July 4. The cruise aboard Radisson
Seven Seas' 180- passenger Song of Flower will include a
reenactment of the lavish feast enjoyed by Kaiser Wilhelm I of
Germany, Tsar Alexander II of Russia, and Alexander III at a Paris
restaurant on June 7, 1867.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hudson River
</P>
<P>
   James Fenimore Cooper called The Hudson River ``this nation's
Rhine . . . the mighty river, complete with our own humble castles,
legends, and ancient associations.'' Now cruises are being offered
in summer aboard the 63-foot Crescent. The vessel is followed by a
chartered bus that meets the boat at docks to take travelers to
historical and scenic spots, then brings them to a variety of inns
and hotels where their luggage will be waiting. The cruises are
planned for June 13-20, Sept. 12-19. Sept. 26-Oct. 3, and Oct.
10-17. The all-inclusive cost is $1,890. For information, call Karl
Rodman of River Valley Tours at 800-836-2128.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
