<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR SHOULD BUILD BRIDGES TO UNIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knowing that organized labor almost made Scott Harshbarger a
winner in a close gubernatorial election last fall, Governor Paul
Cellucci ought to consider building _ not burning _ bridges between
his administration and the many unions that campaigned against him.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, as was expected, Cellucci is rewarding some of the
unions that endorsed his candidacy. Teamsters Local 25 received
$125,000 from the governor's budget for a truck-driving program.
The money reportedly was shifted from the state AFL-CIO's training
programs to the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Professional Firefighters of Massachusetts,
which endorsed Cellucci early in his campaign, received, among
other rewards, a generous increase in a $1 million fire education
program that pays overtime to firefighters who teach prevention in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign last year, Cellucci received the support of
the carmen's union, which received a generous collective bargaining
agreement with the Cellucci administration as well as a kept
promise to abandon the privatization program, which was once a core
of the Weld-Cellucci administration.
</P>
<P>
   While it is expected that Cellucci will reward unions who helped
him get into the governor's chair, it may not be so prudent to
punish the unions that backed Harshbarger. That apparently is what
the Cellucci administration is doing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the administration recently removed a union
representative of IBEW Local 103, which backed Harshbarger, from
the state Electricians Licensing Board and replaced him with a
non-union contractor who is a member of Associated Builders and
Contractors.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Cellucci may have further alienated the IBEW
(International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers) and other unions
by appointing a non-union member to the licensing board.
</P>
<P>
   And shifting state funds from the state AFL-CIO's training
program to the Teamsters Local 25 truck-driving training program
will serve only to enhance the possibility of an even stronger
AFL-CIO campaign against him in the 2002 election, especially if
the Democrat is a more widely accepted prolabor candidate than was
Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's apparent decision to punish the unions who backed
Harshbarger may backfire, almost assuring that the state AFL-CIO,
which represents most of the larger unions in Massachusetts, will
endorse the next Democratic gubernatorial candidate.
</P>
<P>
   And ``endorse'' is the key word Cellucci might carefully review.
Under the state AFL-CIO's guidelines, a gubernatorial candidate
must receive two-thirds of the voting members of the AFL-CIO board
to be endorsed by the labor organization.
</P>
<P>
   If he reversed himself by working with, and not against, the
unions that endorsed his Democratic challenger, though he might not
be endorsed by the AFL-CIO, but he might prevent his next
Democratic opponent from receiving the necessary two-thirds vote.
</P>
<P>
   As Cellucci well knows, it was the AFL-CIO's resources, along
with a few other unions, that nearly snatched victory from the
governor in the last hours of the election. If Cellucci continues
to alienate the unions that voted for Harshbarger's endorsement, as
well as adding a few more to the list, the governor is virtually
assured an even stronger campaign against him from organized labor
in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Cellucci believes he can win again without union support
in 2002. But he might consider that if Harshbarger had been more
appealing to rank-and-file union members, Harshbarger would be
governor  &UR; today &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In essence, by building rather than burning bridges with the
AFL-CIO and its affiliated unions, Cellucci would be working toward
another successful campaign, rather than going down in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
