<SLUG> BC-BOOK-READER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK GROUPS AND OPRAH MAKE FOR UNLIKELY BEST SELLER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Reader,'' a sparely written but morally complex,
erotically charged novel by an obscure German writer, begins with a
startling image: an adolescent boy throwing up in public.
</P>
<P>
   Unromantic as it is, the incident leads to a passionate affair
with a mysterious woman more than twice his age, a former SS guard
at Auschwitz suspected of responsibility in the deaths of hundreds
of female concentration camp inmates. Only she knows the full
extent of her guilt, but that's not her most closely guarded
secret.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely candidate for bestsellerdom, one might think. But,
think again. After a slow start _ it's been in print in this
country for nearly two years _ ``The Reader'' by Bernhard Schlink
(Pantheon/Vintage) is suddenly heading for big sales and the top of
best-seller lists. Thanks to the enthusiasm of reading groups
around the country _ and especially to Oprah Winfrey, who picked
``The Reader'' as her book club's March selection _ Schlink is
about to become a literary household name in America.
</P>
<P>
   A German state court judge, Schlink also teaches law at Humboldt
University in Berlin and will appear on Oprah's show next Tuesday.
He will be questioned about ``The Reader'' both by Winfrey and
members of her book club. ``I think it's going to be great,'' he
said on the phone from his home in Bonn. ``I understand that she is
very smart and well-read and I look forward to an interesting
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   One question the 55-year-old Schlink is likely to be asked but
seems reluctant to answer directly is whether the ``The Reader,''
set in post-war Germany, is autobiographical. ``This is a book
about my generation and there are things in it from my life, but
it's a novel and that's not the same as an autobiography,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it can be read as a parable of German guilt, atonement,
and yearning for absolution, ``The Reader'' is also a love story
and a tale of crime, punishment, and perhaps redemption.
</P>
<P>
   The reader of the title and narrator of the novel is Michael
Berg, who at its start is 15 and suffering from hepatitis. When he
gets sick in the street on the way to school one morning, Hanna
Schmitz, a 36-year-old street-car conductor, takes him into her
apartment and cleans him up. At his mother's suggestion, Michael
brings Hanna flowers as a gesture of thanks and they begin an
affair that is both intensely erotic and strangely ritualized.
After lovemaking they take turns bathing each other and then, at
her insistence, Michael reads to Hanna from one of the classics he
is studying in school.
</P>
<P>
   The affair ends when Hanna abruptly disappears, leaving Michael
feeling both guilty and betrayed. Did he do something wrong? Or was
something done to him?
</P>
<P>
   They meet again when Michael is a 21-year-old law student
attending a war crimes trail at which Hanna is a defendant. He
realizes then what her real secret is, one so shameful to her that
rather than reveal it, she admits to something she didn't do.
Filled with revulsion at her crimes, Michael can't bring himself to
intervene and Hanna is given a long jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, after a failed marriage and a retreat into legal
scholarship, Michael begins to read his favorite books into a
recorder and sending the tapes to Hanna. After a time, she starts
writing him notes commenting on the books he reads and they develop
a new kind of relationship.
</P>
<P>
   When Hanna has completed her sentence and is to be released from
prison, the now middle-aged Michael must directly confront feelings
about her, the generation she represents, and his own future. The
result is poignant and tragic but also hopeful, suggesting that for
Michael, and Germany, it's now possible to address the past without
being dominated by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a book about the Holocaust; we have had many books
in German about that,'' Schlink says. ``But it's one of the first
books about my generation dealing with the generation from the war.
Many people feel that our generation is finally finding its voice.
We have had a hard time freeing ourselves from a fixation on the
generation before and you can't understand us unless you understand
that.''
</P>
<P>
   His own father, Schlink says, was a professor of theology who
lost his teaching position when the Nazis came to power. A Lutheran
minister, he did not serve in the military in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Published in Switzerland in 1995, ``The Reader'' was an
immediate critical and popular success in Germany. It has since
been translated from German into more than a dozen languages.
Americans at first showed little interest in the book, and a
promotional tour by Schlink in 1997 attracted almost no attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a real word-of-mouth book and a book-group
book,'' says Katie Barrett, publicity director of Vintage Books.
Random House, which own Pantheon and Vintage, does not release
sales figures but Barrett reports that, although the book was well
received by critics, it sold only modestly in the hardcover
Pantheon edition. Since it came out in paperback early last autumn,
however, sales have ``increased substantially'' every month with
multiple sales to reading groups given much of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   Selection by Oprah has been known to increase a book's sales by
half a million copies or more, and ``The Reader'' is reportedly now
selling briskly on line and in bookstores around the country,
largely in the $11 Vintage trade paperback edition. And the book is
near the top of Amazon .com's ``Hot 100'' list _ at No. 5, it is
outpacing even ``Monica's Story,'' which is at No. 18. On Sunday,
``The Reader'' was No. 1 on the New York Times paperback fiction
bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   As much as readability, discussability is what makes for a good
reading-group book. Besides food for thought, ``The Reader''
provides topics almost guaranteed to produce lively exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I enjoyed the discussions about it even better than
the book itself. There were six of us and we all had different
opinions,'' says Paula Hartstein, member of a Newton book group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easy read but grows increasingly demanding as it goes
on and raises uncomfortable moral issues,'' notes Virginia Inglis
of Needham, a member of the same group. ``I was challenged and
stunned by some of the things I got out of it.'
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, ``The Reader'' belongs to a recognized literary
genre with the formidable name of Vergangenheitsbewaltigung, which
means ``coming to terms with the past.'' For American readers,
however, the novel fits into no such neat category.
</P>
<P>
   Some see it as a story of obsessive love. To others, it's about
the sexual abuse of a child, the punishment of a war criminal, the
destructive effect of secrets on relationships, the banality of
evil, and the healing power of literature. Still others see it as
an apology for the Holocaust and an indictment of the
self-righteousness and self-absorption of Germany's post-war
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the discussion in reading groups is about the character
and motives of Hanna, who is central to the novel but sketchily
described by Schlink. He gives her little to say, for instance,
doesn't describe her in detail, and gives few clues about her
motives.
</P>
<P>
   As with so many of the adults who loomed large in the early
lives of his generation, says Schlink, much about her is mysterious
_ especially her past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanna was a mystery to Michael, and I have mixed feelings
about her,'' he acknowledges. ``She had a brutal side and was
brutal during the Third Reich and to Michael afterward. But in a
way she was also a lost soul. It would be easier for us if these
people were all just monsters, but that's not the way it was.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1503EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
