<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-23 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RANDOM WALK DOWN STAT STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Users of the Club, proclaims the radio ad, ``are 400 percent
less likely to have their cars stolen.'' United Parcel Service's
retirement compensation, the Globe reports, is ``213 percent less
than United Airlines.'' A forecaster says there's a 50 percent
chance of rain on Saturday and a 50 percent chance on Sunday, hence
a 100 percent likelihood of weekend showers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 100 percent less of any amount is zero, the Club is
absolutely guaranteeing your car won't be stolen, and then some.
Those poor UPS pensioners must be paying their former employers,
rather than collecting retirement checks. And the weatherperson
shouldn't need a calculator to figure out that in this case, 50
plus 50 does not equal 100; experience alone should make that clear
enough.
</P>
<P>
   These goofs are examples of innumeracy, as the counterpart of
illiteracy has been called since the word was coined around
midcentury. (In his 1993 book ``200 percent of Nothing,'' A. K.
Dewdney credits the coinage to Douglas Hofstadter, the cognitive
scientist and Pulitzer Prize-winning author. But the Oxford English
Dictionary's first citation comes from a British report on
education, dated 1959, when Hofstadter was just 14. He could have
come up with the term independently _ he's a smart guy _ but it
seems unlikely that an American child's coinage would burrow so
rapidly into British educational lingo.)
</P>
<P>
   John Allen Paulos, who recounts the forecaster's blunder in his
1988 book ``Innumeracy,'' thinks word people should be doing less
verbal nit-picking and more calculating. ``I remember once
listening to someone at a party drone on about the difference
between continually and continuously,'' he writes. Yet later that
 &UR; evening &LR; , the forecaster's blooper ``went right by the self-styled
grammarian.''
</P>
<P>
   The sporting world, for some reason, attracts people at once
devoted to numbers and wildly indifferent to probability. The same
people who calculate free-throw percentages and earned run averages
with ease will talk about ``hot bats'' and ``streaks'' to describe
series of events that are not, statistically speaking, unexpected.
As we discovered last spring, in an early foray into the subject,
even sportswriters differ on how many wins (or losses) it takes to
make a streak.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the number, it looks as if this year it's got a new
name. Last year's losing streak is this year's on the schneid, an
old term for a cold spell that's having a hot season among sports
commentators. Richard Roeper, a Chicago Sun-Times columnist, was
moved to protest last week that the buzz of the schneid was already
deafening: ``I used to think the most grating and overused term in
sports was `He goes yard,' which has nearly replaced `He hits a
home run' in the vernacular of some sportscasters,' writes Roeper.
``But `go yard' is pure baseball, whereas `off the schneid'' is
much more versatile and thus ubiquitously annoying. . . . Soon
we'll be hearing that if Susan Lucci ever wins an Emmy, she'll
finally be `off the schneid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As Paul Dickson explains in The New Dickson Baseball Dictionary,
a 1999 update of the 10-year-old compendium, schneid is derived
from schneider, a term denoting a major loss in various card games.
(Schneider, in turn, comes from the German for ``cutter,'' or
tailor.) When you get off the schneid, you've put the losing streak
(real or perceived) behind you. Already, as Roeper notes, the word
is being extended to mean ``jinx,'' as in ``put the schneid on
Kerry Wood.''
</P>
<P>
   How schneid got from the tailor's shop to the card table to the
baseball diamond remains unclear, says Dickson, but it's not a
question that's generated much speculation. The mysterious fungo,
on the other hand, generates many paragraphs of competing theories
with their roots in fun/go, fungible, and fungus, among others. And
the debate over Chinese home run _ racial slur or corruption of
``Chaney's home run'' in a turn-of-the-century game in Salem? _ is
equally entertaining, if equally inconclusive. If someone's put the
schneid on the Sox this season, Dickson's dictionary may provide
fans an alternative baseball fix.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a word to the wise sports reporter: Whatever's going on
with Garciaparra's arm, it's his biceps we're talking about. Ain't
no such thing as a bicep: Singular or plural, it's biceps, from the
Latin for ``two-headed.'' Drop that final s, and the language gods
just might put the schneid on you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
