   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, March 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY-APPRECIATION (Plant City, Fla.) _ Consider the
strawberry. It is the most perfect of fruits: alluringly red,
subtly perfumed, shaped like a heart, sweet as a smile. By R.W.
Apple Jr. With map. With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SCARY-STAIRS (Undated) _ Daunting staircases make for risky
dining. By Amanda Hesser. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PASSOVER-FISH (Undated) _ While keeping tradition in mind, there
is always some room for culinary variations at Passover. For
example, instead of making the usual gefilte fish, which is
typically made from a freshwater fish like pike or whitefish, I
prepare delicate quenelle-like gefilte fish, using fresh and smoked
salmon. With recipe. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   MELLOW-BEER (Undated) _ The newest beer of Rogue Ales sounds
more aggressive than it is. Brutal Bitter is actually a
full-bodied, deeply flavored, intensely hoppy brew. By Elaine
Louie.
</P>
<P>
   DINING-SOLO (Paris) _ Dining alone in the United States is not
exactly unpleasant, but it is often uncomfortable. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEST-KITCHEN (Undated) _ Rather than invest in stove-top
smokers, some cooks rig up their own. The home versions work, but
do they work as well as the specialized versions? By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ A companion for cheese lovers; passover
foods; sleek onions.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ Chef Michael Romano's column,
featuring pan-seared applewood salmon.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The Minimalist: Applesauce-glazed
pork. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINETALK (New York) _ I recently attended a dinner devoted to
wines, all of them white, of the Domaine Trimbach, one of the
best-known producers in Alsace. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ Capsule review of Canoe Ridge Merlot,
1996, Columbia Valley, Washington.
</P>
