   STEPHANOPOULOS SPEAKS: ``All Too Human,'' the awkward title of
the new memoir by President Clinton's former adviser, George
Stephanopoulos, seems meant as a commentary on the author's
famously flawed former boss and on the author himself. The book
depicts Clinton as a man of contradictions, a politician whose very
''shamelessness is a key to his political success.'' (Includes
4-column B&AMP;W photograph of George Stephanopoulos sitting at his
desk and a color photo of the book cover)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: It should come as no surprise that the third
volume of Henry Kissinger's ambitious, all-embracing memoir of
public service, ''Years of Renewal,'' turns out to be a
distinguished and important work. (Includes color photo of book
cover)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: It is difficult not to pity the characters in
Lois-Ann Yamanaka's novel ``Heads by Harry.'' At first glance they
all appear to be such losers. Watching these lives, and the lives
of all the characters, existing on the edge of despair and
hopefulness, is what gives ``Heads by Harry'' its appeal. Includes
color photo of book cover)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Mary Pipher, best-selling author of
``Reviving Ophelia'' and ``The Shelter of Each Other,'' is 50, a
number suggestive of halfway, a midpoint. It suggests that the long
backstretch is behind us and the homestretch around the next turn.
(Includes 1-column color mug shot)
