<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEMINIST-DALY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-23 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMINIST-DALY-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (Undated): ... ``different environment''
<TEXT>
<P>
   And it is an environment that some prominent scholars say is
necessary. Harvey Cox, professor at Harvard Divinity School, who
calls Daly a prophet, says that women talk differently about things
when men are not present, ``and that's simply a fact of life. So
while it's important to have inclusive education, I am still aware
of the fact we haven't moved beyond patriarchy. If and when we ever
do, all education, without exception, could be coed. But we aren't
there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston College would like to differ. Administrators at the
Jesuit school insist that barring men from the classroom is a form
of sexual discrimination prohibited by both Title IX and school
policy. What's more, they say, they've been telling Daly that for
25 years. Jack Dunn, a college spokesman, says that Daly has been
reprimanded several times in connection with eight male students
who have objected to being excluded over the years. In one 1979
case, a university official escorted the student into her class for
several weeks until he dropped out. In the other cases, the male
students dropped the matter, or Daly took one of many leaves of
absence. This time, however, BC says Daly must agree to teach men
in her class. Or she's out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was avoided in previous years. It will not be avoided
now,'' says Dunn. ``We will not back down. It is a legal issue. It
is a fairness issue. It is a justice issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, some wonder, is it an issue that Mary Daly is fighting at
70? Why, after all these years of wrangling with BC, hasn't she
just gone somewhere else? Partly because the market for feminist
separatists is not exactly roaring. But equally because, as Daly
sees it, ``patriarchy is universal,'' so what would it matter?
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that one day last fall senior Duane Naquin showed
up in her classroom. Naquin, 22, wanted to take her course on
feminist ethics. But when he sat down on the first day of class,
Daly took him out to the hall and, according to Naquin, ``she said,
`I do not allow men in my class.' She added, `It's nothing
personal, it's just because you're a man.' I found that very
offensive, completely irrelevant of who I was. I was literally
awestruck.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Daly offered to teach Naquin individually, Naquin said
he wasn't interested and went to school officials. He also got a
lawyer at the the Center for Individual Rights, a conservative
Washington, D.C., law firm that has successfully challenged
race-based admissions in Texas, and says it has 30 lawsuits
pending. In a fund-raising letter, the group identifies one of its
priorities as ``the increasingly urgent task of confronting radical
feminist doctrines and ideology.'' In October, BC received a letter
from the firm threatening to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and her lawyer argue that she was only reprimanded once in
1989 and that otherwise BC never objected to her practice of
teaching men privately. That they are doing so now, she contends,
is because they know it's a hard time for all ``deviants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing something ethically wrong,'' Daly declares.
``And all this stuff about legalism, this is nerdy-turdy little
legalism, legalist fundamentalism. It's just like religious
fundamentalism. Deadly. Nonintellectual. Stifling. It's not about
fairness. It's just evil.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds: ``I am calling upon Boston College and other
universities not to succumb to right-wing pressure. To realize this
is not about discrimination. It is about dumbing down and creating
a white male monoculture.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly the first time she has called for action. In a way,
she's been doing that throughout her career, ever since BC denied
her tenure in 1969 and then, astoundingly, reversed itself after
1,500 students _ all men, as women were not admitted at the time _
marched in protest. In 1971, when Daly became the first woman to
preach at Harvard University's Memorial Church, she led a walkout
of a third of the congregation in protest of patriarchy. Three
years later, Daly was denied full professorship at BC and she
remains an associate professor.
</P>
<P>
   That fact is seen by some as a measure of her unrelenting
commitment to her cause. ``I regard Mary Daly as a prophet,''
declares Jim Carroll, a writer and former Catholic priest. ``She is
right, and religious establishments of almost all kinds are wrong.
Just by staying at BC all these years, by refusing to allow herself
to be changed, she has helped keep alive a broader hope that even
those of us who are not radical on the subject can cling to. If
there were no Mary Daly, all of us would be impoverished.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, however, admits that he stopped reading Daly's books
long ago, finding them too ``exclusivist.'' And there are those who
find Daly's provocative, sometimes self-righteous manner
alienating. During an interview, for example, Daly responded to
several questions by reading aloud from one of her books, once
exclaiming, ``This is very well written.'' Asked about the
difficulty of writing during her legal battle, she warned a
reporter not to portray her as a victim. ``The last thing I am is a
victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly's legendary and ribald humor _ nowhere more evident than in
her 1987 book, ``Websters' First New Intergalactic Wickedary of the
English Language,'' a collection of post-patriarchial definitions _
seems at low ebb these days. She later telephoned the reporter to
say that she had been tired during the interview and could not
recall much of what she had said as she was taking antibiotics
``the size of horse pills'' because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Coakley, a professor at Harvard Divinity School, recalls
when Daly was invited to speak at the school three years ago during
Women's History Month. Daly was nearly an hour late. When she
finally arrived, she said she had forgotten something and then
walked into an adjacent library, according to Coakley, passing
through an emergency doorway and tripping the alarm. When at last
she began to speak, she did not give an original address, but read
from one of her published books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, on the one hand she's the grand old lady of feminist
theology, so she was applauded, but other people were fed up with
the laziness of the whole thing,'' says Coakley. ``I have great
admiration for her, but I don't want to get too near her, frankly.
I find her absolutely infuriating.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, suggests Coakley, do many younger women who recoil at
the notion of feminism, much less separatism. ``Mary Daly looks
like a bag lady who has been rejected by society and does not
represent the glamour and consumer success which by and large they
want. She may be a historic figure, but she is not for them a
desirable model. They precisely do not want to be like her.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter Heyward, a theology professor at Episcopal Divinity
School and a lesbian feminist who briefly taught men and women
separately in the early 1980s, finds Daly's focus on gender at once
inspirational and annoying. ``Mary Daly has the guts a lot of us
don't,'' says Heyward, 53, who is also an Episcopal priest. ``But
it is more complicated than she often says it is.''
</P>
<P>
   On the BC campus, curiously, Daly has had a less polarizing
impact. While faculty members have keen opinions about her
writings, many have never met or even seen her, given that Daly has
spent 14 of her 33 years at BC on leave. A conservative student
newspaper once ran a piece titled ``Can You Spot Mary Daly?'' Daly,
according to other faculty members, does not attend faculty
meetings or collaborate with her colleagues, and her campus
presence is limited to her occasional classes. So it is with
decidedly mixed emotions that the campus community now reads of her
in the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has definitely been underappreciated as a scholar at BC,''
says theology professor Lisa Sowle Cahill. ``But her refusal to
allow men into her class I do not find defensible. If we as a
university are committed to inclusion in the classroom, then to
exclude men or women is not defensible.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there is a prevailing perception of Daly as man-hater, a
few say it is flat-out wrong. John McDargh, an associate theology
professor at BC for 18 years, says that Daly has gone out of her
way to work with some male students. He told of one
African-American student who had been beaten by white students and
was about to drop out when Daly took him under her wing and taught
him how to survive in a hostile environment. Now, McDargh thinks
Daly has become a target for antifeminist backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real sorrow at the way in which this woman whose
scholarly contributions, whatever you think about them, have been
unquestionably transformative of the way in which we think about
religion and gender, is coming to the end of her career in a way
that feels demeaning and insulting,'' says McDargh. ``I think she
is genuinely afraid of her future, of unemployment and no income.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she would say so. Daly bristles at pedestrian questions
about money, rolls her eyes on the subject of health insurance. She
is a stolid combatant, publicly at least, and words are her
weapons, not emotion. If, at times in the past, Daly has
contemplated retirement, if she has gazed out her window at the
shimmering waters of Crystal Lake and thought of a different kind
of life, if she has simply felt tired of it all, now she cannot.
The ax is still aloft.
</P>
<P>
   But, then, maybe that is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no defeating this woman at this point,'' says
Carroll. ``She has made her point very powerfully. She has forced
BC to deal with her right from the beginning, and to BC's credit
they have. So she changed BC, surely. She changed us all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
