<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1060 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEMINIST-DALY-2TAKES-     03-23 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMINIST-DALY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR REFUSES TO OPEN HER CLASS TO MEN
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Daly is a world-recognized theologian and radical feminist
philosopher. She has written seven books and exults in the
possibility of language. Some hail her as a prophet. Even those who
do not nod to her linguistic inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But do not for a minute think that Daly, 70, who has six
graduate degrees and has taught at Boston College for more than
three decades, lets all that education get in the way of her point.
</P>
<P>
   On men: ``They have nothing to offer but
</P>
<P>
   doodoo.''
</P>
<P>
   On herself: ``I'm a positively revolting hag.''
</P>
<P>
   On BC: ``My employer is stupid. It's the same old thing they've
been doing all along, oppressing women.''
</P>
<P>
   On federal law that may bar her from excluding men from her
classes: ``Nerdy-turdy little legalism.''
</P>
<P>
   On that last one, Daly's future now teeters precariously. After
a quarter-century of wary wrangling over Daly's insistence on a
women-only classroom _ she teaches privately the few men who
persist _ BC told her earlier this year that she must admit men or
retire. But if school administrators thought now might be an
opportune time to rid themselves of the sizzling tongue that has
lashed them all these years, if they thought the old radical would
slip quietly into the dark of a conservative night, or that Daly
might even want to spend her eighth decade reflecting in her small
Newton apartment overlooking Crystal Lake, they were very, very
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Daly has spent a lifetime aiming her slingshot as high as
she could see, and then pointed it a little higher. She is not
ready to lay it down. She took her first shot at the Catholic
Church, universal oppressor of women. Then there was God the
Father, dismissed as the manifestation of global patriarchy. And
the young men who wanted to get into her class on feminist ethics.
And then the women who fault her separatism as simplistic, who
criticize her for ignoring the issues of race and class. All of
which leaves the federal government and its Title IX, which
prohibits sexual discrimination at schools that receive federal
funds, looking like a knock-kneed 100-pounder clinging to the
ropes. Or so she might hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Title IX was meant to give equality to women. To reverse it
into this caricature now, to try and give equality to men in a
white male-dominated society, is absurd,'' fumes Daly. ``It's
irrelevant to the discussion. . . . And no one even sees that it's
funny. That's the worst part. They don't even laugh. What? Mary
Daly and Title IX! It's too bizarre for comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, however, is not exactly laughing. Mary Daly may have been
a vaunted heroine of the 1970s with the double ax of the amazon
gripped in her hand, her in-your-face lesbianism, and her book
``Gyn/Ecology,'' in which she describes atrocities committed by men
against women and prescribes a pure state of female being. She may
thump the couch arm and insist that feminism is strong as ever. She
may be lionized by those who admire her sheer intellectual force
and originality, if not her authoritarian manner.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed and Daly's separatism is as repugnant to
some young women as it is to the men who are its target. The
lawyers in her fight with BC are just beginning to battle in
earnest, but Daly's practice of excluding men, variably tolerated
as a benign eccentricity or lauded as fair redress, may now be
found illegal.
</P>
<P>
   It is a battle of principle, a fitting finale to a career that
has sought no less than to alter the course of world civilization.
For just as BC has drawn its line in the sand, so Daly refuses to
surrender on a point that goes to the heart of her philosophy and
life's work. On leave _ the university says it is unpaid, but
Daly's lawyer says she is receiving her salary _ since this latest
go-round over her policy erupted after a male student objected to
exclusion, Daly has rejected a retirement package and is uncertain
what to do next. But on one thing she is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to be myself,'' exclaims Daly. ``I'm Mary Daly. I'm
tough. I'm strong.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is not polite. On a blustery winter afternoon recently,
Daly is fresh back from an out-of-town speaking engagement the
night before. A reporter arrives at the door of her second-floor
apartment for an interview three minutes early. Daly opens the door
and stares. The reporter apologizes for being early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do early,'' Daly says flatly.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter offers to leave, or sit quietly in a corner until
Daly is ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd still feel your vibes,'' says Daly, shaking her head.
</P>
<P>
   When the reporter returns 15 minutes later, Daly is welcoming,
but not much happier. Although she has agreed to talk about her
dispute with BC, questions about Title IX are ``boring,'' she
grumbles, her employer ``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   What she wants to talk about are her books, which are tucked in
the stacks that line the walls of her four-room apartment, about
her philosophy, and about her post-Christian feminism that she
first articulated in her internationally acclaimed book, ``Beyond
God the Father,'' in 1973. She wants to talk about her work as a
``Pirate, Righteously Plundering and Smuggling back to women the
gems which have been stolen from us by the patriarchal thieves,''
as she wrote in her 1992 intellectual autobiography, ``Outercourse:
The Be-Dazzling Voyage.'' She wants to talk about the four spiral
galaxies that compose the theological voyage that took her from her
birth in the year Oh!, as she calls it, and away not just from the
Catholic Church but Christianity and the ``necrophilia of
patriarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   If it were not for the intrusion of the BC affair, she would, in
fact, be sitting at the cluttered desk in the middle of her living
room, right there beneath the posters from her speaking engagements
and the pictures of spider webs and dragons, cat toys strewn about
her feet, writing a sequel to her last book, ``Quintessence . . .
Realizing the Archaic Future: A Radical Elemental Feminist
Manifesto,'' about the sixth dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this daughter of Schenectady, N. Y., only child of a
traveling salesman and a telephone operator, product of 26 years of
Catholic schooling, is sitting in her baggy blue pants and black
sneakers in an apartment she has rented for 10 years talking about
lawyers. Her amiable gray cat, F. Cat Draiochta O'Dalaigh _ F. is
for Fearless, Draiochta means ```of magic''' in Irish, and
O'Dalaigh is a Daly ancestor _ is rubbing determinedly against her
thigh. She is running her hands through her short-cropped gray hair
and explaining why it so important that her female students have a
classroom of their own, a space removed from the omnipresent
patriarchy, so that they are not inhibited by men or slowed by the
men's inability to understand woman's experience. So they are able,
in short, ``to forge ahead. To soar!'' Even the small candle
burning on the bookshelf cannot leaven her grim approach to all
this explaining. Yet again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a man were in the class he would be very likely to say,
`Oh, no. I am oppressed too.' . . . He would say, `I can't cry. I'm
not allowed to express myself, wah, wah,' '' Daly explains,
feigning tears. ``OK. Let them go talk among themselves and
complain. Not everything is about you, you, you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not being mean,'' adds Daly. ``I'm trying to be good to my
female students and give them what they are longing for and they
cannot find in the whole big monstrous institution.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of people agree with her. Daly, who joined BC in 1966,
taught only men until women were admitted in 1970 and began
teaching men and women separately in 1974. Since then, Daly has
offered to teach males privately and has done so, she says, in
about a dozen cases. And that's just the way some female students
like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her class was the most engaging, amazing personal experience I
have had at this school,'' says BC senior Kelly Matthews, one of 14
students who sent a letter to college administrators last month
supporting Daly. ``I generally do not feel uncomfortable voicing my
opinion when men are in a class, but I absolutely prefer all-woman
space to discuss women's topics. It is a vastly different
environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1524EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
