<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-MURRAY-BOS &LR;      03-23 1656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-MURRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRENCE MURRAY PLAYS `BOSTON CARD' AND WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When Terrence Murray, Fleet Financial Group Inc.'s
chief executive, launched his latest attempt to persuade BankBoston
Corp.'s Charles Gifford to merge, he used more than charts and
spreadsheets to pitch a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to Gifford's strong attachment to the proud,
215-year-old BankBoston, Murray also played to his rival's loyalty
to the city of Boston. By teaming up, he argued, the two companies
could ward off bidders from outside the region, ensuring the
survival of a large hometown bank in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic theme Terry developed was, `Together, we can have a
Boston-based, world-class, sophisticated institution,'' said a
BankBoston executive involved in the transaction. ``The region and
the economy will benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   That Fleet, which descends from a Providence institution founded
in 1791, never talks about its own historic roots suggests how
little Murray cares for tradition. So it is not surprising that as
Murray pitched his merger idea, he masterfully transformed
Gifford's image of Boston past into a vision of Boston future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry,'' the source said, ``played the Boston card.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the feisty Fleet chief dealt himself a winner. Last
week, after clinching a blockbuster deal to buy BankBoston for $16
billion, Murray _ the son of a factory worker from blue-collar
Woonsocket R.I. _ firmly established himself as king of the hill in
New England banking. Although Fleet had long ago surpassed
BankBoston as the region's biggest bank, Murray's takeover of
America's oldest bank marked the ultimate victory for the
59-year-old businessman. Once seen as an interloper, Murray had
finally taken hold of the crown, in effect dethroning his rival,
the epitome of Brahmin Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray is now more than just the head of the nation's
eighth-largest bank. The new company, Fleet Boston Corp., has a
combined $178 billion in assets and has overnight emerged as a
superregional bank that analysts expect to become a strong national
and international competitor. In coming years, Murray is likely to
mold the new company in his trademark aggressive style, lending
Boston an image that is perhaps more entrepreneurial and less
buttoned-down.
</P>
<P>
   More straight-talking, hard-nosed businessman than polite,
pin-striped Yankee, and full of burlap speech that contrasts with
Gifford's gossamer rhetoric, Murray is likeable and full of
home-spun stories.
</P>
<P>
   He is also brusque and private _ qualities that lead many
observers to view him as the antithesis of the socially active
Gifford, a man dubbed ``Mr. Boston'' for his community work.
</P>
<P>
   While Murray is widely admired around town for his business
sense and corporate charity, he doesn't appear to care much about
what people think of him. By contrast, civic-minded Gifford, 56, is
protective _ and promotive _ of BankBoston's public image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry probably sees making the bank strong and competitive as
his major contribution to the city, as opposed to being more
social,'' said John Cullinane, a Boston-based investor who has
known Murray for three decades. ``I honestly don't think he'll be
as high profile and social as Chad.''
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to what he calls the ``core values'' of Fleet Boston,
Murray spoke in an interview last week of ``a determined sense of
responsibility to our region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about the arts, humanities, the community,'' said
the red-haired Murray, a prodigious reader of biographies and an
avid collector of American 19th and 20th century landscapes. He
recently bought his first nude.
</P>
<P>
   How generous a corporate donor Fleet Boston will be remains to
be seen. In any case, Murray likes to keep much of Fleet's
corporate giving private. (The company, bigger than its rival,
donated $13.5 million to various causes last year, compared with
BankBoston's $11.5 million).
</P>
<P>
   But already there are positive signs, including a pledge by the
new company to create a $100 million charitable foundation. Of
course, Gifford will take over Fleet Boston when Murray retires in
2001, under a carefully crafted succession plan laid out in the
merger pact. And Murray could not have done his deal without equal
cooperation from his old rival, with whom he says he has become
fast friends.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Murray's imprimateur on Boston promises to be
distinct.
</P>
<P>
   Cast as an outsider by many Bostonians despite his Irish
ancestry, even after he barged his way into town by acquiring the
failed Bank of New England eight years ago, Murray has always
scorned status. He is happiest at his residences in Providence and
Narragansett, R.I., shooting the breeze with old friends. (He also
maintains an art- and antique-filled apartment overlooking Boston
Public Garden).
</P>
<P>
   Before the merger agreement, Boston was in danger of becoming an
anomaly. In an era of rapid consolidation, in which both Fleet and
BankBoston became takeover prey for larger banks from outside the
region, the city might have continued to grow as the world's mutual
fund capital but without a major hometown bank. It could still end
up that way if a company outside the region sets its sights on the
new Fleet Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, at least, Murray has ensured that Boston at least
in some ways is more like Zurich _ a city with giant banks, money
management firms, and insurers _ than Dallas, where once-large
banks have been sold to competitors outside the region.
</P>
<P>
   Murray has certainly had ample practice being the gobbler rather
than the gobbled. With the exception of BayBanks Inc., which
BankBoston bought in 1996, Murray has spent the past 10 years
cobbling together a regional empire by acquiring many of the most
attractive midsize franchises in the Northeast, including Norstar
Bancorp., Shawmut National Corp., and NatWest Bank. More recently,
he shaped Fleet into a diversified financial services company by
acquiring credit card, money management, and stock brokerage
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has a company that could become national in scope but is
still rooted on Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some respects, Boston is very sophisticated,'' Murray mused
in his downtown Fleet office. He repeatedly looked at a telescope
perched on the sill of his 37th-floor window. ``In others, it's
very local. It takes decades for (traditional viewpoints) to break
down here, where it just takes years in other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray has always stood somewhat aloof from Boston's social
whirlwind. When he chaired the city's American Ireland Fund gala in
November, he seemed to take a rare step into the public spotlight
more out of pride in his ethnic heritage than out of a desire to
schmooze with the movers and shakers of the Boston Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about Terry Murray is that he responded to the
distant drum of the ancestral echo,'' said Kingsley Aikins, the
fund's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's Horatio Alger past, long the stuff of legend in banking
circles, is a far cry from Gifford's more privileged upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   As the son of a textile mill laborer in rough-and-tumble
Woonsocket, the mischievous Murray was always in trouble. At an
Irish wake for a family friend, the youth burst into hysterical
laughter when his grandfather tripped and fell under the casket and
couldn't get up. At the age of 9, he got himself thrown out of
Catholic public school after slapping a nun who had whacked him for
disrupting catechism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't stop laughing at things,'' said Murray, an avid
golfer who turned pink with laughter as he recounted the episodes.
``It wasn't mean stuff. It was just at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray's behavior was unruly enough for his father to yank
him out of high school for a year to work the night shift in a
local textile mill. He eventually entered Providence Country Day
School on a scholarship and went on to Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing Harvard in 1962 with an English degree and
mediocre grades, he applied to 26 stock brokerages for a job, but
was roundly rejected. That year, as a consolation prize, he joined
Industrial National Bank of Providence.
</P>
<P>
   Over more than three decades, he would slowly, methodically turn
the tiny, unknown bank in the smallest state into one of the
nation's 10 largest banks, doing dozens of deals that left his
competitors trampled or reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet overtook BankBoston in assets and deposits several years
ago. But it was not until the scrappy Murray sealed the deal to
acquire his rival last Sunday that he became the personification _
and survivor _ of Boston banking.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the latest proof that he is one of banking's most
aggressive dealmakers, Murray is showing a softer side. While one
of his lieutenants calls him the ``Celtic Chieftain'' and others
crow that Fleet ``bagged'' BankBoston, Murray graciously refers to
the deal as a merger of equals _ even though Fleet's is the
surviving stock.
</P>
<P>
   He even says that he is no longer 100 percent focused on
business. ``I think I enjoy life a lot more,'' he said, referring
to his close-knit family, which includes his wife, Suzanne, their
five children, and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Murray is far from finished with deal making.
</P>
<P>
   He recently paid a visit to TransAmerica Corp., the San
Francisco-based insurance giant recently acquired by giant Dutch
insurer Aegon, to see how large insurers do business. When asked if
he had his eyes on John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., as
rumored in Boston, he replied only that he was interested in
expanding in financial services.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that Boston's new king of the hill has
his eyes on a larger landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about the BankBoston transaction for years,'' he
said, looking out across the city and harbor. ``The idea of a large
global company based in our back yard is important to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
