<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLACEBO-ETHICS-BOS &LR;      03-23 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLACEBO-ETHICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE OF PLACEBOS ON MENTAL PATIENTS QUESTIONED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last decade, at least 850 patients seriously ill with
schizophrenia were given dummy sugar pills instead of medications
known to work, as part of US-approved studies of experimental
anti-psychotic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 70 percent of the patients randomly assigned to receive a
placebo, as the dummy pill is called, experienced such a worsening
of symptoms that they had to withdraw from the trials, and at least
one patient committed suicide, according to a Globe review of the
experiment data.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you possibly put somebody on placebo when they could
commit suicide?'' said Karin B. Michels, an epidemiologist at
Harvard Medical School and a prominent critic of the use of
placebos in trials of new drugs, when effective medications for
diseases are already on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The studies, mainly funded by pharmaceutical firms, have
primarily involved patients at state mental institutions and
Veterans Affairs hospitals from Massachusetts to California,
according to the Globe's review of both published studies and
unpublished data reported to the US Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, they're treating the mentally ill like lab rats. This is
absolutely outrageous,'' said Paul K. Ling, a Quincy psychologist
who is a leader in the Massachusetts-wide Consortium for
Psychotherapy, which advocates greater access to care for the
mentally ill. ``They are exploiting the most vulnerable segment of
the population.''
</P>
<P>
   In tests of drugs for many medical conditions, especially those
for which there is no good treatment, placebo controls are common.
But patients with cancer or fast-moving bacterial infections, for
instance, would never be put on sugar pills as part of studying
potentially new chemotherapy drugs or antibiotics. They would
instead be given medications already known to work to compare with
patients given the trial medication.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of using a so-called placebo control in testing
experimental anti-psychotics and certain other drugs, even when
there are already effective medications on the market, has long
been demanded by the FDA as a scientific ``gold standard'' to
measure drug efficacy, and pharmaceutical firms and researchers
have complied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in good science. We believe in following FDA
regulations,'' said Dr. Bert Spilker, senior vice president of
scientific and regulatory affairs for Pharmaceutical Research
Manufacturers of America, commonly known as PhRMA, an industry
group. As a result, he said, ``Usually, good science and good
ethics prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   But after a Globe series on psychiatric research that
highlighted drug-testing issues in November and amid growing
concerns by some ethicists and scientists, the FDA and the National
Institute of Mental Health now plan to review the use of placebos,
according to federal officials and others familiar with the
agencies' deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is sponsoring a symposium next month on placebo
experiments in general, not just for the mentally ill, and has
invited a prominent critic, Dr. Sidney Wolfe of Public Citizen's
Health Research Group, along with others, to debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe series focused on experiments in which mentally ill
patients were allowed to deteriorate after being deprived of drugs
that have worked for them or after having been given substances
that actually worsen their psychosis.
</P>
<P>
   The series has helped spur a debate on drug-testing practices,
particularly placebo use, by the American College of
Neuropsychopharmacology, an international psychiatric research
group, according to one scientist who has participated in the
heated discussion over the use of placebos.
</P>
<P>
   The series has also prompted the Massachusetts Department of
Mental Health to put on hold two studies involving placebos while
new research guidelines to protect patients are finalized in the
next month, said Dr. Paul Barreira, a DMH deputy commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   And the National Bioethics Advisory Commission, appointed by the
president, has recommended that the US Department of Health and
Human Services retain the Institute of Medicine to review
placebo-controlled studies, along with research that induces
psychosis in people with mental illness, according to Eric M.
Meslin, the commission's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe's new analysis looked at unpublished data submitted to
the FDA in the 1990s by pharmaceutical firms for three
antipsychotic drugs that have since been approved: Zyprexa
(olanzapine), Risperdal (risperidone), and Seroquel (quetiapine).
And it reviewed the published scientific literature for those
drugs, and a fourth _ Serlect (sertindole), which was withdrawn
from consideration after an FDA advisory committee questioned its
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the more than 850 patients given a placebo, 236 were in
studies of Zyprexa, 195 in studies of Risperdal, 206 in studies of
Seroquel, and at least 221 in studies of Serlect, according to the
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   According to the review of the published literature, the Globe
also found that researchers enrolled patients who were so severely
ill that their ability to understand the risk of being given a
sugar pill was questionable.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one 1996 study said patients assigned to a placebo
had met ``criteria for schizophrenia with acute exacerbation,'' and
yet were said to have given ``written informed consent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another 1996 study said patients on a placebo had been
experiencing ``acute exacerbation'' for an average of 91 days, and
had been hospitalized for almost three weeks on average, before
signing up for the research.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe review also found that psychiatric researchers even
anticipated a high dropout rate among patients on placebos as a
result of worsening symptoms. For example, a 1997 study stated that
``as expected, lack of efficacy was the primary reason for
withdrawal and was seen most often in the placebo groups,'' with 35
out of 51 patients on a placebo, or 69 percent, withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of the drug Zyprexa that ended in 1995, a 34-year-old
man committed suicide while on a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the more than 850 people placed on a placebo in studies
across the United States and Canada in the 1990s, a couple of dozen
of them were enrolled through the state's Massachusetts Mental
Health Center, under the auspices of a Harvard associate professor
of psychiatry, Dr. Alan I. Green. Based on the state's changing
research guidelines, those studies, completed several years ago,
would probably not be allowed at the DMH facility now.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Green said, ``I think you always want to ask
the question, `What's ethical?' The FDA has determined that the
only way to figure out whether a drug works or not, in certain
areas, certainly in this area, is to use a placebo control.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``The whole field, including the FDA, including
ethicists, is trying to decide the best way to conduct trials. I
think everybody is trying to do the same thing, which is to make
newer, better medications available. As better medications become
available, the way you think this through conceivably could
evolve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe's new findings, along with the already rising concern
about the use of placebos, prompted scientists and ethicists to
sound an even louder alarm last week about the use of placebos in
certain studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most harmful ongoing research abuse in
North America,'' said Dr. Charles Weijer, bioethicist and assistant
professor of medicine at Dalhousie University in Canada, who helped
devise new Canadian guidelines prohibiting placebo use in certain
studies, particularly those involving people with schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is appalling,'' said Adil Shamoo, a University of Maryland
bioethicist who co-founded Citizens for Responsible Care in
Psychiatry and Research with Vera Hassner Sharav.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a drug that has been demonstrated by convincing
evidence to be safe and effective for a life-threatening disease,
one should not go back after that point and use placebos in future
trials,'' said LeRoy Walters, director of the Kennedy Institute of
Ethics at Georgetown University in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would categorize schizophrenia as a life-threatening
disorder,'' especially with the relatively high risk of suicide,
Walters said. ``There should not be a placebo group in my view.''
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials could not be reached for comment on Friday, but
have previously said they require a placebo for scientific rigor,
to make sure the drugs under study are efficacious.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth J. Rothman, a professor of epidemiology at Boston
University School of Public Health and editor of the journal
Epidemiology, disputed the FDA's claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people who think you can't do a study without a placebo _
they're wrong,'' said Rothman, who co-authored with Harvard's
Michels a widely cited article in the New England Journal of
Medicine criticizing the misuse of placebos.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rothman said, using a placebo for comparison in tests
of experimental drugs instead of medications known to be effective
may lead to the approval of drugs that are better than nothing, but
worse than the best that is already on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Globe correspondent Robert Whitaker contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1600EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
