<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENSTRUAL-BLEEDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE ARE OPTIONS TO HYSTERECTOMIES TO SOLVE SEVERE MENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Elizabeth Hemstead didn't pay much attention to
her periods until they stretched beyond a week, then two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a nuisance more than anything else,'' said
Hemstead, a high school athletic director and coach. She attributed
her fatigue to a hectic schedule of teaching and coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I was going to give blood one day and they did that
little test, and sure enough, I was anemic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For an estimated 180,000 women each year, the solution to
dysfunctional uterine bleeding or severe menstrual periods has been
a hysterectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Caused by a hormonal imbalance, the problem strikes an estimated
20 percent of all women at some point in their lives, usually at
puberty or just before menopause as was the case with Hemstead, who
is 49.
</P>
<P>
   In a few cases, the bleeding is so severe that not even pads or
tampons can stanch the flow. Although not medically serious, such
excessive bleeding can lead to everything from anemia to personal
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Some women get relief from oral contraceptives to balance their
hormones. Others may temporarily improve their symptoms with
dilation and curettage, a procedure to scrape out the uterine
lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bleeding that takes over your life,'' said Dr. Eileen
Joyce, an obstetrician and gynecologist for Upstate Ob/Gyn
Associates and St. Peter's Hospital in Albany. ``You could bleed
enough to need a blood transfusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hemstead is no longer anemic and her menstrual flow is
light and regular, thanks to uterine balloon therapy, the latest in
a new wave of treatments to offer an alternative to the traditional
hysterectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, she was one of the first few thousand women in the
United States to undergo the procedure, a 10-minute outpatient
surgical technique that permanently removes the endometrial lining
of the uterus, using heated fluid inside a balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cauterizing the endometrial cells so they can't bleed
anymore,'' Joyce said. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration
approved the procedure, known as ThermaChoice, 15 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier method to stop bleeding, known as rollerball, is
similar in concept and uses a tiny roller to cauterize the inside
of the uterus. But that procedure, which requires a physician to
expand the uterus with fluid, has come under increased scrutiny
because of potentially fatal complications.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts say that balloon therapy is safer and less risky
because the fluid is encased in a balloon. ``The balloon now gives
us a very simple cure, without significant side effects or
complications,'' said Dr. Kate O'Keeffe, a Glens Falls, N.Y.,
obstetrician and gynecologist.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the temporary side-effects include cramping and
discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Not all women are eligible for balloon therapy. Physicians must
first rule out any other gynecologic problems, such as fibroids, an
abnormally shaped uterus, or a cancerous condition.
</P>
<P>
   And because balloon therapy destroys the endometrium, which is
necessary to support a pregnancy, it is only for women who don't
want children.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, balloon therapy doesn't work for everyone. Clinical
data shows that about 15 percent of patients see no change in their
bleeding, while 30 percent stop bleeding altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Yet O'Keeffe believes balloon therapy will eventually help cut
down the number of elective hysterectomies in the United States at
a savings to the health care system and women.
</P>
<P>
   While a hysterectomy is a major surgery requiring three days in
the hospital and six weeks recovery time, uterine balloon therapy
can be completed on an out-patient basis. Most women can resume all
activities, including sexual intercourse, a week to 10 days after
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much less invasive. It's also much less costly,'' said
Dianne Anderson, a registered nurse and vice president for patient
services at Glens Falls Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ThermaChoice costs about $2,500, compared with $8,000 to $10,000
for a hysterectomy and is generally covered by insurance. Hemstead
is just relieved that her periods are lighter and shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of my life has really improved,'' she said.
Although she knows many women who've had successful hysterectomies,
she's glad she had an alternative. ``This was certainly a much
better option.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood is the Times Union's health writer. She can be
reached at 518-454-5445 or at swood(at)timesunion.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
