A1129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-23 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANT SURPLUS TEMPTS GOP TO ABANDON CONSERVATIVE FISCAL POLICY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 bY THOMAS OLIPHANT 
C.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Where are the conservatives when we need them?
</P>
<P>
   Emerging in Congress is a budget strategy that would probably
keep the national debt from being reduced in a time of
unprecedented surplus, lead to substantial deficits in the future,
and create a huge entitlement program for millions of Americans who
don't need it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason conservatives are not mobilizing to oppose such an
irresponsible future is that they are deeply implicated in it; this
is the budget being readied for consideration by Republicans in
both branches, not just the budget types like Pete Domenici and
John Kasich, but the Social Security privatizers lead by Bill
Archer in the House and Phil Gramm in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget remains extremely vulnerable to opposition
from moderates who are likely to find its Draconian cuts
unpalatable. However, it remains the party's vehicle in Congress
and is certain to heavily influence the nascent presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise in the products of Domenici's Senate Budget
Committee and Kasich's House counterpart is the extent to which
they do not do what Republicans claimed they would do more credibly
than President Clinton _ guarantee that budget surpluses would be
used to pay down the national debt held by the public, thus
lowering crunching government interest costs and freeing more
capital for productive investment in the country's amazingly strong
economy, as well as taking a huge step toward putting Social
Security in shape for the Baby Boom's retirement.
</P>
<P>
   When Domenici and Kasich first went public with the
``framework'' for the budget, they promised to ``lock away every
penny of the Social Security trust fund surpluses for our nation's
elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that they have written their actual budget resolutions, it
turns out that what they mean by the elderly and Social Security
are two different things.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP resolutions are designed to fit with legislation by
Senator Spencer Abraham of Michigan to create a ``lockbox'' for
those anticipated surpluses. In essence, this legislation
prescribes sharp reduction in the limit on debt held by the public
over the next decade, with two provisions for adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   One is responsible, up or down in the debt limit depending on
the actual fiscal results.
</P>
<P>
   The other is dangerous. It would permit increases in the debt
limit to the extent resources are needed to fund ``reform'' of the
system.
</P>
<P>
   The reform is privatization, pure and simple, permitting the
creation of individual retirement funds with two percentage points
of the existing payroll tax in a scheme that (especially in the
House versions of it) is also designed to produce no reduction in
future Social Security benefits. The plan would cost trillions over
the next generation, and the funding mechanism would be the Social
Security surpluses that will continue to accumulate for about
another 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   One place the Republican budgets most assuredly will not allow
to be a source of money would be any non-Social Security surpluses
that might appear in the future. This is where the gigantic
allowance for income tax cuts, military spending increases and
sharp cuts in the operating budget of the government all come into
play with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, in return for partial privatization of Social
Security, the national debt could easily remain in the trillions
for our kids to choke on while the economic stimulus and other
domestic opportunities from its near-eradication would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. With backing from the center and progressive
wings of his party, the president's proposal would put 77 percent
of any government surplus into Social Security (62 percent) and
Medicare (15 percent), with another large chunk available to help
middle-class and working-poor Americans establish retirement
accounts outside Social Security. As now written, the Republicans
go in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, there are ways that these contrasting visions
can be reconciled by imaginitive politicians interested in
solutions during this brief period of possibility before next
year's politics gradually takes over everything.
</P>
<P>
   If not, this is an issue easily capable of dwarfing all the
others.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
