   N.Y. Times News Service entertainment budget for papers of
Wednesday, March 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   ARTIST-INSPIRATION (New York) _ Inspiration, like opportunity,
often comes cloaked in strange guises. For Jim Hodges, a Brooklyn
artist, it came in a life-changing way because a cashier at a
Korean deli did what cashiers do hundreds of thousands of times
every day in New York. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   HUMANA-THEATER-FESTIVAL (Louisville, Ky.) - Though the play
``Y2K'' was an inexhaustible subject of conversation at the 23rd
annual Humana Festival of New American Plays at the Actors Theater
of Louisville this weekend, theater professionals were also
focusing on another festival phenomenon: the attempt to blur the
boundaries between actors and audience. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   GELMAN-ART-COLLECTION (Paris) _ When Jacques Gelman died in
1986, he and his wife had two quite separate collections: one of
works by modern masters like Picasso, Matisse, Braque and Balthus,
which was kept in New York, the other of paintings and drawings by
this century's most prominent Mexican artists, which was on display
in their home in Cuernavaca, Mexico. When Mrs. Gelman died last
May, she bequeathed the modern masters collection, comprising 85
works worth over $300 million, to the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
New York. But the final home of the Mexican collection is still in
doubt. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC-CONFERENCE (Austin, Texas) _ In the past at the South
by Southwest convention, for years the rock business' most
important cavalcade of performances and panel discussions, talent
scouts came looking for tomorrow's rock stars. But something was
different this year. The change was best represented by the agenda
of one scout from a major label. Speaking on condition of
anonymity, he said he had come here not to sign a band, but to
prevent his label from signing one. By Neil Strauss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOMWAITS-MUSIC-REVIEW (Austin, Texas) _ ``I must sound like
George Burns!'' Tom Waits commented midway through his performance
on Saturday night as part of the South by Southwest festival at the
Paramount Theater here. By Neil Strauss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NINE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Marvin is a former drug addict who
has returned from California to the small town in Montana where he
grew up. His notion about the illusory nature of meaningful
decisions seems on the mark very early on in Kevin Canty's smart,
gritty, unsentimental new novel, ``Nine Below Zero,'' in which love
and despair are set in a sorrowful, desperation-laden Western
landscape. Richard Bernstein reviews .
</P>
<P>
   TV-NORM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Norm Show,'' which has its
premiere Wednesday on ABC, could go either way, depending on the
scripts ahead. At its best, it proves that jerky-guy characters and
actual humor can co-exist. Anita Gates reviews .
</P>
<P>
   TV-ITS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The ``Seinfeld'' DNA is unmistakable
and the title entirely off-putting, but those are misleading first
impressions of ``It's Like, You Know . . .,'' a witty, charming,
acerbic comedy in which a cynical New Yorker parachutes into the
midst of a group of Los Angeles friends. Caryn James reviews .
</P>
</TEXT>
