<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-0324-COX     03-23 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-0324-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS URGE CLINTON TO WITHDRAW TROOPS FROM HAITI
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI -- Influential congressional Republicans called on
President Clinton Tuesday to heed the advice of the top U.S.
military commander for Latin America and withdraw American
peackeeping troops from Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unrest and political instability mean that U.S. troops are
spending an increasing amount of their energy watching their backs,
rather than pursuing humanitarian projects,'' the Republicans said
in a letter.
</P>
<P>
   It was signed by six Republicans, including Sen. Jesse Helms
(R-N.C.), chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and
Rep. Benjamin Gilman (R-N.Y.), chairman of the House International
Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gen. Charles Wilhelm, who leads the U.S. Southern
Command, told the defense subcommittee of the House Appropriations
Committee that troops have been unable to create stability in
Haiti, and that he feared for their safety. He recommended an end
to the permanent U.S. troop presence.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' request follows a two-day series by Cox
Newspapers on Haiti. Cox Newspapers reported that $2.2 billion in
American taxpayer money had brought neither a working democracy nor
real progress to the poor Caribbean nation.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1994, Clinton sent 20,000 troops to Haiti to
restore democracy. Today, about 500 troops remain to build schools,
repair roads, and perform other humanitarian tasks at a cost of
about $22 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the political situation in Haiti has become
increasingly unstable. Political assassinations are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Haitian President Rene Preval dissolved parliament,
essentially imposing one-man rule.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the Republicans said money and troops assets
must be freed up in light of a massive reconstruction effort in
Central America, which was devastated last year by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   According to Raul Duany, a spokesman for the U.S. Southern
Command, about 2,500 U.S. troops are participating in medical and
engineering projects in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said U.S. troops will remain in Haiti
into the near future, although their presence is being constantly
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
