 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, March 24, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ President Clinton said Tuesday that
NATO was ready to carry out air strikes against Serb targets after
the failure of a last-gasp Kosovo peace mission. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV (Washington) _ Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov abruptly cancelled his U.S. visit amid the growing
likelihood of air strikes against Serb targets, Vice President Al
Gore announced Tuesday. In a statement, Gore said he had discussed
the U.S. failure to win a peace deal on Kosovo with Primakov aboard
his aircraft en route to Washington. Primakov then changed course
over the Atlantic and headed home. (Early summary by wires.) By
John M. Broder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) Susan H. McDougal, whose
steadfast refusal to answer prosecutors' questions about President
Clinton put her in jail for 18 months, crisply and directly
answered those very same questions in a Federal court on Tuesday,
testifying that she had no knowledge of any wrongdoing on Mr.
Clinton's part. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN-TRIAL (Pontiac, Mich.) Insisting upon acting as his
own lawyer in his trial for first degree murder, Dr. Jack
Kervorkian stumbled in the first day of testimony Tuesday, asking
witnesses legally inappropriate questions and raising impermissible
legal arguments as he tried to convince a jury that he should not
be convicted for his role in ending the life of a seriously ill
man. His lack of legal skill so handicapped his case that he was
told he could not call his key witness, the wife of the dead man,
unless he can convince the judge that the woman's testimony would
be relevant. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MERGERS (Paris) It looks like a replay of the 1980s on
Wall Street: Hostile takeovers, ``bear hugs,'' white knights and an
endless stream of extraordinarily high-priced investment bankers
pitching new deals every day. Certainly, Europe has never seen a
boom in mergers and acquisitions like the one now in full force.
Yet for all the talk about Europe's single market and single
currency, and despite the rise of hostile takeovers, something big
is missing. Very few cross-border deals have taken place, and those
that are in active discussions have run into problems. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-GAMBLING24-C     03-23 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-GAMBLING24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS MOVES TO BAN INTERNET GAMBLING
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Congress gets its way, it may be tougher to bet
the house with a click of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   With more than a billion dollars likely to be gambled over the
Internet this year, Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., introduced a bill
Tuesday that would expand law enforcement's reach into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl's bill would update the Federal Wire Act of 1961, which
governs gambling over the telephone. It would ban both online
casino games and sports gambling, although online ``fantasy
baseball'' leagues and the like would remain exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of businesses that offer gambling over the Internet could
be fined an amount equal to the bets they have handled and be
jailed for up to four years. But Kyl dropped federal penalties for
individual bettors, which had been included in last year's version
of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation sailed through the Senate last year on a 90-10
vote, but eventually bogged down when the House Judiciary Committee
turned its attention to the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   To judge by Tuesday's hearing before Kyl's Judiciary
subcommittee, his current approach enjoys wide bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., testified that Kyl's bill is
needed because current laws are inadequate. She warned, however,
that any measure ``should not slow down the Internet'' or burden
online businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Attorney General Betty Montgomery, a Republican, delivered
the endorsement of the National Association of State Attorneys
General, which usually seeks to curb federal inroads into state
laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a threat to the traditional independence of
state law enforcement,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that an Internet gambling ban ``will be difficult
to enforce,'' she added: ``The continued rapid growth of the
industry and the inability of states to enforce their varied laws
and policies is just one more reason that federal legislation
should be enacted quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl also said he had won the support of Internet service
providers, including giant America Online Inc., to cut off links to
gambling Web sites, many of which are licensed by cash-starved
Caribbean and Central American countries.
</P>
<P>
   But with Americans expected to wager a record $650 billion this
year, a blend of political pressure and technological problems
could stall a cyber-gambling ban.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tom Bell of the Cato Institute, a libertarian-leaning
Washington policy center: ``The architecture of the Internet makes
prohibition easy to evade and impossible to enforce. As an
international network, moreover, the Internet offers instant
detours around domestic bans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is also somewhat unhappy with Kyl's
effort, the senator noted in an interview. ``They are on the
razor's edge,'' he said. ``They are prosecuting some cases right
now under the (1961 Wire) Act, and they're fearful that defense
lawyers could cite my bill as evidence that the current law doesn't
apply to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not called to testify, but submitting written comments at the
Kyl hearing, was an association representing Internet gambling
operators called the Interactive Gaming Counsel. Sue Schneider, the
group's chairman, called for regulation of Internet gambling rather
than an outright ban.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
