<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASSOVER-FISH-NYT &LR;      03-23 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSOVER-FISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW IDEA FOR FISH ECHOES SEDERS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The menu for a Passover seder, the dinner that starts the
eight-day observance of the holiday, is largely determined by
ritual and tradition. Certain ceremonial foods, like matzohs,
bitter herbs and wine, must be served. The rest of the meal is
often dictated by family expectations, which can often seem just as
immutable.
</P>
<P>
   While keeping tradition in mind, there is always some room for
culinary variations at Passover, which this year starts on March
31.
</P>
<P>
   For example, instead of making the usual gefilte fish, which is
typically made from a freshwater fish like pike or whitefish, I
prepare delicate quenelle-like gefilte fish using fresh and smoked
salmon, and serve it with horseradish mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   Another variation was suggested to me by a dish at Le Bernardin,
the French fish restaurant in Manhattan. Though Le Bernardin,
unlike some restaurants in New York, will not be serving a special
Passover menu, Eric Ripert, the chef and one of the owners, has
come up with an appropriate dish: steamed halibut in borscht with
warm chive-horseradish sauce.
</P>
<P>
   It is a delicious and visually stunning dish that hits the
correct flavor notes for the holiday menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do something with beets,'' Ripert said. ``I looked
up borscht in some cookbooks and adapted it for a fish dish.''
</P>
<P>
   For families with roots in Russia or Poland, the beets and
horseradish _ familiar ingredients in those countries _ may evoke
memories of Grandmother's seders years ago. One could chill the
sauce and, instead of the halibut, substitute ovals of gefilte
fish, which is often served with beet horseradish.
</P>
<P>
   To conform to kosher dietary laws, mayonnaise can be used
instead of creme fraiche for a meal that contains meat. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STEAMED HALIBUT IN BORSCHT WITH WARM CHIVE-HORSERADISH SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Eric Ripert, Le Bernardin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil or corn oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 cup julienned fennel
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sliced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped savoy cabbage, plus 3 of the darker outer leaves,
finely julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 quart well-seasoned chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   4 cups peeled and julienned fresh beets (about 1{ bunches)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creme fraiche, sour cream or mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   \ cup prepared white horseradish
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced chives
</P>
<P>
   8 halibut steaks or fillets, each 4 to 6 ounces, or 8 portions
chilled gefilte fish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oil in a heavy 3-quart saucepan. Add onions and fennel
and cook slowly about 5 minutes, until softened. Tie garlic, thyme,
parsley and chopped cabbage in a double thickness of cheesecloth
and add it to saucepan along with stock and beets. Simmer 15
minutes. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Remove from heat.
Discard cheesecloth and its contents. To serve the dish chilled,
refrigerate beet mixture at least 4 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring 3 cups water to a boil in a small saucepan. Add
julienned cabbage leaves, cook just until bright green, then drain.
Set leaves aside, covered, to keep warm; for a cold dish,
refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mix creme fraiche, sour cream or mayonnaise with horseradish,
sugar and chives. If using mayonnaise, thin it beforehand with 2
tablespoons water. This sauce can be gently warmed in a small
saucepan or chilled to serve cold.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, steam halibut until fully cooked outside and just
warm inside, 6 to 8 minutes. Keep warm. Reheat beet mixture, spoon
into warmed shallow soup plates, sprinkle with julienned cabbage
and top with fish. Or spoon chilled beet mixture into shallow soup
plates, add cabbage, and top with gefilte fish. Serve horseradish
sauce, warm or chilled, on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
