<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRAWBERRY-APPRECIATI     03-23 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAWBERRY-APPRECIATION-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BERRIES THAT GOD WORKED OVERTIME ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANT CITY, Fla. _ Consider the strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most perfect of fruits: alluringly red, subtly
perfumed, shaped like a heart, sweet as a smile. It is an emblem of
summer, the most fulfilling of seasons. The English essayist
William Butler got it right 400 years ago when he wrote,
``Doubtless God could have made a better berry, but doubtless God
never did.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also the most frustrating of fruits: difficult to grow,
vulnerable to disease, costly to harvest, dauntingly perishable.
Until the development of railroads in the middle of the 19th
century, strawberries had to be eaten where grown, as soon as they
were picked. Their fleeting season was a season of celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the strawberry socials that flourished long ago in small
town America, often in churchyards picturesquely decked with
Japanese lanterns. Hence Zola's Nana, a city girl, ecstatic at her
first sight of strawberry fields, squatting in the mud and plucking
the ripe, juicy fruit as the rain pelted down.
</P>
<P>
   Escoffier thought strawberries a sufficiently royal delicacy to
name a dessert he invented _ strawberries macerated in orange juice
and curacao, served in a crystal bowl with creme chantilly _ after
the Russian royal family, the Romanovs.
</P>
<P>
   In England, brimming bowls of strawberries during the Wimbledon
tennis matches still epitomize the summer social season.
</P>
<P>
   But today winter strawberries are taken for granted by consumers
in New York and Philadelphia and Chicago, who have no idea how much
ingenuity, technique and labor have been lavished on the project of
growing them out of season and getting them to market.
</P>
<P>
   They are never quite as satisfying as the ones snatched from the
garden in June and drenched in cream, any more than trucked-in
sweet corn ever quite matches the succulence of home-grown. But
they are more than reasonable facsimiles, and miraculous, if you
think about them, sitting perkily there on the market shelf while
arctic air swirls outside.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the strawberries consumed in the eastern half of the
country during the winter come from farms within a 50-mile radius
of Plant City, a little Florida town with lots of strawberry-red
signs, just east of the urban sprawl of Tampa. This is the Winter
Strawberry Capital of the World, the local chamber of commerce
says, and it seems never to have occurred to anyone to challenge
the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Why here? The local soil is sandy, which is good, but other
places have sandy soil. More important, Plant City is about as far
north (and therefore as close to the winter-bound urban markets) as
practical, given the berries' susceptibility to frost damage.
</P>
<P>
   It also got an early start, in the 1880s, when Henry B. Plant
brought the railroad across the peninsula from Jacksonville to
Tampa, with a stop here. Many modern growers are great-grandsons of
the strawberry pioneers, who named their town for the railroad man.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the berries travel by refrigerated truck. Picked by
hand at 8 in the morning, deposited by the picker directly into a
pint basket sitting with 11 others on a cardboard flat, that flat
sitting with 111 others on a pallet, a ripe strawberry goes
straight from the field to a broker's chiller, a boxcar-size room
that takes the fruit down to about 36 degrees, and from there
directly into a refrigerated truck.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m., the truck will be out on Interstate 4, headed north,
and 48 hours after that, with any luck, the berry will be on sale
in a supermarket somewhere in the snow belt.
</P>
<P>
   By then _ and here is the problem, for all the hybridization and
advances in cultivation and transport methods in recent years _ the
berry will already be halfway through its useful life, even if
harvested at the optimum moment and handled with care.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries cannot be picked green, like bananas, and ripened
artificially; they must be picked when they are fully ripe, and
they remain at peak flavor for only four or five days after that.
If they are mishandled _ if, for example, they are washed or their
green caps are removed too soon, and not just before they are eaten
_ they will deteriorate much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The berries' shelf life can be increased slightly by wrapping
whole pallet loads in stout plastic bags and replacing the air
inside with carbon dioxide, which retards spoilage. But that
increases the price.
</P>
<P>
   Other things being equal, strawberries picked toward the end of
the season tend to be sweeter. Other things being equal, those that
have ripened during moderate weather tend to be sweeter than those
that have been subjected to too much heat or too much cold. But
other things are not always equal, as Erin Best of the Florida
Strawberry Growers Association readily concedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they get to the retailer, who knows how long they sit in
the warehouse?'' she asked. ``Are they kept in coolers until they
go on sale? Are they displayed in refrigerated cases or not? All
that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Best's tips: choose berries with bright green caps; brownish
caps mean old fruit. Look for uniformity of size and color; if the
bottom layer differs from the top, that's a sign that the picker is
cutting corners. And if you are not going to eat the berries almost
as soon as you get them home, spread them out on a cookie sheet and
put them into the refrigerator that way.
</P>
<P>
   This is a high-investment, hard-labor, drive-you-crazy
business,'' said Billy Simmons, 46, a fourth-generation strawberry
farmer, who tried working in an office but gave up the security of
a regular paycheck for the precarious pleasures of tilling the
soil.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Each year, he said, brings some new trial. A couple of years
ago, the growers spent weeks watching temperature gauges and
listening for alarms each night, talking nervously with their
neighbors on a radio-telephone network, ready to spray their fields
with water to coat the strawberry plants with protective shields of
ice.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, there was no frost. But 10 days of rain left many
berries unappetizingly soggy. This year, robins are the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, lovable old robin redbreasts, in their thousands. As
Simmons stood alongside one of his fields, explaining cultivation
methods to me, his son Shad, 18, raced from one corner of the
property to another, hopping out of his truck to fire his 12-gauge
shotgun into the air and scatter the birds.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what he or others in the nearby fields fired,
whether blanks that banged impressively or shells that whistled
noisily, the robins flew just a few yards before alighting on
another tempting row of strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like World War III,'' Simmons said. ``I've got two guys
blasting away, 12 hours a day, for all the good it does. It's the
worst case of robins we've had in 10 years, 500-600 in one field.
You have to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Why not cover the plants with nets? asked the visiting weekend
gardener. Money, Simmons answered; covering a few rows of
strawberries in a family plot is simple, but protecting Plant
City's crop would take 253 million square feet of netting.
</P>
<P>
   Comically primitive as the gunfire may seem, it holds the losses
down. But it is the only thing primitive about growing strawberries
in winter, which is in all other respects a prime example of
modern, capital-intensive, technology-assisted agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are grown in raised beds _ long hillocks of mounded
earth, two feet wide, formed and compacted by a shaping device
towed through the fields by a tractor. The shaper is then unhooked
and another device hitched up. It buries plastic tubing in the
hillocks and covers the rows with black plastic sheeting.
</P>
<P>
   The tubing carries water and fertilizer directly to the plants'
roots; the sheeting retains heat and moisture and inhibits the
growth of weeds.
</P>
<P>
   When planting time comes in October, the plants are set by hand,
mostly by Hispanic workers, some of them migrants, through holes
punched in the plastic. Most of the plants come from Nova Scotia or
Quebec. Summers are cooler there, Simmons explained, which means
the tender seedlings are less subject to ``bugs and blights.'' The
last season he used Florida-grown plants, he said, he lost almost
two-thirds of them to one disease or another.
</P>
<P>
   That was no insignificant loss. Hybrid strawberry plants cost
$80 a thousand, and an acre holds about 20,000 plants. Since
Simmons farms more than 30 acres, about average for the 150 growers
in the area, he spends about $50,000 every fall on seedlings. It
takes 100 million plants to fill the fields that surround Plant
City, which produce close to 20 percent of the nation's
strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   The first fruit appears on the plants after roughly 35 days, and
it keeps coming, so the berries must be picked manually and
individually, like grapes for a beerenauslese wine. At any given
moment, a plant contains tiny, immature, white berries, half-grown
green berries and big, mature red berries, so glossy they look
almost as if they had been coated with enamel.
</P>
<P>
   The pickers work the same row 30 to 50 times before the season
ends in April or May, when the weather gets too hot (and California
strawberries flood the market).
</P>
<P>
   Virginia strawberries grow wild in the Eastern United States;
the cooking writer Edna Lewis mentions picking them along streams
and fence rows in her Virginia childhood. For two centuries, they
were the world's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1712, a French engineer brought another species, the
Chilean strawberry, back from a voyage to South America; his name,
incredibly enough, was Frezier, pronounced like ``fraisier,'' which
means ``strawberry plant.'' A cross of the two New World varieties
on the Plougastel peninsula in Brittany produced the garden
strawberry now cultivated everywhere, in a wide number of
hybridized varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of Simmons' strawberries are Sweet Charlies, and a
third are Camarosas. Camarosas are California-bred, but Sweet
Charlies are Florida natives, developed at the nation's only
research lab devoted to strawberries, the Research and Education
Station of the University of Florida, located near Dover, just a
few miles down the road from the Simmons properties.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, scientists there produce 100 to 150 experimental
genetic crosses. Seeds taken from them are germinated, and 10,000
to 15,000 plants are set out in trial beds each year. The
scientists consider themselves lucky if 1 in 10,000 shows promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This center has released two varieties in 10 years,'' said Dr.
David D. Dunigan, a plant virologist on the Dover staff. ``We have
a couple now that we're keeping a close watch on. This is no work
for people in a rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry hybridization is a kind of balancing act. Obviously,
bad-tasting strawberries won't sell, so those are eliminated. The
goal is a juicy sweetness, balanced by a slight undertone of acid,
in a berry that is soft, with no hint of woodiness, but still firm
enough ``to make it to Montreal in the back of a semi,'' in
Dunigan's words.
</P>
<P>
   Looks and size do not affect taste, but they affect sales.
Everyone knows that perfectly symmetrical scarlet jumbos can taste
like polystyrene. The very best strawberries I ever tasted came
from the village of Dalat, in the mountains of Vietnam _
phenomenally sweet little things, bursting with juice, the essence
of strawberrydom. They were also mottled and misshaped, just the
kind of thing American consumers scorn.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to flavor, glamour and road-worthiness, Dunigan and
his colleagues look for good plant architecture. If the berries
develop underneath the leaves, they are hard to pick efficiently,
so the scientists choose varieties whose berries stand apart from
the foliage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet another attribute the breeders seek is disease resistance,
which is one of the reasons they are so partial to Sweet Charlie,
which was named for the late Dr. Charles Howard, the hybridizer who
came up with it. Sweet Charlie is naturally resistant to
Colletotrichum acutatum, a highly dangerous fungus that attacks
strawberry plants.
</P>
<P>
   No variety is perfect, of course. And even the best varieties
require the most finicky kind of care throughout the growing
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be out there in the fields with them every single
day,'' Dunigan said. ``It's nothing like planting corn and hanging
around, waiting for the harvest. Growing winter strawberries is the
most technical and the most intensely managed system of agriculture
that I know of.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is to be expected, I suppose, when the result is another
out-of-season treat for the pampered shoppers of 20th-century
America. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY SOUR CREAM SHORTCAKE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar, plus additional for sweetening berries and sour
cream
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chilled butter
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   About { cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 quart fresh strawberries, hulled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Into a large mixing bowl, sift
together flour, baking powder, \ cup sugar and salt. Add cream
cheese and chilled butter. Using a pastry blender or two knives,
cut the cream cheese and butter into the mixture until it resembles
coarse cornmeal.
</P>
<P>
   2. Break the egg into a measuring cup, and beat lightly with a
fork. Add enough milk to make } cup. Pour the egg mixture into the
flour mixture, and stir. Knead the dough inside the bowl just until
it is blended and cohesive, about 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   3. Shape half of the dough into a flattened ball, and place in a
greased 8-inch round cake pan. Pat the dough flat to the edges of
the pan. Brush the top of the dough with the melted butter. Shape
the remaining dough into a flattened ball, and place in the pan on
the buttered dough, patting flat to the edges. Bake until golden
brown, 17 to 20 minutes. Remove from heat and cool.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place sliced strawberries in a mixing bowl, add sugar to
taste and mix well. Place sour cream in a small bowl, and add sugar
to taste, mixing well. To serve, remove cake from pan, and pry
layers apart with a knife; they should split where the dough was
buttered. Place the bottom layer on a serving plate: top with
strawberries. Place the second layer over the strawberries: top
with sour cream. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY POTS DE CREME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Francis Coulson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes, plus 6 hours' chilling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces strawberries (7 or 8 large berries), hulled
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons Cointreau. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 275 degrees. In the container of a blender,
combine strawberries, sugar and egg yolks. Process until pureed.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring a kettle of water to a boil. Pass strawberry mixture
through a fine sieve into a bowl. Add 1 cup cream and Cointreau.
Mix well. Divide mixture evenly among four 1-cup ramekins. Place
ramekins in a baking dish, and add enough boiling water to come
halfway up the sides of ramekins.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place the baking dish in the oven, and bake until the custard
is just set and slightly wobbly in the center, about 1 hour. Remove
from the oven; place ramekins on a rack and cool. Cover with foil
or plastic wrap, and refrigerate at least 6 hours. To serve, pour 1
or 2 tablespoons of cream on top of each custard, so that each time
a spoonful is eaten, cream fills the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unless strawberries are perfect, they may need a little help to
be called dessert. All but one of these treatments take 15 minutes
or less, using hulled berries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sprinkle sliced berries with sugar _ a tablespoon to a quarter
cup per pint _ and let sit 10 minutes until they have juiced up a
bit. Sprinkle them with orange liqueur or fresh orange juice cut
with a little lemon. Or turn them with a teaspoon or more of
balsamic vinegar and a little black pepper; garnish with fresh
mint.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fold sliced berries into a mixture of sour cream or yogurt and
lightly whipped cream, about one cup per pint. Add sugar to taste,
and let sit five minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ Place 2 cups sliced berries in a baking or gratin dish. Top
with a cup of heavy cream, whipped to soft peaks with a couple of
tablespoons of sugar. Broil until lightly and evenly browned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a granita: Puree 2 cups berries, then add sugar and lemon
juice to taste. Pour into a shallow glass or ceramic dish and
freeze about two hours, stirring to break up the crystals every 30
minutes. It should be slushy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Bittman
</P>
