<HEADER>
A1268 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-FRAUD24-COX     03-23 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FRAUD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATOR TO MOVE AGAINST INTERNET STOCK FRAUD
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In response to a flood of consumer complaints
charging securities fraud on the Internet, a key senator said
Tuesday she would soon sponsor bipartisan legislation that would
grant regulators more power to combat the swindles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working on legislation to help them do a better policing
job,'' said Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, in concluding two days of
hearings as chairman of the Senate permanent investigations
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   The panel heard a litany of abuses cited by a host of witnesses,
including Richard Walker, director of enforcement at the Securities
and Exchange Commission (SEC), which watches over U.S. financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the same scams, but just in a new medium,''
Walker said. He said they include phony stock offerings, pyramid
schemes that depend on an ever-expanding base of new investors,
attempts to manipulate the securities markets, and illegal touting
of stocks through online newsletters, bulletin boards, chat rooms,
and mass e-mailings.
</P>
<P>
   The Collins bill would give the SEC more power to base its
enforcement actions on the findings of state regulators. Under
current law, it must probe each individual charge separately,
rather than relying on relevant evidence previously gathered by
state investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Collins would expand the SEC's sanction power,
permitting the agency to ban anyone from becoming a stock promoter
if he or she had fallen under a prior SEC ban from working as a
broker or investment adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said both legislative steps would enhance the agency's
ability to do its job.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, he noted, some people who had been barred from the
brokerage business build fresh careers as stock promoters, teaming
up with unscrupulous brokers who push targeted stocks on their
unsuspecting customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be able to bring faster cases based on how successfully
we have
</P>
<P>
   seen it work the other way,'' Walker also said. State securities
regulators currently utilize SEC-generated data for their own
enforcement actions, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan, the panel's ranking Democrat, said
he would back both provisions. ``We need to shore up enforcement
mechanisms'' and review current penalties to dampen Internet
securities fraud, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Collins' two-pronged approach, Levin said he favors
requiring financial investment sites to provide links to Internet
sites of regulatory agencies such as the SEC or state consumer
protection units.
</P>
<P>
   Another subcommittee witness, G. Philip Rutledge, deputy chief
counsel of the Pennsylvania Securities Commission, said: ``One of
the most important actions which can be taken now to help protect
investors from securities fraud on the Internet is making the
information maintained in the central registration depository
operated by the National Association of Securities Dealers,
accessible to public investors via a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
