<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1272 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALDEZ-ANNIVERSARY-SP     03-23 1734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALDEZ-ANNIVERSARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN YEARS AFTER EXXON VALDEZ DISASTER, CHANGES ARE VISIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORDOVA, Alaska _ The day was clear and visibility on Prince
William Sound was unlimited, but two escort vessels hovered close
by the Chevron Mississippi earlier this month as the tanker swung
past Bligh Reef.
</P>
<P>
   It was here, 10 years ago today, that the unescorted Exxon
Valdez, which had moved out of shipping lanes to avoid icebergs
calved by the Columbia Glacier, ran aground and disgorged more than
11 million gallons of oil into one of America's premier sanctuaries
of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson we learned from that oil spill is that we must pay
the price of prevention because we know the cost of complacency,''
said Alaska Gov. Tony Knowles.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Cordova fisher Kara Bergquist put it: ``The idea of
`cleaning up' an oil spill is a joke. If you don't prevent it, you
aren't going to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has developed ``the world's safest transportation
system'' for oil, and put in place the world's greatest
concentration of spill cleanup equipment, Knowles said in an
interview earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   One weak link remains in the chain.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of 28 oil tankers plying Prince William Sound are
equipped with double hulls. The additional safety cushion would
have reduced the 11-million-gallon Exxon Valdez spill by as much as
60 percent, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   And key architects of the Sound's enhanced emergency response
and tanker escort system _ the oil industry and the U.S. Coast
Guard _ have continued to resist similar measures in other
sensitive waterways, including the Strait of Juan de Fuca, that
ship and receive oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear was, if they built it for Alaska, they'd have to put
one in other places,'' said Knowles, alluding to the lack of tug
escorts elsewhere on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Along the route once traveled by the Exxon Valdez, tankers now
have plenty of company. Last month, the Alyeska Pipeline Co. took
delivery of a new, 10,192-horsepower tractor tug. Exceptionally
maneuverable, it can approach and nudge a tanker from any
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Alyeska has created a $60 million a year program called the Ship
Escort Response Vessel System, or SERVS, that is designed to
provide assistance instantly if a tanker loses power or steering,
or runs into any other difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Each oil-laden tanker leaving Prince William Sound has at least
two escort ships from the moment it leaves the pipeline terminus at
Valdez until it hits the open waters of the Gulf of Alaska. A
transponder on board allows ships' positions to be precisely
monitored at all times.
</P>
<P>
   An ocean-going tug stays within a quarter mile of the tanker for
its entire transit through the Sound. A tractor tug also is on hand
for passage through the confined waters of Valdez Narrows and past
Bligh Reef. When the tractor tug's job is done, a sentinel vessel
from Naked Island then joins the tanker for its journey through
open waters of the Sound.
</P>
<P>
   At Cape Hinchinbrook, the Sound's entrance, a deep water rescue
tug appears to join the ocean-going tug that has been with the
tanker since Valdez. ``It stays on station until the tanker is 20
miles out in the Gulf of Alaska,'' said Greg Jones, SERVS assistant
manager for Alyeska.
</P>
<P>
   The elaborate safety system did not come about without pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Congress passed the Oil Pollution Act in response to
public outcry after the Exxon Valdez spill. It substantially
increased polluters' liability for spills and established a
billion-dollar national cleanup fund.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation set up two Regional Citizens Advisory Committees
to monitor safety measures in Alaskan waters.
</P>
<P>
   One became a catalyst for safety measures in Prince William
Sound. It campaigned for more cleanup gear and more tug escorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil industry had this huge fear that what they did here,
they would have to do everywhere else,'' said Michelle O'Leary, a
Cordova fishewoman who served on the council until last November.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Prince William Sound, oil-laden tankers entering the
Strait of Juan de Fuca off the Washington coast receive no escort
for more than 70 miles until they pass Dungeness Spit east of Port
Angeles, Wash. A rescue tug has been stationed at Neah Bay, but
only as a 60-day experiment that expires in May.
</P>
<P>
   With the safety measures they have helped implement in Prince
William Sound, Alaskans have applied their expertise to other West
Coast tanker routes.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Stephens, veteran tour boat operator out of Valdez, praises
spill-prevention measures taken by the Coast Guard. The failure of
the Coast Guard to track the Exxon Valdez before the spill was a
major, albeit unreported, factor in the 1989 disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coast Guard has been a big part of prevention measures we
now have in place,'' Stephens said. ``For instance, they've put
transponders in tankers, so they can be tracked and followed every
moment they are in the Sound. It is something that should be done
all the way up and down the West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rest of the world could get to where we're at _ and we
still have a ways to go _ transportation would be far safer,
particularly along our coastlines,'' Stephens added.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, however, the Coast Guard testified this
winter against legislation to require tug escorts for all oil
tankers as soon as they enter the Strait of Juan de Fuca.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency has argued that it should be allowed to
complete a lengthy risk assessment study on such issues as whether
tug escorts would be a help or hindrance in congested waters off
Cape Flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Prince William Sound residents are unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well and good that they have a vessel traffic system down
there that can spot a tanker heading toward the rocks. What the
hell are they going to do about it if a tug is not there?'' asked
Dan Lawn of the Alaska Forum for Environmental Responsibility, a
conservation group oriented to marine safety.
</P>
<P>
   In the years before the Exxon Valdez disaster, Lawn represented
the state of Alaska's Department of Environmental Quality in
Valdez. He repeatedly reported Alyeska's inadequate spill response.
Nobody listened to him then.
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries groups also tried to point out shortcomings in spill
response. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, delivered a sweeping safey
assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wernher von Braun, you know, the spaceman, assured me that all
of the technology of the space program will be put into the doggone
tankers and there will not be one drop of oil in Prince William
Sound,'' Stevens told fishermen during pipeline construction in the
1970s, referring to the famous German-American rocket scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody talks like that anymore. Alaskans are impressed by the
new tugs, the spill cleanup equipment stationed around Prince
William Sound, and the annual cleanup training given to the crews
of 350 fishing vessels under contract to Alyeska.
</P>
<P>
   Even such hard-nosed critics as Dan Lawn are also singing the
praises of Alyeska's new president, Bob Malone, who has signaled
aggressive commitment to excellence in safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have everything we need? No,'' said Lawn. ``But are we
getting closer to where we need to be? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Stephens chaired the advisory committee until recently. He
stood beside Knowles and Malone on the bridge of the tractor tug
last when Alyeska took delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've understood a number of things,'' said Stephens. ``The
Sound was injured (by the Exxon Valdez) in a way that it will be
many, many years before it comes back. Once a spill is out there,
you can't clean it up. We simply can't have another major spill.''
</P>
<P>
   Alyeska's Jones echoes the point. ``Prevention is our principal
focus,'' he said. ``We believe the challenge of a (potential) large
oil spill is that you don't want to have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Alyeska is not only buying equipment, but using it. ``We're
going to do a lot more drilling with the tug fleet so if the day
comes when they have to act, they will know instinctively what to
do,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens is worried on one count. Oil prices are down and
companies are making cutbacks in Alaska and elsewhere. He worries
about safety along the trans-Alaska pipeline and in the terminal
and tank farm at Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles argued, however, that spill prevention along the
pipeline and in Prince William Sound is ``a non-negotiable point.
It is not dependent on the price of oil.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of double-hulled tankers _ chief worry of those who
predicted the Exxon Valdez disaster _ won't be remedied any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that the vast majority of tankers loading up
in Alaska _ and unloading oil on Puget Sound _ have shells that are
only an inch and a half thick.
</P>
<P>
   Congress gave the oil shipping industry until 2015 to equip all
tankers in U.S. waters with double hulls.
</P>
<P>
   The one oil producer that has switched entirely to double-hulled
tankers _ CONOCO _ does not load up oil from Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The largest shipper of Alaskan oil, British Petroleum, has
chartered three double-hulled tankers for use in Prince William
Sound.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO Marine is building three large double-hull tankers. It will
start using the 125,000-ton, 895-foot-long state-of-the-art vessels
on the Valdez-to-Puget Sound run next year. The new tankers will
have two independent sets of rudders, propellers and engines. Bow
thrusters, combined with twin propellers, will greatly increase
maneuverability.
</P>
<P>
   While it has built double-hulled tankers for the international
trade, Chevron still uses a single-hull tanker to take on oil at
Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   And Exxon, whose tanker ran aground on Good Friday a decade ago?
</P>
<P>
   The company has argued that oil spills have dropped dramatically
in the last 10 years. Exxon says it supports the largest research
and development program in the oil industry, sharing with
competitors multiple advances in cleanup technology.
</P>
<P>
   Still, SeaRiver Maritime, Exxon's shipping subsidiary, sees no
need to build double-hull tankers for operation on Alaska's Prince
William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The company has told the citizens' advisory committee that
production at Alaska's North Slope oil fields is declining, and
that it will end tanker shipments out out of Valdez long before the
federal requirement of double hulls takes effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
