<HEADER>
A1291 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAHL-AZR &LR;      03-23 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAHL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO STOPPING STAHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Television reporter Lesley Stahl has heard from only
one person since her memoir, ``Reporting Live,'' was published in
January.
</P>
<P>
   And the call came through a third party. Via that circuitous
route, former first lady Nancy Reagan let Stahl know that her
husband, former President Reagan, did not have Alzheimer's disease
while in office, as Stahl speculated in her book. End of message.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl well might have been flogged by other principal players
who appear in this account of her celestial career. Her words paint
many as rogues.
</P>
<P>
   Former colleague Daniel Schorr accused her of stealing documents
from his office that he actually had leaked to the ``Village
Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   President Carter's press secretary, Jody Powell, froze her out
of White House press conferences until she sparked a dust-up that
persuaded him to change his tune.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS cameraman once heaved his equipment into his truck in
disgust when he discovered that the blond female newcomer _ Stahl _
would be the anchor on his story.
</P>
<P>
   Newsman David Brinkley gave her the sage career advice, ``You're
a pretty blonde. You should stay in New York and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But only Nancy Reagan has called.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, no news is good news. In writing the book, Stahl, in
fact, did go back and interview ``gobs of people'' she expected to
write about, ensuring that her memories matched theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reporting Live'' is no ambush job. She does not pull a George
Stephanopoulos, blindsiding former friends with a titillating
tell-all.
</P>
<P>
   This is an engaging account of one woman's career born of the
affirmative-action movement that won her her first network job. It
ends with her appointment as ``60 Minutes'' correspondent and the
ascendancy of CNN, whose dominance in broadcast journalism has
dulled the glitter of all network jobs.
</P>
<P>
   During the golden age of network news, Stahl says, ``I was a
little princess.''
</P>
<P>
   Princess Lesley will appear Sunday at Arizona State University
as part of the ``Unique Lives &AMP; Experiences'' series of lectures by
celebrated women.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, she reports that on that night, one of her most
significant stories will be airing on ``60 Minutes,'' where she has
worked since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But Stahl, by phone from New York, says it's not an interview
with a foreign power or an expose of horrific social conditions in
a Third World country _ areas in which Stahl has made her name.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of this rare two-part episode is famed director
George Lucas, whose fans are awaiting the ``Star Wars'' prequel
this May. In Part 1, Stahl treats viewers to a preview of ``Episode
I: The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   In Part 2, she gives the moviemaker the same treatment she would
the king of some oil-producing nation _ in-depth profile, scrutiny
of his private life and visits to his famed Skywalker Ranch and
Industrial Light &AMP; Magic studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty nifty,'' Stahl says.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps landing Lucas takes the sting out of losing that
ratings-busting Monica Lewinsky interview to rival Barbara Walters.
Yes, Stahl would have liked grilling Lewinsky. Yes, she tried _ and
failed _ to land the big fish.
</P>
<P>
   How would her interview have been different?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been different just because it would have been
me doing the interview,'' she says. ``Barbara asked (begin ital)
all (end ital) the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl left her White House assignment before Bill Clinton moved
into the Oval Office, so she has not followed his presidency in the
way she did his three predecessors. Her big interview with Clinton
came while he was governor of Arkansas and a rising Democratic
star.
</P>
<P>
   Did the reputed womanizer flirt with her?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all!'' she laughs. ``What's wrong with me?''
</P>
<P>
   Gender often has intruded on _ and sometimes aided _ Stahl's
career. For many female newscasters, success comes down to The
Hair.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl's was conventionally blond, which in the early 1970s
threatened to taint her as a less-than-serious journalist. But she
freely admits that the '70s were also a time when news stations
were being pressured to put women and minorities on the air.
</P>
<P>
   The good old boys at CBS, then the shining star of network news,
reluctantly invited Stahl into their treehouse, and she hung on
like Tarzan despite frequent efforts to shake her loose.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she earned a reputation as one of the toughest
interviewers in town, labeled variously as ``a bulldog,'' ``poetry
in motion,'' ``stakeout queen,'' ``an honorary man'' and ``one
demanding bitch-monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporting Live'' reveals a more vulnerable Stahl, constantly
calling her parents, Dolly and Lou, for a critique of her on-air
performances. Dolly bought Lesley's clothes until Lesley was 30 and
advised Lesley to get a face lift when Lesley was 39, Stahl says.
</P>
<P>
   Friends also call Stahl ``a softy'' when it comes to her family
_ husband Aaron Latham, a magazine journalist and screenwriter,
whose bouts of depression before seeking medical help scared the
living daylights out of his wife, and daughter Taylor, now a senior
in college.
</P>
<P>
   Over the telephone, as she munches on lunch, Stahl comes across
as a combination of all those things _ quick-witted, genial,
jubilant about what she calls ``the best job on television.''
</P>
<P>
   At ``60 Minutes,'' she has her pick of stories and works with
other legends of the small screen _ Mike Wallace, Morley Safer,
producer Don Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   As the next election approaches, Stahl doesn't miss slogging
along the campaign trail. The beauty of ``60 Minutes'' is that she
can interview any candidate she wants _ including a new Dole this
time around, Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents and White House wannabes have been her stock in
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Once, on a flight while interviewing presidential candidate and
former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt, Stahl began feeling the bumps of
turbulence and grabbed an airsickness bag. Babbitt, whom Stahl
assessed as too honest for his own good, kept on talking until his
wife, Hattie, stepped in and suggested the interview was over.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl angered Sen. Gary Hart of Colorado when she pressed him
about changing his last name from Hartpence and shaving a year off
his age. He stormed out after the interview.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush was ``playful . . . funny.''
</P>
<P>
   President Carter was ``distant.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl was smitten with President Reagan, as was every other
reporter and member of Congress who knew him, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody liked Reagan because of the sweetness that is
pervasive about his personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his term, however, Stahl began to notice that
Reagan seemed to suffer occasional lapses, where his eyes would
glaze and take him into another world _ Stahl calls them ``little
vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Reagan's Alzheimer's evident even then? Doctors will not
speculate, unable to diagnose by long-distance, Stahl says.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Nancy Reagan dismisses such notions, insisting the
former leader of the free world suffers a post-presidential
affliction.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Stahl to be moving on to another beat any time
soon. Her job at ``60 Minutes'' is the pinnacle of broadcast news,
she says, and the longevity of its correspondents is envied by
newspeople who get the bum's rush at maturity. Morley Safer is 67.
Mike Wallace is a ripe 80. Stahl is 57.
</P>
<P>
   For Stahl, there is no next job.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who come here don't leave,'' Stahl says. ``It's a
wonderful job. I love the club. You don't think `What next?' when
you get to this level.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
