<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-KITCHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKERS: PLAIN OR FANCY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., fyi, the column mentioned in graf 5 is being filed as
SALMON-MASTER-CHEF)  
 (HLW)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paula Katz, who lives on the Upper West Side, wanted
to buy a stove-top smoker for her mother-in-law. She went to
Zabar's, fully intending to make the purchase. But after one look
she came home empty-handed. ``What is it?'' she said, ``A roasting
pan, a rack and a lid?'' Her mother-in-law already had all that,
she said, and besides, it would be just something else to be
crammed into a closet.
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame her? There is plenty of specialized kitchen
equipment out there _ bread machines, pasta makers, crockpots _
whose usefulness is disproportionate to the amount of space it
demands. A weighty price tag doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Some home cooks and chefs have rebelled. Rather than investing
in stove-top smokers, for instance, they rig up their own, using
equipment they already own. The home versions work, but do they
work as well as the specialized versions?
</P>
<P>
   I tested the Camerons Stove-Top Smoker Cooker _ the most widely
available brand in Manhattan _ against a homemade contraption to
see if the differences were great enough to justify paying $48 to
$69.99.
</P>
<P>
   The Camerons comes with little containers of wood ``dust'' _
oak, cherry, alder and hickory _ and is very easy to use. Following
the recipe by Rick Moonen of Oceana in this week's chef column, I
sprinkled a little dust in the base of the pan, placed the drip pan
on top, and turned on the heat. When the dust began to smoke, I
placed the salmon fillets on the rack, set it on top of the drip
pan and closed the lid. I shut off the heat and waited 10 minutes.
When I uncovered the pan, the fish was pink on the edges and cooked
about a millimeter into the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   For the improvised smoker, I used a 14-inch carbon-steel wok,
aluminum foil for a lid and a baking rack small enough to fit
inside. I poured in applewood chips and heated them until they
began to smoke. Then I placed the salmon fillets on the rack,
centered it in the wok and covered the whole thing tightly with
aluminum foil. Again, I let the ``smoker'' rest closed for 10
minutes off the heat. This salmon looked just like the other, only
a little less cooked on top.
</P>
<P>
   My kitchen has no exhaust system, so before smoking I opened all
my windows and disconnected my smoke detector. But neither smoker
did much damage, since the lids trapped all the smoke. Searing
steaks actually produces more smoke.
</P>
<P>
   After the smoking, I seasoned and browned both batches of salmon
in hot oil and finishing them in a 450-degree oven. Both turned out
beautifully, with crisp, brown skin and moist, smoky flesh.
</P>
<P>
   I also compared smokers by smoking the salmon fillets over
medium heat until they were fully cooked _ about 15 minutes a
pound. Again, both smokers worked equally well: they infused the
fish with a smoky scent while they cooked.
</P>
<P>
   But the wok, which cost me just $20 at Zabar's and was re-usable
_ as a wok _was just as convenient and saved me $28 and precious
inches of cabinet space. Besides, it fits better on a single
burner.
</P>
<P>
   So I vote with Ms. Katz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
