<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL TRIAL IN MALAYSIA ENDS SUDDENLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ With one last judicial twist and one last
cry of outrage from the defense, the politically charged
sex-and-corruption trial of Malaysia's former deputy prime
minister, Anwar Ibrahim, came to a sudden end on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Judge Anthony Paul refused to hear a demand by the defense
that he step down because of what they said was pro-prosecution
bias, Anwar's team of nine lawyers refused to deliver a closing
argument. The judge then charged all nine with contempt and banged
his gavel to close the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who sits as the trial's sole judge and juror, said he
would announce a verdict in two weeks on four sex-based corruption
charges. If convicted, Anwar faces a maximum of 14 years in prison
along with a five-year ban on political activity. In addition, he
is due to face a second trial on four charges of sexual misconduct
and one more charge of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very unfortunate for the judicial system in this
country,'' Anwar said of the judge's actions on Tuesday. ``It is
tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   But the trial, which opened with a display of Anwar's black eye,
received in a police beating, has damaged far more than the
reputation of Malaysia's judicial system. In a harsh display of
political feuding and judicial gamesmanship, it has shaken the calm
and confidence of one of the region's more stable and optimistic
societies.
</P>
<P>
   It has soiled the reputation of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad,
72, and ruined the career of his former heir apparent, Anwar, 51.
It has brought into public the underside of Malaysian governance,
including political corruption and police abuses. It has aroused a
surge of dormant discontent around the country and boosted the
popularity of Malaysia's Islamic fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   The conduct of the trial has left the judge open to Anwar's
complaints of bias.
</P>
<P>
   In a pivotal decision last month _ after allowing the
prosecution to present graphic accusations of sexual misconduct to
lay the groundwork for its corruption charges _ Paul ruled that the
sex was irrelevant and barred the defense from presenting testimony
to rebut the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to hear testimony from some of Anwar's chief accusers
that they had been coerced into saying he had sex with them. He
disallowed testimony about an audiotape that the defense maintained
would show that some charges were fabricated for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   And he barred as irrelevant Anwar's chief defense argument _
that the trial amounted to a political punishment by his former
mentor, Mahathir, for Anwar's opposition to his economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   But Anwar and his lawyers did not let those rulings stop them
from speaking out in the most concerted attack Mahathir has ever
faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a police state,'' Anwar said at one point, in the kind
of public accusation rarely heard in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagreed and now I am out,'' he said at another point,
clearly referring to Mahathir. ``Yes, an ultimatum was given on
Sept. 2 saying that I either resign effective that day or charges
will be preferred against me in a number of related offenses
ranging from sexual misconduct to treason.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar refused to resign and was fired that day. He was arrested
18 days later after making a political tour of the country in which
he drew huge crowds to hear his demands for the reform of a system
that he had helped to lead for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   These events came at a time of heightened concern in Malaysia
over the regional economic slowdown, during which Anwar had become
increasingly public about his disagreements with Mahathir over
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Anwar _ or at least his supporters _ appeared to be
preparing an early challenge to the leadership of Mahathir, who had
seemed to be dallying over his plans to step down in the coming
years in favor of his deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir's politically brutal move against his deputy
neutralized that challenge, at least in the short term. But the
prime minister overturned one of the more stable blueprints for
political succession in the region and removed one of the leading
standard-bearers of a younger generation of potentially more
liberal Southeast Asian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, however, still seems firmly in control of Malaysian
politics, with the nation still looking to him to set its policies
and once again, name a successor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1721EST &QL; 
