<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      03-23 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALSATIAN WHITES SHOW VERSATILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a scale of 1 to 10, I would rate most wine dinners
that showcase only white wines at about 4, ranking in excitement
somewhere between arm wrestling and the novels of Judith Krantz.
But that didn't prevent me from hustling over to La Caravelle in
Manhattan recently to a dinner devoted to the wines _ all of them
white _ of the Domaine Trimbach, one of the best-known producers in
Alsace.
</P>
<P>
   La Caravelle holds such dinners now and then for anyone willing
to spend $225 to sample the wines of a certain producer, paired
with food from the restaurant. I wanted to see if the dinner would
rival my Trimbach meal of years ago at the family's home in
Ribeauville, France.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Trimbach, one of the owners, and I tasted some wines, one
an astonishing 1923 riesling, then tucked into what was a feast. I
still remember the main course, a baekenofe, an Alsatian meat and
vegetable stew.
</P>
<P>
   But why dwell in the past? The Caravelle meal, prepared by the
restaurant's chef, Cyril Renaud, was not hearty Alsatian fare but a
memorable dinner skillfully attuned to the Trimbach wines.
</P>
<P>
   It is not being dismissive of Renaud's achievements to note that
these remarkable wines made his job easier. Alsatian wines, the
Trimbachs' included, are deceptively big, powerful and complex,
unlike most white wines. Good rieslings, in particular, will
complement almost any dish.
</P>
<P>
   The Trimbachs, who have been making wine since 1626, own or
lease 60 acres of vineyards in Ribeauville and in neighboring
towns. They buy both wine and grapes to produce 60,000 cases a
year. Most is good affordable wine from traditional Alsatian
grapes: muscat, pinot blanc, pinot gris, riesling and
gewuerztraminer.
</P>
<P>
   They also produce very special wines, including a
gewuerztraminer called Seigneurs de Ribeaupierre, and two
rieslings, the Cuvee Frederic Emile and the extraordinary Clos Ste.
Hune, one of the finest dry rieslings in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Fine German rieslings are made with a touch of sweetness, which
is brought into balance by the right amount of acidity. Alsatian
rieslings, however, are dry. That doesn't mean they lack intensity
or fruit. Like the best German rieslings, wines like the Cuvee
Frederic Emile, which sells for $25, and Clos Ste. Hune, $50, can
preserve their freshness for decades.
</P>
<P>
   That 1923 I had was more than 50 years old. But you can also buy
a 3-year-old Trimbach riesling for $12 that is fine for drinking
right now.
</P>
<P>
   Top-quality wines don't jump from the fermenting tanks ready to
drink. The Cuvee Frederic Emile needs three to five years in the
bottle to develop its complex flavors; the Clos Ste. Hune will
continue to improve in the bottle for a decade. Some of these wines
don't come into their own for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Grapes for the Frederic Emile come from a vineyard on the steep
slopes of the Osterberg, a mountain that drops conveniently to the
back door of the Trimbach cellars. The Clos Ste. Hune is from a
postage-stamp-size vineyard below the 14th-century church and
graveyard in the neighboring village of Hunawihr.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate the versatility of Trimbach wines, Renaud paired
a young flowery muscat with a tartar of oysters and scallops, and a
fruity 1996 pinot blanc with a lobster and avocado salad. A lightly
smoked and grilled Atlantic salmon was matched with a full, rich
pinot gris _ a 1996 Reserve Personelle Hubert Trimbach, which had
the extra weight demanded by the salmon's richness.
</P>
<P>
   But those were just the starters. The main course, a confit of
foie gras and boned squab, was the elegant setting for the first of
the great rieslings, a 1993 Cuvee Frederic Emile. The intense
flavors of the dish would challenge many red wines, but not this
riesling.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us considered the high point of the evening to be the
tasting of two vintages of Clos Ste. Hune, 1983 and 1993. At 16,
the 1983 was beginning to show its intense concentration and depth.
The 1993 showed an understated elegance that made it a delight to
drink. Against logic, I preferred the 1993, even if it will be
better 20 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come were a gewuerztraminer, a Seigneurs de
Ribeaupierre 1990, which was served with an Alsatian Muenster, and
a vendange tardive 1986 Clos Ste. Hune with dessert.
</P>
<P>
   No gewuerztraminer compares with the best from Alsace, which
have intense fruit flavors and a flowery bouquet. The Trimbach
style is rather lean and understated but the Seigneurs de
Ribeaupierre is still a rich, muscular wine.
</P>
<P>
   Vendange tardive, which means late harvest, is made from grapes
left on the vine long after the regular harvest, so that the water
in them can evaporate, leaving only the concentrated juice. The
Trimbach late-harvest rieslings have been aptly described as
``massive wines.'' They are almost dry, with intense fruit flavor,
and might go with game dishes. But I prefer them as aperitifs, with
no culinary distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to gainsay Renaud's dessert, a baked apple with
orange-peel ice cream. It was an attractive combination that wisely
made no attempt to upstage the Clos Ste. Hune.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
