<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SALMON, SMOKY MEETS SHARP AND SWEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the last of eight columns by Rick Moonen, the executive
chef and an owner of Oceana in Manhattan. His collaborator on these
columns was Dorie Greenspan. Next week: Claudia Fleming, the pastry
chef at Gramercy Tavern in Manhattan.)  
 (HLW)  
 By RICK MOONEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Often, the most successful meals evoke a childhood
memory. This dish was inspired by a long-ago trip to a ballpark,
where I had a smoky grilled hot dog that was slathered with sharp
mustard and topped with crunchy, slightly sweet relish. When I
became a chef, I decided to create a dish with the same trio of
flavors: smoky, sharp and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like a leap from an all-beef frank to a velvety
salmon fillet, but I think I have captured the essence of what we
love in a hot dog by lightly smoking salmon and serving it with a
sweet-sour cucumber relish and a creamy horseradish-and-mustard
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking the salmon is mostly about fragrance: you pick up on the
aroma immediately, but once you dig into the dish, the smoke's
flavor recedes into the background as a minor note.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking a fish in a home kitchen is easy. You can use a
commercial stove-top smoker or improvise one with a heavy frying
pan, a cake rack that fits into the pan (press one-inch balls of
foil underneath the rack to give it needed height) and a lid.
</P>
<P>
   A wok is also perfect for this: because of its sloping sides,
you can eliminate the foil ball step.
</P>
<P>
   Scatter applewood chips over the bottom of the pan, turn on the
over-the-range exhaust system if you have one and heat the chips
until they smoke. Put the fillets on the rack and into the pan,
cover the setup, remove it from the heat and let the smoke waft
around the salmon for 10 minutes. The fillets will still be cold
and their edges will look a little dull, but their natural fats
will have grabbed the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking does not cook the salmon _ searing and roasting does _
and the fish emerges fragrant, perfectly moist and seductively
smoky.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon, like a hot dog, requires cool condiments. The
cucumber relish needs to chill until it is so crunchy it is
downright noisy when you eat it.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce _ chilled, tangy creme fraiche jazzed up with
horseradish and Dijon mustard _ is bold enough to match the
salmon's richness. This dish is a long way from the humble hot dog,
but it satisfies in just the same way.
</P>
<P>
   PAN-SEARED APPLEWOOD SMOKED SALMON WITH CUCUMBER-RED ONION
RELISH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus 30 minutes for chilling cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   2 medium English cucumbers (also known as European or hothouse
cucumbers), each about } pound, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   { medium red onion, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup coarsely chopped fresh dill leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   \ cup white horseradish
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup applewood chips (see note below)
</P>
<P>
   6 salmon fillets, skin on, 7 ounces each and 1 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   Chopped chives, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. To make the relish: Slice cucumbers in half lengthwise, scoop
out seeds and slice \ inch thick. Toss cucumbers with kosher salt
and put them in a colander. Weight them down lightly, cover and
chill for at least 30 minutes or for as long as 12 hours. Drain
cucumbers, and toss them with the onion, sugar, vinegar and dill.
Season with salt and white pepper, cover and chill until needed.
Relish can be refrigerated for a day.
</P>
<P>
   2. To make the horseradish cream: Whip the creme fraiche with a
whisk until it is as thick as mustard. Fold in the horseradish and
mustard, add salt and pepper, and cover and chill until needed.
Mixture can be kept in the refrigerator for 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. To make the salmon: Center a rack in the oven, and preheat to
450 degrees. If using a stove-top smoker, follow manufacturer's
instructions for cold smoking. If fashioning your own smoker, place
applewood chips in wok or pan over high heat on top of stove. While
they are heating, brush a cake rack with the olive oil. Place
salmon fillets skin side down on rack. When applewood chips start
to smoke, after 5 to 10 minutes, put rack with salmon into wok (or
into pan, raised on 1-inch balls of foil) and cover tightly. Remove
from heat, and let stand for 10 minutes. Remove salmon, and season
fillets with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place a 10-inch ovenproof saute pan over high heat. When it
is very hot, brush skin of fish generously with the softened
butter. Put fillets skin side down in saute pan, and immediately
press them with a spatula or place another skillet on top of them;
stop pressing or remove top skillet after 1 minute. Cook 1 minute
more, put pan in oven, and roast 4 to 5 minutes, or until fillets
are cooked through but still moist inside.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, place a mound of drained relish in the center of
each plate, surround with horseradish cream and top with a salmon
fillet, skin side up. Sprinkle each plate with chopped chives, and
serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Applewood chips are available from People's Woods/Nature's
Own, (800) 729-5800.
</P>
</TEXT>
