<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the Cheese Lover, A Companion for the Road &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the population explosion at the cheese counter these days,
a guide that fits into a pocketbook could come in handy. ``The
Cheese Companion'' (Running Press, $24.95), Judy Ridgway's slim
guide, is filled with tempting color photographs and evocative
descriptions of about 50 varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Commonplace cheeses, like Edam, alternate with esoteric
examples, including Spanish tetilla, a mild cow's-milk cheese in a
distinctive, pointy pyramid shape; picodon, a nutty-tasting French
goat's-milk cheese, and Cornish yarg, a nettle-wrapped cow's-milk
cheese made from an old recipe (its name is that of the cheese
maker spelled backward).
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions of appropriate wines for cheeses are also given, as
is an overview of cheese-making and history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frozen Gefilte, Easy to Cook &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gefilte fish for Passover seder dinners (this year, the first
one will be next Wednesday) usually comes from jars in the
supermarket, or perhaps from a fancy food market. Now, there is
another alternative, a bit closer to homemade: A &AMP; B Famous Gefilte
Fish, a raw mixture sold frozen that is easy to cook.
</P>
<P>
   It comes in four styles: sweet; less sweet; sugar-free, which is
very bland, and salmon, which is also very sweet. All are sold in
one-pound rolls and can be cooked without thawing. If the fish is
thawed, it can be formed into balls and cooked.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon takes 35 minutes, but the others need 90 minutes.
Adding pepper, salt and a little vinegar to the cooking liquid, in
addition to onions and carrots, enhances the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The kosher-for-Passover variety is made with mashed potatoes,
because some orthodox Jews will not eat matzoh meal that has been
in contact with liquid. Matzoh meal is used for the non-Passover
kind. But in taste and texture, it is hard to tell the difference.
</P>
<P>
   A &AMP; B Famous Gefilte Fish, $6.99 a pound, is sold at Kosher
Marketplace, 2442 Broadway (90th Street) in New York City, where
sample tastes are available, and at Gristede's and Shop Rite
supermarkets, among other outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Matzohs for the Observant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matzohs are being marketed for the very observant or the
wheat-avoiding. Whole Foods, 117 Prince Street (Greene Street) and
2421 Broadway (89th Street), is selling handmade shmurah matzohs
(shmurah means ``closely watched'') from Brooklyn _ big, lightly
charred round disks that have an earthier taste than the ordinary
supermarket matzohs.
</P>
<P>
   A one-pound box is $14.95, a dollar of which goes to the Simon
Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods also has oat-flour, wheat-free shmurah matzohs from
Israel, $18.95 for a one-pound box. To order: (212) 982-1000. The
oat matzohs are also sold at Mrs. Green's Natural Markets in
Scarsdale, Mahopac, Mount Kisco, Yorktown Heights, Katonah and
Larchmont, N.Y., for $16 a box. These markets also carry Israeli
organic wheat matzohs, $2.99 for 14 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   From France, a Sleek Onion &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Call it a racing onion, this ultra-sleek new produce arrival
that is done up in a smooth nut-brown skin and whose inside is
white tinged with lavender. The onion, from northern France, where
it's simply called an ``oignon long,'' looks like a shallot with
delusions of grandeur but does not have the slightly herbaceous
flavor of a shallot. It's fresh and sharp, with just a touch of
sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to take advantage of its shape is to halve it the
long way and cook it like endive: baked, simmered in consomme or
simply roasted or grilled. It is also excellent for stuffing but
can be eaten raw, finely slivered into a salad. The onions will be
available for $1.89 a pound starting next week at Fairway, 2127
Broadway (74th Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132nd Street).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
