<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA WINES BECOMING MORE POPULAR AROUND THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JIM HAMMETT WineToday.com   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Americans are increasingly more
sophisticated wine drinkers, new statistics on 1998 California wine
shipments show.
</P>
<P>
   ``American consumers are moving upscale to high-end varietal
wines, shifting their preferences away from many white and blush
jug wines, which declined in stores last year,'' said an industry
analyst, Jon Fredrikson of Gomberg, Fredrikson &AMP; Associates in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrikson's firm works with the Wine Institute to analyze the
wine industry. On Monday, the firm released its most recent
statistical report compiled from various government and business
sources. These studies are widely regarded as the most
comprehensive source of information on California wine sales.
</P>
<P>
   While sales of white wine continue to outstrip that of red table
wines, the report found demand for aged red wines and wine in
limited productions grew three-fold in sales over the past seven
years. Also, exports of California wine grew a sharp 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   California table wine priced $7 and above at retail was the
fastest-growing segment, with a 14 percent volume increase. While
this category represented 19 percent of the state's table wine
production, it generated 44 percent of winery table wine revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Total California winery sales to the United States and abroad
was about 437 million gallons in 1998, up 3 percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. consumers purchased most of this volume, as California
wineries shipped 388 million gallons nationwide for a 73 percent
share of the domestic wine market, or about three out of every four
bottles consumed. The estimated retail value of the state's
domestic wine shipments was $12 billion, up 5 percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic sales of premium California table wine _ figured for
750 milliliter bottles costing $3 and above _ expanded by 8
percent. These sales comprise 53 percent of the volume and 79
percent of the winery revenues. Popular-priced jugs, those under $3
per 750-milliliter bottle, fell 3 percent and accounted for 47
percent of the volume and 21 percent of the revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Equally significant to California wine sales in 1998 was the
surge in exports. The huge 1997 harvest boosted wine inventories
and enabled California wineries to supply their flourishing export
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary numbers from the U.S. Department of Commerce place
the value of U.S. wine exports in 1998 _ 90 percent of which is
Californian _ at $537 million, a 26 percent increase over 1997.
Volume shot up 20 percent to about 72 million gallons. The largest
market was the United Kingdom, followed by Japan and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that exports are the story this year,'' said Eileen
Fredrikson, a partner in Gomberg, Fredrikson &AMP; Associates. She said
growth of exports for the first time outstripped growth of domestic
shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrikson said it was particularly significant that sales to
Japan were up 112 percent in 1998. She attributed that increase to
a depressed economy causing more people to eat at home and news
about the benefits of wine causing health-conscious Japanese to
choose wine to accompany their meals.
</P>
<P>
   Total 1998 wine sales in the United States _ including domestic
and imported wines _ grew 1 percent over 1997 to about 531 million
gallons. The estimated retail value was up 5.5 percent from 1997 to
some $17 billion for total sales of wine in the United States,
Commerce Department figures show. The slow volume growth and
stronger revenues also mirror the shift from jug wine purchases to
premium wines.
</P>
<P>
   (Winetoday.com is a daily Internet wine publication published by
the New York Times Co. and The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif.
The Web address is http://www.winetoday.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
