<HEADLINE>
DINING ALONE NEED NOT BE A LONELY EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ We were four strangers. Each of us had happened upon a
narrow, smoky Alsatian restaurant in an unfashionable part of Paris
and taken a seat around the right-angled end of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, we found ourselves in a lively conversation about
the rise of the supermarket in France and the decline of the small
bakeries and food shops. We debated whether golf was a bore and
argued over the Frenchman's insistence that Alsatian pinot noir was
the only wine to drink with sauerkraut.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sort of experience that is almost unthinkable in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Dining alone in the United States is not exactly unpleasant, but
it is often uncomfortable. Solo diners, escaping briefly from the
office, may be common at lunch, but at dinner, when the demands of
the workaday world are put aside, they are considered downright
strange.
</P>
<P>
   Americans think of dining out primarily as a social activity, an
entertainment to be enjoyed with company. It falls into the
category of going to a movie, where couples and groups are the
norm, rather than a bookstore, where the lone browser is accepted.
A solo diner, intent simply on savoring a dinner, is assumed to be
missing out on a key element of the experience, and therefore must
be lonely, sad or depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at them, and they say: `He doesn't have friends. How
come he's by himself?''' said Jean-Claude Iacovelli, who grew up
outside of Paris and who now owns three restaurants in downtown
Manhattan, Jean-Claude, SoHo Steak, and Velli.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few times, I remember showing up by myself at
restaurants in New York, only to be welcomed by the host's raised
eyebrows of surprise and an almost imperceptible flash of pity.
Seating is generally behind a pillar or near the kitchen,
presumably to keep the lonely fly from spoiling the otherwise happy
soup.
</P>
<P>
   Things might be different at a local diner or cafe, where being
a regular may take the sting out of solitude, but show up alone
often enough and even a welcome familiarity may be tinged with
pity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in our society think strangely of people dining alone
in restaurants,'' said Joseph Bastianich, an owner of Babbo
restaurant in Greenwich Village. ``It's much more a part of
everyday life in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you talk to restaurateurs, solo diners are not actually
that uncommon in New York. Often they are business travelers, on
their own in a strange place and unwilling to settle for room
service or the hotel dining room.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, solo diners in New York are like
asteroids in orbit, circling endlessly without ever bumping into
one another. That's why my experience at Alsaco, the little
restaurant in Paris, seemed so unusual.
</P>
<P>
   We made an odd quartet, for sure. A Frenchman in a dark blue
sweater dotted with cigarette ashes who whipped out a wood-handled
switchblade to saw off slices of his boiled pig's knuckle; an
elderly Englishman in a fine old tweed jacket, who consumed a
platter of grilled pork sausages slowly and meticulously, carefully
dabbing his mouth with a napkin as his jeweled cuff links gleamed;
a Belgian shoe designer with the thick neck and powerful arms of a
rugby player, who inhaled his soup as if he had a train to catch,
and me, savoring a huge plate of juniper-scented choucroute garni.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't exactly burst into conversation. But a tart flambee,
my first course, was the icebreaker. They stared as the waitress
set the huge tart in front of me on a wooden board. The flat, crisp
crust was irregularly shaped, like a map of western Europe, and
topped with cream, onions and bacon. It was delicious, as they all
agreed after I gave them each a slice. Why not? It was way too much
for me to finish, and soon we were all breaking bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' the Englishman asked the Belgian, ``when you were just a
small boy did you turn to your daddy and say, `I want to be a shoe
designer when I grow up?'''
</P>
<P>
   American attitudes toward solo diners may not be relaxed enough
to permit such acceptance or intimacies, partly because of
restaurant economics. In New York, at least, the restaurant
business depends more on volume than in Paris, and the sight of one
person sitting at a table for two stirs visions of red ink among
owners. What's more, lone diners usually drink proportionately less
than groups, further cutting the profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   But to an increasing number of enlightened New York
restaurateurs, that attitude is shortsighted. Single diners may not
maximize profits initially, but they may be instrumental in
creating new business. ``Single diners are always the most open,
and a lot end up being very interactive with the server,''
Bastianich of Babbo said. ``It's a good opportunity to show what
your restaurant is about.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rather than stick the single diner near the bathrooms or
kitchen, thoughtful restaurateurs do things like making the bar
comfortable for a meal, as at O Padeiro, a Portuguese restaurant in
Chelsea, where the handsome bar is small but spacious enough to
accommodate diners rather than just drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   More restaurants, like Mercer Kitchen, Tabla and Asia de Cuba,
are adding communal tables, which would seem like natural places to
seat single diners, although more often than not these seats go to
groups. Most important, though, is simple consideration, and a pair
of sensitive antennae.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put them at a good table where they can be comfortable,''
said Iacovelli, who says he regularly serves solo diners from the
Mercer and SoHo Grand Hotels. ``If they have a book, we put them in
a corner. If they want to talk, we pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Paying attention sometimes has its own rewards. In Paris, as I
was wondering what to have for dessert, the Frenchman insisted I
try the gewuerztraminer sorbet. I did, and it was wonderfully
refreshing, the perfect finish to the meal. Without the fellow
sitting next to me, I never would have known.
</P>
</TEXT>
