<HEADLINE>
INTENSE MERLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canoe Ridge Merlot, 1996, Columbia Valley, Washington. About
$19.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state continues to produce some of the most
intriguing red wines in this country, wines with the intensity of
flavor that marks the best California wines but with a leanness and
elegance few California wines can match.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter cold in eastern Washington during the winter of 1996 cut
the size of the grape crop but did not affect the quality of the
wine. The result, thanks to a long, cool summer, is a wine of
intense flavors, a Bordeaux-like body and a long, luxurious finish.
</P>
<P>
   Canoe Ridge, partly owned by the Chalone Group in California,
specializes in merlot. The blend here includes 6 percent cabernet
sauvignon. It was aged in French and American oak for 16 months,
and 15,000 cases were produced, so it shouldn't be too difficult to
find.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
