<HEADLINE>
BEST JOBS? HOW DOES YOURS RATE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's the same for every kid, isn't it? When they dream
about what they want to be when they grow up, don't all little boys
and girls picture themselves as . . . a Web site manager?
</P>
<P>
   Actuary, then? Computer systems analyst? Software engineer?
(begin ital) Mathematician? (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Uh, no. But maybe they should, according to ``Jobs Rated
Almanac,'' a new book that rates the best and worst jobs in the
country. According to the book, those are the top five. (Roustabout
ranks last.)
</P>
<P>
   The author, Les Krants, used data from the government, trade
groups and telephone surveys to rank 250 jobs according to six
criteria: income, stress, physical demands, potential growth, job
security and work environment.
</P>
<P>
   It's a combination that, on first glance, makes for some
interesting rankings. The president of the United States, for
instance, checks in at a measly No. 229, between butcher and truck
driver.
</P>
<P>
   Which sounded about right to Max Cotton. Cotton, the owner of
Cotton's Meats and a butcher himself (``I can take it from the
field to the freezer''), wasn't surprised his profession ranks
higher than chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics, I think, is the dirtiest thing in the world,''
Cotton said. ``Whoever does the best, convincing job of lying will
get elected. Do I have a better job than the president? Yeah, I got
a better job than the president.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glad to be 11th &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paralegals rank No. 11, news that tickled Tammy Zaccaria. She's
a paralegal at Peskind Hymson &AMP; Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I do,'' she said. ``It's great to know that I
didn't waste my time.''
</P>
<P>
   What's even greater is how much higher paralegals rank than
lawyers, who ostensibly have the better job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to be an attorney,'' Zaccaria said. ``But
they're No. 60 on the list, so I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   What she does know is how to use the newfound knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go in and ask for a raise now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any such list is loaded with land mines _
perceptions, misconceptions, personal preferences, that kind of
thing. No one would seriously base career plans on such a study.
Which is my justification for newspaper reporter ranking No. 176,
between real estate agent and chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine such a list causing anyone to quit his day
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Web site manager _ I couldn't even dream of that,'' said Dave
Weiss, a dentist (No. 86). ``That's way beyond my wildest dreams.
They say dream big, but I'm a small person inside. I can't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, he's happy where he is, between agricultural
scientist and cashier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-five and above, I don't know what they are,'' he said.
``But if I had to pick another job that I covet, I'd be hard-put at
this point.'' &QL; 
Bound to be better &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Roswell, a bookbinder (No. 92) and the owner of Roswell
Bookbinding, likes his job, too. But there is that one
lower-ranking job that intrigues him . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be president,'' he said. ``I'd be a good one. I'd be a
hell of a lot better than the one we've got now.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for it to happen. For one thing, it would mean a
precipitous drop on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a pay cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Other oddities: professional baseball players rank No. 202,
basketball players 205 and football players 211. And astronaut (No.
180) ranks just below bartender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astronaut would be pretty cool,'' said Hans Bittikofer, a
bartender at Durant's. ``But you'd probably have to go to school
for a long time to do that. You don't have to do much schooling to
do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bittikofer showed little interest in occupying the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get paid as much as the president, but I have a pretty
damn good job,'' he said. ``I have a lot of fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could convince him to trade places with Bill Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' he said. ``Except for the sex. He probably
has more sex than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   No word on how Web site managers rank in that department. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
