   WEATHER-QUITS _ ATLANTA _ Longtime head of the Weather Channel
resigns abruptly. No successor is named. We check it out. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)CHECKFREE _ A look at two start-up
companies, one in Atlanta and one in North Carolina, which are
competing in the online bill-getting and bill-paying field, which
is led by Checkfree in metro Atlanta. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GATECH-RANKING _ Georgia Tech ranks third in the nation among
engineering schools, just behind MIT and Stanford. We look at what
the ranking, in US News and World Report, is based on and what Tech
thinks about it. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PAY _ Atlanta's low cost of living coupled with fairly
hefty paychecks catapults the metro area above high tech centers
like California or Boston, pay trackers and recruiters say. Our
closest nemesis in the Southeast: Fairfax County, Va., which
recently swiped the America Online telecommunications center out
from under us. Raleigh's Research Triangle Park gives Atlanta a run
for its money. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SMALLBIZ _ AUSTIN _ H.V. Villegas &AMP; Co., an Austin company, is
one of two Texas companies that will be helping small companies
qualify under the new Small Business Development program of the
U.S. Small Business Administration. The program is to certify small
businesses as socially and economically disadvantaged so they can
compete for federal contracts. A look at the program. (Austin
American-Statesman). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WAGES _ ATLANTA _ When it comes to pay, Atlanta may be the
information technology field's best kept secret. The low cost of
living coupled with fairly hefty paychecks catapults the metro area
above hot shot high tech centers like California or Boston, pay
trackers and recruiters say. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL-DIVERSITY _ATLANTA _Valerie Ferguson, perhaps the highest
ranking woman and African American of a major hotel company, spoke
today about the importance of diversity in the hospitality industry
during an ACVB-sponsored summit. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED _ ATLANTA _ Tom Burbage, the new man in charge at
Lockheed Martin's Marietta plant, is used to hot seats. Since 1995
he's led the company's high-profile F-22 fighter program. He used
to be a Navy test pilot and for fun is a competitive rower. He
brings a can-do attitude to the new post, which he assumes at a
time of challenges and questions about the plant's future.(Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEST-DRIVE _ 1999 Acura Integra GS-R front-drive coupe.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ Technology is an ongoing process, with one
innovation often leading to another. Nowhere is that more apparent
than in the automotive industry, specifically in driver-assisting
safety innovations. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ I went, I saw, I marveled and I walked
away from this year's International Auto Show in Atlanta feeling a
bit awed, somewhat confused and deeply concerned. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOTRODS-MUSIC _ What is it with music lovers and their cars?
Three car-crazy Austinites, guitarist Jimmie Vaughan, Continental
Club owner Steve Wertheimer and Chuy's owner Mike Young, spend lots
their money and time on old cars newly redesigned that look sharp,
just like in the good ol' 50s. During SXSW these cars and others
were seen; even Rhino Records will release a 4-disc ``Hot Rods &AMP;
Custom Classics: Cruisin Songs and Highway Hits'', a set inspired
by and dedicated to the three Austinites who celebrate the
inspiration of the open road on rock 'n' roll, from ``Maybelline''
through ``Little Red Corvette.'' (McLeese, Austin
American-Statesman). 50. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ A lot of diligent retirement savers are suffering
from sticker shock. They converted a traditional individual
retirement account to a Roth IRA last year, and it's just now
soaking in that they have to pay income tax on the money they
transferred. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
