<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FUNERAL-HOME-LAWSUIT _ Eliza May, who recently was fired from
her job as director of the Texas Funeral Service Commission, on
Tuesday is expected to sue the state and funeral home giant SCI
over her firing. She says the funeral company and state officials
appointed by Gov. George W. Bush sought to stop her from fully
investigating illegal embalming practices by SCI. Bush and several
lawmakers have received thousands of dollars from SCI's political
action committee. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH-DOLE _ Elizabeth Dole speaks at San Antonio meeting of
National Petrochemical and Refiners Association. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   PBP-PHILANTHROPIST (DEVELOPING) _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla., _
Millionaire developer and philanthropist Thomas Worrell has been
snubbed by Taos, New Mexico, residents in his attempts to redevelop
about 20 buildings there, mostly old homes and mansions. Six weeks
ago, a $4 million mansion he owns there was burned, and last week,
someone shot at a security guard at the home. TV news clips show
other buildings have been spray-painted with ``Go home, Worrell!''
(McGinness, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
