<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARIBBEAN-TRADE24-COX     03-23 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEAN-TRADE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAHAM URGES EXPANSION OF CARIBBEAN TRADE POLICY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trade restrictions should be eased on products from
the Caribbean and Central America, a congressional panel was told
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But textile manufacturers and their employees warned that
unfettered trade could harm U.S. cotton growers and garment
workers.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are proposals to eliminate tariffs on products covered
by the 1983 Caribbean Basin Initiative (CBI), which set lower
tariff rates. The proposals are aimed at giving Caribbean and
Central American countries trade status similar to Mexico's under
the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
   The treatment of textiles has been a key issue in the trade
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., has sponsored a bill to eliminate
tariffs on textiles assembled in CBI countries from cotton and yarn
grown or processed in the United States. He said the barriers
should be reduced to help the region devastated by hurricanes
Georges and Mitch, and to protect U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is critical to the security of the U.S. and the countries
within the region that the people of the Caribbean Basin have real
opportunities in the legal economy so they are not forced to turn
to drug trafficking or illegal immigration to feed their
families,'' Graham told the House Ways and Means trade
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he believed differences between his bill and one in
the House that would allow textiles to be assembled in the region
from material grown or produced anywhere in the world could be
worked out in a House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham said the most difficult hurdle would be to get the
bills through each chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Without the CBI extensions, Graham warned, the Caribbean
countries face the threat of enormous competition from China by
2005, when current quotas on Chinese textiles are lifted under
international trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up two green golf shirts, Graham noted that one was made
in China from cotton grown, spun and woven there. Another shirt was
made in Nicaragua from cotton grown, spun and woven in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicaraguan shirt had a slightly higher wholesale cost than
the Chinese shirt, but Graham said there was a market for it
because of the quota on Chinese textiles.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Caribbean textile industry can be strengthened over
the next five years, Graham warned that it would be undercut by
Chinese exports in 2005. That could throw thousands of Caribbean
garment workers _ and American cotton growers and textile
manufacturers _ out of work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Larson, assistant secretary of state for economic and
business affairs, also urged the panel to adopt CBI expansion.
President Clinton's proposal would not lift restrictions as much as
Graham's bill, but Larson said some change was necessary to ensure
economic stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
   F. Ronald Rayner, president of the National Cotton Council of
America, which supports Graham's bill, said it would help protect
the domestic textile industry. But Rayner warned that if
Asian-based textiles are given tariff protection through CBI
legislation, it would hurt American growers.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Mazur, president of the Union of Needletrades, Industrial
and Textile Employees argued that the CBI legislation was
unnecessary because Caribbean Basin apparel imports have increased
from 18 percent of the U.S. market share in 1993, when NAFTA was
adopted, to 24 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
