<HEADER>
A1335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GELMAN-ART-COLLECTION     03-23 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GELMAN-ART-COLLECTION-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVABLE TREATS FROM THE BANQUET YEARS OF MEXICAN ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Jacques and Natasha Gelman were art collectors in the
most beneficent sense of the word. ``Jacques liked to say that he
was not the owner, merely the link that carried the art from the
studio to the museum,'' recalled Pierre Schneider, a French curator
and longtime friend of the couple. ``But they were always
discussing where the paintings should end up. Their greatest
anxiety was to keep the collection intact. They considered it a
work of art in its own right.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, by the time Gelman died in 1986 at age 77, the couple
had two quite separate collections, to which the widowed Mrs.
Gelman continued to add: one of works by modern masters like
Picasso, Matisse, Braque and Balthus, which was kept in New York,
the other of paintings and drawings by this century's most
prominent Mexican artists, which was on display in their home in
Cuernavaca, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Gelman died last May at age 86, she bequeathed the
modern masters collection, comprising 85 works worth over $300
million, to the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York. The gift
had been anticipated. A few years earlier she had endowed the
Jacques and Natasha Gelman curatorship of pre-World War II
20th-century art at the museum, and she financed restoration of a
gallery that carries the couple's name and is expected to house the
collection late next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the final home of the Mexican collection is still in doubt,
and in the meantime it has become a peripatetic homage both to
Mexican art and to the Gelmans as collectors. ``Modern and
Contemporary Mexican Painting From the Collection of Jacques and
Natasha Gelman,'' a 73-work show that runs through May 8 at the
Mona Bismarck Foundation near the Trocadero in Paris, is also
expected to travel to Argentina, Spain, New Zealand and the United
States over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   While the works donated to the Metropolitan Museum are more
valuable, the Mexican collection in many ways offers a truer
picture of the Gelmans' tastes, dreams, friends and long years
together. They knew most of the painters represented in the show,
and Diego Rivera, Frida Kahlo, David Alfaro Siqueiros and Rufino
Tamayo were among the artists commissioned to paint Natasha's
portrait. Put differently, the Gelmans collected European art, but
they belonged to the Mexican art scene.
</P>
<P>
   Born in St. Petersburg, Russia, in 1909, Gelman arrived in
Mexico City in 1938 via Berlin and Paris with a view to expanding
his movie distribution business to Latin America. Two encounters
changed his life. He met Natasha Zahalkaha, a divorcee from Moravia
(now in the Czech Republic) who was visiting Mexico; they married
in 1941. Then, as he prepared to produce his first movie in Mexico,
Gelman discovered Mario Moreno, a comedian who became known to the
world as Cantinflas and with whom he formed a highly profitable
movie partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly wealthy, Gelman turned his attention to collecting art.
Rivera was at the height of his fame, yet Gelman could easily
afford to have the artist paint his wife; the 1943 portrait shows
Mrs. Gelman lying on a blue sofa, with arum lilies filling the
background. The Paris show includes eight other works by Rivera,
who with Jose Clemente Orozco and Siqueiros made up the Big Three
of Mexico's post-revolutionary muralists and painters. The Gelmans
also bought works by Orozco and Siqueiros, although Mrs. Gelman
never liked Siqueiros' portrait of her.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's collection of 12 works by Kahlo, Rivera's wife, is
particularly impressive and includes six self-portraits as well as
Kahlo's small 1943 portrait of a pensive-looking Mrs. Gelman
bedecked in fur. This portrait was the first painting to hang in
the Gelmans' new home in Mexico City. And it is hardly surprising
that Gelman was able to persuade Tamayo to return briefly to
figurative painting in 1948 to provide his version of Mrs. Gelman
in oil.
</P>
<P>
   The largest number of works in the Mexican collection (29 of 98)
are by Gunther Gerszo, an abstract painter who worked as a movie
designer in the 1940s and 1950s for Gelman but also for Luis Bunuel
(and others working out of Mexico City's Churubusco Studios) before
devoting himself entirely to painting. Gerszo, now 83, met the
Gelmans in 1944 and remained close to them throughout their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gelmans were completely obsessed by art,'' Schneider said.
``They couldn't have children, but the collection became their
child. I met them in 1968 when I was preparing the Matisse
centennial exhibition in Paris, and in the years that followed I
never heard Jacques discuss movies. He never reminisced. He only
talked about art.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Paris show also includes paintings by Maria Izquierdo,
Carlos Merida, Carlos Orozco Romero, Juan Soriano, Agustin Lazo and
other Mexican painters from the middle years of this century. After
her husband's death, Mrs. Gelman continued to acquire new art to
fill holes in the Mexican collection (just as she did with the
modern masters' collection) and to include contemporary artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted a Francisco Toledo and also a better Maria
Izquierdo, though we didn't find one she wanted,'' said Robert
Littman, the curator of the Paris show and head of the new Vergel
Foundation, which now owns the Gelmans' Mexican collection. ``But
she always would also say, `You have to buy your own generation.'
So I would show her younger artists and we'd put their works in her
house for a while to see if she liked them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, while three of the Mona Bismarck Foundation's
galleries are given over to Mexico's modern figurative painters, a
fourth room is dedicated to contemporary Mexican art that Mrs.
Gelman bought in the 1990s. Among the new artists are Miguel
Calderon, 28, who photographed himself in Mexico's Natural History
Museum disguised in an Afro wig and false beard and threatening
stuffed tigers with a pistol, and Paula Santiago, 30, who used rice
paper to create tiny reproductions of Mexican peasant shirts and
then ``embroidered'' them with her own blood and strands of hair.
</P>
<P>
   While Littman expects to continue adding to the collection with
money from an endowment from the Gelmans, his more immediate
concern is how to carry out the Gelmans' wish to have it installed
permanently in a Mexican museum. ``She said that would be my
problem,'' Littman said. ``The ideal solution is a private museum
that is not attached to the government, but there isn't one.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility had been the Cultural Center for Contemporary
Art in Mexico City, which opened in 1987 and which Littman headed.
But the center's owner, the Televisa television group, closed it in
November for financial reasons. Among the alternatives are the
National Museum of Art, which is being restored by a group of
businessmen; an old customs house in the Caribbean port of Veracruz
suggested by the local governor, Miguel Aleman, and a space in the
historic heart of Mexico City being renovated by the National
Autonomous University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collection will not be donated, but rather will be on
deposit,'' Littman said. ``It's a tremendous collection, and it
deserves a good home. I'm even willing to entertain suggestions
from the government. We're in no rush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
