<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LIFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From pride to confidence, unseeded Life College celebrates NAIA
championship
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He is scheduled for his second operation in six days,
but Roger Kaiser has something that will help to ease the pain
during today's procedure _ a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Life University coach watched Monday as his team win its
second NAIA title in three years with a dramatic 63-60 victory over
Mobile (Ala.) University in Tulsa, Okla. The team received a big
welcome upon its return to town Tuesday, but Kaiser, the former
Georgia Tech All-American, will have to delay his celebration as he
is scheduled for gall-stone surgery today, less than one week after
surgery for kidney stones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably won't feel any pain at all because of this
experience,'' said Kaiser, who missed the team's second-round game
against Oklahoma City suffering from pain related to the first
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The unseeded Running Eagles capped an unbelievable tournament
run by rallying from a 26-point second-half deficit for the
victory. Guard Corey Evans, the tournament's most valuable player,
was the hero of the championship game, as he hit a long-three
pointer with two seconds remaining for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt it,'' said Evans. ``That was the biggest shot of
my career. I didn't think it was going in. Thank God it did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who was stunned the most _ us or them,'' Kaiser
said. ``They were beating us so badly, all I was thinking about was
trying to make the game respectable. We kept talking about pride.
Then that pride turned into confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Evans, who scored 121 points in five tournament games,
including 16 of his team-high 22 points in the second half Monday,
said some doubts entered the minds of the Running Eagles (29-10)
after Mobile went up 50-24 with 17:07 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't give us a chance, but we started to think we
could win this thing after we came from 16 points down to beat
Concordia in our third game,'' said Evans, a 6-1 junior from Cocoa,
Fla. ``But in the second half (against Mobile), it looked like
those guys weren't going to let us back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the last 17 minutes, though, Life, the first unseeded
team to the win the NAIA national title, outscored Mobile 39-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamaal Horton (12 points), Chummy Johnson (12) and Allen
Stozier (8) started to hit some big shots, and we started to force
turnovers,'' Evans said. ``They weren't timid, but they lost their
concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, who won his first NAIA national title in 1974 while at
West Georgia College, called this five-game tournament run ``the
most satisfying'' in his 27-year career as a college coach. The
team entered the season with high expectations but had the most
losses of any team since the 1993-94 season, the third year of the
program's existence.
</P>
<P>
   The Running Eagles also had the nation's longest home winning
streak snapped at 99 games and was defeated at home by
Auburn-Montgomery in the Southeast Regional. Through it all, they
worked their way to the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It was very satisfying) especially under the circumstances,
(after) not having a good year,'' Kaiser said. ``We got beat badly
at home (by Auburn-Montgomery in the Southeast Regional) before we
came out. Then we fall behind by big margins in two or three of our
games and come back to win them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing feeling I wish everybody could experience _ a
lesson about life,'' Kaiser said. ``You never give up on anything.
These guys didn't, and I can't be anymore proud of them than I am
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
