<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARY-STAIRS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SCARY AT THE TOP: VERTIGO AS RESTAURANT TREND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have just had a long meal at Tabla _ three courses and
plenty of wine. When it's time to leave, you are feeling fine.
</P>
<P>
   Until you reach the staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Before you lies a steep, sweeping curve of steps. Suddenly your
legs feel less steady; the descent is dizzying. With the handrail
in a death grip, you take a deep breath, and a step.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fearful moment, but one that more New Yorkers are facing
when they dine out. Just a few years ago, upstairs rooms were used
only for banquets and the occasional overflow crowd. They were
closed off by small hidden staircases, and were the seating
equivalent of Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   But the restaurant boom, along with rising rents for
street-level space, has led a growing number of restaurateurs to
expand upward. Now, the second floor dining room is commonplace _
it may even be the best room in the house. But once you've gone up
to dine, there's only one way out: down the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   One misstep and everyone seated on the ground floor will be your
audience. And those who have done it never forget.
</P>
<P>
   Walecia Konrad, an editor at Smart Money, was on a first date at
the Mackinac Bar and Grill, now the Ocean Grill, on Columbus
Avenue. They were walking down the splendid marble staircase at the
entrance _ when suddenly she found herself on the ground, looking
up. ``It was out of a cartoon,'' she said. ``My legs just came
straight up. There was nothing graceful about it.'' Well, there was
one saving grace: at least Mackinac Bar and Grill had no
first-floor tables. That was three years ago. For a long time, she
couldn't bear to walk by the place. Her date? Never heard from
again.
</P>
<P>
   Moments like that are all the worse because so many of these
staircases are beautiful, impressive structures _ just the thing
for a grand entrance or exit. Scaling the one at Tabla, for
instance, is like climbing steps to a palace. The staircase at Asia
de Cuba is a slim, minimalist low-lighted shaft _ more like a
catwalk.
</P>
<P>
   In smaller restaurants, where every inch counts, function
overrules form. Some of these staircases feel more like gateways to
medieval towers.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case, ``obviously part of it is revenue,'' said Iva
Kravitz, the director of marketing at Bogdanow Partners Architects,
which designed the multilevel Obeca Li and the two-story Union
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Making a second-floor space a dining area instead of offices is
an easy way to make more money. If the restaurant can add drama,
too, then all the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make the staircase both central and open to both floors,''
Ms. Kravitz said. But that seems unusually cruel to diners for whom
staircases feel like coordination tests.
</P>
<P>
   Every night at Union Square Cafe, an unlucky few must scale one
of New York's most frightening staircases of all. It's about as
narrow as a rain gutter, and navigating it is like climbing a
ladder. It leads to a mezzanine with seven tables.
</P>
<P>
   Those seven tables can make a big difference to the bottom line.
It used to be that a restaurant needed to have 60 to 70 seats to
make money. ``Now, if you're not at 110 or 120, you can't pay the
health insurance,'' said Clark Wolf, a New York restaurant
consultant. Those seven tables could be worth $100,000 a seat a
year, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Department of Buildings code generally
requires restaurants with occupancies of more than 75 on the second
floor to have staircases at least 3 feet 8 inches wide, with steps
that rise no more than 7 inches and a tread no less than 11 inches.
At Alouette, for instance, on the Upper West Side, the stairs are
11{ inches by 7 inches, just within the code. Comfortable going up,
dicey coming down.
</P>
<P>
   But even extra-wide staircases, like the one at Ruby Foo's Dim
Sum and Sushi Palace, can be like a pass through a fun house. You
can hold on to only one handrail, and to one side the width of the
step is quite deep, forcing you into an antelopelike stride.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, it's made of a highly polished wood. Add a few
drops of rainwater off someone's coat, and it's like walking on
ice. The one at Tabla is within code but is made of dark wood in a
dimly lighted space.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't the design of the staircase that is perplexing, its
placement can be. Asia de Cuba's seductively lighted staircase is
inviting, but it takes you upstairs to a rum bar. Who needs a
sobriety test on the way down? Since the restaurant opened 17
months ago, the steel handrail has been reinstalled. The iron grips
of wary diners had pulled it loose.
</P>
<P>
   At Babbo, the staircase to the second floor dining area was
practically all that was left from the previous restaurant, the
Coach House. The chef, Mario Batali, and his partner, Joseph
Bastianich, wanted to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tall, grand structure that escalates rapidly to the
second floor. The tables on the ground floor are arranged like a
horseshoe around it. The staircase is so steep that even if you
stand at the top of it stone sober, you suffer from vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   When you are walking down the carpeted steps, Batali said, ``you
really feel what it's like to be prom queen.'' But for most people,
it's more about getting to the bottom as quickly as possible
without anyone noticing. It's a long way down, and the only thing
to break your fall is a large table covered with wine and flowers.
It wouldn't be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought certainly someone would tumble in the first six
months,'' Batali said. But so far, the only spill was by a waiter
carrying a tray of glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Petrecca, a reporter at Advertising Age and a chronic
tripper, regards the Babbo staircase with deep fear. ``I wonder if
they can see up my skirt,'' she said, ``but I also worry that if I
fall down there, everyone and their brother would see.'' At
restaurants like Docks in midtown, where a central staircase leads
to the bathrooms, she avoids going to the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants keep a careful eye out for people like Ms. Petrecca.
Babbo's wait staff is trained to screen people descending the
stairs. ``If they see someone even slightly tipsy or unable to do
the stairs,'' Batali said, ``they go over and assist them.''
</P>
<P>
   At Union Square Cafe, a towel is kept at the reservation desk to
wipe down the stairs leading into the main dining room if anything
spills.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative may not be far off. Soon there may be more
restaurants like Celadon, which provides a safe, secure elevator as
the centerpiece of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Diners may wear their stilettos _ and merely press a button. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
