<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0324-CO     03-23 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0324-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., OTHERS EVACUATE PERSONNEL IN BOSNIA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By Susannah A. Nesmith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- With the possibility of a
NATO-led attack on neighboring Yugoslavia increasing, international
agencies Tuesday began to evacuate their staff from the
Serb-controlled region of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Several embassies, including that of the United States, have
urged their citizens not to travel in the Republika Srpska (CQ),
the Serb state within Bosnia, because of the possibility of Serb
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. government employees were pulled out of the Serb state
Tuesday and embassy officials sent a letter to several U.S.
contractors and non-governmental agencies in the region urging them
to evacuate as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of the High Representative, the organization
responsible for implementing the peace plan in Bosnia, closed its
satellite offices in the Republika Srpska over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our satellite offices are very small operations and very
vulnerable,'' said said James Fergusson, spokesman for the peace
plan organization.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday morning, two hand grenades were set off in the
parking lot of the organization's office in Banja Luka, the capital
of the Republika Srpska. No one was injured and only one car was
damaged in the explosion, Fergusson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Banja Luka office was not among those evacuated by the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate incident, a key highway in the Serb state was
closed for several hours overnight by Serb demonstrators. The
demonstration was set off by rumors that members of the NATO-led
military peacekeeping force in Bosnia had shot rubber bullets at a
Serb politician passing through a checkpoint on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the peacekeeping force denied the rumors,
insisting that the politician hadn't even been stopped at the
checkpoint and pointing out that its soldiers aren't issued rubber
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report is pure fabrication,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Sheena
Thomson.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration and the hand grenade attack are evidence of
increasing tension in the Republika Srpska. Two key political
setbacks at home combined with the threat of air strikes on Serbs
in neighboring Yugoslavia have only served to fuel feelings among
many Bosnian Serbs that the entire international community is
against them.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago an international arbitrator announced his decision
to make Brcko a neutral district, taking control of the
strategically important port away from Bosnian Serbs. The same day
the Serbs lost control of Brcko, the Office of the High
Representative removed the hard-line Serb
</P>
<P>
   president of the Republika Srpska from office, further angering
many Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily protests were held in Brcko following the decision,
though none turned violent.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   For the past month, officials of NATO-led military peacekeeping
force have been searching the Republika Srpska for secret weapons
caches. The searches were prompted by the discovery of two trucks
smuggling nine tons of weapons from the western Republika Srpska
through Brcko to some point in the eastern part of Republika
Srpska, or possibly even to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some indication that there are still some undisclosed
weapons
</P>
<P>
   storage sites,'' Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the NATO-led force is looking for the
sophisticated surface-to-air missile launchers that the Yugoslav
army used against American fighter pilots in the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the UN High Commission for Refugees is bracing for
the possibility more Albanian refugees will flee into Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 Kosovo Albanian refugees in Bosnia have asked the
agency for help since the conflict started, according to
spokeswoman Ariane Quentier. Another 70 come to Bosnia every week,
though she said the agency hasn't seen any increase in the past few
days, despite the recent Serbian offensive in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Susannah A. Nesmith is a free-lance writer who lives in
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
