<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-0324-CO     03-23 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-0324-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRIMAKOV CANCELS TRIP TO U.S. OVER KOSOVO
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW -- Ordering his airplane to turn around while over the
mid-Atlantic, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov abruptly canceled his
visit to Washington Tuesday as NATO warplanes were poised to strike
Serb targets.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov decided to return to Moscow rather than face the
embarrassing prospects of holding talks in Washington while NATO
bombs Serbia, a close Russian ally. Russia has strongly opposed air
strikes, calling for further negotiations in an attempt to settle
the stalemate over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's U-turn marks a low-point in post-Soviet Union
relations between the Washington and Moscow. Yet Russia,
economically and politically weak, has little pressure to bring to
bear on the United States and NATO as it desperately seeks billions
of dollars in Western aid.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's decision to turn back came after two telephone
conversations Tuesday with Vice President Al Gore, the latter while
the Russian prime minister was over the Atlantic. Gore informed
Primakov that diplomacy had failed to resolve the Kosovo crisis,
and reportedly told him that bombing of Serb positions was
``inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   During a stopover in Shannon, Ireland, before the decision was
made to turn back, Primakov told reporters that NATO strikes ``defy
common sense and could destabilize the situation in the world. We
are categorically against this, categorically.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from meetings with U.S. officials, Primakov was to have
held crucial talks in Washington with the leaders of the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank. Those talks were to
be part of Russia's efforts to seek financial help to ease its deep
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, officials in Moscow warned that Russia may respond
to NATO strikes by helping to rearm the Serbs, contrary to United
Nations sanctions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be an aggression, so the country which is attacked
must have weapons to defend itself,'' said Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov's comments came as reports emerged that a Russian cargo
plane carrying MiG jet fighters had been seized last week in
Azerbaijan. Officials there said the plane was bound for
Yugoslavia, in violations of the arms embargo against Belgrade. The
Russian foreign ministry said the cargo plane was headed for
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, asked about the MiGs during his stopover in Ireland,
said: ``We have not broken the sanctions yet.''
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. and Russian officials insisted the round of meetings
between Primakov and Gore was merely postponed, the sudden decision
and Russia's tough talk about possibly arming the Serbs marks a
further souring of U.S.-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
   It also reflects Russia's increasingly feeble position in world
diplomacy since the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991. Russia is
seeking to dig itself out of a severe economic slump amid political
disarray. Ailing President Boris Yeltsin has become increasingly
powerless.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov put Russia's prestige on the line as Moscow stood by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in hopes that Russian
diplomats could broker a settlement and avoid NATO strikes. Russia
offered to supply troops to the NATO-led peacekeeping force for
Kosovo, an offer Milosevic eventually rejected.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, senior Russian officials had hinted throughout the
day Tuesday that Primakov would postpone or cut short his U.S.
trip. The government faces intense pressure from the opposition
Communist Party and other nationalists who favor a tougher line
toward America and closer support for fellows Slavs in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev warned that NATO strikes could
spark a Vietnam-style war in the middle of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In similar fashion, officials across the Russian political
spectrum denounced U.S. air strikes on Iraq last December with Cold
War-style rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Russian opposition leaders have called on Russia to cancel its
cooperation with NATO if warplanes attack Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO strikes are also likely to further stall Russian
ratification of START II, said Gennady Seleznyov, chairman of the
Communist-controlled Duma, the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate ratified the arms control treaty in 1996. But
despite pleas from Yeltsin, the Duma has continually put off a vote
on the treaty, which would cut Russian and American nuclear
arsenals to about 3,500 warheads apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
