<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1353 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      03-23 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE CALLS TOUTS LESS GOVERNMENT IN SPEECH TO BUSINESS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT FLORES  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In a wide-ranging speech that was heavy on themes
but light on specifics, prospective Republican presidential
candidate Elizabeth Dole said Tuesday the public had lost faith in
the government because it is too big and too bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is remember the wisdom of our country's
Founding Fathers,'' Dole told 2,200 members of the National
Petrochemical and Refiners Association, which was meeting in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to dust off that 10th Amendment to the
Constitution,'' Dole said, referring to the amendment that
relegates to local governments those powers not specific to the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who is in the process of exploring support for a
presidential bid next year, touched on issues such as crime,
education, drug eradication and national defense and repeatedly
emphasized a need for strong family values.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never return to an age of innocence, but we can return
to an age of rediscovery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Dole said America must ``restore public
schools to greatness, return safety to our streets'' and set a goal
of ``ridding our society'' of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The America given to us by our parents is much better than the
one we are turning over to our kids,'' Dole said. ``We've been
embarrassed to talk about the values that made our lives good, like
discipline and modesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's 35-minute speech was laced with several anecdotes about
her public service career that began with the Federal Trade
Commission more than 30 years ago. She served as Transportation
secretary in the Reagan administration, Labor secretary in the Bush
administration and was president of the American Red Cross until
January, but Dole has not held an elected office.
</P>
<P>
   She did not take questions from reporters or members of the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   However, in responding to a question from the association's
president, Dole said the country's biggest challenge is to develop
a strategic defense system. She cited North Korea's development of
nuclear weapons as a major reason for the immediate need for a
shield against missile attacks from rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who was popular fixture in the 1996 presidential campaign
of her husband, former Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, is considered one of
the GOP's top prospective candidates next year. The other is Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, who earlier this month formed his own
exploratory committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
