<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE OSCARS, THE COMPLAINTS 
GREATLY EXAGGERATED RUMORS
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC and the Academy Awards broadcast took a pounding from
critics after Sunday's show, the main targets being its extreme
length and Whoopi Goldberg's performance as host.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Davies, the ABC executive in charge of the broadcast,
said Tuesday that the first order of business for next year's show
would be insuring that it did not drag on. ``A four-hour and
seven-minute Oscar show is obviously too long,'' Davies said of
this year's length.
</P>
<P>
   The goal every year is three and a half hours, rarely achieved,
he said, for all the reasons that a live television event is an
unwieldy beast. But this year's show had special problems with
length, Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   One was the usual challenge: acceptance speeches that go on too
long. Davies pointed out that the first big award went to James
Coburn, ``a film legend,'' as he called him, and thus someone whose
comments were not going to be drowned out by music, the usual way
speeches are cut short. Once Coburn went on a bit long, the tone
for the night was set, Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's show was also stuffed with tribute pieces,
partly because the Academy felt obligated to mention film figures
who had died, like Frank Sinatra and Stanley Kubrick. But the extra
tribute pieces were also a way to solve one of this year's special
problems: There were not, Davies said, ``a lot of huge, popular
films, or huge stars for that matter, with nominations.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers had to try to grab the audience with the kind of
names they like to see, Davies said, adding, ``The only way to lure
them into being presenters is to ask them to give out a tribute to
someone they admire.'' John Travolta introduced the Sinatra
segment, and Nicolas Cage gave the Thalberg Award to the producer
Norman Jewison.
</P>
<P>
   Davies was effusive in his praise for Ms. Goldberg, whom he said
performed admirably in ``one of the most difficult roles in the
business, one that very few people can do.'' She was hampered, he
said, by a crowd that was less than ideal for any comic. ``That was
an extremely cold room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics assailed Ms. Goldberg for some of her material,
which was occasionally racier than what is generally heard on the
Oscar show. Davies said that ABC had received no calls objecting to
her jokes and that she had mainly made subtle comments that
``adults get but go over the heads of children.'' He did
acknowledge that she had let slip one barnyard epithet but he put
that down to the ``risks of live television.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as ABC and the Academy are concerned, we'd love to have
her do the show again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be a tough invitation for her to accept, given the
nasty comments. Davies said harsh criticism of the show and the
host was becoming an issue for the producers. ``It's becoming more
and more difficult to persuade anyone to do these programs,' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With ratings down from last year, when the dominance of
``Titanic'' brought hordes of teen-age viewers with it, Davies
suggested something he would like to see in next year's show:
``Lots of nominations for the `Star Wars' sequel.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Blues Clueless
</P>
<P>
   The rumors sound like the Beatles hoax of the late 1960s, when
word spread that Paul McCartney had died and that the proof was
that he was barefoot on the ``Abbey Road'' album cover and that you
could hear ``Paul is dead'' if you played the song ``Revolution No.
9'' backward.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 30 years later, an almost identical hoax is swirling around
a different sort of cultural icon: Steve Burns, the cheery young
man in a green-striped rugby shirt who is the host of the preschool
show ``Blue's Clues'' on Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet prankster has spread word that Steve was killed in a
car accident and that a look-alike has been hired to play him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very different from Paul McCartney,'' said Angela
Santomero, the show's chief writer and one of its co-creators.
``It's very different when these are 2-to-5-year-old children
you're talking about. Steve has become someone they trust, someone
they almost have a play date with and go on adventures with, and
thinking he might not be there anymore is really upsetting to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The rumor has spread nationwide among parents and day-care
providers. They, of course, could be expected to withhold it from
toddlers, but there is concern that older children could see the
rumor on the Internet and tell younger siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Such a concern prompted Rosie O'Donnell to invite Burns to
appear on her daytime talk show, and he did. Burns has also kept up
a busy schedule of public appearances, speaking at a
UNICEF-sponsored children's television forum in Chile last week,
and participating in a reading for blind and dyslexic children on
Monday in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to be back in the studio in New York, recording
new episodes, next week.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1806EST &QL; 
