<HEADLINE>
`THE NORM SHOW': ADVENTURES IN SOCIAL WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You can't take my dog,'' insists a man who had left his
dachshund at the pound but has now changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're social workers, pal,'' replies Norm Henderson, who has
adopted the dog. ``We can take children.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a brave comedy writer to pen that exchange (of course
the National Association of Social Workers isn't thrilled with it),
and that's a good sign for ``The Norm Show,'' which has its
premiere Wednesday on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Norm is played by Norm Macdonald, formerly of ``Saturday Night
Live,'' who is also one of the new show's writers and executive
producers. The bad signs for the series are a strained gag early in
the premiere about a dog who does nothing but sit and stare (Moose,
who plays Eddie the Jack Russell terrier on ``Frasier,'' could sue
and win) and one of the most annoying, overinsistent laugh tracks
in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The track becomes less disturbing as the gags get funnier, and
luckily they do. When Norm, a former professional hockey player now
doing court-ordered community service in social work (oh, sure,
that's realistic), first thinks about getting a dog, he explains,
``I love the idea of having a friend that I can lock up when I'm
not using him.''
</P>
<P>
   When it turns out that the teen-age boy he is counseling had
only stolen a comb, Norm dismisses him with words of wisdom: ``You
come back when you stab somebody, all right, Billy?''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie, a real social worker, is played by the fabulous Laurie
Metcalf, who started with the Steppenwolf Theater Company and went
on to win three Emmys for her role as the failure-prone but
determined sister in ``Roseanne.'' In the second episode of ``The
Norm Show,'' Ms. Metcalf manages to bring intelligence even to a
story line about a male client who smells really bad because of his
fear of physical contact with water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Norm Show'' could go either way, depending on the scripts
ahead. At its best, it proves that jerky-guy characters and actual
humor can coexist.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE NORM SHOW'
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m. ET Wednesday on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Created by Bruce Helford and Norm Macdonald. Produced by Mohawk
Productions in association with Warner Bros. Television. Bruce
Rasmussen, Rob Ulin, Deborah Oppenheimer, Helford and Macdonald,
executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Norm Macdonald (Norm Henderson), Laurie Metcalf (Laurie),
Ian Gomez (Danny) and Bruce Jarchow (Curtis).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1807EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1357 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHECKFREE-COX     03-23 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECKFREE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CheckFree to have competitorsBy Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two southern start-ups are starting to compete with
CheckFree, the Norcross, Ga.-based company trying to make the
Internet the place where people get and pay their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Derivion, an Alpharetta, Ga. start-up, and InvoiceLink, a
Greensboro, N.C., company, pitched for venture capital at last
week's Venture Market South conference, sponsored by Red Herring
magazine and held in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Derivion is not a direct competitor with CheckFree.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree has dominated the early stage of the electronic
payment processing market. What was a $1 billion electronic
bill-paying industry in 1997 is growing rapidly, according to
Killen &AMP; Associates. The Palo Alto research and consulting firm,
thinks it will be an $18.8 billion market by 2005, so there is
still a lot up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The market includes Transpoint, a venture between Microsoft and
First Data Corp., with a minority investment from Citibank; EDS and
Integrion. Killen sees that group thinning, either by merger or
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you pay bills electronically, by telephone or computer,
chances are CheckFree handles the paying of that bill, either by
sending a paper check or linking the bill payer to the biller.
CheckFree has signed more than 40 of the largest billers. The
company also has a deal with Yahoo!, the largest Internet portal,
according to Avivah Litan, a Gartner Group analyst. The deal, which
neither company has announced, would make Yahoo! a place where
people would go to see electronic versions of their bills and pay
them.
</P>
<P>
   Start-up Derivion considers itself a service company. It charges
companies that send recurring bills a fee for each transaction,
usually between 25 cents and 30 cents a customer, per bill, each
month. Derivion handles the entire process of posting a bill on a
Website: letting people know the option is available, enrolling
people in the program and taking the bill data and converting it
into a form that can be posted on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Derivion targets the mid-sized market, which it defines as
companies that send out between 50,000 and 1 million bills each
month.
</P>
<P>
   The company has two customers and letters of intent for two
others, said Greg Rable, Derivion's chief executive officer.
Derivion, which started in February, 1998, employs 25 people, 15 in
Toronto, 10 in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Derivion announced it will be iXL's ``preferred
provider'' for Web-based bill-paying and bill-presenting
technology. iXL is an Atlanta interactive ad agency that designs
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Derivion's investors include Bert Ellis, chairman and CEO if
iXL; Boland T. Jones, chairman of Premiere Technologies; Rex Fuqua,
managing director of Fuqua Ventures and Sergio Zyman, who was chief
marketing officer for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   InvoiceLink, founded in 1997, is considered a ``creative
upstart'' and an ``attractive choice for banks and billers,'' said
Litan, a Gartner Group analyst.
</P>
<P>
   InvoiceLink, which employs 11 people, is targeting the
business-to-consumer and business-to-business market.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
