<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEO of Weather Channel resigns unexpectedly
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After 17 years Michael J. Eckert is resigning as chief
executive of the Weather Channel effective March 31. Eckert was one
of the founders of the Weather Channel and served as CEO for 14
years.
</P>
<P>
   No successor has been named. In the interim, John O. ``Dubby''
Wynne, president and chief executive of the parent company _
Landmark Communications _ will act as CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Eckert said in an interview that his departure involved
personal, as well as professional considerations. ``A couple of
life things were also going on and that happens with CEOs,'' he
said. ``Every CEO, maybe every person, hits a point where it's time
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Weather Channel, it's a fabulous business,'' he
says. ``But you factor in a lot of holistic things. Our kids are
out of the house. My wife and I are adventurous types. We like
skiing and hiking and we just thought we might try to do some
things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future of the Weather Channel, Eckert says the
transition will be smooth. `` I have a wonderful leadership team.
(Interim CEO Wynne) isn't going to have to spend much time with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   While he may not play an active role in choosing the next chief
executive, Eckert says there are some qualities necessary to take
the cable channel into the 21st Century: ``I have a theory that
there are five attributes people are looking for in all media. It
must be personalized, customized, convenient, fast and portable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next CEO should be someone who has a sense of where
technology is going _ not just the big picture, but how to make
money from it. That's the next person's challenge and it's not an
insurmountable challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Landmark Communications executives weren't available to comment
Thursday, but industry watchers were struck by a comment Eckerd
made Monday: ``Periodic changes in any organization's leadership
are necessary for them to remain vital and challenged.'' Some see
that as a sign the company might want to bring in new blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing about the Weather Channel is that they really
haven't been able to expand,'' says John Higgins of Broadcasting
and Cable magazine. ``They just really haven't found a way to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventeen years is a long time to be CEO of a cable channel,''
says Matt Stump, editorial director of industry trade magazine
CableWorld. Stump says Eckerd might be the third longest tenured
cable exectutive. ``That's an extremely long time in this business,
which in last three or four years is rapidly changing.''
</P>
<P>
   He also says the Weather Channel is facing increasing challenges
as ratings remain predictable, with sharp increases in viewship
when the weather turns foul. ``But on the flip side, ``Stump says,
``it has great potential for interactivity for the Internet and for
the PC.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckert, who celebrated his 52nd birthday this past weekend, says
he ultimately wants to go back to work. ``There might be
opportunities for me in Atlanta,'' he muses. ``There may be some
cable, venture capital players who are looking for somebody like me
that I might be able to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
