<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   By 11 a.m. Tuesday, temperatures had risen into the middle 50s
across parts of Montana as a dry, warm ridge of high pressure held
steady over the northern Rockies and western Canada. Not only will
the sprawling warm ridge continue to embrace the region Wednesday,
but it will also impede the eastward progression of a Pacific low
pressure system west of Vancouver Island.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy swells up to 20 feet high will pound the beaches in parts
of Oregon and Washington Wednesday as winds associated with the
Pacific low continue to agitate offshore waters. Moreover, showers
will speckle western Washington and Oregon as a pool of
high-altitude cold air drifts inland.
</P>
<P>
   The brunt of the precipitation associated with the Pacific
system will be born by central and southern California as a potent
jet stream disturbance is flung inland on its southern flank.
Moderate to heavy rains are possible, particularly at low
elevations of west-facing slopes of the Coastal Range, while heavy
snow develops in the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered showers and thunderstorms will erupt over
parts of Texas as a Pacific jet stream disturbance, which Tuesday
night slipped southward of the blocking ridge over Montana and
Wyoming, lifts very humid air from the Gulf of Mexico. Large hail
and downpours are possible across northern and central Texas to
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rain will develop along the New England seaboard as a
disturbance pivots northeast from the central Appalachians. Rain
may mix with wet snow at higher elevations farther inland.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Spring Floods
</P>
<P>
   Spring is flood season. In a typical year, melting snowpacks can
conspire with increased rainfall to make river and stream flooding
a threat. Sometimes, in northern areas, ice jams exacerbate the
floods on swollen rivers. This year, spring flooding is less likely
than normal over much of the nation. The generally mild winter in
the eastern states means that water locked in the remaining snow
cover is relatively scant. Meanwhile, in the mountains of the
Northwest, near record snow has brought an increased risk of
serious floods, but also an important boost in water supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
