<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Norm Show' stuck in D for `disappointing'
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norm MacDonald might be the funniest guy we have who doesn't
have a place to be funny. Dimply and droll, wuvable and wicked, he
killed 'em as the Weekend Update anchor on ``Saturday Night Live,''
right up until the day he was fired. His standup is legendary for
being the most outlandish routine this side of Chris Rock _ right
up to the moment audiences traditionally walk out on it.
</P>
<P>
   So what does TV do? Sticks MacDonald in a blandly generic sitcom
where his flat, devastating delivery can only occasionally peek
through _ right up until the day it's cancelled.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's forgettable ``The Norm Show,'' premiering tonight at 9:30,
revolves around MacDonald as Norm Henderson, professional hockey
player kicked out of the sport for gambling and tax evasion and
sentenced to five years of community service. Norm works in a
social services office where he alternates between toeing the line
and crossing it.
</P>
<P>
   Helping him do both: go-getter social worker Laurie, played a
little creepily by the wound-too-tight Laurie Metcalf of ``Scream
2''; and balding bad-boy-wannabe Danny (Ian Gomez).
</P>
<P>
   But there's too much situation to this situation comedy; it
unreels like MacDonald playing a role in an ``SNL'' skit that's not
working and won't ever end. His best lines only make a little
bearable the dreariness that surrounds him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't I have sex with a client?'' he asks. ``It's not like
we're psychiatrists. Or undertakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday TV will accomodate MacDonald's deadpan, slacker
Norm-ness. But not until it finishes off this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Norm Show''
</P>
<P>
   Airs tonight at 9:30 on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: The wrong show.
</P>
<P>
   `It's Like' is an L.A. show about nothing
</P>
<P>
   By Drew Jubera
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Meet the love child of ``Seinfeld.'' Created by former
``Seinfeld'' writer-producer Peter Mehlman, this smug and zippy new
ABC sitcom seems sprung straight from the shallowest end of George
Costanza's brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does this qualify as a discussion?'' one just-arrived
character exclaims to friends chattering on a patio about Elliott
Gould driving a Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's so great about L.A.,'' he's told. ``You don't
even have to be listening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Like, You Know . . .'' is the show about nothing that
George might have concocted if he had been a little more clever and
wanted you to know it _ right down to the over-calculated,
what-the-hell title. If there's a lot to laugh at here, there's
also a lot less to like.
</P>
<P>
   It's set in, like, you know, Los Angeles, of course. Most of it
takes place either in a car or the mansion of bald trust-fund
eccentric Shrug (Evan Handler). Robbie (Steven Eckholdt) lives in
Shrug's dream guest house; he's also wealthy, from a pay-per-view
business that televises the Jewish high holidays (``pay-per-Jew'').
One neighbor is the actress Jennifer Grey (``Dirty Dancing''),
played by the actress Jennifer Gray (``Dirty Dancing''), who sports
her new nose and new self-deprecating humor.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the single, underemployed, self-obsessed crew is
Robbie's best friend Arthur (Chris Eigeman), a New York magazine
writer doing a story on Los Angeles; and masseuse /summons server
Lauren (A.J. Langer).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Like, You Know'' is at its vapid best when it gives voice
to the yuppie Andy Rooney that lives, whines and wonders inside its
target audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it amazing Germany didn't change its name after World
War II?''
</P>
<P>
   ``ValuJet changed their name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they should have changed the name Germany to something
nice-sounding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . Aspen.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of ``It's Like, You Know'' centers on the
in-the-know-ness of an L.A. that's the punch line of a thousand
stand-ups. While ``Seinfeld'' was set in New York, New York rarely
was mentioned; the city was a vast terrarium where it seemed all of
America's absurdities and neuroses and banalities could be
accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   To laugh along with this relentlessly clever show is to be
stamped an insider. You feel good about yourself when you get a
joke; you just don't often see yourself in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Like, You Know. . .''
</P>
<P>
   8:30 tonight on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's like, you know, OK.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
