<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-GAMBLING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS PUSH BAN ON INTERNET GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: RECASTS lede, pickup 2ndgraf: Internet gambling))  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under pressure from state law enforcement
officials, lawmakers on Tuesday renewed a push to enact legislation
that would ban gambling over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Internet gambling is estimated to be a $600 million per year
business and is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet gambling is a serious issue,'' Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.,
said during a Senate Judiciary panel hearing on the issue. Kyl,
chairman of the Technology, Terrorism, and Government Information
Subcommittee, estimates more than $1 billion will be gambled over
the Internet this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet gambling enhances the addictive nature of gambling
because it is so easy to do. You don't have to travel. You can just
log on to your computer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Legal gambling is a $50 billion annual industry that includes
casinos, slot machines, state lotteries and horse and dog-track
racing. It is regulated by states that have varying laws on
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys general have asked Congress for a federal ban on
Internet gambling because they argue they cannot police such
activity on a global network that defies state borders. They say
they cannot enforce Internet gambling even if states have their own
laws that ban such activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling is already one of the most regulated industries in
the world, yet the Internet of one of the most heavily unregulated
and inherently difficult phenomena to regulate in modern time,''
said Ohio Attorney General Betty Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular form of Internet wagering is sports betting,
but casino-type games are becoming more popular as the Internet
becomes faster.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal law makes placing a bet or sending gambling
information over telephone lines illegal, but the 1961 law predates
the Internet. Most computer users connect to the Internet through
phone lines but it is also possible to use cable television lines
and satellites, technically skirting federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect the Internet creates a loophole in gambling laws,''
said Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Justice Department charged 21 owners and managers
of Internet gambling firms with illegally violating the 1961
telephone law, but law enforcement officials say the federal law
still needs updating to give authorities a good chance of
successfully prosecuting Internet gambling operators. Eight people
pleaded guilty, one is fighting the charges and the others remain
at-large.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl plans to reintroduce legislation this week that would ban
gambling on the Internet. It would impose fines equal to the amount
that a business received over the Internet or $20,000, whichever is
greater, and impose prison sentences of up to four years on those
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would require Internet providers such as America
Online to cut service for any illegal gambling site upon a state or
federal court order. The Senate passed a similar bill 90-10 last
year but the issue never made it to the House floor. House
lawmakers are also expected to reintroduce the legislation this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Saum, the director of agent and gambling activities at the
National Collegiate Athletic Association, said Internet gambling is
attracting growing numbers of students who place sports wagers on
the Internet with credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``A growing consensus of research reveals that the rates of
pathological and problems gambling among college students are
higher than any other segment of the population,'' Saum said. Many
college students have access to the Internet as well as easy access
to credit cards that are marketed on campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Internet gambling sites typically require people to open an
account by providing a credit card number. Most sites require a
deposit of about $250 in order to play. Bets on sports teams, for
example, can range from 25 cents to hundreds of dollars. Betting
losses are charged to the credit card while winnings are posted as
credits, although in some cases gamblers report that they never
received their winnings.
</P>
<P>
   People can also play poker, blackjack and a variety of other
card and dice games with the click of a computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost 300 Internet gambling sites, up from about 15
just two years ago and recent studies have suggested that people
are increasingly becoming addicted to Internet gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl and other lawmakers admit that federal legislation won't
stop all Internet gambling, especially in cases where gambling
operators set up shop overseas, which is a common practice.
Countries like Antigua, Costa Rica and Grenada license Internet
gambling sites.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery argued that a federal ban on Internet gambling would
still be useful because ``a public stance of prohibition tells
consumers that they should be extremely wary of Internet
gambling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
