<HEADLINE>
$25 MILLION FOR USC MUSIC SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The University of Southern California announced on
Tuesday that its music school had received a $25-million gift from
the philanthropist Flora Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   The school said it was the largest donation ever made to a music
school in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sample, the university's president and a jazz drummer,
and Larry Livingston, the music school's dean, said the gift would
help finance the increasing efforts to train students and prepare
them for careers through market-oriented programs.
</P>
<P>
   The music school, which was founded in 1884, will be renamed for
Ms. Thornton, 85, the widow of Charles ``Tex'' Thornton, the
founder of Litton Industries, one of the country's largest
industrial conglomerates until it was broken up several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The university's music program has about 1,000 students. In
addition to classical music training it offers programs in such
areas as jazz, studio guitar performance and scoring for motion
pictures.
</P>
</TEXT>
