A1371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATECH-RANKING-COX     03-23 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATECH-RANKING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech among the best in engineering
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech, which has been striving to rise in
prominence among the nation's best engineering and technology
schools, took a step toward its goal this week.
</P>
<P>
   The College of Engineering, Tech's flagship, moved up to third
among the best of class in the annual survey by US News and World
Report, a list sometimes criticized but broadly consulted by
students, employers and competing schools.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 engineering schools, according to the list, include
MIT, Stanford, Georgia Tech, Michigan, California at Berkeley,
Illinois, Cal Tech, Carnegie-Mellon, Purdue and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tech can boast of high marks for the College of
Computer Science, ranked 13th in its category, and the DuPree
College of Management, which came in 33rd.
</P>
<P>
   Tech President G. Wayne Clough, who has led a drive to improve
the standing of the school, was pleased and gave credit to his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased that the impressive work of our faculty and
students is so highly regarded at the national level,'' Clough
said. ``I'm particularly pleased that one of the nation's most
unique programs, our joint program with Emory University in
biomedical engineering, was ranked among the finest.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article accompanying its voluminous listings of the
academic best, the weekly news magazine cited the means used to
evaluate the colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The publications uses statistical information such as the
achievement scores of students accepted for study, job placement
statistics, and various scores. It also employs an elaborate survey
of the opinions of competing institutions about who is best in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Clough, a Tech graduate who has taught at Stanford, a perennial
leader on the lists, has said that attaining prominence is
important in moving the school forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graduate education is extremely important as we continue to
transition to a high-tech, information-based economy,'' Clough
said, ``and the work conducted on this campus plays an important
role for the state and the nation as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The school is already being watched by the technology community.
Last week James Meindl, the Tech professor directing new research
into new chips, was recognized for his leadership by the
Semiconductor Industry Association at a Washington dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Clough acknowledged that academic surveys have their doubters
but put it in some perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important not to try to put too fine a point on these
things,'' he said. ``For instance, the distinction between being
the number one and number three ranked college is pretty difficult
to assess in scientific terms. But what pleases me about the
rankings has been the across-the-board improvement our schools have
shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
