<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NINE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NINE BELOW ZERO': LOVE AND FATE IN A LAND THAT BREATHES
DESPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By his own admission, Marvin Deernose, half Native American,
half something else, doesn't know a great deal about anything, but
he does know that we are not masters of our own lives, even if we
think we have control. He enunciates a kind of chaos theory about
the events of life. It's like that game in which you slide a penny
through a slot and it bounces down a series of nails that make it
go either left or right. ``The thing is, you can never tell where
it's going to end up at the bottom,'' Marvin says. ``Some little
thing comes along and shifts the penny off course by a millionth of
an inch and it comes out completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin is a former drug addict who has returned from California
to the small town in Montana where he grew up, hoping that there
will be something there on which he can anchor his lighter-than-air
existence. His notion about the illusory nature of meaningful
decisions seems on the mark very early on in Kevin Canty's smart,
gritty, unsentimental new novel, ``Nine Below Zero,'' in which love
and despair are set in a sorrowful, desperation-laden Western
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Early one morning, while driving his pickup home from his
girlfriend's house, Marvin sees an overturned Cadillac down an
embankment. The driver, suspended upside down by his seat belt, is
Henry Neihart, a former Montana senator whose life is saved by
Marvin's timely arrival. When Henry's granddaughter, Justine
Gallego, arrives in Montana from Oregon to take care of him, Henry,
now blind and not long for this earth, invites Marvin to dinner to
thank him. Justine and Marvin, two tormented and disillusioned
souls, form an attachment that is one part true passion, two parts
death wish, and the unfolding of their dangerous, jagged and
unplanned relationship provides Canty's narrative thread.
</P>
<P>
   Canty, whose previous novel was the highly praised ``Into the
Great Wide Open,'' has produced a new work finely tuned to the
precariousness and treachery of human need. Never mind that the
basic themes of ``Nine Below Zero'' are well worn: there is the
woman escaping the crumbling marriage, the ordinariness of
tarnished dreams. The love affair of Justine and Marvin is a kind
of duel between two late 20th-century emotional desperadoes who
sometimes seem to be imitating something they've read about the
inescapable soullessness of a world with plenty of avenues to
self-defeat and no God.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the return to the old homestead, in this case a
cattle ranch, for the expected death of the family patriarch, who
is Faulknerian in his brooding presence and his old-fashioned
authority. Some of the passages of ``Nine Below Zero'' are
reminiscent of ``While I Lay Dying.'' Henry is blind yet
sharp-eyed, a worthy match for his wayward granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   But Canty gives these themes new life with characters of
unobtrusive complexity and a setting that is the perfect physical
emblem of their longing and despair. Justine is married to an art
professor at the university who is a decent man, but their
relationship has never recovered from the death of their 4-year-old
son, Will, in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still dead,'' runs a refrain in the afflicted mind of Justine,
who, having suffered wounds herself, inflicts them on others with
barely a thought of remorse. ``Still dead, still dead, the little
voices said.'' Justine behaves badly, and while we understand the
sources of her self-centeredness, Canty's laudable aversion to
sentimentality keeps him from providing her with excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd done bad enough things, she'd been malicious and mean,
she'd stolen small things and even once _ once before Marvin _
she'd cheated on her husband, but never once in her life had she
done anything bad enough to merit the punishment she'd taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin is a very different creature, but, like Justine, he is
among the walking bruised and wounded. He is rootless. His memories
are of deer hunting with his father, but he has lost the Indian
lore and adopted instead an ironic demeanor tempered by bursts of
sincerity, as when he takes the daughter of his pre-Justine
girlfriend, a bartender at the Sportsman's Lounge, to midnight mass
on Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin is dissatisfied and contemptuous but he is also
self-aware, noticing for example that ``his capacity for
self-forgiveness was unlimited.'' He looks at others in Rivulet,
his Montana town, enviously and dismissively, the way that
Dostoevski's Dmitri Karamazov viewed Russian peasants, as happier
than he is but undignified by spiritual struggle. ``He imagined
them bound to each other with a thick web of connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivulet, he believes, is ``the place where people stayed when
they were too slow or stupid to get out, the place where people
came to when they got afraid of the big wide world.'' For him,
Justine is the rich woman, the senator's granddaughter, not an
inhabitant of the same planet as he. But for that very reason she
becomes his obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Canty's handling of their prickly relationship is distinguished
by his book's Montana background, an unforgiving place where the
cattle farms are hemmed in by tract houses with views of other
tract houses that have views of the mountains. His approach is also
distinguished by plain good writing, terse and profane. ``The
silence, as they sat and started to eat, was raw, half naked, full
of bare patches and open sores like a dilapidated calf,'' Canty
writes of Christmas dinner at Henry's. To get from silence to a
dilapidated calf is an achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Canty's story rolls inexorably toward danger, his characters
driven on in the spirit of Marvin's theories about human volition.
His figures live on the reckless extremes where every gesture seems
fateful, and Canty is in full command all the way to the end.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NINE BELOW ZERO'
</P>
<P>
   By Kevin Canty
</P>
<P>
   373 pages. Nan A. Talese/Doubleday. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
