<SLUG> BC-NY-JVC-JAZZ-FEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JVC JAZZ FESTIVAL TO OPEN WITH SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 27th annual JVC Jazz Festival on June 14 to 27
will present some of the leading names in jazz, rhythm-and-blues
and Latin music, with performers appearing in 36 places around New
York. The festival will open with a series of concerts at the
Sylvia and Danny Kaye Playhouse featuring mostly swing-era shows,
including ``Revisiting the Kingdom of Swing,'' produced by the
clarinetist Ken Peplowski.
</P>
<P>
   There will be concerts by some of the biggest figures in
mainstream jazz, including Herbie Hancock, Wayne Shorter, Dave
Brubeck and Oscar Peterson. Brazilian music will be honored in a
rare appearance by Caetano Veloso and by Carlinhos Brown. Latin
music will be represented by Ray Barretto and Kenny Burrell in a
salute to Duke Ellington, and by a concert by two Cuban pianists,
Chucho Valdes and Gonzalo Rubalcaba. Tito Puente will share the
stage with Poncho Sanchez and his band.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Note Records will celebrate its 60th anniversary with two
concerts, including a night of music by Greg Osby, Charlie Hunter
and Brian Blade. Other shows by younger musicians include double
bills of Diana Krall and Joshua Redman, and Dave Holland and Brad
Mehldau; a tribute to John Coltrane with Donald Harrison, Carl
Allen and others, and a tribute to Kenny Kirkland that will include
Branford Marsalis and Sting.
</P>
<P>
   Rhythm-and-blues will be represented by James Brown and Ray
Charles, and there will be a concert of three blues artists, Buddy
Guy, Jimmie Vaughan and Shemekla Copeland. Some of jazz's most
popular singers are also to appear, including Cassandra Wilson and
Shirley Horn, and a concert will feature Manhattan Transfer, Anita
O'Day and Kevin Mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the festival will include three free outdoor
concerts at Bryant Park; the performers have yet to be scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
