<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, March 24. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
PHOENIX-FINES (Phoenix) - Errant drivers who ignore traffic tickets
face bigger fines, suspended drivers' licenses, blemished credit,
and even jail. That isn't stopping thousands of Phoenix area
residents from cruising the streets with unpaid citations and
``what-can-they-do-to-me?'' attitudes. Phoenix court spokesman
Kevin Kane estimated that one cited driver in three ignores traffic
tickets and doesn't even show up in court. It's such a serous
problem that Phoenix's lawyers are developing a civil suit
collection process for traffic fines that could allow the city to
win judgements and place liens on drivers' homes, Kane said.
According to Phoenix court records, $162 million in unpaid fines _
predominantly traffic fines _ have been turned over to collection
agencies. By EDYTHE JENSEN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MODULAR-FOOD (Phoenix) - If you master the few basic cooking
techniques, you can interchange ingredients with complete abandon
and come up with a vast menu of dishes. I call it ``modular
cooking,'' and it means you can build up your own ``recipes'' from
whatever you have in your larder. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved in
the ``D'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
STAHL (Phoenix) - TV broadcaster Lesley Stahl dishes some dirt in
her new memoir, ``Reporting Live,'' but this is not a titillating,
moneymaking tell-all. It's the engaging story of one of the leading
journalists in network news, a woman who admits she benefited from
affirmative action and made the most of it. By BARBARA YOST. Story
moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ When they dream about what they want
to be when they grow up, don't all little boys and girls picture
themselves as . . . a Web site manager? Actuary, then? Computer
systems analyst? Software engineer? Mathematician? Uh, no. But
maybe they should, according to ``Jobs Rated Almanac,'' a new book
that rates the best and worst jobs in the country. By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
