<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-PAY-COX     03-23 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-PAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For young techies, Atlanta's the place
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Most high tech professionals look to Silicon Valley or New
York's Silicon Alley for fat paychecks and high-caliber careers.
Not Antony Chan or Ann Magruder.
</P>
<P>
   The Gen Xers say they can get all the Silicon Valley they want
in Atlanta _ along with a little Southern hospitality. And the
pay's not bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta seems to be a hotbed for opportunities. The people
I've talked to refer to it as 'Hotlanta'' or the Silicon Valley of
the East','' said Chan, whose pay will jump 30 percent when he
arrives in Atlanta next week from Sarasota, Fla. to work in
information technology consulting for Eagle Technology. The
24-year-old looked at Dallas, Chicago and New York before settling
on Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Vanderbilt University grad Magruder, 22, passed up
Houston and Nashville last year to work as a software consultant at
Atlanta software developer Manhattan Associates. She ruled out
Silicon Valley because ``just from talking with people who've been
there, I didn't really like the feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Money isn't enough for top IT talent. The deciding factor often
boils down to cost of living and comfort _ and that's where Atlanta
often gets the nod against rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta salaries _ especially those in information technology
_stack up rather impressively against other hotshot high tech
centers when cost of living, low unemployment and other quality of
life issues are considered, according to wage trackers and
recruiters. And that's a plus for worker-hungry firms in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A growing reliance on computer networks, heavy focus on Y2K
projects and the emergence of electronic commerce are pushing IT
salaries higher. Several recent wage surveys place Atlanta at or
near the top in IT pay.
</P>
<P>
   The metro area is an especially good drawing card for help-desk
managers, database administrators, systems programmers and network
administrators. A top help-desk manager can command close to
$80,000. A systems programmer and network administrator can expect
average annual paychecks of $70,542 and $60,832, respectively,
according to MATRIX Resources' latest quarterly hiring survey.
</P>
<P>
   Those three salaries topped those in Phoenix, Dallas and
Research Triangle Park in North Carolina. Professionals with
Internet and intranet skills and software and web developers also
are in big demand here, according to Robert Half International, a
specialty staffing service.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary look at hiring, RHI Consulting, a unit of
Robert Half International, found that the South Atlantic region,
which includes Georgia, had the strongest projected hiring in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what we're seeing on a national scale is a strong
demand for Internet services and Atlanta has the same demand,''
says Reesa Staten, research manager at RHI in Menlo Park, Calif.
``A lot of the companies in Atlanta are looking for IT
professionals to help them provide or develop Internet-based
application.'' RHI predicts IT salaries will rise 7.3 percent in
1999 nationwide, double the wage hike in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is not a bad first-stop for college grads. An IT grad
with a master's degree in information systems or computer science
can start at $30,000 to $40,000, wage trackers estimate.
</P>
<P>
   With 165,000 high tech jobs in more than 9,000 companies, Metro
Atlanta is among the top eight tech centers in the nation, and
ahead of other Southern tech centers such as Raleigh, N.C. and
Austin, Texas, according to the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce.
The metro area ranks even higher in pay and opportunity for high
tech workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's in the top five,'' says recruiter Rick Rice,
director of permanent placement at MATRIX.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really good job offer,'' said Magruder, 22, who has
had a pay raise since joining Manhattan Associates seven months
ago. ``Pay was very competitive with other cities.'' But the bottom
line for Magruder was comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a small town girl,'' said the Ocean Springs, Miss.,
native, who wouldn't divulge her salary. ``I thought Atlanta still
had the feeling of a small town, but offered all the amenities of a
big city. It just sort of comes down to what I call 'southern
comfort'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our wages are competitive on a national basis and extremely
competitive in the Southeast,'' said Sam Williams, president of the
Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce, which did a study last year
looking at Atlanta's high tech ranking nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's closest rivals in the South: Research Triangle Park,
Dallas and Fairfax County, Va., which recently beat suburban
Atlanta's Cobb County for a telecommunications center for America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas and Raleigh topped Atlanta in pay in seven of eight IT
management jobs tracked in MATRIX's latest quarterly hiring survey.
Dallas was the frontrunner in pay in 14 of the 18 nonmanagement
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research Triangle is closer to us in cost of living than
Northern Virginia,'' Williams said. ``Our advantage is R&AMP;D and the
intellectual community we have among the universities and
established companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Those looking to advance their career and income through high
tech giants such as IBM and Northern Telecom are more apt to be
drawn to Research Triangle Park. Atlanta is more likely to attract
entrepreneurially minded candidates drawn by the likes of
MindSpring, WebMD and ISS, industry experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on skills, level and complexity of the
equipment,'' said Jim Reese, Randstad's managing director of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Rice: ``I've never seen so many organizations looking for
so many people. I tell you, if you want to compete in Atlanta,
you've got to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
