u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TROPICANA-PACKAGING-N     03-23 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROPICANA-PACKAGING-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROPICANA INTRODUCES NEW PACKAGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW SAUER   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ In its ongoing quest for at-a-glance
identification, Tropicana has introduced new packaging for some of
its juices.
</P>
<P>
   The new packaging for the Season's Best line is aimed at
simplifying labeling and adding color to differentiate various
juices, pulp content and nutritional additives. The products will
debut in stores this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The new packaging identifies the juices as ``Pulp Free,'' ``With
Pulp,'' ``Calcium'' or ``Double Vitamin C.''
</P>
<P>
   To promote the new look, Tropicana plans to offer coupons for
Season's Best nationally in the Sunday editions of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Tropicana introduced new packaging for its Pure
Premium not-from-concentrate products shortly after the
announcement that the juice company was being bought by PepsiCo
Inc., based in Purchase, N.Y. The aim was similar. The new
packaging also included clearer charts of nutritional values and an
updated logo.
</P>
<P>
   PepsiCo said Tropicana posted a profit of $40 million on $722
million in sales for the fourth quarter of 1998. Sales rose 5
percent, driven largely by a continued growth in the Pure Premium
product. Tropicana's profits were dampened by increases in the cost
of oranges during an unusually small Florida orange harvest.
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Sauer writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.
This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
