<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-ANTHRAX-HNS &LR;      03-23 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-ANTHRAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLDIER DISCHARGED FOR REFUSING ANTHRAX VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A soldier who was twice demoted and then
discharged from the Army for refusing to take an anthrax
vaccination said Tuesday he had no regrets about the position he
took.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Garner Jr., 23, said he was reduced from specialist to
private and given an ``other than honorable discharge'' Monday
night, averting a military trial.
</P>
<P>
   A one-time infantryman and paratrooper with the 82nd Airborne
Division who had served in the honor guard at Fort Sam Houston, he
was facing a court-martial for refusing to take the vaccine for
anthrax, a highly lethal biological agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to get out of the Army like this,'' said Garner,
who fulfilled a boyhood dream by entering the service in 1994.
``But it's better than the alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   A sergeant with an impeccable record, Garner was reduced in rank
to specialist earlier this month for refusing to be inoculated
against anthrax before being reassigned to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Garner could have been jailed and given a dishonorable discharge
if convicted of refusing to follow an order, For Sam Houston
spokesman Phil Reidinger said. He would not reveal details of
Garner's discharge, citing the Privacy Act.
</P>
<P>
   Garner joined a small but growing number of military personnel
who have refused to take the vaccine, which is being given to the
nation's 2.4 million-strong force.
</P>
<P>
   Some 157 personnel have refused to take the vaccine, a series of
six shots given over 18 months, followed by an annual booster, Army
Medical Command spokeswoman Cynthia Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, seven of nine soldiers refusing to take the vaccine have
been discharged, with two other cases pending, Army spokeswoman
Elaine Kanellis said.
</P>
<P>
   No one yet has been court-martialed for refusing to take the
shots, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine has been given to 230,074 service members, civilians
and contractors, 86,748 from the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Those refusing to take the vaccine have raised fears it might
trigger Gulf War syndrome, a mysterious, often-crippling malady
that has struck thousands who helped drive Saddam Hussein's troops
from Kuwait in 1991. Some foes of the drug also have claimed it may
cause sterility and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon insists the vaccine is safe. Still, the Air Force
last week revealed it would form a team headed by its assistant
vice chief of staff, Lt. Gen. David Vesely, to review the drug.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force study is the only one of its kind among the
services, Defense Department spokesman Jim Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Garner said he had no regrets about his stand against the
vaccine. He will lose all service benefits and risks being denied
jobs in such fields as teaching and law enforcement because of his
discharge status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say their problems are going to get bigger as time wears
on,'' Garner said of military personnel refusing to take the
vaccine. ``I think mine are pretty much over.''
</P>
<P>
   Word that Garner was spared a trial and heading home was
gleefully received by his parents, who live near Lubbock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud as a peacock of him,'' ex-Army infantryman and
disabled veteran Robert Garner Sr., 47, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what they might say about him,'' said the
soldier's mother, Jeannie Garner, 48. ``He's not a coward or
anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's just something he feels real strong about and I
agree with him,'' she continued. ``I've always told him, `Bobby, go
with your conscience.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
