A1396 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFINERY-CANCER-TWOTA     03-23 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFINERY-CANCER-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE TO LOOK FURTHER INTO BRAIN CANCER CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUGAR CREEK, Mo. _ Residents near the former Amoco Oil Co.
refinery in Sugar Creek may have a greater-than-expected risk of
developing brain cancer, according to a Missouri Department of
Health study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined cancer cases between 1985 and 1997 in two ZIP
codes _ 64053 and 64054, which include parts of Independence and
Sugar Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The study, state officials stressed, is considered preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, residents were concerned and confused by the
findings. State officials scheduled a public meeting for Tuesday at
Lanard Hall in Sugar Creek to further explain the study.
</P>
<P>
   More analysis will be required, the study cautioned, to
determine whether an excess number of brain cancers actually
exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know that we've found more brain cancer cases, not
deaths, than we expected to find,'' said Marianne Ronan, chief of
Missouri's bureau of cancer control. ``With these preliminary
results, we need to keep looking in Sugar Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's author, Eduardo Simoes, said Monday that the number
of brain cancers found in the study was not extremely elevated. But
it was high enough to warrant further study.
</P>
<P>
   The study found 15 brain cancer cases in the two ZIP codes; it
expected to find only about seven.
</P>
<P>
   The probability of finding such an elevated number, Simoes said,
is about 5 in 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department's study concluded that it should elevate
its inquiry to the next level, a process known as Level 3 that
state health officials began to use this year. It marks the first
time the Missouri Health Department has ordered such a study.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution from the old refinery, which Amoco operated from 1904
to 1982, has migrated into neighborhoods in Sugar Creek and
Independence. The pollution includes chemicals such as benzene,
which has been linked to leukemia in humans. Although the causes of
brain cancer are unknown, it has been linked to exposure to
chemicals in the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco recently offered owners of about 130 properties in a
polluted area 154 percent of their property's fair market value
plus $5,000 in moving expenses. Residents also are involved in a
federal class-action settlement approved last summer. The case is
now on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Upgrading the state's investigation to Level 3 means the
geographic area in question will be expanded. As part of its new
study, Simoes said, the state will look at cancer cases in Jackson
County and possibly parts of Clay County to make sure an excess of
brain cancer does not exist in a wider area than Sugar Creek.
</P>
<P>
   He also will consider whether to widen the study area around the
refinery, although he said he thought the possible exposures to
pollution from the refinery were greatest in the two ZIP code areas
studied.
</P>
<P>
   The study released Monday did not find much evidence of elevated
numbers or clusters of leukemia and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma _ two
other cancers associated with exposure to chemicals in the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Further analysis, the study concluded, would be required to
determine whether clusters of the three types of cancers exist in
the Sugar Creek area. Although the possibility cannot be ruled out,
it is unlikely that such clusters will be proved, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's cancer inquiry process, a study can be
elevated to Level 3 if there's some evidence of a cancer cluster or
a heightened concern in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studies are showing some smoke,'' said Simoes, a Health
Department physician and epidemiologist. ``And it's a highly
publicized thing now. There's a lot of concern in the population.
And we can't be ignorant of (the concern) now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put all that together and we're justified in doing further
study.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morantz, a Kansas City physician who has treated many
Sugar Creek brain cancer patients, has launched with the University
of Kansas his own study of brain cancer incidence in the Sugar
Creek area. Jackson County is helping to pay for the study.
</P>
<P>
   Morantz said Monday that he agreed it would be proper to elevate
the state's study to a higher level given the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough suspicion to go on to Level 3,'' Morantz said.
</P>
<P>
   In his ongoing study, Morantz said 39 brain tumors between 1986
and 1996 have been found. But his study is looking at a wider
geographic area _ five ZIP codes near the former refinery site.
</P>
<P>
   In Jefferson City on Monday, Ronan said she would understand if
Sugar Creek residents were a bit baffled by the new study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the community may still have frustration with our
process,'' Ronan said. ``But we want to give them the best
information we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this information, while there are a lot of maybes tied in
there, the only way we'll know if there's more than maybes is to
continue following our process.''
</P>
<P>
   It's very difficult, she added, to determine whether a cancer
cluster exists. It's even more difficult to know whether it's
linked to any particular source. ... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
