<HEADER>
A1400 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIOSTATE-PROFILE     03-23 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOSTATE-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Penn plays prophet, catalyst
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He boldly predicted that Ohio State would go where no current
Buckeye had gone before. But other than a return to the NCAA
Tournament, even Scoonie Penn had no inkling Columbus would
rediscover the old world order in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought he was off the wall,'' Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien
said about his point guard's forecast that the Buckeyes would reach
the NCAA's for the first time in 1992. ''I just wanted us to be
better than we were a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Penn was a practice phenomenon but game-day
spectator who could only watch as Ohio State suffered one of the
worst winters in Buckeye basketball history. ''Sitting out last
season was very tough,'' said Penn, who had helped take O'Brien and
Boston College to two NCAA's, then sat out last season after
following his coach from BC to Columbus, Ohio. ''The hardest part
was just watching the guys go 8-22, knowing there was nothing I
could do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 22 losses tied the school record for futility. In the last
four of their five consecutive losing seasons, the Buckeyes were
34-88. But before he had fired a single 3-pointer in Big Ten play,
Scoonie vowed that Ohio State was NCAA material.
</P>
<P>
   ''Scoonie's mentality was he's played two years in college and
two years he's played in the NCAA Tournament,'' O'Brien said. ''So
his mentality is when March comes around, you're in the NCAA
Tournament. But he obviously knows more about this team than I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   However, not even Scoonie foresaw this. After a second-place
finish in the Big Ten, the Buckeyes advanced to the Sweet 16. Two
victories followed in the South Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Those wins advanced Ohio State beyond even Scoonie's wildest
dreams _ into Saturday's Final Four semifinal against UConn. Of the
four teams in St. Petersburg, only the fourth-seeded Buckeyes
aren't a No. 1 seed. But their improvement from eight wins last
season to 27 this season is the best for any NCAA Tournament team.
This team has become the school's most celebrated since the early
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the state of Ohio was the epicenter of the college
hoops universe. With three sophomore starters including Jerry Lucas
and John Havlicek, Ohio State beat Cal for the 1960 NCAA title. The
Buckeyes were national runners-up to Cincinnati in 1961 and '62.
After the '68 team, however, it would be 31 years before Ohio State
finally returned to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst? Scoonie. ''He's the difference in that team from
last year to this year,'' Auburn coach Cliff Ellis said after Penn,
with four fouls and his team trailing 52-46 with 10:14 left, scored
13 of his 19 second-half points, and 26 total, to oust Auburn.
''They won eight games a year ago and they've won how many this
year? He's not a good guard; he's a great guard. He's their heart
and soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Salem, Mass., Penn was 5-feet-9 as a high-school
freshman and has grown just an inch since. He was the Massachusetts
state player of the year as a high-school senior and the 1996 Big
East freshman of the year. He led BC to the '97 Big East Tournament
title. But then O'Brien left his alma mater after 11 years as head
coach. He was dismayed after losing a couple of prize recruits to
heightened admissions requirements after a football gambling
scandal at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ''The previous two years, I had a good time,'' Penn said. ``But
the way the program was going and where it was headed, I wasn't
sure I wanted to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Penn waited his turn in Columbus, practicing with the
Buckeyes and sneak-previewing the skills that would make him this
season's Big Ten co-player of the year. In practice, Scoonie and
any four subs drubbed the starters. Regularly. The one Buckeye who
stuck with Scoonie: Michael Redd, the 6-foot-6 hometown left-hander
and one of the sweetest-shooting guards in the college game. ''I'd
never heard of the kid,'' Penn said. ''But that first day they
opened the gym, I said, 'This kid can play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The two guards played one on one and went hard in drills. ''He'd
push me around; I'd push him around,'' Penn said. ''Sometimes, we'd
get into it _ pushing, somebody elbowing somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ohio State has elbowed its way back into the Final Four.
Penn and Redd combined for 48 points against Auburn and 42 against
St. John's. After Penn landed hard in the regular-season finale at
Penn State and bruising his backside, his shooting suffered; he hit
just 31 per cent of his shots _ 15 for 48 _ in the next four games
and then started out 1 for 6 against Auburn, although he finished 9
for 16.
</P>
<P>
   Then he helped finish off St. John's with 22 points, eight
assists and three critical free throws in the last 44.4 seconds.
''I think my teammates look to me for that,'' Penn said. ''When
things get tough, I think I'm the guy with the ball in my hands.
I'm not afraid to take the tough shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Or speak his mind.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO STATE UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   Location: Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Final Fours: Nine (1939, 1944, 1945, 1946, 1960, 1961, 1962,
1968, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   National titles: One (1960).
</P>
<P>
   Record: 27-8.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Jim O'Brien is 35-30 in two seasons at Ohio State,
270-247 overall.
</P>
<P>
   How they got there: Ohio State, the fourth seed in the South,
defeated Murray State 72-58 and Detroit 75-44 in the first two
rounds at Indianapolis, beat top seed Auburn 72-64 in the region
semifinals and edged third seed St. John's 77-74 in the region
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's games
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut vs. Ohio State, 5:42 p.m. (CBS)
</P>
<P>
   Duke vs. Michigan State, 8:12 p.m. (CBS)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
