<HEADER>
A1402 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFINERY-CANCER-2NDTA     03-23 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFINERY-CANCER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUGAR CREEK, Mo. ... any particular source.
</P>
<P>
   Last July longtime Sugar Creek residents Bud and Barbara
Chappell contacted state and federal health officials. They were
concerned about what they thought was an unusually high number of
brain cancers in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Chappells have been concerned about the refinery
site's pollution and its slow cleanup. They asked state officials
to study the cancer cases.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said in October that they would conduct a
scientific investigation into whether there was an excess of cancer
in the Sugar Creek area. They said they had already confirmed 36
cancer cases in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The study released Monday was the result of that scientific
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Simoes said he hoped he would be able to complete the Level 3
study this year. If it confirmed the excess brain cancer risk,
further study would be required to determine a possible cause, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, the Chappells gathered in their living room
with friends and their attorney, Beverlee Roper, to await delivery
of the state report.
</P>
<P>
   The results were both satisfying and disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   What mattered most was that the study meant they still had no
clear answer to their health questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to know,'' said Barbara Chappell, ``is whether we
should live here or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Chappell, who is a candidate for the city's Board of
Aldermen, said the report was written in such a technical style
that it would be difficult for almost anyone to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lost me after `Dear Mr. and Mrs. Chappell,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Haman, another alderman candidate pushing for faster
cleanup of the former refinery site, read the report with the
Chappells and Roper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they leaving out 64050?'' Haman asked. ``By doing that
they're not looking at the plant's air emissions,'' which would
have blown west toward that ZIP code area.
</P>
<P>
   Later, under the glare of a television camera, the emotion
welled in Barbara Chappell's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She thought of a neighbor whose son died of brain cancer, and
how her friend longs to know whether the tumor was related to the
neighborhood's pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't given her an answer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's report was not formally discussed during Monday
night's Sugar Creek Board of Aldermen meeting.
</P>
<P>
   However, much of the meeting featured debate between board
members and spectators who criticized the city's relationship with
Amoco over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Chappell asked Assistant City Attorney Bob Buckley whether
he stood to receive legal fees in the buyout program offered by
Amoco. Buckley said that he did not.
</P>
<P>
   Haman suggested that the city had been careless in its relations
with Amoco, adding that visitors inspecting the city's documents
pertaining to Amoco allegedly had found several sealed and
unopened.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Creek Mayor Charles Dumsky denied that.
</P>
<P>
   Dumsky, who received a summary of the state report Monday, said
after the meeting that he welcomed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a final answer,'' he said. ``I want closure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
