</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times is planning 9 columns of coverage on
KOSOVO for the paper of Wednesday, March 24. These stories are
scheduled to move tonight in The New York Times News Service report
in the ``i'' news file.
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times News Service Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone:
(888) 346-9867; e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ NATO is poised to begin air strikes
against Serbia after the Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic, in
talks with U.S. envoy, refused to agree to a ceasefire in the
province of Kosovo. By Jane Perlez. (Eds.: note dateline and byline
changes.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and locator map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS (Berlin) _ From the first encounter between
Richard Holbrooke and Slobodan Milosevic in 1995 through many
desperate sessions at the Bosnian peace talks in Dayton to the
fruitless talks in the Serbian capital that ended Tuesday, a
particularly charged chemistry has existed between the Yugoslav
leader and America's Balkan envoy: a web of repulsion, rancor and
grudging respect. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS (Brussels, Belgium) _ The Yugoslav armed
forces and paramilitary police units that NATO warplanes would
attack to try to stop the fighting in Kosovo are regarded as tough
and well-equipped, and far more powerful than the Bosnian Serb
forces that allied warplanes bombed four years ago. Before allied
warplanes would attack any of these forces, allied officers said,
NATO commanders would try first to destroy as much as possible of
Serbia's considerable ability to shoot down planes with its
sophisticated integrated air defense system. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With map locating both NATO and Yugoslav troops and military
installations.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV (Washington) _ Shortly after 1 p.m. Tuesday, an
angry Russian prime minister en route to Washington ordered his
pilot to turn his Ilyushin airliner around and return to Moscow.
Primakov was in an untenable situation, having argued for months
against the use of force against Moscow's allies in Serbia.
Whatever he might have hoped to gain from three days of meetings
with Vice President Gore, President Clinton, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and international financial officials, was now
overshadowed by the likelihood of U.S.-led military action in the
Balkans. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Did Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic miscalculate in talks with Richard Holbrooke?
``Maybe he didn't,'' a senior U.S. official said, suggesting three
possibilities. ``Maybe he thinks we're bluffing, or he thinks he
can't survive if he agrees to the Rambouillet accords, even
modified, and especially can't agree to a foreign force on Yugoslav
soil because of history or politics or whatever, or third, he's
still planning some sort of deal at some point in this process.''
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The Yugoslav foreign
minister said Tuesday that his country could not accept a ``biased
policy of diktat'' from the West, whose bombing would violate
international law. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Monday night, Serbian police
raided this suburb on the southern end of Kosovo's capital,
Pristina The panic in this suburb is just one sign of the increased
tension in the city. Both Serbs and ethnic Albanians are
frightened, as the violence of the war in the countryside has begun
encroaching upon the city, and NATO air strikes appeared imminent.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, this Kosovo-related story is skedded:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMS (Moscow) _ Azerbaijan seized a Russian cargo plane
carrying six MiGs, saying the cargo was headed for Yugoslavia.
Russia said the plane was headed to Slovakia. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
