<HEADLINE>
THE GIVE AND TAKE OF CONVERSATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   D &UR; rew Barrymore &LR;  has a heart-to-heart with  &UR; Liv Tyler &LR;  in the
latest issue of Interview magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What were your favorite television shows growing up?''
Barrymore asks Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Dukes of Hazzard,' `He-Man' and `The Brady Bunch,' ''
answers Tyler. ``I remember when I was in first grade, I was living
with my grandparents in Virginia at the time, and they cut my
television privileges back to like half an hour. And I remember
crying because that meant I couldn't watch `He-Man' and `The Dukes
of Hazzard.' It was the biggest crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so amazing,'' says the analytical Barrymore, ``that
there's a time in your life when the big issues are getting to
watch television shows, and then you get older and the problems are
so BIG.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Tyler replies: ``What were your favorite shows?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING SOME PRESIDENTIAL LESSONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about a run for the presidency, Governor  &UR; George W. &LR; 
 &UR; Bush &LR;  of Texas has embarked on a cram course on presidential
matters _ like foreign policy _ reported the New York Times last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians in both parties said they had never seen such a
comprehensive and elaborate undertaking,'' said the story,
``particularly this early in a campaign. There may never have been
a `serious' candidate who needed it more.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sedge Thomson &LR;  figured out _ and we confirmed with the New York
Times _ that it was the last sentence of that paragraph that was
the subject of Friday's Editor's Note: ``As published,'' said the
note, ``the article included an opinionated sentence casting doubt
on his mastery of those issues. The sentence was sent as a message
between editors after the article was written, and the reporters
were never aware of it. The comment was typed in a nonprinting
computer script, but converted into print through a command
error.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Lauren Bush &LR; , 14-year-old niece of George W.,
granddaughter of  &UR; George &LR;  and daughter of  &UR; Neil &LR; , has begun a
career as a model, but W reports that her mother,  &UR; Sharon Bush &LR; ,
won't let her undress in semi-public, as models do, with male
hairdressers and other professionals looking on. Photographer
 &UR; Bruce Weber &LR;  said of her: ``She's pretty enough to be a Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Rhena Schweitzer &LR; , 80-year-old daughter of  &UR; Albert &LR; 
 &UR; Schweitzer &LR; , was in town over the weekend visiting  &UR; Gene &LR; 
 &UR; Schoenfeld &LR; , who took her to see the San Francisco Ballet's
performance of ``Lambarena,'' based on the work of her father.
Before the performance,  &UR; Evelyn Cisneros &LR;  told Rhena _ whose father
had thwarted her girlhood desire to be a dancer _ that she would be
dancing especially for her.
</P>
<P>
   _ Divorce papers filed on behalf of violinist  &UR; Pinchas &LR; 
 &UR; Zukerman &LR;  against his wife of 13 years, actress  &UR; Tuesday Weld &LR; ,
charge that she didn't show enough interest in his work. Zukerman
quotes Weld as saying, ``Why do I need to go to another concert
when I've heard the piece before?''
</P>
<P>
   Weld's lawyer,  &UR; Norman Sheresky &LR; , admitted to New York magazine,
``She did get a little tired of the same concerts all the time,''
but indicated the complaint was minor.
</P>
<P>
   _ An ad placed by a Palo Alto woman in the latest issue of the
New York Review of Books, &LR;  seeks an ``escort to an elegant
millennium party.'' The seeker wants a 60ish man ``who is willing
to devote a year to perfect our dance steps.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked by Movieline magazine to name another actress with whom
she'd like to work,  &UR; Sissy Spacek &LR;  named  &UR; Meryl Streep &LR;  and
 &UR; Glenn Close &LR; . ``Can't someone find a movie to plot all of us in
together? They can cast  &UR; Leonardo DiCaprio &LR;  as one of our sons so
all the young girls will come see it.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Joseph Fera &LR;  says he learned on a ``Charlie Rose'' show the
night  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR;  died that the baseball great and  &UR; Henry &LR; 
 &UR; Kissinger &LR;  had been introduced years ago and ``became fast
friends,'' thus Henry the K's possible role as a eulogizer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Minnesota Governor  &UR; Jesse Ventura &LR; , attending the Independent
Spirit Awards in Hollywood last week, was asked whether he was
excited to meet so many movie stars. ``I think it's more fun for
them to be around me,'' he said, in remarks quoted in the Los
Angeles Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
