<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-FLYER-TESTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tests on Wright Flyer give scientists surprises
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Wind tunnel tests of a full-scale Wright Flyer
replica wrapped up in California last week with surprises for both
airplane researchers and wind tunnel operators.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer researchers from the Los Angeles section of the
American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics spent from March
1 through March 18 assembling and testing a replica of the
wood-and-fabric machine the Wright brothers used to make the
world's first powered flights in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers, mostly retired aerospace scientists and
engineers, worked with the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration to test the flyer in a giant wind tunnel at the NASA
Ames Research Center on Moffett Field in Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   The AIAA research team, dubbed the Wright Flyer Project,
collected data on how the flyer behaved in winds of up to 30 miles
per hour, the speed at which Daytonians Orville and Wilbur Wright
flew the original craft in strong head winds at Kitty Hawk, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some surprises,'' AIAA wind tunnel engineer Rich Grimm
said Monday from his home near Los Angeles. ``The cloth wings
seemed to change shape more than we expected under aerodynamic
loads.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant the flyer would have flown a little differently than
predicted by previous tests with rigid, small-scale models. It also
means the original flyer's performance likely was different than
previous research has indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The group has just begun to refine and analyze the wind tunnel
data, Grimm said. Besides gathering historical information, the
project team hopes to use the data to build a more stable replica
of the Wright Flyer and fly it at Kitty Hawk on the 100th
anniversary of powered flight in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   NASA researchers also discovered their cavernous wind tunnel,
designed to test large-scale aircraft models at speeds up to 350
miles per hour, develops eddies in its otherwise smooth air flow at
low speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a huge effect,'' wind tunnel manager Pete Zell said,
but it caused the relatively lightweight flyer to rock from side to
side during tests. As a result, some tests had to be run for
minutes at a time instead of seconds to gather enough data to
cancel out the effects of the unstable air.
</P>
<P>
   Zell said the flyer was removed from the tunnel on Monday.
Project member Marilyn Ramsey said it will be reassembled and put
on display in an aviation museum at the Federal Aviation
Administration's Los Angeles-area regional office.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
