<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T'S DEBT OFFER DRAWS INVESTORS' ATTENTION AS BOND PRICES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of government securities rose modestly Tuesday
as investors focused primarily on AT&AMP;T Corp.'s record-setting
global bond offering priced earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds received a lift from the record corporate offering as
securities firms that underwrote the corporate debt bought back
Treasuries they had sold as a hedge against losses. Also, a
slumping stock market added to the buying momentum as investors
sought refuge from equities.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond rose 12/32, to 95 26/32.
Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
fell to 5.54 percent, from 5.57 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   To help meet strong investor demand, AT&AMP;T sold $8 billion of
debt in a global offering, increasing the size of the deal from an
announced $7 billion on Monday, which was up from the initially
planned offering of $5 billion to $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Appetite for the blue-chip giant's deal, which was underwritten
by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Salomon Smith Barney Inc., far
outstripped supply and garnered about $12 billion in orders,
according to some traders.
</P>
<P>
   The company had filed registration statements with the
Securities and Exchange Commission for permission to sell as much
as $13 billion of debt and plans to borrow more this year, possibly
$3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal included $2 billion of five-year notes, up from $1.75
billion and priced to yield 5.735 percent, or about 64 basis points
more than Treasury securities with a similar maturity; $3 billion
of 10-year notes, up from $2.5 billion at a yield of 6.032 percent,
or 84 basis points over notes with a similar maturity; and $3
billion of 30-year bonds, up from $2.75 billion that were priced to
yield 6.582 percent, or about 94 basis points over similar
Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   When it was priced, AT&AMP;T's debt offering became the largest
investment-grade deal ever in the corporate bond market. And
because of its size, it took on bellwether status as it becomes
part of the Lehman bond index, which fueled demand from
institutional investors who felt they must have exposure to it.
</P>
<P>
   Before AT&AMP;T's offering, Worldcom Inc., now known as MCI
Worldcom, held the record for the largest high-grade deal after
selling $6.1 billion in debt last August.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Joseph Battipaglia, chief investment strategist for Gruntal &AMP;
Co., said the deal came in at a slight discount to where other
single-A-rated corporate bonds are trading. ``Yes, the securities
have fair market value, which is where you would expect them to be
selling if you wanted them to move from off the shelf and into the
hands of investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew C. Palmer, a managing director and corporate bond manager
at ASB Capital Management, a company in Washington with more than
$6 billion in bonds, said, ``After all the AT&AMP;T issue had been
expected for quite some time and the bonds had been discounted over
and over again, tightened a bit when they became too cheap, than
discounted again. Right now I think the deal has a fair market
value.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, based in New York, was in the market to sell bonds for the
first time in almost four years to help pay for recent
acquisitions. ``This is going to be a bellwether corporate bond,''
Palmer said. ``It will also be a popular deal for nondomestic
investors who tend to buy the names they know, and AT&AMP;T they
know.'' Traders said another reason for the good attraction was
that there is little likelihood that the company will turn into a
high-yield company overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently completed its $32 billion purchase of
Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's second-largest cable
provider. It is also paying $5.5 billion to a TCI unit, Liberty
Media, and acquiring IBM's global network business for $5 billion
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's debt is rated A-1 by Moody's Investors Service and AA- by
the Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury will auction $15 billion of new two-year notes
Wednesday that were being offered at a price to yield of 4.97
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
