<SLUG> BC-DOLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE STRESSES MORAL RENEWAL IN TEXAS SPEECH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Republican presidential prospect Elizabeth
Hanford Dole told a gathering of oilmen Tuesday that Americans must
recover the core values of the past to meet the challenges of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never return to an age of innocence,'' Dole said. ``But
we can move on to an age of rediscovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the annual meeting of the National Petrochemical and
Refiners Association, Dole paid tribute to America's recent social
and technological revolutions but said change has often come at the
expense of virtue.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks, Dole's first in Texas since announcing her
presidential exploratory committee March 10, underscored the
decidedly measured approach the former head of the Red Cross and
erstwhile Cabinet member is taking in this precampaign phase.
</P>
<P>
   She made no mention of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, her closest
rival in the GOP presidential race. Instead, she sounded themes
similar to the ones she used in a speech to a gathering of
dermatologists Monday in New Orleans. In some cases Dole even used
the same language.
</P>
<P>
   She took only two questions, both of them from an official of
the petrochemical group and kept the news media at a considerable
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from the podium to center stage throughout her 40-minute
address, Dole seemed relaxed but well rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of Bob Dole, former Senate Republican leader and the
1996 GOP presidential nominee, Elizabeth Dole routinely places
second to Bush in polls around the country. Bush has formed an
exploratory committee, but has not yet formally entered the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than address the apparent front-runner in his home
state, Dole invoked long-standing GOP themes such as a less
powerful federal government. She called Washington ``too big, too
bloated and too bureaucratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole also focused on foreign policy in response to a question
about America's biggest challenge. On the day that NATO prepared
airstrikes in Kosovo, she expressed concern over North Korea's
nuclear strike capability and said the United States must quickly
develop a missile-defense system.
</P>
<P>
   While never elected to public office, Dole said her experience
at the Red Cross and as a member of the Reagan and Bush
administrations has prepared her for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Dole called public education a top priority, but while she
mentioned the need for academic reform, Dole also stressed a
broader theme of moral renewal. The hope of the nation, she said,
is ``the conscience and character of its children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never go back, not an inch,'' said Dole, especially
mindful of the women's movement. At the same time, Dole said the
changes of the past 40 years have yielded ``a pornographic culture
and a society that no longer blushes.''
</P>
<P>
   She lamented the plight of the nation's youth, recalling a
generation of children who lived ``in homes whose locks we didn't
turn.'' The remark was not unlike ones Kansas native Bob Dole made
during his 1996 run for the presidency, when he too saw yesterday's
values as an answer for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they lack is living in a world without worry,'' Dole said
of America's youth. ``In seeking to make America better, we've
neglected what's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole added that the nation's drug problem must be addressed with
a ``moral seriousness'' and said the president of the United States
must use the bully pulpit to convince kids that ``drugs aren't
cool, they kill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My passion doesn't come from polls,'' said Dole. ``We need
leadership on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
