<HEADER>
A1432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-MUSIC-CONFERENCE-     03-23 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-MUSIC-CONFERENCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH TIMES: ROCK'S INCUBATOR TURNS DOWN THE HEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the past at the South by Southwest
convention, for years the rock business' most important cavalcade
of performances and panel discussions, talent scouts came looking
for tomorrow's rock stars.
</P>
<P>
   Acts like Fastball, Lisa Loeb, the Presidents of the United
States of America, Cake and even Hanson set deals in motion here.
But something was different this year.
</P>
<P>
   The change was best represented by the agenda of one scout from
a major label. Speaking on condition of anonymity, he said he had
come here not to sign a band, but to prevent his label from signing
one. The group's contract with his label had expired, he said, and
he wanted to make sure no one else at the label tried to renew it
at the band's showcase performance.
</P>
<P>
   During this convention, held from Wednesday to Saturday, it was
impossible to ignore the effects of record-label consolidation and
rock's cyclical fall from commercial grace. The atmosphere was like
Bourbon Street in New Orleans after Mardi Gras but when even the
die-hard revelers have gone home, leaving the streets dirty and
desolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd see the day when I didn't care about Sonic
Youth,'' said another major-label talent scout, referring to the
seminal New York alternative rock band. ``It's sad what's happened
to indie rock. This is the least exciting year I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it went. The number of major labels at South by Southwest
severely dwindled this year, with almost no top executives in
attendance and many lesser employees opting to stay home. Even the
bulk of smaller independent labels didn't bother to bring their
most popular bands, only the struggling ones.
</P>
<P>
   The convention center and showcases for unsigned bands seemed
emptier than usual, though a conference spokeswoman said attendance
was up slightly from last year's 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   And most tellingly, a new music-industry class emerged: the
great unemployed, laid off as a result of consolidation, chiefly
Universal's recent acquisition of Polygram. Most were trying to
find new opportunities but ended up just sharing war tales, like
the Mercury employee who remembered colleagues being summoned to a
room 50 at a time to get laid off one January afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Nighttime concert showcases were no longer just for unsigned
bands: they were also for former Polygram bands like Radish and
Robbie Fulks, both of whose record deals were recently terminated.
</P>
<P>
   Overall there was a sense that festival goers were no longer on
the cutting edge. Speakers at panels agreed that the biggest thing
happening in music today was setting beats to rhymes: rap. Yet here
they all were, holding the rock banner in the air and wondering
when people would start noticing it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is booming, the Internet is popping, the Dow is
reaching 10,000, but the music industry is acting like it's waking
up from a really bad hangover,'' said Andrew Rasiej, who heads the
New York Nightlife Association and a charity called Mouse, which
brings computer networks to schools.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This feeling of neglect, of having missed the bus, was also
common at a separate convention in Miami, the Winter Music
Conference, a five-day event for electronic dance music that ended
on the day South by Southwest began.
</P>
<P>
   When alternative rock began to wane commercially three years
ago, major labels looked to electronic dance music to plug the gap.
Instead, as pop veered back into the middle of the road with the
Spice Girls, Hanson and fey boy bands like the Backstreet Boys, the
contrarian fringe movement came not from white music (the rock of
South by Southwest or the electronica of Miami) but from black
music, showing just how little control the established industry _
denizens of conventions like these _ has over pop success.
</P>
<P>
   (To be fair, the Miami conference isn't all electronica: it's
also known for its component of Latin dance music, a genre with
sales on an upswing and one that the established business is even
less equipped to deal with than rap, despite a few visionary
executives who began taking crash courses in Spanish this winter.)
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a viable rock undercurrent in some ways made South
by Southwest a success, signaling an end to mercenary concert going
and a return to music for music's sake. Some at the conference
simply chose to see the group Built to Spill perform three nights
in a row, and they were better off for it.
</P>
<P>
   This ever-changing Boise, Idaho, group boasted its strongest
lineup, blurring lyrically astute songs into sonically intense
guitar solos and proving itself to be one of the closest things
alternative rock has to a classic rock band.
</P>
<P>
   Younger performers like Diane Izzo, a songwriter from Chicago,
probably would have been the object of a major label bidding war
three years ago, hailed as the next P.J. Harvey or Liz Phair.
Instead, Ms. Izzo played her winningly dark-minded rock this year
in a half-empty club with few record executives in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to Austin's deep well of songwriters, it was
possible to go out every night and hear great music without ever
attending a show by anyone under 35. (As talent scouts will tell
you, with the same conviction with which they once said that rap
was dead, no one over 35 is going to be the next big thing.)
</P>
<P>
   Semi-reclusive artists well past their showcasing days, like Tom
Waits and Jeff Beck, flew into town in hopes of building excitement
for their new albums. The back garden of a Mexican restaurant
played host to a high-spirited jam including Joe Ely, Freddy
Fender, Rosie Flores and Ruben Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   A fatigued Lucinda Williams turned in a lackluster performance
in support of a terrific album. Guy Clark, Clarence (Gatemouth)
Brown and the always talented, always inconsistent Terry Allen _
with a guest appearance by David Byrne _ performed to a packed
house at Liberty Lunch. (Willie Nelson was scheduled to perform
with Leon Russell, but the show was rained out.) Even Wanda
Jackson, the 61-year-old rockabilly queen, played one night at 1
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to past years, when the shows with the most buzz
(jargon that conjures images of both swarming and irritation) were
by young alternative rock bands, this year's most talked-about show
was by a pop star, Robbie Williams, formerly of Take That. He
erected an elaborate arena-ready performance in the tiny garden of
an Austin club to kick off an American campaign that he hopes will
make him as big a celebrity here as he is in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   As conference goers complained of the lack of hip-hop, only a
handful of people ended up at the best of the week's few rap shows,
by the savvy-rhyming Ugly Duckling, of Long Beach, Calif., at Bob
Popular. They performed as teen-agers outside took turns
demonstrating a loose-limbed style of break-dancing as part of what
they called the Texas swing-hop scene.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting shows were the oddest. Todos los Manos were
a German group featuring members from Chile, Brazil and Hamburg
singing in Spanish, Portuguese, French and English (but not German)
and playing hard-driving songs that switched styles every 30
seconds. Bellatrix, a mostly female quintet from Iceland, packed
Bob Popular one night, mixing violin, drum loops, and wailing,
biting avant-rock vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese bands once again matched their American counterparts in
talent and diversity, from the big-beat dance-rockers Boom Boom
Satellites to the obsessive record collector known as Fantastic
Plastic Machine to the guitar-bashing girl pop group Seagull
Screaming Kiss Her Kiss Her.
</P>
<P>
   Despite so much good music, many people left the conference with
the sinking feeling of having spent a week treading water with a
rock tied to their legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to give the music back to the people,'' Lucinda
Williams said in a keynote speech that began the conference. ``I
don't think major labels are working anymore.'' On a panel on the
closing day of the conference, David Byrne echoed her sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   This moment in pop may seem like a time of low spirits and
layoffs. But in retrospect it may prove to be one of the most
exciting periods to be involved, especially with the changes that
will be wrought by the Internet; label consolidation; the sale of
concert companies, record labels and options on song royalties to
Wall Street, and the rise of easy-to-use computer programs enabling
anyone to become a producer. Those out of work today may be the
ones starting companies vital to reassembling the business in
coming years.
</P>
<P>
   All this hasn't gone unnoticed by the producers of South by
Southwest: in recent years they've started conferences on
interactive technology and film to surround the music festival,
clearly envisioning a day when the rock convention seems as quaint
as a television without cable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
