<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMANA-THEATER-FESTIV     03-23 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMANA-THEATER-FESTIVAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT FESTIVAL, ALMOST ALL THE WORLD IS A STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ In a scene with a strange sense of deja vu,
two federal agents corner a man in a SoHo warehouse in New York and
besiege him with questions and accusations while saying,
unconvincingly, that he is free to leave at will. The man, an
erudite editor at Random House, cynically passes off the
interrogation as mere harassment until he realizes the earnestness
of the agents' inquiry and the extent of their knowledge about him.
</P>
<P>
   As Arthur Kopit's new play, ``Y2K,'' slips smoothly into a
flashback, it becomes clear that the editor and his wife have been
victimized by an invidious computer hacker who has completely
undermined their lives. Vicious lies have become, to the world at
large, seemingly unassailable truths, and the editor's favorite
quotation from Flaubert gains a new relevance: ``Everything you
invent is true.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sizzling 80 minutes, the play, the centerpiece of the 23rd
annual Humana Festival of New American Plays at the Actors Theater
of Louisville, exposes the control that computers can have over
lives, morality, even bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The title of the play refers not only to the threat of a
computer breakdown at the millennium but is also a metaphor for the
subjugation of man by machine. A work that starts out as a dark
comedy becomes a horrifying cautionary tale, a kind of contemporary
version of a Jacobean revenge play.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the principal characters is acutely delineated: the
editor (Graeme Malcolm), who is jolted from his plateau of
complacency; his superchic wife (Lucinda Faroldo), for whom
trendiness is paramount, and the hacker from hell (Dallas Roberts),
whose power of invasiveness is as awesome as the gaps in his
cultural background. Only two things seem to matter to him: sex and
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   With diverse knowledge of the intricacy of the Internet, Kopit
plays with questions of reality, illusion and delusion _ and
paranoia. The work is filled with artful twists and turns (and a
few plot strands need tying up). As directed with precision by Bob
Balaban, ``Y2K'' provokes a shudder of anxiety that should be
repeated wherever it is staged. To borrow from Kopit's dialogue,
the play has ``a lethal feedback.''
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Y2K'' was an inexhaustible subject of conversation at
Louisville this weekend, theater professionals were also focusing
on another festival phenomenon: the attempt to blur the boundaries
between actors and audience.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Jory, the producing director of the company, has explored a
wide range of theatrical experience in previous festivals, making
his most significant contribution the discovery of new female
playwrights. But rarely has the festival moved away from formal
theatrical structures.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the theater opened the doors to
site-specific events, including what was referred to as ``a car
play,'' ``What Are You Afraid Of?'' by Richard Dresser. Outside the
theater, a shabby town car was parked for the weekend. In it, at
15-minute intervals, a play was presented, with a rather
astonishing ratio: two actors in the front seat and an audience of
three in the back seat. With such limited seating, there was a
waiting list for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   On cue, the driver invited a pretty hitchhiker into his vehicle,
each taking a chance on the other's stability. While bantering and
moving into a romantic relationship, the hitchhiker observed,
``Just the two of us, not a soul around'' _ except, of course, for
the three voyeurs in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The sketch had a rollicking spontaneity. After the performance,
the actors took a bow in the street in front of the car, an action
that must have startled passengers in passing vehicles. Though
brief, the dialogue could have a future life: it is a play that
literally can be taken on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, people were lined up inside the theater to
listen to a series of five ``telephone plays,'' picking up a
receiver to overhear conversations. While several of the
playwrights tried to cram too much plot into their allotted three
minutes, a few understood that the message was itself the medium.
Diana Son (author of ``Stop Kiss,'' recently at the Public Theater)
wrote a clever dialogue between former lovers in which the
apparently Insignificant Other turned out to be triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of eavesdropping so evident in the car and telephone
plays was also felt on the theater's main stage with an anthology
of eight 10-minute plays by writers under 30. As is often the case
in Louisville, the women were the most accomplished contributors:
Caroline Williams (with a comedy about office politics), Sheri
Wilner, Julia Jordan and, especially, Brooke Berman. Ms. Berman's
``Dancing with a Devil'' is a harrowing memory of rape and its
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   The central theme in these and other plays was an identity
crisis: young people trying to find themselves, older people trying
to redefine themselves and the protagonist in ``Y2K'' adrift
without passport or portfolio.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Two full-length works expressing this theme seemed to have at
least a regional interest: David Rambo's ``God's Man in Texas,'' an
overlong battle between ministers for control of a Houston
megachurch, and ``Cockfighter,'' a rustic coming-of-age play as
adapted by Vincent Murphy from a Frank Manley novel. Naomi Iizuka's
``Aloha, Say the Pretty Girls,'' tracking a group of tiresome young
people who repeatedly cross paths on a journey that takes them from
New York to Hawaii and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Far more appealing was ``Cabin Pressure,'' devised and directed
by Anne Bogart with her company of actors. For this performance
piece about actors and audiences, Ms. Bogart deconstructed the act
of theater as the actors analyzed and made physical their various
approaches to their art and offered snapshot scenes from plays by
Noel Coward and Edward Albee.
</P>
<P>
   In an antic coda, the actors did a lampoon of audiences, miming
their fidgets and gestures _ lolling, shifting in their seats,
sleeping, and, occasionally, being moved by what they saw on stage.
</P>
<P>
   As an additional offering there was ``The T-shirt Project.'' Six
playwrights wrote playlets short enough to fit on a shirt. The
T-plays were on sale (for $20 apiece) at the theater with the
suggestion that the buyer could wear one, read it and act it out.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Kushner composed a dialogue in sonnet form, Mac Wellman
introduced an epic for 22 dwarfs in red fezzes and Wendy
Wasserstein wrote a colloquy in which famous playwrights from
Shakespeare to Tennessee Williams competed in writing T-shirt
slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Aphra Behn had the last words: ``Women playwrights at Louisville
_ 35 years of scribbling for excellence,'' an appropriate epigraph
for the Actors Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the weekend there was an exhibition of set
design (by Ming Cho Lee and others) and there were panel
discussions, one with playwrights who teach playwriting. Marsha
Norman, who achieved her first recognition at Actors Theater, said
that her advice to writers was to determine what their ``true
content'' was, indicating that it should be something so endemic to
them that ``if they didn't write about it, we wouldn't know about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the weekend's contributions by that description, it
was clear that Kopit's play qualified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
