<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV (Washington) _ Shortly after 1 p.m. Tuesday, an
angry Russian prime minister en route to Washington ordered his
pilot to turn his Ilyushin airliner around and return to Moscow.
Primakov was in an untenable situation, having argued for months
against the use of force against Moscow's allies in Serbia.
Whatever he might have hoped to gain from three days of meetings
with Vice President Gore, President Clinton, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and international financial officials, was now
overshadowed by the likelihood of U.S.-led military action in the
Balkans. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ News analysis: When the Clinton
administration put shoring up Social Security at the top of the
national agenda early last year, White House officials said the
first order of business was to make it politically safe to have a
frank debate about the options. Fourteen months later, the two
parties have an array of choices before them. But while it has
proved safe to talk about Social Security, it remains a question
whether the two parties have enough courage and trust to move
beyond the oratory and actually do something. By Richard W.
Stevenson. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With primer graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) Susan H. McDougal, whose
steadfast refusal to answer prosecutors' questions about President
Clinton put her in jail for 18 months, crisply and directly
answered those very same questions in a Federal court on Tuesday,
testifying that she had no knowledge of any wrongdoing on Mr.
Clinton's part. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN-TRIAL (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Insisting upon acting as his
own lawyer in his trial for first degree murder, Dr. Jack
Kervorkian stumbled in the first day of testimony Tuesday, asking
witnesses legally inappropriate questions and raising impermissible
legal arguments as he tried to convince a jury that he should not
be convicted for his role in ending the life of a seriously ill
man. His lack of legal skill so handicapped his case that he was
told he could not call his key witness, the wife of the dead man,
unless he can convince the judge that the woman's testimony would
be relevant. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
