<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT EXPANDS JUDGES' POWER TO MONITOR TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a substantial victory for defendants in product
liability suits, the Supreme Court on Tuesday gave federal judges
new authority to keep expert testimony of questionable reliability
out of the courtroom and away from the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding on a decision of six years ago that established
federal judges as powerful monitors of the quality of scientific
evidence presented in their courtrooms, the court said Tuesday that
the approach it endorsed then was not limited to testimony about
purely scientific principles.
</P>
<P>
   Judges were obliged under the federal rules of evidence to play
the same gatekeeping role when it came to testimony based on
technical or other specialized knowledge, Justice Stephen Breyer
wrote for a unanimous court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In fulfilling that obligation, Breyer said, judges should take a
flexible, case-by-case approach, tailored to the potential witness'
experience and field of expertise, whether it be engineering,
economics, handwriting analysis, or any of numerous other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life and the legal cases that it generates are too complex''
for sharp dividing lines between different kinds of expertise, he
said. Further, Breyer said, ``It would prove difficult, if not
impossible, for judges to administer evidentiary rules under which
a gatekeeping obligation depended upon a distinction between
`scientific' knowledge and `technical' or `other specialized'
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The lower court in this case, reflecting generalized confusion
among the lower federal courts over the scope of the Supreme
Court's 1993 decision in Daubert vs. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals,
had ruled that the judge's gatekeeping role was limited to
testimony based on ``the application of scientific principles.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury itself should be able to appraise the value of expert
testimony that relied on ``skill- or experience-based observation''
instead of scientific principles, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in Atlanta, ruled in a dispute over the reliability of
testimony by an expert in tire failure in a lawsuit growing out of
an automobile accident.
</P>
<P>
   By overturning the 11th circuit's limited view of the Daubert
precedent and finding the tire expert's testimony inadmissible, the
court Tuesday added an important weapon to the arsenal of critics
of the civil justice system who have complained that ``junk
science'' has been finding its way into too many courtrooms and
distorting the deliberations of unsophisticated jurors.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Kumho Tire Co. vs. Carmichael, No. 97-1709, attracted
briefs from a variety of business groups urging the court to make
it clear that the judge's role was an expansive one. Groups
representing trial lawyers and consumers, on the other hand, urged
the court not to take from juries their historic function of
evaluating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The case Tuesday was a lawsuit brought by a family whose Ford
minivan was involved in a single-car accident on Interstate 65 in
Baldwin County, Ala. Seven people in the minivan were injured and
one was killed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the vehicle's tires had blown out, and the plaintiffs,
suing the tire manufacturer, wanted to present testimony by an
expert in tire failures to prove that the accident was due to a
manufacturing defect rather than wear or poor maintenance of the
tire, which was bald in spots and had imperfect repairs of two
punctures.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court in Mobile, regarding the proposed
testimony as technical rather than scientific, nonetheless applied
the approach of the Daubert decision. Finding the expert's
analytical methods insufficiently reliable, the court excluded the
testimony and granted summary judgment to the tire company.
</P>
<P>
   In reversing that ruling, the 11th circuit said the trial court
should not have applied the Supreme Court's guidelines in the
Daubert decision for evaluating scientific testimony. These factors
were: whether the expert's theory or technique had been tested;
whether it had been subjected to peer review and publication;
whether there was a high ``known or potential rate of error'' in
the method, and whether the theory or technique enjoyed ``general
acceptance'' within a ``relevant scientific community.''
</P>
<P>
   In his decision Tuesday, Breyer said a trial judge could pose
any or all of those questions, as circumstances warranted. The
court then went on to apply the analysis to the tire expert's
proposed testimony, concluding that the district judge had properly
exercised his discretion to exclude it.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens, while agreeing with the court's
overall approach to the issues, dissented from the portion of the
decision that applied the analysis to the case at hand. The appeals
court was in a better position to review the record and come to a
final judgment in the case, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
