<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1456 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MUTINY-LADN     03-23 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MUTINY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEMAN HOPES TV MOVIE `MUTINY' CHANGES HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Morgan Freeman loves history.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a country, we don't really know a great deal about
ourselves,'' said the actor, who has starred in such historical
dramas as ``Glory'' and ``Amistad.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Freeman didn't know much about the worst stateside
disaster of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy took place July 17, 1944, when a ship loaded with
ammunition exploded at Port Chicago in San Francisco Bay, instantly
killing 320 naval personnel, most of them African-American sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, like Freeman, you were only slightly aware of the
catastrophe or its aftermath. The event, which injured an
additional 390 and leveled a nearby town, was quickly hushed up and
rarely discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was a massive explosion somewhere in the U.S.
during World War II,'' Freeman said. ``I didn't know Port Chicago
was in California. Movies like `Glory' and `Amistad' tell of
moments in American history that were hidden. History buffs know
about these stories, but the general public knows nothing. I
strongly believe you must know your history in order to know
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The disaster, followed by the court-martial of 50 sailors, is
the subject of ``Mutiny,'' an NBC movie produced by Freeman's
company airing Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Before the nighttime explosion, sailors had complained about
long hours and unsafe conditions for handling munitions _ a task
for which they were untrained. Afterward, they were assigned the
same duty at another Navy base. Fearing the same fate that befell
their comrades, 50 sailors refused their assignments and were
charged with mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   After only 80 minutes of deliberation by a specially convened
military court, the men were found guilty and sentenced to hard
labor. All were dishonorably discharged from the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Although a memorial to those lost in the disaster today stands
on the waterfront of Port Chicago, now known as the Concord Naval
Weapons Station, Freeman and the elderly survivors of the tragedy
hope for an act of Congress to exonerate those who were convicted
despite evidence that racism played a hand in both the explosion
and the dishonorable discharges. So far, there has been no response
from President Clinton. Tuesday, California Congressman George
Miller (D-Concord) lined up a Bay area law firm to try and get the
record changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things many people are going to be exposed to for
the first time (when watching `Mutiny') is seeing Negro seamen
doing the work they were doing _ that's going to be a big
surprise,'' said real-life survivor and Toronto resident Robert
Routh Jr., who was blinded in the home-front explosion but did not
take part in the mutiny. ``Historically, no one really knows the
actual good and great contribution that was made by the kind of
work that came out of Port Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-time Oscar nominee Freeman served as co-executive producer
through his 2-year-old film and television company, Revelations
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   David Ramsey, Michael Jai White and Duane Martin portray some of
the sailors involved, although no actual names were used for any
characters except that of Thurgood Marshall (Joe Morton).
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said he was surprised to learn of the support the
court-martialed sailors received from Marshall, then of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and
later a Supreme Court justice. Marshall campaigned to have the
dishonorable discharges reversed, but failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just know what we've been told in the history books. Nobody
knows anything about this incident or black involvement in the war,
especially people who've studied Warld War II,'' said Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Mutiny'' reveals a wartime Navy as segregated as the
deep South of that era, a period Freeman is familiar with. He sees
the Port Chicago explosion as a turning point for race relations in
the Navy and increased safety in munitions loading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Mississippi in a divided society,'' he explained.
``That made me who I am today. I didn't grow up in a society that
told me one thing and showed me another.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``Mutiny,'' Freeman visited filming locations and took part
in preproduction, including actor auditions for the part of Vernon
Nettles (Ramsey), an ambitious young man who looked forward to
fighting for his country but joins with the others in protest
against their dangerous assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big part of African-American history I didn't know
anything about which was a big attraction to me,'' Ramsey said.
``There's a real human element to the story. These were men with
great honor and dignity who went to war for this country. At a
minimum, I think the case should be reopened. But it's going to
take more than a TV movie to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 15 survivors of the Port Chicago court-martial
still alive, most of whom have changed their names out of shame.
Among those found by the producers of ``Mutiny'' was Carl Tuggle,
who was convicted and sent to the brig for 30 days before being
shipped overseas on cleanup duty and eventually released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want people to know that things happened during World
War II that the government is not revealing to the public, and that
case out there in Port Chicago, Calif., is a good example,'' said
Tuggle, who lives in Cincinnati and is in his 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk down the street and ask the average person who lived
during that period, and they'll say they don't know anything about
it ... because the government didn't want anyone to know anything
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, who recently finished shooting his part in the
forthcoming film by Neil LaBute (director of 1997's ``In the
Company of Men''), said he wants future Revelations projects to
have some social significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to make movies that would inform as well as
entertain,'' he said, ``because so much of our history is taught
through the entertainment medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Also part of Freeman's company is Lori McCreary, who
co-executive produced ``Mutiny.'' A native of Concord, where the
explosion took place, McCreary recalls hearing stories of the Port
Chicago catastrophe as she was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not knowing all the details, I had heard a lot about it,'' she
said. ``The six survivors who came to the set _ I thought they'd be
bitter. But they have so much reverence and joy for the armed
forces still. They showed up the day we were shooting the funeral
scene for all those killed. I'd be talking to these guys, and as
soon as `Taps' started playing, they took off their hats and stood
at attention and paid their respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're quite remarkable men.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
