<SLUG> BC-OPEC-MEETING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL COALITION AGREES TO SLASH CRUDE PRODUCTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ A group representing most of the world's
biggest oil-producing nations formally agreed Tuesday to slash
crude production by 2.1 million barrels a day in a concerted effort
to boost world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   But whether this 14-nation coalition of OPEC and nonaffiliated
oil producers spanning five continents can hold together long
enough to rescue its struggling economies remains an open question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good deal,'' said Mehdi Varzi, director of
research for Kleinwort Benson Securities Ltd. in London. ``This is
a good start. We just don't know how long compliance will go.''
</P>
<P>
   The oil markets, which had been expecting just such a 2.1
million-barrel-cut, were less congratulatory Tuesday. Oil prices,
which had risen strongly ahead of the meeting, fell 23 cents to
close at $15.51 on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have followed crude upward in recent weeks,
tracking the climb of crude oil prices. The Department of Energy
reported earlier this week that the national average price of a
gallon of regular gasoline was $1.02. That's up about 10 cents a
gallon from where prices stood about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prices began to rise in late February after Tosco Corp. shut
down its Avon refinery in Martinez, Calif., due to an explosion
there that killed four people.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers expect gasoline prices to continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   George Gaspar, an analyst with Robert W. Baird and Co. in
Milwaukee, expects additional increases of as much as 10 cents a
gallon. He said the cuts could continue to buoy gasoline prices
into the fall when prices typically decrease slightly as colder
weather makes driving less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   While the oil markets reacted skeptically, the oil ministers did
all they could to make this major reduction seem like routine
business.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries _ in a
20-minute session Libyan Oil Minister Abdalla Salem El-Badri
described as ``the shortest meeting in history'' _ ratified an
agreement in which 10 of the group's 11 members will cut their oil
production by 1.7 million barrels a day over the next year. That
represents a 7 percent reduction in those members' daily output.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone agreed,'' Badri said, adding the meeting was marked
by a ``good atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other, non-OPEC producers _ Mexico, Norway, Russia and Oman
_ also promised to slow their crude production by another 388,000
barrels a day. Together, the 2.1 million-barrel-cut should trim
world production by about 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only OPEC member Iraq, whose oil exports are controlled by
United Nations sanctions, was given the go-ahead to continue
expanding production.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. sanctions permit Iraq to sell up to $5.2 billion of oil
every six months to purchase food and medicine, but because of
capacity constraints, Baghdad has been unable to produce even that
much.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi Oil Minister Amer Rasheed said Tuesday that his country
plans to kick up production by about 300,000 barrels to 3 million
barrels a day by the end of the year, a level that _ depending on
how prices react _ would likely approach the U.N.-imposed cap.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC and non-OPEC producers rubber-stamped an accord reached
earlier this month at The Hague and orchestrated by the cartel's
powerhouse Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spirit of cohesion, solidarity and responsibility has
prevailed amongst us, and oil exporters _ from both within and
outside OPEC _ have reached a decision, which, I believe, goes
beyond expectations,'' declared Algerian Oil Minister Youcef
Yousfi, the current OPEC president.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan Oil Minister Ali Rodriguez Araque said the meeting
had restored the group's ``spirit of brotherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood Tuesday was in contrast to the conclusion of OPEC's
last meeting, when the member-states could reach reach no consensus
on how to proceed and oil prices responded by plunging to historic
lows.
</P>
<P>
   While oil prices have recovered this month, they are still short
of the goals set by the OPEC countries, which are shooting for
prices around $20 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   In London, North Sea Brent crude oil for delivery in May fell 15
cents to $13.73 per barrel. While that's up from less than $10 a
barrel in February, it's not much better than last year's average
$13.30 _ a 22-year low, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stocks of gasoline have been declining and continued to do
so last week, according to figures released late Tuesday by the
American Petroleum Institute. The trade group said gasoline
inventories fell by 4.7 million barrels to 221 million barrels,
while crude oil stocks rose by 823,000 barrels last week to nearly
338 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Varzi believes the next few months will be critical for the
coalition members to demonstrate they are serious about making
substantial cuts. Otherwise, oil prices could tank once again.
</P>
<P>
   Few oil analysts believe the 14 nations will actually cut
production by a full 2.1 million barrels. But a sustained reduction
of just 1 million barrels a day would give prices a substantial
boost, analysts say, while a compliance rate of 75 percent would
push prices up somewhere in the $17 to $20 range by the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Varzi argues the current accord is good for an extra $1 or $2 to
the price of crude, if the parties can demonstrate their commitment
to the agreement over the next couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement Tuesday is the third time in a year OPEC and
nonaffiliated producers have teamed up to cut production. Mexico
has been a key player in all three agreements.
</P>
<P>
   But Jorge Chavez Presa, Mexico's deputy energy minister, said
Tuesday the world is not seeing the creation of some kind of
neo-OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are special circumstances,'' Chavez said. ``We are an
independent producer, and as long as we see the need to take action
we will do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The often-quarrelsome OPEC members had little trouble reaching
an agreement Tuesday because the group's two largest members and
chief rivals _ Saudi Arabia and Iran _ had already worked out their
differences ahead of time. Saudi Arabia made a key concession,
agreeing to drop below its production floor of 8 million barrels a
day for the first time since the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the sacred floor of 8 million or displeasing Iran,''
noted Nawaf Obaid, a visiting fellow at the Washington Institute
for Near East Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudis also accepted an Iranian demand that Tehran be
allowed to calculate Iran's cuts assuming production based on
Iran's stated production, which is 300,000 barrels a day higher
than the Saudi's estimate of the country's output.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian delegation, which typically arrives days ahead of an
OPEC meeting for the usual series of back-and-forth negotiations,
arrived in Vienna only a few hours before the start.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC producers also have good reason to find common ground,
since the low crude prices have ravaged their national budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's Rodriguez said his government had budgeted spending
this year assuming a price of $9 a barrel for Venezuelan crude. But
by mid-February, Venezuela was fetching only an average $7.35 a
barrel for its crude, an 18 percent shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Since The Hague announcement was reached, Venezuela's prices
have risen, and Caracas now estimates its oil will average about
$9.15 a barrel this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
