<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1461 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;        03-23 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
!bbox! !bold! The  show : !off! ``It's Like, You Know ...''  
!bbox! !bold!The stars : !off! Chris Eigeman, Steven Eckholdt, Evan
Handler, A.J. Langer and Jennifer Grey.  
!bbox! !bold!Where : !off! KABC (Channel 7).  
!bbox! !bold!When : !off! 8:30 tonight. !bbox! !bold! The  show : !off! ``The Norm Show.''   
!bbox! !bold!The stars : !off! Norm Macdonald and Laurie Metcalf  
!bbox! !bold!Where : !off! KABC (Channel 7).  
!bbox! !bold!When : !off! 9:30 tonight.!dlim!!head! It's like, you
know ... !dlim!!shead! ... a West Coast incarnation 
of Jerry Seinfeld and his buds !dlim!!by1! By  Rob Lowman  
!by2! Daily News Entertainment Editor !dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; I's like, you know, ``Seinfeld'' for the left coast.
Instead of Kramer, Jerry, George and Elaine, ``It's Like, You Know
...,'' the new ABC series premiering tonight, has three guys and
two girls sitting around doing nothing in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it will have half the success of ``Seinfeld'' _
especially in the heartland _ is the big question. (ABC reportedly
wasn't quite sure what it had on its hands; hence it's being aired
as a midseason replacement.) But if it fails, audiences will be
missing one of the more offbeat and just plain funny series to come
along on network television in a while.
</P>
<P>
   The resemblance to ``Seinfeld'' is not a coincidence. ``It's
Like'' was created by Peter Mehlman, a veteran writer/producer of
the long-running series. But ``It's Like'' is a lot more than a
knockoff. It takes L.A. on its own weird, seductive terms and
affectionately lampoons it.
</P>
<P>
   As Robbie (Steven Eckholdt), a transplanted East Coaster who has
made a fortune with his pay-per-view scheme for the Jewish High
Holy Days called ``Pay Per Jew,'' says to his friend Arthur (Chris
Eigeman), a New Yorker who has come out to LaLa Land to write a
book called ``Living in Los Angeles _ How Can You Stand It?'':
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to be like everyone else, talking about how you
hate L.A. ... how the people are so dumb, so plastic, so silicon,
how nothing is open late, how you have to drive to take a walk, the
murder trials last two years, the marriages last two months, the
houses are ugly, the clothes are loud, the bagels are doughy, the
pizza sucks. Then you throw in the earthquakes, aftershocks,
mudslides, road rage, race riots, guns, tasers, pepper spray. And
just as your head's about to explode, one warm afternoon you play
softball and you think to yourself, `My God, it's January.' The
next day you wake up, and it's two years later. You sold out every
belief you held sacred, and you don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   If the first three episodes of ``It's Like, You Know ...'' are
any indication, Mehlman and his writers are on the way to taking
shallowness to new _ and hilarious _ depths. Along the way,
conversations touch on such hot topics as why the letter Q doesn't
come at the end of the alphabet; would you rather be on the corner
of Florence and Normandie when the riots broke out or on Normandy
Beach during D-Day; and why Elliot Gould was driving a Honda.
</P>
<P>
   The second show takes place almost entirely in Robbie's house,
where the cast spends an afternoon watching a live freeway chase.
(It's like an L.A. version of a ``snow day.'') When Arthur
protests, Robbie explains that ``the entire city is going to sit
around like idiots watching the car chase.'' And they do,
second-guessing the driver's moves and waiting for something to
happen in their wacky sunshine variation of Luis Bunuel's ``The
Exterminating Angel.'' Later, Arthur laments, ``Someday I'll look
back on this day and not remember any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Seinfeld'' was about nothing, ``It's Like, You Know ...''
is about the nuance of nothing, but it also seems to be willing to
let its characters have a bit more self-awareness than Jerry and
the crew ever had.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``It's Like'' is top flight. Eigeman, who made his
mark in Whit Stillman's films ``Metropolitan,'' ``Barcelona'' and
``The Last Days of Disco,'' is suitably cranky. Eckholdt
marvelously glides between being shallow and knowing that he is.
</P>
<P>
   The other regulars include Evan Handler who plays Shrug, a
trust-fund rich and insecure native Angeleno; A.J. Langer, who was
on ``My So-Called Life'' as a masseuse/process server; and, in a
``Larry Sanders''-esque inspired bit of casting, Jennifer Grey of
``Dirty Dancing'' fame as herself _ after a nose job.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Grey really did have a nose job to get more roles. Now
she's playing a fictional version of herself _ and doing a darn
good job of it, too. And it's that kind of loopiness that
television needs more of. Let's hope ``It's Like, You Know ...''
gets the chance to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's ``The Norm Show,'' which is like, you know,
simply shallow. Also premiering tonight, it stars ``Saturday Night
Live'' alum Norm Macdonald as a former hockey player working out a
community-service sentence as a social worker. The premise is built
for cheap laughs but rarely delivers, although just when you're
nodding off, Macdonald comes up with a zinger. But it's not enough
to keep you tuning in. In the meantime, ``Norm'' wastes the talents
of Emmy winner Laurie Metcalf in a thankless role.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1464 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUKNOW-TVREVIEW-LADN     03-23 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUKNOW-TVREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S LIKE, YOU KNOW ... AN L.A. REINCARNATION OF `SEINFELD'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Tonight in lede graf refers to Wednesday, March 24)  
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's like, you know, ``Seinfeld'' for the left
coast. Instead of Kramer, Jerry, George and Elaine, ``It's Like,
You Know ...,'' the new ABC series premiering tonight, has three
guys and two girls sitting around doing nothing in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it will have half the success of ``Seinfeld'' _
especially in the heartland _ is the big question. (ABC reportedly
