<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR AND VIOLENCE BUILD IN AND AROUND PRISTINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-U.S., RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The suburb was deserted. Washing flapped
on clotheslines, cars were parked outside the houses, but there
were no people. Four figures, two women and two children carrying
bundles and bags, were hurrying up the hill away from the houses.
</P>
<P>
   They started to run as a black jeep bumped along the muddy track
between the houses. The residents were fleeing what they thought
was a police jeep. They had cause to fear.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Serbian police raided the ethnic Albanian
suburb, on the southern edge of Pristina, Kosovo's provincial
capital. The neighborhood is a quiet cluster of houses on a
hillside, near the town hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrived at 7 p.m. in three or four armored jeeps with
mounted machine guns and an armored personnel carrier. They
announced their arrival with a burst of machine-gun fire.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparently unprovoked action, they raided houses, beat
people and smashed cars, windows and household goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people saw the violence, they panicked and started to
run,'' said Hilmi Tahiri, the local representative of the ethnic
Albanian political party, the Democratic League of Kosovo. Within
minutes the suburbs' 500 houses had emptied.
</P>
<P>
   The panic is just one sign of the increased tension in the city.
Both Serbs and ethnic Albanians are frightened as the violence of
the war in the countryside encroaches on the city and NATO air
strikes appear imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian police operation on Monday was followed by attacks
on two ethnic Albanian cafes in the center of the city.
</P>
<P>
   In one attack, a gunman sprayed more than 30 bullets into the
glass-fronted Cafe Magic, on a central street. One person, a
well-known actress, was killed and several people were wounded. On
Tuesday children peered through the punctured windows in curious
horror. Glasses of beer stood half full on the tables, and blood
stained the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, at the Cafe Koha, someone wrenched open the
door and threw in an explosive. The blast killed one person and
injured two, the force of it blowing out the door and buckling the
metal grills over the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Police reacted instantly and aggressively, setting up roadblocks
and checking people at gunpoint. Clearly on edge, police officers
opened fire on a 14-year-old boy who tried to run away from a
roadblock. The youth was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Residents took no chances Tuesday. Restaurants, shops and cafes
were closed by 5 p.m., and by the time darkness fell, the streets
were deserted except for police officers. Both Albanians and Serbs
said they feared the violence would only worsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today nowhere is safe,'' said an Albanian housewife who would
give her name only as Hajrija. She said her sister lived downtown,
near the cafe that was sprayed with bullets. ``She is so afraid,''
Hajrija said of her sister. ``She has young children. She keeps
calling me and crying on the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from such random attacks, the Albanians fear violence from
police and from armed Serbian civilians. They say NATO air strikes
could bring retaliatory attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO bombs, they will have us all in their hand,'' said a
63-year-old pensioner named Halil, one of the few people who
refused to leave the hospital suburb. ``However it started, the
situation is spinning out of control. Every situation has a final
line and things are ready for that line to be crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not flee. ``I have nowhere else to go,'' he
said. ``The worst that they can do is kill me, but better that it
happens in your own house than in a field or in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs in Kosovo, who constitute only 10 per cent of the
population and who often speak out against the West and NATO with
aggressive passion, muted their anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners attending a funeral for one of four policemen killed on
Sunday in an ambush in central Pristina said they feared more
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will get worse and worse, even if we hope conditions will
get better,'' said Miodrag Mitic, one of the mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues of the dead officer said they saw no way out of the
situation. ``It has now become a usual thing to shoot at
policemen,'' said a senior colleague. He had lost six men in just
two weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not see a way out,'' he added with a heavy sigh. ``It is
politics, something others decide.''
</P>
<P>
   As mourners passed behind the coffin through Lapje Selo, where
the funeral was held, Serbian MiG fighter jets roared overhead,
taking off from the nearby airport and wheeling away through the
sky. A heavy explosion sounded in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder to the quiet Serbian village, which has been
largely untouched by the year-long conflict, that the war is in
full progress.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy shelling continued around Poljance, 25 miles northwest of
Pristina, as Serbian forces pushed westward against positions above
the road occupied by Albanian rebels. There was also activity near
Podujevo, north of Pristina, where houses in at least one village
were on fire.
</P>
<P>
   In Lapje Selo, Serbs said they feared the consequences of NATO
strikes more than the actual bombs and spoke of the possibility of
losing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course NATO is more powerful than us,'' Mitic said. ``We
are only a small country.'' He said air strikes would herald the
end of Serbs' lives in Kosovo because the Albanians, and in
particular rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army, would not show
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have to leave,'' he said. ``If the government cannot
protect us here, we may have to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
