u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-TRUCKS-730&AMP;ADD     03-23 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TRUCKS-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TRUCKING COMPANIES MOVE AGAINST HIGHER COSTS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLE OF SHEPPEY, England _ When European nations hang out their
shingles to attract foreign investors, Britain's appeal runs
something like this: come to Britain for low labor costs, low
taxes, low overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wood doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, a trucker based on this marshy island at the mouth of the
River Thames, runs 20 rigs carrying construction equipment the
length and breadth of Britain. And, when the government announced a
10 percent rise in the price of diesel fuel and a 50 percent
increase in some truckers' license fees in its annual budget this
month, Wood decided it was time to move, legally at least.
</P>
<P>
   So, Wood plans to set up a subsidiary in the Netherlands _ RW
Haulage International _ where his trucks will be licensed as Dutch
trucks. As European Union vehicles, they will have the same access
to British roads as any other European truck.
</P>
<P>
   But, since the Netherlands, like the rest of continental Europe,
has much lower license fees than Britain _ roughly $1,100 per
vehicle in the Netherlands, compared with $9,000 in Britain _ Wood
expects to save $160,000 annually for his $5-million-a-year
business. Despite the Dutch registry, he will continue to pay
relatively low British wages and British taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Others are pondering similar calculations. After this month's
budget, some 1,500 haulers called the Road Haulage Association,
which represents about one third of Britain's haulage companies, to
inquire about the technicalities of incorporating in continental
Europe, said Steve Williams, a representative of the association.
</P>
<P>
   One of Britain's biggest operators, Eddie Stobart, whose fleet
comprises 800 trucks each bearing a different woman's name, is
thinking about registering 200 of his rigs in Luxembourg, and ``may
rename them Helga or Nicole,'' a spokeswoman for him said.
</P>
<P>
   So incensed are Britain's truckers that hundreds of them,
including Wood, clogged central London with their rigs Tuesday in
protest.
</P>
<P>
   By moving abroad, the haulers will be reversing a trend of
continental companies seeking tax-breaks in Britain, opening one of
the first chinks in Britain's argument that, alone among Europe's
major economies, it is a haven from high costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that haulage is now becoming a very European
business,'' Williams said. ``So European haulers can come in here
and work without paying the same costs as we do. It's not a very
level playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the decision by Wood, 48, and others to `'flag out''
their vehicles in foreign lands is the latest sign of unease among
Britons that, while their government tells them direct taxes are
falling, a combination of indirect taxes and retailers' margins
means they pay more for fuel, cars, computers, cigarettes, liquor
and many other goods than anyone else in Europe or the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   British truckers now pay the highest fuel and license fees in
Europe _ over $5 a gallon for diesel fuel _ twice what it costs in
Luxembourg _ up to $9,000 a year to license a single 40-ton,
five-axle rig, 17 times the cost in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Since a European Union directive in 1998, moreover, all European
Union road haulers have been permitted to carry loads not simply
into and out of each other's countries but also to carry loads
internally. Consequently, European trucking companies are rolling
into Britain and offering to haul goods at one third Wood's price.
</P>
<P>
   A German truck, for instance, powered by cheap diesel fuel
purchased in Belgium or France before crossing the Channel, can
pick up a load of steel in Sheffield and drop it off in London _ a
practice that was once banned _ without paying British license
fees.
</P>
<P>
   The British authorities, though, contend that the battle is
really not about competitiveness but cleanliness, pitting pounds
and pennies against environmental policies intended to meet
Britain's international commitments to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   The price rises on pollutants like diesel fuel, said Vickie
Sheriff, a spokeswoman for the Department of the Environment,
Transport and Regions, are offset by lower prices for cleaner fuels
like low-sulfur diesel and unleaded gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle is that the polluter pays,'' she said. Trucks
with six axles, similarly, qualify for much lower license fees than
five-axle rigs because they do less damage to the highways.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to the Road Haulage Association, Britain's 65,000
haulage businesses employ 500,000 drivers and a similar number of
ancillary staff, carry 1.65 billion tons of goods a year _
four-fifths of all domestic freight _ and contribute over $7.4
billion of the $49.5 billion the government collects in excise and
fuel taxes and duties. The latest price increases, Williams said,
will jeopardize 50,000 of those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, jobs are cheaper in Britain than in much of
continental Europe because hourly wages are generally lower, and
Britain does not insist on the same levels of social spending,
personal taxes or corporate taxes. Indeed, John Reid, the transport
minister, said, ``Britain is not only cheaper than our major
European rivals when it comes to road transport, but comes out
almost on top of the list worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Haulers who are thinking of relocating to other European
countries should consider these facts very carefully before making
a decision,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   What the authorities are not considering, Wood argues, is that
continental European haulers operating in Britain ``have already
made their profit by the time they arrive'' with a tankful of cheap
diesel fuel. They offer internal haulage in Britain at a discount
rather than return home empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally flagging-out was meant as a threat,'' Williams
said, ``but now it's becoming a reality because so many people have
had problems with the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Wood put it, ``I'd rather go to Holland than go out of
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
