<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUHN-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life is indeed beautiful when Scoonie's involved
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS _ Jim O'Brien watched the Oscars on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to a lot of movies,'' the Ohio State basketball coach
said.
</P>
<P>
   By going to the movies, most coaches mean they go to their
offices and watch movies of the next opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, real movies,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign film, Life is Beautiful, was mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best movies of all time,'' O'B said, and he
immediately recognized the irony _ life is beautiful for a coach
going to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons O'B and the O'Buckeyes are heading to
St. Petersburg this week is the remarkable relationship between the
guards, Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd.
</P>
<P>
   A season ago, most OSU basketball games were The Michael Redd
Show with the other guys _ his ``staff,'' as it were _ adjusting
the microphones, fixing the lights, focusing the cameras. Redd took
1 of every 3 shots, led the Buckeyes in scoring and was named the
Big Ten Freshman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   But the season was covered with Redd ink: The Buckeyes went
8-22. Life wasn't beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   And then came Scoonie.
</P>
<P>
   Redd knew he was going to lose shots (down from 18 a game to
15.5) and points (down from 21.9 to 19.7). What he didn't know is
that he was going to be shunted into the background by a media that
can't get enough Scoonie.
</P>
<P>
   Like the radio disc jockey who locks himself in the control room
and plays Stairway to Heaven nonstop for a month, coverage of the
Buckeyes has tended to be All Scoonie All the Time.
</P>
<P>
   And with cause. In Ohio, Scoonie is Babe Ruth. You market a
Scoonie doll right now, you buy an island in the Caribbean next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Why this didn't cause friction is still an open question. But it
hasn't, and it's as simple to quantify as watching them play
together. The chemistry between these two strong personalities is
at the core of OSU's turnaround from Final Breath to Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   We've all seen dozens of teams where one ball isn't enough;
where two stars work against each other like pit bulls in a dog
fight.
</P>
<P>
   This team avoided that abyss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happened,'' O'Brien said, denying any credit.
``Scoonie showed up, and within a couple of days, all the guys
welcomed him with open arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no animosity,'' Redd said. ``You want the best
players to come in because that makes you better.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy to say. Not as easy to enact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me out last year when he wasn't playing,'' Redd
said. ``He kept telling me, 'Keep your head up. You're playing
well.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Redd's English teachers will be thrilled. I didn't touch up the
quote. He actually said, ``playing well,'' not ``playing good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship blossomed from the very start,'' Scoonie
said. ``Why should he get mad at me if I'm here to help out?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, because it's happened so many times at so many places. He
had the spotlight; you took it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down and talked,'' Scoonie said. ``We talk all the
time. I know this: If I was Big Ten Freshman of the Year and scored
21 a game but finished 8-22, I would want someone to help me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Logically, yes. But this is basketball, where jealousies and
egos ripping teams apart are as common as backdoor cuts in a
Princeton scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize you can't do it all,'' Redd said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I said, but you're 19. Nineteen-year-olds aren't supposed
to understand that.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Redd looked at me and laughed. ``Scoring means nothing
to me,'' he said. ``I want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He is. They are. And life is beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
