</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOST-ROLEPLAYERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio State's success a team effort
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS _ Guards Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd get all the ink
as Ohio State's scoring stars. But their supporting cast deserves
equal credit for the team's improbable climb into the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Ken Johnson, Jason Singleton, Brian Brown and George
Reese have been invaluable in the NCAA tournament. And as their
confidence builds with each victory, their game only seems to get
better. Some highlights of their contributions:
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, OSU's 6-11 junior center, had seven blocks and 12
points in the Bucks 77-74 victory against St. John's in last
Saturday's regional final. St. John's coach Mike Jarvis called
Johnson ``the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Singleton, a 6-7 power forward, contributed 13 points vs. the
Red Storm _ his highest point total in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve forward Reese grabbed a career-high 15 rebounds in OSU's
second-round victory over Detroit. Freshman guard Brown was 3-for-3
from 3-point range in that same game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a collection of guys that do a couple things pretty
well but have some limitations,'' OSU coach Jim O'Brien said.
``When you have some limitations, you really have to have guys that
understand what their roles are. And all of these kids have
accepted (them).''
</P>
<P>
   They've been able to do that, in large part, because ``this is
an ego-less collection of guys,'' O'Brien said. They understand
Penn and Redd are the ``marquee'' players.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien points to Singleton, a poor perimeter shooter, and
sophomore forward Jon Sanderson, a starter yanked from the lineup
in the NCAA tournament, as two players who have willingly
acceptedlesser roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason Singleton understands his role as well as anybody I ever
coached,'' O'Brien said. ``Have you seen Jason take a lot of
perimeter jump shots?''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Jon Sanderson,'' O'Brien continued. ``He starts the whole
year and he finally gets a chance to get into his first NCAA game
and then I tell him, 'You're not starting.' And his response is:
'OK fine.' Instead of complaining, he wants to see how he can do
(his bench role) a little bit better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a wonderful group of guys to coach. They are
very receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   By accepting their roles, the players have clicked. Team
chemistry has never been better, they say. Jealousy is
non-existent. Everybody just wants to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken has to block shots, rebound. Jason has to get on the
fastbreak and finish, rebound, play great defense,'' Sanderson
said. ``Brian Brown handles the ball and distributes the ball.
Everyone has their roles and everyone seems pretty happy with it.
As long as we're winning, that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his new role as a reserve, Sanderson said: ``If I have to
come off the bench and contribute in that regard, that's definitely
fine with me. I'm just extremely grateful to be a part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien admits it's been an easier sell with the Buckeyes 27-8
and Final Four-bound, instead of 8-22, like last season. He said he
would love to coach a team comprised of several high school
All-Americans, such as the one Duke has now. (Who wouldn't?) But
O'Brien wouldn't trade this Ohio State squad for any other one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
