<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGANS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PANEL APPROVES PLAN OFFERING ORGANS TO IN-STATE PATIENTS
FIRST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Organs recovered in Texas would be offered to
in-state patients first and the statewide organ distribution system
revamped under a bill approved Tuesday by a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is about ensuring that decisions about organ
allocation and availability are made by patients and medical
professionals at the local level, not by federal bureaucrats in
Washington,'' said state Sen. Mario Gallegos, D-Galena Park, author
of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos' Senate Bill 862 is part of a trend among states toward
crafting their own alternatives to new federal guidelines for organ
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved by the Senate Health Services Committee, will
head to the Senate after members do some more work shoring up its
provisions, said state Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower Mound, committee
chair.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson amended Gallegos' bill to include a measure establishing
a single, statewide organ donor list. If enacted, the list would
replace a current distribution system in Texas that is based on
three regional lists.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, donated organs in Texas are offered first to patients
served by the bank that collected them. If there is no match, the
organs are shared regionally and then nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government last year announced new transplant
regulations to take effect Oct. 1. Generally, the guidelines call
for sharing organs nationally, with the sickest patients receiving
the highest priority.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos' plan has divided those in the field of organ donation
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is backed by several prominent transplant surgeons
in The Texas Medical Center in Houston, in addition to Houston's
LifeGift Organ Donation Center and many transplant recipients.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the plan are also gathering steam _ hoping to
head off Senate approval of the bill, and a companion measure in
the House filed by state Rep. Kyle Janek, R-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Silvestri, media services manager with the Dallas-based
Southwest Transplant Alliance, called the Texas-first plan
``selfish and provincial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a state's rights issue, this is a human rights
issue,'' Silvestri said. ``This is a reactionary plan to the new
federal guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   A better approach would be to direct organs to those who need
them most, regardless of what state the organs were collected in,
bill opponents said. Medical advances in organ preservation have
made it possible to send them farther distances to meet critical
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Creech, a heart transplant recipient from Houston, said he
supports the bill because it would create a more equitable system.
Creech said the federal guidelines would increase Texans' waiting
time for many organs and increase the costs associated with
exporting organs great distances.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos disputed claims his bill amounts to ``hoarding'' organs
for Texans, noting the state would continue to share with others as
it does now.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, those associated with the organ transplant field
agreed the biggest problem in Texas and the nation is the shortage
of donated organs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Texas exported 222 organs to other states, according
to Gallegos, and received 77 from elsewhere. There are an estimated
3,300 Texans currently awaiting organ transplants. Last year, about
1,600 organs were donated in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos' bill, if enacted, would include patients from other
states who come to Texas for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Other states that have taken steps to protect their organ
supplies from export are Louisiana, Oklahoma, South Carolina and
Wisconsin. Gallegos said the Texas bill would take into
consideration the concerns expressed by opponents of his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there is a great deal of debate about what is best
for Texas,'' Gallegos said. ``I am anxious to work with my
colleagues in the Senate and the House, as well as Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry and organ transplantation professionals, to figure out
compromise language that resolves this issue to everyone's
satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
