<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PROFITS FROM GARAGE SALES ARE NOT MONETARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, March 25)  
(lb) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS  
 
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I much prefer going to garage sales to having them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the junk in our house reached critical mass just
eight months after we moved in, I decided it was time to sort and
sell.
</P>
<P>
   My 8-year-old was suspicious, having been traumatized by our
moving sale last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that time I woke up and saw that kid carrying off my
favorite toy?'' he asks still.
</P>
<P>
   The way he sees it, garage sales are the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   So I was surprised when he took this one in stride. He seemed
delighted to see people milling about, examining discarded
videotapes and bubble rockets and outgrown ``Small Soldier'' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a party,'' he said, settling in to count the money.
</P>
<P>
   Then the 2-year-old came sleepily down the garage stairs.
</P>
<P>
   She took one look and started gathering every toy she could
reach from the tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine,'' she said. ``Mine, mine, mine.''
</P>
<P>
   After some persuasion, she got to keep her yellow fabric
umbrella, and I got to put everything else back.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to guess what people would buy as they were walking down
the drive, but I was always wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One teen-age girl, who bought ``The Seven Habits of Highly
Effective People,'' had just come from taking the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-school guidance counselor bought all the cookbooks, the
magazine holder and some small plastic bugs for a model of the rain
forest she was making with her students.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors came by with children grass-stained from softball
practice. Soon, there were five kids playing in our yard, the first
time such a spontaneous group had formed since we moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Adam and Sarah were delighted.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of customers informed me my signs had swung upside
down. So I headed off to right them, leaving my husband in charge.
</P>
<P>
   This is always dangerous since:
</P>
<P>
   A) He would have donated everything to charity instead of
bothering with a sale.
</P>
<P>
   B) Now that there was already a sale in progress, he would
gladly sell anything for a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   When I came back, I was carrying a child's wooden rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me you actually BOUGHT something from a garage sale
in the middle of OUR garage sale,'' he said, amazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody gave it to me when I was putting up the sign in front
of her house,'' I replied, shrugging. ``We can sell it if you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah wandered over with wide eyes. ``It's so BEAUTIFUL,'' she
said. Jim rolled his eyes. I smiled. Sarah sat and rocked.
</P>
<P>
   As the customers dwindled, I started packing boxes for the
Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   A final car pulled up with a mother, daughter and grandmother.
The girl, translating for her elders, explained they were from
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   I told them anything in the boxes was free, and they sorted for
15 minutes, filling up a bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother thanks you very much and says to tell you that my
grandmother will be taking these things back to her country when
she returns, to give them out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of it _ my fuzzy bedroom slippers and Adam's Bart Simpson
doll getting a second lease on life in the former U.S.S.R. You've
got to love garage sales.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
