<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-MOORE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKY MOORE IS UCONN'S DEFENSIVE STOPPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ You want defense? Ricky Moore can play the D, bay-bee.
He's a whirling dervish of arms, and legs, and hip checks. On a
smaller scale _ OK, a ``much'' smaller scale _ Moore is to the
Connecticut men's basketball team what Deion Sanders is to the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sanders, Moore sticks to the other team's best player and
you just don't hear from him again: Michigan State All-American
Mateen Cleaves shot 2- of-15 from the floor when they played;
Pittsburgh's Vonteego Cummings was 2-of-18 in one game; and
Stanford's Arthur Lee was 4-of-13.
</P>
<P>
   In the NCAA Tournament West Regional final Saturday that sent
Connecticut to its first Final Four, Moore, a 6-foot-2 guard, held
Gonzaga's best NBA prospect, Matt Santangelo, to 1-of-9 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get in a guy's chest,'' said Moore, a senior who
has been a starter the past three seasons. ``It's tough to shut a
guy out. But I'm a competitor. And no matter who the other team
brings in, it can be Michael Jordan, I'm going to do my best to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding Jordan might be a bit far-fetched. But Moore did a nice
job on cross-over king Allen Iverson, holding the then-Georgetown
star to 4-of-15 shooting in the 1996 Big East Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes, of course, are much higher Saturday, when Moore will
match elbows with Ohio State's James ``Scoonie'' Penn in a
tournament semifinal in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's role is clear. First-team All-America junior forward
Richard Hamilton scores most of the points and gets most of the
media spotlight. Point guard Khalid El-Amin runs the team. Moore
runs through picks, takes charges and plays in-your-face defense.
He has as much of an effect on the game as anybody, despite
averaging a modest seven points and four rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Calhoun calls Moore the best defensive player he has
ever coached. That is no small compliment from a man who has
coached more than 800 career games and seen the likes of Donyell
Marshall, Ray Allen and Scott Burrell go pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky has incredible athletic ability, and he's smart,''
Calhoun said. ``He could play any sport. He'd be a terrific
cornerback. He's got the attitude, the speed, the toughness. And
he's got the will to want to shut the other guy down.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore studies film of the opposing player as ambitiously as he
studies a political science textbook. He then combines brainpower
with a blend of strength and quickness. He gets in the face of jump
shooters like Santangelo, and he backs off guards who like to
drive, such as Cleaves and Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get more of a charge out of locking a guy up,'' Moore said.
``The way I look at it, if I'm playing good defense, that's going
to make our guys better. That's more important to me than scoring.
I can score. I scored a lot of points in high school, but we've got
guys here that can score. I want to stop the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Used to be, Moore was ``The Guy.'' He came to Connecticut as a
national top 40 recruit, having averaged 21.7 points and 8.4
assists per game at Westside High School in Augusta, Ga. He led his
team to a 33-1 record and its first Class 3A state title. He was
named runner-up in voting for Georgia's Mr. Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's game improved steadily in his first two seasons at
Connecticut. He averaged 4.7 points per game as a freshman. He
averaged nine points and a team-leading 5.4 assists per game as a
starting sophomore point guard.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies' recruitment of El-Amin in 1997 put the brakes
on Moore's offensive development. El-Amin took Moore's starting
point guard position. Moore, if he was to stay at Connecticut,
would have to move to the off-guard and change his focus from
offensive to defensive playmaker. Moore's family, thinking his new
role would hurt his chances to go pro, talked to him about
transferring to a school where he could showcase his talents.
</P>
<P>
   Moore stayed at Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to help the guys here win a championship,'' Moore
said. ``I get respect because we are winning. I know I'm a pretty
good offensive player. But this is not about me. It's about the
team. We're trying to win a championship here.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that Moore can't score if he has to. When
El-Amin sat on the bench for more than 15 minutes of the first half
against Gonzaga because of foul trouble, Moore took control. He had
nine points, three assists and three rebounds in 19 first-half
minutes, keeping the Huskies in the game until El-Amin returned. In
the second half, he returned to his customary role, putting the
clamps on Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we brought Khalid in and made him the starter, Ricky made
a decision to do the best thing to help the team win,'' Calhoun
said. ``That is play defense. But that's not to say that he can't
score. He can run the offense whenever we need him to, and when
people don't guard him they pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so much better because Ricky is on our team.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
