<HEADER>
A1499 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DEBUTS-SPI &LR;      03-23 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DEBUTS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 ABC's WEDNESDAY LINEUP BOLSTERED BY TWO SMART SITCOMS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC's ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' and ``The Drew Carey Show'' may never go
down as classic TV comedies in the style of ``I Love Lucy'' and
``The Dick Van Dyke Show,'' but they're better than most of the
stuff that's out there.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for their new temporary stablemates, ``It's like, you
know ...'' and ``The Norm Show,'' which join Dharma, Greg and Drew
in the Wednesday lineup, giving ABC a foursome certainly as strong
as the one NBC sends out on Thursday nights. All ABC needs is a
decent 10 o'clock drama instead of another incarnation of ``20/20''
_ gee, if only it hadn't canned ``Maximum Bob,'' or ``Cupid,'' or
``Cracker'' _ and it might become the Wizard of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the wrong idea. ``It's like, you know ...,'' created
by former ``Seinfeld'' writer/producer Peter Mehlman, isn't another
``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Norm Show,'' featuring deposed ``Saturday Night Live''
player Norm Macdonald and ``Roseanne'' star Laurie Metcalf, is a
little rough around the edges. But it's easy to see promise in both
series, which is something ABC should get excited about in this
midseason of major mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   With ``It's like, you know ...,'' Mehlman brashly re-creates the
Seinfeldian ethos, this time with a cast of five instead of four.
To use Mehlman's words, it's about ``people coming out to L.A. in
search of their dreams and reinventing themselves completely.''
</P>
<P>
   But after watching three episodes, it's like, you know, Mehlman
was just saying that so critics wouldn't say ``It's like, you know
...'' is about nothing. That would be way so Sein-fully derivative,
even for television.
</P>
<P>
   So you be the judge. Here's a conversation from the pilot
episode, featuring four of the five characters: Robbie, Shrug,
Arthur and Jennifer. Robbie starts it by mentioning that he saw
Elliott Gould on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Shrug: ``What was he driving?''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie: ``A Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer, disbelieving: ``A Honda?''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie: ``A Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrug: ``Maybe it was a rental.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie: ``I think it was his Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrug: ``Why would he drive a Honda?''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer: ``Maybe he does voice-overs for Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie: ``Maybe he owns a Honda dealership.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrug: ``Maybe it was his wife's Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer: ``Maybe he doesn't know it was a Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrug: ``Maybe it was an Acura Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie: ``No, it was a Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur, the vexed New Yorker trying to grasp what passes for
conversation in L.A.: ``Aaaargh! Will you listen to yourselves? Who
cares what Elliott Gould drives? How does this qualify as a
discussion?''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie: ``That's what's so great about L.A. You don't even have
to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Or substantial, for that matter. The more trivial, the better.
At least from Mehlman's Left Coast observatory, where he has spent
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Mehlman moved to Los Angeles in 1989 because he says he needed a
change of scenery. He had worked at the Washington Post, wrote and
produced Howard Cosell's ``Sportsbeat'' show from 1982-84, then
free-lanced out of New York for five years after that.
</P>
<P>
   In L.A., Mehlman hooked up with Larry David, whom he had known
in New York. David hired Mehlman to write for a new show called
``Seinfeld,'' and Mehlman ended up staying for six years.
</P>
<P>
   For the TV audience, one-time Seattleite Chris Eigeman plays the
wide-eyed, often incredulous, transplanted New Yorker _ a guy named
Arthur Garment, ostensibly in L.A. for a short time to do a
magazine piece on why he hates L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Arthur will be staying a little longer, mainly
because he's smitten with Lauren (A.J. Langer), an L.A.-based
masseuse/process server he met on the plane. He's also impressed
that the real Jennifer Grey of ``Dirty Dancing'' and ``Red Dawn''
lives next door to Robbie (Steven Eckholdt).
</P>
<P>
   Grey, made virtually unrecognizable by a nose job, has a ball
poking fun at herself. Her castmates are strong, too, particularly
Evan Handler as Shrug, an enormously wealthy ``trustafarian'' who's
never known what it is to work for one's money.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a problem in the early going, it's that the
performers aren't interacting as much as they're reciting funny
lines. Fortunately, most of the lines recall the barbed-wire
spikiness of ``Seinfeld.'' If the cast settles in and the writing
stays sharp, ABC has a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Norm Show,'' ABC has a very close relative of ``The
Drew Carey Show.'' Like Carey, Macdonald is a snide comic who rubs
many people the wrong way, not the least being NBC exec Don
Ohlmeyer, who canned Macdonald from ``Saturday Night Live'' because
Ohlmeyer wasn't amused. Like Carey's show, Macdonald's also has
that dark ``Roseanne'' feel to it. Not surprising, since Bruce
Helford, a former executive producer of ``Roseanne,'' is co-creator
of both ``Drew'' and ``Norm.''
</P>
<P>
   While Macdonald is often as profane as an NBA coach, his show is
remarkably mild. Still, producer Helford always manages to tweak
the network censors, apparently to assert his manliness or
something. It's probably the only reason ``The Norm Show'' is rated
TV-14 while ``It's like, you know ...'' gets a TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional blue lingo aside, ``The Norm Show'' has some good
things happening. There's the marvelous Metcalf, who plays Norm's
gullible mentor/colleague/friend. And there's the versatile Ian
Gomez, fresh off his spectacular performance as Javier, the gay
cafe manager on ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald is his usual sarcastic self, playing a deposed hockey
player relegated to the penalty box for five years for failure to
pay taxes. To avoid prison, he agrees to perform community service
as a social worker. Sure, it makes no sense. But it's worth
suspending disbelief just for this exchange between Norm and a guy
who wants to reclaim the dog Norm bought at the pound.
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``You can't take my dog!''
</P>
<P>
   Norm: ``What do you mean, pal? We're social workers. We can take
children!''
</P>
<P>
   In humor-challenged places, lines such as this will be dissected
and examined for their appropriateness. In more relaxed circles,
people will laugh. And that's good.
</P>
<P>
   It's like, you know ... Half-hour comedy series about a New
Yorker trying to make sense of life in L.A. Starring Chris Eigeman,
Steven Eckholdt, Jennifer Grey, Evan Handler and A.J. Langer.
Premieres Wednesday night on ABC. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The Norm Show. Half-hour comedy series about a hockey
player-turned-social worker. Starring Norm Macdonald, Laurie
Metcalf and Ian Gomez. Premieres Wednesday night on ABC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
