<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELITE SEASON SHOWS UCLA IS ON RISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA speaks of building its women's basketball
program to compete with the nation's elite _ the Tennessees, the
Louisiana Techs. The Bruins' season ended Monday night with a
26-point loss to Tech, showing how far away they remain from that
goal. And also showing they are moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built a great foundation,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier
said. ``This team has a fantastic springboard. It's been a great
year.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won its first Pac-10 title, won 26 games, reached the Elite
Eight for the first time and made the NCAAs in consecutive seasons
for the first time (they made consecutive AIAW Final Four
appearances in 1978 and '79). And maybe it made the Bruins'
faithful temporarily forget the UCLA men.
</P>
<P>
   ``People realize,'' Maylana Martin said, ``there is a women's
basketball team at UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, there were no seniors on this team, meaning
another season of Martin's leadership and turnaround bank shots,
Janae Hubbard's domination in the middle, Marie Philman
outrebounding taller players, Melanie Pearson's outside shooting,
LaCresha Flannigan's speed and defense and Carly Funicello's help
in the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``May, she's already talking about her senior year,'' Olivier
said. ``She'll want to go out and be a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Erica Gomez, who broke Ann Meyers' career assist record this
season, has talked about not returning because she graduates in
June. A sprained ankle in the regional semifinal against Colorado
State and a one-sided loss to Tech might have influenced Gomez's
decision, but even if she calls it a career, UCLA has the personnel
with Michelle Greco and incoming freshman Nicole Kacmarski to carry
on.
</P>
<P>
   Greco, from Crescenta Valley High, proved her worth by filling
in for Gomez after spending most of the season watching and
learning. She has shown she can take over.
</P>
<P>
   Kacmarski, from Farmingville, N.Y., is the top prep guard in the
nation, according to Blue Star Scouting Report. She averaged 25.9
points and 5.2 assists last season and was named to USA Today's
All-USA honorable mention team. She also was named All-America by
Street &AMP; Smith's and earned state player of the year honors as a
13-year-old eighth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record my freshman year was 13-14,'' Gomez said. ``Each
year, we've improved and we're getting better and better. We're
getting more famous. People recognize us. Now, UCLA is known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
