<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-KOSOVO (Washington) _ U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke fails to
convince Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace
deal in the troubled Serbian province of Kosovo and heads to
Brussels to brief NATO chiefs. Meanwhile, President Clinton
consults congressional leaders to curry support for a NATO
bombardment. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-KOSOVO (Washington) _ With the NATO bombardment of
Serbian positions almost certain, the Senate scrambles to express
support for U.S. military personnel _ despite big questions about
wisdom of President Clinton's policies in the Balkan region. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-GAMBLING (Washington) _ Lawmakers, led by Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz., renew their push to enact legislation that would ban
gambling over the Internet. It's now a $600-million-a-year business
that is mushrooming. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ Relatives of James Byrd Jr., the
Texan who was dragged to death behind a pickup truck, and Matthew
Shepard, a gay student slain in Wyoming, call for state and federal
laws against hate crimes. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SEARCHES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court, weighing the
constitutionality of the war on drugs, considers whether the police
need a warrant before seizing and searching a car suspected of
having been used in a cocaine deal. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-ANTHRAX (San Antonio) _ A soldier who was twice demoted and
then discharged from the Army for refusing to take an anthrax
vaccination says he has no regrets about the position he took.
Robert Garner Jr., 23, says he was given an ``other than honorable
discharge,'' averting a military trial. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROCKET-MAN (Houston) _ Bradley Barker, the suspect in the 1998
slaying of Joseph Wright, says he is not the killer and plans to
file a lawsuit against the Harris County Sheriff's Department.
Barker says he was in Fort Smith, Ark., at the time of the killing.
Wright and Barker were involved in a lawsuit with their business
partner over a rocket belt, the direct descendent of the one used
in the 1965 James Bond movie ``Thunderball.'' By ERIC HANSON.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-TEXAS (San Antonio) _ In a speech that was heavy on themes
but light on specifics, unannounced Republican presidential
candidate Elizabeth Dole tells oil industry representatives that
the public has lost faith in the federal government. By MATT
FLORES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ORGANS-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A state Senate committee approves
a closely watched bill that would require organs harvested in Texas
to go to in-state patients first. Opponents are vocal on this new
frontier of protectionism, but the Houston lawmakers pushing the
bill are lining up co-sponsors. By JULIE MASON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Senate passes a bill
that would increase penalties for drug dealers to a maximum of 15
years in prison if someone dies as a result of using that drug. The
penalty is now a maximum of two years. By KATHY WALT. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-INVESTMENTS (Austin, Texas) _ State Rep. Sylvester Turner,
D-Houston, says he wants to do something to create greater public
disclosure about whether funds invested by the University of Texas
Investment Management Co. are prudently managed. Turner says he
believes this can be done without revealing investment strategies.
By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-MEETING (Vienna, Austria) _ A group representing most of
the world's biggest oil-producing nations agrees to slash crude oil
production by 2.1 million barrels per day in a concerted effort to
boost oil prices. By DAVID IVANOVICH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Hillary Clinton may chat with the
ghost of Eleanor Roosevelt in the White House corridors, but
Elizabeth Dole also has a lot in common with Franklin Roosevelt's
intelligent, independent-minded wife. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-UCONN (Undated) _ Over the past decade, Jim Calhoun has
built one of the nation's elite college basketball programs at
Connecticut. Year after year, his teams have been nationally ranked
and highly seeded, yet this year marks UConn's first trip to the
Final Four. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-OHIOSTATE (Undated) _ For a school that produced such
college basketball legends as Jerry Lucas and John Havlicek, Ohio
State had fallen on hard times in recent years. Before this year's
magical run to the Final Four, the Buckeyes had endured seven
consecutive losing seasons and hadn't been to the Final Four since
1968. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ Riding high with seven wins in their
past eight games, the Houston Rockets believe they are starting to
fit all the pieces together. And as they head into what looms as a
relatively easy part of the schedule, they know this is their time
to make a move in the Western Conference playoff standings. By
MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
