<HEADER>
A1502 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOTEL-DIVERSITY-COX     03-23 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-DIVERSITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lodging industry told to brace for changes
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hospitality executives were told Tuesday to expect ``a
tremendous amount of change'' in the lodging industry, including
further consolidation among hotel owners, more high-tech services
in rooms and greater diversity among workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last decade has been known as the golden era of the
lodging industry,'' said Valerie Ferguson, regional vice president
and managing director of Loew's Philadelphia Hotel and former
chairwoman of the American Hotel &AMP; Motel Association. She gave her
outlook at an industry summit on diversity, held at the Hyatt
Regency in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, more than 45 mergers among hotel
companies have been completed and that's not expected to stop, said
Ferguson, a former general manager of the Hyatt Regency and
Ritz-Carlton hotels in Atlanta. At least 15 deals have been
announced this year. Much of the activity has been fueled by Wall
Street's interest in the lodging industry, resulting in a
``deluge'' of money, she said. There are 75 publicly traded hotel
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong summit was sponsored by the Atlanta Convention &AMP;
Visitors Bureau's diversity marketing committee in conjunction with
the Atlanta Business League, the Asian American Hotel Owners
Association and the Atlanta Hispanic Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said technology will allow hotels to offer guests
offices away from the office, with services such as
teleconferencing, computers and Internet access from their rooms.
But there are few issues more important to the industry than
managing diversity, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our markets and labor pool are becoming increasingly
diverse,'' said Ferguson, one of the highest-ranking women and
African-Americans in the hospitality industry.
</P>
<P>
   She warned that few companies can risk a public relations
disaster similar to what happened with the Denny's restaurant
chain. Five years ago, Denny's paid $54.4 million to settle two
class action lawsuits that alleged racial discrimination. Recently
the company announced a $2 million advertising campaign aimed at
sparking discussions on the importance of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the industry employs about 16 million people. That is
expected to grow between 30 percent and 40 percent over the next
decade. Employees filling those jobs will come from the nation's
fast-growing minority populations _ Hispanics, African-Americans
and Asians, Ferguson said. With an annual turnover rate of 52
percent, the industry is challenged is to hire _ and retain _
workers from diverse backgrounds, she added.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the industry has maintained an ``average'' grade
addressing those issues, said Gerry Fernandez, president of the
Multi-Cultural Foodservice &AMP; Hospitality Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   On the marketing side, Fernandez said hospitality executives
must recognize the buying power of minorities. African-Americans
alone have estimated purchasing power of $450 billion annually, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is taking the first step by coming together to
collect research and plant the seeds for the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be easy, he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black community has not had a positive image of the
industry,'' Fernandez said. ``The image for years is that all we
can do is cook and clean. And the industry has done nothing to
change that perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, possibilities include management jobs as well as
ownership of restaurants and hotel properties. Atlanta businessman
Gary A. Cross is tapping into those opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Cross is among a group of entrepreneurs who recently purchased
the 100-room Travelodge Suites in downtown Macon. He also is one of
the developers of a new hotel planned for Auburn and Piedmont
avenues in Atlanta. The proposed hotel is expected to open next
year at the site of the now closed Palamont Motor Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Cross said he once sold hotel franchises. He observed that other
ethnic and racial groups often banded together and bought or
developed properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized they controlled a lot of the money and a lot of the
power, especially to employ people,'' he said. ``When
African-Americans own properties, we can do likewise. We can hire
people and trade with other African-American businesses. That's
true economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelia M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
