<HEADER>
A1506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED24-COX     03-23 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burbage soars to take on Lockheed challenge
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tom Burbage is used to hot seats.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 3 1/2 years, he's led Lockheed Martin Corp.'s
high-profile F-22 fighter program, shepherding it through a barrage
of technical and political obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   He once was a Navy test pilot, and he's an avid rower who hopes
to participate in a national masters competition on Lake Lanier
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Now Burbage, 51, is taking on another challenge as the new
president of Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems, headquartered at
the company's Marietta, Ga. plant.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion, announced last week, makes Burbage the division's
fourth president in five years. He follows the retiring Bill
Bullock, who was installed in 1997 to troubleshoot problems, cut
costs and improve manufacturing processes at Cobb County's largest
private employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really just kind of begun that journey,'' Burbage said.
``My job is to try and take us to the next level, to increase the
competitiveness of the company and expand the business base.''
</P>
<P>
   Burbage assumes responsibility for all plant programs, which
include the F-22 and the updated C-130J cargo plane _ both facing
near-term obstacles _ along with modification work on other planes.
</P>
<P>
   Plant employment has dwindled from 11,500 to 9,200 in the past
five years, and it will fall more if sluggish C-130J sales don't
pick up soon.
</P>
<P>
   There's even been speculation Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed
Martin might close the Marietta plant and move its programs, a
theory roundly denied by the company.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage exudes glass-half-full optimism, noting the plant has
fared better than a lot of contractors in the post-Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've probably got the most robust portfolio of any military
aircraft manufacturer, with both the F-22 and the C-130J here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage said he's confident the F-22 will enter production
despite concern about high costs that the General Accounting Office
last week warned will exceed congressional caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the Air Force needs and wants the plane,
although it will be procured in smaller numbers than anyone ever
envisioned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be cost pressures, but we feel we're
on top of them and are within the congressional caps. The GAO's
report tended to mischaracterize some of that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he's confident Lockheed Martin will secure enough
U.S. and foreign C-130J orders to sustain production beyond 2001,
when current orders will be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage, who formally assumes the president's job April 5, said
he's not yet ready to talk about any strategy shifts or structural
changes he might implement.
</P>
<P>
   His selection was a mild surprise. Executive Vice President
Terry Graham, a Lockheed Martin veteran who had left the company
but was brought back as Bullock's No. 2, was considered by some the
more likely successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been on the F-22 for 3 1/2 years, and that's about as
long as anyone stays on a program like that,'' Burbage said. ``So I
was expecting to move, but where was another question.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham remains in the executive vice president post, a key
day-to-day operations and marketing job.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage is a 19-year Lockheed Martin veteran who moved to the
Marietta plant in 1991, after prior stints in California and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He's a Naval Academy graduate and spent 11 years in the Navy,
mainly as a test pilot. One of his three daughters followed his
footsteps into Annapolis and the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage no longer flies but recently rode in the back seat of an
F-15 chase plane to watch an F-22 during a flight test over Edwards
Air Force Base in California.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than just an executive perk, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt like I needed to see the airplane in the air,''
he said. ``You get a really vivid picture of how it flies that
really can't be duplicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Burbage is known as a candid and unpretentious executive. He's
sometimes kidded for folding his 6-foot-4 frame into a well-used
Honda del Sol he drives back and forth to his home in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets harassed a lot for that car,'' said his wife of 30
years, Ellen, who drives an even older Honda Civic. ``Our cars
don't identify who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Burbage's rowing hobby is rooted in a devotion to fitness _ he
goes to work early to work out at the plant gym _ but has become
more than that. He admits his plans for the national competition in
August might be sidetracked by the demands of his new job but
added, ``I'm going to keep trying to shoot for it.''
</P>
<P>
   When twilight allows, he's known in his neighborhood as the guy
who rows a skull on a small lake near the Burbages' house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always watches him row up and down this lake,'' Ellen
Burbage said. ``I'm a little concerned he may not have time now,
but I can't see him giving it up.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TOM BURBAGE FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Title: President, Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems
</P>
<P>
   _ Responsibilities: All programs handled at Lockheed Martin's
Marietta plant
</P>
<P>
   _ Prior jobs: Vice president for F-22 fighter program since
1995; vice presidencies for Lockheed Martin Navy programs, the AFX
aircraft program, business development and Washington operations
</P>
<P>
   _ Education/military service: Naval Academy graduate, MBA from
UCLA and master's in aeronautical systems from the University of
West Florida. Eleven years of active Navy duty
</P>
<P>
   _ Personal: 51 years old. Married to Ellen Burbage, three
daughters. Home in Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
