u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT &LR;      03-23 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV OFFICIAL DEFENDS BELGRADE'S POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-U.S.,
RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(HLW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The Yugoslav foreign minister said on
Tuesday that his country could not accept a ``biased policy of
diktat'' from the West, whose bombing would violate international
law.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the minister, Zivadin Jovanovic, was by turns
sarcastic and defiant, saying Yugoslavia threatens no other country
and did not deserve to be bombed for offending Washington's pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia desires a peaceful resolution to Kosovo that
provides extensive autonomy, self-government, democracy and human
rights to the province's population,'' he said. But Yugoslavia, as
a sovereign state, ``cannot accept foreign troops to occupy our
land, while our authorities and forces must leave the territory.
What kind of sovereignty is that?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   In ``an internal affair,'' and without going to the United
Nations, both NATO and the United States are ``destroying the
system of international law,'' Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the United States cared only about inserting NATO
troops into Kosovo, not about any just political settlement there,
and desired to punish Belgrade because Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright ``could not bear the idea of her failure.''
</P>
<P>
   He denied that Serbian forces were engaged in an offensive
against the Kosovo Liberation Army or burning ethnic Albanian
villages, saying that Belgrade's troops were only responding to
attacks upon them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he himself understood the consequences for a Yugoslavia
at war with the West, its army damaged, its isolation deepened, its
poor economy further degraded, Jovanovic said he understood them
very well. ``We may develop at a slower pace,'' he said, smiling
thinly, ``but we will develop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
