<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-WOMEN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's Final four will have to do without regulars as Lady Dogs
get set for Duke
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A women's Final Four without Tennessee or Connecticut?
The giants of women's college basketball, who defined the sport in
this decade, are nowhere to be found with a national championship
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there's Georgia, which will be making its fifth trip to
the Final Four under coach Andy Landers and its third in five
years. With only one senior on the team, Georgia secured its Final
Four berth Monday with an 89-71 victory over Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's better this time because nobody expected us to be
there,'' said Georgia senior Pam Irwin-Osbolt.
</P>
<P>
   The last two times Georgia advanced to the Final Four, Tennessee
blocked the road to the national title. But with the Lady Vols and
Connecticut eliminated, the path toward a possible national
championship appears to be clearer.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was in line to play both, had they not been knocked off
_ UConn by Iowa State in the Mideast semifinals and the Lady
Volunteers by Duke in the East finals on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Tennessee has done has been good for women's basketball,
as did Connecticut's undefeated season (1994-95),'' Landers said.
``Their stories have been good. But when it's the same people over
and over again, it becomes kind of predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The road took a twist and a turn and a fork somewhere else,''
he said, ``and that's good for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Landers and his players expressed some regret that they
didn't get another chance at Tennessee, which accounted for three
of Georgia's six losses this season. The Lady Dogs will face Duke,
which upset the three-time defending champion 69-63 in the East
Regional to become the first school to have men and women in the
Final Four in the same year since Georgia in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia team was en route to Athens, Ga. from Cincinnati
late Monday when word came that their SEC rivals would not be
joining them in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really weren't concerned with who we were going to play, we
were just excited about going to the Final Four,'' junior forward
Angie Ball said. ``I kind of wish we were the team that knocked
them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the absence of the two traditional powers, the Final
Four should have enough fresh stories to savor while the Tennessee
and UConn camps watch the action from the comfort of their living
rooms. Georgia, which will be making its fifth trip to the Final
Four and will play Duke on Friday, isn't an unfamiliar name among
the game's elite despite never having won it all. Neither is
three-time champion Louisiana Tech, which has 12 previous Final
Four appearances but hasn't been in the winner's circle for 11
years.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's first and only trip came in 1994, and Duke has never
been this far before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wide-open now,'' Louisiana Tech's Monica Maxwell said.
``It's anybody's championship to win.'' The Lady Dogs are striving
to maintain the consistency that has steered them in the
post-season. Although the team has only two upperclassmen among its
regulars, Landers said this year's team is starting to jell, much
like his young 1995 Final Four team did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, like I told the other groups, that there's
greatness that's waiting to come out,'' Landers said. ``It was
about the regionals that they started to dig some of it out. This
group hasn't always been the picture of consistency, but we're
starting to come together at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Landers and his players expressed some regret they didn't get
another chance at Tennessee, which accounted for three of Georgia's
six losses this season. The Georgia team was enroute to Athens late
Monday when word came that their SEC rivals would not be joining
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really weren't concerned with who we were going to play, we
were just excited about going to the Final Four,'' junior forward
Angie Ball said. ``I kind of wish we were the team that knocked
them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the absence of Tennessee and Connecticut in the Final
Four, the Lady Dogs are striving to maintain the consistency that
has steered them in the post-season. Despite having only two
upperclassmen among its regulars, Landers said this year's team is
starting to jell much like his young 1995 Final Four team did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, like I told the other groups, that there's
greatness that's waiting to come out,'' Landers said. ``It was
about the regionals that they started to dig some of it out. This
group hasn't always been the picture of consistency, but we're
starting to come together at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S FINAL FOUR
</P>
<P>
   At San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's games
</P>
<P>
   _ Duke (28-6) vs. Georgia (27-6), 7 or 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Purdue (32-1) vs. Louisiana Tech (30-2), 7 or 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Championship game:
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   All games on ESPN
</P>
