u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMP2000-COLUMN-COX     03-23 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMP2000-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgians wary of jumping on bandwagon too early
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In some states, politicians have flocked to the
presidential-campaign-in-waiting of Texas Gov. George W. Bush. The
scene is somewhat different in Georgia, and the experience of four
years ago may have something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   By this time in 1995, Georgia's Republican congressional
delegation was in lock step behind Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas) and
his well-financed presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The move was led by Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell, and the
support extended to statewide officials and state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The hope was that when the campaign headed south after the Iowa
Caucuses and the New Hampshire Primary, Gramm would be
well-positioned to score momentum-generating wins in South Carolina
and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff?
</P>
<P>
   Gramm dropped out of the race before the Georgia Primary and the
politicians scrambled to throw their support elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly did not work out too well being out there early
last time,'' said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), who so far is uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the unhappy outcome with Gramm, Coverdell is again
leading the charge, this time for Bush, and he has Reps. Mac
Collins and Charlie Norwood with him.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the delegation has declined to make an
endorsement so far. Other Georgians are choosing sides. Cobb
Commission Chairman Bill Byrne, Gwinnett Commission Chairman Wayne
Hill and David Ralston, the 1998 GOP nominee for state attorney
general, are co-chairmen of Lamar Alexander's Georgia steering
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. Mack Mattingly is a national co-chairman of the
campaign of former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine publisher Steve Forbes has former Georgia Christian
Coalition Chairman Jerry Keen seeking support among religious
conservatives nationwide. And state Republican Chairman Rusty Paul
will join the Forbes campaign when he steps down as chairman in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Primary concern
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Zell Miller changed the date of Georgia's presidential
primary in 1992 and reaped a reward, a keynote address at the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   If Gov. Roy Barnes has similar hopes, he had better think again.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has said he is considering moving up the primary from
March 7, when California and New York, and possibly Florida and
Pennsylvania, also will hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   His concern is that Georgia would be lost among the behemoths of
presidential politics. The nominees in both parties may very well
be known by the time the votes are counted on the 7th. But
advancing the primary is unlikely to generate the kind of attention
from the candidates and the media that Georgia saw in 1992. Miller
led the fight to change the date so that Georgia would vote before
most other Southern states. Miller's candidate, then-Arkansas Gov.
Bill Clinton, won his first primary in Georgia and did not look
back.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Republican pollster Whit Ayres said, ``Whatever
attention you get will likely last just a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   State Republican Chairman Rusty Paul said he isn't sure that
many campaigns will even make a big push in the South because of
the looming contest in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that a little bit of money could get you a big
kick in Iowa and New Hampshire. Then you headed south with some
momentum,'' Paul said. ``You can't do that this time. If you don't
go play in California, it's over.''Staying in the House
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley (R-Fla.) had already met with Majority Leader
Dick Armey and Majority Whip Tom DeLay last week when he got a call
from aides to Speaker Dennis Hastert. ``They said he was coming to
see me and the topic would be remaining in the House,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley took himself out of the running last week for the Senate
seat that Sen. Connie Mack will give up at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in both parties are pressuring their members to stay put
because a change of just six seats in 2000 would swing control of
the House to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is on districts that would be competitive were there
no incumbent. At least eight Democrats with notions of running for
the Senate have heard from party leaders, said Erik Smith,
spokesman for the House Democrats' campaign committee. ``We tell
them, `We need you here. You have a great opportunity to serve in
the majority and you will have a whole lot more power here than as
a freshman senator in the minority,''' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Rep. Robert Menendez (D-N.J.) and Rep. Sherrod Brown
(D-Ohio) have agreed to pass up Senate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders also are pleading with members whose
term-limit pledges come due next year. Rep. Tillie Fowler (R-Fla.)
and Rep. George Nethercutt (R-Wash.) are weighing running again in
spite of their pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse won't run
</P>
<P>
   Two-time Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson is
expected to announce today that he will pass up another try for the
White House in 2000, The Associated Press reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is supposed to make the announcement on the campaign Web
site of his son, Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr. (D-Ill.). The site is
www.jessejacksonjr.org.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
