<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS24-COX     03-23 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE VOTES TO AUTHORIZE AIR STRIKES IN KOSOVO CRISIS
 &HT;    560&AMP;add. With KOSOVO-US.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate provided last-minute support Tuesday
night for a NATO air assault on Yugoslavia, voting 58-41 to
authorize the attacks even as U.S. and allied pilots prepared to
carry them out.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution authorized President Clinton ``to conduct
military air operations and missile strikes ... in cooperation with
our NATO allies.'' But several senators made clear they expected
Clinton to seek fresh approval from Congress before sending U.S.
ground forces to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts are widespread in Congress about the goals, costs and
exit strategy for the operation, intended to protect rebelling
ethnic Albanians in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo from attacks by
the government in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday morning, the Senate appeared ready to vote on a
resolution that would have blocked funding for the military action.
But after the president met with about 30 leaders from both parties
at the White House to tell them that the strikes were imminent,
resistance evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Senate's most outspoken critic of the military action,
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, emerged from the White House
resigned to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not we agree with the policy, it's a different
question ... if, in fact, troops are in harm's way,'' she said in
announcing that she was dropping her resolution. The measure would
have blocked funds for the intervention unless a peace agreement
was reached first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want (President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia)
to get the impression that the troops would not have the full
support and that the president wouldn't have the support.'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Senate floor Tuesday evening, Hutchison repeated her
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing a sovereign country that has not threatened the United
States of America is a very serious step,'' she said. ``I think it
is premature to do what we are going to be doing.'' She voted
against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   While she was willing to drop her move to block the air strikes,
Hutchison said, she had extracted a promise from Republican leaders
``that if there is going to be a war declared, it will be Congress
that will declare it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans shared Hutchison's misgivings about involving
American troops in a civil struggle that has roots going back 600
years and no clear resolution in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still am concerned about taking military action in a country
where there's conflict within their own borders,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi. ``How will it be paid
for? Where will it lead?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton of Washington compared the authorization of
air strikes to the Gulf of Tonkin resolution that was used as the
legal basis for the buildup of troops for the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma said, ``I don't think you can
bomb a country into a peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic backers countered that the action was necessary to
uphold NATO and stave off chaos in the former Yugoslavia, even as
they conceded that the public was not yet convinced about the
necessity of sending U.S. planes to war.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, the most vigorous defender of
intervention, said lawmakers had urged Clinton to work much harder
to persuade the American public. Biden said they told Clinton: ``We
should be with you, but make your case to the American people more
clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has promised to address the nation on the planned
bombing, although no date has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps of greater concern to lawmakers was the absence of a
clear route out of the Kosovo involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we start this process, we better be prepared to finish it,
which means we better be prepared to go to Belgrade,'' Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla., said, complaining that the Clinton administration
had not satisfied his concerns about long-range policy in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said military action was necessary to back up the
repeated threats the United States has made by ``drawing a line in
the sand which Milosevic keeps kicking in our face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no good news in it,'' said Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga.,
who supported Clinton but also raised questions about how the
operation. ``We have to define our objectives,'' he said, adding
that the goals should be as modest as possible so that the forces
can be withdrawn quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do is keep the bar low enough that (the
goals) can be achieved,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
