u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV-NYT &LR;      03-23 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PRIME MINISTER ABRUPTLY CANCELS TRIP TO WASHINGTON WHILE EN
ROUTE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-U.S., RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shortly after 1 p.m. on Tuesday, an angry Russian
prime minister, en route to Washington for some of the most
important talks of his short tenure, ordered his pilot to turn his
Ilyushin airliner around and return to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov was a few hundred miles
northeast of Newfoundland when he received a satellite telephone
call from Vice President Al Gore. Gore grimly informed him that a
last-minute diplomatic effort had failed and that the United States
and NATO were preparing to deliver a barrage of air and missile
strikes against Serbian targets in Kosovo and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov was in an untenable situation, having argued for months
against the use of force against Moscow's allies in Serbia.
Whatever he might have hoped to gain from three days of meetings _
with President Clinton, Gore, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and officials of the International Monetary Fund _ was now
overshadowed by the likelihood of American-led military action in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primakov told the vice president, `We categorically oppose
this,''' according to a senior American official privy to the
telephone conversation. ``He was so committed to coming here that
he took it as far as he possibly could, until he realized he
couldn't avoid a situation that he found completely unacceptable.
So he turned back.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's abrupt decision to cancel his visit to Washington was
a mark of the significant souring in the U.S.-Russian relationship.
Administration officials said that the split over Kosovo, which has
been festering for some time, could poison discussions on a variety
of matters, particularly Russia's desperate need for cash to cover
its foreign debts and keep its economy functioning.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, like all Russian prime ministers under the
unpredictable President Boris Yeltsin, is also in a precarious
domestic political position. His mission to Washington was designed
in part to bolster his political standing at home by presenting him
in high-profile meetings with top officials to negotiate for new
commitments of Western financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had warned Primakov for the past
several days of the awkward timing of his visit, with the United
States and its European allies preparing to carry out an ultimatum
to President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. But Primakov pressed
on, even after Gore told him at 9:30 on Tuesday morning, when
Primakov was in Shannon, Ireland, for a refueling stop, that there
was little hope that Milosevic would relent and accept allied
demands that he withdraw his forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:50 a.m., Primakov left Shannon, intent on coming to
Washington until 1 p.m., when Gore reached him aboard his aircraft
with word that allied air strikes were imminent. Richard Holbrooke,
the U.S. troubleshooter for the Balkans, had just left Belgrade,
where his efforts to persuade Milosevic to back down were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov was approaching Gander, Newfoundland, not far from U.S.
airspace, when Gore's call was connected. A senior administration
official paraphrased Gore's side of the conversation this way:
``Yevgeny, my friend, this is what happened in Belgrade. We feel we
must go to the next stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The official added, ``In no sense did we uninvite him or make
him unwelcome. We just wanted him to know what cards he had in his
hand. The Russians had always said that if the bombing began while
Primakov was in Washington, he would speak out strongly against it
and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov and Gore are co-chairs of the U.S.-Russia Joint
Commission, a body that meets twice a year to discuss a variety of
matters of common interest. This session was to have been devoted
to Russia's dire economic situation, particularly its inability to
make good on $17 billion in interest payments due this year to
international lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda also included arms control, the environment,
agricultural sales and efforts to halt the spread of nuclear
weapons. But all that will have to wait. Gore and Primakov did not
set a date to reconvene.
</P>
<P>
   In a formal statement issued by the White House on Tuesday, Gore
said: ``The prime minister and I are both committed to a strong
bilateral relationship,'' ``and we are both convinced that work of
the commission helps strengthen that relationship. We will take up
the important work of the commission at a time when both sides can
better focus their attention on the issues before us.''
</P>
<P>
   The bland words mask a deep division between Washington and
Moscow over the Balkans that dates to the collapse of the Soviet
Union and the unraveling of Yugoslavia. Friction over the expected
NATO military action could affect the broader relationship between
the two major powers, administration officials acknowledged on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright made an effort on Tuesday to contain the damage from
the dispute over Kosovo, according to aides. She spoke by telephone
for more than a half-hour with her Russian counterpart, Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov, said James P. Rubin, the State Department
spokesman. Albright told him she hoped the United States and Russia
could find a way ``to deal with the situation and continue to work
in other ways,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has expended huge amounts of time and money
into bringing Russia into the global trading system as well as
keeping its 7,000 nuclear warheads under close control. Russia's
failing economy has produced a long-running crisis that has caused
enormous hardship among the Russian people as well as jitters among
Russia's global lenders. Moscow is also irritated at the expansion
of NATO to include Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is putting a lot of strain on our ability to conduct some
of these other negotiations,'' one official said. ``Do we recognize
that the Kosovo thing hasn't made it any easier? You bet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
