</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-MAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN KILLING OF ROCKET BELT BUSINESS PARTNER DENIES
WRONGDOING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ark., N.Y.) 
(See optional ending) 
 
By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The man Harris County sheriff's detectives call the
only suspect in the slaying of his rocket belt business partner
denies any role in the killing and says he plans to sue the county
for violating his civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly had nothing to do with his murder,'' Bradley W.
Barker said Tuesday, ``absolutely not, absolutely, positively
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The rocket belt, a Buck Rogers-type contraption strapped on like
a backpack, is similar to the rocket belt used in the 1965 James
Bond movie ``Thunderball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officials have said their investigation has eliminated
all possible suspects other than Barker, who said he was in Fort
Smith, Ark., when Joseph Wright, 37, was beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   His body was found July 19 in his northwest Harris County home.
Harris County, which includes most of Houston, has 3.1 million
people and is the largest county in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Barker, 44, said he has no idea who killed Wright and had not
spoken to him for at least a year before his death.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, Barker and Thomas L. Stanley were partners in American
Rocket Belt Corp., which owned a hydrogen peroxide-powered rocket
belt, dubbed the RB2000. The belt could propel a man aloft for
about 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The belt is an improved version of a machine developed in the
early 1960s by Wendell Moore, an engineer at Bell Aircraft in
Buffalo, N.Y. Built for the Department of Defense, its 20-second
flight duration made it impractical. Since the patents on that belt
have expired, others have copied the design and improved it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Stanley sued Barker and Wright for allegedly conspiring
to defraud the corporation of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   Four days before his death, Wright agreed to help Stanley, 54,
recover the rocket belt, last flown publicly at an NBA party for
the Houston Rockets at the Houston Ship Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot who flew in that event, Bill Suitor of Lewiston, N.Y.,
said he unstrapped the belt after the flight and handed it to
Barker, who put it in a trailer and drove off.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said he does not have the rocket belt and does not know
where it is.
</P>
<P>
   He said sheriff's detectives took him into custody Aug. 19 and
held him for two days without charges being filed and denied his
requests for an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have just tormented me,'' he said. ``They have told my
family members that I killed this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Barker said several people in Arkansas told detectives he was
there at the time of the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have definitely slandered my name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Major Juan Jorge said the department received a letter
from Barker in September concerning the allegations, but that he
has never made a formal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge said Barker has informed him that he would have to make a
sworn statement to the department's internal affairs unit before it
could look into his allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge noted that Barker was in the County Jail recently on a
theft charge and did not even file a formal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   That charge accuses Barker of theft of a firearm from Stanley. A
hearing is scheduled April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said the charge is false and part of Stanley's vendetta
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said the lawsuit and slaying of Wright have dominated
his life for several years.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1994, Stanley said, Barker attacked him with a
hammer, splitting his head open and nearly tearing off a finger.
Barker was convicted and received deferred adjudication. Charges
against Stanley were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said he wants the rocket belt back as well as other
assets of the corporation amounting to about $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   That case is scheduled for trial May 17 in the 269th Civil
District Court in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rocket belt contains two tanks filled with hydrogen peroxide
and a third containing nitrogen under high pressure. When the
throttle is opened, the nitrogen pushes the hydrogen peroxide into
a catalyst pack, made up of tightly packed samarium nitrate-coated
silver screens.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the catalyst, the propellant turns into
high-pressure superheated steam that blasts out two nozzles,
providing the lifting thrust.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
