<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS-8     03-23 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE AND MILOSEVIC: REPULSION, RANCOR, RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-U.S.,
RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ When Slobodan Milosevic and Richard Holbrooke first met
in August 1995, an onlooker remarked of their prolonged and
animated exchange, ``The two egos danced all night.''
</P>
<P>
   From that first encounter in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, through many
desperate sessions at the Bosnia peace talks in Dayton, Ohio, to
the fruitless talks in the Yugoslav capital Tuesday, a particularly
charged chemistry has existed between the Yugoslav president and
Washington's Balkan envoy: a web of repulsion, rancor and grudging
respect.
</P>
<P>
   Through its highs and lows, its tantrums and its truces, the
relationship has brought results _ most conspicuously, a belated
peace in Bosnia that was forged in Ohio in November 1995 and has
held ever since. But on Tuesday, it seems, nothing could be
conjured from the old ties, not even a diplomatic phrase.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in the Balkans is ``the bleakest since we began
this effort almost four years ago,'' Holbrooke told CNN, adding
that Milosevic was not even ready to enter serious talks on the
deployment of a NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   These words, bereft of any hint of compromise, appeared to open
the way for the United States and its allies to reverse course and
bomb the country led by the man they rehabilitated and turned into
their de facto ally at Dayton just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long road for Holbrooke. The observer who watched
and recorded the egos dancing that first night in Belgrade was
Robert Frasure, a seasoned State Department official who was killed
five days later in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, as Holbrooke knows, it was Milosevic who sent
Frasure and two other senior American officials to their deaths on
Aug. 19, 1995, by refusing to provide security guarantees for a
flight from Belgrade to Sarajevo and so obliging the officials to
take a dangerous mountain road where their vehicle crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since that accident, on a mission he was leading, Holbrooke
has been obsessed by the memory of his fallen colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a man seldom lacking in energy or drive, the loss has
added an overwhelming personal determination to somehow wrestle
Milosevic to the floor and bring an end to the wars of Yugoslavia's
slow destruction that began in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Another memory has also colored Holbrooke's relationship with
Milosevic, whose 12 years in power have coincided with an almost
uninterrupted cycle of killing. That memory is of the start of the
Bosnian war in the summer of 1992, when Holbrooke was a direct
witness to the murderous Serbian rampage against the Muslims that
marked the first six months of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In Banja Luka, at the heart of the horror, a Muslim survivor of
a Serbian concentration camp handed Holbrooke a wooden carving of
man with head bowed. Asked once if he thought of that carving when
speaking to Milosevic, he replied, ``No, it's not that linear.'' He
added: ``But I understand the connection. I'm sure we all do.''
</P>
<P>
   The connection, of course, is the one between Milosevic and the
killing for which he has so often denied responsibility: the single
chain that links the Serbian leader's quashing of Kosovo's autonomy
in the late 1980s, his relentless whipping of the Serbs into a fury
of nationalist indignation, and his arming of the marauding Serbian
militias of 1992 that hounded Muslim civilians into packed camps in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has never had any illusions about any of this; he
would not argue with the notion that he has been talking to an
unusually destructive man. But when he began his diplomacy in 1995,
he found Milosevic was anxious to end a Bosnian war that was
turning against the Serbs. There lay the seeds of a bond of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   There were other elements to the initial success of the
relationship. Milosevic's dismissal of detail _ referred to, in his
broken English, as ``mere technology'' _ was attractive to
Holbrooke, who likes the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian leader's extraordinary power _ he gave away Sarajevo
with a wave of the hand at Dayton _ was also useful to the American
envoy: In effect, Holbrooke was able to move fast because he had to
deal with only one man.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting, cajoling, laughing, raging, the two men gradually
learned how to deal with each other. Each understood that the other
had a deep respect for force. Milosevic has made a habit, as in
Kosovo, of applying military might even as he talks. Holbrooke was
convinced by the successful NATO bombing of Bosnia in 1995 that
Balkan diplomacy unbacked by force amounts to dithering.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoir of Balkan diplomacy, ``To End a War,'' Holbrooke
held back from an in-depth portrait of his Serbian interlocutor, no
doubt because, as events have proved, he knew he had unfinished
business.
</P>
<P>
   But at one point Holbrooke wrote, ``Watching Milosevic turn on
the charm, someone observed that had fate dealt him a different
birthplace and education, he would have been a successful
politician in a democratic system.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That ``charm'' has not been much in evidence of late, and it
seems clear that the intensity, even the thrill, of the two men's
initial jousting has gradually given way to a battle marked mainly
by sourness and mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   After his Kosovo diplomacy last October, which brought a fragile
truce that soon collapsed, Holbrooke expressed only exasperation
over his meetings with Milosevic, saying he would be happy if he
never had to return to Belgrade again.
</P>
<P>
   But events have brought this most forceful of American diplomats
back to the scene of his first meeting with Milosevic, only in
changed circumstances. Kosovo, of course, is not Bosnia. It is
still seen by many Serbs as the womb of their civilization; it
lies, formally speaking, within Serbia; it is the place where
Milosevic's rise to power began.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the question of placing foreign troops on Serbian soil
is as explosive as any can be in Belgrade. It was precisely
Serbia's refusal to allow the Austro-Hungarian police into the
country to investigate the killing of the Hapsburg heir, Archduke
Franz Ferdinand, that ushered in World War I. Such acts resonate in
Serbia as if they happened yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Having fought, for much of the last 200 years, for the territory
it now controls, Serbia is passionately, irrationally and often
destructively attached to every inch of it. Even a man of the power
of Milosevic can scarcely ignore this overwhelming national
sentiment, as Holbrooke knows.
</P>
<P>
   How, in these circumstances, he thought he could sway the
Serbian leader _ squeeze out one last waltz in the long dance _
remains unclear. On Tuesday the envoy expressed indignation at how
American plans were being ``grossly mischaracterized'' by Serbian
politicians and suggested that their comments revealed ``a lot of
history'' and ``a lot of misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing new about this state of affairs. A lot of
history and a lot of misunderstanding have accompanied Serbia's
destructive implosion for more than a decade. What is new is that
Holbrooke seems unable to use Milosevic to bully his way past the
Serbian bravura.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spent many hours with him, but I would not say that I
know him in the sense that I can see inside his mind,'' Holbrooke
said Tuesday of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy is about understanding even the most destructive of
minds. Holbrooke has proved unusually adept at that. But perhaps
his _ and America's _ patience with the Serbian leader has simply
run out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
