<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEVORKIAN-TRIAL-720&AMP;A     03-23 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVORKIAN-TRIAL-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTING AS HIS OWN LAWYER, KEVORKIAN STUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Insisting upon acting as his own lawyer in his
trial for first-degree murder, Dr. Jack Kevorkian stumbled
conspicuously through the first day of testimony on Tuesday, asking
witnesses legally inappropriate questions and raising impermissible
legal arguments as he tried to convince a jury to acquit him for
his role in ending the life of a seriously ill man.
</P>
<P>
   His lack of legal skill was especially evident as he sought to
call his first witness, the wife of the dead man. He was unable to
convince the judge that the woman's testimony was relevant and
should be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, what you seek to introduce is not cognizable under the
laws of the state of Michigan,'' Judge Jessica Cooper of Oakland
County Circuit Court told Kevorkian early Tuesday afternoon out of
the hearing of the jury, which was dismissed so that she could
discuss Kevorkian's efforts to introduce testimony from the wife,
and his other proposed witness, the dead man's brother. Prosecutors
contend that the testimony would serve only to promote the jury's
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law in Michigan is very clear,'' she said, patiently
explaining to the 70-year-old pathologist that she could not let
the man's relatives testify that the man consented to his death,
because consent is not a legal defense for murder. ``And I know
that you disagree with that,'' the judge continued, ``and I know
that that's what you want to talk to the jury about. But you can't.
The jury doesn't decide whether the law is correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, she decided that the defense would submit a brief by
Wednesday morning, laying out their arguments for the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented a key piece of evidence Tuesday: a
videotape that Kevorkian made of himself injecting the man, Thomas
Youk, with a fatal dose of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   But while that evidence and Kevorkian's weak performance as a
lawyer may allow prosecutors to shut down much of his legal
defense, it is hardly certain that a jury will convict him of
murder, which could mean a life sentence. Experts say it will be
tough to convince a jury that granting a desperately ill man's wish
to die is equivalent to the average person's idea of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Cooper was careful to lecture Kevorkian only when the jury
was out of the room. She repeatedly implored him to reconsider his
decision to represent himself. On Monday, before jury selection
began, she had cautioned him about the risks, asking if he had seen
the inside of a state prison. He said he had seen the prison-break
movie ``The Shawshank Redemption'' twice.
</P>
<P>
   In court on Tuesday, as Kevorkian's proposed witness was being
discussed, the judge said, ``You need to have counsel here and in
the waiver of counsel you put yourself in a difficult position.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kevorkian said he did not think a lawyer could explain his
position better. So the judge urged him to pay closer attention to
the coaching of two lawyers who were advising him on the case. From
the defense table, the lawyers, admittedly frustrated, frequently
beckoned to Kevorkian during his arguments, but he did not always
appear to heed what they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is attempting to convict you of murder in the first
degree,'' said the judge, referring to the prosecutor. ``If your
attorneys are telling you that there's something going on here that
you need to object to than you need to get up and object.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I cannot be here as a law professor and a judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, who claims to have helped more than 130 people commit
suicide, is on trial in the September death of Youk, 52, of
Waterford Township, Mich., who suffered from amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   It is the fifth trial for Kevorkian; he was acquitted three
times, and a fourth case ended in a mistrial. But in each of the
four previous trials he was charged with violating assisted suicide
laws, not with committing murder. In those cases, Kevorkian did not
inject people directly but used a ``suicide machine'' that allowed
them to pull a string and administer the dose themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In each of those trials, he was represented by the flamboyant
and aggressive lawyer Geoffrey Fieger, who helped persuade the jury
that Kevorkian was simply acceding to the wishes of a terminally
ill person.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In this case, prosecutors believe they can prove murder partly
because of Kevorkian's videotape, which he took to the CBS
television news program ``60 Minutes.'' The program was broadcast
in November, along with an interview in which Kevorkian dared
prosecutors to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution started and finished its case Tuesday morning,
presenting the videotape, along with excerpts from the ``60
Minutes'' broadcast. Kevorkian cross-examined two of the
prosecution's three witnesses, becoming confrontational with the
third, his longtime nemesis, the Oakland County medical examiner.
For example, he asked the medical examiner if he was personally
against euthanasia, a question not legally permissible.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, who has not yet said whether he will testify himself,
argues that he did not intend to kill Youk, only to end his
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors initially charged Kevorkian with assisted suicide as
well as murder, but they dropped the lesser charge after Judge
Cooper ruled that the defense could present evidence of Youk's pain
and suffering in an assisted suicide case, but not in a murder
case.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling appeared to be limiting the defense strategy on
Tuesday, as Kevorkian sought to have Youk's wife, Melody, testify
about how her husband wanted to end his suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're talking about is mercy killing,'' Judge Cooper
said, explaining that euthanasia is not a defense for murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you may say it's mercy killing, but I call it something
else,'' Kevorkian replied. ``I call it a medical service for an
agonized incurably suffering patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian appeared to be becoming agitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have fine stipulations of law standing in the way, to
a dedicated physician, and I am, my integrity would be killed,
destroyed if I turned my back on that patient,'' he said. ``That's
worse than taking my life. Why do you think I don't fear prison? My
intent is not to kill. It's to do my duty as a physician. And that
often has disagreeable outcomes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2023EST &QL; 
