<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1528 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STAKE-0324-cox     03-23 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STAKE-0324-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO CRISIS COMES DOWN TO AIRSTRIKES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- NATO on Tuesday ordered airstrikes against Serb
military positions, citing a ''moral duty'' to end the bloody
repression of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and a strategic interest
in preventing a widening conflict in the troubled Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   With U.S. pilots poised to lead the attack, President Clinton
said he reluctantly approved military action only after the
collapse of months of diplomacy aimed at halting a Serb campaign
that has left more than 2,000 dead and a quarter of a million
homeless in the tiny province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must stop an authoritarian regime from repressing its
people in Europe at the end of the 20th century,'' said NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana. ``We have a moral duty to do
so...and we will fulfill it.'' Hundreds of NATO warplanes and
support craft -- 250 of them American -- stood by ready to bomb the
Serbs and a half dozen U.S. ships and submarines awaited nearby,
bristling with long-range cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Calling on Americans ''to say a prayer,'' for the safety of U.S.
pilots, Clinton said the dangers they face are outweighed by the
risks of inaction, an option that would invite ``more massacres,
more refugees, more victims, more people crying out for revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a two-hour White House briefing on the crisis by
Clinton and his top foreign policy advisers, Republican and
Democratic congressional leaders emerged to offer support for the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 58-41 late Tuesday to support the mission, and
House Speaker Dennis Hastert said he expected a similar action on
his side of the Capitol soon.
</P>
<P>
   Solana announced the NATO decision hours after special U.S.
envoy Richard Holbrooke ended a last-ditch effort at diplomacy in
Belgrade, where Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia, repeated his opposition to a U.S.-backed plan that
calls for placing 28,000 NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As a somber Holbrooke left the Yugoslav capital, Milosevic
braced his country for imminent war and declared a nationwide state
of emergency, mobilizing thousands of troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case war is imposed on us, we will defend from the
aggressors with all available means,'' Gorica Gajevic, the
general-secretary of Milosevic's Socialist Party, said during an
emergency session of Serbian Parliament. ``We are not accepting
foreign military troops on our territory under any excuse and at
any price, even at the price of bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, some 40,000 Serb troops and police backed by an
estimated 300 tanks and other armored vehicles were massed in or
around Kosovo, a province of 2.2 million 90 percent of them ethnic
Albanians in the Yugoslav state of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Solana stressed that the NATO strikes he ordered are meant to
end the bloody repression those troops have inflicted upon ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, not the Serbian public at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is not waging war against Yugoslavia. We have no quarrel
with the people of Yugoslavia, a people who for too long have been
isolated in Europe because of the policies of their government,''
Solana said. ``Our objective is to prevent more human suffering,
more repression, more violence against the civilian population of
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the NATO decision prompted an immediate split between
the United States and Russia, which has opposed military strikes
against the Serbs, who share historic and cultural ties with the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic gesture high above the Atlantic, Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov cancelled a long-scheduled official visit
to the White House, ordering his airplane to turn around between
Ireland and Newfoundland after Vice President Al Gore, in a
15-minute telephone conversation, informed him of NATO's position.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Solana stressed the dangers the Kosovo crisis
poses to regional stability in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The tinderbox for World War I, a savage killing ground in World
War II and a frontier where East clashed uneasily with West
throughout the Cold War, the Balkans, Clinton said, have been an
achilles heel in European stability throughout a tumultuous
century.
</P>
<P>
   Both Solana and Clinton made clear, however, that the decision
to strike was driven by a determination in Washington and European
capitals to prevent a repeat in Kosovo of Serb offenses that left
more than 200,000 dead and another 3 million homeless in 3.5 years
of fighting in neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did we learn in Bosnia,'' Clinton said, speaking to a
group of state and local officials in Washington. ``We learned that
if you don't stand up to brutality and the killing of innocent
people, you invite the people who do it to do more of it. We
learned that firmness can save lives, and stop armies.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO airstrikes have two objectives.
</P>
<P>
   The primary goal is to compel Milosevic to accept the
international peace plan, and the NATO implementation force the
plan would mandate.
</P>
<P>
   White House and Pentagon officials acknowledge privately that
there's no assurance that military action would force Milosevic to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Failing that, the strikes would continue with the aim of
damaging the Serb military machine to the point that it could no
longer sustain its campaign of terror against Kosovo civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to prevent more human suffering, more
repression, more violence against the civilian population of
Kosovo,'' said Solana.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the House approved a measure backing the use
of U.S. troops as part of a NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo in
the event such a force was approved by both the Kosovar Albanians
</P>
<P>
   and Yugoslavia. For the moment, at least, Clinton has ruled out
the use of U.S. ground troops to try to impose peace upon Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a passionate plea for support for the NATO airstrikes, the
president recalled the war in Bosnia, in which Serb troops fought a
decision by the democratically elected Bosnian parliament to secede
from the former Yugoslavia, which shattered into five pieces
following the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Atrocities were committed by Serbs and non-Serbs alike in
Bosnia, but the vast majority of military attacks against civilians
were committed by Serbs. They laid siege to the city of Sarajevo,
routinely fired on women and children and systematically shelled
villages, burned homes and otherwise terrorized non-Serb
communities.
</P>
<P>
   That war ended in the fall of 1995, only after a week and a half
of NATO airstrikes against Serbs followed by weeks of U.S.-led
diplomacy ending in the Dayton peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted that the carnage and destruction Milosevic
visited upon Bosnia could not be repeated in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When President Milosevic started the war in Bosnia seven years
ago, the world did not act quickly enough to stop him,'' said
Clinton. ``Innocent people were herded into concentration camps.
Children were gunned down by snipers on their way to school. Soccer
fields and parks were turned into cemeteries...this was a genocide
in the heart of Europe. It did not happen in 1945; it was going on
in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
