<SLUG> BC-SIXFLAGS-SURVIVORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE HORROR OF CAPSIZED WATER RIDE, DEATH APPEARED NEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
And JAN JARVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As Ginny Venneberg described it, her two
young daughters were drowning in a ride at Six Flags Over Texas and
she was helpless to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   Venneberg herself was upside down under water. It was dark. She
was disoriented. Her leg was broken. She could not find her
children, and she feared the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we were going to make it,'' Venneberg, 40, said
Monday at Fort Worth's Cook Children's Medical Center, where she
and her daughters _ Jessica, 9, and Ashley, 7 _ described Sunday's
harrowing experience on the Roaring Rapids ride at Six Flags in
nearby Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   An Arkansas woman, Valeria Cartwright, died in the accident, and
10 people were injured, including the Vennebergs.
</P>
<P>
   Venneberg's husband, Fred, was kept overnight at Arlington
Memorial Hospital, where he was checked out for an irregular
heartbeat, probably due to the stress of the ordeal, Ginny
Venneberg said. Jessica had bruises on her stomach and back from
the raft's seat belt, and Ashley was unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Vennebergs had arrived Friday from Lawrence, Kan., for a
spring break vacation. It was their first visit to Six Flags, and
they were taking advantage of a free ticket that third-grader
Jessica had won in a competition called MathCounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Venneberg said the raft started taking on water soon after
the ride started.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the raft flipped, Venneberg said, water in the round
boat was at midcalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't draining away. I told another lady, `This boat is
going to sink,' '' she said. ``The boat kind of stopped on a ridge
like it couldn't get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly it was dark and they were under water, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Christie Wilson, 23, of Everman, Texas, was also on the raft.
She said that when she felt it popping up into the air, then
flipping over into the water, she was grateful that her friend
somehow managed to reach over and unhook the seat belt that held
them both in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had she not done that, I don't think I would be alive now, ''
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Once under water, Wilson said, she was apparently the only one
who did not have the seat belt still on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel people struggling, arms just trying and trying to
get the seat belt off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the confusion, Wilson didn't know what to think, she just
reacted, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all thought we were going to die,'' she said. ``The
water was very cold. I couldn't see anything because the water was
so dark green.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she got her bearings, Wilson spotted a little girl in the
water whose seat belt was still on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get the seat belt loose, so I just grabbed hold of
her and pulled her out,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   That little girl may have been Ashley Venneberg, who said she
wasn't sure who rescued her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another woman got me to a safe spot,'' Ashley said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, too, was unsure who the girl was amid the chaos. She
said she just struggled to hold the child's head above water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get out because we were too far from anything,''
Wilson said. ``She was barely breathing, and she had taken in a lot
of water. Finally somebody who worked there got another raft.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley's sister, Jessica, said she believes she and at least two
others were pulled out by her dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared. I thought I was going to die,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said she noticed that at least three people had jumped
into the water to help in the rescue. She said her friend tried to
help a man whose head was trapped between the rubber seal and the
hard plastic shell of the raft.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was trying her hardest to hold the raft up so he could get
out,'' she said. ``It was hard because the water was moving and she
was floating down the river with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the next thing she realized, was she was being
pulled to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Venneberg said her family had planned to stay in the area
for a week but that they were hoping to fly home yesterday evening
instead.
</P>
<P>
   She said she harbored no resentment toward the amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful my family is alive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica, asked if she would ever go on the ride again, said: ``I
won't go on that ride, but I'll go on other ones.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
