<SLUG> BC-SIXFLAGS-RESCUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK VISITOR TRIED TO SAVE WOMAN WHO LATER DIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAN JARVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Valeria Cartwright still had a pulse when
Wendy Crown began a desperate struggle to save her life as the
woman floated face up inside a raft in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a faint pulse; I had sporadic breathing,'' she said.
``There was still life going on in that body.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright, 28, of West Helena, Ark., was dead on arrival at an
Arlington hospital on Sunday after the Roaring Rapids raft she was
riding at Six Flags Over Texas in Arlington capsized. Ten others
were injured when the boat overturned in four feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Crown, who said she is certified as a master dive instructor,
was waiting with her son to ride the Roaring Rapids when she saw
the raft in the water underneath a bridge suddenly dip down, make a
loud noise and flip.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who is trained in water rescue, Crown said she was
prepared to offer her help as she began moving toward the area
where the boat capsized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hollered out, `I'm a dive instructor,' '' she said. ``A
staff person told me, `Do not go in the water.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But she could see wallets and watches floating in the water and
Crown said one Six Flags employee nearby appeared to be
hyperventilating. So Crown took off her hiking boots and went in
the water, where she could see people in the raft floating face up
in the water. She said she saw one man being tended to, so she
moved toward a woman whose eyes had rolled back in her head.
</P>
<P>
   She checked the pulse of the unconscious woman, who she later
learned was Cartwright. The woman's camera was still tied to her
belt when Crown approached her and began performing mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did five to eight breaths and she started throwing up in my
mouth,'' said Crown, 44, a financial adviser in Richardson. ``I
sensed that she had started breathing, then she convulsed.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued trying to revive her and estimated that it took
her 15 to 20 minutes to reach the dock, where a uniformed man
pulled her to the deck and took over.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the dock, Crown said, she ran into one of Cartwright's
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said a prayer on the dock,'' Crown said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
