<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXFLAGS-SAFETY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCEDURES AND SAFETY AT SIX FLAGS TO BE REVIEWED
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies SIX FLAGS-SURVIVORS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By SEAN WOOD c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ A review of safety procedures and emergency
responses will be part of a Six Flags Over Texas investigation of
an accident that killed a 28-year-old park guest Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Roaring Rapids ride had been inspected by park employees
Sunday morning and had a clean bill of health from the Texas
Department of Insurance. But an accident late Sunday afternoon
killed Valeria Cartwright and injured 10 other people.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials, ride safety inspectors, insurance officials and
safety officials from the park's corporate parent descended on Six
Flags on Monday to investigate the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really casting a very wide net,'' said Nancy St. Pierre,
Six Flags spokeswoman. ``We're looking at our procedures, how we
responded and what the ride was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The park does not require water-rescue training for the staff at
the ride, which sends passengers in rafts through a simulated set
of river rapids. St. Pierre said none of the park's water rides,
including Splashwater Falls and the Log Ride, requires water-rescue
training.
</P>
<P>
   That could change after a review of the accident, she said. She
would not speculate on whether more employees will be trained in
cardiopulmonary resuscitation. The only employees now required to
have CPR training are the park's paramedics. Four certified
paramedics were on duty at the park at the time of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   When the accident occurred, the ride operator brought the ride
to an emergency stop and notified park operations. Park operations
then called the security office and the health and safety office.
An official in the health and safety office dispatched two
paramedics to the scene to assess the situation before calling 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our employees did exactly what they are trained to do,'' St.
Pierre said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the park's paramedics arrived, St. Pierre said,
other park security and operations people had heard the call over
their radios and arrived on the scene. Park employees, along with
some Roaring Rapids passengers, helped free people from the
overturned raft, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, park officials said that they had no idea what caused
the accident and that the ride was in full compliance with state
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically looked to make sure everything was in order,''
said Mark Hanna, spokesman with the Texas Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance department requires that all rides be inspected
annually by either an independent ride inspector or the ride
owner's insurance company. Amusement parks also must carry at least
$1 million in liability insurance on each ride and must make
quarterly injury reports.
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre said all the rides at the park had been checked by an
independent inspector before March 6, the start of the park's 1999
operating season.
</P>
<P>
   The ride was also inspected Sunday morning by Six Flags
employees. Four departments _ fiberglass, electrical, mechanical
and operations _ signed off on it, park officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come out and reinspect each and every ride,'' St.
Pierre said. ``Every morning there is a major inspection. Every
inch of every ride is inspected.''
</P>
<P>
   During the off season, everything that carries passengers is
removed and tested for stress and structural damage. All seven
boats that were operating Sunday at the Roaring Rapids ride had new
components, such as tubes, seat belts, upholstery and ropes
securing the tubes to the raft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an impeccable safety record,'' St. Pierre said.
``Safety is paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   All employees working at a ride are tested on the park's
response to emergency situations and must correctly answer at least
90 percent of the questions, St. Pierre said.
</P>
<P>
   All five employees who were working at the ride at the time of
the accident are seasonal employees and had passed the required
safety tests, St. Pierre said. While some employees are trained on
more than one ride, St. Pierre said these employees were all
trained on the Roaring Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
