<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN24-COX     03-23 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO airstrikes only temporary solution to age-old conflict
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ For some reason I have a hard time keeping up with
who is killing whom over what in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the centuries-old religious and tribal feuds of
the Middle East is a walk in the park compared to that chunk of
land in Europe that has been conquered, split up, and forced
together so many times that there shouldn't be any fight left in
the current inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a millennium or two of being pushed around has made the
separate ethnic, cultural and religious groups fighting mad over
unresolved grudges passed from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
   Now the United States and NATO are prepared to take sides in
these ancient Balkan blood feuds by dropping bombs on Serbs who
have been busy killing and running off their own citizens in the
southern Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of Serbia's Kosovo residents are Albanians.
Albania is a country west and south of Serbia's Kosovo province.
Albania is primarily Muslim, whereas Serbia is primarily Orthodox
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo has never been an independent nation. But Kosovo's
Albanian secessionists proclaimed Kosovo as the independent
Republic of Kosovo in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army launched vicious attacks against
Serbian government forces. Predictably, that was followed by much
more vicious attacks by superior Serbian forces against Kosovo's
Albanian citizens.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevec and other Serbian officials
apparently have decided that if Kosovo's Albanians want to live in
an independent country then the Serbian military will force them
out of Serbia and back into Albania, or anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Serb nationalists are still resentful over the battle of Kosovo
Field in 1389 when Serbia's Prince Lazar was executed after his
capture by Turkish forces. A Serb posing as a deserter was able to
stab to death Turkish Sultan Murad I before Serbia fell under
Ottoman rule. That Serb, Milosh Obilich, is celebrated today.
Obilich's sacrifice 610 years ago is being used today to punish the
Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell the good guys from the bad guys in this region
of the world except when one side gets the upper hand and starts
killing noncombatants when there are television cameras around to
beam the carnage into homes worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The only times when these diverse ethnic, religious and cultural
groups in the Balkans have not been at each others' throats were
under repressive totalitarian regimes such as Germany's Nazis or
the Soviet Union's communism.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs were accused of employing similar ``ethnic cleansing''
policies against the Bosnians the last time President Clinton sent
U.S. military planes into the region. Then, as now, members of
Congress wanted to know exactly what was America's national
security interest in the former Yugoslavia and how long would our
troops be there.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments in support of U.S. military intervention in the
Balkans are basically two _ one strategic and the other ethical.
</P>
<P>
   The strategic argument holds that the violence must be contained
before it spills out to Macedonia, Greece and Turkey, causing
worldwide alliances to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   The ethical argument holds up the example of the Holocaust and
the shameful reluctance of the United States to get involved in
European affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Both are compelling arguments.
</P>
<P>
   It's inconceivable, however, that dropping a few bombs will have
any permanent impact. The animosities nurtured by the Balkan
peoples have roots that stretch back more than a thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans, we should do what we can, when we can, to relieve
suffering worldwide. At the same time, we must recognize that we
can't solve all the world's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
