<HEADLINE>
MALONE: OSUNA NOT READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ A year ago, right-hander Antonio Osuna began
the season as the Dodgers closer. This season he might begin it by
making rehab appearances with Single-A San Bernardino in the
California League.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who's encountered setbacks in trying to return from elbow
surgery, might not be ready for the season opener April 5 against
the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at him probably not being ready,'' Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone said Tuesday. ``There's no advantage taking
risks. If (he's ready) one week into the season, two weeks into the
season or a month, there's no reason to take a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who was 7-1 with six saves and a 3.06 ERA last season,
underwent surgery to remove a bone spur in his pitching elbow Sept.
8. He experienced discomfort in his elbow after throwing a few
bullpen sessions earlier in the spring. The Dodgers backed off his
work routine until the soreness went away, and Osuna threw on the
side with manager Davey Johnson late last week.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said there is nothing wrong with the repaired components
of the elbow and was pleased with Osuna's progress in the last few
days. However, Malone said he would like to get Osuna into five to
seven spring games before he's declared ready for the season.
Including today's game with the Cleveland Indians, the Dodgers have
11 exhibition games remaining, which doesn't give Osuna much time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things have to happen every day for us to think he can be
ready to open the season,'' Malone said. ``My guess is he'll be
close enough to where he'll go with us when we go west. If he needs
game action, San Bernardino won't be far behind us (in starting the
season) and he could go there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sheffield named in suit: The Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel
reported that Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield was named in a
paternity suit filed in Florida's Broward County Court. The suit
alleges Sheffield is the father of Garrett Wan-Dre Sheffield, born
Jan. 13 to Wandra Y. Carey.
</P>
<P>
   The paper said Carey is seeking child support, medical and life
insurance for the child. Sheffield wasn't in Dodgertown on Tuesday
because it was an off day. He couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The suit adds to the tumultuous spring training for him. He's
been plagued by a sore right shoulder, expressed frustration about
playing left field, talked about retirement and said he felt
singled out for Dodgers' stance against facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Johnson said shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek, bothered by shin splints the last few days, should be
ready to play today. . . . Right-hander Ismael Valdes continued his
stellar spring with another strong outing. He allowed one run on
five hits in five innings in a Triple-A game against the Florida
Marlins. Valdes struck out three and didn't walk a batter.
</P>
</TEXT>
