<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AZERBAIJAN DETAINS RUSSIAN MIG SHIPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV, KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Azerbaijan has detained a Russian transport plane that
was ferrying arms to Yugoslavia in violation of an international
embargo, a senior Azerbaijani official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Vafa Guluzade, chief foreign-policy adviser to
President Heydar Aliyev, said the transport plane was carrying six
MIG jet fighters for the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   Guluzade said the plane took off from Kazakhstan and was
impounded last week after stopping in Baku, capital of Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations brought a sharp denial from the Russian Foreign
Ministry, which insisted that the plane had been bound for
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Slovakia said, however, that they knew nothing
about the shipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Slovak Republic does not have any connection with these
MIG's,'' a spokesman for the defense ministry, Pavel Vitko, said in
a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the mystery, documents obtained by authorities in
Azerbaijan variously listed the cargo as destined for North Korea
and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The detention of the plane occurs at a critical juncture.
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov of Russia said on Tuesday that NATO
air strikes could lead to an end of the United Nations ban on arms
for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities insist that they have been abiding by the
embargo.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is a huge AN-124 with a Russian flag painted on the
nose that has been sitting at the Baku airport, cordoned off by
Azerbaijan guards, since last week. The crew and passengers _ 18
Russians and 14 Kazakhstan citizens of Russian ethnicity _ have had
their passports confiscated and are being detained at a hotel
there.
</P>
<P>
   The plane took off from the southern Kazakh city of
Taldy-Kurgan. Russian-made fighters are stored in Kazakhstan
because of its dry weather, according to Paul Beaver of Jane's
Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   Russian air force officials said the plane was owned by the
Volga-Dnieper Co., which controls much of the air-cargo business in
Russia. The Russian Foreign Ministry said, however, the plane was
owned by the Polyot Aviation Co., another Russian entity.
</P>
<P>
   The plane arrived in Baku for refueling, Russian officials said.
Azerbaijani customs officials said its papers were not in order.
</P>
<P>
   Flight plans filed in advance by the Russians listed the final
destination as Pyongyang, North Korea, the customs officials said.
The documents said the plane was carrying 50 tons of cargo and a
crew of 18.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijani officials said they had found six MIG-21 fighters,
broken down to fit in the transport plane, and almost twice as many
people on board. The crew reportedly insisted then that the cargo
was being sent to Bratislava, Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Slovakia denied that.
</P>
<P>
   A customs declaration on the plane also listed the recipient as
the Agroplast Co. in the Czech Republic. The sender was listed as
the Uralsky Metallist Plant in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   A Czech official said Agroplast produced granite and sandstone,
not military hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with such discrepancies, Azerbaijan started an
investigation. Guluzade, who has criticized Moscow, said the cargo
was intended for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   If the cargo was intended for Yugoslavia it is not clear whether
the operation was sanctioned by the Russian government or it was a
rogue maneuver by corrupt executives.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has not taken the seizure lightly. Deputy Foreign
Minister Leonid Drachevsky met Aliyev in Baku on Tuesday and
demanded the release of the plane. He said the detention violated
international law.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan has ignored that demand. Relations between Azerbaijan
and Russia are strained. Azerbaijan has been particularly irritated
with Russia's use of fighter planes and antiaircraft systems in
neighboring Armenia, Azerbaijan's chief adversary.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Azerbaijan has sounded the
alarms about the Russians. In March 1998, Azerbaijan customs
officials detained a Russian truck on its way to Iran. The truck
was laden with 22 tons of stainless steel that could be used to
make missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had asked the Russians to stop the shipment,
which left from Moscow. The Russians failed to do so. The Americans
kept the seizure quiet, but then Azerbaijan decided to announce its
triumph.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
