<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT TIGHT-LIPPED ON DECLARATION OF STATEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After meeting with President Clinton on Tuesday,
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, remained tight-lipped about
whether he would unilaterally declare a Palestinian state on May 4,
as he has indicated he might, and administration officials said
they gleaned no clue about which way he might be leaning.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton told Arafat that the United States is
firmly against such a declaration.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also reassured Arafat that the United States would
stand by him through the remainder of the peace negotiations with
Israel, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the hourlong session, which was sandwiched into a
day when the administration was laying the groundwork for NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, Arafat declined to discuss the
substance of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very, very extensive and in-depth conversation on
this issue, and I will not deliberate on what took place between me
and him,'' Arafat said through an interpreter in a brief session
with reporters in the White House driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that came out of the meeting with
President Clinton,'' he added, ``is that in spite of all the
difficulties and obstacles we face today, President Clinton has
shown me the determination to protect and to preserve and to move
forward in the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat had requested the presidential session as part of what he
termed a consultation process that he is conducting with world
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He is heading to Canada from here and plans to visit Russia,
Japan and possibly China.
</P>
<P>
   Before the meeting, Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, told
reporters, ``I think the president will reiterate our long-held
position that a Palestinian state is a subject for final status
talks,'' meaning that the United States, like much of the
international community, wants Arafat to defer any declaration of
statehood to the final peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader faces mounting pressure at home to stick
with making a proclamation on May 4 _ the day when a transitional
period of limited self-government is supposed to end.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, senior administration officials said that
Arafat did not raise the question of whether he expected a promise
of recognition from the United States if he deferred the
declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't raise it,'' said one official, adding that the
president offered no incentive for Arafat to hold off on a May 4
declaration. But he said Clinton emphasized that the United States
would stick by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stand by and insure that this process does come
to a conclusion,'' the official said. ``The commitment to seeing an
accelerated permanent-status approach, to not having it open-ended,
to being there every step of the way _ that was something that the
president did emphasize to Chairman Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat did not tip his hand on what he would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically in a guessing game at this point,'' said
another official. ``Trying to read the tea leaves is premature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
