<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN'S INNER CIRCLE INVESTIGATED FOR CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The evidence is still flimsy, and the political motives
are obvious, but Russia's chief prosecutor's office confirmed on
Tuesday that it was investigating corruption inside the Kremlin
itself, aimed at members of President Boris Yeltsin's inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on orders from Yuri Skuratov, the general prosecutor who
last week defied a Kremlin order to resign, investigators have
seized documents from the offices of the presidential
administration's powerful property-management office, headed by
Pavel Borodin.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation marks a new phase in Russia's latest round of
political warfare, in which the weapon of choice is ``kompromat,''
the Russian word for compromising material that is routinely
collected and stored by politicians for use against their enemies.
Given the level of official corruption at all levels of the Russian
government, no one doubts that there is enough ``kompromat'' to go
around.
</P>
<P>
   One clear example of the use of ``kompromat'' was a secretly
taped video showing Skuratov naked in bed with two women, which _
on orders that could have come only from the Kremlin itself _ was
broadcast on a government television station on the night the upper
house of Parliament voted overwhelmingly to let him keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Russia's periodic anti-corruption campaigns have
steered clear of the Kremlin. But on Tuesday, even as the
prosecutor's office made its investigation public, yet more
``kompromat'' against the Yeltsin entourage was tossed into the
public arena, suggesting that the president's political enemies,
sensing his growing isolation, are zeroing in on a weakened target.
</P>
<P>
   The most outrageous accusation came from a top-ranking Communist
Party official, Viktor Ilyukhin. He charged that Tatyana Dyachenko,
the president's daughter and political adviser, was holding shares
through an intermediary in an Australian company that received $2.3
billion in foreign credits issued to the Russian government last
year.
</P>
<P>
   These and other charges have been vehemently denied by Kremlin
officials as ``pure nonsense.'' Borodin, in a television interview,
called the investigation into his office, which he said began 10
days ago, a ``political farce.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Kremlin on Tuesday reactivated its
investigation into Skuratov's own behavior and the circumstances
surrounding the making of the compromising videotape. The
commission investigating the case had interrupted its work when
Yeltsin abruptly fired its chairman, Nikolai Bordyuzha, who was
also Yeltsin's chief of staff _ reportedly because of his
mishandling of a case that had turned into an embarrassing defeat
for the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Borodin's property-management office is a vast empire of office
buildings, apartment blocks, clinics, country houses and vacation
spas used by government employees. The investigation of the office
followed a Jan. 22 raid by Swiss investigators at the offices of
Mabetex, a construction company based in Lugano with extensive
business throughout the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Among Mabetex's best-known projects was its work on the Russian
government building known as the White house _ the headquarters of
both houses of Parliament _ after it was shelled in 1993. Mabetex
also was employed for the lavish restoration of Yeltsin's Kremlin
office building, where, Borodin said, Mabetex had a $49 million
contract to supply furniture and do finishing work on the
building's interior.
</P>
<P>
   Although no charges have been filed against the company here or
in Switzerland, the accusations that have surfaced during
Skuratov's investigation suggest that Mabetex paid Kremlin
officials to secure the lucrative contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's chief prosecutor, Carla del Ponte, arrived in
Moscow on Tuesday for two days of meetings with Skuratov about
Swiss-Russian cooperation on a series of criminal investigations,
which Skuratov's office says includes the continuing investigation
into the Kremlin's ties to Mabetex.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of her visit gave legitimacy to the Russian
prosecutor's investigation, although Ms. del Ponte has so far had
no comment on the subject of her talks, which are taking place at a
country retreat outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Moscow on Tuesday, Behgjet Pacolli,
president of Mabetex, suggested that his company was being used as
``a card in dirty political intrigues.'' He also said the campaign
against Mabetex might have been mounted by its various Russian
clients that owe the company $260 million, including $20 million
owed by the Kremlin's property-management office.
</P>
<P>
   Pacolli denied published reports that his company had built a
dacha outside Moscow for Mrs. Dyachenko.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first public mention of Mabetex was made last week in a
telephone interview of Skuratov by a Russian television reporter _
on the morning after the compromising video was shown on the
Russian government channel. Skuratov was interviewed as he was
driving to a Moscow hospital for an early morning meeting with
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov said the videotape had been used to force him to submit
a resignation letter on Feb. 1, which at the time was attributed to
his health. In fact, Skuratov said, he was being blackmailed to
prevent him from pursuing the Mabetex investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Skuratov's own credentials as a corruption fighter remain
open to question, given his generally lackluster performance during
his 3{ years in office. Many political analysts also contend that
the cases on which he has said publicly that he is working indicate
that he shares the political bias of his supporters within the
anti-Yeltsin opposition _ in particular within the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   But as the war of ``kompromat'' continues, more players have
entered the game. On Tuesday, one radio station reported that the
sexual escapades of another top law-enforcement official are now
available on tape.
</P>
<P>
   And Yeltsin's former bodyguard Alexander Korzhakov, who had a
public falling-out with the president several years ago, wrote in a
newspaper article on Tuesday that he was prepared to publish
damaging material about Yeltsin's own extramarital affairs if the
Kremlin failed to rein in its attacks on Skuratov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
