<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' ROAD: LESS TRAVEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's comfort to be found in the Lakers' just-completed 3-3
road trip, it is this: It's over. And it should get easier from
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit less than I thought we would get when we
started off the road trip,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``It was a
long, hard trip, with a lot of adjustments. I feel very fortunate
to be out of it 3-3.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Dennis Rodman, the Lakers stammered to a 1-3 start, then
won the last two games of the trip after he returned and, perhaps
not coincidentally, rediscovered their defense.
</P>
<P>
   If they can simply keep both their defensive intensity and
Rodman around for any length of time _ an iffy proposition in both
cases _ the schedule will provide the only other edge the Lakers
need to finish the season strongly.
</P>
<P>
   Of the remaining 22 games, 13 are at the Forum _ including the
next four in a row, seven of the next eight and nine of the next
11. And the remaining road trips are short and sweet _ five
one-game trips and a pair of two-game trips.
</P>
<P>
   The only hitch in the latter half of the schedule is two sets of
three games in three nights.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers also play less frequently, with more recovery
time, from here on out. So far, the schedule has included only one
instance when the Lakers had more than one day off between games (a
two-day stretch Feb. 12-13).
</P>
<P>
   Coming up, they'll get three straight off-days twice (March
30-April 1 and April 14-16) and two straight off-days three times
(April 22-23, April 27-28, April 30-May 1).
</P>
<P>
   Those much-needed breaks will afford them both time to heal and
time to practice, which has become all the more important since the
acquisition of new players Rodman, Glen Rice and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking at the three days we'll have off coming up
soon here as a good opportunity to get two good practices in and
hopefully gain a little bit of cohesiveness that we're missing,''
Rick Fox said. ``We've still got a number of games to go. But this
was our toughest run.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis gave the team Tuesday off.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shoeless Dennis: Several media outlets have confirmed what
Rodman told everyone Sunday _ that Converse has terminated its
contract with him, erasing the final year of a $15 million deal. He
was due to earn $3 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's new spokesman said he will fight the contract
termination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis has a contract with Converse,'' Matt Labov told the
Associated Press. ``Dennis has not breached any terms of the
contract and we expect Converse to honor the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Converse did not comment, but analysts said the move probably
has more to do with the decline in popularity of expensive athletic
shoes than with anything Rodman has done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
