<HEADER>
A1551 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      03-23 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-LED ATTACK IMMINENT AGAINST KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S.-led airstrikes against Serbian military
positions were imminent as Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
refused to halt attacks in Kosovo and to agree to a cease-fire with
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done everything we could do to solve this issue
peacefully,'' President Clinton said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said at alliance
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, that he had authorized military
action against Yugoslavia. Improving weather and the opportunity
for a full night of cruise missile attacks in the opening volley
indicated the assault would begin Wednesday night. British Defense
Secretary George Robertson also indicated the attack would begin
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic international implications were highlighted by the
decision of Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who was en
route to Washington, to order his jet to return to Moscow. Russia
objects to NATO military operations against fellow Slavs, and Vice
President Al Gore told Primakov in a ground-to-air telephone call
that airstrikes might be launched while the Russian delegation was
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO order followed the failure of a final mission to
Belgrade by U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke, and brought the West to
one of its most harrowing points since the end of the Cold War.
Holbrooke, before flying to Brussels to brief NATO chiefs, said it
was the ``bleakest'' moment in the latest dispute over the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``All efforts to achieve a negotiated, political solution to the
Kosovo crisis having failed, no alternative is open but to take
military action,'' Solana said. He ordered U.S. Army Gen. Wesley
Clark, supreme allied commander in Europe, to begin action with the
more than 400 aircraft and a half dozen missile-armed ships at his
command.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav Premier Momir Bulatovic declared a state of emergency
because of an ``imminent threat of war.'' Major international air
carriers halted flights to the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department ordered U.S. diplomats remaining in
Belgrade _ less than two dozen _ to close the embassy and leave
Yugoslavia. The missions of most European Union members appeared
ready to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton set the stage for NATO bombardment by telling
a labor union audience in Washington about Holbrooke's two days of
talks with Milosevic: ``We got nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is now united and prepared to carry out its warning,''
Clinton said. ``If President Milosevic is not willing to make
peace, we are willing to limit his ability to make war on the
Kosovars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, after wrestling with doubts about the mission,
passed 58-41 a resolution supporting the air attacks. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The initial attack on Serbian positions was expected to be made
with cruise missiles from U.S. warships and a British submarine in
the Adriatic Sea. The initial targets were to be Serbian
anti-aircraft installations and command centers.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with a bipartisan delegation of House and Senate
members, Clinton said the approaching mission was ``no slam dunk,''
and he conceded the dangers faced by U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are risks to our pilots, and there are risks to people
on the ground, who themselves are innocent bystanders,'' Clinton
said in a subsequent address to the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Workers. ``But the dangers of acting must be
weighed against the dangers of inaction. If we don't do anything
after all the to and fro that's been said here, it will be
interpreted by Mr. Milosevic as a license to continue to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Yugoslavia has a
``fairly substantial'' air-defense system. ``And, therefore, we
will take very seriously the threat posed by this air defense
system and do our best to suppress that....''
</P>
<P>
   The second wave of attacks would likely feature U.S. B-52
bombers based in England. The bombers can launch cruise missiles
from out over the Adriatic, out of range of the Yugoslav defense
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Yugoslav military officers stationed at a NATO air
operations center in Italy for a year were being sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. forces would lead the attack, Britain and France
said they would participate, and the action is backed by the newly
expanded 19-member NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``To walk away now would not only destroy NATO's credibility, it
would be a breach of faith'' with Kosovo's ethnic Albanian
majority, British Prime Minister Tony Blair told the House of
Commons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reminded his union audience _ and the broader audience
of Americans in general: ``This is not the first time we've faced
this kind of choice. When President Milosevic started the war in
Bosnia seven years ago, the world did not act quickly enough to
stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that Milosevic, in his intransigence, ``is still
denying his responsibility for the crisis, defying the
international community and destroying the lives of more people.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of airstrikes, Clinton said, is an attempt to limit
Milosevic's ``ability to win a military victory and engage in
ethnic cleansing and slaughter innocent people and to do everything
we can to induce him to take this peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton referred to an accord put forward by a six-nation group
in recent talks in France and accepted by the Kosovar Albanians,
including the Kosovo Liberation Army, but rejected by Yugoslav
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The pact calls for Yugoslavia to accept NATO forces, including a
U.S. contingent, to be stationed in Kosovo to police the cease-fire
</P>
<P>
   Many Kosovar Albanians seek independence or alliance with
Albania, a position that Washington does not support and which is
anathema to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on Milosevic to return autonomy to Kosovo because
it ``is the only way in the wide world over the long run he's going
to be able to keep Kosovo'' part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, with its 90 percent ethnic Albanian population, is a
province of what remains of Yugoslavia. Milosevic, a Serb, denied
Kosovo autonomy 10 years ago as the old Yugoslavia was breaking
apart after the death of Communist strongman Tito and the fall of
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. refugee officials estimate that of Kosovo's 2 million
residents at the beginning of the decade, 190,000 had fled before
the latest Serb assault and that another 240,000 people have been
displaced over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
