<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-RWANDA-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN SEEKS INQUIRY INTO U.N. ROLE IN RWANDA MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Five years after the worst massacre in recent
African history, Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Tuesday proposed
an independent inquiry into the U.N. role in the killing frenzy in
Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Security Council last week, the
secretary-general asked the Council to support an inquiry, a
spokesman for Annan said Tuesday. The inquiry, which is to have
``full access'' to U.N. records, including sensitive diplomatic
cables, would establish facts and reach conclusions about the
response to the tragedy, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan wrote that he sought the inquiry because of the scale of
the killings and to resolve the questions that ``continue to
surround the actions of the United Nations immediately before and
during the period of the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter follows widespread criticism of Security Council
actions before and during the massacre, as well as criticism of
Annan, who was heading the organization's peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 800,000 Tutsi and moderate Hutu were killed in
Rwanda from April to June 1994 after a plane carrying the
presidents of Rwanda and Burundi was shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have contended that Annan played down a warning from
Gen. Romeo Dallaire, who was the U.N. commander in Rwanda, that
Hutu extremists were planning a massacre, and that Annan denied him
permission to seize hidden arms intended for use in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement about the inquiry drew a mixed response from
human rights figures. David Rieff, an analyst who has written
critically about Annan, called the inquiry long overdue. ``It shows
you that for all the talk of institutional reform, the sclerotic
nature of the U.N. is unchanged,'' Rieff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Amnesty International representative at the United Nations,
Florence Martin, praised the initiative, saying, ``Apart from the
issue of what the body did or did not do to prevent the genocide _
and it has a fairly miserable record in this regard _ any lessons
learned from Rwanda would be most welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Annan said the inquiry would have a time limit
and that its findings would be public.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Annan requested support for ``this important
undertaking.'' Diplomats here said the president of the 15-member
Council, Qin Huasun of China, expected to respond favorably to the
initiative by Thursday, unless other members objected.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium and France have opened inquiries into the massacres, as
has the Organization of African Unity. In addition, the United
Nations has set up a tribunal to consider evidence of war crimes
against individuals involved in the killings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-CALHOUN-HNS     03-23 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-CALHOUN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
In his postgame news conference Saturday, Connecticut coach Jim
Calhoun said the Huskies' victory over Gonzaga in the West Regional
final wasn't just for this year's team but for all his former
players who had come close to reaching the Final Four only to
experience heartbreak.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The near misses in regional finals have been well-documented,
from Christian Laettner's overtime buzzer-beater for Duke in 1990
to the misfortune of running into UCLA en route to its national
championship in 1995 to having to play North Carolina in its home
state in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sweet 16 disappointments, the Huskies faced Duke in 1991,
bowing to the eventual national champion. They ran into a red-hot
Florida team that beat them in overtime on its way to the 1994
Final Four. And they shot a season low from the field in '96 to
suffer a devastating loss to Mississippi State, which also advanced
to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   So as far as his players were concerned, Saturday's victory
wasn't really about them. It was for Jim Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I wanted him to go to the Hall of Fame the right
way,'' UConn point guard Khalid El-Amin said. ``I didn't want him
to go as the best coach never to have gone to a Final Four but
rather as one of the best coaches ever.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't in question. In 13 seasons at Connecticut, Calhoun
has 2{ times as many wins as losses (302-120). He is 552-257
overall in 27 years of coaching, and now, on the heels of his
seventh Sweet 16 appearance and fourth Elite Eight berth, he will
for the first time coach in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a better coach today than I was yesterday or last
week,'' Calhoun said after Saturday's victory.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers lend his comment credence. They have been
consistently good throughout his career and spectacular in the
'90s. He began the decade with a 31-6 record in 1989-90, earning
him National Coach of the Year honors from five media
organizations. In the last 10 seasons, he has averaged nearly 26
wins, going 255-74. His teams have won the Big East regular-season
title six times this decade and the tournament crown four times.
They won both this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I average 26 wins a year for the next 10 years, I'll be
happy _ happy, but not satisfied,'' Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, like it or not, the Final Four is the pinnacle
of college basketball success, and without a good showing in the
NCAA Tournament, 26-win seasons end in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to all the questions I get about it, 100 percent of
how you're judged comes from what you do in these three weeks,''
Calhoun said. ``I've coached 800-plus college games, but the
measuring stick is Final Four appearances. Is it fair? I don't make
the rules, but I know the way the game is played. Every step you
take in the Tournament, the pressure increases exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some who whispered that Calhoun perhaps bowed to
that pressure. After all, his Northeastern teams went to five
Tournaments from 1980-86. They, too, never got to a Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun's explanation is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fate and other good teams and players got in the way,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Huskies made sure Gonzaga didn't. Getting beaten by
a Cinderella team would seem all too familiar to a coach who has
seen his teams fall in about every way possible in the Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach never talks about it, but with the talent we've had here
(10 players have gone on to NBA careers), I'm sure it's frustrating
not to have been (to the Final Four),'' forward Richard Hamilton
said. ``The thing is, at this level, stuff happens that has nothing
to do with coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Now another set of pressures begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to make up more lines for different questions,''
Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   Though UConn (32-2) will be the only first-timer in the Final
Four, the Huskies will be the favorite in their semifinal against
Ohio State (27-8), which rebounded from an 8-22 campaign to become
the first team in history to get this far after failing to make the
Tournament the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Connecticut, people don't settle for anything
but the best,'' junior forward Kevin Freeman said. ``We got here;
now everybody expects to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a team that doesn't worry about pressure. We
turn pressure into good, because we want to be the hunted team, the
team with the bull's-eye on their back that everybody wants to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that's Duke (36-1), which is riding a 31-game
winning streak into the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke is far and away the best team in the country,'' Calhoun
said. ``But I haven't always seen the best team win the national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the best coach. And whether Calhoun is better today than he
was yesterday, he finally can etch his name into a spot where it
has long belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along, we are good enough to make a ride, and I
think we have made a pretty good ride already,'' Calhoun said
before the Gonzaga game. ``Winning the national championship is our
ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer the question, `Will I get relief (from a Final
Four trip)?' Once we get there, I won't have to answer the same
question. I will have to answer, `Can I get back there?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
