<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      03-23 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE IS LITTLE CONSENSUS ON WHAT WOULD FOLLOW BOMBS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The stated purpose of NATO airstrikes against Serbian
military targets is to avert a humanitarian catastrophe in Kosovo,
but analysts say it could have the opposite effect unless NATO is
willing to follow up by sending in ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials and President Clinton say the airstrikes are
aimed at getting Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to stop the
ethnic cleansing of Albanian villages in Kosovo, and to get the
Serbs to sign an agreement that would end the fighting and give the
Yugoslav province autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   It is Milosevic's refusal to accept the agreement, and in
particular to allow 28,000 NATO troops into Kosovo to police it,
that has led to the latest confrontation. But analysts say it was
NATO's refusal to send in ground forces, and accept the casualties
that would result, that emboldened Milosevic to defy the Western
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Military and political analysts say NATO's pledge to rely
exclusively on air power dramatically limits the alliance's ability
to force Milosevic to capitulate. And they predict that ethnic
Albanian civilians in Kosovo will face immediate reprisals for
NATO's bombs, with massacres on a scale far greater than those that
prompted Western nations to intervene in Kosovo in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Eyal, director of the Royal United Services Institute
for Defense Studies, said airstrikes will destroy Yugoslav military
installations but leave ethnic Albanian civilans at the mercy of
Serb forces, without any international monitors or forces to
prevent, or even document, atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Michael Rose, the British general who led international
peacekeeping forces in Bosnia in the last round of ethnic strife in
the Balkans, said NATO can do little to change the situation in
Kosovo, and could make it worse, if it relies exclusively on
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   James Lyon, a Sarajevo-based analyst for the International
Crisis Group, said NATO was literally ``winging it'' by relying on
air power alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like hitting a hornet's nest and standing back to see
how they'll react,'' said Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say Milosevic may actually welcome NATO
airstrikes, seeing them as enhancing his political stature as
someone willing to stand up to the West, especially the United
States. Such defiance appeases ultranationalists who are
Milosevic's coalition partners, and plays well to a population that
some say has a persecution complex. By exploiting Serbian
nationalism, even as he presided over the breakup of the former
Yugoslavia and the deterioration of the Serbian economy, Milosevic
has held onto power.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have said the first wave of airstrikes against
Yugoslav air defense systems and air bases would be carried out by
cruise missiles fired from US warships and a British submarine in
the Adriatic Sea. The second and subsequent waves of airstrikes
would be carried out by some of the 400 NATO aircraft based in
northern Italy, and would be aimed mainly at wiping out air bases
not destroyed in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts agree that the mobile Serb forces that have been
driving out civilians and burning villages in Kosovo, creating the
humanitarian disaster that Clinton said the NATO attacks are aimed
at ending, will not be targeted until NATO is satisfied that its
jets can attack with minimal risk of being shot down. In the
interim, the number of civilians killed on the ground could mount
quickly. An estimated 2,000 have died in the year since the Kosovo
fighting began.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts also agree that unless Milosevic capitulates
quickly, or NATO follows up its air attacks with substantial ground
troops to fight Yugoslav forces dug in along the Macedonian border
with Kosovo, there is little chance the western allies will achieve
their objectives.
</P>
<P>
   The reliance on airstrikes could produce results similar to what
has evolved in Iraq, devastating the country's air defenses but
leaving a defiant leader intact. And they will entail considerably
more risk to NATO pilots, most of them American.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Beaver, a military analyst for Jane's defense publications,
said the Milosevic regime has spent the last five years diverting
resources into military spending, despite Yugoslavia's worsening
economic condition. Beaver says the Yugoslav defenses are
formidable.
</P>
<P>
   As General Michael Ryan, the US Air Force commander, told the
Senate Armed Services Committee, ``There is a distinct possibility
that we will lose aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, are not convinced, likening the Yugoslav forces
to Saddam Hussein's Republican Guard, which collapsed within days
of coming under intense attack during the Gulf War. Lyon says the
Yugoslav forces would ``cut and run'' if NATO followed airstrikes
with ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Lyon acknowledges a NATO ground assault is unlikely, given
the lack of political will in European capitals to commit ground
forces, and the unwillingness of Washington to stomach even minimal
casualties in conflicts where American interests are ill-defined.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, in a moment of frustration at a NATO conference
in London, a German general uncharacteristically voiced regret that
NATO had ruled out the threat of using ground forces in Kosovo.
That general, and many analysts, say that Milosevic would not be
nearly as defiant and antagonistic toward NATO if he believed that
his forces would face NATO infantry.
</P>
<P>
   Lyon said NATO can change that dynamic immediately ``with firm
action followed by ground forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Spyros Economides, a professor of international relations and
European politics at the London School of Economics, said that
despite NATO's reluctance, the confrontation will gradually rachet
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Milosevic will sustain considerable losses before he
gives in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, ultimately, he added, the terms for ending the conflict
will be the partition of Kosovo, with the Serbs keeping portions of
northern and western Kosovo that are rich in natural resources and
dotted with monasteries that are historically and religiously
important to Serbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
