<HEADER>
A1556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-PORTRAIT24-COX     03-23 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-PORTRAIT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Portrait of dragging victim to be auctioned
 &HT;    By Brad Mayhar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ About seven months after its unveiling at Lamar
University, a portrait commemorating Jasper dragging death victim
James Byrd Jr. will go on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got one bid from an L.A. real estate man,'' said Ricky
Jason, CEO of Houston-based Colorblind Entertainment and co-owner
of the portrait. ``He bid $1.5 million. We have another bid from a
tribe in Africa that bid $2 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason would not release the identities of the bidders, but said
the non-profit Colorblind Entertainment planned to donate proceeds
from the sale of the portrait to the Hughen Center for disabled
children in Port Arthur, an NAACP Youth Center and the Muscular
Dystrophy Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along, our idea was to do something to help and get
something good out of this,'' Colorblind board member Robin Zaruba
said. ``As far as donations, that was our plan all along.''
</P>
<P>
   The portrait will remain in a Houston vault until the end of the
auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to leave it up for auction until we feel we have
enough bids,'' Jason said. ``When we're through taking bids, the
board will meet and determine how much to give to each charity. We
want to be able to go there with a nice check because some of those
kids might need new computers, wheelchairs, crutches, or games or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Although department heads at the Hughen Center and MDA could not
be reached for comment, receptionists at each of the charities
confirmed they had been contacted by Colorblind.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with about 60 artists, Jason and Zaruba paid
painter Scott Weldon $200 to paint the portrait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were saddened by the pictures they were showing us,'' Jason
said. ``We wanted the family to have something nice to remember him
by.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorblind representatives gave six replica copies of the
portrait to members of the Byrd family.
</P>
<P>
   Since its unveiling at Lamar University, the portrait has
appeared at several Texas schools, the NAACP Image Awards, the YMCA
Awards, Rice University and has been viewed privately at a Beaumont
prison by blues legend B.B. King's son, Riley.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Jason and other Colorblind representatives took the
portrait to Houston to be seen by heavyweight boxing champion
Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after its unveiling at Lamar's Dishman Art Gallery,
the portrait and frame _ which have a combined appraisal value of
$500,000, according to university contracts and a police report _
sustained a cut in the right side of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   About a week later, university officials discovered a new chip
in the top of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   Jason believes someone intentionally damaged the portrait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we decided to leave it there, because we want the
world to know that there is still hate,'' he said. ``We also don't
want to take a chance on damaging the historical portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of three suspects charged with chaining Byrd behind a
pickup and dragging him to his death down a country road on June 6,
1998, John William King, was found guilty and sentenced to the
death penalty on Feb. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the second suspect 31-year-old Lawrence Russell
Brewer, will begin on May 17. Authorities have not yet set a trial
date for the third suspect, 23-year-old Shawn Allen Berry.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the auction, contact Colorblind
Entertainment and CompuCord Studios at (281) 774-9050 or (409)
351-9188.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Mayhar Writes for the Lufkin Daily News, Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
