</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC REJECTED ALL EFFORTS TO COMPROMISE, U.S. OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-U.S.,
RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Through six hours of negotiations over
two days with the U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke, President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia refused ``every opportunity'' to avoid an
onslaught of NATO air power, a senior American official said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been any sign of compromise, I would suggest that
we probably wouldn't be on the way to the airport right now,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior American official engaged in the talks, which
were aimed at halting Serbian attacks on ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo, said quietly, ``Given the choice of NATO troops in Kosovo
or NATO bombs, he chose the bombs.'' The official said that
allowing foreign troops to enter Kosovo, a province of Serbia,
proved insurmountable for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   During the talks, Holbrooke and Christopher Hill, the U.S.
ambassador to Macedonia, went over and over the consequences for
Milosevic, his army and his country if he did not bend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic said he did understand,'' Holbrooke said before
leaving Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Did Milosevic miscalculate? ``Maybe he didn't,'' one of the
American officials said, suggesting three possibilities. ``Maybe he
thinks we're bluffing. Or he thinks he can't survive if he agrees
to the Rambouillet accords, even modified, and especially can't
agree to a foreign force on Yugoslav soil because of history or
politics or whatever. Or third, he's still planning some sort of
deal at some point in this process.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Milosevic ``knows how to reach us,'' the official
added.
</P>
<P>
   The official referred to the talks last month in Rambouillet,
near Paris, on a peace plan that would involve sending peacekeepers
to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that in past contacts, which began with the 1995 Dayton
accords that ended the fighting in Bosnia, Holbrooke and Milosevic
had been able ``to find some humor in the situation, because even
in the most tense negotiations, there can be moments of levity.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time, there were no such moments. Instead, an official
said, Milosevic issued ``a steady stream of vilification, a long
litany of injustices committed against the Serbs and accusations of
some international cabal against Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   The European Union negotiator here, Wolfgang Petritsch, said his
own talks with Milosevic, along with Hill and a Russian envoy,
Boris Mayorsky, were also difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``He only wants to believe what he wants to believe,'' Petritsch
said. ``He is not ready in any way to engage even in a meaningful
discussion about alternatives and what can be done. He never refers
to any of the issues that are of real relevance at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the drumbeat from NATO countries about what they
see as a need to bomb Serbia in order to halt the fighting in
Kosovo, the officials refused to discuss what results any bombing
might have on Milosevic and his rule.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he feared that bombing _ what NATO calls
humanitarian intervention _ could unleash worse attacks by Serbs
against ethnic Albanians and vice versa, one official said,
``That's our greatest concern by far _ by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Some senior NATO officials have expressed the hope that a
sufficiently severe blow to the Yugoslav and Serbian military might
be enough to topple Milosevic. Serbia and little Montenegro are the
last republics remaining in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In what some officials interpreted as a sign of nervousness at
the top, Milosevic demoted his chief of military security, Gen.
Aleksandar Dimitrijevic, on Tuesday night and replaced him with
Gen. Geza Farkas.
</P>
<P>
   Last autumn, after an earlier NATO threat of air strikes,
Milosevic replaced the chief of staff of the Yugoslav army, Momcilo
Perisic, who had warned of the dangers of taking on the Western
allies, and the internal security chief, Jovica Stanisic, who is
said to have criticized Belgrade's policy in Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some Yugoslav officials, less ready than their president to
confront the West, also expressed concern that Montenegro would use
this crisis to declare independence from Belgrade, as Slovenia,
Croatia, Macedonia and Bosnia have done over the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of Belgrade on Tuesday night, there was increased
nervousness and anger with the West as the Yugoslav prime minister,
Momir Bulatovic, declared a ``state of imminent war emergency.''
But there were few signs of war preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after Tuesday night's television news, lines of
automobiles at gasoline and diesel stations grew up to three blocks
long. While diesel has been scarce for months and lines are not
unusual, Tuesday night's were much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Ella Fitzgerald at a club called Wunderbar, Vesko
Stefanofski, a 21-year-old theology student, called American policy
``totally stupid,'' saying it would ``destroy a Christian Europe.''
(Most Albanians are Muslim.)
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night on a private entertainment television channel
called Pink, a much-advertised Arnold Schwarzenegger comedy called
``Twins'' was replaced by ``The Battle for Kosovo,'' an epic about
the defeat of Serbs by Turks in the 14th century that is at the
heart of the Serbian national consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the oratory from the loyal Serbian parliament, which met
all day in a televised session to reject the idea of allowing
foreign troops into Kosovo, aggravated the tension. A nationalist
deputy, Stevo Dragesic, said, ``If we give them Kosovo now, nothing
will stop them from taking Vojvodina,'' a province in northern
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the republic of Serbia, Milan Milutinovic, said
the West had given Belgrade a choice between ``troops or bombing,
nothing in between.'' The West ``didn't say take it or leave it, _
just take it,'' he said, and he called the Serbs ``moral winners.''
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
