<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIMLER-CHRYSLER-755&AMP;     03-23 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-CHRYSLER-755&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWOFOLD MANAGEMENT CAUSES STRAIN AT DAIMLER-CHRYSLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The merger in November of Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler
Corp., presented at the time as a merger of equals, is producing
considerable unhappiness among some American managers at
DaimlerChrysler AG who contend privately that the combined company
has come to be dominated by Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent developments have worried some of the Americans,
although the company's American leaders say that their subordinates
should not be concerned. A half-dozen highly regarded executives
have resigned or retired early since the merger.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's fruitless negotiations this winter to buy a
stake in Nissan Motor Co. of Japan were led by German executives
using investment bankers in Germany. And nine of the 11 executives
in the management tier directly below the company's two chairmen
are German, although the new company's management board is divided
equally between Americans and Germans.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of auto executives say that they expect Robert
Eaton, the former chairman and chief executive of Chrysler and now
one of the chairmen of DaimlerChrysler, to retire as soon as the
end of this year instead of staying the three years after the
merger that his employment contract allows.
</P>
<P>
   American managers still at DaimlerChrysler also complain
privately that more and more decisions are being made at Daimler's
former headquarters in Stuttgart, Germany, even though
DaimlerChrysler officially has dual headquarters there and in the
Detroit area.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Meyers, the former chairman and chief executive of
American Motors, which Chrysler bought in 1987, said that Germans
were dominating DaimlerChrysler now and that this was hurting
company morale in the United States. ``To have to go and kneel at
the altar of Stuttgart has to be demoralizing,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler executives acknowledge that some employees here
are worried about the effects of the merger. But they say that
these concerns _ particularly the persistent and anxiety-causing
rumors that more plum jobs will be going to Germans _ are
unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you have a merger as big as this one, you're going to
have certain things be started, and quite frankly there's an awful
lot of rumor,'' said Thomas Gale, DaimlerChrysler's executive vice
president for North American design. ``It's unfortunate, but it's a
fact of life.'' Because there is little overlap between Chrysler
cars and Mercedes-Benz cars, there are actually few posts for which
American and German officials are vying, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stallkamp, the president of DaimlerChrysler's North
American operations, said that he did not think authority was
becoming concentrated in Germany. Concerning anxiety among the rank
and file, he said: ``I don't believe it's building. I believe it's
diminishing, if it was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some departures of executives are to be expected at a company
that had virtually no attrition in its top ranks for years, he
added in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stallkamp, who used to be Chrysler's president, said that he and
other senior executives had spent so much time traveling to
Stuttgart, Tokyo and elsewhere outside the office that a misleading
perception might be created among some subordinates that decisions
were no longer being made in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not communicating enough to our midlevel management, and
that's our fault at the top,'' he said, while adding that German
executives had also been complaining about their increase in travel
time. ``It's crazy, our schedule _ we've flown to Europe for a
two-hour meeting and flown back.''
</P>
<P>
   Some German managers have been fretting that American executives
have too much influence, and DaimlerChrysler executives use this to
suggest that the merger must therefore be striking an appropriate
balance between the two nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the guys who are sitting in departments where the boss
is American, there is also frustration, particularly among those
who are not able to speak English clearly,'' said Roland Klein, a
former spokesman for Daimler-Benz who is now the chief spokesman
for DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Daimler side of the company has lost virtually no
prominent executives since the merger, while the Chrysler side has
lost several. Ford Motor Co. hired the two Chrysler senior vice
presidents for minivans and vehicle engineering last month, while
General Motors Corp. hired Chrysler's vice president for
communications. Chrysler's executive vice president for
manufacturing retired early at the start of this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most recent departure came on Monday, when DaimlerChrysler
announced that the managing director of Chrysler's tiny German
sales division, Hans-Bernhard Port, had left the company and that
his duties had been added to those of Eckhard Panka, the
Mercedes-Benz executive responsible for German sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural differences, while perhaps seeming unimportant on the
surface, can pose serious problems in international mergers of
automakers. Renault SA had to sell its controlling stake in
American Motors to Chrysler in 1987 because clashes between
American and French executives produced managerial chaos; a planned
merger of Renault and Volvo AB was called off six years later
because French and Swedish managers could not get along.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly controversial within Chrysler has been Eaton's
decision last year to accept as part of the merger a three-year
tenure, after which Juergen Schrempp, Daimler's former chairman,
will become the sole chairman. Meyers, the former American Motors
chairman, said that Eaton's move had undermined the rest of
Chrysler's managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He declared himself a lame duck, and when he did that he was
finished. He no longer became the person to go to on anything,''
Meyers said. ``He can't protect the existing management.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallkamp said that Eaton's declaration might ``have caused some
temporary'' concern but that any such concern had abated. While it
might have been helpful for the merger in the short term if Eaton
had not disclosed his plans, the long-term management of the
company demanded a clear line of corporate succession, Stallkamp
said.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said that Eaton had agreed last year to leave after three
years or sooner if the work of the merger is completed before then
and that this had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Robinet, an auto consultant in Farmington Hills, Mich.,
said that any international merger of automakers would take a long
time. ``It really will take many years,'' he said, ``for Chrysler's
entrepreneurial background and mentality to nest with Daimler's
different way of doing things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
