<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Indian Wells President Under Fire
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Indian Wells Water, the Sonoma startup that is marketing bottled
water as an American Indian enterprise, said it ``is re-evaluating
the role'' of its president, Brian N. McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it learned that McCarthy was involved in
several past business failures after a story about Indian Wells ran
in The Chronicle last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Company Chief Executive Officer Jim Stevens said the number and
severity of McCarthy's business failures ``were apparently not
turned up in investigations'' by the Mille Lacs Band of American
Indians before it bought a 10 percent stake in the company for $10
million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Indian Wells aims to become a major force in the $4.3 billion
U.S. bottled water business by tapping springs and building
bottling plants on American Indian lands and returning profits to
the participating tribes.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that McCarthy has been named in civil
lawsuits in connection with companies he ran in the past, Stevens
stated, ``to our knowledge, he has never had a judgment against
him, nor has he been convicted of a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy conceded this week that some of his previous ventures
were unsuccessful, but denied that he was personally responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCarthy founded Indian Wells and still owns about 30
percent of it, when the Mille Lacs agreed to invest in the company,
they insisted that Stevens _ a former executive with Perrier,
Coca-Cola and Suntory Water _ become CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said McCarthy's responsibilities are ``entirely
operational,'' rather than financial, and center on negotiations
with prospective tribes. In the wake of The Chronicle story,
several of McCarthy's former colleagues and investors alleged that
McCarthy was involved in at least four businesses that failed.
These allegations include:
</P>
<P>
   _McCarthy previously founded a company, also called Indian
Wells, that distributed water to homes and offices in the North
Bay. The firm was liquidated about four years ago, costing
investors an estimated $3 million. McCarthy said the company was
undercapitalized.
</P>
<P>
   But he blamed the company's demise on bad business decisions
made after he was removed as president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   _McCarthy co-founded Watermark Corp., another Bay Area water
company that once had 24 stores and 18 delivery trucks. It filed
Chapter 7 bankruptcy and was liquidated in 1990, owing its major
investor $15 million. McCarthy said the company's problems occurred
largely because its main investor, Commercial Intertech Corp. of
Ohio, cut off financing after it became the subject of a hostile
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  _Brichard &AMP; Co., which was &UR;  &LR; founded &UR;  &LR; by McCarthy and Richard
Roland, managed eight real estate limited partnerships in Phoenix
and San Diego. The San Francisco company reportedly raised $56
million by selling shares in the partnership to about 3,500
investors in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Several former salesmen say investors lost everything after the
partnerships went bankrupt. Various lawsuits were filed, but
McCarthy blamed the bankruptcies on American Resource Corp., a
defunct Los Angeles real estate firm that bought Brichard's assets
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   _McCarthy and Roland also operated several Burger King
businesses in Michigan. At least one of them filed for bankruptcy.
McCarthy said the businesses were profitable and the bankruptcy
filing was a technicality designed to keep Burger King from
rescinding a franchise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
