<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1565 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: PaineWebber's Veteran Market Strategist Saw the
Tumble  Coming 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
PaineWebber's Ed Kerschner saw it coming.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Paine's chief investment officer released a
research note on Monday declaring that the stock market ``was
increasingly vulnerable to a 5 to 15 percent correction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is a little bit overvalued, (and) I think you'll
see the Dow hit 9,500 before you see 11,000,'' Kerschner said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, after yesterday's 218.7 point sell-off of the Dow to
9,671.8, Kerschner's comments may not seem that clairvoyant. But
the veteran market strategist made those prescient remarks on
Monday evening from the comfort of his Embarcadero hotel suite some
15 hours before Tuesday's tumble.
</P>
<P>
   Kerschner isn't new to making gutsy market calls. In 1987, the
New York Times credited the strategist with giving fair warning of
the Black Monday collapse of October 1987. More recently,
Institutional Investor magazine praised him for predicting the
surge in consumer spending that is driving the latest phase of the
bull market.
</P>
<P>
   While he remains relatively bullish over the long haul,
Kerschner said the impetus for his bearish short-term call was
pretty straightforward: His economic models indicated that the
stock market is overvalued. And that means investors are paying too
much for stocks, Kerschner said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Dow Jones industrial average sits at 10,000, 10,500
or 9,500, ``it would seem that the market is at least a little
ahead of itself,'' Kerschner said.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber's financial models indicate that the fair value of
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index for year-end 1999 is 1,250. After
hitting its all-time high of 1,316.55 on March 18, the S&AMP;P 500 got
whacked 2.7 percent yesterday _ plunging 34.9 points to close at
1,262.14
</P>
<P>
   Thus, with the S&AMP;P still 12 points above 1,250, stocks continue
to be a little pricey, and the market has some additional ground to
give.
</P>
<P>
   When the broader S&AMP;P 500 index _ the market indicator that most
pros prefer to use over the Dow industrials _ was hovering above
1,300, it was at a level that might be justified 12 months from
now, Kerschner noted.
</P>
<P>
   However, unless interest rates move meaningfully lower and (or)
earnings growth is significantly higher than the 5 to 8 percent
projected by Wall Street analysts, investors can expect _ in the
best case _ to see the market stall at its current level for a few
months, Kerschner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now, there is the very real possibility that, if this
market doesn't simply run out of steam and stall, you could expect
to see'' the Dow industrials falling as far as 9,000 before the
market starts to rebound, Kerschner said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Kerschner contended that it is reasonable for the
S&AMP;P 500 to trade 10 percent above or below the 1,250 mark. ``But to
expect the market to get excessively overvalued, that is, to move
up 10 to 20 percent from (all-time high levels) is a risky
proposition,'' Kerschner said.
</P>
<P>
   So what does it all mean?
</P>
<P>
   If corporate profits don't start to improve (and judging by some
of the dour pre-announcements that have been made in recent days
this is doubtful), the market will continue to be choppy at least
until the middle of the summer, said Kerschner, whose current
portfolio allocation is 60 percent stocks, 25 percent bonds and 15
percent cash.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all of the faux fervor over the industrials busting through
the 10,000 barrier, an important point was lost: There are very few
fundamentals (such as increasing profits or lower interest rates)
that would justify stock prices that are higher than their already
lofty levels.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, the way that the Dow toyed with 10,000
during intra-day trading was incredibly wimpy. That could be
because the current market has no business being above that
arbitrary benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It barely made it twice, and then there wasn't any follow
through,'' Kerschner noted.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the respected investment strategist thinks that
the traditional media's obsession with the Dow is a waste of
perfectly good trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Dow 10,000 is about as significant as the Year
2000, which is pretty insignificant,'' Kerschner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the hoopla is reminiscent of many of the more sensational
stories the press has seized upon in recent years, where the story,
the denial and the story of the denial become the story,'' said
Kerschner, referring to the O.J. Simpson trial and President
Clinton's sexcapades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here the chorus of pundits universally denying any
significance to the 10,000 level itself seems to be just the
material that is being used to make the story a story,'' Kerschner
said.
</P>
<P>
   This columnist pleads guilty as charged.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
