<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1566 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHONES-SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Consumers to Choose Local Toll-Call Carrier
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, Californians will be able to choose which
phone company carries their local toll calls, much like they choose
a long-distance provider, according to a decision by federal
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission said yesterday that
regional Bell companies, including Pacific Bell, must make it
easier for customers to use competing carriers for local toll calls
_ regional calls outside your own area code.
</P>
<P>
   The commission set a deadline for Pac Bell and other companies
to implement ``dialing parity'' _ an arcane term that basically
means customers will be able choose AT&AMP;T or MCI or any competitor
to process local toll calls.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, if a Pac Bell customer in San Francisco picks up the
phone and dials a number in San Jose, Pac Bell collects a toll for
that call. Customers who want to use a competitor such as AT&AMP;T to
make a local toll call must first dial a seven-digit access code to
get around Pac Bell's system.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's ruling means that on either May 7 or in mid-July,
customers will be able to sign up with a local toll carrier, then
just dial 1 plus the area code and phone number for these types of
calls. Customers who don't select a carrier will still use Pac Bell
by default.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC set two deadlines for implementation _ May 7 for Baby
Bell companies that have a local toll plan approved by a state
commission and mid-July for those that don't. It's unclear which
category Pac Bell fits in.
</P>
<P>
   The California Public Utilities Commission in the past has said
it would require implementation as soon as Pac Bell is allowed to
offer long-distance service, which has not yet happened. But the
PUC has also said it would comply with any FCC order.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of when local toll competition starts, the decision
could mean lower local toll rates as competitors flood the market
and try to capture customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good thing. We may see more consumers willing to
switch carriers and we may see more competitive prices,'' said
Charles Carbone, a consumer advocate with the Utility Consumer
Action Network in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling caps two years of bitter arguments between Pac Bell
and its rivals, who disagreed about when dialing parity should be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Telecommunications Act gave competitors the right to
handle these calls, but the Baby Bells balked at opening the local
toll market before being allowed into the long-distance market.
They argued that it would give long-distance companies an unfair
advantage and take away a lucrative source of revenue for the Baby
Bells.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been tied up in state commissions and at the FCC
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell officials said they were still reviewing the FCC
decision but indicated they don't support the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan right now is for simultaneous entry. Obviously from
the FCC's perspective, that's not going to be the case,'' said Bill
Mashek, a spokesman for Pac Bell. ``We will review the FCC's order
and evaluate its impact on the market. We hope that this is an
indication from the FCC that they will begin to open up the
long-distance marketplace as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitors such as AT&AMP;T and MCI, who have been eager to get
into the local toll market, said they will soon start soliciting
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to respond,'' said James Peterson, a spokesman for
AT&AMP;T. ``This market should have been open to competitors already.
The sooner other companies are allowed in, the sooner consumers
will start to benefit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
