<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKFORCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 California Given Low Grades for Its Workforce
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
California is still not doing enough to train the highly skilled,
educated workforce necessary for the state's booming high-tech
industry, according to a report being released today by the
American Electronics Association.
</P>
<P>
   The state received a D+ grade from the AEA for the quality and
availability of an educated workforce, just a slight improvement
over last year's D grade.
</P>
<P>
   The annual report card, put together by the AEA and 35 of the
state's biggest tech companies _ whose agenda is to have a large,
educated workforce to choose from _ ranks the state's high-tech
climate on categories such as education, taxes and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   This year, California got an A for electronic commerce but still
scored low for its corporate taxes, high cost of living and
congested roads. Company officials and the AEA say these factors
impede the state's ability to attract and retain high-tech
companies, which are being courted heavily by other states such as
Texas, Oregon and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Unless California starts training its students in the areas of
math and science and tackling these other issues, company officials
warn, the state that built the high-tech industry will watch it
slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is growing by leaps and bounds, and other states are
attracting high-tech workers out of California,'' said Theresa
Casazza, executive director of state public policy for AEA. ``We
want to make sure California is as competitive as it can be so we
keep the hub of the high-tech industry here.''
</P>
<P>
   The report card is a jumping-off point for legislators, who are
meeting with 100 high-tech executives today in Sacramento to
discuss the information technology industry. The AEA compiles the
information so it can point legislators toward issues that need
attention, Casazza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to create a dialogue, and the report card is a way to
set the stage and have a framework for discussion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The AEA and 35 of California's biggest high-tech companies began
ranking the state's performance in 1992. With the high-tech
industry accounting for more than 780,000 jobs and 62 percent of
the state's exports, it has become a vital part of California's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But while the state is No.1 in high-tech employment, companies
here face a severe shortage of qualified workers to fill the
high-paying, skilled jobs available.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Casazza said, is that California's schools
are not training students well enough. The AEA and companies are
hoping to push legislators to continue making improvements in the
state's academic arena, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The AEA gave the state a slightly higher grade this year because
of new science standards that are being implemented in California's
K-12 grades. But the state still lags behind others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas, Oregon, Washington adopted standards years ago,''
Casazza said. ``We need to focus on teacher training, on
significant class size reductions ... and improving technology in
classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   But the state does have at least one bright spot. California
received an A grade, up from an A- last year, for being a driver of
the electronic commerce phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Many of California's companies produce the hardware, software
and content used in selling products over the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
