<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Checking Out A Firm Before You Invest
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; QUESTION: &LR;   &LR; Before investing in a business venture, what can you do
to check out its track record and that of its top executives?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSWER: &LR;  Obviously, checking out a small or privately owned
enterprise is more complicated than researching a large publicly
traded company that files disclosure documents and is followed by
stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The first, but often overlooked, job is to check a person's
resume by calling references, colleges and former employers. If
it's a business, check with the Better Business Bureau, licensing
authorities, local chamber of commerce and the state Department of
Corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Next, turn to the Internet. Do keyword searches on popular
search engines, or check Web sites for newspapers and magazines
where the person has lived or the business has operated. (The
Chronicle's Web site is  &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .) &LR;   &LR; Other sites, such as Dow
Jones Interactive, let you search thousands of publications at
once, for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other Internet sites where you can check
lawsuits, judgments, liens and bankruptcy records. Some require an
annual or monthly subscription, others charge a per-use fee. Among
the most popular:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lexis-Nexis ( &LR; www.lexis-nexis.com &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   _ CDB Infotek ( &LR; www.cdb.com &LR;   &LR; /public &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   _ AutoTrack ( &LR; www.dbt.com &LR;   &LR; /products/products.htm &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   _ KnowX ( &LR; www.knowx.com &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   Online searches, however, are hardly foolproof.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fallacy is that you can find everything on the Internet
and it is free,'' said Lynn Peterson, a private investigator and
public records researcher who runs PFC Information Services in
Oakland. She suggests that only about 10 or 15 percent of important
information is available online, and then only in skeletal form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine times out of 10, you will need to retrieve a copy of the
information from case files,'' she said. That's easier for
professional researchers who have a network of court retrievers
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes skill to navigate databases and mine the right
information. Peterson, who charges about $150 an hour, works
primarily with attorneys and venture capital firms who want to
check out entrepreneurs before they make a major investment. The
cost for a complete search is often $750 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   You can find public records researchers in the Yellow Pages
under Information Retrieval Service and Research.
</P>
<P>
   Taxing Online Auctions
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the tax liabilities for the growing number of
individuals who are selling goods on eBay and other online
auctions?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are now more than 150 online auction sites, and a lot
of folks are treating the revenues like the proceeds from a garage
sale or newspaper classified ad. In other words, they are not
reporting gains and losses on sales of property to the IRS or the
state.
</P>
<P>
   That's a violation of tax laws, according to Internal Revenue
Service spokesman Larry Wright. ``They should be paying tax on the
gains they generate from the sale of goods, the same as a
storefront retailer,'' he said. But he acknowledged ``that it might
get murky figuring the cost basis of Aunt Mabel's brooch.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright added that ``e-commerce poses new challenges to tax
administrators'' but as far as he knows, the IRS has not yet asked
online auctioneers to turn over information on transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Wright would not discuss future IRS audit strategies. But he did
say, ``It doesn't take a nuclear scientist to recognize that if
online auctions represent a large dollar amount, the agency will
most likely be interested in the tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals and sole proprietors who sell items should file a
Schedule C attached to their Form 1040 individual tax returns
detailing auction income and expenses. If the seller operates in
California and sells in-state, a state sales tax likely should be
collected from the buyer and reported as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
