<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Yahoo About to Snap Up Broadcast.com
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Yahoo is on the verge of acquiring online video company
Broadcast.com for $4 billion in stock in a deal that would bring
film and audio clips to Yahoo's popular Internet portal, industry
sources said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo co-founder Jerry Yang, CEO Tim Koogle and President Jeff
Mallett have met with executives of the Dallas company, and a deal
could be inked within days, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported yesterday that Yahoo of Santa
Clara may offer $110 to $120 for each share of Broadcast.com.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo shares stumbled yesterday on the news during a down day on
Wall Street. They fell $9.50 to $155.50, while Broadcast.com stock
slid $4.50 to $112 after soaring 37 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo isn't the only one pursuing Broadcast.com. Microsoft, NBC
and America Online reportedly have expressed an interest in it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Yahoo and Broadcast.com declined comment.
Analysts, though, said the multibillion-dollar purchase would be a
wise investment for Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   As the Web grows in popularity, consumers increasingly are
subscribing to high-speed Internet connections so that they can
view clips of audio and video, such as the immensely popular ``Star
Wars'' movie trailer that debuted last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yahoo is one of the Internet's most popular
destinations, detractors say its content is text-heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com offers a range of streaming video clips from news
to concerts and sporting events. It is best known, however, for
Webcasts of President Clinton's testimony in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal and the Victoria's Secret lingerie fashion show last month,
a multimedia event that drew more than 2 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The company reaches about 800,000 cybersurfers a day who can
choose from nearly 400 radio stations and 40 television and cable
networks. Broadcast.com has begun to beam earnings reports and
investor conferences for major corporations.
</P>
<P>
   A buyout of Broadcast.com would shore up Yahoo's site with one
of the Web's most popular services and help it keep pace with its
rivals, industry sources say.
</P>
<P>
   In January, AtHome Corp. purchased Yahoo archrival Excite for $6
billion in a deal designed to deliver bring TV-like images and
sound to Excite.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NBC's Snap.com introduced a lightning-quick online
service rich with voice and sound earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The deal for Yahoo, if it goes through, would represent its
second major acquisition this year. In January, it paid $4.6
billion in stock for Internet community GeoCities.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo currently has a $1.35 million stake in Broadcast.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
