<SLUG> BC-PGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PG&AMP;E Resolves Tree-Trimming Accusations
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Suddenly dropping its uncompromising posture, Pacific Gas and
Electric Co. yesterday agreed to settle charges it endangered the
public by failing to trim trees away from high-voltage power lines.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face came in the form of a memorandum of understanding
reached yesterday with enforcement staff at the state Public
Utilities Commission. The terms were not made public, but such
agreements generally include payment of money by the accused and a
commitment to take corrective action.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the memorandum will be made public in a week or so
when it is put out for public comment.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came one week into hearings at the PUC in which
the utility stood accused of more than 500,000 counts of violating
state laws requiring utilities to keep trees pruned a safe distance
from electric wires. Until now, the utility had insisted it would
fight the case through the PUC and on into the courts, if need be.
</P>
<P>
   Had the utility been found guilty and the case reached the
penalty phase, PG&AMP;E could have been fined an astronomical sum. Each
count could have resulted in a fine of $500 to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum penalty _ a whopping $10 billion _ could not have
been levied because it clearly would have violated state
prohibitions of ``excessive fines,'' but a lesser fine, still in
the millions, was considered a distinct possibility.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E spokesman Leonard Anderson said the company believes it
could have won the case but decided instead to negotiate a
settlement since it represented ``a mutually acceptable outcome on
all issues raised in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Schulte, head of the enforcement division at the PUC that
reached the agreement, said he's confident ``the agreement we've
reached will make the system safe and allow both sides to move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the incriminating information cited by PUC investigators
was culled from the electric utility's own records.
</P>
<P>
   Company records show PG&AMP;E took money from its ratepayer-funded
tree-trimming budgets from the late 1980s to early 1990s to fund
other programs and boost profits. Managers received bonuses for
cost cutting.
</P>
<P>
   The utility diverted $77.6 million from its tree-trimming budget
to other uses from 1987 and 1994. During that same period, it
under-spent authorized budgets for maintenance of its distribution
system by $495 million, according to PUC staff research.
</P>
<P>
   That information, backed by supporting documents, compelled the
commission to open an investigation of PG&AMP;E's tree-trimming
practices last September that culminated in this week's settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may surprise customers, it's legal for a utility to
take money from ratepayers for one purpose and spend it on another
use, even manager bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The utility is presumed to know how best to manage its business.
But whatever the spending level, the law requires utilities to
protect the public by operating its business safely.
</P>
<P>
   They must keep trees trimmed a minimum of four feet from power
lines in state-controlled areas during fire season and no less than
18 inches from trees in urban areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2109EST &QL; 
