<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO SUPPORT AIR STRIKES AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Badly divided, the Senate voted on Tuesday night to
support NATO air strikes against Yugoslav military targets.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 58 to 41, approved a one-sentence resolution
authorizing President Clinton to launch American bombing and
missile attacks as part of NATO's efforts to end the crisis in the
Serbian province of Kosovo. Sixteen Republicans joined all but 3 of
the Senate's 45 Democrats in support of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators wrote the resolution's spare
language on Tuesday afternoon after it became clear from meetings
with Clinton's top national security advisers that an aerial
assault was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, senators from both parties expressed
reservations about, or outright opposition to putting American
pilots at risk and bombing a sovereign European nation. But with
NATO's air attack seemingly inevitable, many Senate critics muted
their protests and reluctantly closed ranks behind the
administration's policy, which aims to halt a Yugoslav army
offensive in Kosovo and force the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, back to the peace table.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who backed the resolution, summed up
the ambivalence of many senators: ``Congress and the American
people have good reason to fear that we are heading toward another
permanent garrison of Americans in a Balkan country where our
mission is confused and our exit strategy a complete mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   But inaction would be worse, McCain said. ``Our adversaries
around the globe will take heart from our inability to act in
concert to defend our interests and values.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats insisted that air strikes were necessary and
inevitable to stop the killing in Kosovo, maintain NATO and
American credibility and prevent the violence from spreading
through southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As a last-ditch diplomatic effort failed in Belgrade on Tuesday,
the White House sought to marshal support for NATO's bombing
campaign, and Clinton met with about 45 Senate and House members
for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Secretary of Defense
William Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, then briefed Democratic and Republican senators.
Finally, the president wrote Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the
majority leader, for the Senate's support.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were sharply divided, with critics warning of
American casualties in an operation the Pentagon has termed very
risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``American lives are being put in jeopardy because of a civil
war in Kosovo,'' said Sen. Robert Smith, R-N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1575 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVENTORY-SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVENTORY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Inventive Inventory Management   By Peter Sinton 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Longs Drug Stores had a big inventory problem. The cost of stocking
a typical pharmacy was getting out of hand, soaring to $200,000 a
year from $28,000 two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Roath, president of the Walnut Creek chain, was looking
for ways to curb the costs when he stumbled on a San Francisco
startup called Nonstop Solutions at a technology conference a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting proved profitable. Longs became the first company to
test the firm's novel service that allows pharmacies to cut
delivery costs without hurting customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Since last April, Longs has cut the time that inventory sits in
its central warehouse by 58 percent (from 24.3 days to 10.2 days)
and cut the time prescription medications sit at 362 stores by 25
percent (from 41.6 days to 31 days). Despite the changes, Longs
pharmacies are still able to fill 98 percent of prescriptions from
stock on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Nonstop has helped Longs cut inventory financing
costs by about &LR;   &LR; $60 million, which freed enough capital to buy a
20-store drug chain.
</P>
<P>
   The software is the brainchild of Nonstop co-founder Hau Lee,
who teaches business and industrial engineering at Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of academics and entrepreneurs have focused on
``just-in-time'' inventory practices and other methods to maximize
use of materials and lower costs on the manufacturing side of
business.
</P>
<P>
   But comparatively few have studied what happens to products once
they leave the factory and wend their way to wholesalers, retailers
and eventually customers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonstop and its venture capital investors, who have plowed $9.5
million into the company over the past two years, believe Lee's
methodology is the first breakthrough in managing inventory flow
for wholesalers and retailers in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The worst fear for many merchants is that their customers will
go to a store, ask for an item and it won't be in stock. To play it
safe, wholesalers and retailers inflate their inventory forecasts
and overstock goods at every step of the process.
</P>
<P>
   To solve this dilemma, Lee came up with a new approach called
``demand chain optimization'' that is based on more than 100 pages
of proprietary algorithms. Nonstop's software-based service uses
data supplied by its customers to analyze the relationship of
critical costs, including inventory, transportation, handling and
administration.
</P>
<P>
   It then tailors a daily report that spells out how to deliver
thousands of products to hundreds of stores in a way that maximizes
profits and meets customer demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a very detailed analysis of the characteristics of every
item one is managing,'' said Lee. ``No drug is the same. We look at
demand variables like whether consumers buy at a certain time each
week, month or season. We then massage the data to find the best
way to replenish each product, location by location, at the lowest
overall cost at a targeted level of service.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Nonstop may suggest delivering an expensive drug
like Prozac a few times a week because the cost of stocking the
pills is higher than the additional shipping costs. Conversely, it
might make sense to keep a larger inventory of inexpensive generic
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Nonstop Solutions is so confident in its prescription for
helping drug wholesalers and retailers slash inventory and reduce
distribution costs that it guarantees major savings before it
charges clients a monthly fee. While Lee provided the technological
know-how, Nonstop's other co-founder, Homer Dunn, provided
managerial expertise. Dunn started out in marketing at IBM and
subsequently helped start three other high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Better inventory management is important in the pharmaceutical
industry. It typically takes a drug 150 days to reach the customer
from the time it is manufactured, with the financial cost of
keeping inventory accounting for 71 percent of the total delivery
expense.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nonstop does not sell or license its sophisticated
software, but offers its service on a five-year contract, clients
do not have to hire experts. And beyond a $100,000 ``opportunity
assessment'' charge that Nonstop bills new clients to identify
areas of improvement, customers don't pay a dime until they get
results.
</P>
<P>
   Roath said Longs is happy to pay Nonstop around $45,000 a month
in fees since that is only a small fraction of what the drug store
chain has realized in savings.
</P>
<P>
   However, Nonstop's start was hardly auspicious. The first
incarnation of the business as Nonstop Logistics in 1995 was a
flop.
</P>
<P>
   The company initially planned to serve supermarket suppliers. It
raised about $6 million from major trucking and warehousing
companies with the aim of creating a Federal Express-type
hub-and-spoke distribution center that would send trucks loaded
with just the right mix of goods to stores.
</P>
<P>
   That approach ran aground when existing wholesalers who deliver
goods from individual suppliers felt seriously threatened by this
new service model and persuaded several supermarket chains to
withdraw their support of Nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   For Dunn, the setback meant having to shrink the company from 80
to 10 employees, go back to the drawing board to develop a new
business model, and find new financing.
</P>
<P>
   The company resurfaced as Nonstop Solutions in 1997,
specifically to work with wholesalers and retailers in the
pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   Altos Ventures, a 3-year-old Menlo Park venture capital firm
started by Stanford MBA grads familiar with Professor Lee, and REI,
another local venture capital firm, put up the first $3 million in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, one of the best-known venture
capital firms in the country, invested $5 million last April after
hiring a UCLA professor who could understand Lee's math to confirm
its commercial potential.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiner Perkins partner Ted Schlein said Nonstop scores high in
all categories. ``In the field of demand chain optimization, all
roads lead to Hau Lee,'' he said. ``Nonstop's `special sauce'
really is special as shown by Longs' success. It's rare that a new
technology provides such immediate, quantifiable cost savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Longs, the company has landed seven other major
customers, including three of the largest pharmaceutical
wholesalers and three of the largest retail drug store chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective is to hit a home run in the pharmaceutical
industry to prove what Hau Lee's science can do,'' said Dunn.
``Then we will move to other industries from auto supplies to
department stores to electronics as well as mail order, catalog and
online retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Nonstop hired Jeff Galt, former chief executive of
Knight Ridder's online information service company, as CEO to
manage its fast-growing business. Galt said revenues are likely to
jump from about $1 million last year to $5 million this year and
$25 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to expand its workforce from 60 to more than
100 by the end of 1999. It anticipates a public stock offering
sometime next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
