u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-565&AMP;ADD     03-23 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVISIVE STEEL-QUOTA DEBATE MOVES TO THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Mich., N.Y., Texas)  (lb) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing a wave of protectionist sentiment, two top
trade officials argued Tuesday that a House measure to impose
quotas on steel imports would hurt the U.S. economy and lead to
raw-material shortages and rising prices, and could set off a trade
war.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warnings, steelmakers and some senators vowed to
push for quotas that they argue are needed to save a basic U.S.
industry.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, speaking before
the Senate Finance Committee, said the quota bill, while ``well
intentioned,'' would be ``neither in the national interest nor in
the interest of the steel industry.'' She was joined in testimony
by Commerce Secretary William Daley.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which swept through the House this month by a vote
of 289-141, would roll back amounts of imported steel to levels
from the mid-1990s. That vote came in response to a surge of
low-cost imports from Asia and Russia late last year that brought
down steel prices, which have just begun to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our economy continues to grow, demand for steel products
remains strong,'' said Ms. Barshefsky, who repeated the Clinton
administration's intention to veto any quota measure. ``Imposing
quotes at this stage, when it looks like the market is beginning to
stabilize, could have the unintended effect of disrupting the
market, with effects that could reverberate throughout the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and the administration are wary of alienating
organized labor, which is lobbying hard for the measure. Though it
would violate World Trade Organization rules, and though it faces a
tough reception in the Senate, Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., its
sponsor, said: ``Over the next two weeks, the United Steelworkers
Union will unleash a terrific lobbying campaign in every member's
district.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure the House passed, steel imports would be
limited to volumes based on monthly averages gleaned from a
three-year period before July 1997. The economic crises in Asia,
Brazil and Russia shut down demand in the home country; moreover,
massive devaluations of their currencies made the steel inexpensive
for markets here.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. steelmakers have brought anti-dumping suits against many
countries, which have since cut steel exports to the United States.
Russia, for example, has voluntarily agreed to reduce its exports.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in testimony pitting protectionists against free-traders
and the steel industry against the administration, the bill's
supporters said quotas were needed to protect a shrinking U.S.
steel industry from ``illegal foreign predators.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of quotas, including Ms. Barshefsky and Daley, said they
supported an alternative proposed in the House that would make it
easier for the industry to seek remedies under existing trade law
when faced with sudden surges in imports. This measure, sponsored
by Reps. Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., would
lower the standards for taking such cases to the International
Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Steel industry leaders, however, insist quotas are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is: Do we want a steel industry in the
United States?'' George Becker, the United Steelworkers Union
president, said. ``We know there's an overcapacity of steel in the
world. If we do not act decisively in the present crisis, there
will be no American steel industry in the 21st century.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His views were echoed by Curtis Barnette, chief executive of
Bethlehem Steel Corp., who said: ``We are in a period of record
demand, and we are experiencing widespread losses in our industry.
There is only one cause: imports.''
</P>
<P>
   But several users of raw steel criticized quotas, saying they
would cut off the supply of specialty products that U.S.
steelmakers do not produce and could lead to retaliation against
their own products.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Porter, chief procurement officer for Caterpillar Inc., a
maker of heavy equipment, said his company ``strongly opposes the
steel-quota legislation.'' He added that it ``could lead to direct
retaliation against our exports and undermine the international
trading system.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, sharply criticized the bill, calling
it ``a prosperity killer that would send the Dow down 2,500 points.
It would be a move to protectionism. We're a prosperous country
right now, and if we start a trade war, we will be the great
loser.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2117EST &QL; 
