<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS FALLS TO KRAJICEK IN QUARTERFINALS OF LIPTON
CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ The shoulders were sunken, the head was
bowed, the racquet spewed sour notes like an out-of-tune piano.
Though Pete Sampras is back again in his accustomed perch as the
men's No. 1 player in the world, he and his game have not yet
caught up to his numeral.
</P>
<P>
   The bludgeoned backhand volley that missed the court and set up
his adversary's second match point Tuesday was visible proof of his
current shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who entered the 1999 race belatedly after opting for a
Hawaiian vacation instead of the Australian Open, was gaining the
momentum to match his restored ranking here at the Lipton
Championships. But he was treated like a doormat Tuesday in the
quarterfinals by his nemesis, Richard Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   A day after regaining the top spot, the second-seeded Sampras
played the shrinking violet against the seventh-seeded Krajicek and
made a 6-2, 7-6 (8-6) exit that was exceptional for its meekness.
And for its many flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Along with giving away a 4-1 lead in the tie breaker, where he
double faulted at 4-3, Sampras undermined his nine aces with eight
double faults. And he undercut his 30 winners with 32 unforced
errors, 22 more than Krajicek, now the highest remaining seeded
player here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, as long as I can live up to it,'' Krajicek said,
electing to take it as a positive omen that the last time he
defeated Sampras in a high-stakes quarterfinal, he captured his
only major championship, at Wimbledon in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While Sampras followed last week's No. 1, Carlos Moya to the
sidelines, the women's portion of the draw remained truer to form.
</P>
<P>
   But the defending champion Venus Williams was forced to fend off
a surprisingly tenacious 6-3, 5-7, 7-6 (7-4) twilight challenge
from 27th-ranked Anke Huber to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was a mutually brutal exchange of baseline ballistics in
which Huber pinned the sixth-seeded Williams to the backcourt by
design. Searing returns from the German, whose forehand repeatedly
provoked last-gasp backhand mistakes from Williams, twice denied
Williams when she served for the match in the third set. But once
in the tie-breaker, Williams charged to a 4-1 lead and nailed her
first match point when Huber soared a forehand wide.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of 13th-seeded Anna Kournikova, who failed to
survive an erratic outing against Austria's Barbara Schett, 6-1,
1-6, 6-1, Tuesday in the fourth round, the favorites kept
themselves in contention. Top-seeded Martina Hingis eliminated
Marlene Weingartner, 6-0, 6-2; second-seeded Lindsay Davenport
ousted Elena Likhovsetva, 6-2, 6-0, and seventh-seeded Steffi Graf
trampled Natasha Zvereva, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek's latest subjugation of Sampras, whose exit leaves the
Lipton men's draw without an American semifinalist for the first
time in a decade, marked his fourth consecutive victory over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got my number for the time being,'' Sampras said. ``The
guys that give me problems are the guys that serve big. When his
serve comes down, it's coming down from a crane.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Krajicek needed only nine aces, including a
137-mile-an-hour bullet that helped him finish off the first set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he doesn't like to see my name in the next round,''
Krajicek said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
