<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-2000-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE JACKSON WILL SKIP 2000 RACE, ADVISERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who has strongly signaled
recently that he does not intend to run a third time for the
Democratic presidential nomination, plans to announce his
intentions on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson would be a long, long shot for the nomination, he
commands a loyal following among liberal Democrats and would
complicate the campaign of Vice President Al Gore, the leading
Democratic hopeful. Gore has devoted years to cultivating a
friendship with Jackson in the hope that he would sit out the race.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview broadcast over the weekend on Black
Entertainment Television, Jackson, asked whether he would run,
said: ``I'm inclined not to. I'm not very motivated to at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining that he wanted to concentrate on efforts outside
government, such as pressing Wall Street to offer more start-up
capital to minority groups, Jackson said, ``Beyond politics is a
private sector challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, speaking to reporters in Chicago, where he will make
his announcement, Jackson, ever mindful of the suspense factor,
said: ``You can rest assured that tomorrow we will share with you
what we intend to do and how. We intend to impact public policy in
a major way in 1999 and 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also plans to announce his decision on Wednesday on the
Web page of his son, Rep. Jesse L. Jackson Jr. of Illinois. His son
has publicly urged the elder Jackson to run.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson does not enter the race, former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey is left as Gore's only rival so far. Other Democrats who
seriously toyed with running but bowed out are Sens. Paul Wellstone
of Minnesota, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, John Kerry of Massachusetts,
and Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 57, is one of the most prominent black political
leaders in the nation. He ran for the Democratic nomination in 1984
and again in 1988, and has weighed seeking the nomination in
subsequent elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leaves a big gaping hole _ and the other candidates are
going to scurry to fill it in,'' said David Axelrod, a Democratic
strategist in Chicago who is not affiliated with any candidate.
``He is a natural spokesperson for a large number of Democrats _
not just minority Democrats but poor, white working-class voters _
who feel disenfrachised. And it's a base that would be there for
him any time he stepped into the race. Now those voters are up for
grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson had insisted for months that he was still
contemplating entering the race, many leading Democrats had not
expected him to run. He had not established even a bare-bones
campaign structure and had not begun soliciting donations, which is
particularly crucial this year because the condensed schedule of
primaries and caucuses puts a premium on early fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Jackson drew attention for his role as a
spiritual adviser to the Clinton family during the impeachment of
President Clinton. Jackson founded Operation PUSH more than 25
years ago and is president of the now-merged Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition, a nonprofit organization that seeks economic and
political power for minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is also Clinton's special envoy to Africa and host of
the CNN program ``Both Sides With Jesse Jackson.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
