<HEADER>
A1596 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SPARKS-LADN-(SLAN     03-23 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNUCKLEBALLER PROVING TO BE INVALUABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ In the world where baseball players drive
Mercedes Benzes, Angels pitcher Steve Sparks is more of a minivan
guy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Sparks can't afford a Mercedes _ he signed a
one-year contract during the offseason for $1.35 million. It's just
that Sparks, his wife Michelle and their two children (Alexa and
Blake and another on the way) have learned to live a frugal
lifestyle out of necessity.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you spend nine years in the minor
leagues, in places like Helena, Mont., and Beloit, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks has spent winters working odd jobs, including one as a
substitute teacher near his home in Sugarland, Texas. As recently
as the fall and winter before the 1998 season, Sparks would wait
for that 5:30 a.m. phone call from the school-district office for
the invitation to teach.
</P>
<P>
   This past offseason, Sparks was ``Mr. Mom,'' shuttling the kids
to and from school and taking care of household duties while
Michelle went to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``She takes care of everything during the season, so it's my
turn to help out,'' Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the way of life in the Sparks family. It has
worked in the tough times so there's no reason to change, Sparks
believes, now that he's making good money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it'll change anything,'' said Sparks, 33.
``We're pretty much grounded in what we want to do with our lives.
I'm never not going to work. . . . Neither of us grew up with much.
So we appreciate and are thankful for the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might super-size at McDonald's, or buy two-ply toilet
paper, but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks earned this year's salary because of last year's
performance. After joining the club in June, Sparks went 9-4 with a
4.34 ERA in 22 games (20 starts). He had a six-game winning streak
from June 29 to Sept. 2 and pitched into the seventh inning or
later 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   He was about as reliable as a knuckeballer can be, even though
there was no reason to expect anything from him.
</P>
<P>
   After eight full seasons in the minors, Sparks thought he had
arrived in 1995 when he went 9-11 with a 4.63 ERA with the
Milwaukee Brewers. Instead, Sparks found himself back in the minors
for much of 1996, then blew out his elbow in the spring of 1997
when he tried to halt his throw on a relay tothe plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subconsciously, after that year (1995) I felt I could pitch
there for a while,'' Sparks said. ``I didn't take it for granted,
but subconsciously I felt I belonged.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks had reconstructive surgery on his right (pitching) elbow
after his injury in '97. He didn't pitch at all that year, then
went job hunting after the Brewers released him. He called team
after team but found no takers until getting Angels general manager
Bill Bavasi on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we had some pretty good hitting clubs, and I
noticed if knuckleballers are on, there was really no defense
against them,'' Bavasi explained. ``And the hitters would be a
little off in the next game too. They'll give you a lot of innings
and a completely different look.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi agreed to give Sparks a shot, but Sparks didn't exactly
set the world on fire. He was 0-4 at Double-A Midland and 0-4 at
Triple-A Vancouver. The win-loss record was deceiving, though. It
wasn't an indication of how he was throwing and the Angels called
him up on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a weapon not a lot of people have,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``And when it's working, he wins games. Right
now the challenge is making sure we have a guy who can catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Molitor said it was the best knuckleball he ever faced.
Coming from Paul Molitor, that was good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that he finally has another opportunity to pitch in the
big leagues, Sparks takes the mound with a do-or-die attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally felt every start I was pitching for my job,'' he
said. ``I put a lot of pressure on myself. I'll do the same this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this year, who knows? Sparks is well-aware that
knuckleball pitchers have a history of pitching into their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel if I can stay in shape, I can stay for a while,'' he
said. ``Some of those guys (knuckleballers) leave because of a knee
or a hip, not their arm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
