<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1602 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER     03-23 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER-$ADV28-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAIN UP ON A LONDON WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 28)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some things I love about London theater: The curtain
is often at 7:30, so you can eat afterward at a sane hour. Tickets
cost less, on the whole, than in New York. You can take your drink
(or your ice cream) back to your seat without fear of reprisal.
Some bathrooms are right next door to the auditorium, not through
winding corridors and down dangerously steep stairs. The theater
names are grand (the Royal Court, the Prince of Wales, the Duchess,
Her Majesty's). And later you get to toss your head and say, ``Oh,
I saw it in London.''
</P>
<P>
   And although it hurts me to let everyone know this, the
trans-Atlantic theater weekend, once the province of the rich and
social, is now well within the reach of any slightly profligate
American.
</P>
<P>
   Mine began when a friend saw Virgin Atlantic's $99 one-way
winter air fares between London and New York (it's actually $135.50
each way after taxes and whatever). Then she told me about a Web
site she had discovered for ordering theater tickets:
www.albemarle-london.com. It included not only all the relevant
information on each play and musical on the West End but also
excerpts from major reviews of each production and seating charts
for each theater. This was too easy.
</P>
<P>
   I asked a colleague who works in London for her recommendations,
and she faxed back five pages of listings from Time Out London,
with circles, checks, stars and handwritten comments.
</P>
<P>
   I chose ``Copenhagen,'' a wartime drama about physicists that
came highly recommended; ``The Weir,'' an Irish drama set in a pub
(previews were to start in New York last week), and a revival of
``Betrayal,'' my favorite bleak Harold Pinter love story. I
regretted not having time for ``An Inspector Calls,'' which I'd
missed in New York; Tom Stoppard's ``Invention of Love'' or
``Oklahoma!'' People I respect swear that the British production
captures the dark side of Laurey, Curly and Jud's homespun
triangle. And it would have been a hoot (the most Oklahoman word I
can think of) to hear proper Londoners twanging about tall corn and
fringed surreys. But weekends are short.
</P>
<P>
   Ordering through the Internet, which I hadn't tried before, was
a snap. I filled in the form with the name of the show, the date,
the seat location, (the stalls, of course, being the British
equivalent of the orchestra) and ticket price, typed in my credit
card number and hit ``send.'' By the next day, I had confirmation
by e-mail and notification that the tickets would be waiting at the
theater. And in every case, they were. Of course, the 23 percent
booking fee pretty much negated the price advantage for London
theater. I paid about $61, $51 and $36.
</P>
<P>
   Not that buying West End theater tickets at the last minute
isn't a possibility. A friend and I had done it on my last visit to
London, three years ago, when we strolled by the box office of the
theater where an extremely well-reviewed revival of ``Company'' was
playing. We asked for two good seats in the stalls that night and
got them. And on this trip, when one of my traveling companions
decided at the last minute to join me for ``Copenhagen,'' she was
able to pick up a single ticket for that evening's performance _
saving about $13 over what I had paid.
</P>
<P>
   But I was in the mood for certainty. I would have better things
to do on my first day in London than wander from theater to theater
buying tickets. Better things, like taking a nap.
</P>
<P>
   And not doing that was my first mistake. We arrived in London on
a mild Friday morning in February, a flight that was short on
legroom but long on entertainment options. There were around 15
movies, most of them current, available on our tiny seat-back video
screens. On the flight back, I saw, among other things,
``Elizabeth.'' I had been persuaded, by the friend organizing the
trip (there were four of us), to stay in a small hotel near Russell
Square that she knew. I do not generally enjoy hotels for which the
most favorable description is ``clean,'' but I couldn't argue that
it was affordable. For this reason, when my companions announced
that they intended to skip the post-flight nap, I did the same.
Going back to our sanitary but unglamorous accommodations just
wasn't as appealing as settling in under Frette sheets and a fluffy
down comforter at the Berkeley. I stayed awake. I came to regret
it.
</P>
<P>
   The problems began about halfway through the first act of
``Copenhagen'' that night. Yes, this is a play about Niels Bohr,
the Danish physicist; his wife, Margrethe; and Werner Heisenberg,
the German physicist who was author of the uncertainty principle,
standing around talking one weekend in 1941. This is the ``My
Dinner With Andre'' of the West End. It is not, as many critics
have already noted, in any way boring. The characters seem to be
rattling on about physics and war and Nazi occupation, but they're
really talking about morality and the unknowability of just about
everything. It would not do to nod off.
</P>
<P>
   At the interval (a k a intermission), my friend Joan confessed
that she was having the same problem. We strolled into the stalls
bar (each section of the theater has its own bar; I love
class-consciousness!) and ordered red wine, which turned out to be
the temporary alertness boost we needed.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else around us, we were reluctant to go back into
the theater before finishing our wine. But when the bells began
ringing to summon us back to our seats, we, unlike New York
audiences in the same situation, had an alternative. A nice man
came around and offered to pour our wine into plastic glasses so we
could take it back to our seats.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of thing that I always remember about London
but think I must have imagined the last time. That and the
necessity of buying one's program (2 to 2.50 pounds, as it turns
out, or $3.25 to $4).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After the play, we looked up the block and saw Taste of India, a
restaurant recommended by a friend. We had a delicious, mildly
spicy light supper (shared appetizer, main course and bread, plus
one more glass of wine) for about $15 each.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I headed for the Royal National Theater complex
and the Saturday matinee of ``Betrayal.'' Never having been to the
National or any of its sister institutions, I was horrified by what
I saw on the map. It was actually on the other side of the Thames
at an Underground stop with the daunting name of Waterloo. It was
as if Manhattan's Lincoln Center had been moved to Queens County.
</P>
<P>
   Reality turned out to be much less frightening. Waterloo was
three tube stops from Leicester Square, in whose general
neighborhood I had had lunch (a gorgeous cheese omelet in the
downstairs wine bar of Cafe des Amis du Vin), and it is impossible
to get lost between the station and the theaters. Since then, I've
learned that lots of people prefer the stroll over Waterloo Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betrayal,'' which I had known only from the film version with
Jeremy Irons, Ben Kingsley and Patricia Hodge, is about an
extramarital affair, told in reverse chronology (it begins with
their meeting years after the breakup and ends with their first
kiss). It was so well done that I barely thought about Jeremy Irons
all afternoon, which is something of a feat. It was a jolt _ but
oddly reassuring _ when, as the lovers embraced, an elderly woman
in my row announced in her loudest voice, ``This is the end, I
think.'' And I had believed that all the annoying audience members
were in New York.
</P>
<P>
   All this theatergoing meant that very little time was spent at
our hotel, St. Margaret's, although I had come to admit that it was
very pleasant. It was on a quiet, pretty street of white row
houses, an invigorating but not tiring stroll (15 to 20 minutes)
from the West End. The breakfast room was cheerful. The people at
the front desk were friendly and helpful. But I don't know what we
were thinking when we reserved not a double, not a triple, but a
quadruple room.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I do. We were thinking that there would be three of us, so
rather than having one person suffer financially, we had looked
into triple-room rates. When our fourth, Karen, found out that
she'd be able to join us after all, we lost our heads and asked for
a room that would accommodate us all. Yes, it was a lot like
college revisited, this huge room with four single beds, two tiny
closets, one drawer apiece, a minuscule black-and-white TV and the
smallest bathroom I've ever seen on land. Now I remember why I
couldn't wait to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   That night, our all-woman travel party (two art directors, an
editor and a divorce lawyer, who had left behind varying
combinations of husbands, children and pets) went to see ``The
Weir.'' For the first two plays, I had had fabulous seats (sixth
row center, in both cases). At this theater, we were in the second
row center, which seemed a little too up close and personal. But
``The Weir,'' by Conor McPherson (the hot young Irish playwright of
the moment, now that Martin McDonagh has had his season of American
fame), is a five-character play in which scary stories are told
while vast amounts of ale are consumed, so we began to feel as if
we were just the customers at the next table.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Barbara suggested we go to Rules, which is billed as
the oldest restaurant in London (two centuries or so). The future
Edward VII and Lillie Langtry used to meet here _ in a private
room, of course. But Rules was full, so we took the recommendation
of an employee there and went to Porters, around the block, where
we had a perfectly nice selection of English specialties from
Cumberland pie to trifle. The following night, we made reservations
and went back to Rules for a fabulous, elegant dinner. With wine
and beer, appetizers, Dover sole for two, roast pheasant for two
and dessert, the meal came to about $60 each and was well worth it.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much theater on Sundays in London, but there are a
few matinees and I was determined to find something worthwhile.
According to the listings, I had a choice of ``Annie'' (saw it when
Sarah Jessica Parker was a little girl), ``Buddy'' (the Buddy Holly
story, now in its ``10th triumphant year'') and ``The Street of
Crocodiles.'' I went with the crocodiles. This was the same
production, from the Theatre de Complicite, that had received
glowing reviews at the Lincoln Center Festival last year. Inspired
by the work of the Polish writer Bruno Schulz, the play (which has
since closed in London) tells its stories in a largely nonverbal
style that one critic described as ``perceptual anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was spoiled by the preceding three examples of verbal
brilliance, maybe I just wasn't in the mood for people turning into
birds, maybe I was distracted by the particularly young, rowdy
crowd; whatever the case, I was a little disappointed. But being
thrilled with three out of four shows seen within 48 hours is not a
bad record.
</P>
<P>
   There was time, between Friday morning and our departure for the
airport on Monday afternoon, for a few things other than theater. I
made the obligatory shopper's homage to Harrods, which on the
ground floor seems more and more like a theme park every year. But
on the upper floors, accidentally passing through the riding habit
and accessories section, I was reassured that I was indeed in a
foreign land. I spent some time at my other favorite store, Harvey
Nichols, beginning with a pile of evening bags on sale on the
ground floor and ending with a superb decaf cappuccino on the
groceries floor.
</P>
<P>
   I even managed to fit in a short visit to the British Museum,
two blocks from our hotel, and one to Dickens House. Charles
Dickens was quite a theater type himself, and one room consists
mainly of 19th-century theater programs and memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet if he were around now, he'd order his tickets on the
Internet.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   WAY-OFF-BROADWAY, TO THE WEST END
</P>
