<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1613 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-LOW-CULTURE-$ADV     03-23 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-LOW-CULTURE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROLLING `LOW' CULTURE FOR HIGH-FLYING IDEAS: A SPORT OF
INTELLECTUALS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s, the literary critic Roland Barthes described
some of the quirky French wrestlers who were then attracting
attention: one had ``an obese and sagging body'' and an ``asexual
hideousness''; another was ``short and arrogant like a cock''; a
third possessed an ``arrogant and ridiculous character.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barthes was not interested in just describing these
bizarrely costumed musclemen. When he looked at wrestlers throwing
each other out of the ring or torturing each other in excruciating
holds that inspired grotesque grimaces, he saw figures out of
Racine and Moliere. He saw the gods of Greek drama. He compared
wrestling to a ``triumphant classical art'' offering an ``ideal
understanding of things.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he considered the very excess of wrestling _ its
overwrought gestures, exaggerated physical types, obvious role
playing, and cavalier approach to rules and manners _ to be the
keys to wrestling's meanings. Boxing, he explained, told a story,
but wrestling was a succession of sensations. It was a spectacle,
not a sport. And its great subjects, displayed with ornate
iconography, were Justice and Suffering.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Barthes, who was often both brilliant and
iconoclastic, saw wrestling the way intellectuals see everything,
as a reflection of Big Ideas. And Big Ideas loom even larger if
they are found in Low Things. Which is where, since Barthes, many
intellectuals, writers and academics have been searching for them.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, Barthes could have had very little inkling of
how far this immersion in the Low could go. Norman Mailer once
provided a paean to the ``white Negro'' and celebrated the
street-level artfulness of graffiti; now academics go further,
turning out elaborate studies of cross-dressing, peep shows and
cockfights.
</P>
<P>
   The Beat writers showed a certain appreciation for the frisson
of criminality; now the excess, the shocking, the disgusting and
the pornographic have inspired scholarly disquisitions. There is
nothing these days that is too Low for High thought: trailer parks,
snuff films, Mickey Mouse. Some of this is because of the
unparalleled power of American popular culture, its extraordinary
influence with world audiences and its aggressively democratic
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Boundaries are dissolving so fast that even the lowly life of a
cultural critic is swept up in the maelstrom: in recent months I
have written about swimming pools, video games and lingerie as well
as Arnold Schoenberg, Isaiah Berlin and Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   But high-toned discussion of the Low is also the preoccupation
of a new university discipline known as ``cultural studies,'' in
which everything is fodder for anthropological and political
contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   In contemporary analyses, any distinctions between, say, a drama
by Racine and a wrestling match with Hulk Hogan might be considered
accidents of taste and class; graffiti and Rembrandt etchings might
be seen as different primarily in their means of production and the
marketing forces affecting their value, and peep shows and horror
films might have as much significance as any cineaste's
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   One intellectual force behind this change has been a form of
Marxism. While in traditional criticism esthetic distinctions are
central, Marxist analysis of culture tries to discern social or
political meanings, the particular interests that various works
serve and their usefulness in revolutionary projects. For a while,
writers like the esthetician Theodor Adorno and the intellectuals
that gathered around Partisan Review tried to reconcile Marxism
with high achievement in the arts. But no longer. Advocates of
university-centered cultural studies tend to argue that any
distinctions between high and low are themselves merely political.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal is to reveal the deeper political meanings latent
in all cultural activity. In this view it may even be that
wrestling matches reveal more about society than elaborately
disguised ``higher'' activities.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from this neo-Marxist view, there is another influence
on these intellectual preoccupations: a Western fascination with
cultures believed to have a closer connection with Nature. Such
cultures may possess forms of knowledge ignored by the rationally
structured sciences of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau is often named as this tradition's godfather, but this
view, which combines a romance about a lost world with a
dissatisfaction with the high culture of the West, has had
important consequences for the interpretation of world cultures.
The anthropologist Claude Levi-Strauss has shown, for example, that
even the notion of the ``primitive'' has to be revised: myths of
so-called primitive societies display sophisticated systems of
thought. Contemporary multiculturalism taps into similar
sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   This romance remains potent even within Western culture, in
which intellectuals _ who have presumably been exquisitely trained
in rational analysis _ look to more ``primitive'' activities with a
certain amount of envy. Those who have mastered their bodies and
use their bodies for power have certainly tapped into a kind of
knowledge not usually associated with intellectual life;
intellectual envy mounts when the physical mastery also comes from
a culture that is deemed more ``natural.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a dark side here: this envy has helped inspire
disastrous intellectual devotion to various forms of criminality as
well as to German fascism and Third World terrorism. The envy,
however, also has an influence on intellectual considerations of
Low culture, in which admiration can end up tempering any left-over
sense of condescension.
</P>
<P>
   But the strange thing about the ideologies of Marxism and
Romanticism, which have had such an impact on university and
intellectual life, is that it is possible to reject their
prepackaged views about Good and Evil and find something revealing
about their approaches.
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't have to go as far as the cultural-studies radicals
to argue that there are meanings latent in mass culture; one
doesn't have to be a Romantic to attend to aspects of human
existence other than the rational, and one doesn't have to accept
either view that there are no other distinctions worth making. Such
issues may now be worth wrestling over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
