<SLUG> BC-OIL-MEET-ART-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL COUNTRIES APPROVE WORLD CUTBACK OF 3 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic showing percentage change in production for major
oil-producing nations is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ With remarkable speed and unity, OPEC clinched
a far-reaching agreement with four independent oil-producing
nations on Tuesday to cut world output by 2.1 million barrels a
day. The move, if carried out, would significantly reduce the
supply of crude oil and drive up the price of gasoline and other
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The pact, announced here, is to take effect on April 1 and last
for a year. It would reduce daily world oil production of 70
million barrels a day by about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was reached despite resilient skepticism about the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' ability to stop
cheating by its own members. On the contrary, there is now
considerable optimism that the cutbacks will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy to see a new spirit in OPEC,'' said the
Algerian oil minister, Youcef Yousfi, after the group completed the
deal at the ANA Hotel. Yousfi, who is OPEC's president, added: ``To
those who doubted our resolve, we have proven with our solidarity
we can exceed expectations. To people who predicted the imminent
demise of OPEC, I say `Not yet.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although the 11-nation producers group no longer has the same
grip on the global petroleum markets that it commanded in the 1970s
and early '80s, it still provides almost 40 percent of the world's
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread anticipation of the production cutbacks, which were
negotiated in advance, had already pushed oil and gasoline prices
up in the United States, the world's biggest user of petroleum
products. In the last few weeks, gasoline prices for U.S. consumers
have risen more than 8 cents a gallon and are back over $1 a gallon
on average nationwide for the first time in four months.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC ministers predicted that the cuts announced Tuesday would
push up oil prices to $17 or $18 a barrel from the current $14- to
$15-a-barrel range by this summer. That could translate into a
further 10-cent-a-gallon retail increase for gasoline in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement presented an extraordinary show of solidarity,
with Norway, Mexico, Russia and Oman joining OPEC in promising to
shut down 388,000 barrels a day of their production. The deal
suggested that producers in and out of the cartel are intent on
reversing a slide in prices that has lasted for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Until two years ago, these independent oil nations rejected any
serious collaboration with OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new spirit of cooperation between oil-exporting countries
has brought clear results,'' said Ali Naimi, Saudi Arabia's oil
minister, who led the effort. He pointedly noted that the agreement
had strong political underpinning. ``Several heads of state
directly participated in these negotiations by telephone,'' Naimi
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi officials said that Crown Prince Abdullah, the effective
ruler of Saudi Arabia, which is the world's largest oil producer,
had joined President Mohammad Khatami of Iran and the heads of
state of Venezuela, Algeria and Mexico and smaller Persian Gulf
countries to support the pact.
</P>
<P>
   Underlining the care that OPEC took in orchestrating its
announcement for maximum effect, the accord was adopted in minutes
and announced in one of the shortest OPEC meetings in the group's
40-year-history, lasting less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually took 10 minutes from the moment the resolution was
proposed to the moment it was unanimously adopted,'' said Abdallah
al-Attiyah, Qatar's oil minister, at a lunch immediately following
the deliberations. ``The message to world oil markets from oil
producers is solidarity, unanimity and resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   As always with OPEC, it remains to be seen if the discipline and
resolve displayed here on Tuesday will last. As prices creep up,
temptation increases among producers to cheat by pumping more oil
to get more revenue. That is part of the reason that oil prices
have fallen so steeply in the last few years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Members of OPEC such as Nigeria, Indonesia and Venezuela are
suffering severe budget deficits partly because crude oil is
selling at so low a price. This has only increased the pressure on
them to grab any additional income that increased sales would
bring.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the pact was signed Tuesday, there was widespread
skepticism about the commitment of Russia to cut 100,000 barrels a
day from its exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``A barrel cut by Saudi Arabia is not the same as a barrel cut
by Russia,'' said Nordine Ait-Laoussine, Algeria's former oil
minister. ``When the Saudis say they will cut, they do cut. The
Russians are another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest commitment to reduce output came from Saudi Arabia,
which said it would cut back by 585,000 barrels of crude oil a day,
or 7 percent of its daily production of 8 million barrels. Under
the agreement, 10 members of OPEC will reduce output by a total of
1.7 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, an OPEC member and once a leading producer, is not being
asked to reduce its output of 2.6 million barrels a day. It needs
to pump as much oil as possible under the oil-for-food progra
</P>
</TEXT>
