<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. TRADE OFFICIALS WARN OF DANGER OF STEEL QUOTAS
</P>
<P>
   Facing a wave of protectionist sentiment, two top trade
officials contended that a House-passed measure to impose quotas on
steel imports would hurt the American economy, lead to raw material
shortages and rising prices and could set off a trade war. Speaking
before the Senate Finance Committee, United States Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Commerce Secretary William
Daley said the quotas could disrupt the steel market. In spite of
these warnings, the steel industry and some Senators vowed to push
for quotas.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS OF STRAIN AT DAIMLERCHRYSLER
</P>
<P>
   The merger in November of Daimler-Benz and Chrysler, presented
as a merger of equals, is producing considerable unhappiness among
some American managers who contend privately that DaimlerChrysler
has come to be dominated by Germans.
</P>
<P>
   BANK OF NEW YORK TO BUY TRUST UNIT
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of New York agreed to buy the trust bank of the Royal
Bank of Scotland for an undisclosed sum, making the Bank of New
York the world's largest custodian of investor assets. The Bank of
New York said the purchase would raise its total of assets under
custody to $5.9 trillion worldwide, moving it ahead of Chase
Manhattan. Shares of Bank of New York fell $1.25, to $36.9375.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T SELLS $8 BILLION IN BONDS
</P>
<P>
   Prices of government securities rose modestly as investors
focused primarily on AT&AMP;T's record $8 billion global bond offering.
The yield of the benchmark 30-year Treasury fell to 5.54 percent
from 5.57 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO TO TEST CLEANER DIESEL FUEL
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Richfield says it has developed a cleaner diesel fuel
for trucks and other large vehicles that will soon be tested on the
road in California, a national leader in pushing for the
development of cleaner-burning fuels.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-AMERITECH DEAL CLEARS HURDLE
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department gave conditional approval to the planned
takeover of Ameritech by SBC Communications, a deal that would
create the nation's largest local telephone company. The deal,
valued at $60 billion when it was announced last May, still
requires the approval of the Federal Communications Commission,
which is reviewing it.
</P>
<P>
   POWER PLANT UNITS TO COMBINE
</P>
<P>
   ABB Asea Brown Boveri, the world's leading
electrical-engineering company, and Alstom of France have agreed to
combine their power plant manufacturing units as recessions in Asia
reduce profits. The joint venture, with $11 billion in annual
sales, will leapfrog General Electric to become the world's biggest
maker of generating equipment. Goeran Lindahl, the chief executive
of ABB, said the company planned to use a $1.5 billion payment from
Alstom to make acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Edison International, California's second-biggest utility,
agreed to buy 16 power plants in Illinois from Unicom for $4.8
billion in cash as it expands into the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH TRUCKERS MOVING ABROAD
</P>
<P>
   Faced with far higher license fees and diesel fuel costs than
their Continental rivals, British truck drivers are losing
business, even within Britain. So some are ``flagging out'' _
incorporating elsewhere in Europe, but they will continue to pay
lower British wages.
</P>
<P>
   TWO NISSAN PARTS UNITS TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motor said two parts supplier subsidiaries, Calsonic and
Kansei, would merge, furthering the troubled auto maker's efforts
to simplify its sprawling operations, as it considers Renault's bid
for a 35 percent stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
