<SLUG> BC-SENATE-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELUCTANT SENATE SUPPORTS NATO AIRSTRIKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate gave reluctant support Tuesday to NATO
airstrikes against the forces of Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic
as a bipartisan group of lawmakers backed President Clinton's
effort to stop the killing of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-41 vote, however, was hardly a unified statement of
support for Clinton's policy in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Voting against the resolution were 38 of 55 Republicans,
including Texas Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison, and
three of 45 Democrats, because they fear all-out war in the region.
Republican Sen. Thad Cochran of Mississippi was not present for the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if we're not coming close to starting World War
III, we're starting a protracted involvement,'' declared Sen. Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith, R-New Hampshire, also voiced opposition, warning
his colleagues that authorizing force against Milosevic ``is a
mistake ... and we're going to regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote came after Republican leaders agreed to shelve
amendments offered by Hutchison and others that would have blocked
funding for U.S. involvement in a NATO mission unless Clinton
submitted a detailed plan to Congress, complete with a timetable.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to set aside those amendments was made after 30
members of the House and Senate met with Clinton at the White
House. He told them that although he hoped for their support, he
planned to go ahead with military action anyway. He said the NATO
air campaign would be aimed at forcing Milosevic back to the
negotiating table, or failing that, degrading his ability to
continue war on ethnic Albanian separatists fighting for
independence from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement signed by the Kosovo Albanians two weeks ago,
28,000 NATO troops, including up to 4,000 Americans, would be sent
to Kosovo as peacekeepers. But Milosevic has rejected the plan,
vowing to fight any attempt to insert foreign forces into Serbian
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., who voted against the authorization
of force, continued to insist that unless NATO forces are invited
in, any attempt to interfere in the situation in Kosovo militarily
would amount to ``an act of war'' on a sovereign nation, as
Milosevic contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake, if we conduct airstrikes against Yugoslavia,
we're going to war,'' Nickles said, adding that he believes the air
campaign will escalate to commitment of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., also questioned why the Clinton
administration considers Kosovo more important to U.S. interests
than other countries where ethnic conflicts rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are far greater slaughters taking place in the Sudan and
elsewhere around the world,'' he said, calling it ``highly unwise
and not worth'' the investment of U.S. lives and money to tangle
with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to the Vietnam War, he called the measure
authorizing use of military force ``this Senate's Gulf of Tonkin
resolution,'' the passage of which triggered the long U.S.
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton's comparison of Kosovo to Vietnam and other conflicts
drew an angry and blunt response from Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del.,
who rejected the contention that the United States has no interests
to protect in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Europe, not Africa or Asia,'' Biden shot back. ``The
loss of life in Somalia and the loss of life in Kosovo ... have
totally different consequences for the interests of the United
States ... What happens if the flood of refugees goes rolling into
Macedonia,'' he said, insisting that the failure of NATO to act now
would damage its credibility and allow the conflict to spread to
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no choice but to deal with this genocidal maniac,''
Biden said, referring to Milosevic. ``We have 365,000 (NATO) troops
in Europe right now to preserve the stability in Europe. ... If
that is a bad idea, then we shouldn't have anybody in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate in the Senate raged Tuesday as U.S. special envoy
Richard Holbrooke's 11th-hour attempt to convince Milosevic to
accept a Washington-brokered peace deal was ending in failure.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison told reporters as she left the White House meeting
that she was convinced that NATO aerial assaults were ``imminent.''
When asked if she would support a resolution authorizing the NATO
bombings, she indicated that she would likely vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``While many people may disagree with the president's policies,
I would not want Mr. Milosevic to get the impression that the
troops would not have the full support, and that the president
wouldn't have the support he needs, if we have troops in harm's
way,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hutchison, who has been a leading critic of the
administration's policies in Kosovo and Bosnia, called on Clinton
to provide Congress with a more comprehensive mission plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing a sovereign country that has not threatened the United
States is a very serious step,'' she said. She later voted against
the resolution, an aide said, because the administration had not
made a convincing case for it.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison and other Republicans had been prepared to withhold
funding for U.S. involvement in the NATO operation. But vocal
opposition from within Republican ranks to blocking U.S. action
also worked in the president's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is considering a run for the
Republican presidential nomination, took the Senate floor to oppose
amendments offered by Hutchison and others to block U.S.
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Milosevic as a ``remorseless, bloodthirsty''
dictator determined to wipe out the ethnic Albanian population in
Kosovo, McCain pointedly disputed claims by some GOP colleagues
that the killings in Kosovo have not been significant enough to
warrant NATO action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atrocities are the signature of the Serbian Army. They've been
carrying out atrocities since 1992,'' McCain said in remarks that
were highly critical of the Clinton administration for not
following through on two previous threats to stop the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not permit the genocide that Milosevic has in mind for
Kosovo to continue ... We are at a critical hour,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former Navy pilot who was shot down over Hanoi during
the Vietnam War and held prisoner for six years, also used his
speech to warn Americans about the risks of U.S. involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not, in all probability, be a casualty-free
operation,'' he said, adding that the nation would ``likely witness
some heartbreaking moments at Dover Air Force Base'' in Delaware if
Americans are killed in action and brought home for burial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
