<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MERCY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID LEADER REFUSES TO LEAVE UNTIL WORKERS ARE EVACUATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The head of operations for a Northwest-based aid agency in
Kosovo refused to abandon his Albanian staff Tuesday despite fears
of imminent NATO air strikes and massive Serbian retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Heselius, a 66-year-old great-grandfather who has worked
in Kosovo for Mercy Corps International since 1993, said in a
telephone interview Tuesday night that he made two round-trips from
the Kosovo capital of Pristina to the Macedonian border that day to
evacuate several of his Albanian staff. He was able to get most of
them safely across the frontier, but a few were denied entry
because they lacked the proper paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of crossing the border to safety, Heselius and an
American colleague, Scott Charlesworth, twice returned to the
increasingly tense Kosovo capital to help their local staffers
obtain the required exit documents. Tuesday night, the two
Americans were among the last foreigners remaining in the
strife-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty lonely around here,'' an exhausted Heselius said
after arriving back in Pristina for the second time. ``You get a
little bit of a strange feeling now, when the streets are nearly
empty and you can see the fear in people's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Braving Serb checkpoints and the promised threat of NATO air
strikes, Heselius, Charlesworth and their Albanian colleagues who
were unable to get into Macedonia returned to Pristina in two Mercy
Corps vehicles shortly before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Heselius said the group, including four Albanian adults and
seven children, would gather again at 8 a.m. Wednesday. They will
try to obtain the necessary exit documents for the Albanians and
then head straight for the border, about an hour's drive from
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Heselius said he understood the dangers and wanted to get out of
Kosovo as soon as possible. But he said he could not abandon
Albanian Mercy Corps staff and their families who desparately want
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was leading these convoys today and feel I'm responsible for
getting these people out,'' said Heselius, a former businessman who
lived in Kirkland, Wash., from 1991 until 1993, when he joined
Mercy Corps and was sent to Kosovo. ``I feel it is necessary to
help them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a NATO air strike, most analysts predict massive
Serbian retaliation against the Albanian population as well as any
foreigners remaining in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, it will happen if the bombs fall,'' Heselius said
of Serb retaliation. ``There will be a lot of problems here. That's
why we've got to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Heselius is Kosovo country director for Portland-based Mercy
Corps, overseeing some $25 million in aid programs provided by the
agency in Kosovo since 1993. The agency's 49 staff, including nine
expatriates, have provided food, winter gear, stoves, clothing,
seeds and other help to more than 250,000 people, about 10 percent
of the province's total population, Mercy Corps president and
co-founder Dan O'Neill said in the agency's Redmond, Wash., office.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill described the bearded, silver-haired Heselius as man of
``strong Christian faith who is able to get along with most
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's keeping his wits about him in a very difficult
situation,'' O'Neill said. ``He has a very strong sense of
commitment to our staff _ which is our policy everywhere we work.''
</P>
<P>
   Heselius said he decided to evacuate staff Tuesday after the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, the main humanitarian
organization in Kosovo, decided to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Heselius said he also felt obligated to accompany those denied
entry to Macedonia back to Pristina because of the increasing Serb
military presence in Kosovo. Military checkpoints have been the
scene of numerous abuses throughout the war-torn Balkans. The
presence of foreigners can sometimes alleviate the danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one incident tonight when we were stopped by an armed
soldier who made some nasty remarks about us and NATO,'' Heselius
said. ``He just wanted to see what kind of reaction he could get
out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   In Heselius' first trip to the Macedonian border Tuesday, he led
a convoy of 22 vehicles, from Mercy Corps as well as other
humanitarian agencies. He then led some of the vehicles back to
Pristina after some of the Albanians were denied entry. At
nightfall, he led a second convoy back to the border, but again
some of the Albanians needed more documents and had to be taken
back to Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Heselius said Pristina was extremely tense Tuesday afternoon and
evening, with the sound of gunfire echoing through surrounding
suburbs and people displaced by fighting wandering the roads with
nowhere to go. One Albanian staff member of the International
Rescue Committee, a U.S. aid agency, was killed in a grenade attack
on a cafe. Another IRC staffer was wounded, Heselius said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of incidents are just going to increase, I'm
afraid,'' Heselius said. ``The Serb military presence is
increasing. We had tanks driving past here the other day, about 50
of them coming right up our road. We've seen a lot of troop convoys
and planes and helicopters overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   Heselius said he's looking forward to joining his wife in
Florida, where the couple recently bought a home. They have four
children, 10 grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Corps International's web site is at: www.mercycorps.org
</P>
<P>
   or call 800-292-3355 ext. 250.
</P>
</TEXT>
