<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole takes stage at state oil convention
 &HT;    (EDS: Corrects tagline to credit Palm Beach Post.)
 &HT;    By Kelley Shannon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Potential GOP presidential candidate
Elizabeth Dole visited the home state of possible rival Gov. George
W. Bush on Tuesday, warning that Americans must return to a time of
responsibility and values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual and national character are what we need,'' Dole
said in a speech to the National Petrochemical and Refiners
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has become too bloated and too
bureaucratic, Dole said, and some federal money, particularly in
education, should be turned over to state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must restore our public schools to greatness, returning
discipline and parental involvement to every school in America,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The power of the presidency also should be used in the battle
against illegal drugs, Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need leadership on this issue, and certainly the
bully pulpit of the White House is one place where leadership must
be provided,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole didn't mention the other Republicans who may seek the
presidential nomination in 2000. But she did speak of her decision
to form a presidential exploratory committee to study a possible
run. Bush has also formed such a committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, wife of former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, the GOP
nominee for president in 1996, said her qualifications for the job
include Cabinet posts she held in the Reagan and Bush
administrations and her work as head of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the fact that this would be her first run for a
public office, Dole said: ``Well, I was president of my student
government at Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   On a serious note, she cited her Cabinet posts as secretary of
labor and secretary of transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the fact that I've had thirty-plus years in
service to the public. This has been my passion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Shannon writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
