<HEADER>
A1632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-CANKER-COX     03-23 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CANKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State burns canker-infected citrus trees
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With a spray of diesel fuel and the
flick of a cigarette lighter, state contractors began torching
grapefruit trees Tuesday in a Hendry County grove infected with
citrus canker bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The burning was the first step in the planned destruction of
about 280 acres of orange and grapefruit trees at two commercial
groves in the state's largest citrus-growing county.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions were just right,'' said Wendell Bowman, a
senior management analyst who is supervising the fires for the
state Department of Agriculture's Division of Plant Industry.
</P>
<P>
   Crews burned about 10 acres of red grapefruit trees Tuesday at
Siboney Citrus Inc., where 260 acres of orange trees and grapefruit
trees are to be destroyed in the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, state inspectors found evidence of the disease at
the Siboney grove _ about 500 acres just west of the Palm Beach
County line. A few weeks later, they saw it at a nearby grove owned
by the Seminole tribe of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Lab results last week confirmed what state pathologists were
sure of: The groves are infected with Asian citrus canker, which
kills citrus trees, but is harmless to people and animals.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to stop the canker bacteria, which can be carried
on clothes and equipment and spread by wind and rain, is to destroy
infected trees.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors uproot the trees and let them sit in 15-foot piles
to dry for several days before setting them on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those trees ignite very easily,'' said Jack Neitzke, director
of the Division of Plant Industry's Immokalee Canker Project.
</P>
<P>
   The fires must be put out an hour before sundown. Once the
burning is complete, contractors turn the soil to cut roots and
bury the remaining plant material, Neitzke said.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of 260 acres _ about 43,000 trees _ at Siboney
is expected to cost the state about $70,000. In addition, the state
will pay to burn about 21 acres of grapefruit trees at the Seminole
grove, Neitzke said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government this month pledged $25 million to battle
canker in Florida. The state legislature still is working on a plan
to find an additional $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The objective is to stamp out the disease before it devastates
Florida's $8.5 billion commercial citrus industry, which employs
more than 121,000.
</P>
<P>
   Grove owners, who will not be reimbursed for the lost trees, are
required to wait at least one year before replanting in the burned
areas, Neitzke said.
</P>
<P>
   Once state inspectors complete surveys of land surrounding the
infected groves, possibly as early as next week, quarantine
boundaries will be established.
</P>
<P>
   Any grove operating within or handling fruit from the quarantine
area will have to comply with state guidelines on sanitation,
decontamination and transportation of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a quarantine,'' Neitzke said. ``It's just a
matter of where.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Waresh writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
