<HEADER>
A1638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILANTHROPIST-COX     03-23 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILANTHROPIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arson hits Delray developer's ski retreat
 &HT;    By Chuck McGinness
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Developer and philanthropist Thomas Worrell
was welcomed with open arms by city officials and other investors
when he began buying and restoring old historic buildings downtown.
</P>
<P>
   But after Worrell undertook a similar venture in Taos, a ski
town in New Mexico's high desert country, a mountainside mansion he
was renovating as a family home was destroyed by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the New Mexico fire marshal's office and Taos
Fire Department concluded the Feb. 12 fire, which caused $1.8
million to $2.4 million in damage, was arson. Fire officials
estimated the 14,000-square-foot, two-story home would have been
worth about $4.5 million when completed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more than two dozen buildings Worrell has bought in
Taos have been covered with graffiti, with messages such as ``Go
home, get out'' and ``Watch your back.'' On March 15, three shots
were fired at a security guard outside Worrell's 150-year-old
adobe-style home, which he plans to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northern New Mexico has always been suspicious of outsiders,''
said Taos District Attorney John Paternoster, whose office is
conducting the arson investigation with the state police.
</P>
<P>
   But Paternoster also said the arson investigation is focusing on
``disgruntled former employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Worrell, 53, was not available for comment Tuesday, but his
representatives said some in Taos view him as an outsider trying to
take over the town.
</P>
<P>
   Taos Mayor Fred Peralta said a few folks who ``were used to
things the way they were'' did not take a liking to Worrell and the
way he flaunted his wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time somebody comes in and does the things he has done, it
always raises questions about why he's doing it,'' Peralta said.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell, who made his multimillion-dollar fortune selling
newspapers, discovered Taos a couple of years ago when he was
looking for a special place to take his wife, Odette, for her
birthday, his Delray Beach attorney, Rodney Romano, said.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled between the massive adobe landmarks of St. Francis of
Assisi Church on the south and the Taos Indian Pueblo on the north,
the town of about 10,000 permanent residents attracts an influx of
winter visitors for some of the nation's finest skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Taos also is known as an arts center, with more than 80
galleries featuring paintings, pottery, sculpture and other art
with a Southwestern flavor. The blend of Indian, Spanish and Anglo
cultures gives the community its distinctive character.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell ran into trouble early on in Taos for not following
historic preservation rules, Peralta said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Worrell has hired a historian and architect to
restore the buildings as much as possible to their original
condition. ``He's trying to be sensitive to local customs,'' Romano
said.
</P>
<P>
   In both Delray Beach and Taos, Worrell has drawn criticism for
the bright colors and flashy features he uses in his redevelopment
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell converted one of Delray's oldest houses, a 1905
Methodist rectory, into his real estate development office and gave
it a pink and turquoise paint job. His buildings in the first block
of South Swinton Avenue and near the city's railroad tracks are
bright yellow, green and peach.
</P>
<P>
   In Taos, some think Worrell's taste is sinful, Peralta said.
Others think it gives downtown a much fresher face.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell has no plans to leave Taos, despite the threats and
violence, Romano said. To show his commitment, he has opened a home
school for children from poor families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's been very good to the community and supported a
number of activities and organizations he didn't have to,'' Peralta
said. ``He's trying to become a productive member of the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McGinness writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
