A1639 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LIKE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT'S LIKE, YOU KNOW ...': L.A. TAKES A BEATING IN SHARP
NEW  SITCOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's Like, You Know ...'' is the worst show title on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Who'd ever admit to watching ``It's Like, You Know ...''? You
might say, ``I caught `Frasier' last night,'' or ``I stayed home
and watched `Homicide.''' But, ``I saw `It's Like, You Know ...'''?
Huh-uh.
</P>
<P>
   A shame, because ``It's Like, You Know ...'' could be the
season's best new comedy. Not counting ``The Sopranos'' on HBO, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of two diverting new comedies on ABC Wednesday night.
The other, ``The Norm Show,'' catches Norm Macdonald on a quick
rebound after his dishonorable discharge from ``Saturday Night
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``It's Like, You Know ...'' is the attention-getter because
it dabs a vague ``Seinfeld'' fragrance onto a cheeky satire of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The show's creator is Peter Mehlman, a writing and producing
veteran of ``Seinfeld.'' His New Yorkish take on L.A. is revealed
through the character of Arthur (Chris Eigeman), an East Coast
magazine writer who has agreed to experience L.A. so that he can
harpoon it in a book.
</P>
<P>
   (It's Eigeman's first TV series, but you'll recognize him as the
Pac Bell man in the commercials from a few years ago, or as the
actor who stretched his vowels and his neuroses in the Whit
Stillman movies ``Metropolitan,'' ``Barcelona'' and ``The Last Days
of Disco.'')
</P>
<P>
   As Arthur, Eigeman stays in L.A. with his college roommate,
Robbie (Steven Eckholdt), who is occupying a guest house belonging
to his buddy Shrug (Evan Handler). Shrug is rich _ trust-fund rich
_ idle, slightly guilty about it all, and bald.
</P>
<P>
   There are your three guys. The show's two women may be more of
an inspiration. Lauren (A.J. Langer) is a masseuse and a legal
process server. Better still is Jennifer Grey, of ``Dirty Dancing''
and ``Red Dawn'' notoriety, as herself, the friendly neighborhood
actress living next door to the guest house.
</P>
<P>
   The show's short scenes, quirky characters in roles big and
small, and lack of potent plot turns all seem to reflect Mehlman's
``Seinfeld'' background. But the emphasis on satirizing Southern
California gives ``It's Like, You Know ...'' its own reason to
exist.
</P>
<P>
   The city's dominant car culture figures in the first two shows.
Tonight, Robbie is a hero, and is introduced to a fashion model,
simply because his car horn is broken. And much is made of the fact
that Robbie and Shrug spot Elliott Gould driving a Honda. Next
week, the five characters spend an entire day watching a high-speed
freeway chase on TV. It's the L.A. equivalent of a ``snow day.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is L.A. so ripe for biting? If you need to know, here's
Robbie:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take a drive to take a walk. The houses are ugly,
the clothes are loud, the bagels are doughy, the pizza sucks, the
murder trials last two years, the marriages last two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you throw in earthquakes, aftershocks, mudslides, road
rage, race riots, guns, tasers, pepper spray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as your head's about to explode, boom, one warm afternoon
you play softball and you think to yourself, my God, it's January.
Next day you wake up, it's two years later, you've sold out every
belief you hold sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   About then, he might have added, you find yourself eating Dodger
dogs and figuring you could beat the traffic if you left in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``The Norm Show,'' it has a perfect picture of who its
star is and what qualities, or lack of qualities, Macdonald
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald's exasperated boss on the show (Bruce Jarchow) says
it: ``You know, I can never tell if you're joking or you're just
plain stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it, Norm Macdonald in 14 words. He's a bit old
for a slacker, but you get the impression that he started early in
life.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald plays Norm Henderson, a former professional hockey
player who was banned from the sport for gambling and tax evasion,
and who is employed as a social worker as his community-service
penance. One misstep and he's off to jail.
</P>
<P>
   The humor is in a character who cares not a whit about other
people _ accentuated by that joking or just plain stupid attitude _
and finds himself in a job that's all about other people's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   When a client goes bad, Macdonald shrugs and says to a
colleague, ``I lost one, so what?'' But TV is TV, so in due course
the viewer learns that ol' Norm is rotten and lazy on the outside
but tender inside.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his nonchalance drives his closest work companion nuts.
That would be Laurie Metcalf, late of ``Roseanne,'' as a
rule-conscious social worker who is appalled, and maybe a bit
intrigued, by Norm.
</P>
<P>
   The show seems to be as loose-jointed and insouciant as its
star. But the writing, at least on the pilot, can abruptly kick and
rear itself to a point.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Norm adopts a dog tonight, and then the original
owner wants it back. Norm won't give it back. Hey, says the guy,
you can't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're social workers, pal,'' Norm tells him. ``We can take
(set ital)children.(end ital)''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
