<HEADER>
A1642 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIXFLAGS-DROWNING-TEX     03-23 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXFLAGS-DROWNING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER RIDE SURVIVORS SAY RAFT FILLED WITH WATER BEFORE IT CAPSIZED
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies SIX FLAGS-SURVIVOR, SIX FLAGS-SAFETY, and SIX
FLAGS-RESCUE) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT THARP, 
RENEE C. LEE 
And SEAN WOOD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Before their boat flipped over and trapped
them underwater Sunday evening at Six Flags Over Texas, passengers
on the Roaring Rapids Ride said they noticed water rising above
their ankles, followed by a crashing sound.
</P>
<P>
   Ride inspectors gathered around the site of the tragedy on
Tuesday, examining a series of pipes designed to sit underwater and
create the rides' white-water effects. The pool area, just 200 feet
from the end of the ride, marks the approximate spot where
passengers recalled the raft striking something or becoming jammed
on an object beneath the churning water.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after feeling the impact, the 12-seat raft dipped below
the water surface on the downstream side, causing the current to
push the rear up and over, survivor Courtney Hanks and others said
on Tuesday. During the ordeal, survivors and park officials said,
the raft had become separated from its doughnut-shaped inflatable
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I thought it would go back down. When I saw we
weren't going down, I took the seat belt and ripped it off of us,''
said Hanks, 18. ``I saw it happening. I thought, `I'm going to
die.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve people were strapped in their seats when the boat tipped
over about 5:20 p.m. Visitors and park security workers jumped in
the water to help rescue the passengers but were unable to save
28-year-old Valeria Cartwright of West Helena, Ark. Ten passengers
were treated for injuries, and two remained hospitalized last
night.
</P>
<P>
   The park will reopen as scheduled on Saturday, but the ride will
remain closed until the investigation is complete and a Texas
Department of Insurance inspection is conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials said they are investigating several different
situations that could have caused the deadly accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're casting a wide net,'' said park spokeswoman Nancy St.
Pierre. ``We're not going in with blinders on.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre said the ride had been shut down earlier Sunday to
inspect a problem that was discovered by the park's computer
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our maintenance people came out, inspected the ride, reset the
ride and tested the ride before letting people back on it,'' she
said. ``That was in the conveyor belt area. It had nothing to do
with the accident on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre would not comment on any theories by passengers about
what caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with TIG Insurance, the Irving-based insurance company
of Six Flags' parent, Premier Parks Inc., also declined comment on
possible causes of the fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still investigating and it's too early to draw any kind
of conclusion,'' a TIG spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Park maintenance and safety officials are investigating the
accident along with Premier's safety engineer. Investigations are
also being conducted by the ride's manufacturer, Intamin AG, and
officials with Canyon Manufacturing, which made the inner-tube
base.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Insurance oversees ride safety and
requires the operator to perform annual inspections, carry at least
$1 million in liability insurance on each ride and file quarterly
injury reports for each ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Roaring Rapids ride has been a popular attraction since it
was installed in 1983. The 1 1/2 to 2 minute ride sends passengers
in rafts through a series of rapids. Water flows over pipes
installed laterally along the course to create turbulance and move
water through the course.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors said they felt something was wrong before the boat
capsized. Ginny Venneberg, 40, was sitting on the upstream side of
the raft and noticed that the downstream end of raft hit what
looked like a platform and came to a stop before it capsized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see something there,'' said Venneberg from her home in
Lawrence, Kan. ``It looked like a platform. Maybe it was made of
wood. I don't know what it was, but it was like it didn't have
enough water for the boat to go over it. I don't remember hearing a
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Venneberg, like several other passengers on the ride, also said
there was ankle- to calf-deep water inside the raft before it
capsized. Venneberg said she recalled commenting, almost in a
joking way, to another passenger that the raft was going to sink if
the water continued to build up.
</P>
<P>
   She said she's been on the water ride and similar rides many
times before, and that she had ``never seen it fill up that much''
with water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was higher than I've ever seen it in those boats,'' she
said. ``Usually it splashes in and runs out, but this didn't and it
began it to worry me.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Wilson, 23, of Everman, Texas, said that many of the
passengers were commenting about how the raft was going to sink if
more water accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were half serious and half joking,'' she said. ``We were
not consciously thinking that something was seriously wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Then ``it felt like it hit something,'' she said. ``It felt as
though it jammed against something and came to a dead stop.
Everybody was looking like, `Why have we stopped and the farthest
end away from me began to sink. My end was at the top and it began
to lift straight up in the air, almost perpendicular. The water was
pushing so hard, it pushed us straight over.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Martin, an associate professor of civil and environmental
engineering at the University of Texas at Arlington, said that
based on the reports from the passengers, extra water in the raft
could have caused it to capsize if there was a wave of water coming
from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wave lifts up the raft, the water inside rushes up front,
changing the center of gravity and further destabilzes the raft,
possibly toppling over,'' Spindler said.
</P>
<P>
   Spindler added that he would need to know the size of the raft,
the weight of the people inside the raft and the distribution of
weight to determine exactly what effect the extra water inside may
have had. He said the excess water may not have drained properly
from the raft if the tubes surrounding the raft were underinflated
or improperly attached to the raft.
</P>
<P>
   But Spindler said there is a point that if there is too much
water in the raft, it won't tip over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a critical point at which the water has to be to have
that effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Busch Gardens Tampa Bay, a theme park in Tampa, Florida, that
has a ride similar to Roaring Rapids, employees are required to
follow and observe rafts from the banks throughout the ride, said
Margaret Norquist, public relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``They follow them for safety reasons,'' she said. ``We have
cameras that allow us to monitor the raft as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafts for the Busch Gardens ride, which is called the Congo
River Rapids, have never taken in water, other than the normal
amount that comes in over the sides during the ride, Norquist said.
There have been no injuries reported since the ride was introduced
in 1982, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Busch Gardens will not change its safety procedures and the
Congo River Rapids will continue to operate despite the Arlington
accident, Norquist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very thorough safety feature in place and all of our
rides are inspected every day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
