<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1643 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGOLAND-ATTRACTIONS-     03-23 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGOLAND-ATTRACTIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOW THE LEGO BRICK ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-LEGOLAND and BC-LEGOLAND-NEARBY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miniland, with its stunning Lego-built reconstruction of New
York, Washington and New Orleans, among other places, is the
LEGOLAND masterpiece. But several other attractions combine to
create an interactive atmosphere of wonder:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Legoland band, whose jaunty tunes can be heard in most
corners of the park, is not your usual group of strolling
minstrels. The orchestra consists of brightly colored instruments
placed in a row near the park's entrance. Stand on the colored
circle corresponding to an instrument and water begins shooting up,
music begins to play. When enough people stand on enough circles,
the whole fountain band, called Stepping Tones, kicks in, and
oompah fills the California air.
</P>
<P>
   _ An elevated monorail provides the best views of the park and
surrounding hills, and riders have plenty of time to look, for the
Sky Cycle will never be confused with a roller coaster. The cars
are pedal-powered, for one thing. Only if young (or old) legs tire
do the electric motors in the Lego-themed vehicles kick in.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the ground, the most comprehensive look at the park comes
from the seat of a boat inching its way along the moatlike lake
that traverses the park. The pace of the trip reminds one of barge
rides on San Antonio's River Walk, with Legoland riders treated to
Lego-rendered shore attractions like Mount Rushmore and the Taj
Mahal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Legoland has the stated aim of raising America's expectations
of theme-park cuisine. The Fun Town Market offers a massive salad
bar, pastries, fresh bread and fruit, but the hot entrees set the
place apart. My Swiss stir-fry, potatoes and vegetables, was
prepared while I waited. It was delicious, as was my wife's
ravioli.
</P>
<P>
   _ Legoland devotes 13,000 square feet to its youngest visitors,
kids ages 2 through 6. It's called Playtown, with a colorful maze
for kids to crawl, hide and swing on, a miniature train, and
interactive adventures _ talking to the Lego fire chief on the
telephone, listening to a heartbeat through a stethoscope.
</P>
<P>
   _ Legoland more or less insists on occasional rest. For that,
the Enchanted Walk is as fine a place as any. The path leads
through a forest, with Lego fish leaping from a real brook, gray
Lego rabbits, Lego deer, Lego fox, Lego owls and squirrels in real
trees. The peace and quiet is real, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1644 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-23 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SAVING PRIVATE GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore could do worse than to take a lesson from
the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitability can be insufferable.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president could turn out to be the ``Saving Private
Ryan'' of presidential candidates. Last summer, Steven Spielberg's
World War II movie was proclaimed all but certain to win best
picture. It was worthy. It was good. It was dutiful. There was
nothing flashy or sexy about it. It was, in short, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But after months of hearing about the front-runner's
invincibility, Academy voters couldn't wait to overturn it _
preferring to make love, not war _ and give the statuette to a
sassy Elizabethan upstart with a biting political campaign and a
clever message.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Al might do well to nudge aside his Dreamworks team and
lend an ear to Harvey Weinstein, the Miramax big shot who toppled
``Ryan'' with his ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has all the classic trappings of the front-runner. He has
bulldozed endorsements from the Democratic chieftains, Dick
Gephardt and Tom Daschle, and scooped up money from Wall Street to
Hollywood. He recycles small, poll-tested policies and bite-sized
issues, like creating a special telephone number for commuters in
traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   His itsy-bitsy ``livability'' issues echo Dick Morris, who
brought President Clinton back from the brink of political
extinction by having him cater to the worries of self-centered
boomers. But some Gore supporters wonder if it's wise to repeat the
trick.
</P>
<P>
   There's a weird syndrome kicking in. The more the vice president
hugs his mantle of inevitability _ the closer he moves to the prize
he has wanted his whole life _ the more skittish he gets about
taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   His Hollywood gurus want to rush in with some speech coaching.
His old friends see the pressure building and tell him to loosen
up.
</P>
<P>
   The more afraid he is to make mistakes, the more mistakes he
makes. The more the coast looks clear, the more Gore throws
impediments in his own way.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has the background and accomplishments to be
president, he takes no Clintonesque joy in campaigning and seems
insecure, giving curiously flat and airless speeches and needlessly
inflating his feats and his history.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the vice president has repeated the mistake he made
with ``Love Story'' and drawn ridicule by boasting that he was the
father of the Internet and a master at cleaning hog waste and
plowing farmland with a team of mules.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so afraid to make mistakes,'' said one Democrat who has
worked with him and likes him. ``You hold everything in and hold
everything in and hold everything in and then all of a sudden,
stuff pops out.''
</P>
<P>
   He first played the Good Son to his father, the legendary
Tennessee senator and populist stemwinder. He then played the Good
Brother to the wayward and sweet-talking Bill Clinton, in a sort of
West Wing version of ``East of Eden.'' Now he seems tongue-tied and
timid.
</P>
<P>
   The closer he gets to the crown, the less Prince Albert is able
to integrate the two sides of his personality. He shows the more
appealing side to reporters and friends in private. But get him on
a podium and he coils and clinches, reading even the simplest
greeting or expression of gratitude in a dead-zone voice.
</P>
<P>
   At a Gore 2000 fund-raiser at a Washington hotel, one prominent
Democratic supporter derided Gore's freeze-dried remarks with a
sardonic aside, saying, ``Gee, he should think about bottling
that.'' Tipper Gore didn't help the sizzle factor by introducing
her husband as ``a fine fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton doesn't even bother to recover from mistakes. He
just keeps going. Al Gore spends a week plotting a strategy to fix
his mistake and finally comes up with a self-deprecating joke at
just the moment everyone has started forgetting the original gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 2000 race is between two dauphins born at third
base. Al and George are the sons of famous politicians named Al and
George. While they both may suffer from famous-father syndrome,
they are reacting against their dads in different ways. Gore's
supporters worry that he is too controlled and zombielike. George
W.'s supporters fear he isn't controlled enough and in the heat of
a campaign may become hotheaded.
</P>
<P>
   One has yet to articulate in a fetching way. One has yet to
articulate at all. It won't be long before we look back
nostalgically to the days when politics was entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
