<HEADER>
A1645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIWI-BANKRUPT-550&AMP;ADD     03-23 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIWI-BANKRUPT-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 KIWI AIRLINES FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY; TAKEOVER BY PAN AM EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story is a late substitute for DAIMLER-CHRYSLER on the
Business Day front page.) 
(mk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kiwi International Airlines filed for bankruptcy protection
Tuesday, stipulating that it had a commitment from Pan American
Airlines Inc. of $3 million in new financing to pay off Kiwi's
debts.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives of both airlines, the Chapter 11
bankruptcy filing in New Jersey was structured to lay groundwork
for a takeover of Kiwi by Pan American, which itself was acquired
while under bankruptcy court protection in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Kiwi said there would be no interruptions in
flights.
</P>
<P>
   For Kiwi, a once-innovative, employee-owned carrier best known
for its budget-fare flights from Newark, N.J., International
Airport, the move Tuesday promised a financial reprieve only hours
after the Transportation Department threatened to revoke its
operating certificate.
</P>
<P>
   The department, saying it was no longer confident of Kiwi's
management, cited large financial losses by the airline and its
failure to pay fees at airports from which it operates, which
officials said have accumulated into an unpaid debt of $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department said Kiwi, based in Newark, had an
operating loss of $19.8 million in 1998 and a net loss of $20.6
million for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Unless an acceptable financial revamping plan is submitted by
Kiwi within two weeks, the government said it may withdraw the
airline's authority to fly, perhaps leading to disruption and
losses for passengers who have booked tickets on Kiwi flights weeks
or months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department rarely revokes airline certificates,'' said
Rodney Slater, the transportation secretary, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He said one reason to publicize the threat against Kiwi was to
``prevent potential harm and inconvenience to customers.''
</P>
<P>
   If consummated, a takeover of Kiwi by Pan American would combine
two of the nation's most beleaguered airlines. Both carriers, now
privately held, have emerged from bankruptcies. A Kiwi spokesman,
Robert Kulat, said Tuesday night that any final takeover
discussions would not take place until after Kiwi had satisfied its
debts and emerged from bankruptcy court protection. But he added
that Pan American would have a leg up on any other potential
suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Pan American, which for decades was among the nation's largest
airlines before it sought bankruptcy protection in 1998, was
acquired that year by Timothy Mellon, a descendant of the
Pittsburgh Mellon dynasty, and David Fink, a partner and co-owner
of Guilford Transportation Industries, a rail freight company in
New England.
</P>
<P>
   The two investors have since operated Pan American as a charter
airline, expanding their fleet to seven jets from only two when it
was acquired. By acquiring Kiwi, Pan American could gain regularly
scheduled access to the airports used by Kiwi in Newark; Orlando,
Palm Beach and Miami in Florida, and San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly interested,'' said Fink in an interview
Tuesday from Pan American's headquarters at the former Pease Air
Force Base in Portsmouth, N.H. Asked if the company would keep a
budget rate fare strategy, using Newark as a hub for a combined
airline, he said, ``We would like to do the best that is possible
along those lines but would try to avoid the problems that Kiwi has
encountered.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such problems have plagued both Kiwi and its passengers in
recent years. The airline, founded by pilots from several bankrupt
airlines in 1992, had been instantly popular with New York area
customers because of its low-rate flights, including a $99 ticket
from Newark to Orlando, before running out of money and filing for
bankruptcy protection in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It was rescued by an outside investor new to the airline
industry, Dr. Charles Edwards, a Baltimore physician who bought
Kiwi and has retained his position as its chairman while continuing
a regular practice in spinal surgery.
</P>
<P>
   After initial hopes that Edward's infusion of cash, known to be
more than $5 million, would reverse its decline, Kiwi encountered a
rash of customer complaints the last two years about things like
erratic service and canceled flights. It was forced to cancel its
service to Boston last year after it fell behind in payments to
Logan International Airport, which threatened it with eviction.
</P>
<P>
   Using only leased aircraft, Kiwi has seen a sharp erosion in its
fleet, which fell to only six planes in February after two were
repossessed.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday night, Kiwi said it had named Gene
Gillespie, a lawyer who has had much day-to-day authority over its
operations, as its chief executive. It said Edwards would remain as
chairman, but in an interview, Kulat, the company spokesman, said
the Transportation Department had made clear that it wanted Edwards
removed from day-to-day management authority.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to speculate on financial terms of a takeover by
Pan American, Kulat said Kiwi was confident that its fresh infusion
of cash would suffice to appease its creditors and meet the demands
of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's threat that it could be shut down by the
government _ perhaps in less than a month _ Kulat said Kiwi
employees were continuing to encourage people to book flights far
in advance. ``We are telling people we will be here for them,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2202EST &QL; 
