<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      03-23 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After an 11th-hour diplomatic effort failed,
President Clinton on Tuesday set the stage for almost immediate
NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia, warning Americans that US
involvement in the conflict would not be a ``a slam-dunk.''
</P>
<P>
   With a bombing campaign against Serbian targets now apparently
just a matter of timing and tactics, congressional leaders who had
opposed US military involvement reversed course, saying they wanted
to support the troops.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov was on his way to
Washington when he responded to the escalating crisis by directing
his pilot to return to Russia. Vice President Al Gore had told
Primakov he could not guarantee that airstrikes would not take
place during the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Airstrikes quickly gained an appearance of inevitability after
US special envoy Richard Holbrooke left Belgrade Tuesday morning
without getting Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to sign a
peace agreement. Holbrooke described the situation with the Serbian
leader as ``the bleakest since we began this effort almost four
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The envoy then flew to Brussels to brief NATO leaders on his
failed talks with Milosevic. Afterward, NATO Secretary General
Javier Solana announced he was directing US General Wesley Clark,
the alliance's military commander, to launch airstrikes in
Yugoslavia. Solana said he made the decision after extensive
consultations with the allies and after it had become clear that
all attempts to achieve a negotiated political settlement had
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said Yugoslavia had failed to heed the demands of the
international community to accept an interim peace agreement and
end the use of force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert invited Clinton to appear before a
joint House-Senate session after the attack begins to explain his
decision. Clinton, who sent a letter to Congress explicitly asking
for congressional support for airstrikes, said he would consider
it.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the first phase of a NATO-led bombing
campaign is aimed at ``blinding'' Serbia's substantial air defense
radar and missile systems with an attack by Air Force bombers and
cruise missiles launched from US Navy ships and submarines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plans for a swift and severe air campaign,'' said
Kenneth Bacon, Pentagon spokesman. ``We believe this will be
painful for the Serbs. We hope that relatively quickly'' they
``will realize they have made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has eight B-52 bombers based in England that could
fly to the Adriatic and launch cruise missiles without having to
enter Yugoslav airspace, Bacon said. The Navy also has four
warships and two attack submarines in the Adriatic armed with
Tomahawk cruise missiles. Of the roughly 400 allied aircraft,
almost half are American.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the B-2 Spirit bomber, whose stealth technology is
designed to make it almost invisible to enemy air defense systems,
could be deployed. It has never been used in combat before.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton briefed about 40 key members of Congress in the White
House residence for the second time in four days on the imminent
strikes. Then he used a speech at a labor conference to offer his
most detailed rationale for the US policy in the Balkans, even
invoking the history of conflict in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He said America's involvement in Kosovo is about ``our values.''
He asked, ``What if someone had listened to Winston Churchill and
stood up to Adolf Hitler earlier? How many peoples' lives might
have been saved?''
</P>
<P>
   The president said military action would limit Milosevic's
ability to carry out ethnic cleansing against the Albanians, as
well as prevent a refugee crisis and a wider war that could spread
beyond the Balkans to neighboring Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do it now, we'll have to do it later, and more
people will die, and it will cost more money,'' Clinton said. He
also suggested a long-term strategic reason for US involvement.
``Our children need a stable, free Europe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to level with you. . . . This is like any other
military action. There are risks in it,'' Clinton told the
convention of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a slam-dunk,'' he added. ``This is a difficult
issue. . . . I believe that the position I have taken is the best
of a lot of bad alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   As events swiftly spiraled toward a showdown in Kosovo, Primakov
abruptly postponed his visit to discuss economic and scientific
cooperation between the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has long opposed any attack on the Serbs but joined the
United States and four European nations to formulate the self-rule
plan for Kosovo that Milosevic rejected.
</P>
<P>
   According to administration officials, Gore spoke twice to
Primakov _ when his plane was on the ground at Shannon, Ireland,
and then over the Atlantic. One official said Gore was firm about
the possibility of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of airstrikes appeared temporarily to blunt
congressional criticism of the administration's overall policy in
the Balkans, as well as opposition to the use of US forces in the
region. In his meeting with congressional leaders, Clinton told
them airstrikes would proceed with or without their support.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than consider a measure to block funding for American
military action, as scheduled, the Senate on Tuesday night voted
58-to-41 to approve a resolution supporting US troops, despite some
members' concerns that the mission was ill-defined and lacked an
exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a different issue when action becomes imminent,''
said Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Texas Republican, after the
White House meeting. ``While many people may disagree with the
president's policies, I would not want Mr. Milosevic to get the
impression'' that US forces were not fully supported.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Senator John F. Kerry said, ``I think the way
we got here is less than ideal, but I believe that we need to
follow through on the effort to reduce Milosevic's military
capacity as the lesser of bad choices, and I hope that it can lead
to adherence to a legitimate peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said he strongly supported Clinton's
efforts in the Balkans and felt the president ``has clearly gone
many extra miles for peace. Unfortunately, it now appears that the
only language the leaders of Serbia understand is force.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the Senate floor, Senator John McCain, an Arizona
Republican, said now was the time to support the commander in
chief, but he pointed out there are widespread concerns on Capitol
Hill about what could be ``our most challenging and perilous
military action since President Clinton took office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress and the American people have good reason to fear that
we are heading toward another permanent garrison of Americans in a
Balkan country where our mission is confused and our exit strategy
a complete mystery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton said his natural tendency was to ``do
everything I can to avoid'' war, but Holbrooke ``got nowhere'' in
his two days of talks with Milosevic and ``NATO is now united and
prepared to carry out its warning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Milosevic is not willing to make peace, we are
willing to limit his ability to make war on the Kosovars,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Americans to note that the latest Balkan conflict has
no natural boundaries. He also urged people to ``say a prayer for
the young men and women in uniform, who are going to be there to do
what I, as their commander in chief, order them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
