<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1651 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  bc-LADN-S24MUNSON     03-23 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
bc-LADN-S24MUNSON
regretted forsaking more than half a million dollars to attend USC.
It was shortly after Eric's freshman year, and he had returned home
to San Diego for the summer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He said he was looking forward to going back to school,''
Steve said. ``I asked him if he wanted to go back to play baseball?
He said, no, what he really missed was his friends and going to
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Munson figures to become a millionaire in less than three
months. The USC catcher is projected by some scouting services as
the No. 1 pick in the amateur draft but for sure a top-five pick.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of falling into any of the trappings associated with
being perhaps the most-hyped college baseball player in the nation,
Munson has made a point of making himself just another college
student in his three years as a Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   Munson lives with three teammates at USC, none of whom are
starters, when he could easily have his own apartment. When he
rides his bike around campus, wearing his floppy hat, he's as
anonymous as anyone else. And he never yells at his teammates,
although he could certainly get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way I am. No matter what happens,'' Munson
said. ``You can never get too excited. You can never get high or
low.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's one reason Munson refused to become too giddy when
the Atlanta Braves offered $585,000 to sign him straight out of
Mount Carmel High in San Diego. Instead, Munson went to USC, a move
that seems a master stroke based on what teams will have to pay him
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a major-league catcher waiting to happen,'' USC coach
Mike Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   But Munson insists he never got caught up in the financial
possibilities while making his decision to go to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned it down. Money's never been a problem,'' Munson said.
``College is a tough act to follow. Growing up from the age of 18
to 21, maturing and growing up. It's made me a better person. I
would have missed out on so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is `Are you glad you went to
college?' I am.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue that point because college has been an almost
ideal experience for Munson. He was The Sporting News' Freshman of
the Year in 1997 after hitting .336 with 13 home runs and 56 RBI.
Last season, he led USC to the College World Series title in Omaha,
hitting .392 with 16 home runs and 56 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Omaha and winning a national championship, you can't
put a price tag on that,'' Munson said.
</P>
<P>
   This year he was named Collegiate Baseball's preseason National
Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good a hitter as there is,'' said Loyola Marymount
coach Frank Sanchez, a former USC assistant. ``He's left-handed,
hits with power and can hit to all fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Munson has shied away from focusing much on his
accolades, preferring to talk about the Trojans instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to pay attention to that stuff,'' Munson
said. ``It doesn't get you any wins. I've never put any pressure on
myself or the team.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not even worried about having a big junior season to ensure
his draft status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have seen me play for four years now, since my
junior year of high school. They know what I can do,'' Munson said.
``I don't have to go out and hit five home runs every game. It's
based on projectability.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't all been perfect for Munson. Last year he suffered a
stress fracture in his foot that caused him to miss 16 games. He
returned to the lineup just before the playoffs but did not receive
medical clearance to do anything other than hit. By the time USC
reached the College World Series, Munson decided to make an
executive decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``My foot wasn't completely healed,'' Munson said. ``I went
against doctors orders and caught.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended up hitting .476 in the World Series and catching every
game. The decision to play full-time was a no-brainer in Munson's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an unbelievable feat,'' Munson said. ``We lost our
first game to LSU, the defending champions, and then we won five
straight games, including beating LSU twice.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Series was extra special for Munson because he had
about 30 friends and relatives at each game. His uncle, Bob Munson,
was an All-American pitcher at the University of Nebraska, and his
father played on the Cornhuskers' basketball team for one season.
</P>
<P>
   Munson's parents have attended every home and away USC baseball
game the past three seasons, except for a trip to Hawaii during
Eric's freshman year. This weekend, the Trojans probably won't have
many fans on their road trip to Washington State, but Steve will be
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm afraid to add it up,'' Steve said of the money
spent following his son. ``It's just something my wife and I have
enjoyed doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of Munson's final season also didn't go quite as
planned after USC got off to a rocky start, losing 11 of its first
15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough. We were in every ballgame we played. We lost a
lot of one-run games,'' Munson said. ``We're kind of young. We had
some people playing out of position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have regrouped, however, evening their record at
14-14, and are 5-1 in the Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a whole new season,'' Munson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
