<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHIOPIAN-RUNNER-TRIA     03-23 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIAN-RUNNER-TRIAL-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLDE, WINNER OF THE 1968 OLYMPIC MARATHON, AWAITS A MURDER TRIAL
IN ETHIOPIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JERE VAN DYK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia _ On a hot morning in late November, the
dry season in Ethiopia, women lined up outside the Federal High
Court building carrying umbrellas or wearing cotton scarves over
their head to block the sun. Men stood on the opposite side of a
small dirt road by a row of trees. Under the watchful eye of
soldiers carrying Kalashnikov rifles, they submitted to frisking,
then filed up several steps into the one-story courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   They had come to witness what are known here as the Red Terror
Trials, an attempt by the government to prosecute those accused of
the killings and atrocities that occurred during the 17-year
struggle for political power following the Ethiopian revolution in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women were friends or relatives of either the
victims or the people charged with killing them, and they sat
placidly on one side of a wooden barrier as two groups of
prisoners, totaling about 200, were brought before the court. The
room was spare, with a few formal trappings _ a purple cloth
backdrop, three dark wood judges' chairs and Ethiopian flags with
bright silver spear points.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners stood as a prosecutor read the charges. Most of
the prisoners were obscure, some sickly or destitute. But one man,
wiry and dignified-looking in a blue suit, white shirt and striped
tie, drew whispers _ ``that's him'' _ as he stood with his head up,
looking straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   His name was Degaga ``Mamo'' Wolde, and more than 30 years ago,
in October 1968, he stood on a victory stand in Mexico City,
smiling and waving. With a victory in the marathon, he had become
the second Ethiopian, after Abebe Bikila, to win an Olympic gold
medal. Wolde became a national hero and a vital link in the rich
tradition of distance running that has distinguished Ethiopian
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Now he was on trial on charges of genocide and illegal detention
of prisoners during the reign of terror that followed the overthrow
of Emperor Haile Selaisse in 1974. Wolde is accused of shooting and
killing a young boy as a member of an urban precinct group known as
a kebele; he denies doing it, and his lawyer's defense in court is
that the government can produce no witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The trial that day in November was put off until December. It
was later rescheduled for March 29. Wolde, now either 67 or 68
years old, remains in the prison he entered in 1993, protesting his
innocence and waiting for a deliverance he believes will come.
</P>
<P>
   Wolde's guilt or innocence may be unknowable, but truth and
guilt remain murky concepts in post-revolutionary Ethiopia. And as
the government sifts through the horrors of the past two decades
and tries to form a path to the future, Mamo Wolde has discovered
that there is no shield strong enough to prevent prosecution, not
even Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
   On a dusty street outside the courthouse, Atnafu Bogale, Wolde's
lawyer, stood by his old, white Volkswagen. Bogale was hired by the
International Olympic Committee in 1996 to represent Wolde, and
indeed the former runner has some high-powered people watching his
case, including the IOC's humanitarian division and Amnesty
International. So far, they have failed to secure any special
treatment from the Ethiopian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mamo and the others are charged with killing 12 to 14 young
people sometime between March 1978 and March 1979,'' Bogale said.
``He is also charged with illegally detaining, or imprisoning, 12
to 13 teen-agers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogale said there was no mention in the prosecution's case of
place, weapons or a specific date, all of which the law required.
He said he objected to this, and to the form and content of the
charges, in July 1996, three years after Wolde was imprisoned, when
his case came to court and he pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a year for the special prosecutor to respond,'' Bogale
said. ``The court did not accept our objections.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, following a famine in the north and unrest in the
Eritrea region of Ethiopia, more than 100 young military officers,
known as the Dergue (pronounced DERG), deposed the 700-year-old
Christian monarchy headed by Emperor Selaisse and instituted a
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   By 1975, Lt. Col. Mengistu Haile Mariam had assumed power, and
for parts of the next 16 years the Dergue waged a conflict both to
preserve its own power and to defeat its primary political
opponent, the Ethiopian Peoples' Revolutionary Party, or EPRP.
</P>
<P>
   According to Amnesty International, tens of thousands were
killed during the civil war. Some say the figure could be as high
as 300,000. The years 1977 and 1978 were particularly brutal, and
designated by the term Red Terror.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dark time, many of those who lived through it said in
interviews. Civil war ravaged the country, and those living in
Addis Ababa often awoke to blood in the streets. Food was scarce
and schools were closed. Neighbors fought and spied on each other.
It is taken almost as fact here that there was not a family in the
capital that did not lose at least one member.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, Bogale contended, there was no nobility of
purpose. The line blurred, he said, between deliberate killing and
the horrors that arise out of an armed struggle for power.
</P>
<P>
   Girma Wakjira, chief special prosecutor for the government, said
there was no such gray area. ``Mamo Wolde executed one of these
people, which we will make clear in open court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wakjira's office, which he said was independent, was established
in 1992 to prosecute crimes committed by the Dergue. He said that
Wolde was vice chairman of his kebele and head of its revolutionary
guard. ``He led an armed unit that picked up counterrevolutionaries
when ordered to by the government, and executed them,'' Wakjira
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One night, Wakjira said, Wolde and his men took 12 young
students and teachers, members of the EPRP, from their prison
cells, divided them into small groups and shot them to death by
firing squad.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat in his office in the Supreme Court Building, with
stacks of paper and video cassettes on his desk, Wakjira, 49, was
resolute in his conviction that the government's mission was a
noble one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give my neck that Mamo Wolde's case is based upon nothing
but the facts,'' he said. ``For the first time in our history we
are holding our leaders accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   In a small contemporary office across town, Selome Taddesse, the
official government spokeswoman, drew on an American cigarette as
she voiced support for Wakjira's prosecution. Yes, she
acknowledged, Wolde had brought great pride to Ethiopia; but the
Red Terror left young people lying dead in the streets every
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dergue targeted the youth,'' she said. ``They came for me
at 5 a.m., when I was 13.'' She was eventually freed and later went
to the United States and attended Mount Holyoke College.
</P>
<P>
   Taddesse said the trials the Ethiopian government was holding
were the only ones of their kind in Africa. ``The IOC has hired a
lawyer for Wolde,'' she said. ``What about the mothers who lost
three or four children. Where is their lawyer? It has to do with
being rich and poor.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the civil war, many factions in Ethiopia were vying for
political power and independence, a situation that continues to
this day. But by 1991, the Dergue had been defeated, and emerging
out of the war was a coalition government headed by the Ethiopian
Peoples' Revolutionary Democratic Front.
</P>
<P>
   When that happened, Wolde, like thousands of others, was
imprisoned by the government. According the Wakjira, there are
currently about 5,400 charged with crimes that include torture and
murder; about 3,200 of them are in prison, and the rest are either
dead or in hiding. Those on trial have been denied bail because of
fears that they would flee.
</P>
<P>
   The government is in the early stages of trying these cases, and
there have been no convictions yet.
</P>
<P>
   Aberash Wolde Semiate, Wolde's 27-year-old wife, sat in the
living room of their small house in Addis Ababa. Like most
dwellings in Ethiopia, it is made of baked mud and straw, built
with money given to Wolde by Selaisse after winning his gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Against one wall was a low cabinet with a few trophies and a
small television. She and Wolde have two children, a boy, 6, and a
girl, 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldiers came and got him in September of 1992,'' she said.
``He was released three months later and given a paper saying that
he was free of Red Terror charges. Then they took the paper back,
saying he was free only because he had bronchitis and a liver
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolde was imprisoned a second time, released and then imprisoned
again in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The incident in question remains a tangle of conflicting
accounts. But everyone agrees that Wolde was an active member of
Kebele 11, a large concrete block compound on a dirt road a few
hundred yards from Wolde's house. The kebeles were set up by the
Dergue to serve as community centers, to help organize the
disparate sections of the city and to take responsibility for tax
collection and other administration.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was required to belong to one or face arrest. There are
currently about 328 kebeles in Addis Ababa, a sprawling city of 3.5
million at 8,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wolde denies being a member of the Revolutionary Guard,
the prosecution says he was. As a member of the military, Wolde
acknowledged in an interview, he was authorized to carry a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Semaite, who married Wolde in 1988 after his first wife died,
said her husband was very secretive; it was not until much later
that she questioned him about that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mamo told me that one night during the Dergue he was called to
the kebele,'' she said. ``A boy was there tied on the ground. Mamo
asked why the boy was there. He was told to be quiet or that he
would be taken away as a counterrevolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the kebele were there. One was asked to shoot
the young man. He did. After that, the chairman of the kebele told
Mamo to shoot him to be sure that he was dead. Mamo and the
chairman argued. Mamo shot, but did not shoot the boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The body was found the next day 200 yards away, at a busy
intersection, in front of the walled compound of Miruts Yifter,
Wolde's successor as a national running hero. Yifter, who won the
1980 Olympic gold medals in the 5,000 and 10,000 meters, now lives
in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Legusse Zelle, who was a guard at Kebele 11, said that he later
talked to Wolde about the incident. ``He told me that he
sympathized with the boy and that with tears in his eyes he shot
the ground,'' Zelle said. He pointed to a large walled dirt-brown
compound across the road, where the boy had lived. The family has
moved away.
</P>
<P>
   The Addis Ababa Central Prison, holding about 2,000 prisoners,
is at the end of a cracked, paved road, in the heart of the city,
with concrete guard towers and corrugated metal roofs. Male and
female guards, in drab olive sweaters and jackets representing
their military status, sit in the shade holding rifles.
</P>
<P>
   Down a dirt path and through another steel door is a section of
the prison called Alem Bekagne or ``No More the World'' _ meaning
they would not see the outside world again _ where Wolde and 400
other prisoners are kept.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
