<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCO-DIESEL-LADN     03-23 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCO-DIESEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCO TO ANNOUNCE CLEANER-BURNING DIESEL FUEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a development that could further scrub deadly
pollutants from Southern California's air, Atlantic Richfield Co.
is expected to announce it has created a cleaner-burning diesel
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary testing found that the new fuel, which Arco calls EC
(or emission control) diesel, reduces soot by 15 percent and
nitrogen oxide emissions by 5 percent without compromising fuel
economy.
</P>
<P>
   It was developed at ARCO's Engineering &AMP; Technology Center in
Anaheim during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Arco will recruit a fleet of trucks and buses to conduct an
extensive road test of the fuel, which will be produced in small
batches at the company's Carson refinery this spring. The test
should start sometime in the summer, said Roger Truitt, president
of Arco products, the company's marketing and refining unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope people will want to get in on this test. We are
confident that our demonstration program will show an immediate and
significant reduction in particulates and (nitrogen oxide)
emissions from diesel engines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fine particle pollution, the foul-smelling black clouds belched
from diesel powered trucks, buses and automobiles as well as
industrial sources, are a bigger health hazard than ozone, the main
component of smog. Last year, after a decade-long debate, a panel
of state scientists agreed that diesel exhaust poses a serious
cancer danger and urged state environmental regulators to initiate
steps to protect the public.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Campbell, a policy associate with the West Los
Angeles-based Coalition for Clean Air, said that the toxic quality
of diesel fuel is a concern. And he wants government agencies
involved in any test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course any improvement in fuel reformulation is a step
forward. We should really be concerned and start thinking about
moving away from petroleum-based fuels and more toward cleaner if
not zero-emission fuels like electricity and natural gas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The California Air Resources Board expects 738,900
diesel-powered vehicles on the road in California by the year 2000.
That's only 2 percent of all vehicles, but those diesel engines
will produce about 30 percent of the nitrogen oxides and 65 percent
of particulates fouling California's air, said board spokesman
Allan Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very interested in what Arco comes up with. Anything you
can do to reduce diesel emissions has a significant beneficial
effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the state agency and the South Coast Air Quality Management
District are expected to participate in Arco's test. In the late
1980s, Arco developed reformulated gasolines that are in widespread
use today and have led to some improvements in the air quality of
the state's biggest cities.
</P>
<P>
   EC Diesel will have a higher cetane rating, which is similar to
the octane rating of gasoline, and contain less sulfur and
aromatics than the diesel used today. Arco officials hope to start
production once the demonstration program is completed but that
decision will rest with the company's board.
</P>
<P>
   Truitt said that the fuel costs about 15 cents a gallon more to
make than regular diesel fuel, but production expenses would
probably drop when it is made in larger quantities. But the company
would also have to make an undetermined investment in its refinery
to make the fuel, something that could be a costly proposition. For
example, Arco spent about $500 million in upgrades to make the
reformulated gasoline in use today.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the amount of sulphur in diesel could make it possible
to fit buses, trucks and cars with new catalytic converters and
achieve an even bigger reduction in emissions, Arco officials said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Arco is working with Ford Motor Co. and catalytic
converter manufacturers to design new engines and converters that
will produce even lower emissions with the new fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important milestone, and Ford ... is glad to be
part of this program,'' said Neil Ressler, chief technical officer
and vice president of research and vehicle technology at Ford.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHIOPIAN-RUNNER-TRIA     03-23 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIAN-RUNNER-TRIAL-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ADDIS ABABA: are kept.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wolde arrived for an interview in a small room with yellow
plaster walls and a single light bulb. He was wearing a T-shirt and
a red-green-and-white warm-up suit. A prison administrator and two
guards holding rifles stood nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I am accused of torturing and killing
people and that I am innocent,'' he said. ``I am a victim of
hatred, but I don't know who is behind it.'' He was small and thin,
his forehead deeply lined and his eyes watery. He has bronchitis,
and throughout a 90-minute interview exhibited a deep cough.
</P>
<P>
   Wolde said he was elected by the kebele to serve the people and
denied being a member of the revolutionary guard. He said he did
not know anything about the boy and denied being there on the night
he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the guards around him, he appeared nervous and chose
his words carefully. ``There was a war going on between the Dergue
and the EPRP at that time,'' he said. ``I was not on either side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know really why I'm here,'' he added. ``There is
nothing I know about that incident.''
</P>
<P>
   During the interview, guards came and went, stopping to listen
if they heard him talking about his athletic career, smiling as he
told old tales. Wolde said he joined the army when he was 18 or 19.
Like most Ethiopians, he is not sure of his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a soldier,'' he said. ``I became a runner and was half
runner-half military, later full military. My job was to guard his
majesty and his palaces and to travel with him.'' He said that in
1978 and 1979 his job was to be an assistant coach of the national
track team and to attend sports events. Nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Wolde was born in the small village of Dirre Jille, 40 miles
south of Addis Ababa. His father, a peasant farmer, died when Wolde
was a boy, and so did his mother. He lived with his godfather and
went to school until the fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually joined the army and participated in sports matches
among the government ministries. He wanted to be like his hero,
Bikila, the winner of the Olympic marathon in 1960 and 1964, who
was also a member of Selaisse's palace guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abebe Bikila made me want to run,'' Wolde said. ``He was my
guiding light.'' Together, they would train at an air force base
near the town of Debre Zeit.
</P>
<P>
   Wolde's first Olympics were the 1956 Games in Melbourne,
Australia, where he ran the 1,500 and 800 meters and did not medal.
``We flew there in DC-3's,'' he said, shaking his head and
laughing. ``It took eight days to get there. We were practically
dead when we arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   He ran the 10,000 meters and the marathon in the 1964 Olympics
in Tokyo without winning a medal. By the mid-1960s, however,
African distance runners were distinguishing themselves on the
world's athletic stage, among them Bikila; Kenya's Kip Keino and
Wilson Kiprugut, and Tunisia's Mohamed Gammoudi.
</P>
<P>
   The showcase came in the high-altitude setting of Mexico City,
providing an advantage to East Africans who had grown up running on
their hilly native terrain. Wolde won the marathon and finished
second in the 10,000 meters. Keino won the 1,500, beating the
favored American, Jim Ryun. African runners swept the 5,000- and
10,000-meter races and finished 1-2 in the steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Wolde won the bronze medal in the marathon at
the Olympics in Munich, a race Frank Shorter won.
</P>
<P>
   To be an Olympic champion in Ethiopia is to have songs written
about you and parades given in your honor, as Wolde and other
athletes have had. After Mexico City, Wolde became a national hero,
like Bikila before him and Yifter afterward, and today Haile
Gebreselaisse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our names will ever die,'' Wolde said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolde shares a cell in Addis Ababa Central Prison with six
others. He is allowed to see his wife and children only on
weekends, when prisoners stand in small groups on one side of a
fence and families on the other, three feet apart. His wife brings
him extra food four other days, but cannot see him then. ``Every
week my family comes and I can shake my children's hands,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether the prosecutor will present witnesses
against Wolde when the trial resumes. The death penalty exists in
Ethiopia and can be applied in Wolde's case, but that is unlikely.
``I swear in the name of Jesus that I did not commit these
crimes,'' Wolde said. ``It is better to kill me than accuse me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogale was asked about Wolde's contention that he was not even
present when the killing took place. He shrugged. There were prison
guards all around him, Bogale pointed out. ``What do you expect him
to say?''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Wolde was present. Even his wife said Wolde
was called to the kebele that night. What Mamo Wolde did that night
is a question in the hands of a judicial system trying to pluck
answers from the complexities of 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bogale's first line of defense is legal: how can Wolde be
convicted if no one comes forward to say he saw it happen? The
lawyer seemed to indicate a fallback position. The circumstances
matter, he said. Politics should be taken into account. So should
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my information is concerned, Mamo was not
involved,'' Bogale said. ``Even if he is found to have committed
the crime, it was not voluntary. He might have been forced to do
it. That is the position we are taking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
