<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-SAFETY-680&AMP;ADD-NY     03-23 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-SAFETY-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDDER FLAW CITED IN BOEING 737 CRASHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Colo., Va.)  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Va. _ The Boeing 737 is vulnerable to extremely
rare rudder malfunctions that come and go and leave no trace, but
have caused two crashes and several other close calls, the staff of
the National Transportation Safety Board said Tuesday. The staff
said that the airlines, the Federal Aviation Administration, and
the Boeing Co. had not learned what they should have from those
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The staff presented those conclusions and other highlights of a
1,000-page report on the crash of USAir 427 near Pittsburgh in 1994
to four members of the board at a meeting that was supposed to
establish the probable cause of that accident, and present a new
evaluation of the crash of United Flight 585 in Colorado Springs,
Colo., in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The board intends to complete work on the report, and 10
recommendations, on Wednesday. One of those, a proposal to make the
rudder mechanism of the plane more ``reliably redundant,'' could
have enormous financial implications for Boeing, which has produced
more than 3,000 737s, and for the airlines that fly them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the airplane is trying to tell us something,'' said
Dr. Bernard Loeb, the board's chief aviation safety official. ``We
believe it has been for a while,'' he added, describing a history
of ``bumps, kicks, pulsations and so forth,'' in addition to the
two crashes and a malfunction in flight that threatened the pilots'
control of an Eastwind Airlines 737 near Richmond, Va., in 1996.
But he said, ``We do not know right now what is causing these.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff argued Tuesday that a hydraulic valve in the rudder
system can jam so that a pilot tapping a pedal to move the rudder
slightly in one direction, will actually swing the rudder all the
way in the opposite direction, where it sticks. The Eastwind pilots
said that they responded by stomping hard on the pedal to try to
move the rudder the other way. Investigators, who said they
believed the crews of the crashed planes behaved the same way, said
that such an action only maintains the jam.
</P>
<P>
   One investigator on Tuesday called the flaw ``insidious.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no physical evidence, the staff members acknowledged,
and they resorted to weaving together the recorded grunts of the
crew members in the last few moments of flight, together with other
scanty evidence preserved on relatively primitive flight-data
recorders.
</P>
<P>
   All 132 passengers and crew members were killed on the USAir
crash. The United crash killed all 25 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Malcolm Brenner, a specialist with the board on how people
interact with machinery and one another, said this ``rudder
reversal'' was the only scenario that tied all the factors together
plausibly, the pilots struggling with a rudder that moved on its
own, grunting with exertion.
</P>
<P>
   Board investigators brought in specialists from as far away as
Russia to analyze the grunts of the first officer in the USAir
plane, and then integrated the timing of those sounds with the
plane's movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we recognize this is circumstantial evidence, this may
be some of the most direct evidence we have,'' said Brenner, a
medical doctor and human-factors specialist.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of Tuesday's meeting, Boeing called in reporters to
present its view that there was no evidence for mechanical
malfunction. On Tuesday the company distributed a statement
stressing numerous improvements that have been made or are being
made, without abandoning its idea that all the problems could be a
result of pilot error.
</P>
<P>
   In pointed questions, though, James Hall, the chairman of the
safety board, established that of all the parties to the
investigation, including the airline, the valve manufacturer and
others, only Boeing held this view.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members said Boeing's argument would require a pilot to
hold the rudder pedal in the wrong position for more than 10
seconds, and for the other pilot to ignore this.
</P>
<P>
   The company emphasized that the Boeing 737 had carried 5 billion
passengers on 77 million flights, and that ``somewhere in the world
there is a 737 taking off every six seconds.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The four members of the board who are expected to vote on
Wednesday expressed disappointment that the FAA had responded
slowly or not at all to recommendations the board had already made.
</P>
<P>
   One recommendation was for better flight-data recorders. Hall
complained that investigators had to go to Europe to find 737s,
which are built in the United States, equipped with data recorders
that could capture the details of rudder malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   The United Airlines plane had five parameters, or categories of
data; the USAir plane had 11. Some planes built in the same era
have more than 100 parameters.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the FAA's response to recommendations that better
flight-data recorders on 737s be installed immediately, George
Black Jr., one of the board members, said, ``I fail to understand
how something so good can be so sluggishly responded to.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members blame a lack of data for the long investigation,
which has been going on for four and a half years and is the
longest in the board's history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
