RUNNER-1, 3-23 -- Mamo Wolde, the former Olympian champion, in an
Ethiopian Prison during a recent interview. Wolde, who won the gold
medal for wining the marathon at the 1968 Olympic games, now is on
trial on charges of genocide and illegal detention of prisoners
during the reign of terror that followed the overthrow of Emperor
Haile Selaisse in 1974. (Jere Van Dyk/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 23, 1999 -- CLOWN-FLOATER, 3-23 --
Kevina Joshua, 10, gets tips on applying her clown makeup from a
professional, Lisa Chapman, with the Ringling Bros. Barnum and
Bailey Circus on Tuesday at the Sacred Heart Elementary School.
After some instruction in clowning around, the children at the
school, who are in a program co-sponsored by the Police Athletic
League, will star in a special session of the circus in early
April. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PLANT CITY, Fla. -- March 23, 1999 --
STRAWBERRY-APPRECIATION, 3-23 -- Strawberries are harvested
recently. Almost all the strawberries consumed in the eastern half
of the country during the winter come from farms within a 50-mile
radius of Plant City, a little Florida town just east of the urban
sprawl of Tampa. This is the Winter Strawberry Capital of the
World, the local chamber of commerce says, and it seems never to
have occurred to anyone to challenge the claim. (Denis Poroy/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. -- March 23, 1999 --
BBN-METS-WILSON-FLOATER, 3-23 -- Mets pitcher Paul Wilson at a news
conference on Tuesday. A magnetic resonance imaging test in New
York on Monday showed that Wilson has a torn ligament in his right
elbow. The injury will probably result in Wilson undergoing his
second major pitching arm surgery in 2 1/2 years. (Gary I.
Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PHILADELPHIA -- March 21, 1999 -- PA-HDTV-TOWER, 3-21 --
From right, David O'Neil, Kristine Soffa and Susan Haddon walk on a
farm last week where the installation of a high-definition
transmission tower is planned. For almost a year, local residents
and a tower company have been engaged in a spirited fight over the
company's plans to erect a 1,289-foot steel tower to send out the
signals that will be needed for the next generation of television
sets. A tower of that size would rank as one of the tallest
structures in the United States. (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SPRINGFIELD, Va. -- March 23, 1999 -- AIR-SAFETY, 3-23
-- Gregory Phillips, left, makes a presentation on Tuesday to the
National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) during a briefing on
the cause of the crash of USAir flight 427. Dr. Vernon Ellingstad
is at right. The staff of the NTSB tried to make a case that two
crashes of Boeing 737 and a serious incident on a third are a
result of an ``insidious'' mechanical failure that has not yet been
adequately addressed. (Scott Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NY10) WASHINGTON -- March 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP, 3-23 --
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright leaves a meeting with Senate
Democrats on Tuesday followed by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., left,
where they discussed the situation in Kosovo. Richard Holbrooke,
Clinton's special envoy who met in Belgrade with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic in a last ditch effort to avoid NATO air
strikes, declared his meeting a failure. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK-- March 23, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-PROTEST, 3-23 --
Actors and activists Ossie Davis, left, and his wife Ruby Dee,
foreground center, wait to be arrested while protesting outside New
York City police headquarters on Tuesday. To date, more than 300
people have been arrested in protests which organizers said will be
held until the officers who killed Amadou Diallo, an unarmed West
African immigrant, are arrested. (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HOUSTON -- March 23, 1999 -- FOOD-FAJITAS-HNS, 3-23 -- A
Fajita platter at Tortugas Coastal Cantina in Houston. Fajitas have
earned their stripes as a favorite Tex-Mex food - as common as
tacos and enchiladas. (Betty Tichich/Houston Chronicle Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- March 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ASSESS-3, 3-23 --
Secretary of Defense William Cohen leaves a meeting with Senate
Democrats where they discussed the situation in Kosovo on Tuesday.
Richard Holbrooke, who met with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic on Tuesday in a last ditch effort to avoid NATO air
strikes, declared his meeting a failure. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- March 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ASSESS-2, 3-23 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, center, speaks to reporters
about the situation in Kosovo while standing in the doorway of his
Capitol Hill office on Tuesday. After President Clinton held a
briefing for the senior leadership of the House and Senate on the
latest developments in Kosovo, Congress shelved a move to keep
American troops away from Yugoslavia. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK-- March 23, 1999 -- ARTIST-INSPIRATION, 3-23 --
Jim Hodges poses in front of his latest work comprised of
artificial flowers and thread in his studio in the Williamsburg
section of Brooklyn. Extra napkins dispensed by a local coffee
vendor gave birth to ``Diary of Flowers,'' an array of 565 crumpled
napkins that Hodges pinned to a gallery wall in early 1994. The
work was the centerpiece of his first solo exhibition. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- March 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ASSESS, 3-23 --
President Clinton, while addressing members of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees in Washington,
used the opportunity to outline the current situation in Kosovo on
Tuesday. A mirror at right reflects House Minority Whip David
Bonior taking notes. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- March 23, 1999 -- MIDEAST-U.S., 3-23 --
President Clinton shakes hands with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat as National Security Advisor Sandy Berger, second from
right, and Dennis Ross, the U.S. special envoy to the Middle East,
look on before their meeting at the White House on Tuesday. Arafat
met with Clinton and his aides to discuss the Middle East peace
process. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 23, 1999 -- SCARY-STAIRS-2, 3-23 -- A
patron negotiates the stairs at Celadon, a restaurant which also
provides a safe, secure elevator for its customers. Just a few
years ago, upstairs rooms at restaurants were used only for
banquets and the occasional over flow crowd. But the restaurant
boom, along with rising rents for street-level space, has led a
growing number of restaurateurs to expand upward. (Norman Y.
