<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1667 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1STLD-     03-23 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AUTHORIZES AIRSTRIKES AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(CORRECTS length of `four-year' war in Bosnia in 7th graf; adds
sentence in 9th graf with results of Senate vote.) (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-U.S., RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The North Atlantic Treaty Organization authorized
airstrikes against Yugoslavia on Tuesday as President Clinton
declared that force was necessary to halt the aggression of the
Serbs against ethnic Albanians in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign, using primarily American aircraft and cruise
missiles, was poised to begin over southern Serbia and targets in
Kosovo under the cover of night Wednesday, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It would come almost a year after the conflict in Kosovo began
and more than six months after NATO, backed by the Clinton
administration, first threatened the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   In his first full explanation of why the administration had
decided NATO should strike, Clinton said in a speech to a union
group here on Tuesday: ``If President Milosevic is not willing to
make peace, we are willing to limit his ability to make war on the
Kosovars.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing concerns in the Pentagon about the possible loss of
pilots as they deal with the air defense systems of the Yugoslav
Army, Clinton said: ``I want to level with you. This is like any
other military action. There are risks in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said that not acting against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic would ``discredit'' NATO by showing that ``we
didn't keep our word.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he was acting after lessons learned from
the four-year war in Bosnia. ``We learned that if you don't stand
up to brutality and the killing of innocent people, you invite the
people who do it to do more of it,'' he said. ``We learned that
firmness can save lives, and stop armies.''
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO military plans accelerated, Milosevic's forces in
Kosovo continued to set fire to houses, sending ethnic Albanians
fleeing into the countryside. Serbian artillery targeted villages
in the central Drenica region, the traditional heartland of the
guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 senators and congressmen met with Clinton at the
White House Tuesday morning, and after hearing his arguments for
intervention, rallied around him by canceling a planned Senate
debate on Kosovo. The Senate voted tonight 58 to 41 in support of a
one-sentence resolution authorizing President Clinton to launch
bombing and missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a debate for another time. We are at a critical
hour,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the near certainty of air strikes, the Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov turned his aircraft around over the
Atlantic Ocean as it was heading for Washington and postponed a
planned three-day visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, adamantly against NATO air strikes, had made clear that
Primakov would take it as a personal slap in the face if Serbia, a
traditional if frayed ally of Russia, was attacked during
Primakov's visit.
</P>
<P>
   The authorization of the airstrikes by NATO Secretary General
Javier Solana occurred at NATO headquarters in Brussels Tuesday
night after Clinton's envoy, Richard Holbrooke, failed to persuade
Milosevic to agree to a ceasefire in Kosovo that would pave the way
for talks on a peace settlement already agreed to by the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who has negotiated many times in the past with
Milosevic, talked with the Yugoslav leader for about six hours in
Belgrade. Lt. Gen. Edward Anderson, accompanying Holbrooke, spelled
out to Milosevic that NATO was planning a heavy air campaign that
would crush his forces in and around Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But while Holbrooke was trying to induce Milosevic toward the
path of peace, the Serbian parliament, apparently under orders from
the authoritarian leader, railed on Tuesday against foreign forces
in Kosovo. ``This was the ultimate two-finger salute by Milosevic
to his friend Holbrooke,'' a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   After the collapse of what administration officials called a
``last chance'' for Milosevic, a subdued Holbrooke flew to NATO
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, where he briefed Solana.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Solana gave the go ahead to NATO's Supreme Commander
Gen. Wesley Clark to go ahead with an air campaign. The Secretary
General called Holbrooke a ``great diplomat'' but said that NATO
was taking over.
</P>
<P>
   The planned air attacks would come after a series of diplomatic
efforts by the Clinton administration in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Last October, after the massacre of more than 20 ethnic Albanian
civilians by Serb forces, Holbrooke persuaded Milosevic to agree to
a ceasefire in Kosovo, accept more than 1,000 unarmed monitors and
reduce the number of troops. But within two months Milosevic
violated the agreement by increasing the number of troops and
unleashing them in attacks against civilians and ethnic Albanian
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   After another massacre in January at Rajak, Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright orchestrated a diplomatic effort that
culminated in peace talks in France. But while the ethnic
Albanians, including the Kosovo Liberation Army, signed on to an
agreement that gave Kosovo autonomy rather than independence,
Milosevic treated the talks with contempt.
</P>
<P>
   When Holbrooke presented the settlement to Milosevic on Monday
and argued that it suited the Yugoslav leader because it called for
the disarming of the guerrillas, Milosevic was equally dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   As the last minute diplomatic efforts gave way to military
action, Milosevic's forces in Kosovo showed no sign in letting up
in their effort to wipe out the guerrillas of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian offensive, which intensified Saturday as
international monitors left, continued on Tuesday , humanitarian
officials still in Kosovo said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees said Tuesday
that 25,000 ethnic Albanians had been forced to flee their homes
since last Friday and that another 85,000 had become refugees since
the end of peace talks in Rambouillet, France, last month. In all,
there were about 460,000 ethnic Albanian refugees, the United
Nations agency said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since NATO has threatened force against
Milosevic, the State Department said it was suspending all
activities at the American embassy in Belgrade and the remaining
core staff, including the charge d'affaires, Richard Miles, were
leaving Wednesday morning. Other Western embassies, concerned about
being targets of Serb anger, said they were also closing.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO geared up for the final showdown Wednesday night,
administration and NATO officials said they saw only a remote
chance that Milosevic would back down. ``For Milosevic to change
his mind _ I'd say that's very remote,'' said a NATO official.
</P>
<P>
   Both NATO and Pentagon planners said that the air campaign would
target Yugoslav military bases, lines of communication, fuel
supplies and ammunition dumps. The idea was to crimp the ability of
the Serbian police units and Yugoslav soldiers to wage war in
Kosovo where they have been burning homes and hitting at KLA
positions.
</P>
<P>
   After a briefing by the Pentagon on Tuesday, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., said: `Unfortunately it's going to be a
devastating series of attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing how the air attack would unfold, a NATO official said
that once the air defense systems had been taken out, and supply
dumps and radar attacked, mobile missiles would be tracked down.
``If they concentrate in one place, we smash them, if they move, we
find them,'' said the official. In this way, Milosevic's ground
force would be ``left without protection,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The risks to everyone _ civilians on the ground and the pilots
in the air _ were much higher than in the desert warfare that the
Pentagon has waged against Iraq, planners said.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking the sophisticated air defense systems of the Yugoslav
Army was also less inviting in another respect. ``There won't be
the impressive hits of a desert war and there may not only be
misses but also collateral damage,'' a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   There was also some nervousness about whether air power would be
enough to persuade Milosevic to give up. ``What do we do then?''
asked a Pentagon official, repeating a concern expressed last week
at a congressional hearing by Gen. Charles Krulak, commandant of
the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats said Tuesday there was mounting concern about
the need for prolonged attacks against Milosevic's forces. This
could provoke a slaughter in Kosovo by Serbs against ethnic
Albanians and in turn retaliation by ethnic Albanians against
Srbs, said a European diplomat who was about to depart Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If pictures emerge from Kosovo of a slaughter, then there will
be a lot of pressure for the intervention of ground troops,'' the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials said there were no plans for intervening with
the NATO soldiers who have been stationed in Macedonia in
preparation for entry to Kosovo as a peacekeeping force. ``Nobody
is putting together an invasion force, it has never been part of
the discussion,'' said an administration official.
</P>
<P>
   For some diplomats and officials at NATO headquarters in
Brussels, where Clark has made no secret of his judgment that an
air campaign was justified against Milosevic long ago, the mood
this evening was almost jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's accelerating and exhilarating,'' said one official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
