<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RACISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE ON BIAS MEASURE TESTS BIPARTISAN CIVILITY IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla., Miss., Ga., Okla., Mich.)  (mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``The people watching this debate must be
scratching their heads,'' Rep. Michael Forbes, R-N.Y., said as he
took his turn on the House floor Tuesday to argue over whether
Congress should pass a resolution that condemned all bigotry and
racist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Those people undoubtedly scratched over the outcome: The
resolution failed, its fate sealed by the opposition of most
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But what looked, from a distance, like an excursion into some
political ``Twilight Zone'' was an exquisite example of partisan
feuding, political maneuvering and the short shelf life of
Hershey's Kisses. On the House floor Tuesday, the fuzzy bromides
articulated by members of Congress at a bipartisan civility retreat
in Hershey, Pa., over the weekend had already begun to look stale.
</P>
<P>
   It is necessary to rewind for a bit. Last month, Rep. Robert
Wexler, D-Fla., introduced a bill that called on Congress to
condemn a white supremacist group. The rub was the specific group
he selected: the Council of Conservative Citizens, before which
both Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, and Rep. Bob
Barr, R-Ga., had given speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, suspicious that Wexler and other Democrats were
simply trying to embarrass them, decided on a different tack.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., who also happens to be the only black
Republican in the House, introduced his own anti-bigotry bill,
calling on Congress to condemn any and all racist groups but not
mentioning the council by name. Republicans scheduled his
resolution for debate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting the measure to his colleagues Tuesday afternoon,
Watts made special note that it did not ``single out for
condemnation any one organization or individual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be so particular,'' Watts said, ``would be to commit a
crime of omission by giving a pass to other groups that espouse
prejudice, in effect saying that their bigotry is not so offensive
as to be worthy of our condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Both during the 40-minute debate on the floor and afterward,
Democrats and a few Republicans said that a resolution so broad was
a statement of the obvious: Of course Congress condemned racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This resolution is a ruse,'' said Rep. John Conyers Jr.,
D-Mich., who is the senior black House member, adding that it was
``characteristic of Republicans who want to get civil rights on the
cheap and show the country they're really not Neanderthals.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had reasoned that Democrats would be forced in the
end to vote for Watts' resolution, which was so uncontroversial on
its face. But enough Democrats voted against it that it did not
muster the two-thirds majority it needed.
</P>
<P>
   In the final tally, 254 members _ 218 Republicans and 36
Democrats _ voted for the resolution, while 152 members, mostly
Democrats, voted against it and 24 voted present. Four members did
not show up.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans proclaimed that Democrats looked petty. ``It's an
unfortunate political act,'' said Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., of
their votes. ``I truly find it inexplicable.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that Republicans were trying to make Democrats
look bad, and would fail miserably. ``Most Democrats have such an
excellent record on civil rights that they do not need to worry
about being labeled anything but proponents,'' Wexler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
