<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH UNDER ATTACK FOR STANCE ON GAY, HATE CRIMES ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's stance on sensitive
social issues has touched national nerves as gay leaders and their
allies Tuesday criticized the probable presidential candidate's
opposition to including homosexuals in a state hate crime law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently being a compassionate conservative does not include
protecting the victims of hate crime or their families,'' said
Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the Human Rights Campaign, a
national gay rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   Birch was joined in her criticism by the nephew of James Byrd
Jr., the black man from Jasper, Texas, who was violently dragged to
his death, and the mother of Matthew Shepard, a young gay man who
was tortured and left to die on a fence post in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   John William ``Bill'' King was convicted of capital murder in
the Byrd case and was sentenced to death. Two other defendants are
awaiting trial. The Shepard trial is scheduled to begin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gay leaders not only were angered by Bush's stand on hate crimes
but also by his statement this week that he opposes gay adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   Their harsh criticism underscores the difficulty facing Bush as
he tries to step through the quagmire of tricky social issues in
his preparation for a White House bid. He cannot win Republican
primaries without support from faith-based conservatives, but to
compete in a general election, he must win the support of moderates
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has recently been under attack from advocates on
both sides of the abortion issue for saying he did not believe the
nation was ready to overturn the Supreme Court decision legalizing
the procedure. Bush said he believed, however, that abortion was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Campaign is pressing Congress to approve
federal hate crimes legislation. But the participants quickly
singled out Bush for criticism because of his recent remarks
regarding a hate crimes bill pending in the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush said he opposed including sexual orientation in
a measure to clarify a 1993 state hate crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the gay issue, Bush has been ambivalent about the
measure called the James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Act, which would also
increase criminal penalties for hate crimes, provide specialized
training for police officers and provide civil remedies for
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said all crime is hate crime,'' he said. ``People
when they commit a crime have hate in their heart. And it's hard to
distinguish between one degree of hate and another.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding another bill before Texas lawmakers that would bar
gays from adopting children in the custody of the state, Bush said,
``I'm against gay adoptions. I believe children ought to be adopted
in families with a woman and a man who are married.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lack of support for hate crime legislation came under
criticism recently by Democratic presidential candidate Bill
Bradley who vowed to make it a campaign issue if he ends up facing
Bush in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday sympathetic relatives of hate crime victims weighed
in on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Shepard, the mother of Matthew Shepard, said that Bush
should reconsider his opposition to including sexual orientation in
hate crimes measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stand is indefensible,'' said Shepard, who tearfully spoke
of her son's killing last fall by two suspects who professed their
hatred of gays.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's nephew, Daryl Verrett, said he was ``disappointed'' at
Bush's position and said that any hate crimes bill approved by the
state Legislature should include sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said that the governor has not
decided whether he would sign the hate crime legislation despite
his comments about the sexual orientation provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush believes in tough anti-crime laws and will
carefully consider legislation proposing to rewrite the Texas hate
crimes law,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   On the bill banning gay adoptions Edwards said, ``Texas law
already forbids gay couples from adopting children. Governor Bush
is opposed to gay adoptions. He is not taking a position on
legislation that is being rewritten by committees every day. He
will take a position on legislation when it reaches his desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics said they were not surprised at Bush's stands on gay
issues given his political ambitions and the need for a Republican
presidential candidate to placate the religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not being a statesman. He is being a candidate,'' said
Texas state Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, the sponsor of the
hate crimes measure.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson predicted Bush would not veto the hate crimes measure,
with the sexual orientation provision, if it lands on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he has the guts to veto it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Hardy Garcia of the Lesbian Gay Rights Lobby of Texas said
that Bush's recent remarks on gay issues belie the moderate image
he has cultivated so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks that because he doesn't call names and hasn't
been ranting and raving that he is a moderate,'' she said. But
Garcia said Bush's stand on gay issues amounts to ``a kinder and
gentler form of bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
