<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-CENTERS-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SPRING, AND NEW SCIENCE CENTERS ARE ABLOOM ON CAMPUSES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Mass., N.J., N.Y., Ohio)  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last great science building boom on American campuses came
in the late 1950s and early '60s, when the nation was desperate to
catch up with the Soviet Union in the race into space. (Remember
Sputnik?)
</P>
<P>
   Today, new science centers are once again sprouting like
high-tech crocuses at colleges and universities from Barnard to
Caltech.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne L. Narum, an education consultant in Washington who is an
expert on undergraduate science teaching, estimates that $2 billion
to $3 billion is being spent this year on new construction,
renovation or planning for science centers at 1,000 campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University plans to pump as much as $200 million over
the next five years into new science programs, including the
construction of a center for the study of genetics. Haverford,
Hofstra, Holy Cross, Kenyon, Macalester, Middlebury, Princeton,
Ursinus, Williams and Wooster are among the institutions large and
small that have made commitments to multimillion-dollar science
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable is the $6 million Center for
Environmental Studies scheduled to open next fall at Oberlin
College in Ohio: it will function like a tree. Constructed of
special low-maintenance materials, the building makes use of
high-tech equipment to absorb, store and conserve energy.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the building boom are many, but the most
straightforward is that old science buildings were becoming
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that if you're going to strengthen the learning
environment, you can't put new projects into old wine skins,'' Ms.
Narum said. ``Many of the post-Sputnik buildings were, to put it
mildly, inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   Some buildings were crumbling or unsafe, she said, and many
lacked enough space for computers. But beyond their physical
limitations, the old buildings are proving unfit for the way
science is taught today.
</P>
<P>
   Educators and administrators say science teaching has undergone
a revolution in the four decades since Sputnik. The line between
disciplines has blurred: much research involves not simply physics,
chemistry or biology, but collaboration among the three. Even
undergraduates are expected to do their own research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Undergraduate students are now conducting experiments and
doing things close to the cutting edge that in the past could be
done only by practicing scientists _ like measuring levels of
pesticides found on the fruit that they buy in the local grocery
store,'' said Jim Swartz, dean of the college at Grinnell College
in Iowa, which recently opened a $15.5 million renovated science
center.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Narum says the old buildings get in the way of such
teaching. ``The whole design concept was outmoded,'' she said.
``Chairs were screwed to the floor so that collaboration and
teamwork the way scientists do science was impossible, and you
couldn't solve that problem by putting wheels on the chairs because
the floors were tightly tiered. It became clear that to make a
genuine difference in the way science was being learned, there
would have to be some major capital expenditures.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Carla Ramas, 20, a senior who is majoring in biopsychology at
Barnard College in Manhattan, which has just opened an $8.8 million
science building, says the new emphasis on science at Barnard is
exciting because it draws attention to the frontiers of science.
``My sense is that with progress in cloning, genome mapping and
everything else,'' she said, ``we're at the breakthrough point of
something important.''
</P>
<P>
   The money for these projects is raised in a variety of ways.
State legislators in Connecticut have appropriated large sums for
science centers. The University of Connecticut's newly opened $56
million chemistry building contains 88 research laboratories
customized for specialties like biochemistry and organic chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Private institutions look to foundations, alumni and wealthy
individuals. The University of Redlands near Palm Springs, Calif.,
for example, has just completed an $18.5 million drive to finance
the first two of four buildings in a new science complex that will
begin to open in the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Still others, like Hofstra University on Long Island, have gone
deeply into debt to finance new science centers. The $8.2 million
cost of Hofstra's science building, due to open in the late spring,
was part of a $55 million bond issued last July, bringing the
university's total debt to $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the high cost of these new structures, some critics
ask how much actual science will be taught in them, as opposed to
gaudy multimedia displays intended to impress alumni, donors and
prospective students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If flashy presentations in these centers allow the dumbing
down of scientific content, then students may not receive the
benefits promised,'' said Robert Pollack, a professor of biological
sciences at Columbia University and former dean of Columbia
College.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Narum, the science teaching consultant, expects the boom
to continue. In 1989, she founded Project Kaleidoscope, a network
of colleges and universities interested in improving undergraduate
science teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The group uses foundation money to organize meetings and
workshops for colleges and universities eager to pick up tips on
how to develop improved spaces for science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I bump into at these workshops and conferences,''
Ms. Narum said, ``are taking very seriously the work of shaping the
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
