<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1679 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     03-23 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE M IN MSU ISN'T FOR MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silly me. I thought Michigan State won the Big Ten title and
advanced to its first Final Four in two decades because of a superb
point guard, an exquisite bench, toughness, togetherness and solid
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last 48 hours, I've learned the real reason for
Michigan State's success: Magic Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what he wants us to believe.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to root for your alma mater, to attend games and
support the players. It's quite another to thrust yourself into the
spotlight, box out those who deserve it and dominate the
proceedings as if it were 1979 and your Spartans were facing Larry
Bird and Indiana State.
</P>
<P>
   In his craving for attention, Johnson has stolen the moment from
Michigan State guard Mateen Cleaves, coach Tom Izzo and the gang.
Johnson now refers to himself as the Spartans' ``big brother.'' He
gave pep talks to Jason Klein and A.J. Granger before the Kentucky
game. Everywhere the Spartans go, Johnson is sure to follow. In
fact, he has watched practice and proffered advice throughout the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but I don't remember him lending a hand when Michigan
State won 16 games a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although Magic has done his best to overshadow them, some great
stories are emerging from East Lansing. Izzo, the fourth-year
coach, is best friends with San Francisco 49ers coach Steve
Mariucci. Cleaves has overcome a back injury, lost weight and
ascended to the nation's point guard pantheon. And don't forget the
Flintstones _ the quartet of players from Flint, Mich., who form
the Spartans' soul _ Cleaves, shooting guard Charlie Bell, power
forward Antonio Smith and super sub Morris Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Good team, great material, a showdown with Duke looming. Too bad
it all gets lost in this Magic moment.
</P>
<P>
   __ On guard: Duke, Michigan State, Connecticut and Ohio State
have nothing in common except the most important element in
tournament survival: great guards.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's Scoonie Penn is the best point guard around. He
combined with shooting guard Michael Redd to produce 42 points, 14
rebounds and 13 assists against St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping Khalid El-Amin and Richard Hamilton is the key to
stopping Connecticut. Duke's William Avery and Trajan Langdon are,
well, William Avery and Trajan Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves isn't in Avery's class as a scorer, but he's a powerful
ballhandler and effective penetrator _ which means he has the
skills to challenge Duke's pressure defense. If he keeps the
turnovers low, the Spartans have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Asked last weekend if his Huskies could beat
any of the seven teams remaining, Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun
said: ``I'm convinced six. Seven, I don't know. Can (Duke) be
beaten? Yeah, but it's going to take an A-plus game.''. . .
</P>
<P>
   If Washington coach Bob Bender takes the Vanderbilt job as
expected, the Huskies will pursue former assistant Ritchie McKay,
currently at Colorado State. If that unravels, Gonzaga's Dan Monson
and Pepperdine's Lorenzo Romar might vault to the top of the list.
(Romar played at Washington.) Athletic director Barbara Hedges
can't go wrong either way. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Like Arizona last year, St. John's fell victim to the Maryland
factor. Both teams defeated the Terps in the Sweet 16, figured
they'd survived their toughest challenge and were poorly prepared
for the Elite Eight: Arizona lost to Utah, St. John's to Ohio
State. . . .
</P>
<P>
   NCAA executive director Cedric Dempsey says $4.5 billion is
illegally wagered on the NCAA Tournament. I lost $10 of it in the
office pool. North Carolina in the Final Four? What was I thinking?
. . .
</P>
<P>
   As the coach at Tulsa, Georgia and Kentucky, Tubby Smith has
compiled a 15-4 record in NCAA Tournament play. After the loss to
Michigan State, some Wildcats fans would have you believe he's no
better than Billy Tubbs. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Each tournament host _ for the West Regional, it was Arizona
State _ receives an operations manual from the NCAA that's two
inches thick. It includes rules for number of cheerleaders, band
members, mascots, schedules for the media, concession stand and
parameters for advertising placards. Aren't there more important
matters for the NCAA to address than press hot dogs? . . .
</P>
<P>
   Preparation is coach Jim O'Brien getting Ohio State ready for
St. John's zone defense _ the same defense that stifled Indiana.
Execution is shooting 54.7 percent against it. . . .
</P>
<P>
   What does it say about New Mexico now that Lobos coach Dave
Bliss has taken the Baylor job? . . .
</P>
<P>
   CBS' Al McGuire would be a much better analyst if he never
spoke. McGuire said Sunday that Duke's Chris Burgess might leave
for a Mormon mission next year. Well, Burgess is leaving, all
right: it's called a transfer. Don't be surprised if he surfaces at
UCLA. . . .
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering why Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski has lost his
courtside exuberance, he's scheduled for hip-replacement surgery in
April.
</P>
<P>
   __ And finally: Gonzaga, which returns three starters and its
best reserves, visits UCLA on Dec. 11. The Bruins better start
preparing for that motion offense this week.
</P>
<P>
   __ And finally II: Now that a federal judge has struck down the
use of minimum SAT scores to determine initial eligibility, it's
only a matter of time until a nonathlete challenges their use in
university-wide admissions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
