<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: VANISHING POCKET TIMETABLES; CRUISE NEWS; OFFICE
IN THE SKY; FARE OPPORTUNITIES; WARNING ON TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Also moved in ``t'' category) 
(lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The airline pocket timetable is not yet a relic, but the handy
guide is becoming harder to come by. American Airlines no longer
publishes one. American, a unit of AMR, said the information _
flight numbers, departure and arrival times, stops and connections
_ was widely available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The other big airlines do not plan to follow American's lead,
though some are making changes. United Airlines, which spends about
$2 million printing some 200,000 copies of each of its six editions
yearly, has eliminated its timetables for individual cities. ``We
had about 200 cities,'' said Joe Hopkins, the spokesman for United,
a unit of UAL, ``so by eliminating them we saved quite a bit of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   U S Airways also eliminated city timetables some time ago but
has no immediate plans to do away with the pocket timetables. Delta
Air Lines also intends to keep its pocket edition, which it
publishes quarterly in printings of about 800,000. But because it
stopped listing connecting flights last September, the pocket guide
has been greatly slimmed down. And the number of individual city
timetables, which do list connecting flights, has also been trimmed
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, when Continental Airlines was operating under
bankruptcy protection, it eliminated its printed timetable except
for its most frequent fliers, but as the airline returned to
solvency, it reinstated it for everyone. These days its timetable
is compact and condensed.
</P>
<P>
   American Express and OAG Worldwide publish monthly pocket
guides, which list the flights of most airlines and are purchased
mostly by business travelers. Both companies also deliver the data
electronically, and OAG announced Tuesday that its database of
600,000 worldwide flights was available through Palm Pilot, the
electronic hand-held personal organizer, and would soon be
available on the Palm VII.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise News
</P>
<P>
   Guess whom Silversea Cruises has added to its roster of year-end
speakers, along with Buzz Aldrin, the former Apollo XI astronaut,
and Winston S. Churchill, the grandson of the famed British prime
minister? None other than Andrew Morton, the biographer of both
Diana, princess of Wales, and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Cruises, meanwhile, has equipped its fleet of 10 ships
with more than 65 portable defibrillators for treating heart
attacks at sea. The portable units are in addition to the larger
defibrillators in each of the ships' medical centers.
</P>
<P>
   Office in the Sky
</P>
<P>
   When All Nippon Airways begins daily service between Tokyo and
Chicago in mid-April, its 747-400s will have some unusual features.
These include a self-service bar and work stations in first and
business class, complete with desks, high-back swivel chairs with
seat belts, telephones, a fax machine and electrical outlets. First
class will also have what the Japanese airline believes will be the
first on-board rice cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Fare Opportunities
</P>
<P>
   Now that last weekend's settlement between America West and its
flight attendants appears to have averted a strike, look for travel
bargains as the airline tries to lure back passengers. That is the
usual carrot that airlines dangle before disaffected or
inconvenienced passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines, for example, which is still being hurt by a
two-week pilots' strike in September, has just announced its latest
sale. For travel through Sept. 10, adults who fly in midweek and
stay over a Saturday can each take along two children aged 2 to 17
for a reduced rate. As a result, a round-trip flight between New
York and Seattle is $434, and a child's round-trip fare is $198.
Tickets must be bought by April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Warning on Turkey
</P>
<P>
   Anyone planning to travel to Turkey should be aware that Kurdish
guerrillas have warned foreigners to stay away, adding that they
will make targets of resorts and other tourist destinations. The
threats, published by a a pro-Kurdish news agency in Germany,
followed a recent series of bombings and arsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
