<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN SHIFT, NATO PLANS ATTACK ON MANY SERBIAN TARGETS,
OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: subs for accuracy in lede, `European' and American
officials) (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV, KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS,
KOSOVO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-U.S.,
RUSSIA-ARMS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic _ a map of military positions in and around
Kosovo _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Initial NATO bombings of Yugoslavia will be
broader and more punishing, focusing on 60 different targets, than
the short, sharp strike that NATO military planners had originally
envisioned, European and American officials said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Some NATO diplomats said that Supreme Allied Commander Gen.
Wesley Clark would have authority to strike any targets he chose in
the first round, instead of having to go step by step or ask for
permission to hit tank or troop concentrations carrying out attacks
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, officials speaking on the condition of anonymity
said air and missile strikes would target more than just those army
and police units waging war against the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo
province, but would attack the Yugoslav military more generally,
striking at targets inside Serbia vital to supporting the
repression. Those include military bases, lines of communication,
fuel supplies and ammunition dumps.
</P>
<P>
   French and American officials also said the second phase of the
attack would follow the first without a break.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that like the raids on Iraq in December,
the strikes would almost certainly occur at night, taking advantage
of American technological superiority. That would leave ``pauses''
during daylight hours during which Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, could agree to accept a peace agreement. ``At any time
he could say `enough,''' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana ordered the airstrikes
Tuesday night, and officials said it would take until Wednesday to
program cruise missile to strike the 60 targets.
</P>
<P>
   Officials still hope that a bombing will persuade Milosevic to
end his repression in Kosovo, but the Pentagon has not declared it
as a goal, largely because officials concede that air power alone
might not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we do then?'' one Pentagon official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A cruise-missile strike _ from ships and submarines as well as
from B-52s based in Britain _ could last a day or two, followed by
an air campaign involving American and NATO jets that could last
two to four days or more, according to officials who have been
briefed on the planning.
</P>
<P>
   One official said the plan is guided more by the targets NATO
hopes to destroy than by a strict timetable. A number of factors,
including weather and the success of Yugoslavia's defense could
affect the duration. ``I don't have a clear idea how long it will
take,'' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, Gen. Henry Shelton,
briefed senators on the scope of the planned strikes on Tuesday,
describing a devastating barrage. ``Unfortunately it's going to be
a devastating series of attacks,'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.,
said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav armed forces and paramilitary police units that
NATO warplanes plan to attack are regarded as tough, well-equipped,
and far more powerful than the Bosnian Serb forces that allied
warplanes bombed four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 90,000 soldiers of the Yugoslav National Army are equipped
with thousands of tanks, multiple rocket launchers, heavy artillery
pieces and surface-to-surface missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Before allied warplanes would attack any of these forces, allied
officers said, NATO commanders would try first to destroy as much
as possible of Serbia's sophisticated integrated air defense
system, which gives it considerable ability to shoot down planes.
</P>
<P>
   This, probably the single most formidable component of the
Serbian defenses, consists of hundreds of Soviet-era surface-to-air
missiles and 2,000 anti-aircraft artillery batteries linked to
radar and guidance systems by a fortified command and control
network. Its main command and control site is at Kopanik in
central-southwest Serbia, according to Jane's Information Group, a
leading British publisher on defense information.
</P>
<P>
   After strikes on the air defense systems, the allies would
concentrate on striking tanks, armored personnel carriers and other
heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 400 allied aircraft from the United States, Britain,
France, Germany, and 10 other countries stand ready to attack from
bases in Italy and England and aircraft carriers in the Adriatic
and Mediterranean Seas. Of those about 200 are American.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Pentagon quietly ordered 15 jets based in Turkey
to patrol the northern ``no flight'' zone over Iraq to bolster the
aircraft already poised to strike Yugoslavia, officials said. Those
aircraft included a number of EA-6B electronic combat jets, which
are important to attacking and evading air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also withdrew a liaison team that had been sent to Belgrade
to coordinate the reconnaissance flights permitted over Kosovo
under last October's cease-fire. A team of Yugoslav officers who
had been sent to NATO's base in Vicenza, Italy, also were sent
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train has pretty much already left the station here,''
Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon's spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and his command did not disclose in advance what targets
they planned to strike first. The main Serbian military bases in
Kosovo are just north of Pristina, with army garrisons located at
Prizren near the Albanian border and Gnijilane.
</P>
<P>
   He did say, ``We know what Serbian capabilities are, we know
what Serbian vulnerabilities are.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied commanders say they believe Serbia's 16,700-member air
force, with more than 60 MIG-21 fighters and 15 MIG-29s, some armed
with air-to-air missiles, according to the International Institute
for Strategic Studies in London, would be no match for the American
and European armada preparing to launch strikes against them.
</P>
<P>
   They have also warned the Serbs against trying to attack the
allied troops gathered in neighboring Macedonia. Those forces were
to be the vanguard of a 28,000-member peacekeeping mission in
Kosovo if Serbia's leaders accepted a settlement providing autonomy
for the province.
</P>
<P>
   Allied commanders have considerable respect for the Serbian air
defense system, which has 1,000 Russian-designed surface-to-air
missiles of different ranges, including SA-6 missiles with
relatively advanced guidance systems. Serbian defenses also include
five other types of surface-to-air missiles of various ranges.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Yugoslav Navy lost most of its bases when Croatia
became independent, Serbian forces in the Adriatic still include
four powerful frigates with surface-to-surface and surface-to-air
missiles based at Tivat on the Adriatic coast that could pose a
threat to allied warplanes and navy ships, the London institute's
latest handbook, ``The Military Balance 1998/99,'' reports.
</P>
<P>
   All allied nations have emphasized that they have no intention
of fighting their way into Kosovo to install the peacekeeping force
envisioned in the peace agreement that Milosevic rejected.
</P>
<P>
   So the question before allied commanders is how effective air
power alone, without ground-based spotters to guide planes closer
to their targets, would be in terrain that is every bit as rugged
and mountainous as it was in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that the kind of laser- and infrared-guided
``smart'' bombs and air-to-ground missiles the United States used
against Iraq, particularly in the desert operations vividly shown
on videotapes taken during the war in the Persian Gulf, would not
necessarily be as effective in the Balkans, if only because clouds
frequently cover the terrain there.
</P>
<P>
   Picking out individual tanks and artillery pieces from 10,000
feet can be like looking for a needle in a haystack, experienced
pilots say, and the 30,000 Yugoslav soldiers and paramilitary
police now operating in Kosovo could draw from an arsenal of
thousands of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   And if allied planes descend to lower altitudes to try to spot
these targets more effectively, the Serbian forces have nearly
2,000 air defense guns they could bring to bear. The tank forces
alone include 239 modernized 1970s-vintage Soviet-designed T-72s
that the Yugoslavs designate as M-84s, brought into action in
Kosovo last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav forces also have about 1,000 older tanks, according
to ``The Military Balance,'' and close to 1,000 long-range heavy
artillery pieces as well as hundreds of multiple rocket launchers
capable of firing heavy barrages into targets on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of this weaponry is in Kosovo, by any means. The allies
threatened earlier this year to bomb military targets inside Serbia
proper if attacks did not cease. Whether the allied target lists
include such major military installations as the main Serbian
airbase at Batajnica, 10 miles west of Belgrade, or Krusevac, the
main tank base in central Serbia, commanders would not say.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has long made most of its own weaponry in Kragujevac,
also in central Serbia, according to Jane's. And if the allies
think that a spectacular demonstration of air power close to home
might be all it took to get Milosevic to change his mind, they
could strike at missile and radar sites on the hills surrounding
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance headquarters here provided no information in advance
about what would be hit, saying that could endanger the safety of
allied pilots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
