<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS TO GET ANSWERED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Angels manager Terry Collins will meet with his
coaching staff and general manager Bill Bavasi tonight to discuss
the final roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk about our strengths and weaknesses and the options
we have,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   No cuts will be made right away because they need the bodies to
play in the remaining Cactus League games. Among the issues that
need to be discussed:
</P>
<P>
   __ Third base. Is it Troy Glaus or Dave Hollins? Glaus has had
an impressive spring (.432, 2 homers, 17 RBI). Hollins has had
hamstring problems most of camp but is coming around and playing
well now. If Hollins wins the job, Glaus goes to Triple-A and frees
up a roster spot, probably for Chris Pritchett. If Glaus wins the
job, Hollins becomes a $2.4 million utility player if the club
can't trade him.
</P>
<P>
   __ Catcher. Charlie O'Brien and Todd Greene are in, Matt Walbeck
is hurt and Phil Nevin is on the bubble. The Angels are considering
making Fausto Tejero their third catcher and trading or releasing
Nevin.
</P>
<P>
   __ Utility infielder. With shortstop Gary DiSarcina a question
mark for opening day, the utility player becomes that much more
important. Jeff Huson, Luis Rivera and Andy Stankiewicz are vying
for the job; Huson is believed to be the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Angels have four ``starting'' outfielders,
Collins said that Orlando Palmeiro will make the team as a fifth
outfielder/pinch hitter ``unless he's traded.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff looks set: Chuck Finley, Tim Belcher, Ken
Hill, Steve Sparks and Omar Olivares are the starters; Troy
Percival, Rich DeLucia, Shigetoshi Hasegawa, Mark Petkovsek, Mike
Magnante and Mike Holtz make up the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   __ Waiting game: DiSarcina had his left forearm re-examined and
X-rayed Tuesday, but the Angels will not release the results until
today. DiSarcina broke a bone in the forearm Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   __ Greene update: Greene caught six innings Tuesday in the
Angels' 14-6 loss to the Arizona Diamondbacks and got the chance to
test his surgically repaired right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Arizona's Luis Gonzalez stole second,
beating Greene's throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fine, it didn't hurt,'' Greene said. ``I didn't care if
he was out, as long as it didn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he'll wait a couple of days and then let Greene
catch seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Greene said the plan for him for this season is to able to catch
two days, then get two days off (or as DH). Under that plan, he'll
catch three or four days per week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's necessarily important how many times a week
I catch,'' Greene said. ``Just because I feel good doesn't mean I
can catch every day. I have to be smart about it. I don't want to
get into a situation where I'm paying for it in July.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene said his goal is to be catching every day by the end of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do everything I can to be an every-day catcher,
he said, ``without killing myself doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Up-Hill battle: Starter Ken Hill was knocked around by the
Diamondbacks Tuesday, giving up six runs (all earned) and four hits
in three innings. He walked four, including three in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all over the place,'' Hill said. ``My mechanics were
off. It was just one of those days for me, it's going to happen. I
tried to make adjustments, but I wasn't out there long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Jim Edmonds returned from missing four games with a tight
groin. In his first at-bat he homered to left and later had a
double. Darin Erstad returned after missing two games because of
the flu and went 2 for 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
