<HEADLINE>
GRIEVING FAMILIES SEARCH FOR ANSWERS TO USAIR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- NTSB-CRASH-FAMILIES-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ USAir Flight 427 seemed to fly again Tuesday, at
least on a video screen. Relying on computer animation and the best
data available, federal aviation investigators recreated the
ill-fated Boeing 737 and the 1994 crash that killed 132 near
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Victims' families watched silently as the simulation showed the
737's tail rudder swing violently to the left. The plane pitched,
rolled over on its back, then spun headlong towards the ground,
disappearing into the blackness of a blank screen. Elapsed time:
28.13 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When that half-minute passed nearly five years ago, it began a
lifetime without a father for 18-year-old William Menarcheck III of
Hopwood, Pa., and his sister, Whitney, 11. Robert Johnson, 32, of
New Bedford, Mass., could never again seek his mother's advice or
savor her clam chowder, oatmeal cookies and perfectly light
cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hanley, of Chesapeake, Va., became a widower at 30. His
wife, Sarah, a USAir flight attendant, was 28 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in your late 20s, you have dreams,'' Hanley said.
``You make plans. But I don't make plans anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   These stories of lost dreams and damaged lives provided a sharp
counterpoint to arcane testimony that marked Tuesday's National
Transportation Safety Board hearing. Convened to determine the
cause of the mysterious crash, experts made their cases in
mind-numbing technical details.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed ``erratic yaw damper behavior'' and ``rudder
deflections'' and ``power control units.'' They ``extrapolated''
and ``interpolated'' mechanical data and ``human input.'' They
spoke of ``rotor issues,'' and ``vortexes'' and ``abnormal servo
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Jamison, 51, of Roanoke, Va., spoke of the father his
grandson will never know. His daughter, Kristi Gerhardt, was six
months' pregnant when Flight 427 crashed, killing her husband and
his son-in-law, Dan Lamanca, 27.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison said it was difficult to watch the computer simulations,
but perhaps no more difficult than the years of not knowing the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a horrible feeling to know people had to go through
that,'' he said during a break in the proceedings. ``But it's
important for people to know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps it make sense,'' said Menarcheck, who was barely a
teenager when his father, William Menacheck Jr., was killed on his
way home from a business trip. ``It makes it seem real.''
</P>
<P>
   While most family members expect to finally get the answers,
many were critical of the length of the investigation, and blamed
the powerful interests involved for the delay. They expressed
frustration, but said they were determined to see it through in the
hope of sparing others their agony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four-and-a-half years is an awful long time to find out how
your husband died,'' said Joanne Shortley of Pittsburgh. Her
husband, Stephen, was 37 when the plane crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his sister, Angelina Hall, 33, of Las Vegas, wore
laminated photos of their mother, Patricia Harris-Offley, of New
Bedford, around their necks. Their hope was not only to learn the
cause of the crash, but to see someone take responsibility for
their mother's death.
</P>
<P>
   Hall choked back tears as she spoke of Harris-Offley, one of 12
children, who raised Hall and her brother alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this happened, I've put off having children,'' she said.
``I wanted to have my mother to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanley demurred when asked to describe his wife. ``I can't go
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had last seen her three days before the crash, when she left
for work at the airline. She turned 28 the day before she died, and
he had planned a birthday celebration for her return.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had confidence in the (safety)'' system,'' he said. ``She
trusted the system. But the system is a bunch of suits trying to
cover their ass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
