u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-NCAA-NYT &LR;      03-23 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-NCAA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 DUKE'S TWO TEAMS ARE SPIRITUALLY JOINED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ The way it was for Seth Creger, a senior majoring
in public policy at Duke University, was typical of the cool,
sophisticated, blase approach common to the undergraduates at this
august temple of higher learning. ``We're beating Tennessee! We're
beating Tennessee!'' he shrieked as he watched the game on
television Monday night in his campus apartment. ``I can't believe
it!''
</P>
<P>
   The Duke women's basketball team was leading highly favored and
three-time defending national champion Tennessee, a team that had
beaten Duke by 16 points earlier this season, in the second half of
the East Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started calling my friends,'' Creger recalled. ```Turn it
on! Turn it on!''' He wasn't the only Dukie who was cool as a
cucumber over the occasion. ``I heard people screaming outside.
People were fired up! I mean, it was so unexpected. I won't say
that students take the men's basketball team for granted here
because of their success but, well, watching the women play
Tennessee was like, `Wow, we can really do it!'''
</P>
<P>
   And do it they did, 69-63. So for the first time in its history,
the Duke women's basketball team will be going to the Final Four,
meeting Georgia on Friday in the semifinals in San Jose, Calif. For
the 12th time in their history, the Duke men will be in the Final
Four, playing Michigan State on Saturday in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   And for only the second time in the 18 years that the NCAA has
run both basketball tournaments will the men and women from the
same school be in the Final Four at the same time; both Georgia
teams lost in the 1983 semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Though a continent apart, Duke's teams will be joined at the hip
spiritually and, surely, intellectually. After all, some of the
players on the men's team even showed up to lend support in person
at Greensboro Coliseum, about an hour's drive west of campus. There
was Chris Carrawell and Shane Battier and Trajan Langdon cheering
in a mezzanine section as the women built an 11-point lead over
Tennessee at the half, then saw it whittled down to 45-44 with
seven and a half minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   But then, truly keeping their poise, the women held on gamely,
not only beating the great Tennessee team, but also stopping its
wondrous four-time all-American, Chamique Holdsclaw, who was held
to 2 for 18 from the field and only 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked real good,'' Langdon said after the game. How do
they compare to the men's team? he was asked. ``Better,'' he said
with a little smile.
</P>
<P>
   The last may have been only a gentleman's reply, but after all
these years of the women's team being just the Ella in cinders to
the basketball princes on campus, it was a term implying nothing
less than great respect. The best the women had previously done in
the NCAA tournament was a loss in the West Regional final last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Like some of the students, the Duke men's coach, Mike
Krzyzewski, watched the Tennessee game on television at home. ``I
wasn't screaming,'' he said Tuesday, ``but there was `Yes! Yes!' _
especially when it was clear they were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't pure joy for Coach K, who has taken the Duke men
to eight of its Final Fours. He saw a cautionary tale in the
storybook victory. ``We're looked at in a way that Tennessee was,''
he said about his team. ``We're the prohibitive favorite to win.
But you saw that with a passionate attitude, and the belief you can
do it, a team at this level can beat just about any other team.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday morning Coach K walked into the office of the
women's coach, Gail Goestenkors, to congratulate her. Coach G was
already watching game film of Georgia. (By the way, the two are
generally called by their initials because, as the Duke athletic
director, Joe Alleva, said, he doesn't hire anybody whose name you
can either spell or pronounce.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be watching game films for the next game so
soon,'' Coach K said. ``Enjoy the journey and what you've
accomplished along the way. Moments like this don't happen very
often.''
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that if Coach G watches any film, it should be
of the Tennessee game, to enjoy the moment, but also to see the
truth that not everything was done right. ``I really appreciated
him coming by,'' said Coach G, ``but I can't slow down. We're so
close to our goal, to be national champions. I already had Georgia
on my mind. I feel I can't take time to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach K has been at Duke for 19 seasons; Coach G for five. Both
built programs that had been foundering. ``They are two of the most
intense and competitive people I know,'' Alleva said. ``And those
qualities help make a great coach.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also able to get the best out of their players. Both
demonstrate a saving grace _ a sense of humor _ that may be
significant in relating to people. When, for example, Coach G's
players came to the bench during a timeout after Tennessee had cut
their lead to 1 point, they found, in this critical moment, that
their coach was laughing. ``I felt them getting tight,'' she
recalled. ``And we didn't need any more stress. I don't think they
knew what I was laughing about, but I just said: `We talked about
them making a run at one point in the game. This is the run. We've
been waiting for it. Now let's go back out and stop 'em.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Coach K, making a connection with a player through a laugh
may be done away from a game, or practice. On Tuesday, while Coach
K was seated and being interviewed for a television program,
Langdon came on the court for practice. He took a shot and it
resounded in the empty gym, empty but for the coach and the
television crew on the far side of the court. ``Trajan,'' called
Coach K, ``could you just visualize it for a minute?''
</P>
<P>
   On campus Tuesday morning, Georgia Schweitzer, the Duke guard
named the most valuable player in the East Regional, had a 9:10
class, U.S. Environmental Policy 149, only hours after her team's
sensational victory. ``I was up just about all night because of the
excitement,'' she said, ``and when I walked into the classroom, all
the kids started cheering. And we were all talking about the game,
even the professor. And then one person walks in and says, `Did you
guys win last night?' Unbelievable!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
