<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOSTATE-OBRIEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHIO STATE COACH IS FAMILIAR WITH NEXT ROADBLOCK: UCONN`S CALHOUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ohio State Coach Jim O'Brien, clutching the net from the South
Regional, had barely descended the ladder last Saturday night when
a question about the Buckeyes' opponent in the Final Four brought a
wistful grin to his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably feeling pretty good right now,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun, who got his
job in Storrs just a few weeks after O'Brien became the head coach
at Boston College in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, O'Brien is delighted to discuss his abysmal 3-20
record against Calhoun during his 11 seasons in the Big East, and
the fact that he has not won in his last 18 games against
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is willing to explain some of the terribly close losses,
how every time he had a good team at Boston College, Calhoun would
show up with a Ray Allen and a Donyell Marshall, how the losses and
the competitiveness took a toll on his friendship with Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   It all plays back now with a laugh because, after all, O'Brien
began this season talking about a far more ignominious record. Last
season, O'Brien's first at Ohio State, the Buckeyes were 8-22 and
last in the Big Ten at 1-15.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Buckeyes are 27-8, and their 16{-game
turnaround ties two schools for the greatest improvement in
National Collegiate Athletic Association history. But neither of
those two teams _ North Carolina A&AMP;T in 1978 and Liberty in 1992 _
made the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, O'Brien hoped only to finish with more
victories than losses and maybe make the National Invitation
Tournament. Instead, Ohio State _ riding one of the best backcourts
in the nation _ began a slow climb up the polls to No. 10, beating
four conference teams when they were in the top 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes' remarkable NCAA run, which included upsets of
top-seeded Auburn and third-seeded St. John's in Knoxville, Tenn.,
left even the soft-spoken O'Brien so jubilant that he did an
arms-flapping, legs-flailing dance with his players at center court
after beating the Red Storm last Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere fact we found ourselves in the tournament right away
indicates we have done very well in comparison to what had gone
on,'' O'Brien, 48, said in a conference call Tuesday. ``The general
feeling was that regardless of what happened, it's all gravy that
we're in the tournament. Then you say you want to win one in the
tournament. It's unbelievable to me that we're in the Final Four,
but what we keep talking about is not settling for this.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, a Brooklyn native who was an honorable mention
all-American at St. Francis Prep, marvels at the turn his career
has taken. After playing in the American Basketball Association
from 1971 to 1975, O'Brien sold computer forms in Boston. In 1977,
with no coaching experience, he was hired as an assistant coach at
Connecticut. He got his first head coaching job in 1982 at St.
Bonaventure and left for Boston College four years later.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had won the Big East tournament in 1997. But O'Brien,
who had played for Bob Cousy and Chuck Daly at Chestnut Hill,
Mass., and who had taken Boston College to an NCAA regional final
in 1994, was on his way out. The administration, citing toughened
standards, denied admission to two recruits who had met NCAA
requirements and four others backed out of their commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College's future was gutted, local high school coaches
were incensed and a bitter O'Brien headed to Ohio State, which had
won a national title in 1960 but had not been in the NCAA
tournament in six seasons. A lawsuit O'Brien filed against Boston
College, in which he alleged breach of contract, was settled out of
court last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had no apprehension,'' O'Brien said. ``From Day 1,
before I even made the decision to come, everybody I talked to all
talked in glowing terms about Ohio State.''
</P>
<P>
   But six months into his job, before the season had even started,
O'Brien threw three players off the team for ``failure to live up
to their obligations as student athletes.'' Two others left the
program. O'Brien had just seven scholarship players, three of whom
had never played a college game. The players were used to losing
and did little else, dropping 17 straight games. The Buckeyes' best
player, point guard Scoonie Penn, sat out the season because he had
transferred from Boston College when O'Brien left.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Brien arrived in Columbus, he was asked if he understood
the pressure the Buckeyes' rabid fans would place on him. O'Brien's
response to the expectations was simple and searing: nothing in
basketball would matter as much as the death of his wife,
Christine, after a long battle with Hodgkin's disease just one day
after Boston College finished the 1990-91 season at 1-15. O'Brien
was left to raise two teen-age daughters, Erin, now 23, and Amy,
22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris was one of the greatest people you could imagine,''
Calhoun said. ``How he handled that, going through a tumultuous
time, and raising two daughters, speaks to what kind of man he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is expected to lose his 19th straight game to Calhoun's
Huskies on Saturday night. But, of course, he has already won.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
