<DOCNO> NYT19990323.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEE-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-23 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: LEE REVIVES AN OLD PAL TO ENTICE THE YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Kan.)  (lb) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Lee Co. was looking for a new way to appeal to young
consumers, it simply dusted off an old icon.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, the bluejeans maker, pulled its decades-old Buddy Lee doll
out of the archives last year and tossed him into new ads using the
tag line ``Can't bust 'em.'' Even the slogan, now aimed at the
hip-hop set, was recycled from a 1940s Lee campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nike may have Tiger Woods, but Lee insists that Buddy sells,
too. Since the Buddy Lee ads were introduced, consumer awareness of
the Lee brand has increased, prompting Lee to update the campaign
with even newer spots and commercials that will be introduced next
month and throughout the spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key goals of the brand was to make sure we were
getting credit for the messages, as opposed to larger brands like
Levi's,'' said Bruce Tait, who works on the account at Fallon
McElligott, the Minneapolis agency that created the new campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, awareness of the Lee brand among teen-agers
and young adults who have seen the commercials has increased to 70
percent from 20 percent, the company said. And retail sales at
Lee's top accounts increased 12 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy Lee has been a big part of that,'' said Gordon Harton,
president of Lee, which is based in Kansas City, Kan. ``They do
relate it back to the Lee brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some retail experts contend that using old images to
push a message of durability and authenticity may not create
long-term appeal among fashion-conscious young consumers who often
favor trendier brands like Tommy Hilfiger and Gap.
</P>
<P>
   The Lee ads and the tag line ``imply sturdiness, and sturdiness
is fine, but you somehow kind of already expect that from Lee,''
said Kurt Barnard, editor of the trade publication Barnard's Retail
Trend Report. ``But it is inconsistent with the image of fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Old-line jeans makers like Lee and its bigger competitor, Levi
Strauss &AMP; Co., which recently announced that it would close nearly
a dozen plants and lay off thousands of workers because of sagging
sales, have been struggling for ways to reach younger consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Harton said that before the reintroduced Buddy Lee campaign, Lee
was using ads that consumers found funny but did not relate to the
Lee brand.
</P>
<P>
   Besides reinforcing the Lee name, the Buddy Lee character is
also meant to remind consumers that the 110-year-old brand
represents ``things that have been around, survived and persevered
over the years,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But will that message also make them want to be seen wearing the
pants on a date?
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have to do is present themselves fashionably,''
Barnard said. ``They need to make it a little more hip _ maybe more
than a little more hip.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its commercials, Lee is pushing its marketing
message by placing the Buddy Lee image in scenes on popular
television shows. For instance, it put the doll's image on walls
during scenes of ``NYPD Blue'' and on T-shirts worn by actors
during episodes of shows that appeal to young viewers, like
``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Dharma and Greg.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee and Fallon McElligott say that the manufacturer is playing
to a strength that newer competitors cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understand that this is not some little gimmick Lee
made up in 1997,'' said Tera Small, a spokeswoman for Fallon
McElligott. ``He comes from our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee introduced the doll in the 1920s to promote its products in
department-store window displays. Demand for the character soon
became so great that the company began selling the Buddy Lee doll,
for $2.50. Today, collectors pay as much as $500 for an authentic
doll; interest in the originals has increased since the character
was brought back to pitch Lee apparel.
</P>
<P>
   In the quirky new spots, hip actors and singers portray
themselves and talk about Buddy's impact on their lives and the
world in general. In one spot, Sarah Michelle Gellar, who plays
Buffy the Vampire Slayer, discusses how Buddy Lee pushes her to be
a better actress, and they are shown working together in a scene
from a modern adaptation of the Ibsen play ``A Doll's House.''
</P>
<P>
   The spots, as well as print ads, are being used to promote new
Lee lines, including popular cargo-style pants as well as loose,
straight-leg jeans and low-rise, boot-cut jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The TV spots will begin broadcasting next month on ESPN and
ESPN2, and will run through the back-to-school shopping season. The
print ads, which will begin running in May in national magazines
like Rolling Stone, Vibe and Mademoiselle, center on Buddy Lee's
life lessons and show various items from the new product line.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a division of VF Corp. of Greensboro, N.C., will also be
showing Buddy Lee commercials this summer at theaters showing
movies aimed at teen-agers and young adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
