u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICK-WOES-NYT &LR;      03-23 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICK-WOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS PICKED WRONG SEASON FOR A REMAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never mind Patrick Ewing missing from the free-throw
line, Allan Houston missing from the perimeter and Marcus Camby
missing, well, everything. The main problem with the Knicks? It's a
franchise that became so consumed with moving beyond its hard-nosed
past and toward its young, athletic future, that it somehow forgot
the present.
</P>
<P>
   In a season with an asterisk that provided a grand opportunity
for a veteran team to win a title, Ernie Grunfeld tried to concoct
a championship team from his imagination. Without much vision, it
is resembling a lab experiment about to combust.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld, among others, is feeling the heat for this
underachieving, 15-12 team. As the Knicks fail to find any
consistency, Grunfeld, the team president and general manager, has
been criticized for not bringing in the right players.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans are incensed he didn't pluck Stephon Marbury from
Minnesota at the trading deadline, as if a young point guard could
solve this team's problems. Others wonder why he and Knick
management committed so much money to role players such as Marcus
Camby, Charlie Ward and Chris Dudley, but the truth is other teams
were eventually going to pay those players similar money.
</P>
<P>
   What you can hold Grunfeld to the fire for: miscalculating the
effects of a ruptured National Basketball Association season. In a
year that cried for stability, he dealt for potential, youth and
talent. At a time when he and the organization should have stayed
with proven veterans and experience, he changed the engine on a car
that needed a tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   Staying put worked for Utah, Indiana, Miami and Portland, teams
who lead their respective divisions. Not one of those franchises
made major alterations to its roster in the off season, preferring
instead to rely on the players that got them to the playoffs last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had known what a short season was going to be like, we
may have handled things a bit differently,'' said Dave Checketts,
the Madison Square Garden president, before Monday's embarrassing
loss to Atlanta at home. ``The clubs that have kept things pretty
much intact are the clubs that have done the best out of the shoot.
We decided to make some changes. We made some changes. We've had
some injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld admits it was a gamble, but it was one he said the
Knicks had to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got knocked out four years in a row in the second round and
our team wasn't getting any younger,'' he said yesterday. ``Also,
we weren't sure exactly how Patrick would come back after being off
for almost a year. We wanted to make an effort to get younger but
remain competitive at the same time. All I can say is, we're hoping
to turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have just finished 9 games in 12 days _ en route to
50 games in 89 days. They alternate between inconsistent and awful,
with an occasional solid effort sandwiched in between. Too often,
they are 12 bodies with no symmetry or cohesion on the floor,
trying to do what they did for some other franchise they used to
play for in some other city. After the Hawks game, in which the
Knicks made 2 of 18 shots in the fourth quarter and were booed loud
and often, the players did not talk about watching Ewing and
standing around on offense or not rotating on defense. They talked
about the effects of the jeering on their ability to play well.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a good sign when your players spend as much energy
blocking the booing out from their minds as they do blocking their
man out under the boards. But then, this is not a mentally strong
team, a group of players who summon resolve when the game is in the
balance.
</P>
<P>
   Those Knicks have come and gone: To Golden State (John Starks).
To Toronto (Charles Oakley). To the Lakers (Derek Harper).
</P>
<P>
   It is not even about heart or desire anymore, not about a
lethargic team that cannot motivate itself and certainly not about
a coach who can't get his team to play. At 15-12, the Knicks as
comprised are simply not that good.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson, playing in immense pain in his right knee, could
not jump high enough to tip the ball to himself while going after a
rebound on Monday. Ewing, proud as he is old, tipped in a missed
shot in the second half and ended up in a heap on the floor. He
rose, only to lope up the court so awkwardly it was as if a
restraining harness was holding him back. On consecutive
possessions midway through the the fourth quarter, Camby missed a
dunk attempt and lofted an air ball. Houston cannot find a rhythm
to his shot and his game that lasts more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to knock the Latrell Sprewell trade which cost
the team Starks, Chris Mills and Terry Cummings because he is a
special talent. But after the nice numbers on offense, you wonder
if Sprewell can knock down a 3-pointer at the buzzer, or even get
to the free throw line with the game in the balance. It has yet to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld has made his share of mistakes, from locking up
hard-to-trade players for untold millions to failing to build
through the draft. Yet his biggest blunder may be failing to
realize this: That if the Knicks genuinely wanted a shot at the
title in this Jordan-less season, shuffling the deck and giving
into the pressure of change was not the way to go about it.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
