A1710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-DOUBLE-RAPE-COX     03-23 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-DOUBLE-RAPE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two recall horror of attack by rapist
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The two women looked at each other and thought
for certain they were both going to die.
</P>
<P>
   Tied together on the bed by the man who had broken into the
house they shared, the women watched as he paced back and forth
with the hunting knife in his hand. The man had raped them once and
was threatening to do so again.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least three different times that night, I thought we were
not going to make it,'' one of the victims testified Tuesday in
district court.
</P>
<P>
   The man sexually assaulted the women three times that night last
April and then stole jewelry and other valuables from their
Northeast Austin home, leaving the women bound on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   The women later discovered that the man who was charged with
assaulting them, Joseph Massingill, has been HIV positive since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Massingill, of North Austin, pleaded guilty Monday to two counts
of aggravated sexual assault with a deadly weapon and two counts of
aggravated robbery with a deadly weapon. Tuesday, the two women
testified during a pre-sentencing hearing about the horror of being
raped and the fear of exposure to HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
Upon learning that Massingill was HIV positive, one of his victims
said she was devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the emotions of the crime came back,'' the woman said.
``There was nothing I could do but wait and see what would happen.
. . . I feel very angry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, both women have tested negative for HIV, but they could
still have the virus. They will take another HIV test next month.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Mike Lynch will sentence Massingill on April 14,
the one-year anniversary of the attack on the two women. Massingill
facesfive years to life in prison for each count of aggravated
sexual assault and aggravated robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Massingill, a painter, declined to comment for this article. His
attorney, Walter Prentice, said it was Massingill's idea to plead
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to accept responsibility for these very serious
offenses,'' Prentice said. ``He didn't want to put the state
through a trial, and so he stepped up and admitted to what he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of Massingill's fingerprints were found in the house,
according to police. One of the women identified him in a police
lineup, and a DNA sample taken from the women's sheets also linked
Massingill to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   When police charged him with the sexual assaults, Massingill was
already in custody on robbery and theft charges for breaking into
residences near his home and stealing cash and other valuables.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, Massingill was addicted to crack
cocaine at the time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Massingill was married at the time. His wife, Deeanna
Massingill, who was in court Tuesday, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The two sexual assault victims testified Tuesday that they had
little warning of the intruder. It was just after the weather
report on the 10 o'clock news when one of the women said she heard
the dog growl and then bark.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing she knew, a strange man was standing in her
bedroom with a three- to four-inch knife. Later, she would find out
that the man had undone the bolt on the door by reaching up through
a swinging doggie door.
</P>
<P>
   The man, she said, demanded sex and told the women to be quiet.
He ordered them to light a candle and to dim the lights.
</P>
<P>
   He raped both of them, and then he bound their hands together
with a cord he cut from a sewing machine. He cut all the phone
cords so that the women could not call for help. Then he attacked
them twice more.
</P>
<P>
   The two women said he later rummaged through their drawers and
closets looking for valuables. He used their restroom and drank
from a milk carton in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   After he left, the women freed themselves and used a mobile
phone to call police.
</P>
<P>
   Since the attacks, the women said they have armed their home
with a burglar alarm and installed bars on the windows. Both women
have concealed handgun permits and own handguns. But, both say,
they still live in fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that anything can make you feel safe again,'' one
of the women said.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Tanamachi writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
