<HEADER>
A1711 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-GUN-LAWSUITS-COX     03-23 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-GUN-LAWSUITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senators debate curb on gun lawsuits
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. Jon Lindsay says a growing national trend
to sue gun makers for the misuse of their products doesn't make
sense and he wants lawmakers to help block such lawsuits in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay on Tuesday asked fellow senators to consider Senate Bill
717, aimed at preventing the state, cities, counties or other
government agencies from suing gun and ammunition manufacturers
without legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Republican said the bill would prevent guns from
being regulated at local levels. He added that if there is a
lawsuit to be filed against gun makers, state lawmakers should have
a say in it and it should be done on behalf of all Texans, not just
those in one city or county.
</P>
<P>
   After lengthy debate, Lindsay withdrew his request for the
bill's approval, agreeing to work on amendments. The bill is
expected to be debated again today.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's bill comes on the heels of a multistate legal attack
on the tobacco industry to recover Medicaid expenses for people who
suffered from smoking-related illnesses. Texas reached a $17.3
billion settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The successes of the attack on tobacco spurred jurisdictions
across the country, beleaguered by gun-related violence, to apply
similar legal principles to wage war on gun manufacturers. So far,
cities such as Atlanta, New Orleans, Chicago and Miami have filed
lawsuits to force the gun industry to ensure that guns are used
properly and aren't distributed to criminals. Many cities are
seeking reimbursement for police and health-related costs
associated with shootings.
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark verdict in New York in February, a jury found gun
makers guilty of negligent marketing in a case in which the
relatives of gunshot victims argued that gun manufacturers
intentionally oversupplied dealers in states with weak gun laws,
and those guns were then resold in states, such as New York, with
stronger laws.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the powerful gun industry has prevailed on
state legislatures to prevent such lawsuits. Georgia state
legislators, for example, have already approved a law to prohibit
local governments from suing gun manufacturers and distributors,
and other states are considering similar legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of Senate Bill 717 is to stop the questionable
lawsuit and ensure that local gun control does not become an issue
in Texas,'' Lindsay said. ``The idea of suing a gun manufacturer
for misuse of its product is frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay said allowing lawsuits against gun makers, ammunition
makers and their trade groups could open the door to lawsuits
against auto makers and knife manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a statewide issue, and, like the tobacco issue, it
should be handled on a statewide basis,'' Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress say it's a national issue and should be
handled by federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., earlier this month led a bipartisan
group of lawmakers who introduced legislation to block cities and
states from filing lawsuits against gun makers and distributors
because of misuse of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's bill would allow individuals to sue gun makers for
misuse of their products and would allow government agencies to sue
the companies for breach of contact or warrant defects.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers spoke against the proposal before Lindsay
agreed to delay further debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it not the job of the judges and the courts and the people
we elect to decide which cases have merit?'' Sen. Gonzalo
Barrientos, D-Austin, asked Lindsay. ``Certainly there are
frivolous lawsuits, but I think we're setting a dangerous precedent
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, has written major bills in the past
to curtail lawsuits in Texas. But he said Lindsay's bill would
treat gun makers as a special group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in many ways a special protection for gun companies,''
said Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
