A1714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNERAL-HOME-LAWSUIT-     03-23 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-HOME-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-funeral agency director sues over firing
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's office tried to thwart a
high-profile investigation into the embalming practices of the
world's largest funeral company after the governor received $35,000
in campaign donations, a whistle-blower lawsuit filed Tuesday
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The ousted director of the Texas Funeral Service Commission, who
had supervised the controversial embalming investigation, contends
she was fired on Feb. 8 for speaking out about interference from
Bush aides and several state lawmakers who also received money from
a funeral home megacorporation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the allegations about Bush and the legislators are
central to the lawsuit filed by Eliza May, the state officials are
not named as defendants. A Bush aide denies that his office did
anything improper.
</P>
<P>
   May sued the Texas Funeral Service Commission and Service
Corporation International (SCI), a Houston-based company that owns
3,700 funeral homes and cemeteries around the world. She also sued
SCI chairman Robert Waltrip, who visited Bush's office last year to
complain that May was leading a ``storm trooper'' investigation
into his company and to seek her termination.
</P>
<P>
   SCI, which had revenues of $2.5 billion in 1997, is appealing
nearly $450,000 in regulatory fines that were recommended by a
Texas funeral commission panel after the 1998 investigation
overseen by May turned up evidence of bodies being embalmed by
unsupervised apprentices in unlicensed locations. The recommended
fines would be the largest ever imposed by the Texas Funeral
Service Commission, but the commission in January decided to
conduct an internal review of the embalming investigation that led
to the proposed penalties.
</P>
<P>
   May is seeking reinstatement as director of the 10-person
funeral agency, which is governed by nine commissioners _ four
funeral directors and five public members. Commission members in
February said they had lost trust and confidence in May's ability
to lead the funeral agency, where her base salary was $42,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   From SCI, she seeks unspecified monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawsuit claims that SCI company officials illegally
interfered with her state job duties, conspired to undermine her
and inflicted emotional distress, including hiring a detective to
investigate her political and civic activities. Until last summer,
May was treasurer of the Texas Democratic Party and is a former
member of its statewide executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lawsuit will show the Texas Funeral Service Commission to
be a state agency that is completely out of control, epitomizing
the very worst that state government has to offer,'' said Derek
Howard, one of May's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it would appear that the governor's office and
other politicians encouraged this dysfunctional behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   May's lawsuit lists several state lawmakers who wrote letters to
the funeral service commission or made phone calls on SCI's behalf
after the embalming investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
   May also contends she was subjected to an unpleasant and
inappropriate grilling during a May 1998 meeting in the office of
Joe Allbaugh, the governor's chief of staff. The meeting was called
by Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston, whose district includes SCI.
</P>
<P>
   Whitmire and Allbaugh were hostile and threatening to May and
Funeral Commission chairman Dick McNeil in front of SCI chairman
Waltrip and his lawyer, the lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for Bush, denied that the
governor's staff took sides at the meeting or showed favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our role was simply to listen and make sure the parties were
communicating effectively,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's office acts based on what is best for Texas,
not based on campaign contributions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Richards, general counsel for the funeral service
commission, said he could not comment on May's lawsuit because he
did not have a copy.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Miller, an Austin lobbyist who represents SCI, said May's
lawsuit has no merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally fabricated; it's totally false with respect to
us,'' he said. ``There's no truth to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
