<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-PARTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN IS SET TO COMBINE PARTS UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Nissan Motor Co. said Tuesday that two parts-supplier
subsidiaries would merge, furthering an effort by the troubled
automaker to simplify its sprawling operations even while
considering Renault SA's offer to buy a 35 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The parts suppliers, Calsonic Corp. and Kansei Corp., are facing
sharp drops in their pretax profit for the fiscal year that ends
March 31, because of deep cuts in Nissan's domestic production. As
part of an extensive overhaul, Nissan is trying to wean its
suppliers from their overwhelming dependence on its business.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan said the two subsidiaries decided on their own to merge.
Although the deal will not be complete until April 2000, the parent
company no doubt welcomed their efforts to combine operations and
share costs of developing new technologies and products.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan will be the biggest shareholder in the merged company,
however, so its links to the suppliers will still be strong.
Calsonic is a major maker of air-conditioning systems and has made
strides independently toward lessening its reliance on Nissan.
Kansei makes auto display systems like sensors and meters.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement did little to resolve the debate among
investors and analysts about the extent of Nissan's obligations to
companies like Calsonic and Kansei. Japanese accounting rules do
not require the fortunes of some of Nissan's suppliers and other
affiliates to be reflected in its consolidated financial
statements, even though the company is responsible for portions of
their debts, pension liabilities, loans and other so-called
contingent liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler Chrysler AG, which considered taking a stake in Nissan
only to walk away from a possible deal after six months of research
into the Japanese company's financial condition and operations, has
been telling investors and fund managers that Nissan's contingent
liabilities are substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become important for investors trying to evaluate
the impact of a potential deal between Nissan and Renault.
</P>
<P>
   Many contingent liabilities must be disclosed under
accounting-rule changes that begin to take effect April 1. But in
the meantime, investors are trying to determine how great Nissan's
exposure is, as well as the potential impact on Renault.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report covering the fiscal year that ended March
31, 1998, Nissan documents liabilities totaling 4.3 trillion yen,
or $36.5 billion at current exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, however, Daimler Chrysler has been telling some
investors and fund management companies that Nissan's
off-balance-sheet liabilities make its actual obligations much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Of the liabilities detailed by Nissan, $21.2 billion are related
to its core car-manufacturing business. Of the remainder,
auto-financing-related liabilities account for $11.8 billion, and
the rest is in loans it obtained to help insulate itself and its
group companies from Japan's credit shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts regard auto-financing-related liabilities as less
worrisome than other forms of debt, as they are secured by
collateral, namely Nissan cars.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler Chrysler has suggested that Nissan's actual obligations
are much higher, according to investors, substantiating suspicions
long harbored by many analysts who follow Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   One said Daimler Chrysler's research suggests that Nissan's
liabilities _ not just its industrial debt and auto-leasing-related
liabilities but other potential liabilities like pension
contributions and loan guarantees to affiliates _ could be as much
as twice the $21.2 billion in core debt that the company has on its
books.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say they do not believe Nissan's so-called
off-balance sheet risks run so high. Steve Usher, an auto analyst
at Jardine Fleming, put such liabilities at ``$6 billion to $10
billion on the absolute outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has said it does not consider its off-balance sheet
liabilities to be significant.
</P>
<P>
   Its board of directors plans to meet on March 27 to consider
Renault's offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
