<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ALBANY, GOP IN SENATE MAKES 3RD VERSION OF BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ All three of the Capitol's power players have now
staked out their positions on the state budget, as the Republicans
who control the Senate announced their package Tuesday. But with
eight days left in the fiscal year, the Legislature appears little
closer to a budget accord than it was a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   The state appears headed for a late budget for the 15th year in
a row; there was no progress Tuesday, but there was no lack of
carping.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference to release the proposed budget, Joseph
Bruno, the Senate majority leader, vented his frustration with the
Democratic majority in the Assembly, blaming them for the lack of
movement. ``It's their fault, totally and completely,'' he said.
``They are spending and trying to be heroes to every interest group
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver noted that his house passed its
own budget resolution a week ago and made public its most important
elements a week before that. ``If they had done it last week, like
we did, we would be that much closer to resolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's spokeswoman, Patricia Lynch, pointed out that Gov.
George Pataki had not become directly involved in the budget
process, despite entreaties from the Legislature. ``So far, the
governor has been silent and unavailable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office, which has sharply derided the Assembly's
budget plans, declined to comment Tuesday on the charges being
exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Senate Republicans took the middle ground
between the governor and the Assembly, with a budget more than $600
million larger than the $72.66 billion plan Pataki announced in
January. Most of the additions are in health care and education,
areas the governor proposed to cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Democrats say their budget is $2 billion more than
the governor's, but the Republicans accuse them of underestimating
their expenses. The governor's budget office says the gap is closer
to $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The two houses have been unable to agree on how much money is
available to spend, the usual starting point for serious budget
negotiations, and Bruno said that without such agreement, there was
no point in going to conference committees.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, the two sides are not far apart on that point.
Everyone agrees that the state is awash in money. The disagreement
is not so much over what is available as over how much of that
bounty to spend and how much to salt away for future needs. The
Assembly Democrats want to set aside $1 billion of the current
surplus as a reserve during the coming fiscal year, though they
would earmark nearly half of it for specific expenses in 2001 and
later. The Senate Republicans would set aside $2 billion, with no
earmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Silver is struggling to find a strategy that would avoid a rerun
of last year, when the governor simply vetoed most of the
Legislature's budget additions championed by Democrats. Bruno,
meanwhile, is trying to strike a balance between the speaker and
the governor, who are barely on speaking terms.
</P>
<P>
   And both leaders have a pressing reason to conclude a budget
quickly this year: For the first time, legislators' pay will be
withheld as long as the budget is overdue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2310EST &QL; 
