<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-23 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGOLAND-TEX     03-23 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGOLAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEGOLAND THEME PARK IS NO DISNEY, BUT IT'S BUILT FOR FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanied by BC-LEGOLAND-ATTRACTIONS and BC-LEGOLAND-NEARBY) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ On a cool, cloudy day in New York City, a
businessman in a gray suit dashes from the tan-brick Helmsley
Palace, a cell phone pressed to his ear. Two limos are parked out
front. Taxis clog the street.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the city, nuns wait on benches inside Grand Central
Station; four girls jump rope on a sidewalk; in-line skaters rush
by street musicians in the urban panoply unfolding beneath the
familiar skyline. The only element missing from this New York
experience, it seems, is the smell of exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after a few minutes of looking, it's easy to forget that
everything in ``this'' New York is made of Lego bricks _ 100,000
bricks for the 25-foot-high Empire State Building, tens of
thousands more for the Statue of Liberty towering above a
mini-harbor; a handful of the smallest bricks for Lilliputian cops
busting a young guy in a plaza. There's Times Square, too, and the
Chrysler Building, the Guggenheim Museum and Essex House, all made
of Legos, sci-fi movielike.
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable replica of Gotham, and found only in one
place, and only since last week. A magical new attraction called
Legoland California debuted Saturday in the oceanside community of
Carlsbad about 30 miles north of downtown San Diego. Boiled down,
the new theme park owned by the Denmark-based LEGO Group combines
Wizard of Oz wonder with the technical wizardry of Frank Lloyd
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Promotional literature insists that the sprawling park, only the
third of its kind in the world, is designed for kids ages 2 to 12.
After a sneak preview a few weeks back, it's unlikely any child
will leave disappointed. My 7-year-old son, who came along as
guinea pig, now wants to move to California. He liked the more
conventional stuff, the electric cars and the squirt guns, and the
more unconventional, like the towering T-rex made of Legos.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'll take New York.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders whether Ole Kirk Christiansen could have imagined
such a place. Christiansen began making small wooden toys in his
Billund, Denmark, workshop in 1932. Two years later, he dubbed his
toys and his workshop LEGO, a contraction of the Danish words ``leg
godt,'' which in English means ``play well.'' It was only
coincidence that in Latin, ``lego'' translates to ``I assemble.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, the forerunner to the Lego brick was introduced. Bricks
with the familiar fastening agents called inner tubes were created
in 1958. LEGOLAND literature boasts that bricks built in 1958 are
compatible with bricks of 1999. Since 1949, the company has
produced 189 billion Lego elements, 30 Lego bricks for every man,
woman and child in the world. Several billion bricks are on the
floor in my son's bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland Billund opened in 1968, Legoland Windsor in England
only three years ago. Legoland California has been under
construction for two years in the hills above the Pacific. It's a
128-acre park that consists of 30 million Lego bricks.
</P>
<P>
   At the Carlsbad park, ($32 for adults, $25 for children and
senior citizens) visitors are greeted by the largest Lego retail
shop in the United States. Across the way, leaning over the
Legoland lake, is a 9-foot-tall red dinosaur built of Lego bricks,
and huge elephants with long white tusks, and a pride of Lego
lions, Lego alligators and a Lego vulture or two.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as you stroll, there's the life-size Lego fireman.
</P>
<P>
   The Lego Bambi and her Lego mother.
</P>
<P>
   Lego Mount Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   The Lego Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   You get the Lego idea.
</P>
<P>
   Early in our visit, we watched a young man make animals from
skinny balloons. Turns out he was one of the few park attractions
not made from Legos. That guy and the jugglers, and the nice lady
who made our lunch.
</P>
<P>
   At Legoland, I soon realized that this amusement park is
different from any other in one crucial respect: Though laid out
like a Six Flags Over Texas, Legoland is a quiet, gentle place made
for wonder, much like spending an afternoon with the bricks at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland is not about amusement-park adrenalin and head rushes.
There is one genuine roller coaster in Legoland, and it is docile
by Texas Giant standards. Instead there are squirt guns, boat
rides, electric cars, a chairlift of sorts where kids can pull
themselves up a 30-foot tower, pulleylike, to get a peak at the
Pacific to the west, then drift gently back to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland restaurants serve exceptional food _ great pizza or
Swedish stir-fry cooked while you wait, and some of the best
Chinese food I've ever eaten. In one corner of the park, near the
15-foot-tall face of Albert Einstein (made of gray Legos) are large
play areas well-stocked with bricks _ where inspired Lego lovers
can attempt their own creations.
</P>
<P>
   But all roads at Legoland lead to New York, or to an equally
impressive depiction of Washington, D.C., nearby, (380,792 bricks
for the U.S. Capitol, 70,000 for the Lincoln Memorial); or San
Francisco; or Bourbon Street at its rowdiest; or a Midwest farm; or
a New England harbor scene, all of them rendered in Legos to the
richest detail.
</P>
<P>
   In aggregate, the models make up a part of the park called
Miniland, where a person can spend all day, in a Lego trance. What
makes Miniland doubly spectacular, of course, is a universal frame
of reference. My son has spent hundreds of hours with Legos over
the years, building space shuttles and airliners and race cars.
I've joined him on occasion, fiddling with the bricks to make a
crude building or two, (how ``do'' you make the roof?) or a bridge
for his train set. Neither of us could have imagined the
possibilities of the art.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who has ever fiddled with a Lego brick, Legoland
California is a new national treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, that makes most of us, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
