r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     03-23 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TRADES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS MAKE MOVES, BUT DO THEY MAKE PROGRESS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the tunnel vision world of Detroit Red Wings hockey,
yesterday undoubtedly was viewed as another banner day _ third
banner of a series, if you're scoring along at home.
</P>
<P>
   This was deja vu, all over again and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   This was like getting Larry Murphy from Toronto two years ago _
only better.
</P>
<P>
   This was like getting Jamie Macoun and Dmitri Mironov last year
_ only better.
</P>
<P>
   In one swoop, the heretofore fluttering Red Wings again struck
at the trade deadline and armed themselves with three tough, solid
and experienced hands for the upcoming playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They're as good as the rival Stars now, Red Wings fans will
chirp, after being conspicuously quiet all season.
</P>
<P>
   As good, maybe _ but better?
</P>
<P>
   First, let me see defenseman Ulf Samuelsson play. Samuelsson,
acquired from the New York Rangers, has a broken foot and will be
out at least another two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Let me see how Chris Chelios, a nine-time All-Star and perennial
top dog in Chicago, fits in on a team already brimming with
pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   Let me see how the defending champion Wings handle this, this
sudden infusion of ... of ... slow, old guys _ or are they wily,
hungry veterans?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, up in Detroit, they were worried. They had pondered
that disappointing 34-30-6 record and concluded that the Red Wings
were swimming upstream. Coach Scotty Bowman's team has been giving
away third-period leads like dinner mints.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings had a 3-2 lead in the third period against Phoenix a
week ago and ended up losing, 4-3. They had a 4-2 lead on national
TV Sunday against Philadelphia and ended up losing, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Their goaltending has been erratic. Their record away from Joe
Louis Arena (15-19-4) has been less than modest.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. These were deals designed to shake up the
complacent Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   But shake the Stars? The assumption would be that the Stars
weren't wary of the three-time champs to begin with. Their recent
words have suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had expressed more than a passing interest in
Samuelsson and in Wendel Clark, whom the Red Wings acquired from
Tampa Bay. The former is injured and also becomes an expensive,
unrestricted free agent on July 1. The latter was the Lightning's
leading scorer, but didn't yesterday's transactions suggest that
the Stars rated Buffalo's quicker Derek Plante as a better fit?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars needed more team speed, and that concern was amply
addressed by dealing for Plante and Benoit Hogue. The price for
winger Clark was not lavish _ a backup goalie and two draft picks.
And given that Stars general manager Bob Gainey had already talked
with Tampa Bay GM Jacques Demers over the Hogue deal, it doesn't
sound like a Clark trade simply slipped through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   The other two Detroit trades _ for Chelios and for Samuelsson _
are more interesting from Stars fans' standpoints. The deals were
consummated for a talented young defenseman, Anders Eriksson, and a
bunch of high draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   To the Stars, who know the echo that can come from a President's
Trophy, draft choices are not exactly currency to be coveted.
Surely, they had as much to offer to the Blackhawks and Rangers
that the Red Wings did.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit immediately extended Chelios' contract by two years to
2002, when the defenseman will be 40 years old. Already deep and
young in that position, the Stars couldn't promise Chelios
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock says the team discovered that it takes
time to blend in new faces, new personalities. ``Six weeks _ one
and a half months _ seems to be the pattern,'' Hitchcock had said
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chelios and Clark also would have taken playing time from ...
who? Some adjustments would have had to be made. The fragile
chemistry _ it's all fragile at NHL playoff time _ would have had
to be tinkered with.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings clearly felt it was worth rolling the dice. Now,
they will be in the hunt, Detroit fans were saying yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   I think the Stars already figured that.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
