<HEADLINE>
ARCO TO TEST A CLEANER DIESEL FUEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlantic Richfield Co. says it has developed a cleaner diesel
fuel for trucks and other large vehicles that will soon be tested
on the road in California, the state that has led the nation in
pushing oil companies to develop cleaner-burning fuels.
</P>
<P>
   The new fuel, developed by an ARCO research unit, has reduced
sulfur, nitrogen oxides and soot by substantial amounts in limited
tests, which are to be broadened in the spring, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Except in California, only modest steps have been taken so far
to clean up the emissions from the nation's truck fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Cars have long had catalytic converters, which have made huge
cuts in emissions. And in recent years, the introduction of
cleaner-burning fuels have further reduced pollution. Yet,
diesel-powered trucks have so far seen few controls.
</P>
<P>
   California, which has had worse pollution problems than most
other regions of the country, required the use of less-polluting
diesel fuel in 1993. The Environmental Protection Agency has
required lower sulfur content since 1996 in diesel fuels
nationwide, though the federal regulations are less stringent than
California's.
</P>
<P>
   However, California may seek to further reduce emissions in
diesel fuel of sulfur, particulates commonly known as soot and
nitrogen oxides that are believed to contribute to the formation of
smog.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating moves by the state, ARCO developed the new fuel on
its own. In early testing on a small number of vehicles, the fuel
reduced particulates by 13 percent, nitrogen oxides by 3 percent
and sulfates, the end product from burning sulfur in fuel, by 97
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, about 7 million gallons of the fuel will be
produced at its refinery in Carson, Calif., south of Los Angeles.
It will be tested by a fleet of 150 trucks, school buses and other
vehicles with diesel engines.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, California is projected to have 740,000
diesel-powered vehicles on the road. While these will make up no
more than 3 percent of the overall number of vehicles in the state,
they emit roughly 25 percent of the nitrogen oxide and 70 percent
of the particulates produced, according to the California Air
Resources Board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
