r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WTA-GLAMOUR-TEX     03-23 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WTA-GLAMOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TENNIS, BEAUTY IS NO LONGER SLEEPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boosters of women's professional tennis could deny up and down
that the future of their sport depends on the glamour of the game's
biggest stars. These are the best female athletes in the world,
they could argue, then go on to cite their grace, their power,
their speed.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't want to watch, especially with several intriguing
rivalries budding and the caliber of play rising?
</P>
<P>
   So, OK, Anna (Kournikova) stirred the passions of young men
around the world with her model-like looks. And, OK, Venus and
Serena (Williams) were seen stylin' in ``Vogue'' and popping off
like Charles Barkley to the media. But, ah, the game, that was the
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Until, that was, last year. Right there on the cover of ``GQ'',
wearing a flashy, form-fitting white dress, was the world's No. 1
player and the sweetheart of the women's game, Martina Hingis,
smiling under the headline: ``The Champ is a Vamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the girl was loving it. And so, too, perhaps, were
those involved in the business side of women's tennis, the
companies and promoters who hope to use the personality and appeal
of Hingis, Kournikova, the Williams sisters and other stars to
create a mega-marketing machine for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age, sports has to be viewed as
entertainment,'' explained WTA vice president Joe Favorito. ``These
are women who look pretty good and who are products of their
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   In women's tennis, Favorito added, glamour ``was overlooked and
under used for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   The WTA bills itself as the largest and most lucrative women's
professional sport and cites $40 million-plus in yearly tournament
prize money, 3.7 million annual tournament attendance and expanding
worldwide television coverage to make its case.
</P>
<P>
   One of its premier events, the $1.95 million Lipton
Championships concludes this weekend in Key Biscayne, Fla., where
last year's final may have showed off the future of the sport with
Venus Williams defeating Kournikova in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   But the sport, while more popular internationally, remains a
sporting afterthought in America. The WTA visits only a few U.S.
markets each year, including Oklahoma City last month, and its
events generally earn mediocre, at best, TV ratings. Further, the
WTA still lacks a major tour title sponsor, its secondary
sponsorships are not up to par compared to other sports, and many
of its events aren't even on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a marketing standpoint, we are at ground zero of a five-
to seven-year plan,'' Favorito acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, relying on the glamour of the game's stars
only makes sense, said Bob Williams, president of Burns Sports, a
Chicago sports marketing company that brings athletes and sponsors
together in endorsement deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early stages of revamping women's tennis \Rthe emphasis
on glamour\S is the right move, and the only move,'' Bob Williams
said. ``They've got to recapture sports fans' attention, and this
is the quickest way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glamour, observed CBS Sports executive Rob Correa, ``gets tennis
exposure in places it hasn't been seen before.'' But, he added,
``it's not a cure.'' Instead, Correa said, the women's game will
grow because of the strength of its personalities, the presence of
American stars and the depth of competition on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   The WTA took a major step forward in the glamorization of the
game last year when it sold for $120 million its worldwide TV
rights for the next nine years to Hollywood producer Arnon Milchan.
The man behind ``Pretty Woman,'' Milchan hopes to use tennis'
pretty women as the lure to attract rich broadcast deals across the
world and bring viewers to their sets.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-promoting tennis' stars by having them make cameo
appearances in movies is just one possibility. So is running tennis
promotional clips called ``trailers'' in movie theaters before film
showings, or attaching them to videocassette movies sold or rented
for home use. Also, movie scenes now set in basketball arenas might
be written to take place on tennis courts. There may even be the
equivalent of golf's successful Skins Game, or some sort of
All-Star Weekend competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the connections to Hollywood,'' said Favorito of
Milchan. ``This will be a great promotional vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Amanda Coetzer and Lori McNeil said they
generally are on board with the changing Hollywood image of their
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a product of the times,'' said McNeil, a Texan and
a veteran of the women's tour. ``You're seeing this in all sports,
like the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   There are concerns, however, that the glamorization has gotten
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   One case in point: Monique Viele, a promising 14-year-old
player, was described in a press release this way: ``Looks more
like a supermodel than a tennis player. Her long, lean, tanned
muscular legs are both an attribute to her great looks and her
speed on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   That approach incites some observers, including Mary Carillo, a
former professional player who is the top women's tennis analyst on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This glamour girl stuff, it's almost kiddie porn,'' Carillo
states. ``I hate it and I think it's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she adds, ``it's unnecessary. The best part of the
women's game is the tennis itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players also are uneasy with certain elements of the
marketing push.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skirts are getting shorter all the time,'' Monica Seles
said. ``As long as women's tennis doesn't become all about who's
wearing the shortest skirt, I'm OK with it. But this isn't
Hollywood.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
