<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FOODSTAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD STAMP ERROR NOT TIED TO YEAR 2000, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A multimillion-dollar error in distributing food-stamp benefits
throughout New Jersey was not rooted in reprogramming computers to
fix a year 2000 flaw, as was first believed, but stemmed from an
overburdened computer memory, state officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the State Department of Human Services said it had
initially overestimated the amount of money involved and the number
of people whose accounts were credited with extra benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The computer error spat out $23 million in unexpected credits,
not $30 million, for 140,000 households, about 30,000 fewer than
first reported, said Jacqueline Tencza, a spokeswoman for the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Food stamp recipients spent $5 million in benefits on Sunday and
Monday in a shopping rush before the problem was reversed about
3:30 p.m. on Monday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   State and Federal officials are weighing whether those who
collected their premature benefits will have to pay them back,
either by not getting any more payments until May or through future
deductions, or whether they will be allowed to keep the
computer-generated benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Most food-stamp recipients in New Jersey get their benefits by
sliding a magnetic card at the cash registers of grocery stores,
deducting each purchase from their monthly benefits. The cards are
administered by a private contractor in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the problem started on Saturday, when a state
analyst started the monthly run of the program that tells the
contractor how much credit to issue to each card.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said that changes last year in the welfare
eligibility rules, including a five-year limit on receiving
benefits, and enhancements being developed by programmers on the
mainframe computer had required more memory.
</P>
<P>
   Adel Ebeid, chief technology officer for New Jersey, said the
mainframe usually runs at 89 percent of capacity, but on Saturday
was running at 92 percent, leaving insufficient memory to run the
food-stamp program.
</P>
<P>
   Since this had never happened before, the analyst decided to run
the program on a backup mainframe instead, Ebeid said. But in
transferring the files to the second computer, the analyst left off
the last digit of the date, typing in 03/20/199.
</P>
<P>
   The computer, not finding the last digit, automatically put in a
zero, reading the date as 1990, and credited April's food-stamp
benefits immediately, as if they were for April 1, 1990. Ebeid said
the regular mainframe would have caught the mistake but the backup
was not programmed to do that.
</P>
<P>
   State officials had recently made year 2000-related changes to
the main computer, and that was why they first suspected that that
was the cause of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   State officials refused to identify the analyst who left off the
9 or even to say whether the person remained on the payroll. ``We
consider it to be a terrible human mistake,'' said Ebeid, who said
the analyst involved had a reputation as a hard worker. ``I think
if you were in his shoes you would feel bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebeid said the mainframe computer had been reprogrammed so its
capacity could constantly be monitored and that there would be
enough memory on the third week of each month for the food-stamp
program to run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
