<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOMEZ-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST GENERATION AMERI
 CAN VIEWS ISLAND PARENTS
 FLED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By PEDRO GOMEZ 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I woke up this morning in Havana, an alluring city I have
dreamed about all my life for one special reason _ if not for a
matter of days, it would have been my birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, I might still be there if not for my parents'
courageous journey in 1962 to the United States. The country opened
its arms to any oppressed Cuban during the early 1960s, a time when
communism was engulfing the island.
</P>
<P>
   My father and mother told me about their neighbor in Havana, the
one who had declared himself a member of the Communist Party. The
old man, as they remember him, mock ingly asked my young parents,
``Why are you leaving Cuba?''
</P>
<P>
   My mother, then pregnant with me, scornfully told him,
```Because I want this baby inside of me to know what it is to live
in a land that is free.'' The neighbor then told my mother that by
the time I reached kindergarten the world would be dominated by
communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget how I cried the day you went off to
kindergarten,'' my mother, Marta Elena, has told me often. ``I
remember every detail of that man's face and the exchange we had.
Leaving was absolutely the right decision, one we never looked back
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Miami, I often fantasized about what it would be
like to visit the land where my parents were born and one I came
within three weeks of seeing as my homeland. Now I will know.
</P>
<P>
   My parents and grandparents spoke so glowingly of Cuba's beauty
that it always seemed like an unreachable utopia. The luster of
what they recalled from the pre-Fidel Castro days of 1959 is no
doubt far different from its current state.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I come to visit the land of my heritage, which sits
only 90 miles from U.S. soil, with an open mind and open eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I will always consider Cuba my homeland along with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   My parents and I flew over Cuba on a trip from Miami to Panama
when I was 14. When the pilot told us over the loudspeaker that our
plane was flying directly over Cuba's interior, I remember how my
father and mother were brought to tears as they gazed out the
window and saw their homeland for the first time in 14 years. The
emotional pull was too much for them to contain them selves.
</P>
<P>
   My parents left for Miami after waiting nearly a year for their
visa waiver from the U.S. government. My father arrived just before
mid night at the local police station to stand in line for a call
at 3 p.m. the next day. He was third in line when my mother joined
him in the morn ing.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 500 people pressing against the doors, my parents
were among the fortunate 30 allowed entry to begin the final
processing for their departure from Cuba. Many Cubans repeated the
process, which took place five days a week for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   My parents have told me of the overwhelming emotions they experi
enced July 25, 1962, the day the government official showed up honk
ing the horn on his Czechoslovakian-made motorcycle to deliver the
pa perwork they had waited 11 months to receive.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcyclist, well known in all Cuban neighborhoods as the
sign of impending freedom back then, pro vided one of the final
obstacles for them to leave Cuba: The mandatory inventory of the
items in their home had to match the one taken 11 months earlier
when they applied for their exit.
</P>
<P>
   One missing item, and the request would have been denied. All
prop erty was now owned by the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   My parents, like all who were leaving Cuba in those times, were
ridiculed by party members in their own neighborhood, being called
``gusa nos,'' or worms.
</P>
<P>
   My father and mother, simulta neously awaiting their exit papers
and my birth, went to Mount Carmel Catholic Church, where they had
married July 15, 1961, nearly every day to pray that I would not be
born in Cuba. If so, it would have meant applying for another visa
and pass port, either of which could take up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed that if I was not born in Cuba my middle name would
be Jude, after the patron saint of lost causes.
</P>
<P>
   For their Pan Am flight from Havana to Miami, they acquired a
falsified letter from a doctor stating my mother was only six
months pregnant, not in her final month, when she would not have
been allowed to fly.
</P>
<P>
   She has often reminded me of how fellow countrymen harassed her
for not allowing her child to be born in Cuba, where they said he
could be raised and decide for himself if he should live there or
in the imperialist West.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine for a moment the U.S. government granting you permission
to leave your land but not before threatening that if you do not
return within 27 days you would be forever considered a traitor of
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For a then-impressionable young couple with a baby on the way,
the torture of hearing those words reso nates to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the types of things a person can never forget,'' my
father, Pedro, told me last week. ``Even the tiniest details live
in my mind forever.''
</P>
<P>
   My parents' DC-6 arrived in Miami on July 29. They had exactly
three changes of clothing (including socks and undergarments) and
nothing else. They were not allowed to take money, jewelry or
photos out of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived in a foreign country, unable to speak the language.
My father, then 22, made 80 cents an hour putting together window
screens in a Miami warehouse, trying to support his 16-year-old
pregnant wife.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two days after they landed in the United States, I was
born at St. Francis Hospital in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   My younger brother, Ricardo, and I know all of these things
because our parents made certain we knew our heritage.
</P>
<P>
   While other first-generation Ameri cans have made similar
journeys to the birthplace of their parents, there is something
unique and riveting when that country is only 90 miles away and has
hidden behind the cloak of communism for nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   So, while it is baseball that brings me to Cuba, it is human
drama that will generate my stories from here. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 444-2364 or at pedro.go mez &LR; pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
