<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-KOURNIKOVA-GLAMOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOURNIKOVA IS ENAMORED WITH TENNIS, NOT ADORATION 
WITH WTA GLAMOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY - Joseph Gulikers, brother David, and two teen-age
buddies were standing in line at a local indoor tennis court late
last month waiting for a chance to play with Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-born teen sensation was hitting balls with
schoolkids as part of a free tennis clinic associated with the
women's pro tournament being held up the road. Anybody in the
gathering of about 200 who showed up with a racket and a pair of
court shoes might get to hit a few with her.
</P>
<P>
   The boys had it all taken care of _ except for the racket and
shoes part.
</P>
<P>
   Doh!
</P>
<P>
   One of Anna's caretakers, hip to their clothes and perhaps
suspicious of their intentions, made sure they didn't get near the
ponytailed blonde in the turquoise and black Adidas warmups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, we got run off,'' moaned a sheepish Travis Gaken, 18, one
of Gulikers' accomplices. ``There goes that.''
</P>
<P>
   As four enamored young Oklahomans could tell you, it's not easy
getting close to Anna Kournikova. And when you're 17, with looks,
wealth, talent and fame like Kournikova, you tend to question most
everyone's motives.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as the leading glamour girl of women's tennis,
everybody wants something from you, don't they? An autographed
ball, an interview soundbite, the precious memory of a brush with
fame.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Kournikova's Oklahoma fans were left with a
practiced smile and a flitting glimpse, as by a Hollywood starlet
making her way into the theater at an opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' a tour official said, sympathizing with Kournikova's
famed reticence, ``you can only smile so much. But she's a lot
better than she was six months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City, at least, Kournikova smiled plenty, signed
dozens of autographs and made her appearances. She also played what
she called some ``A-plus'' quality tennis before taking ill and
being eliminated from the IGA Superthrift Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The tennis, she suggested, is a lot more fun for her than the
fawning that follows her from tour stop to tour stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The celebrity status is something that comes with my job,''
Kournikova stated dryly when asked if she had had enough of this
fame thing. ``If I were wishing really really hard, I don't think I
could change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova lost yesterday in The Lipton Championships, a major
tournament where, last year, she registered her best tournament
finish ever in singles, making it to the finals before losing to
Venus Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her protestations, Kournikova has hardly shied from
media or fan attention, whether by playing up her much-discussed
relationship with Detroit Red Wings star Sergei Fedorov, or by
wearing on-court outfits that some tennis insiders suggest are too
risque.
</P>
<P>
   She is defensive on this point of her appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the women's tour,'' she said of the WTA. ``So women
should look like women. It doesn't mean because we are playing
sports we shouldn't look like women. It's a normal side of young
girls to want to be attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of the criticism, Kournikova is wary of being
pinned down or penned in, even when the question is strictly about
tennis: What are your goals in the game, she is asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't program anything,'' she said. ``If I say tomorrow I'm
going to be number one, and that doesn't happen, I look bad. My
goal is always to improve, to win a tournament \Rshe won the
Australian Open doubles this year, but never a WTA singles title\S.
To continue enjoying playing and having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Her approach to the game, under coach Pavel Slozil, is also more
polished. She might even be ready to translate her immense athletic
talent into a top 10 ranking, perhaps a singles championship.
</P>
<P>
   She has displayed a powerful serve, the speed to run down most
balls and tactical awareness. The shotmaking ability and the
quickness that allow her to blast winners from anywhere on the
court are in ample evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a terrific player,'' assesses Mary Carillo, a former
pro, now a TV tennis analyst. ``She wants to win very badly. She's
very hungry. I just wish people would spend more time talking about
her tennis.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
