<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-PACK-TEX </SLUG>
 
Mavericks guard Robert Pack endures injuries 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ One of the snazziest dressers on the Mavericks team is
point guard Robert Pack. Unfortunately for Pack, he has been
wearing suits during games more times than he cares to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Entering this season, Pack had missed 179 of a possible 328
games over the previous four years because of an assortment of
injuries and surgeries. Now he's facing the drudgery of
rehabilitation once again.
</P>
<P>
   In his first interview since slightly tearing his right
hamstring during a March 13 home game against Vancouver, Pack said
yesterday that he actually injured his hamstring during a March 10
practice session at the Tom Landry Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a meeting and didn't get to go through our regular
routine where we stretch and warm up,'' Pack said. ``We stretched
and kind of jumped into our practice, and throughout that practice
I wasn't completely warm, and I kind of tweaked it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the injury, Pack played 16 minutes the next night against
Orlando and contributed six points and five assists while
responding to treatment by the Mavericks' medical staff. Two days
later against Vancouver, however, his hamstring gave way, and Pack
has now missed the past five games.
</P>
<P>
   For Pack, going through rehabilitation period is becoming too
common. But the eight-year veteran takes solace in the fact that,
unlike in three of his past four injury-riddled seasons, he should
return to action before this season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think it's strange to you for me to be hurt, it's even
stranger to me to have to go through this,'' Pack said. ``I'm just
happy that it's not a season-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easier for me to go through this rehab and work
hard, knowing that I have a chance to come back. That's the way I'm
keeping myself positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pack missed the final 44 games after surgery to
repair a torn ligament in his right thumb. Three years ago, he was
sidelined for the final 51 games of the season after damaging the
peroneal nerve in his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   And during the 1994-95 season, Pack was forced to the bench for
the last 30 games after having arthroscopic surgery to remove loose
cartilage in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Before his latest injury two weeks ago, Pack was in the middle
of one of the best seasons in a Mavericks uniform. As the backup to
starting point guard Steve Nash, Pack was averaging 9.4 points and
3.3 assists per game in only 19.6 minutes while speeding up the
offense with his high-octane way of pushing the ball up the court.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Michael Finley said the Mavericks miss Pack's ability to
change the game's tempo by driving for easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a guy like Robert who has been playing well,
for him to go down it's definitely going to hurt our team,'' Finley
said. ``We now only have one true point guard on the team in
Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   Pack said he doesn't sit around saying `why me?' Neither does he
feel sorry for himself that injuries continue to interrupt his
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has blessed me with this talent and the ability to play
this game and do something I love, and I do love the game of
basketball,'' Pack said. ``If injuries happens, I know He won't
give me anything that I can't handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another thing I'm faced with, and I'll handle it
and get over it, and I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pack longs for the day when he can play an entire season
without an injury. He also longs for the day when he can shed his
suit for a Mavericks uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of wearing those suits,'' Pack said. ``The coaching
staff is supposed to be wearing suits and I'm supposed to be in a
uniform.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
