<HEADER>
A1856 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NTSB-CRASH-SPI &LR;      03-23 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NTSB-CRASH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR CRASHES BLAMED ON RUDDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Va. _ Two horrifying plane crashes and a
disturbingly close call were caused by a rudder malfunction that
suddenly turned Boeing 737s in the wrong direction from that
commanded by the pilots, air crash investigators argued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board investigators
painstakingly dismantled suggestions by The Boeing Co. that pilot
error was the most likely cause of the 1994 crash of USAir Flight
427 near Pittsburgh, and that a freakish meteorological phenomenon
caused the 1991 crash of United Airlines Flight 585 as it
approached the Colorado Springs airport.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the NTSB investigators will urge the board to
adopt a 500-page report containing 34 proposed findings about what
caused the crash of Flight 427, and 10 proposed changes to the 737
_ the world's most-used commercial jet.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations call for improved flight data recorders on
planes, additional pilot training and ask that changes to the 737
rudder design be considered. It would be up to the Federal Aviation
Administration to make any recommendations mandatory for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and the FAA defended their past efforts to improve the
safety of the 737 and said they will weigh any recommendations
after the meeting concludes Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the NTSB's analysis presents anything we did not already
know, or have overlooked, we will assess the safety benefits of
taking further action, and make our decisions accordingly,'' said
Charles Higgins, Boeing vice president of airplane safety and
airworthiness. ``Boeing's commitment to the 737, and all of our
other airplanes, remains the same: when the facts show us an
opportunity to make it even safer, we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said Boeing has already made design improvements, added
maintenance checks and helped develop pilot training in an effort
to prevent future 737 accidents.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has also maintained that its airplanes were not
to blame in the crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, however, NTSB staff investigators outlined the evidence
that the two crashes were caused by a rudder problem on the 737,
and that the accidents could not have been caused by pilot error or
weather.
</P>
<P>
   And the investigators criticized the airline industry's top
regulator, the FAA, for not following all of the board's previous
recommendations for changes to the 737.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trust that when we finish, you and all the American people
will believe that everything possible has been done to determine
what caused this tragedy,'' NTSB Chairman Jim Hall told an audience
that included 100 friends and relatives of the 132 people killed
when USAir Flight 427 crashed near Aliquippa, Penn., on Sept. 8,
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of Boeing's pilot error theory delighted some
relatives of the Flight 427 crash victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are appreciative of what the board is trying to
accomplish,'' said Ernest Germano of Elmira, N.Y., brother of the
pilot of Flight 427. ``They've come to see what Pete Germano was.
... We feel better now than we did before.''
</P>
<P>
   Germano's 737-300 was approaching the Pittsburgh airport at
6,000 feet in clear skies when the rudder mysteriously deflected to
the left, causing the plane to corkscrew into the ground at 300
miles per hour. It exploded into tiny bits. The rudder is the
moveable part on a plane's tail and is used to control side to side
movement.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to understand what happened that day, the
investigators have linked the USAir crash to two other incidents
involving older model 737s.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1991, United Airlines Flight 585 was approaching
Colorado Springs for landing when the plane suddenly rolled and
crashed, killing all 25 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   And in June 1996, Eastwind Flight 517 _ a 737-200 just like the
Colorado Springs jet _ was approaching the Richmond, Va., airport
when it began to roll. The rudder did not respond normally. In that
case, the pilots were able to regain control of the plane and land
safely.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's hearing, NTSB staff laid the blame for all three
incidents on a rare phenomenon called ``rudder reversal,'' in which
the rudder on the Boeing 737 swings in a direction opposite that
commanded by the pilot. The phenomenon, while first observed in the
1960s by manufacturers of a rudder valve, was not recognized by
regulators until the crashes of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has offered alternate theories for the two crashes and
the Eastiwind incident.
</P>
<P>
   The company suggested that the USAir crash and the Eastwind
problem were caused when pilots incorrectly pushed on the wrong
rudder pedal, while the United crash was caused by an extraordinary
atmospheric disturbance known as a wind rotor.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing's theories were rejected by NTSB staff.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that in the case of the United crash, the weather
event cited by Boeing would have had to have been 36 times stronger
than any similar ``wind rotor'' ever recorded in that Rocky
Mountain city.
</P>
<P>
   United Flight 585 is one of only four crashes that the
30-year-old safety board has not been able to find a probable cause
for. It may decide in its final report to be adopted Wednesday that
the probable cause of the crash of the United plane was the 737
rudder.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eastwind incident, Boeing's theory would have required
the pilot to step lightly on the right rudder pedal. But both the
pilot and the first officer insist that in reality the pilot placed
the entire weight of his body on the left pedal.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Brenner, the chairman of the NTSB Human Performance
Group, said Boeing's theory defies common sense in the USAir crash.
It would have meant the pilot pushed on the left rudder and held it
down for 20 seconds as the plane plunged to the ground. Brenner
said normal pilot response to the incident would have been to step
on the right rudder, and then to remove the foot while grappling
with the wheel in an effort to save the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why (would the pilot) enter a full rudder in the wrong
direction, why (would he) maintain full rudder when control was
being visibly lost, and why does the other pilot allow it?''
Brenner asked.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of its 4{-year investigation, the NTSB has
made 20 safety recommendations for the 737, and the FAA has ordered
a variety of changes to the plane. The NTSB believes it discovered
the technical cause of the rudder reversal in 1996, and the FAA
ordered a redesign of a hydraulic valve that moves the rudder.
</P>
<P>
   But concerns about the 737 rudder remain. The NTSB staff said
there have been more than 100 incidents of flight control problem
caused by the rudder. In many of those incidents, pilots reported a
mysterious pulsing or kicking sensation in the rudder pedal.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, a Metrojet 737 experienced an unintended rudder
movement last month and made an emergency landing after the pilots
regained control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crashes of USAir Flight 427 and United Airlines Flight 585
in Colorado Springs have raised questions in many minds about the
design and operation of the 737's rudder system,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these concerns, NTSB officials took pains to defend the
safety of the Boeing 737, which is the world's most popular
jetliner, with more than 3,000 now in service.
</P>
<P>
   The 737 has been in use since the 1967, and is expected to be
used well into the next century, Hall said. Hall said he plans to
hold hearings in Seattle to scrutinize how the 737 is certified for
flight by the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB staff outlined some, but not all, of the recommendations
the board will consider Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The staff and board were most exercised about changes they want
in the flight data recorders aboard the 737. They said better data
would help them solve future accidents, and they criticized the FAA
for not requiring faster action on this issue. The flight data
recorders on the USAir, United, Eastwind and Metrojet planes were
too primitive to measure rudder movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fail to understand how something so good can be so
sluggishly responded to,'' said NTSB board member George Black Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The staff also said it will recommend further specialized pilot
training for dealing with rare flight control malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   The staff also suggested that perhaps the FAA should require
that planes travel slightly faster when certain maneuvers are being
performed to prevent a loss of control that was experienced in the
USAir flight.
</P>
<P>
   In the area of design changes to the rudder, the staff was vague
about its recommendations, but several staffers hinted that they
would like to see a system in which the plane might have two of the
hydraulic power control units that translate the pilot's pedal
action into actual movement of the rudder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a need for greater redundancy in the
system,''said Bernard Loeb, director of the NTSB's office of
aviation safety. ``Despite a lot of the good things that have been
done, more needs to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
