<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-SHOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. OFFICER SHOOTS PIT BULL ATTACKING 85-YEAR-OLD WOMAN AND HER
DOG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE AND RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A pit bull attacked an 85-year-old woman and her
Lhasa apso Tuesday before an off-duty LAPD detective shot the dog
to death, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose identity was not released, was treated for
bites to her hand, police said. Her dog was treated for injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The 7 a.m. pit bull attack in the Panorama City community of Los
Angeles' San Fernando Valley was the latest in a series citywide
that has prompted widespread abandonment of the pets at animal
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to cut the number of stray dogs, Los Angeles City
Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas proposed that all dog and cat owners
be required to spay or neuter their pets or pay a higher fee to be
listed as animal breeders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now common to see stray dogs roaming the streets, many
of which are injured, sick, hungry or running (in) packs,''
Ridley-Thomas said. ``They frighten residents, attack humans and
other dogs and pose a threat to the public safety of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for the Board of Animal Service Commissioners
to report back in 45 days with proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The department killed nearly 60,000 cats and dogs in 1997, an
estimated 44,000 of which were strays.
</P>
<P>
   The humane community generally agrees with the proposal, said
Gini Barrett, a member of the Animal Services Commission and
director of the Humane Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is cutting-edge thinking,'' Barrett said. ``This really
says the city is going to take pet overpopulation and animal safety
very seriously. There are a number of responsible pet owners who
will object to this, but it will be up to them to make their
case.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Panorama City attack, police said shooting the dog was
the only way to stop the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times officers try to use pepper spray on a dog
first, and resort to deadly force later,'' said Foothill Division
Capt. Ken Garner. ``In a situation of life or death like this could
have been, the deadly force was warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie David, Animal Regulation spokeswoman, said the northeast
San Fernando Valley gets a special enforcement twice a week,
catching about 28 dogs each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several packs of dogs there that feed on small
animals and discarded food. It's springtime; we'll see them a lot
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Phongmai, 25, who lives near where the woman was mauled,
said other attacks have occurred recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I keep my dog in the back,'' Phongmai said. ``They
are very dangerous. Two pit bulls attacked another neighbor of mine
last year, and my dad and I tried to help get them apart.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-99 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
